<SLUG> BC-BKN--FRAN </SLUG>
 BLINEBURY-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Seeking a hiding place in Lakerland
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Scottie, we hardly knew ye.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the bolder truth is that in his brief Cup O' Season as
a Rocket, we did get to see the real Scottie Pippen, and that's why
he is suddenly in such a hurry to high-tail it out of town before
he is exposed over the course of an 82-game schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Pippen has come to the realization that even with a
holster filled with silver bullets, some guys are more suited to
being Tonto than the Lone Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, just a few short months after proclaiming his love for the
Houston area and his intention to put down roots, comes Pippen's
yearning to be reunited with his former coach, Phil Jackson in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it might seem a case of requited love, because
Big Chief Triangle openly has talked of his desire to have Pippen
again running his three-cornered offense almost from the moment he
accepted the job as coach of the Lakers. It is a motion offense
that takes the most advantage of Pippen's fluid, raw skills, one
that worked well enough to produce six NBA championships in Chicago
_ though the presence of a certain tongue-wagging extraterrestrial
might have had something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, by having agent Jimmy Sexton work behind the
scenes and by going to former Rockets senior executive vice
president Robert Barr to request a trade to LA, this could be
Pippen's gutless way of admitting he can't stand the heat of being
the main man in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Michael Jordan was on hand to do all the heavy
lifting in Chicago, Pippen was able to drift around the perimeter,
collecting gold rings and accolades as the Bulls' so-called unsung
hero. It was a role that played perfectly into his talent and his
personality, because it often allowed Pippen to showcase his
athleticism while giving him a forum to complain about being
unappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf and general manager Jerry Krause
were always the bad guys and Jordan was always the man who had to
step up in the clutch and get the job done on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after just a few months of an on-the-run elopement with the
Rockets that had its predictable rocky start, Pippen is ready to
take flight again to the West Coast, where this time he would be
able to continue collecting on his superstar contract ($14.79
million next season) while hiding behind the skirts of Shaquille
O'Neal and Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   It is a perfect scenario for Pippen to assert himself. He gets
to be the teacher's pet in Jackson's learning lab, while never
shouldering the full load of the pressure. To Pippen, O'Neal _ and
to a lesser extent Bryant _ merely would become bigger and younger
versions of Jordan, assuming all the risk while Scottie shakes his
head and makes excuses at their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   By lobbying for a trade, Pippen is trying to lay off all of the
blame for his miserable 1999 season on Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich and his offense. But what Scottie is doing is revealing
the essence of his character as a competitor and a teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen spent so much of last season telling everyone how
uncomfortable and unhappy he was with the offense. Yet the coaching
staff defended his play at every turn and said he delivered the
goods. And their noses didn't even grow.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several of his veteran teammates shook their heads in
disgust at Pippen's complaints about the offense, saying all the
chances for him to score and to run were there, if only he would
have taken them. Then Pippen topped off a shameless season by
pointing his finger at Charles Barkley, the buddy who had covered
his back all year, in the Game 1 playoff loss to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Where is the pride to come back and prove everybody wrong?
Didn't he learn that much from Jordan?
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Rockets are caught in a difficult spot, knowing they
are committed to four more years of a player who didn't like his
experience and doesn't believe Rudy T's pledge to open up the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Barr, unofficially the vice president of ego
massages, hurts any effort to placate Pippen, who needs more
pampering and high maintenance than a tractor-trailer full of Miss
America contestants.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets can acquiesce and send Pippen to the Lakers, though
it will take much more than Robert Horry and jump-shooting,
no-defense, grumpy oinker Glen Rice to seal the deal from a
basketball and salary-cap standpoint. Now if the Lakers were to
mention the name Kobe, well, we're definitely talking.
</P>
<P>
   But a deal like that might not sit too well with Pippen. After
all, it would give him one less skirt behind which to hide in LA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
