<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-column-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Elkington drops everything to stand by fallen caddie
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   GLENDALE HEIGHTS, Ill. _ When Steve Elkington stepped from his
car at Medinah Country Club late Thursday morning, less than two
hours before he was to tee off in the 81st PGA Championship, he had
nothing except golf on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   He wore his game face. He couldn't have felt better. After two
solid practice rounds, he couldn't have been more ready for
Medinah's green monster. His caddie, Gypsy Joe Grillo, had slapped
Elk on the back and told him so Wednesday afternoon. Gypsy Joe said
he liked his man's chances.
</P>
<P>
   A huge weekend loomed for Elkington. The PGA has been a special
tournament since he won it at Riviera in 1995, and it carried extra
significance here. He is trying to bolster his 1999 earnings to
secure a spot in the season-ending Tour Championship, scheduled for
his home course, Champions, at the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   He's not there yet. After a difficult year _ his only top-10
finish came at Doral, which he won _ he's right on the bubble. A
third bout with viral meningitis cost him a high finish, perhaps
even a victory, in the Shell Houston Open, from which he had to
withdraw after being 6-under through three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Only the top 30 will qualify for the Tour Championship. He needs
to move up a couple of notches, then build a fail-safe cushion for
himself. No offense, folks, but this man with the perfect golf
swing doesn't want to hobnob with you in the Champions gallery. He
doesn't want his nose pressed to the windowpane while his peers
traipse by on the fairway beyond his rose garden and swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, he had decided to enter four tournaments in a row,
something players of Elk's stature rarely do. The PGA would be the
second of the bunch _ and easily the most important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the PGA,'' Elk said.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, it might be his favorite major.
</P>
<P>
   He said so while we were sitting alone in the ICU waiting room
at Glen Oaks Hospital in Glendale Heights, a Chicago suburb down
the road from Medinah. He was dressed in golf clothes, save for his
spikes, which wouldn't be needed. Elkington had withdrawn from the
PGA.
</P>
<P>
   Walking to the Medinah clubhouse, he noticed a commotion. He saw
a man on a gurney being rushed to a waiting ambulance. Curious, he
looked closer. He saw a frightened face and a familiar one.
</P>
<P>
   Gypsy's.
</P>
<P>
   Now, down the hall, Grillo was being hooked up to a bank of
machines that beep and blink. The popular veteran caddie,
Elkington's good buddy for 13 years, his regular bag-toter since
1996 and his partner for six PGA Tour wins, apparently is out of
danger, but doctors won't be sure until today, after they have put
him through a battery of tests.
</P>
<P>
   Grillo, 48, might have suffered a heart attack Thursday morning.
Then again, he might not have. But it didn't much matter either way
to Elk. How could he go out on the golf course, even for the PGA,
not knowing if Gypsy was OK?
</P>
<P>
   Tournament officials told him they would rustle up a caddie in a
jiffy. Elkington passed. Instead, he got back in his car and
followed the ambulance to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gypsy is family,'' he said, his eyes glistening. ``I wouldn't
have been much good out there, under these circumstances. What if
something happened and I wasn't there for him? What if
</P>
<P>
   ``What if he'd gone down? What if I'd never seen him again?
Look, Gypsy doesn't have anybody. It wasn't a hard decision at all.
This is a guy who cooks for me, who takes care of my kids. He'll
drive over (from San Antonio, his home) and work on my car. There
are a lot more important things in life than golf.''
</P>
<P>
   But Grillo didn't fully second Elkington's emotions. Seeing his
boss standing over him in the emergency room, he frowned.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the are you doing here?'' Gypsy said.
</P>
<P>
   But anybody who understands Elkington, Grillo foremost among
them, wouldn't have expected him to be anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Elk isn't always an easy read. He can be grumpy, impersonal,
aloof. He has a temper. Remember how he took his foot to the wall
of the scorer's trailer at Doral _ after he shot a 64? Nonetheless,
he has a heart that's about the size of his native Australia's
Outback.
</P>
<P>
   He participated in a stirring tribute to the late Dave Williams,
his coach at the University of Houston, when Williams was too ill
to attend a charity gala for the school's athletic department.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who owns a popular steakhouse near Elk's home was
fighting a losing legal battle with a national restaurant chain
over the use of a name. She had, out of desperation, suggested
resolving the dispute on the golf course, and Elk's skills were
solicited on her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Although he never had met her, the particulars of the case
bugged him. To tempt them to back off, he offered the chain's top
executives a free full-day clinic, something that normally would
earn him upwards of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to help that lady,'' he said. ``What's happening to
her is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Elk. Fittingly, his place in the PGA field would be
filled by Bob Friend. It would appear you can't have a better
friend than Steve Elkington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
