<HEADLINE>
DEBRUCE GRAIN FILES MOTION IN OSHA CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Experts who investigated last summer's
fatal DeBruce Grain Inc. elevator explosion near Wichita, Kan., for
a federal agency are unfairly being allowed to work against DeBruce
in private lawsuits, the North Kansas City company alleged in legal
documents filed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce also asserted that the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration ``has selectively leaked information to the national
and local media,'' prejudicing potential jurors and affecting the
fairness of multiple legal proceedings against the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The taint of what has already happened is considerable and
prejudicial,'' DeBruce said in its request to an OSHA appeals panel
to dissolve a stay in the matter and immediately let the company
review OSHA's investigative reports, interview its experts and
begin defending itself.
</P>
<P>
   An OSHA spokesman in Kansas City, Mo., on Thursday said the
agency would have no comment.
</P>
<P>
   The June 8, 1998, blast destroyed sections of the vast grain
elevator complex and left seven workers dead and others injured.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year OSHA issued three dozen workplace-safety
violations against DeBruce, with civil fines totaling $1.74
million.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 36 violations, 26 fell into the most serious ``willful''
category, including at least nine instances of inoperative grain
dust collection systems. DeBruce appealed and the case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   To date, OSHA has not released its investigative report on the
cause of the blast. But its experts publicly have attributed the
explosion to the presence of volatile grain dust in an underground
conveyor-belt tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Investigator Vernon Grose told The Wichita Eagle newspaper last
summer that a seized bearing in that machinery caused friction and
generated enough heat to ignite grain dust.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce officials have taken sharp exception to that, arguing
that grain was not being moved in that area at the time of the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   In a sworn affidavit, a lawyer for DeBruce said C.W. Kauffman,
an expert used by OSHA, was simultaneously working for Industrial
Maintenance Inc. of Wichita, a DeBruce subcontractor that also has
been sued in connection with the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the OSHA Review Commission in Washington stayed all
activity in DeBruce's appeal until federal prosecutors in Wichita
completed their investigation of possible criminal wrongdoing. That
matter also is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   But DeBruce also complained Thursday that OSHA representatives
were working with the Justice Department and eventually would be
allowed to disclose non-grand jury evidence in the case to OSHA for
use in its civil proceeding against the company.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce objects to that because OSHA in effect is continuing to
develop its case against DeBruce despite the stay order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to mitigate the effect of this outrageous
development is to level the playing field by dissolving the stay
... and eliminate the one-sided nature of these actions,'' the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Williams, the U.S. attorney in Wichita, did not return
calls Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing for the stay earlier this year, government lawyers
said it was essential to prevent DeBruce from ``making use of the
liberal discovery procedures applicable to a civil suit as a dodge
to avoid the restrictions on criminal discovery and thereby obtain
documents he would not otherwise be entitled to for use in his
criminal trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Discovery is a legal procedure in which both sides must disclose
certain evidence.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA has 10 days to respond to DeBruce's motion to lift the
stay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
