<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-FAIR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT TAKES ITS TOLL ON MISSOURI STATE FAIR'S OPENING DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDALIA, Mo. _ ``The Best Fun Around'' is the theme for this
year's Missouri State Fair, but opening day was no fun for 50
members of the Sedalia Smith-Cotton High School band who collapsed
in the 100-degree heat after marching a half mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' band director Andy Kroesen said.
``We've done this several years, but we get to the end of this
year's parade and everyone starts dropping. It was only a half-mile
parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarinets, flag poles and band cases were strewn on the ground
as band members, their faces red and their hair drenched with
sweat, were taken to the Red Cross center for treatment. Some were
crying, others vomiting and others shaking.
</P>
<P>
   The students, who were wearing summer uniforms of T-shirts and
shorts and no hats, were taken to the center by ambulances and golf
carts, or in some cases, carried by friends.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Allen, the fair's marketing director, said 22 persons
were treated at the fair's first-aid station. Of those, nine were
taken to Bothwell Regional Health Center, where they were treated
and released.
</P>
<P>
   Four other persons were treated at the Red Cross center. Ron
Pauble, fire chief in Claycomo, Mo., and in charge of the fair's
emergency crew, said these were the worst heat-related problems he
could remember in his 10 years working at the fair.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular person at the fair on Thursday might have been
Todd Lagessie, 34, of Kansas City, Mo., who stood 8 1/2 feet tall
on his stilts and was dressed as a firefighter, spraying people
with a huge squirt gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want a squirt?'' he'd ask passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   Then he'd spray them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get wet, I want to get wet,'' shouted Janie
Fitzpatrick, 10, of Salisbury, Mo., as she ran under Lagessie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever fallen?'' someone else asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't say the `F' word, please,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   You could see the heat in the faces of people as they entered
the Missouri Farm Bureau building, one of seven air-conditioned
buildings on the fairgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, they'd lift their arms and smile.
</P>
<P>
   Back outside, business was less than brisk at the funnel cake
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only sold eight,'' said Misty Ross, 19, of Sedalia,
working at Carol's Funnel Cakes.
</P>
<P>
   The air conditioner in the funnel cake trailer broke Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants a hot funnel cake, but they want a lot of
drinks,'' Ross said as she wiped the sweat from her face.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Whitaker, in blue jeans and a straw cowboy hat, was
sitting in front of a box fan inside a sweltering barn.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old stable hand from Center, Mo., washed down the
horses every two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work 'em hard and they show hard, then we run ice cubes
over them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was hot and dusty in the outdoor arena where a cattle show
was being judged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like we're out in Kansas during the dust bowl,'' said
Barbara Kendrick, 56, of Mineral Point, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandsons were showing cattle and her daughter showing
sheep.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we have a wind or we'd be burning up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The family was camping at the fair, as they've done for the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the hottest it's been so far,'' she said. ``We're
hoping it will cool down tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
