u i BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-1STLD-WR     08-13 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-1STLD-WRITETRHU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA WARNS OF MILITARY ACTION AGAINST TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add six grafs to end of original text.)  (Eds: This story replaces CLINTON-DEFENSE) 
(mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chinese government officials have warned the
Clinton administration that Beijing may be compelled to take
military action to ``punish'' Taiwan for what Beijing sees as moves
toward independence, administration officials and China experts
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In reply, Washington has warned Chinese officials that any
military action by China against Taiwan would bring retaliation by
the United States, administration officials said. In the past week,
the administration has also publicly and privately urged the two
sides to resolve the situation between themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings about the possible use of force have come not from
top Chinese leaders, but lower-ranking Chinese officials in
meetings with administration officials in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It was not entirely clear whether the Chinese officials were
attempting to gauge American reaction to the use of force, or
trying to enlist American help in pressuring Taiwan to back down.
China has considered Taiwan a renegade province since the civil war
ended 50 years ago, and has never renounced the use of force to
reunite Taiwan with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said it was also not clear whether
Beijing had decided what course to take.
</P>
<P>
   If military action was employed, administration officials said,
it could range from striking at Taiwan to seizing an unpopulated
island belonging to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Military action against Taiwan itself appeared to be the least
likely course for Beijing, several administration officials said.
But one official said the military situation in the Taiwan Strait
was ``dangerous'' and ``very delicate.'' For more than a week,
military aircraft from China and Taiwan have been flying close to
each other over the 100-mile-wide waterway, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances are very real for an inadvertent thing or
something more ominous,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States was preparing for ``contingencies'' in the
Taiwan Strait, another official said. But he declined to elaborate
on what those preparations were.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the United States came the closest to a military
confrontation with China since the Eisenhower era after the Chinese
lobbed missiles near Taiwan and the Clinton administration moved
two aircraft carrier groups into the region.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Chinese leaders, who have just returned from
their annual retreat in Beidahe, appeared to be divided on how to
respond to recent statements by Taiwan's president, Lee Teng-hui,
that negotiations with Beijing over the island should take place on
a ``state to state'' basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard-liners want to be tough. Others are saying let's
wait,'' one administration official said. He added that, overall,
China appeared to be ``waiting to see if Taiwan could be put back
into the box.''
</P>
<P>
   The charge d'affaires at the Chinese Embassy in Washington, Liu
Xiaomin, was summoned to the office of assistant secretary of state
for East Asia, Stanley Roth, last week.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony the following day before the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, Roth said that the Chinese and the Taiwanese
had been given six demarches by the United States urging them to
restrain their military activities in the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government may also be sending their warnings about
taking military action to test the United States, several China
experts said. The government has used the South China Morning Post,
a Hong Kong newspaper, to float stories about pending action.
Thursday's edition of the paper said that 500,000 troops of the
People's Liberation Army were being mobilized in a southern
province.
</P>
<P>
   But Pentagon officials have said in the last several days that
they have seen no sign of such massive mobilization.
</P>
<P>
   An effort to take a smaller island belonging to Taiwan would not
need such a large mobilization, however.
</P>
<P>
   A former American diplomat to China, Chas. Freeman, said that he
believed the Chinese were serious in their intent to ``punish''
Taiwan. It was not clear what form that would take, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing regards Taiwan as a Chinese province that must
eventually be rejoined to the mainland. Freeman said recent
statements from Taiwanese officials about a ``state to state''
relationship with China appeared to nudge the island closer to
independence and have encouraged Beijing to be more assertive in
trying to demonstrate its sovereignty with air flights over the
Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   The United States finds itself in the middle of the dispute
because of its pledge to provide for Taiwan's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Washington announced that it was going ahead with the
sale of $500 million of military equipment to Taiwan. Beijing
protested the sale, which had been agreed to between Taipei and
Washington well before the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Several administration officials said they hoped that the
Chinese government's actions would be tempered by two important
dates. The first is the planned meeting between President Clinton
and President Jiang Zemin in New Zealand in September. The second
is the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of
China, on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   These officials and China experts said they believed that
Beijing might be reluctant to take dramatic action against Taiwan
that would mar those two events.
</P>
<P>
   Moderates in the Chinese government appear anxious, for example,
to revive talks on China's entry into the World Trade Organization,
the officials and experts said. That topic is a recurrent one in
talks between Clinton and Jiang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
