r a BC-VFW-CONVENTION-KAN &LR;      08-13 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VFW-CONVENTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME VETERANS WONDER WHETHER PUBLIC VIEWS THEM WITH INDIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The foreign wars were challenge enough.
</P>
<P>
   The home front represents a whole new battle.
</P>
<P>
   The Veterans of Foreign Wars holds its national convention next
week in Kansas City. The gathering, which begins Monday in Bartle
Hall, marks the 100th anniversary of the VFW, the country's
second-largest veterans group, with 1.9 million members.
</P>
<P>
   In honor of the milestone, VFW organizers have invited the
public to an airshow and other entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Several area VFW members, however, aren't sure the public wants
the veterans' company. Many of them wonder whether their years in
uniform spark only indifference in the civilian community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's kids don't have the faintest idea of what veterans
are,'' said Paul Connors, a Vietnam veteran who serves as
quartermaster of VFW Post 30 in Blue Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending upon the age of the individual, the perception of
what a veteran is will be completely across the spectrum. While the
older people from the 1940s and 1950s are aware, teen-agers still
wonder what went on during World War II. I spoke with some young
people who saw `Saving Private Ryan' and they asked me, `Why were
we bombing the French?'
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no concept of what went on during D-Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Connors, like many VFW members, is fighting such disinterest by
working to make veterans in general and the VFW in particular
relevant to the community. In May his post cooperated with other
service groups to organize a child safety and identification
program through St. Mary's Hospital of Blue Springs, Mo. Some post
members also cook for senior citizen food programs and perform
other community service.
</P>
<P>
   But creating significant awareness of veterans, some say, is a
challenge during peacetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have a major war going on, veterans become very
popular,'' said Jerry Jones of Raytown, a Vietnam veteran who
commands the VFW's 4th District in Missouri, covering metropolitan
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have no major war now, so there's no need for the
military and no need for veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   VFW member Margaret Wescott offers a similar perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``There doesn't seem to be much information put out about how
veterans are soldiers willing to give their lives,'' said Wescott,
quartermaster of VFW Post 11555 of Topeka, Kan., the first
female-only VFW post, chartered in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start asking younger people, it's `What's a veteran?'
''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Moskos, a military sociologist at Northwestern
University in Evanston, Ill., even wonders whether the public's
ultimate view of veterans is all that flattering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Moskos said. `` `Forrest Gump' was considered to
be a movie favorable to the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet Forrest was still a moron.''
</P>
<P>
   It all hints at a gulf between veterans and the American
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government dropped the draft in 1973, and the share
of Americans who have served since has diminished. Moskos has
argued that if lawmakers bring back the draft, it would strengthen
ties between the civilian and military worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe it would at least raise awareness of veterans'
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you have a veteran in your family, you probably don't
care or think about veterans,'' said Jim Hughes, assistant
quartermaster of VFW Post 5789 in Lee's Summit, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, former soldiers returning to civilian life
made veterans issues high priority. Through the July 1956 cutoff
date, more than 2.2 million World War II veterans had enrolled in
college through the GI Bill, with the government spending $1,858
for every veteran it sent through school.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran, however, didn't always command such clout. Consider
the different environments for veterans in 1999 and 1931, the last
time the VFW convened in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the federal Veterans Administration was only a year
old.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Department of Veterans Affairs receives more than $17
billion to provide health care to veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans' groups today represent ``one of the more powerful
lobbies in Washington,'' The New York Times recently said.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, VFW convention delegates will consider more than 100
resolutions regarding veterans' care.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1931 convention, however, priorities were more basic.
A federal veterans' administrator drew cheers after promising to do
his best to see that ``no veteran goes hungry or is out in the cold
this winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in part because of debates over benefits or entitlements,
the relationship of veterans and the public has been fluid.
</P>
<P>
   The 1931 convention occurred only months before the lowest
moment in the veterans' movement. In July 1932, Army troops, using
tear gas, routed about 20,000 World War I veterans from their
Washington encampment.
</P>
<P>
   The veterans were demanding an immediate cash payment of a bonus
promised by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   However shameful their treatment, the veterans still didn't
command unflinching sympathy from the public, said Michael Neiberg,
assistant professor of history at the U.S. Air Force Academy in
Colorado Springs, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the Depression hit, the country really began to polarize
over issues,'' Neiberg said. ``And the perception then was that
anyone in the enlisted ranks was a person of pretty low skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today you have to have a high school diploma to get into the
military. That wasn't the case in 1931.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1930, some newspapers were affronted that the World War
Disability Act, passed that year, committed $73 million to veterans
in the middle of hard times. Veterans totally disabled by wounds
could receive as much as $2,400 a year _ this when 65 percent of
Americans earned less than $3,000 yearly.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans benefits today are a familiar concept to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But today's veterans, because of the public's sometimes fickle
regard for their needs, should never assume that their entitlements
are sacrosanct, said Jones of the VFW's 4th Missouri District.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now veterans are fighting a Cold War for their rights and
entitlements,'' said Jones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
