<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEVIN SMITH OUT WITH BAD BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN AND RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys cornerback Kevin Smith
will be out of action indefinitely as he continues to seek a remedy
for a back problem that first surfaced last season.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who did not return to training camp this week after the
exhibition game against Cleveland, went to Dallas and received an
epidural injection Thursday. He will undergo rehabilitation this
week and be re-evaluated Monday by Dr. Drew Dossett, Cowboys
trainer Jim Maurer said. Smith played briefly in Monday night's
exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are seriously hurting at cornerback with Deion
Sanders out indefinitely and now Smith out at least another week
and perhaps much longer. Kevin Mathis, who is slated to start
opposite Smith at cornerback in Sanders' absence, returned to
practice Wednesday after suffering a lower back contusion last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries open the door for rookie Duane Hawthorne, who
impressed coaches in Monday's exhibition while getting the start in
place of Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   Injured safety Charlie Williams (fractured left forearm) is
expected back at practice next week. ROCKET GROUNDED; LaFLEUR WON'T
PLAY
</P>
<P>
   Hopes that Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail would make his Cowboys debut
Sunday against the Raiders in Oakland fizzled Thursday. Gailey said
Ismail will not play in the team's second exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail walked through drills on Wednesday, but did not practice
Thursday due to a sprained left shoulder suffered on Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end David LaFleur is back at practice and looking good,
Gailey said. However, Gailey said LaFleur will likely not play
Sunday for precautionary reasons. ``If did (play) it would be
special situations in a very limited amount,'' Gailey said. IF
HEALTHY, McIVER STARTS
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are targeting the final week or two of training camp
for right guard Everett McIver's return.
</P>
<P>
   McIver is rehabilitating his left knee after surgery in the
latter portion of the 1998 season after suffering a torn anterior
cruciate ligament. Gailey said as long as McIver is healthy he will
be the starter, but he couldn't say if McIver would be ready for
the Sept. 12 opener at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Solomon Page, a tackle from West Virginia, started at
right guard in Monday's exhibition. Page will compete with injured
Tony Hutson (sprained knee ligament) for the position upon Hutson's
return. FRICKE IMPRESSES
</P>
<P>
   Ben Fricke, a recent addition from Amsterdam of NFL Europe, has
impressed coaches enough to have a shot at earning a roster spot.
Fricke, a center, got an opportunity after center Mike Kiselak
suffered a season-ending knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey called Fricke (6-foot, 295 pounds) ``a pleasant
surprise'' and lauded his technique. Fricke, out of the University
of Houston, said he spent three weeks in Houston working out after
the NFL Europe season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is set in stone,'' he said. ``You have to demonstrate
your skills all over again.'' BEATING THE HEAT
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys got a bit of a breather during Thursday's afternoon
practice. Gailey allowed the team to forgo helmets as a way to beat
the heat _ sort of. Most players donned ball caps or bandanans.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature again hit 106 degrees on the practice field with
a heat index of 109.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand all the physcial stuff of how it works, but
evidently you lose a lot of heat through your head and that's how
your body gets rid of all that stored up heat in you. So we're
going to take a look at that,'' Gailey said. McGARITY THE RETURNER
</P>
<P>
   Rookie wide receiver Wane McGarity keeps giving the Cowboys'
coaching staff reasons to keep him. The latest is his ability to
return punts _ a task that before Monday night he hadn't done since
before his Texas Longhorns days.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think about a guy who hadn't caught punts since high
school, and his first game is on Monday Night Football in Canton,
Ohio, at the Hall of Fame, against a left-footed punter, and he
goes out there and catches every one of them ... that's pretty
impressive,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McGarity flawlessly fielded four punts against Cleveland,
returning three of them for a 6.0-yard average. He will get more
work there Sunday at Oakland. AIKMAN'S BLINDSIDE
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman was complimentary Thursday when asked
about second-year Flozelle Adams' switch from right guard to
``protector of Aikman's blindside'' at left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't noticed his play that much, which is a good
thing. I think he's more comfortable there,'' Aikman observed.
``When you have Mark Tunei protecting your blindside for nine
years, and Larry Allen doing it for a year ... you tend to get
spoiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had to worry about that backside. And Flo knows
that I don't anticipate worrying about it this year, either.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
