<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS REACH CONTRACTS WITH TWO, TURN FOCUS TO MATVICHUK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doug Armstrong's ``To-Do'' list continues to grow shorter. But
the Stars' assistant general manager said he knows there's plenty
to accomplish before the Stars open training camp Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong took care of two potential arbitration cases in
Toronto before speaking to an arbitrator, settling a two-year deal
with Jamie Pushor and a one-year deal with Derek Plante before
returning to Texas on Thursday. He now will attempt to sign the
Stars' remaining restricted free agents, the most important of whom
is defenseman Richard Matvichuk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have moved along pretty well this summer, but we still
have a few players we need to get signed,'' Armstrong said. ``Our
goal has always been to get everyone signed before training camp,
and that's no different this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting Matvichuk under contract before training camp begins in
Vail, Colo., is the biggest challenge. In fact, it might be a
challenge to get the 26-year-old defenseman signed before the
season opener Oct. 1. Neither Armstrong nor Matvichuk's agent, Art
Breeze, would comment on potential salary figures, but one source
said the two are far apart in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk, who made $871,000 last season, is seeking a salary
similar to that of Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor's $2.5 million.
The Stars are looking more in the range of $1.5 million, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides appear to have plenty of willpower as far as waiting
is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no question in our mind that Rich is
recognized leaguewide as one of the top five defensive defensemen
in the NHL,'' Breeze said. ``When you consider that and when you
consider his ice time \Rthird on the Stars behind Derian Hatcher
and Sergei Zubov\S, Rich's value is very clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Breeze said that the negotiation ball is in the Stars' court _
that he is awaiting an offer. Armstrong said he is working on that
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What our goal is with every player is to get a contract that's
fair to both sides,'' Armstrong said. ``If either side is unhappy
with the contract, that's not good for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has plenty of experience in waiting out contract
negotiations. Mike Modano and Derian Hatcher have missed training
camp within the past two seasons. And with Pushor now under
contract and negotiations continuing with Brad Lukowich, the Stars
expect to have six strong defensemen _ Hatcher, Zubov, Sydor,
Pushor, Lukowich and Shawn Chambers _ at training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Pushor, 26, was acquired from the Atlanta Thrashers this summer
in a trade for winger Jason Botterill. A defensive defenseman who
played most of his career with the Detroit Red Wings, Pushor is
seen as a younger version of Craig Ludwig, who the Stars said they
will not re-sign. Pushor, who made $350,000 last season with the
Mighty Ducks of Anaheim, agreed to a two-year deal and surrendered
the right to have his case heard by an arbitrator. Terms of the
deal were not released.
</P>
<P>
   Plante's deal is one year for $750,000, a decrease in pay from
the $1 million he made last season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
