r a BC-SHOOTING-CLEANUP-LADN     08-13 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-CLEANUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL-WISHERS GATHER AT SITE OF RAMPAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDS, runs with SHOOTING-SUSPECT, SHOOTING-CASE, SHOOTING-COLUMN,
SHOOTING-KIDS, SHOOTING-HEAL, SHOOTING-CABBIE) 
BY ROBERT MONROE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As crews patched and painted the bullet-scarred
interior of the North Valley Jewish Community Center, well-wishers
came by bearing gifts _ brownies, religious literature or simple
good will.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching as far as the locked and guarded gates of the center
Thursday, visitors of many faiths said they were so appalled by the
acts of Buford Furrow Jr. that they were drawn to the center two
days after the rampage there that wounded three children, a teen
and a grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart brought me here,'' said Jehovah's Witness Dolly
Gerston, 74. ``I don't know anybody here but we all belong to each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerston, who normally drives past the center on Tuesdays on the
way to the grocery store, brought a purseful of Jehovah's Witness
pamphlets.
</P>
<P>
   Repair trucks entered the community center grounds throughout
the day. Iron gates were closed behind them to keep onlookers away.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Rouss, executive director of Jewish Community Centers of
Los Angeles, said that walls pockmarked by Furrow's bullets were
filled and repainted, some windows were replaced and some chairs
were fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Rouss announced that the center will reopen Monday. About 80
children, two-thirds the normal number for a Thursday, took part in
activities at the transplanted day camp. Rouss said that lack of a
swimming pool probably kept some away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some parents are still working on some issues at
home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A guard accepted gifts and allowed flowers to be laid at the
gate but the Center declined offers of help. Some visitors simply
wanted to offer support.
</P>
<P>
   Najee Ali, executive director of Project Islamic HOPE, stopped
outside the center where a shrine of flowers grew steadily
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to show our concern,'' he said. ``Even though
Jews and Muslims have differences in the Middle East, when things
like this happen, it doesn't matter what the issues are.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzie McCarthy and her mother, Janis, bore two platefuls of
baked goods as they walked into the complex where center day camp
and preschool activities have been relocated, a plot of land shared
by a temple and an Episcopal church. The mother and daughter said
they are Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my friends are Jewish and we love the Jewish
community. We wanted to show we care and we do,'' said Suzie
McCarthy, 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how anyone can say they're Christians and not
love Jews,'' Janis McCarthy said.
</P>
<P>
   Rouss said Sabbath services at 6 p.m. tonight at the center will
be ecumenical. He said the event will be a ``community gathering of
solidarity and healing'' but space will limit attendance to center
members and immediate neighbors of the Rinaldi Street complex.
</P>
<P>
   A larger event open to the entire community will take place
Sunday at 2 p.m. at Cal State University, Northridge, Rouss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a large enough place to say that evil will not win. We
will not let this man's evil stop us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Socorro Weinstein, a Catholic whose husband, Daniel, is Jewish,
said she came to the school in person because she couldn't find out
by phone when the center swimming pool would reopen. Her two
daughters Gabriella, 6, and Julietta, 2, would have gone swimming
Tuesday afternoon were it not for the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   She was told her children could swim Tuesday. She plans to be
back then despite the worry that sometimes crosses her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to follow my heart,'' she said. ``I'm really fine and I
think now we're going to be OK here.''
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in volunteering at the North Valley Jewish
Community Center are asked to call (818) 360-2211 on Monday.
Donations can be sent to Jewish Community Centers of Greater Los
Angeles, 5700 Wilshire Blvd., Suite 2705, Los Angeles, Calif.
90036.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
