r s BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     08-13 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
PENNANT RACE SHOULD STIR RANGERS' FANS TO FEVER PITCH (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Did you notice the recent cold front? I
wouldn't exactly call it frigid, but there was definitely a
cooling-off period.
</P>
<P>
   By usual standards, it was an icy reception given the Texas
Rangers during the recent two-week homestand. Where did the fans
go? What turned them off? Wasn't it hot enough for them,
baseball-wise?
</P>
<P>
   Blame it, if you like, on the triple-digit temps, but
made-in-the-shade weather in August isn't a local custom. And when
you're talking triple digits, it doesn't apply to just the weather.
The Rangers remain on pace to reach 100 wins for the season,
totally unheard of around here.
</P>
<P>
   A hot team in North Texas usually translates into smokin'
turnstiles, but ...
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers averaged only 31,000 for the 13 games of the
homestand. Crowds of 40,000-plus happened only twice. Six times,
the attendance dipped below 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   What's the problem here?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe general manager Doug Melvin inadvertently had the answer
when he was talking Thursday about his failure to pursue a trade
for veteran pitcher Kevin Appier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if I failed to take into account Appier being
re-energized by leaving Kansas City and going to a team playing for
something,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   At the major-league trading deadline on July 31, Melvin did
nothing while Appier was acquired by Oakland, where he has had two
strong starts, for a 2-0 record and a sizzling 1.20 earned-run
average.
</P>
<P>
   The recent homestand opened on the weekend of the trading
deadline. Did a passive Melvin drain a certain amount of energy
from the fans?
</P>
<P>
   Winning a division has become mundane stuff for the Rangers.
Everyone, including Melvin, wants more. But the way the Rangers'
pitching rotation is structured, it's very doubtful there can be
more in October.
</P>
<P>
   With low expectations for the coming postseason, and with
microwave heat descending upon the ballpark (only one of 13 first
pitches in the homestand came with the temperature below 94), did
the fans say to heck with it?
</P>
<P>
   Apathy appears to be the case, but we will know for sure in
another week. The next homestand has Boston for the weekend
(starting next Friday), and the Yankees on Monday through
Wednesday. If those six games don't average more than 40,000, then
the fans are definitely yawning this season away.
</P>
<P>
   Do not mistake any of this, however, for a second-guess of
Melvin being docile at the trading deadline. Even if it turns out
he did need to goose the fans, and the team, by upgrading the
rotation, you didn't read it here at the time. Therefore, I have no
second-guess privileges.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what pitchers were available, supply didn't seem to
equal demand. Plus, it did appear time to finally leave the farm
system alone and allow continued growth. Overall, Melvin did the
right thing by sitting tight on pitching trades at the deadline,
and before.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the early returns say his patience backfired.
Again, I'm not one who can second-guess on this issue, but the
facts follow:
</P>
<P>
   Besides Appier, the A's picked up Omar Olivares from the Angels,
and he's 2-0 with a 2.95 ERA in three starts. The Rangers talked
about reacquiring Darren Oliver from the Cardinals, and he's 3-2
with a 2.21 ERA in his past five starts. When Andy Pettitte's name
came up with the Yankees, everyone was scared of damaged goods. But
New York kept him, and Pettitte is 4-1 with a 3.30 ERA in his past
five starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' asking price for Chuck Finley was so steep neither
the Rangers nor Indians could land him. Finley is pitching decent,
with a 1-1 record and 4.12 ERA over six starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to say we did right or wrong,'' Melvin said,
``but for now, Olivares is the one guy we'd like to have. I thought
he was a fit here. But when the Angels wanted to package him with
(infielder) Randy Velarde, we backed off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scouted Appier for three months ``and I never got
the reports I wanted to hear,'' Melvin said, ``plus, Oakland gave
up three pitchers for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other traded pitchers, Kenny Rogers went from the A's to
the Mets. ``They never offered him to us,'' Melvin said. And Juan
Guzman went from the Orioles to the Reds. ``The Reds paid a steep
price,'' Melvin added.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Melvin is trying to drum up a waiver-wire deal for a
pitcher, ``but I can almost guarantee nothing substantial is going
to happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Rangers are close to the stretch run of what
might become the best season in franchise history. But after this
homestand, the next question is how many fans still care? nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
