<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU FACES PRESSING QUESTIONS HEADING INTO FALL DRILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Two-a-days begin bright and early this
morning at TCU. You know what that means?
</P>
<P>
   ``Twice a day, we will be asked whether we can beat Arizona,''
Horned Frogs wide receiver Cedric James quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Twice? Try 457 times. And the question is not just whether TCU
is capable of toppling Arizona, a national-championship contender.
TCU has a number of questions to be answered during two-a-days.
Coach Dennis Franchione just hopes to have them answered before
opening the season against the Wildcats on Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   With full-squad practices beginning this morning, there is no
better time than the present to get started. So here's a list of
the Top 10 questions Franchione finds himself facing as two-a-days
begin:
</P>
<P>
   NO. 10 _ WHO IS GOING TO MAKE ALL OF THE TACKLES JOE PHIPPS MADE
LAST SEASON?
</P>
<P>
   Phipps has taken his pursue-and-destroy linebacking philosophy
to Cowboys camp. So what's the big deal? Well, Phipps registered a
limb-numbing (and team-leading) 153 tackles in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to pick up the load? On his locker, junior Shannon
Brazzell has a sticker that says ``Count on me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't put it up last year because I was a young pup. I was
just following Phipps to see how he got it done,'' said Brazzell,
who started alongside Phipps last season. ``I put that up this year
because I want to be that guy. I wanted guys to know when it comes
down to it they can count on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will play alongside Brazzell is still to be determined, and
coaches will be keeping a close eye on redshirt freshman John
Turntine during two-a-days.
</P>
<P>
   NO. 9 _ WHAT SIDE OF THE BALL WILL KYLE WILLIAMS PLAY ON?
</P>
<P>
   Just call Williams the big man's version of ``Slash.'' He'll be
practicing two positions, tight end and defensive tackle. He'll
spend the first three days of two-a-days at tight end and then do a
little of both on Day 4. Franchione plans to have him settled into
one or the other before the season begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to have to guess today, I'd say he'll be a tight
end,'' Franchione said. ``But we're going to use him wherever we
need him most.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 8 _ WHAT WILL BE THIS SEASON'S BONDING THEME?
</P>
<P>
   Every team needs a cause. Last year, it was about proving the
Horned Frogs weren't as bad as their 1-10 finish in 1997. So what
is this year's team out to prove?
</P>
<P>
   ``That last year wasn't a fluke,'' Franchione said. ``We're
about to find out how much getting that point across means to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   NO. 7 _ WHO IS GOING TO BE THE BACKUP TAILBACK?
</P>
<P>
   At last check, tailback LaDainian Tomlinson wasn't Superman, so
the chances of him carrying the ball on every TCU running play
aren't good. When he goes to the sideline for a breather, who goes
in?
</P>
<P>
   ``Good question,'' Franchione said. ``We don't have an answer
for that today. We have candidates, and we have choices. Now, we
need for somebody to separate themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are junior Charles Jones and redshirt freshmen
LaTarence Dunbar and Frank Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach has said that the second tailback spot isn't taken. He
has a name put in, but it's not promised to anybody,'' Dunbar said.
``I'm going to come out during two-a-days and try to make that
backup role mine.''
</P>
<P>
   NO. 6 _ WHAT CRAZY PROMISE WILL fRANCHIONE MAKE THIS TIME
AROUND?
</P>
<P>
   During two-a-days last year, Horned Frogs punter Royce Huffman
talked Franchione into promising to bleach his hair if TCU went to
a bowl game. One Sun Bowl-berth later, Franchione's salt-and-pepper
locks were blond.
</P>
<P>
   ``They caught me at about Day 8 of two-a-days. It was one of
those things where I said yes in a weaker moment,'' said
Franchione, who isn't figuring on Huffman's late arrival for
preseason drills (he's playing minor-league baseball) to help him.
``By the time he gets here he'll be kind of feisty, and I'll be
wearing down.''
</P>
<P>
   NO. 5 _ WHO IS GOING TO BE THE LEFT CORNERBACK?
</P>
<P>
   There are two positions on TCU's defense without an experienced
player returning or ready to step in. Left cornerback is one of
them. It isn't a good one for an inexperienced player. ``It's such
a high-pressure position for us,'' defensive coordinator Gary
Patterson said. ``Our corner is on an island quite a bit. So it
takes a little bit of a special individual.'' Kendrick Patterson
was penciled in on the depth chart, but his shoulder problems have
left the race up in the air. The front-runner looks to be redshirt
freshman Jason Goss, who had a good spring, with redshirt freshman
Bo Springfield in close pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 _ CAN TCU'S DEFENSE BE AS GOOD AS IT WAS IN 1998?
</P>
<P>
   Minus 23 yards. TCU defensive tackle Shawn Worthen smiles as he
repeats Southern Cal's Sun Bowl rushing numbers to himself. Pretty
good day.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we can be more dominant,'' Worthen said. ``We're
more experienced, so now we can do more things with the defense _
blitzes, coverages. Really, I see last year as being a
steppingstone for this year.''
</P>
<P>
   NO. 3 _ CAN TCU'S PASSING OFFENSE BE BETTER THAN IT WAS IN 1998?
</P>
<P>
   Franchione isn't kidding when he says they have to get better
because they can't get much worse. How much better will depend on
what second-year quarterback Patrick Batteaux and the receiving
corps show they are capable of handling during two-a-days.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to compete, we've got to throw the ball,'' receiver
Cedric James said. ``That means I've got to step it up, and I
expect a bigger season out of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   NO. 2 _ LET'S SAY BATTEAUX GETS LOST ON HIS WAY TO AMON CARTER
STADIUM FOR TCU'S OPENER AGAINST ARIZONA. WHO WOULD START AT
QUARTERBACK?
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a No. 2 signal caller to pencil in?
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs are waiting to make sure Jeff Dover, last
season's backup, makes his grades. If so, he'd be the No. 2 against
Arizona. If not, Franchione will be looking at redshirt freshman
Sean Stilley and sophomore transfer Matt Schobel. Neither has
played a game in college. Would they be ready to play?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 15 practices during spring ball; now, compared to when
spring ball started I definitely feel better,'' Schobel said.
``What you have to realize is we have 29 practices between now and
Arizona. That's like two spring balls, so I'm sure I'll be even
more comfortable than I am now.''
</P>
<P>
   And the No. 1 question TCU needs to answer by the end of
two-a-days: Can this team beat Arizona?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they are known as a powerhouse,'' James said, ``but
this is college football. Anything can happen.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
