r s BC-BBO-ZITO-LADN-(SLANG)     08-13 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ZITO-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FAMILY ZITO: PERSPECTIVE PERFECTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Barry Zito is on the road to Oakland, his mother
is on the road to recovery and they have such a hale wind at their
backs that the inconceivable now appears indisputable:
</P>
<P>
   Zito, a former Pierce College and USC baseball standout, is
going to pitch in the big leagues and Roberta Zito will be around
to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, both mother and son took big steps on Thursday
_ Barry was promoted to the Athletics' Class AA affiliate in El
Paso, Texas, and Roberta walked without help for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Barry's progress was much easier to foresee.
</P>
<P>
   On July 11, Zito was driving a fast car, his scheduled start for
Class A Visalia Oaks a fading speck in his rear-view mirror. The
southpaw was hurrying to Cedars-Sinai Hospital, where his mother
lay with a ravaged liver, fending off death.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta, a woman of smiles and substance, had been bedridden
since January. Her body began failing her in May, a month before
Barry helped lead USC deep into the playoffs and became Oakland's
top draft pick, No. 9 overall.
</P>
<P>
   The contract that Zito, 21, signed with the Athletics in June
contained an escape clause. He was free to leave the Oaks whenever
he wanted, to go to his mother's side. That left Zito torn between
love and honor. His mother is his best friend. Her health was all
he thought about when he wasn't pitching. And yet he also felt
beholden to teammates he hardly knew.
</P>
<P>
   In late June and again in early July, Zito received telephone
calls from his older sisters, Bonnie and Sally. You better come
home, they told him. And hurry.
</P>
<P>
   So Zito hopped in his car _ the first time on a day he was
scheduled to pitch _ and burned energy faster than gasoline
worrying about the impression he was leaving behind.
</P>
<P>
   Zito didn't want his new teammates to get the wrong idea. What
if they labeled him a prima donna? He was alone with that thought
during his drives to the hospital and his family's home in the L.A.
neighborhood of Encino.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to come to a team and leave it at will,'' Zito
said. ``Then your teammates might start to think you have more pull
than the other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Zito's guilt would mutate, taking on new and grotesque shapes,
when he got to the hospital and saw his mother hooked up to all the
contraptions that were keeping her alive. Then the remorse that
washed over Zito would be along the lines of this: His mother was
going to die before he could find all the right words to tell her
how much she meant to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It crossed my mind,'' Barry said.
</P>
<P>
   Death cast a long shadow in the operating room that Roberta was
wheeled into on July 11. A compatible liver arrived by helicopter
at the hospital shortly before Barry did, barely in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every other organ in her body had pretty much given up,'' said
Zito's surgeon, Dr. Walid S. Arnaout. ``It was like a ticking
bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arnaout nearly aborted the transplant because her body
seemed too far gone for the liver to do any good. In the time it
takes to blink, Dr. Arnaout made his Solomon-like decision. He
proceeded with the eight-hour surgery anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, Roberta was able to will herself to sit up. A
few days later she was shuffling along with the aid of a walker and
Wednesday she tried to take her first step. She is due to be
discharged from the hospital on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Her son spent two days with her between starts last week.
``She's looking more and more like the same old mom,'' Barry said.
``It's kind of reassuring for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Her doctors visit her every morning and ask, ``How's our miracle
patient doing?'' They are smiling, but they aren't kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta isn't sure how to reply. She had no idea how sick she
was until her family started filling in the blanks in her memory.
The truth? She'd feel fine if she could just get out of her
hospital frock and resume her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be able to see Barry pitch,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not just a proud mother talking. You'd have to be an
opponent not to enjoy seeing Zito outfinesse batters with his curve
and changeup. Like his mother, Barry is making confetti of all his
projected timetables.
</P>
<P>
   He has a 3-0 record in eight starts with Visalia. He has struck
out 62 batters in 401/3 innings while issuing 22 walks.
</P>
<P>
   Throw out his first outing _ 22/3 innings of hard labor at San
Jose on July 2 when his mother's health was weighing heavily on his
mind _ and opposing batters are hitting .140 against Zito.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got one of the best arms I've ever seen come through
Visalia,'' said Oaks general manager Andrew Bettencourt. ``He knows
how to set up batters, he has got good control. He knows how to
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettencourt said Zito is ``definitely on the fast track.'' Word
of his promotion to Class AA came Thursday night. He isn't expected
to get a big-league call-up this fall but should compete for a spot
in the Athletics' starting rotation in spring training next March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be preoccupied with (getting called up),''
Zito said. ``It's something that's out of my control.''
</P>
<P>
   Give Zito five minutes and he'll find all kinds of faults he has
to fix. In a six-inning outing at San Bernardino last week, for
example, he gave up no earned runs but thrice had to extricate
himself from two-on, no-out jams.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday, he yielded two runs and a walk to San Jose in
the first inning before settling down.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of stuff can keep a perfectionist up at night.
</P>
<P>
   As for his 1.5 strikeouts-per-inning average, Zito advises
against reading too much into that. ``Here the hitters are really
aggressive,'' he said. ``They'll swing at some pitches that hitters
at the higher levels will lay off.''
</P>
<P>
   When Zito was drafted, his family laid off the bubbly, the
cigars and the high-fives. They couldn't bring themselves to
commemorate the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could we celebrate,'' Zito's father Joe said, ``when
Roberta was dying?''
</P>
<P>
   The Zitos were as down as you can get in the penthouse. In one
month their view has changed 180 degrees. The party they put off
planning, for fear it would turn into a wake, is on. And it
promises to be grand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
