<SLUG> BC-RAC-PRICE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NICE RACETRACK' FACES A NIP AND TUCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the folks in San Antonio heard that I was headed to the
``Star-Telegram'', the parting comments always contained something
like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a nice racetrack to cover up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Retama Park is a pit, though there is one in the
infield that they'll refill with water one of these days. It's
still a nice place to watch the races.
</P>
<P>
   More compliments can be made, but the bottom line used to judge
anyone's racing product is purses. And the money bags are three
times larger up here.
</P>
<P>
   But every time someone verbally knighted Lone Star Park at Grand
Prairie, they did so without looking at the fine print. It has not
even been three weeks since Lone Star completed its thoroughbred
season, and the fine print has filled a couple of chapters.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, you've got a nice racetrack up here. But what's going on
during this off-season could have an effect on how racing goes when
the thoroughbreds come back to Lone Star in April.
</P>
<P>
   When racing got started at Lone Star in 1997, it was like the
place was a new Arlington Park, an attractive facility offering
quality purses in some of racing's prime months. Well, Arlington
International Racecourse, which closed the year before Lone Star
opened, will be back next year near Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   They're talking about $300,000 a day in purses up there (Lone
Star offered about $220,000 this year). Though Lone Star general
manager Corey Johnsen says almost all the top trainers at Lone Star
will return next year, things are serious enough that the track
announced a 10 percent purse increase for 2000 before this year's
season was finished. That's the earliest a purse determination has
ever been trumpeted around Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   It's still unclear when Arlington will be racing. But a schedule
that would find Lone Star and Arlington overlapping for all but the
first three weeks of Lone Star's season isn't inconceivable.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Louisiana Downs, and that situation's more unclear.
No one really has a true handle on how much purses can be bumped
with the installation of slot machines next year.
</P>
<P>
   Slots shot purses through the roof at Delaware Park and Prairie
Meadows. But Louisiana Downs had video poker machines for seven
years and purses moved mostly sideways.
</P>
<P>
   What's on the table right now, from Louisiana Downs or
Arlington, isn't enough to go ringing the fire bell.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, this off-season of change is turning out to be a nip
here and a tuck there. Maybe Arlington and Louisiana Downs might
nip at Lone Star's racing product, but other things could happen to
tuck some horses and trainers back into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   The word that the Fair Grounds is bumping the purse for the
Louisiana Derby from $500,000 to $750,000 could ripple positively
toward Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   With such a purse _ only the Santa Anita Derby and Florida Derby
can match it among the Kentucky Derby preps _ a superstar likely
will win it and head somewhere other than Lone Star for a final
Derby prep. But more horses will be in New Orleans running in
allowance races and other stakes events. If they're unsuccessful in
their Louisiana Derby chase, they might be brought here.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not a bad thing if you remember the comments from
Chris Candies when he brought T.B. Track Star to the Lone Star
Derby after training him through the winter at Fair Grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather come here with a good allowance horse from Fair
Grounds than a stakes horse from Oaklawn,'' Candies said.
</P>
<P>
   T.B. Track Star won the Lone Star Derby at odds surpassing 20-1.
He added to Lone Star's stakes program when he was kept here to
race.
</P>
<P>
   It's those sorts of stories that prompt people to say ``You've
got a nice racetrack to cover up there.''
SPOTLIGHT ON... D. WAYNE LUKAS
</P>
<P>
   When it was announced that D. Wayne Lukas would be inducted into
the National Museum of Racing and Hall of Fame, it wouldn't have
surprised many in the horse racing world to hear Lukas respond
``about damn time.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Lukas has been taking the high road, which ended with
his induction ceremony Monday in Saratoga Springs, N.Y. Until this
year, Lukas disputed the eligibility requirements, which hold that
a trainer must have handled thoroughbreds for 25 consecutive years.
It's been documented that Lukas began training thoroughbreds more
than 30 years ago, but some years were broken up by his attention
to quarter horses.
</P>
<P>
   Though Lukas sometimes has referred to his critics in the media
as ``cockroaches,'' none of that was heard Monday. He was
introduced by six former or current assistants: Jeff Lukas, Randy
Bradshaw, Mark Hennig, Kiaran McLaughlan, Todd Pletcher and Dallas
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys have propped me up and carried me so many times, and
I'm not the easiest guy to work for,'' Lukas said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of quarter horses, Lukas joined with prominent
thoroughbred owners Will Farish and Eddie Gaylord to spend $500,000
on a yearling quarter horse filly by First Down Dash out of
champion Corona Chick to top the sale at an auction in California
this week. On the same day, Lukas signed a sales ticket on behalf
of Satish Sanan to buy a thoroughbred filly by Capote at the
Saratoga summer sale.
QUICK HITS STRONACH'S BINGE CONTINUES
</P>
<P>
   Frank Stronach, a Canada-based auto parts magnate whose success
as a horse owner includes 1997 Belmont Stakes winner Touch Gold and
1998 Breeders' Cup Classic champion Awesome Again, apparently has
bought another racetrack or two. Several news sources indicate
Stronach has agreed to purchase Thistledown near Cleveland and
Remington Park in Oklahoma City from the Edward J. DeBartolo Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Stronach has purchased Santa Anita for more
than $120 million and Gulfstream Park for more than $80 million. No
purchase price has been reported on Thistledown and Remington.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Retama Park investors agreed to buy Thistledown,
Remington and Louisiana Downs from the DeBartolo family for about
$70 million, but the deal fell apart when the Retama investors
couldn't attract additional partners.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Downs is considered by many to be the most attractive
investment possibility of the DeBartolo family's generally
unattractive portfolio of racetracks. It has a minimal debt load
and is the only DeBartolo track with expanded gambling (video poker
and slots).
</P>
<P>
   So expect a Thistledown-Remington deal to extract less than $40
million of Stronach's loot.
</P>
<P>
   Stronach's seemingly bottomless barrel of money has been dipped
into by others in the past week. His publicly traded auto parts
company, from which his racetrack acquisitions are a spinoff, has
hit a 52-week trading low. And his former trainer, Patrick Byrne,
reached an out-of-court settlement to obtain more than $300,000 for
training and other fees. DATING IN ILLINOIS
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the three Chicagoland thoroughbred tracks have
until Sept. 21 to come to an agreement over race dates for next
year. If the overlapping dates can't be resolved by that time, the
Illinois Racing Board will mediate.
</P>
<P>
   Sportsman's Park has applied for a spring season (March 1
through May 13) that would conflict with Arlington (May 1 through
Oct. 31). And Hawthorne (Sept. 9 through Dec. 23) would conflict
with Arlington. Sportsman's also has applied for a fall meeting
(Nov. 2 through Dec. 31). nn
</P>
</TEXT>
