<SLUG> BC-FURROW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENTAL-HEALTH EXPERTS CAUTION AGAINST SAYING SYSTEM FAILED FURROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HEATH FOSTER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Family friends and advocates for the mentally ill on
Thursday questioned whether Buford O. Furrow Jr. got the treatment
he needed from Washington state's mental-health system.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Merrill, a friend and neighbor of the Furrows in Olympia
for 24 years, said Furrow's father is angry that his son didn't get
closer supervision from mental health professionals after his
release from prison in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are disappointed that (the system) didn't give him more
help,'' Merrill said. ``If a person doesn't want to take their
medicine, they won't. That is what his dad thinks, that he didn't
take his medication, and he sort of went off.''
</P>
<P>
   But because Furrow's mental-health records remain confidential
under state law, it's not clear that there is more that authorities
could have reasonably been expected to do to prevent Furrow from
allegedly launching his hateful attack on a Los Angeles-area Jewish
day care center Tuesday. Furrow has also been charged in the
killing of a postal worker after the day-care shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Just a week before the attack, Furrow made his regularly
scheduled appointment in Olympia with his community corrections
officer, who concluded Furrow was meeting all the conditions of
release. Officer Pat Gosney concluded that Furrow had been staying
away from alcohol, guns, and the psychiatric workers he had
attacked nine months before, and was consistently taking his
medications. Random drug testing ordered by Gosney had confirmed
those prescription drugs were in his system in July, Department of
Corrections spokesman Veltry Johnson said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that corrections staff did not search Furrow's home
or car for guns or alcohol, as they can legally do.
</P>
<P>
   Critics Thursday charged that given Furrow's mental-health
history, the court also should have ordered intensive mental-health
treatment after his release. The King County Superior Court judge
who handled his case, Harriet Cody, did not order such treatment.
She could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty clear that he came out of the King County
Jail and fell through the cracks,'' said Tom Richardson, Washington
president of the National Alliance for the Mentally Ill. ``Mentally
ill people on medications need supervision. There is an ignorance
on the part of the court in thinking that you can just require
someone to take their medication and that is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   But mental-health professionals Thursday cautioned the public
from jumping to the conclusion that Furrow, a card-carrying member
of the Aryan Nations Church, allegedly sprayed the day-care center
with gunfire because of mental illness. Without having seen his
mental health records, they said it's dangerous to surmise his
violence was a result of his lack of treatment, or could have been
prevented if he had been confined for longer in a psychiatric
hospital, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not appropriate for everyone who demonstrates dangerous
behavior to be in a hospital,'' said psychiatrist Ira Klein,
director of civil adult services at Western State Hospital.
``Thousands of people commit violent crimes, and they aren't
schizophrenics.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that psychiatric hospitals can only treat people for
major mental illnesses, and not hold them because they are racist
or express a desire to do violence against certain groups.
</P>
<P>
   Because of patient confidentiality rules, state authorities
cannot release the files they compiled during the seven months
Furrow spent in two state psychiatric facilities and in a county
jail with a staff of psychologists and psychiatrists.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow's only run-in with police in Washington stemmed from his
attempt to check himself into a Kirkland psychiatric facility last
October.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow told psychiatric workers then that he had been
fantasizing about opening fire at the Alderwood Mall and killing
his estranged wife and her friends. But his plea for help turned
violent when he pulled a knife on psychiatric workers who refused
to give him back his car keys. He only dropped the switchblade when
a county sheriff's deputy pulled his gun.
</P>
<P>
   After his arrest on a Wednesday, the county jail's
well-respected psychiatric unit quickly spotted Furrow as someone
in need of a thorough evaluation. A jail psychologist pushed
deputies to file charges quickly so he could be held for that
evaluation. Deputies did move fast, closing the case on Friday, but
Furrow managed to post bond before prosecutors filed the charges
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he and his parents recognized he needed help, and they
took him to Harborview Medical Center for an evaluation, according
to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after he was charged with second-degree assault, he was
taken to Western State Hospital in Steilacoom for further
evaluation and treatment, Dan Donohoe, spokesman for the King
County Prosecutor's Office, confirmed yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But Furrow was not sent to Western State for an evaluation of
whether he was competent to stand trial, Klein said, and therefore
he was not judged to be insane at the time he assaulted the
psychiatric workers in Kirkland.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one other reason the hospital could have taken him
for treatment: He had been committed because he was deemed a danger
to himself or the community.
</P>
<P>
   Klein could not legally comment on what treatment Furrow
received. But he said the hospital's goal is to evaluate patients,
stabilize them, and then return them to the community supported
with ongoing treatment and medication.
</P>
<P>
   One Dec. 11, Furrow was sent from Western State back to the
county jail.
</P>
<P>
   Klein cautioned that a decision that a patient is stable enough
to be returned to the security of the jail, where their treatment
and medication can be supervised by psychiatric professionals, is
not the same as deciding the person is ready to be released into
the community.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 17, Furrow was arraigned on the assault charges.
Initially, Furrow's defense attorney, Leona Thomas, entered a
not-guilty plea by reason of insanity.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, Thomas' request for more expert evaluation of
Furrow was granted. But the portion of his file containing his
mental health record has been sealed by the court. Later, Furrow
withdrew the insanity plea and entered a guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   Both Klein and Sherry Storms, the Mental Health Ombudsman for
the county, said mentally ill people often decide to plead guilty
to criminal charges because they realize that their stay in a
psychiatric facility would keep them confined even longer. But
neither had specific knowledge of why Furrow changed his plea.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow was released from jail on May 21, and met with his
probation officer in Olympia on June 16, July 6, July 20 and Aug.
3.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow's parents last saw their son on Saturday. Furrow's
mother, Monnie, is ill, and broke down upon hearing the news of
Furrow's arrest, Merrill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what bothers his dad the most was that he shot all
those little kids. He loves little kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporters Sarah Skidmore and Elaine
Porterfield contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
