<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5856 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-FURROW-NORTHWEST-ESSA     08-13 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURROW-NORTHWEST-ESSAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE HAVE BEGUN TO EXPECT THE HATE CRIMINAL TO BE FROM THE WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JESS WALTER  
 SPECIAL TO THE SEATTLE POST-INTELLIGENCER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The satellite news trucks have finished dusting up the gravel
ribbon that leads to Buford Furrow's old house.
</P>
<P>
   Notebooks are full of stories of Furrow's gun-nut racism and
cameras with tight shots of the ``Keep Out'' signs marking his
ex-wife's driveway. After some debate, reporters have decided
against calling her mobile home and outbuildings a ``compound.''
</P>
<P>
   The ubiquitous live shot _ ``it was here that the suspect in
yesterday's shooting may have developed his racist beliefs'' _ was
done four miles away, in Metaline Falls, Wash., which presented
itself rustic and postcard-pretty, home to 260 people who get along
just fine in this rivercut seam of Colville National Forest and
Selkirk Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   On TV and in person, these people come across as disquietingly
familiar. Friendly and easy-going. When they say Furrow kept to
himself, it is a fair compliment. Some of them have no trouble
describing Furrow's former wife, Debbie Mathews, in one breath as
``a great lady, a wonderful mother'' and with the very next saying
that she believes that Jews are the spawn of Satan.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to be surprised anymore at this paradoxical tolerance
of the intolerant.
</P>
<P>
   And the worst part is: This all feels routine. We have begun to
expect the hate criminal to be from the West.
</P>
<P>
   After 18 years of bombings and murders and bank robberies and
cross burnings and racial pamphleteering, the details have begun to
blur into a single story of the West as a place where hatred
blooms.
</P>
<P>
   The places blur too, towns so striking it makes you ache a
little bit, built along cold-running streams and deep mountain
lakes. Even the people start to blur, their honest and admirable
defense of their towns as good places seeming less and less
believable.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the grocery store in Metaline Falls, where a CNN crew
groused about the lack of cell phone service, two local women made
eye contact and shared a sad, knowing smile, recalling the first
time a white supremacist was traced back to this town, back in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said one woman, ``here we go again.''
</P>
<P>
   She might as well be speaking for the entire Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Here we go again puzzling over this region's reputation as a
haven for neo-Nazis, white separatists, Phineas Priests, Identity
Christians, skinheads and the just plain government-weary. Here we
go again looking for explanations that sound too much like excuses
_ the accident of open space, our ethnic homogeny, too much John
Wayne. Here we go again trying to understand how someone like
Buford O. ``Neal'' Furrow could believe he was called to shoot
Jewish children.
</P>
<P>
   Here we go again looking for reasons in the unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Start with space. There are great open chunks of it in the
Northwest, from Southern Oregon to Eastern Washington to Northern
Idaho to Western Montana, places on the map where you can put your
finger and barely cover a town.
</P>
<P>
   People drawn to white supremacy are usually running from society
and feel disenfranchised. They are people who, ironically, seek
refuge in the small-town values of the West.
</P>
<P>
   The religion of the Aryan Nations and other groups is called
Christian Identity and is a mishmash of paranoia, solipsism and
Old-Testament fervor whose theology can be boiled down to the
belief that white American Anglo-Saxons are the true Israelites and
that Jews are descendants of Cain, the result of Satan's seduction
of Eve.
</P>
<P>
   It is a religion of hate, certainly, but also of uncompromising
fear. Christian Identity followers believe we are in a time of
approaching Apocalypse as described in the book of Revelation, and
that it will be manifested as a great racial holy war in which they
will have to defend their families from marauding hordes of
non-Israelites. That's why many followers of Christian Identity
seek mountain retreats in the woods, looking for ``defensible''
houses.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the myth of the West itself, which says that the
taming of the wilderness is that thing which is uniquely American,
what the dean of Western writers Wallace Stegner called ``the
challenge against which our character as a people was formed.''
</P>
<P>
   That appeals heavily to people who see America as a holy land
defending its borders against other races, a place where the
dominant cultural tool is the gun. Gun ownership is practically a
sacrament of Christian Identity churches, survivalism the dominant
way of life.
</P>
<P>
   But the underlying reason for the flourishing of hate groups in
the Northwest may lie with one man.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, a Lockheed engineer and budding white supremacist named
Richard Butler left California for a ``defensible'' 20-acre parcel
of land near Hayden Lake, just north of Coeur d'Alene. He began
touting the Inland Northwest as a white homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Butler's Aryan Nations Church would end up becoming the premier
hate group in the country and a sort of petri dish for neo-Nazis
and others to grow into virulent criminals. Many of the hate crimes
in or originating in the Northwest can be traced to Butler,
spiraling out from him like a string of Old Testament begats.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with The Order, a group of Aryan Nations followers who
formed their own terrorist group in 1984 and killed Jewish radio
talk-show host Alan Berg and pulled a series of bank robberies
meant to fund a larger race war.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, countless groups and individuals have spun off from
Aryan Nations and used The Order as a template for committing
crimes, from murder to robbery to bombings to the most recent _
Furrow's shooting spree this week at a Jewish community center in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, Furrow worked as a security guard at
Butler's compound and was married by Butler to Debbie Mathews, the
widow of Robert Mathews, the founder of The Order who was killed in
a shootout with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents and those tracking hate groups say the
82-year-old Butler is no longer a key figure among the radical
right, but his legacy remains intact.
</P>
<P>
   When, in 1991, an up-and-coming Christian Identity preacher
named David Barley looked to move his America's Promise Ministries
out of Arizona, his group ended up looking in Idaho and Montana,
and ultimately located in Sandpoint, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first impression was good,'' Barley wrote to his followers
when he found his new home in Idaho in 1991, ``and once we looked
around the area (we) saw many positive aspects ... including very
friendly and mostly non-Babylonian government hungry people.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a man called Barley's protege, Jay Merrill, led a
group of three men who bombed an abortion clinic and a newspaper
office and robbed banks in Spokane. There are people like that
everywhere, of course. The Southern Poverty Law Center recently
listed eight active hate groups in Idaho, 10 in Washington, 35 in
California, 48 in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But that's little consolation to the people in Metaline Falls or
to anyone in the West, who must defend their home as a tolerant
place to live and who will hold their collective breath every time
a loner ventures out to commit a crime based on hate.
</P>
<P>
   Jess Walter is the author of ``Every Knee Shall Bow,'' a 1995
book about the case of white separatist Randy Weaver. A free-lance
writer and journalist in Spokane, he also is the co-author of ``In
Contempt,'' Christopher Darden's account of the O.J. Simpson murder
trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
