<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-KIDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING VICTIMS' RECOVERY PROGRESSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TROY ANDERSON, LISA VAN PROYEN AND DOMINIC BERBEO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two days after a gunman's bullets tore into Mindy
Finkelstein's leg, the 16-year-old left the hospital, raising her
arms triumphantly to show the world she was healing from the
hate-fueled attack.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting back tears, Mindy's father read a statement expressing
his gratitude for the community's support following Tuesday's
shooting rampage at the North Hills Jewish Community Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are thrilled that Mindy's recovery is going well and that
we can now go home as a family,'' said David Finkelstein, standing
beside his daughter at Kaiser Permanente Medical Center in Woodland
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our prayers and thoughts are with the victims _ the other
victims and their families,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old James Zidell also was released from the hospital
Thursday, and he spent the day with his wounded leg propped up on a
pillow while he sucked lollipops and played with Beanie Babies,
gifts from police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing really, really good. He's fine and happy,'' his
mother said. ``It'll take a while to heal. He'll have to get on
crutches.''
</P>
<P>
   She figures her son will be healed in a couple weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to move on and just act normal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other children _ 5-year-old Benjamin Kadish and 6-year-old
Joshua Stepakoff _ remained hospitalized Thursday, although Joshua
was expected to be discharged Friday. Kadish was the most seriously
injured and remains in critical but stable condition.
</P>
<P>
   North Valley Jewish Community Center receptionist Isabelle
Shalometh, 68, was released from a local hospital Tuesday night
with wounds to her back and arm.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the San Fernando Valley, encouragement for the
victims poured in Thursday, as police officers delivered flowers
and gigantic get-well cards from the LAPD's Devonshire Division,
which responded to Tuesday's attack in Granada Hills. A company was
going to give the Jewish day-care school with 250 kids teddy bear
T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the three children and two staff members shot at the
community center, Benjamin Kadish's wounds were the worst and his
recovery will take the longest. He was struck in the stomach and
leg, and he remains at Childrens Hospital Los Angeles and his vital
signs remained strong.
</P>
<P>
   His neighbors said they missed the youngster's vibrance and
recalled his smile and love for his puppy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kadish's children play catch with their dad,'' recalled
neighbor Erin Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors of Benjamin banded together to collect money to help
his family with medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very nice. My next door neighbor called me
(Wednesday) night to get the neighborhood together to help the
family,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors are going door-to-door asking for money donations for
the boy and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole neighborhood is concerned,'' said Sherlene Bamossy,
a next-door neighbor to the Kadish family. ``It's a terrible shock.
I can hardly believe it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Another neighbor, Gladis Murray, said knowing one of the victims
brings the horror painfully close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, we thought it was close to home in Granada Hills,
and now, we find out that it's our neighbor. It's real, real close.
We're still in shock,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Another 6-year-old boy who was shot, Joshua Stepakoff, was
expected to be released from the hospital Friday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Porter Ranch youngster was wounded in his left calf and hip,
and he was listed in good condition after the bullet to his hip was
removed at Childrens Hospital Los Angeles, said Steve Rutledge,
hospital spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's neighbors, Keith and Yolanda Douglas, said the boy's
parents have been coming home at 11 p.m. and leave first thing in
the morning to see their son at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stepakoffs are a very warm and loving family,'' Keith
Douglas said, adding the boy's father works for the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory and the mother is in the health-care field.
</P>
<P>
   The Douglases left a ``Welcome Home Josh'' note and a teddy bear
on the Stepakoff's front door.
</P>
<P>
   They described Joshua as a very bright, inquisitive, friendly,
sensitive child who is always riding his bicycle, playing catch or
in-line skating with his older brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them are very close,'' Keith Douglas said. ``It's hard
to imagine two parents who are more concerned with the best
interests of their children in trying to protect them. If something
like this could happen, especially to them, it's sad and
mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Finkelstein, a day camp counselor and Chatsworth High School
senior, left Kaiser Permanente Woodland Hills Medical Center in a
wheelchair, unable to walk because of gunshot wounds to her right
leg.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother said Mindy was mainly concerned about the other
children who were hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's doing OK, and she's worried about the kids,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Finkelstein said that his family's prayers and thoughts
were with the families of the other victims and thanked the
authorities for their ``quick response'' and ``incredible medical
care.''
</P>
<P>
   He also expressed thanks for the ``tremendous outpouring of love
and support'' from friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   A hospital spokesperson said Mindy is expected to make a full
recovery within a couple of weeks, and had already begun physical
therapy earlier Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
