<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-CLASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASH CURB REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The first MLS Kraft Derby revived the
playoff hopes of the San Jose Clash but went far in dampening the
Revolution's chances. The Clash took a 2-1 victory over the
Revolution Thursday &UR;  &LR; night in a battle of teams owned by Kraft
Sports Group.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Revolution's fifth consecutive defeat, leaving them
in fifth place in the Eastern Conference with 18 points in 21
games. It was particularly discouraging since the Clash had only
two previous regulation-time victories.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution started aggressively and imposed their pressing
tactics on the Clash. Mike Burns and Ted Chronopoulos advanced from
the back to create offensive opportunities, and Paul Keegan
injected spirit into the attack from midfield.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clash remained composed and the Revolution seemed to
lose faith in the second half. Keegan departed with a right knee
ligament injury late in the first half and Ivan McKinley left with
a hamstring injury early in the second half. And the Revolution
struggled to maintain their edge.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Clash only tied the score on a corner kick, which was
saved by goalkeeper Jeff Causey, replacing Walter Zenga (knee),
before being kicked into the net by Causey in the eighth minute of
the second half. The Revolution continued to press forward, but
they seemed more desperate than the Clash.
</P>
<P>
   Mauricio Wright brought composure to the Clash defense, parrying
crosses and calmly playing the ball out of the back.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution felt compelled to attack at full speed,
becoming predictable and causing their own downfall by failing to
compensate when defenders went forward.
</P>
<P>
   Former US national team midfielder Dario Brose scored the
deciding goal on a swift counterattack in the 77th minute.
Revolution defender Mario Gori, who played the second half with a
broken left hand, had advanced into the offensive end, and the
Revolution failed to compensate as Eddie Lewis and Scott Bower
played the ball forward through the center of the field to Brose,
who ran in alone on Causey and slotted a shot into the right side
of the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have been working at 200 percent, now I'll have to work
at 300 percent,'' Zenga said. ``We have to find a solution
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution were discouraged after the match, but can revive
their chances with games against Tampa Bay Wednesday, at San Jose
Aug. 21, and at the MetroStars Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seemed to lose faith in ourselves in the second half,''
Keegan said. ``After they tied the score, it was the old attitude
of here we go again. In the first half we played together as a
team, but it didn't seem like that in the second half. Now we have
to just stay together as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronopoulos scored in the sixth minute, the residue of the
Revolution's pressing tactics. Mike Burns intercepted a clearance
and Keegan took a defender to the end line and crossed just over
Chronopoulos. McKinley recovered possession, crossed again, and
this time Chronopoulos glanced a header past goalkeeper Joe Cannon.
</P>
<P>
   John Harkes and Joe-Max Moore had close calls on free kicks in
the first half. Causey was lured out of position often in the first
half, but San Jose could not take advantage. And after the tying
goal, the Revolution visibly faltered.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, there was a change in attitude in our
guys,'' Clash coach Brian Quinn said. ``We started winning the
50-50 balls. The players decided they wanted to play for themselves
and for pride.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
