<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ACURA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT CRUISES BY HUBER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Commuting from Newport Beach to
Manhattan Country Club, Lindsay Davenport spent more time on the
405 freeway Thursday than in her match.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't mind the lengthy commute as she welcomed herself back
in style to Southern California, its colossal freeway system and
cellular-phone-wielding tennis crowd. Davenport beat Anke Huber
6-2, 6-2 in 58 minutes in the second round of the Acura Classic in
Manhattan Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The smooth victory was exactly what the Acura Classic's
defending champ and top seed needed. This is her third California
tournament in three weeks. She became so fatigued from her tennis
schedule that she requested to start the tournament Thursday, and
tournament officials complied. So after getting a bye as one of the
top four seeds, her victory completed the tournament's second
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win this easily, to have an easy match for my first match
really helped me,'' Davenport said. ``I wanted to serve well, hit a
lot of first serves in and not allow her to get on the offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport's game plan worked. Huber, whose serve was shaky
throughout the match, never had a chance. The 24-year-old German
broke Davenport once to pull to 2-2 in the first set. Davenport
then won the next eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport hasn't just been busy on the court. Earlier this week,
she moved from ``Newport Beach to Newport Beach, about two miles.''
Her new house is full of boxes and she's spent any spare time
visiting friends and family in her old neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Move'' is the operative word with Davenport. The 6-foot-2{,
175-pound, 23-year-old has improved her quickness and speed, but
her footwork still is the weakest part of her game.
</P>
<P>
   Huber and Davenport are power players. Since Davenport is one of
the most powerful and steady players on the WTA Tour, Huber's game
played into Davenport's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to try to stay aggressive,'' Huber said. ``There is
nothing more I can do. You have to serve well and return well.''
</P>
<P>
   That is where Huber's strategy is befuddling. Huber, who is 1-9
against Davenport, didn't have the finesse needed to keep Davenport
off balance. Huber did try a few drop shots but not nearly enough
to any damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a pretty good record against Anke Huber and Mary
Pierce,'' Davenport said. ``I don't know why I like the challenge
of hitting against someone like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, fighting Davenport with power, as Huber and Pierce do,
usually is counterproductive. A quick and crafty player, such as
top-ranked Martina Hingis, has a better chance. The two could be
heading to a rematch of last year's Acura Classic final, won by
Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Although she lost to Venus Williams in the semifinals of a WTA
stop in Carlsbad last week, Davenport hasn't been disappointed in
her game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great summer, and so far I haven't felt any
pressure,'' she said. ``Winning Wimbledon really helped take away
the pressure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
