<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEGMENT OF PIPELINE CLOSED AFTER BLAST MAY STAY CLOSED FOR MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLINGHAM, Wash. _ The northern section of fuel pipeline that
ruptured in June and killed three people may remain closed for
months and even into next year, federal regulators indicated
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The line closed after the June 10 accident. Then the federal
Office of Pipeline Safety ordered the Olympic Pipe Line Co. to keep
the 37 miles of pipeline from Cherry Point to northern Skagit
County closed pending the results of tests and implementation of
safety improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators strengthened their control of Olympic earlier this
week, imposing new inspection requirements on the Renton-based
company and ordering it to report any significant changes planned
for the pipeline. The pipeline sections from northern Skagit County
to Portland continue to operate.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley Coyner, who heads the Office of Pipeline Safety, told
reporters Thursday that much more needs to be known before Olympic
can open that northern section.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to allow it to reopen without the facts,'' she
said. ``We're not going to open that line before we are comfortable
the line is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Regulators must analyze data from internal inspections of
Olympic's pipeline in 1996 and 1997, she said. Those inspections,
done by a device known as a smart pig, showed more than 250
anomalies, though the company considered most insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic spokeswoman Maggie Brown said the company has provided
inspection data. But she said the company is still working out the
parameters of what Coyner indicated is vital information: a surge
analysis, which will focus on pressure in the line.
</P>
<P>
   On June 10, a valve in Skagit County intended to relieve excess
pressure apparently malfunctioned, increasing pressure up the line
to the spot of the rupture in the Whatcom Creek watershed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing data, Olympic had weeks of digging
ahead of it. This week, federal regulators ordered Olympic to dig
up and inspect any section of pipeline from Whatcom County to
Renton that may show signs from previous internal inspections of
outside damage.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility under investigation in the June 10 accident is
that construction work for Bellingham water lines may have damaged
the fuel pipeline several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That order means Olympic faces ``a dig a day,'' said Chris
Hoidal, who directs the Western region of the Office of Pipeline
Safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the dig-and-inspect order applies only to Olympic's
16-inch line from Whatcom County to Renton. The company also has a
parallel 20-inch line that runs from Skagit County to Renton, a
main line that continues after Renton to Portland and several
lateral lines, including one through the Rainier Valley and Beacon
Hill in Seattle, another to Sea-Tac Airport and a third to
refineries in Anacortes.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on what is found on the 16-inch line, the order could
be expanded to other sections of the pipeline, Hoidal said.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators' decision to let the pipeline reopen may also
hinge on the investigation by the National Transportation Safety
Board. That investigation may not be complete until next year,
officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hall, NTSB chairman, said the fact-gathering part of the
investigation may be done in January. Then there may be
congressional hearings on the Bellingham accident, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   After its factual report is done, the NTSB will turn to
analyzing what it has found and conclude what caused the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB likely will issue recommendations to the industry and
regulators to prevent similar accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB is:
</P>
<P>
   _Working on pressure tests to try to determine what the pressure
in the line at the point and time of rupture was.
</P>
<P>
   _Preparing to scrutinize data obtained from Olympic's computers.
</P>
<P>
   _Setting up the procedures to test the damaged section of pipe
and the surge relief valve in Skagit County that may have
malfunctioned and increased pressure upstream.
</P>
<P>
   _Trying to arrange interviews with contractors who worked on the
water pipes near the Olympic line.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the investigation is still in the ``Joe Friday
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing you've got to do is get the facts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall and Coyner were in Bellingham on Thursday to tour the site
of the pipeline accident and meet with city officials. Each also
spent more than a hour meeting with the families of the three
people killed: two 10-year-old boys and an 18-year-old man.
</P>
<P>
   David Beninger, a lawyer for the parents of the 10-year-olds,
said the families found the meetings reassuring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
