<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5867 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MISSIONARY-AZR &LR;      08-13 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSIONARY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREED MISSIONARY SPEAKS FOR FIRST TIME ON ORDEAL IN SOUTHERN
RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a marathon against death, but God was on his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many, many times I felt like I was just on the absolute edge
of life and death,'' said Herb Gregg, 52, a Mesa missionary held
hostage in southern Russia for nearly eight months. ``I desperately
wanted to be pulled back from that edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg, who described his ordeal for the first time publicly
Thursday night, said he took solace in prayer and the Scripture he
has memorized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeremiah 33:3 says, `Call on me and I will answer thee and
show you great and mighty things which thou knoweth not,' '' Gregg
said. ``It's actually a challenge by God to pray and ask for great
things. So I did. I asked for my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked God for four other things: That his hand would not be
cut off; that he would not be sent to a death camp; that the ransom
would be paid; and that he would be released.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg spent 230 days in a dim, 6- by 9-foot room in the barracks
of Chechen rebels seeking money for weapons to use against Moscow's
troops. He had only the clothes he was wearing, little to eat, a
thin mat to sleep on and rare human contact.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg was released June 29 after Russian Interior Ministry
troops freed him. He still doesn't know all the details of his
release, only that his captors were still discussing whether he
should live or die on the day of his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the main reason I'm alive is that God just pulled me
right out of there,'' Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife were reunited and spent some time in Europe so
Herb could rest and they could reconnect. He quietly returned to
Arizona in early July to be reunited with his two children, Jason
Gregg and Amy Glover, who is expecting twins.
</P>
<P>
   He's free of nightmares, he said, but will need time to regain
his strength. He's put back on 30 of the 40 pounds he lost but
still appears thin and tired. His finger, severed as part of a
ransom demand, is healing nicely and no longer is bandaged. He can
walk but wears down after 20 minutes or so.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Linda, have been missionaries in Brazil,
Portugal and then Russia for more than 20 years. They expect to
return to missionary work in the future, but Herb Gregg said he
isn't sure about returning to Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's appearance at Scottsdale Bible Church was Gregg's
first in public since his release, when he spoke briefly with
reporters and said to tell his captors ``that God really loves
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels' two goals in capturing him were to convert him to
their extremist form of Islam and to obtain money for weapons,
Gregg said. They had selected him as a target for teaching because
he taught Christianity in an Islamic city, he said. They watched
his comings and goings and knew he would be leaving the orphanage
after a basketball practice that Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   When he would not convert, the kicking began and the talk of
cutting off his hand. At one point, he laid his hand on the towel,
fully expecting it to be cut off, but his captors changed their
minds at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   His captors would ask him why he didn't pray, bowing down five
times a day like they did. He said he did pray. They would tell him
that God is one. He would reply that God is love. He has forgiven
his captors, he said, and prays for them and their salvation.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he tape-recorded a ransom plea for $3 million, and
on April 12, the kidnappers videotaped him as they cut off part of
a right finger and repeated their demand.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Gregg spoke briefly Thursday of the prayers of hundreds of
thousands of people around the world who supported her. She got
letters of encouragement from people in countries she didn't know
existed and shared a story of one small girl who prayed every day
that the ``bad men would let Herb go.'' When the girl's father told
her of the release, the girl said, ``It was because I prayed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Greggs are missionaries with The Evangelical Alliance
Mission, or TEAM, based in Wheaton, Ill. The organization's 1,000
missionaries work in 40 regions of the world. The Greggs taught
English at the university in Makhachkala, the crime-plagued capital
of the republic of Dagestan, coached youth sports and visited
orphanages.
</P>
<P>
   Church of the Redeemer in Mesa and Scottsdale Bible Church are
among the churches that have sponsored their missionary work. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
