<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS ENDS SKID, READY FOR PETE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ The losing streak wasn't compatible to
one of the woeful Clippers terrible skids. But Serena Williams
clipped a losing streak, even though she didn't know of its
existence.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in five attempts, Williams beat Arantxa
Sanchez-Vicario. Williams controlled the match, winning 6-2, 6-3
Thursday night in the quarterfinals of the Acura Classic at
Manhattan Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   No. 6 Williams comically tried to deny she was on a four-match
losing streak to No. 4 Sanchez-Vicario. One loss she said was due
to ``young age.'' Another was because she pulled out with an
injury. Eventually, she conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know,'' Williams said. ``I didn't know I was down
4-0.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams set the tone early, breaking Sanchez-Vicario in the
Spaniard's first service game. Sanchez-Vicario briefly looked as if
she could turn the match around by breaking Williams' serve to open
the second set. But Williams responded with a break in the next
game and four games later in the second set.
</P>
<P>
   Williams could face Martina Hingis, the No. 1 player in the
world, in the semifinals, but she's not concerned with who her
opponent will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if I play Hingis or Pete (Sampras),'' she said.
``It really doesn't matter to me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Zvereva injures ankle: Natasha Zvereva strained her right
ankle and was forced to retire from her match. No. 7 Barbara Schett
had won the first set 6-2, but Zvereva led 4-2 in the second set
when she left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I won the match,'' Schett said. ``I wasn't very
satisfied with the way I played.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Martinez advances: Conchita Martinez advanced against Detroit
native Corina Morariu 7-5, 6-2. Morariu injured her right elbow
during the match. It was evaluated as a strain.
</P>
<P>
   __ The next best thing: Lisa Raymond put a scare into Hingis,
losing 6-1, 4-6, 6-3 Wednesday night. Raymond is playing in the
tournament with partner Rennae Stubbs. Raymond/Stubbs, seeded
third, is the only seeded doubles team left and is in the
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   __ Today's matches: 11 a.m. Larisa Neiland/Arantxa
Sanchez-Vicario vs. Irina Spirlea/Caroline Vis, No. 3 Mary Pierce
vs. Julie Halard-Decugis, No. 7 Schett vs. No. 2 Hingis. 7 p.m. No.
1 Lindsay Davenport vs. Martinez, who is 7-2 against the Newport
Beach resident. &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
