<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-TRADE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS TRADE HAWKINS FOR BARRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Hersey Hawkins knew something was about to happen.
There was this daily flood of phone calls from friends.
</P>
<P>
   So the former Sonics guard figured he would hear another trade
rumor when his phone rang Thursday morning. Only this time, Sonics
president Wally Walker was on the line.
</P>
<P>
   To Hawkins' surprise, a deal had been done.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics continued to revamp their roster, trading Hawkins and
little-used guard James Cotton to Chicago for shooting guard Brent
Barry. Hawkins was caught off guard although a trade involving him
had been anticipated for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing about it is I never heard Chicago,'' Hawkins
said from his home near Charlotte, N.C. ``About the only thing I'm
disappointed about is Wally said they were never shopping me. But
it's evident that they were. He told me teams were calling him. But
if you're going to look to trade me, be honest about it. ... I
mean, I figured once they lost Detlef (Schrempf) that I was next.''
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Hawkins leaves Gary Payton as the only
remaining player from the Sonics' 1996 NBA Finals team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This came up in the last couple of days,'' Walker said. ``We
were open to whatever was required to improve the team. A couple of
things dictate what we're doing. Aside from the proposed rules
changes, how our young guys performed in the summer league impacted
what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker tried relentlessly to complete a sign-and-trade deal with
Hawkins in order to land Washington free agent guard Mitch
Richmond. However, that and a number of subsequent deals faltered
because Hawkins has two years and $8.7 million remaining on his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   It was believed the Sonics were still working on a trade for
Hawkins once they signed free agent gunner Vernon Maxwell earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel indifferent,'' said Hawkins, a Chicago native. ``Of
course I didn't want to leave Seattle. We were really at that point
where we were settled. I'm excited about going back home. I told
Jerry (Krause, Bulls general manager) why didn't they pull the
trigger five years ago? But what more can you ask other than to
finish up in Chicago, where I grew up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins' salary plus Cotton's came close to matching Barry, who
signed a six-year contract with the Bulls in January.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Sonics announced they also signed a back-up point
guard Shammond Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1 North Carolina product starred on the Sonics'
summer league team in Boston. Williams was a 1998 draft pick who
played in two games for Atlanta before being released.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great situation here,'' said Williams, who played at
North Carolina from 1995-98. ``Coach (Paul) Westphal is behind me,
and he has been pushing me this summer. I'm going to come in here
and learn a lot from Gary Payton and do whatever it takes to help
this team become successful.''
</P>
<P>
   By adding Barry, Walker continued his campaign to make the
Sonics younger and more athletic.
</P>
<P>
   Barry, 27, will battle Maxwell for the chance to replace the
32-year-old Hawkins as the starter next to Payton. Barry averaged
11.1 points, 3.9 rebounds and 3.1 assists in 37 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   He is best known for winning the 1996 Slam Dunk Contest as a
rookie for the Los Angeles Clippers. He was traded to Miami two
years later before signing with Chicago as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Critics question Barry's toughness and ability to stay healthy.
However, Barry is an exciting player in the open court because he
finishes plays with flair.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to trade Hersey we needed to receive someone very
special in return,'' Westphal said. ``We think Brent's athleticism,
versatility and youth will fit perfectly with the new direction of
our team. We hate to see Hersey and James go, but this opportunity
was too good to pass up.''
</P>
<P>
   So far the Sonics have passed on 10 players from last year's
25-25 team: Hawkins, Schrempf, Cotton, Dale Ellis, Billy Owens, Don
MacLean, Olden Polynice, Aaron Williams, John Crotty and Brent's
younger brother, Drew Barry.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf signed a free agent deal with Portland, while Ellis and
Owens were traded to Orlando for forward Horace Grant. The team
renounced its rights to Polynice, Williams, Crotty and the younger
Barry on Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Sonics have re-signed second-year forward/center
Jelani McCoy and acquired Maxwell, Grant and small forward Ruben
Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said a deal with forward Vin Baker could be struck next
week. The Sonics also are looking to add another center to the
roster soon. Walker was working with slightly more than $1 million
under the salary cap after Thursday's trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics made no secret about their plan to upgrade the
shooting guard position. The team wanted a player who could slash
to the basket and create a shot off the dribble.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins averaged 10.3 points, 4 rebounds and 2.5 assists last
season. Although he struggled with his outside shot, Hawkins said
in June he could find other ways to score if given the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But Hawkins and the Sonics have gone in different directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish them well,'' said Hawkins, whom the Sonics acquired
from Charlotte before the 1996 season. ``It wasn't going to be the
same. I was thinking about the roster, and even if I was back, it
would have been me and Gary from a team that went to the finals
three years ago. How does (the turnover) happen so fast?''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
