<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S PITCHERS FINALLY FEEL SAFE AND SANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Amazing how different Stan Williams seems _ and not
just because he's pale from arthroscopic surgery on his left knee
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Williams now is a genius. A month ago, he was a dope.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that mitigates against his certification as the
pre-eminent baseball sage is one niggling point:
</P>
<P>
   Every major league pitching coach becomes a genius when the
outfield fences are moved back a first down or so.
</P>
<P>
   In 21 games at the Guilty Pleasure, the Mariners' earned-run
average is 4.29, almost 2{ runs fewer than the 38-game Kingdome
average.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that: For 22{ years, the quest for quality pitching
has been futile NOT because Mariners ownership and management have
been stupid.
</P>
<P>
   They were playing in the wrong park.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well ... addresses in Seattle can be confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us in the media were just as confused. For weeks during
the run-up to the new park, all we talked about was the grousing by
Mariner hitters about the generous dimensions, the heavy, moving
air, the soft grass.
</P>
<P>
   All of us missed a key point.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the roster were pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   In our defense, it must be argued: Who knew?
</P>
<P>
   The club's universal emphasis on dinger-rama the past decade has
helped create a complete whiff by us on the idea that there might
be guys on the roster real happy about the move.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it's not as if most of the 26 Mariners pitchers have
been around long enough this season to finish a handshake, much
less answer a question.
</P>
<P>
   Those few on the roster at the moment are nearly kid-like in
their giddiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it _ the pitchers are raving about it,'' said
Paul Abbott, who pitched five solid innings and was the winner
Wednesday in the 11-2, series-sweeping victory over the Chicago
White Sox. ``You don't have to make the perfect pitch. If you find
yourself in a hole, you can be more aggressive. It takes more
pressure off you.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as he would like to take credit, Williams is quick to
acknowledge it was not exactly his cunning that helped curtail the
staff's term as human pinatas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The park obviously helps a lot,'' Williams said after his
pitchers gave up nine runs in three games against Chicago. ``It's
giving the pitchers some confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know how tough the Kingdome was until we got out of
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the Mariners are just 12-9 at the GP, and they were
massively hosed by the Yankees in the series before the White Sox
staggered to town. Yet it was an 8-5 homestand thanks mostly to
pitching that bordered on _ dare it be said? _ credible.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Kingdome, our pitchers tried to be too careful,''
Williams said. ``If they missed, it's a huge mistake. Here, a
pitcher gets behind a hitter, and he throws up and away and the
ball will stay in the park.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Dan Wilson, who has borne intimate witness to the mound
horrors, attests to the additional wiggle room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitchers can challenge the hitters here more and not give up a
cheap home run to right,'' he said. ``At this point, it has been an
advantage for our pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, 21 games is not definitive, particularly since few
have been played with the wind coming from the southwest, the
sodden direction of spring that will turn fly balls into cannon
shots.
</P>
<P>
   But the psychological value for pitchers is undeniable. Young
pitchers often came into the Kingdome cowering from apocryphal
stories of hurlers scraping the center-field wall during windups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 405 feet to center field in the Kingdome, too,'' Williams
said. ``It just didn't play like it. The 73-degree temperature
never varied, never had moisture, and balls always carry in warmer
air.
</P>
<P>
   ``On turf, grounders go through like bullets. Gappers go for
triples. The Kingdome gave up a higher percentage of hits and a
higher percentage of home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can get to a pitcher. Anytime you get negative thoughts, it
takes room away from positive concentration. And positive
concentration is what's needed to avoid things like walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this park is, is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Just not to Mariners hitters used to the ultrafriendly confines.
Still, the homestand featured bountiful attempts by the offense to
bunt, steal, sneak, subvert, tip-toe and filch some runs, a
delightful contrast to the hairy-knuckle style that proved so
breathtakingly inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Anytime Edgar Martinez attempts three steals in a homestand,
either the continents are about to collide, or Mariners hitters
have ended their resistance to Small Ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to have the experience that we can play this kind of
baseball,'' Wilson said. ``It's good to have options and
alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The awareness was forced upon them too late for this postseason.
At least the next six games back in the crimped yards of Boston and
Toronto will offer clues about retaining the new game for old
parks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a fan can positively concentrate on a green light for
Martinez and a stop light for the pitching staff _ although the
risk is high for a mind blown beyond recognition.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
