<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-LAWYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO'S MOTHER SEEKS TO REPLACE LEGAL `DREAM TEAM' 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a bid to acquire greater control of a civil suit
against the city, the mother of Amadou Diallo hired a new lawyer on
Thursday and wants to replace the ``Dream Team'' of Johnnie L.
Cochran Jr. and five others now representing Diallo's estate,
family members and the new lawyer said on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo's mother, Kadiadou Diallo, hired the firm of Robert D.
Conason, a prominent personal injury lawyer, her family said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not happy with the way they are handling the case,''
her brother, Bob Diallo, said on Thursday night. ``She wants
someone who has got enough time for her, and she wants to get more
involved in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Amadou Diallo was shot 19 times by members of the Police
Department's Street Crime Unit in the doorway of his Bronx home in
February in a case that touched off a furious debate about the
police's treatment of minorities in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Getting rid of the six-member team of lawyers representing the
estate _ Cochran, Barry Scheck, Peter Neufeld, Kyle Watters,
Jonathan Svetkey and Michael Warren _ is not a simple matter
because any legal moves must involve both of Amadou Diallo's
parents, who are divorced and are at odds. New lawyers for the
estate can only be hired by the estate's administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Amadou Diallo's death, his parents, Kadiadou and
Saikou Diallo appointed Wyatt Tee Walker, an associate of the Rev.
Al Sharpton's as the administrator of the estate. The only asset of
the estate would be the proceeds of a succesful civil suit.
</P>
<P>
   Walker selected Cochran and the others. Both parents are now
trying to install an administrator who will represent their
interests more effectively, Watters said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Diallo's intention is to get herself appointed as
administrator, giving her power to hire Conason's firm as lawyers
for the estate, Conason said. He said he planned to file papers
soon to have her installed. Because she is not a resident of New
York state, she would have to have a co-executor, he said, adding
that he expected Saikou Diallo to oppose the motion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 0144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5883 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-PINIELLA-2TAKES-S     08-13 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-PINIELLA-2TAKES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S LOU PINIELLA ON THE BUBBLE AS HE APPROACHES 1,000 VICTORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When the time comes, it will be obvious to Lou
Piniella. He will sit still on the bench. The scraps of paper on
his desk will no longer be covered with lineup ideas. The sound and
the fury will be muted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That feeling inside where you don't get excited before a
ballgame, where you don't enjoy the wins, where the losses don't
hurt you,'' said the Mariners manager. ``I'll know. Nobody'll have
to tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   He has not reached that point, even as defeats have come more
frequently the past two years. Piniella handles losing better now,
because he knows there is only so much he can control. But Anita
Piniella can still tell the subtle differences in her husband after
a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not an I'll-forget-about-it type of guy,'' she said of
her husband of 32 years. ``He's really not. I know what's going on.
He's playing it over and over. The best thing he can do after a
loss is just go to bed.''
</P>
<P>
   And even that's not a sure thing. After all, this is a man who,
as a player, loved to tinker with his swing in the middle of the
night. Anita awakened once to see a figure wielding a baseball bat,
and screamed.
</P>
<P>
   Just Lou. Perfectionist, then and now.
</P>
<P>
   That is why his tenure in Seattle, while leading him to the
brink of 1,000 career victories, has been somewhat disappointing
for Piniella. He takes pride in the club attendance records the
Mariners have set under him; his teams in New York and Cincinnati
did the same.
</P>
<P>
   But at .508, Piniella's winning percentage in Seattle is the
lowest of his three stops. And he has not captured another World
Series ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming here to Seattle, people told me it's not going to
work,'' said Piniella, who needs four victories to become the sixth
active manager to reach the milestone. ``I took that as a personal
challenge. And we've been very representative in the years I've
been here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I satisfied with what we've done? Not really. I'm very
pleased that the team stayed in Seattle and got a new ballpark. But
winning two divisions ... we just didn't keep our team together.
Some of the pieces started going elsewhere. And we've been in a
position here, since '97 anyway, where we've been in transition.
It's not easy to win, that's what I've learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella's chance of staying through that transition depends
largely on how dramatic it is. If the Mariners retain enough of
their core to make a run in 2000 _ and ownership continues to
endorse Piniella _ then he should serve at least through his
contract, which ends after next year. But if the Mariners decide to
start over, they won't do it with Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a rebuilding type manager,'' said Piniella, who makes
more than $1 million a year. ``I don't think (dismantling the team)
will be the situation here in Seattle. But why pay a manager a lot
of money to rebuild? Get a young manager that you can grow with,
and build with him, too. I'm in it to give ourselves a shot to win.
That is my satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   A kinship with Steinbrenner
</P>
<P>
   The Piniellas never thought Lou would stay in baseball after his
18-year playing career ended in 1984. He was active in business and
seemed to have an acumen for it, and he'd already given 23 years to
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then George Steinbrenner called. The New York Yankees principal
owner asked Piniella to stay with the team as a coach, with the
promise that he could become manager one day. That day came in
October 1985, and Piniella directed the Yankees until mid-1988,
serving as general manager for part of his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   After a year as an adviser and broadcaster with New York,
Piniella was up for the Reds job. Steinbrenner spoke with
Cincinnati owner Marge Schott, who was not favoring Piniella, and
gave a winning recommendation. There is a kinship between owner and
former outfielder _ ``I think they're one in the same,'' said
former Yankees reliever George Frazier _ and Steinbrenner remains
fond of Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou is a winner,'' Steinbrenner said. ``If you were in a
foxhole, you would want Lou Piniella in with you. That's about the
biggest compliment you can give a guy. You'd want him right by your
side. He's a warrior, he knows how to win, and he gets the job
done. That's how he was with me, always.''
</P>
<P>
   With Thurman Munson and Graig Nettles, Steinbrenner said,
Piniella was one of three leaders on the Yankees teams that won the
World Series in 1977 and '78.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot of leadership in Lou, I really did,'' Steinbrenner
said. ``You came to recognize it after a while and see it in him.
If there was a fight, he was the first guy in to defend his
teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   And also the first to criticize them for mental lapses. Texas
Rangers coach Bucky Dent, a former teammate, said players who made
mental mistakes knew better than to get on Piniella's bus. He and
other veterans could be merciless.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would verbally beat you up to where you said, `I don't
want to mess up again,''' Dent said.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, now a Colorado Rockies broadcaster, said Piniella was a
student, sometimes noting what moves he'd make in certain
situations. When Piniella became a manager, Frazier said, it was
easy to see who had molded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's Billy Jr.,'' said Frazier, referring to Billy Martin, who
had five managing stints in the Bronx. `` ... With Lou, you get one
or two chances and then you're done, and I think that's strictly
based on how he was raised as a player and who he played for.
Playing for Billy was the same way. Fiery, competitive, players'
manager. Billy, he'd chew your ass and then he'd hug you. I think
Lou's a lot the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners right fielder Jay Buhner, who played for Martin in New
York, sees the same things. You could never outsmart either in game
strategy, Buhner said, and both were open to player ideas. Buhner
and Piniella have clashed over the years, he said, but nothing
lingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I love about the guy,'' Buhner said. ``The next
day, it's `How ya doing, big fella?' like nothing ever happened.''
</P>
<P>
   And also like Martin _ and Earl Weaver, Piniella's minor league
manager _ there's the famous Piniella temper. He's fought it all of
his 55 years, and though he's mellowed ``a hell of a lot,''
Piniella said, it's something he's learned he can't change.
</P>
<P>
   In an era where TV cameras dissect every angle of every cap
kick, dirt swipe and base toss, the temper can make Piniella come
off as rash, if not unstable. On ``Lou Piniella Day'' at Yankee
Stadium in 1984, clips of his tantrums were played to an upbeat pop
song, ``He's So Fine.'' Last month, an ESPN compilation played to
ominous, sinister notes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: sinister notes.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners pitching coach Stan Williams, who has known Piniella 33
years, believes he snaps because he's hard on himself and he cares
_ and not just about winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather see a guy fly off the handle because he let the
team down than be passive about it,'' Williams said. ``That means
they care. And Lou cares. That's why he's a good man to work for,
too, because he's a very caring man. That's something a lot of
people may not know. He cares about his friends. He'll do anything
for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams sees that when Piniella helps old business partners
from deals that never worked out. Anita Piniella sees it in her
husband's compassion for homeless people. Even to those who don't
know Piniella well, that quality comes through.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people profess to believe in something, but when it
comes down to it, they're not there to back it up,'' said Cleveland
Indians manager Mike Hargrove. ``Lou stands by what he believes. He
can be brutally honest, and he's a very funny man, but there's also
a very sincere side that I enjoyed finding out he had.''
</P>
<P>
   `I've got to make it happen'
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in baseball likes to lose, of course. Anita Piniella
recognizes this; if her husband seems like he wants to win more
than others, she said, it could be because he shows emotion like
few do.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is a man for whom winning is primal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anybody detest losing as much as Lou,'' said
bench coach John McLaren. ``I've seen him get physically sick from
losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella does not spout five-year plans. His charge, as he sees
it, is to win with what he has _ now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't adhere to the theory that, well, I don't have the
players, or I need this or I need that,'' Piniella said. ``I've got
to make it happen with what I've got. I've got to shuffle, I've got
to prod, I've got to plead _ whatever I've got to do, I've got to
make it happen somehow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shoulder it. I don't make any bones about it. We don't play
well, I don't blame the players. I don't blame the front office.
It's my job to get the damn team to play better. That's basically
it, you know? And that's the way it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of that effort, some young Mariner pitchers have been
traded, rushed or _ some would argue _ ruined. Lately, Piniella has
shown an increasing acceptance of the Mariners' plan to stockpile
young arms _ and the growing pains that go with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't shown up in the win/loss column yet, but it will,''
Piniella said. ``I know where we're headed and I know it's the
right approach, and we're not that far.''
</P>
<P>
   The rap about Piniella and young pitchers gnaws at him. He was
hailed for his handling of the Reds pitchers in 1990, when they won
the World Series, and also developed Doug Drabek and Bob Tewksbury
as rookies in New York. This year, rookies Freddy Garcia and John
Halama have turned out well.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no mistaking Piniella's belief on pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing has been constant about baseball: Veteran pitching
wins for you,'' Piniella said. ``Yeah, you may have the `Kiddie
Corps' of the Baltimore Orioles back when, but if you look in
general, teams that have veteran pitching, especially late in
ballgames, tend to do a whole lot better than teams that get
younger as they get deeper into the ballgame. That's the experience
factor: you get more consistency, you know more of what to expect.
There are less surprises, and it's more conducive to winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if you look at my track record, and not only here but in
Cincinnati and New York, I've given more young pitchers
opportunities than any manager that's managed as long as I have,
and probably more. Now they say I'm hard on young pitchers. I'm not
hard on young pitchers. I'm not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hard on young pitchers that can't pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophies tend not to change after 1,000 victories, and there
is no doubting Piniella's influence on the Mariners' personnel
moves. Vice president for baseball operations Woody Woodward calls
Piniella ``performance-oriented'' _ which seems a polite way of
saying ``demanding'' _ and relies heavily on Piniella's input.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has more to say in the makeup of the club than just about
any manager in the game today,'' Woodward said. ``There may be
exceptions, but he has more impact during the offseason as we plan
for the following season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the experience winning, and I think when you have a
manager like that, you should take advantage of that. I would
prefer to have a manager who gets involved. His credentials justify
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those credentials include a 517-500 record since joining the
Mariners, who had finished above .500 once in 16 years before he
arrived. Only one other active manager, the Dodgers' Davey Johnson,
has won a title as a player and manager. That credibility was
invaluable in 1995, when Piniella was named AL Manager of the Year
and the Mariners rallied to win the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been in the fire; he knows what it takes,'' said catcher
Dan Wilson. ``When you go through it, you don't realize it, but
looking back (to '95), during that stretch he was more or less
hands-off. Just go out and play. He didn't interfere, because he
knew we all wanted the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner has noticed the way Piniella is adapting to Safeco Field,
calling more National League-style sacrifices and squeeze plays
because runs are at more of a premium than at the Kingdome.
Piniella seems comfortable at the ballpark, except, perhaps, in his
office, where photos and wall-hangings still sit on the floor,
waiting to be displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Contractually, he has every right to decorate the walls as he
pleases. And internally, the desire remains. The biggest reason
he's nearing his 1,000th victory, Piniella believes, is his ability
to get along with people. After 38 years in baseball, leaving
everyone behind would not come easily.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been a hard 38 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially when you take it with the intensity and the care
that he does, you could get to the point where you're a little
tired,'' Anita Piniella said. ``But it won't happen right away.''
</P>
<P>
   There won't be another thousand, Piniella has said, laughing.
But if things don't last in Seattle, he is not prepared to walk
away from managing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yet,'' he said, ``but I don't think about that yet,
because it's not my option. That option belongs to other people. If
it happens, it happens; if it doesn't happen, then I'll go home. I
could see myself going home and enjoying it, I really could. But
I'd like to stay in baseball in some capacity, scouting or
whatever, just to keep my foot in the door a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I know best.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
