<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-HEAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTS PLEDGE TO TAKE STANCE AGAINST HATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDS, runs with SHOOTING-SUSPECT, SHOOTING-CASE, SHOOTING-COLUMN,
SHOOTING-KIDS, SHOOTING-CABBIE, SHOOTING-CLEANUP)  
 
  
BY HARRISON SHEPPARD  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Let the healing begin.
</P>
<P>
   That was the message Thursday night at a forum that brought
together counselors, political leaders and public safety officials
to talk to the community about the shooting rampage that killed a
postal worker and wounded two adults and three children at the
Jewish Community Center in the suburb of Granada Hills.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 people attended the session organized by conflict
resolution trainer Jane Lowenthal, held at a local school.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the officials offered comfort and solace to
community members, they also pledged to stand strong against hatred
and intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you touch one child, you touch all of us and we will not
stand for it,'' said Ruben Zacarias, superintendent of the Los
Angeles Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   The LAUSD, he said, has one of the top emergency response teams
in the country, one that has been sent to the scenes of tragedies
all over the world to offer help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety of our children is a top priority,'' he said. ``We
take this issue of young people learning to respect each other very
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Police Chief Michael Bostic, the San Fernando Valley's
top cop, praised the quick and massive response from emergency
crews Tuesday but said the frightening truth is that it is nearly
impossible to prevent this kind of tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, when someone is this sick, this far gone, with
no remorse, no moral fiber, nothing in his being that's nearly
human, frankly there is not much we can do,'' Bostic said.
</P>
<P>
   A white supremacist suspected of being the gunman turned himself
in to federal authorities in Las Vegas Wednesday, telling them,
according to sources, that the shootings were ``a wake-up call'' to
kill American Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Mayer, director of the Jewish Federation, said he refuses
to be cowed by the violent, racist act.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a parent and as a person who runs a community facility much
like the one that was attacked, I'm not frightened,'' he said,
``and none of the people who work for me are frightened.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, people need to react in a positive way to
``make a world that is safe for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowenthal said she called the meeting to tell parents how they
can talk to their children about what happened and figure out what
to do next to keep children safe at schools and in public areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to see each other face-to-face to have
the chance to see we're more alike than we're different,'' she
said. ``Hate is the worst four-letter on this Earth. If I could ban
only one word, that would be the word I would ban.''
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen children who came to the meeting with their
parents were treated to a tour of a fire engine parked outside.
</P>
<P>
   Those attending included City Councilman Hal Bernson, Fire Capt.
Steve Ruda and Robert Tynoos, director of the University of
California, Los Angeles trauma psychiatry service.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, across town in Hollywood, Assemblyman Wally Knox held
a forum on hate crimes and invited people to sign a 30-foot banner
that read, ``JCC kids, we love you.''
</P>
<P>
   The forum was held to discuss Knox's pending assembly bill to
expand the definition of hate crimes to include those involving
sexual orientation and gender.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
