 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-POLICY (Washington) _ It is the year's other war. While the
nation's attention has focused on Kosovo, American warplanes have
quietly, methodically and with virtually no public discussion been
attacking Iraq. Over the past eight months, U.S. pilots, joined by
their British comrades, have flown some two-thirds as many missions
over Iraq as NATO pilots did in 78 days of around-the-clock war
against Yugoslavia. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   EICHMANN-MEMOIRS (Berlin) _ ``Obeying an order was the most
important thing to me. It could be that is in the nature of the
German.'' This is how Adolf Eichmann seeks to explain his central
role in the extermination by the Nazis of 6 million European Jews
in memoirs published Thursday by the German daily Die Welt. The
statement was part of an attempt by Eichmann to portray himself as
a man driven by a visceral sense of duty rather than hatred, and it
appears in the handwritten reflections that Die Welt says it found
at the Center for Research on Nazi Crimes. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Ordinary citizens and political
commentators are wearily picking their way through the debris of
what some were still calling a government crisis, despite the fact
that Boris Yeltsin has changed his government so many times in the
last 17 months _ four to be exact _ that the word ``crisis'' has
lost all meaning. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SECURITY (Atlanta) _ At rural schoolhouses and urban
campuses across the country, millions of students returning to
class in the next few weeks will encounter a steely array of new
security measures. In many schools, lockers are being removed,
cameras are being installed as hallway monitors and students will
have to swipe a computerized ID card just to get in the door. By
David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ACCESS (Washington) _ The fight here and in cities
around the nation over ``open access'' to high-speed cable Internet
service between AT&AMP;T and a coalition led by AOL and GTE has quickly
turned into the most expensive telecom fight of the year and the
latest full employment act for lawyers and lobbyists. It also
features remarkable alliances like President Clinton's top personal
lawyer and the former top Starr aide who wrote the heart of the
independent counsel's impeachment report. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OLDEST-LIFE (Undated) _ Researchers report in the journal
Science that they have pushed the origins of complex life back by a
billion years, with the discovery of the remains of 2.7
billion-year-old algae in ancient Australian shale. But
commentators on the study say that claim goes a bit too far. By
William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-STRAW-POLL (Des Moines, Iowa) _ From state fairs to ice
cream shops, nine Republican presidential candidates have been
scouring this state for votes, set off by something that,
technically, has no direct bearing on who will capture the
nomination: a straw poll. The poll at Iowa State University in Ames
on Saturday was designed as a scheme for the Iowa Republican Party
to enrich itself. Not once in its two-decade history has the event
predicted a presidential victor. But like it or not, the straw poll
has transformed into what most presidential campaigns agree is the
most consequential political event thus far in the unusually
fast-paced run up to 2000. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-CAMPAIGN (Ames, Iowa) _ Using what his campaign calls a
``Wal-Mart strategy,'' Steve Forbes has held over 180 events in
Iowa and spent millions to woo voters in the state. Some voters
there say they like his business experience and the fact he's a
billionaire. He's built a strong Iowa organization, and that's what
counts in the nearly 25-year-old Iowa straw poll. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEFENSE _ President Clinton's legal defense fund has
raised a total of $6.3 million in 18 months, but the flow of checks
has slowed considerably in recent weeks, causing supporters to
worry that they will not be able to pay off the Clintons' entire
debt before the president leaves office. By Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-OIL (Moscow) _ In November 1997, British Petroleum began
its acquisition of a 10 percent stake in the Russian oil company
Sidanko with a signing ceremony at No. 10 Downing Street. Eighteen
months after the smiles and handshakes, BP, now BP Amoco PLC, is
embroiled in a bankruptcy proceeding and a takeover fight that
threatens to destroy Sidanko and BP Amoco's investment in it. The
situation puts the very future of direct foreign investment in
Russia at risk. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic and locator map have beenn
