<P>
   The discovery of the ancient molecular fossils should help to
paint an entirely new picture of evolution on the early Earth, the
scientists said, and suggests that these microbes were probably the
first to generate oxygen into the Earth's atmosphere and thus
provide the crucial fuel for all advanced living things _ from
plants to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the earliest clear evidence for complex life on Earth
has come from fossil molecules about 1.6 billion years old. But the
Australian team, reporting Friday in the American journal Science,
declares flatly that ``the molecular fossils we report are the
oldest preserved biological molecules in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This age should provide a new calibration point for molecular
clocks and the universal tree of life,'' the team says.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian scientists, headed by Jochen J. Brocks of the
University of Sidney, found their evidence in a drill core that
brought up samples of shale from a depth of nearly 1,000 feet in
the iron-bearing Hammersley Range of Northwestern Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers used the most meticulous chemical techniques
available to make certain that their fossils were uncontaminated by
more recent biological molecules that might have migrated into the
rock core.
</P>
<P>
   And what they found were concentrations of two types of vitally
important fossil ``biomolecules:''
</P>
<P>
   _ One contained traces of fatty molecules called steranes that
could only have been produced by a type of widespread primitive
organism called eukaryotes _ one-celled animals containing a
nucleus and a surrounding membrane _ as opposed to the even simpler
and more primitive organisms called prokaryotes, which have no
nucleus and may have existed on Earth as long as 3.5 billion years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ The other fossils were methylhopanes, chemicals that are
produced only by a class of organisms called cyanobacteria _
sometimes also known as blue-green algae. Cyanobacteria were the
first living things known to exist by photosynthesis and were also
the most important producers of oxygen that made life possible for
more advanced organisms, including the plants and animals of today.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian discovery may be enormously important for
shedding light on the long and shadowy period of Earth's history
known as the Archean age, between the planet's formation some 4.5
billion years ago and the Proterozoic age that began some 2.5
billion years ago, said Andrew H. Knoll, a Harvard evolutionary
biologist who published a commentary on the Australian report
appearing Friday in Science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cyanobacteria are the microscopic heroes of Earth history,
life's great ecological liberators and source of the oxygen that
transformed our planetary surface,'' Knoll said.
</P>
<P>
   And while the evidence for the existence of cyanobacteria as far
back as 2.7 billion years seems strong, Knoll said, ``We can make
only limited inferences about the overall biology'' of the
Australian fossils.
</P>
<P>
   To Norman H. Sleep, a Stanford geophysicist who has long
pondered the possibility of life having arrived on the early Earth
aboard bombarding asteroids from distant reaches of space, the new
fossil evidence suggests that life may well have arrived even
earlier than 2.7 billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The finding shows that you have a tree of life that
essentially starts very, very early in the history of Earth,'' he
said in an interview. ``By 2.7 billion years ago, it appears that
the eukaryotes were already major players on the stage. As for the
2.7 billion number, I'd consider that late rather than early, for
there are subtle hints of earlier impacts from space that might
well have introduced life to our planet.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
