<HEADER>
A6028 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN14-CO     08-13 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES &AMP; SHORT STORIES: Hungary for capitalism
 &HT;    (Eds: Eighth in a series. Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe
Murray reported from Eastern Europe during a visit 10 years ago,
just before the fall of the Berlin Wall. This summer he returned to
write about the changes that have led three former Eastern Bloc
countries _ Hungary, the Czech Republic and Poland _ to become the
newest members of NATO. At the end of the series, CoxNet will
compile some of these columns into our weekly Focus page, good for
running as a Perspective-type page or op-ed feature.)
 &HT;    (A photo is available by calling 404-526-5456.)
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ The day I arrived the Goodyear blimp was flying
overhead. A nice change from having to fly red banners, as required
in the bad old days of communism.
</P>
<P>
   When I was here 10 years ago, Hungary had already squeezed out
of the grip of Soviet rule, had opened its borders with Austria and
was tumbling the giant statues of Lenin and other communist
demi-gods.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly enough, the statues are still around, some 40 of
them that have been gathered together at Statue Park on the edge of
the city, gigantic memorials that serve as grim, granite reminders
of the era of totalitarianism.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that now they're standing their ground for
capitalism, Statue Park being a privately owned, money-making
concern that profits through paid admissions.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that Hungary has taken to the free-market economy in
every way that it can.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some other former Soviet bloc countries, Hungarians
didn't lose the will to work during the years of communism, and
it's not unusual for individuals to hold two and three jobs.
</P>
<P>
   With average income at about $1,000 a month, that's what it
takes to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't yet gotten the hang of customer service. If you
walk into a shop and look around, see nothing that you want and
start to leave without making a purchase, whatever it is that the
clerk is muttering in Hungarian, you can bet it isn't, ``Have a
nice day.''
</P>
<P>
   English is prevalent here but German remains the second language
of Hungary, bordering as it does with Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary has different neighbors in every direction: Slovakia to
the north, Ukraine to the northeast, Romania to the east,
Yugoslavia, Croatia and Solvenia to the south, along with Austria
to the West.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there's a bit of Hungary in every adjoining country,
having had much of its territory taken away after World War I.
That's why you'll find Hungarian minorities throughout Central and
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For minorities inside Hungary, there are the Romas _ what we
call Gypsies. Everybody has to dislike somebody, and the Hungarians
have the Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   A not-uncommon attitude: ``I'm not a racist. I just hate
Romas.''
</P>
<P>
   Ongoing question: Whether it would be better to segregate Roma
children and educate them separately.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you thought the world was safe for democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Education is highly prized here. It's their version of the class
system, to the point that Hungarians don't always recognize the
importance of experience in the field. Given the choice of getting
an advanced degree or advancing in their present job, they'll
choose the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary invented the Rubik's Cube. Most people don't know that.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary claims Dracula as one of theirs as well, never mind what
the Romanians say. Transylvania was once a part of Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Note of caution: When hungry in Hungary, don't order the
Transylvania mixed grill, not if you're looking for a light repast.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pancake-like stack of fried meat, no telling what, topped
off with a generously thick filet of pure hog fat, grilled to a
golden brown. Evidently, there is no Hungarian word for
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Watch out with whom you drink, too.
</P>
<P>
   One of the favorite scams is for a couple of attractive young
women to approach a male tourist and suggest that they step into a
nearby bar to have a few drinks and see what happens next.
</P>
<P>
   After any number of rounds, what happens is that the women
disappear and you find you're stuck with an inflated bar bill that
may amount to as much as $500.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know, you're being escorted to a nearby ATM
machine by a burly bartender who will tell you with a straight face
_ not counting his broken nose _ that those women were strangers to
him.
</P>
<P>
   Gypsies, no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
