<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6029 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-BOS &LR;      08-13 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENAGER GRABS TWO-SHOT PGA LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ Against a backdrop of adult millionaires
squabbling over an issue that everyone agrees should not have been
made public, leave it to a teenager to put up a round of golf that
everyone feels was not possible.
</P>
<P>
   After all, wasn't Sergio Garcia still shellshocked from his
British Open debacle? Wasn't he sporting so many wounds from that
89-83 beating that he would barely find his way around this
7,401-yard beast called Medinah Country Club?
</P>
<P>
   If so, nobody told El Nino, the 19-year-old Spaniard who
reminded everyone at the opening round of the 81st PGA Championship
that golf is the main meal here, that the Ryder Cup controversy is
only table whine. Garcia made the turn at 2 under par, shaved
strokes at the 11th, 14th, and 15th, then closed out a brilliant,
course record-tying 6-under 66 with a 4-foot birdie putt at 18 to
take a two-shot lead over a trio of competitors _ 45-year-old Jay
Haas, lefthander Mike Weir, and unheralded J.P. Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   Play was suspended at 7:57 (CST) with 15 players still on the
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I showed that the British Open was a mistake,'' said
Garcia, the youngest player to lead this championship since it
switched to stroke play in 1958. ``Hopefully you won't ask me
anymore about the British Open.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, request granted. Never heard of Carnoustie. Tell us about
Medinah.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia smiled widely, perhaps the first bright face seen during
this week of pay-for-play pettiness. ``I just played great, hit a
lot of fairways, a lot of greens, and made a couple putts,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A simple plan that Garcia followed splendidly, but some others
had it down pretty well, too, as steady rain throughout the day _
there was a 47-minute delay late in the afternoon due to lightning
_ softened greens that had been thought to be erratic. Instead,
they rolled nicely and were inviting.
</P>
<P>
   And Haas, a quiet, unassuming man who has been on the PGA Tour
for more years (22) than Garcia has been on earth, was the first to
accept the invitation. Off in the sixth group, he birdied the
opening hole, made the turn in 35, then made four birdies coming
home to shoot 68.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' said Haas, ``you just don't get that many
opportunities in major championships. I have to think that I can
still compete out here. At times I can.''
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, Haas was joined at 68 by the pride of
Sarnia, Ont. _ Weir _ and Hayes made it three by early afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A four-player group at 3-under 69 consists of two men who honed
their talents in Japan (Brian Watts and Brandt Jobe), one who
followed in the shadows of David Duval at Georgia Tech (Stewart
Cink), and a last-minute replacement who got the call as he sat in
the fitness trailer (Jerry Kelly, via the University of Hartford).
</P>
<P>
   Also at 3 under, though he will have to resume at the 16th tee
this morning at 8:45, is a player who perhaps should be held up as
a Ryder Cup poster boy in this tenuous time of badwill (Corey
Pavin).
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, back in 1991-95, Pavin's short-drive,
big-heart game served as a blueprint for US Ryder Cuppers, but as
this major championship has been overshadowed by one testy press
conference after another, so, too, has the spirit of that biennial
competition been battered.
</P>
<P>
   The marquee American names were not asked about their rounds as
they completed the opening 18. They were asked to resume this
nonsense of ``He Said, He Said.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is too bad because there were some good efforts turned in.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably by Duval, who opened with a birdie, survived a
bogey-bogey stumble at Nos. 15 and 16, and shot 70. Ironically, it
was the same score shot by two of his colleagues in this Ryder Cup
controversy _ Tiger Woods and Tom Lehman _ as 14 players posted
2-under totals. One was 54-year-old Hale Irwin, who showed that he
is playing on more than just memories of his US Open victory here
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The Senior Tour's best player bogeyed the 18th hole to put a
damper on the three birdies he had made, then stepped to the side
and watched his playing partner, Garcia, convert his sixth birdie
of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' quipped Irwin to reporters, ``I didn't intimidate
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Hale. Though your resume is a monster in achievement, it
doesn't measure up to a monster called Carnoustie. And if that
diabolical place could not shake the spirit of this Young Man Who
Would Be Seve, then nothing can.
</P>
<P>
   For which observers of this somber event should be thankful. It
was, after all, a performance that helped put golf back into a golf
tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
