<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6086 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINTER-COLUMN14-COX     08-13 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Country boy consoles city
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ I admit that I'm inclined to brag on my
country-gone-to-town cousin, the head honcho preacher at the big
Peachtree Road United Methodist Church in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Don Harp, better known locally as Donald Jr., grew up
like the rest of us in the south Fayette County farming community
of Inman. He chopped and picked cotton on his daddy's farm, cut
collards and turnip greens to truck to the market in Atlanta, got
up before school to milk the cow and bring in stove wood.
</P>
<P>
   If he didn't grow up to farm land tended by his family since
Indian times, we thought he might be at least a Class AA baseball
player. He was a fearless and promising catcher, even before he
went off to Young Harris College and prospered under the tutelage
of a youthful professor-coach named Zell Miller.
</P>
<P>
   After college, and a bout with polio, he spent a year farming
with his dad. On weekends when the collard crop thinned out, he
played baseball with amateur teams. ``Got me into some bad
fights,'' remembers Doug Cobb, one of his pitchers now retired from
teaching and coaching in Clayton County.
</P>
<P>
   I was apprehensive a few years ago when the Methodist hierarchy
decided to move Donald Jr. to Peachtree Road. ``Don't go,'' was my
advice. The Peachtree Road church is close kin to the elite Capital
City and Piedmont Driving clubs in Atlanta's social structure. I
thought it a perilous assignment for a country boy from Inman,
where most of us haven't worked our way up to membership in the
Griffin Moose Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get me wrong. Our family has points of pride. While we
haven't produced a governor or anyone that high up, Uncle Harry was
mayor of Fayetteville for a stretch, and so far we've never had
anyone in jail or in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I was surprised when the congregation warmed to
stories about growing up on a farm, and how a small boy was
impressed by such things as the firm but diplomatic way our
grandmother could make Uncle Russ and Uncle Harry, her bachelor
brothers-in-law, stop cussing each other when they got into
arguments while washing squash and cucumbers for the market.
</P>
<P>
   For several years I've been bragging about the success my
formerly country cousin has enjoyed in transplanting his down-home
style to citified, upscale North Atlanta. I've also pointed out
that whenever he personally served communion to Deion Sanders,
Deion almost always made two or three interceptions and ran kicks
back for touchdowns. I often mention that he performed Lewis
Grizzard's only marriage that didn't end in divorce. (I don't think
I'm necessarily compelled to add that Lewis died the next day.)
</P>
<P>
   Donald Jr. maintains a strong interest in our little Methodist
church in Inman, where his great-great-grandfather was a founder,
and where his mother played the piano every Sunday forever. When we
got a new preacher, he asked me to drive Doug Burrell up to
Peachtree Road for a get-acquainted lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The day before we were to go, we heard about the citywide
service of hope and remembrance in the wake of the Atlanta office
massacre and other killings. We called and offered to postpone, but
Donald Jr. said come ahead.
</P>
<P>
   On the way up, we dialed WSB to check traffic. Our host was
being vilified by Neal Boortz for something he'd said in his Sunday
sermon about the country having too many handguns in circulation. I
half-expected Donald Jr. to call in an offer to meet Mr. Boortz in
the parking lot, or maybe threaten to turn things over to Cousin
Kenny. Then I remembered he would naturally follow the advice of a
late and beloved Fayetteville lady who was quick to caution about
getting into what I can paraphrase as urological contests with
polecats.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch, he told us his Peachtree Road church had planned its
own service for the shooting victims and their families. When Mayor
Bill Campbell heard about it, he called to ask that the service be
expanded citywide. Television and all the news agencies were
coming. CNN was going to carry it nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will you say?'' I asked my preacher cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm working on,'' he replied. ``It's tough. What
can you say at a time like this?''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, while I concentrated on a slice of
chocolate cake, the two preachers fell into shop talk. They were
talking about theology. ``I learned most of my theology growing up
in Inman,'' Donald Jr. told Doug Burrell. I think I know what he
meant. Basically, Inman theology says ``Do what's right, and do it
right now.'' Our grandmother said it her way. Some of our uncles
sometimes added a ``dammit'' for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   In more eloquent words, that was the Rev. Don Harp's message to
his city and to his country in Atlanta's service of hope and
remembrance, as Christian, Jew, Muslim and Hindu came together
before one God, saying the same things, even when the words were
different. Mayor Campbell said afterward that hour at Peachtree
Road can mean more to the city than the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Watching on TV, I felt a lot better about the city of Atlanta,
and the people of Atlanta, than I have in a long time. Through the
tears, we got a glimpse of a city greatly changed, and also of what
it can become.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
