<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6088 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN14-COX     08-13 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Right to own guns gets harder to embrace with each attack
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``Now some misfit has pumped 70 rounds into
children at a day-care center in Los Angeles. It's depressing. I
think I'll sell my guns,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' asked my friend. ``I was just thinking about going
out and buying a gun. Maybe I'll take one of those classes so I can
carry one with me everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   His reading of the latest shooting spree was that gun violence
has become so pervasive that he might need a gun to protect
himself.
</P>
<P>
   As a lifelong gun owner, I wince with every report of another
shooting spree. I've been wincing a lot lately.
</P>
<P>
   I know that America's growing anti-gun legion will use the
latest warped act of gun violence to call for more gun
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I know that guns in the right hands represent no
more threat to society than chocolate-chip cookies, I also know
that far too many wrong hands hold guns.
</P>
<P>
   Why America is experiencing a growth market in wrong hands and
guns, I don't know. I doubt that anyone knows.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association and pro-gun enthusiasts hold all
guns blameless. Their solution for the escalation of gun violence
lies in the vigorous prosecution of people who use guns to commit
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, except it is fantasy to believe that the United
States will ever produce a population so law-abiding, loving and
rational that the misuse of firearms would no longer be a concern.
</P>
<P>
   Short of divine intervention, which we cannot count on, violent
and unstable criminals will always be with us.
</P>
<P>
   Vigorous prosecution of people who blast holes in their fellow
citizens is a great idea. But vigorous prosecution cannot bring
shooting victims back to life or ever make them whole again if they
survive.
</P>
<P>
   The chance of banning guns in the United States is somewhere
between nil and none. That option is a nonstarter.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, America has an estimated 192 million privately
owned guns and a population only slightly higher _ approximately
270 million. The genie is out of the bottle. There's no putting it
back.
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, in order to win acceptance of the freshly
penned Constitution of the United States, America's revolutionary
founders added the Bill of Rights, a document specifically designed
to curb the powers of government and ensure individual liberties
important to the citizens of this new nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Second Amendment of the Bill of Rights states: ``A
well-regulated militia, being necessary to the security of a free
state, the right of the people to keep and bear arms, shall not be
infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   The founders understood how important guns in the hands of
citizens were to winning their revolutionary war. The gun right was
important to these new U.S. citizens not only to fight off foreign
invaders but also to keep any new government from becoming as
despotic as the deposed British crown.
</P>
<P>
   The Second Amendment was not intended to give citizens the right
to use guns when they go hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-gun champions often claim that certain guns ``do not have a
legitimate hunting purpose.'' So what? From a constitutional point
of view, those observations are meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Hunting has nothing to do with the right to keep and bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   The gun question Americans need to ask is whether the founders
could have been right then and wrong now. Have technology and
events passed the amendment by?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there is enough wiggle room in the Second Amendment to
require the registration of guns and the testing and licensing of
gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, my friend may feel the need to keep and bear
his own gun.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: rnethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
