<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When gravity will do, you don't neeed glue
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Short ends and offcuts today, headed by a gentleman
who is making a coffee table and wants ``a piece of glass set into
the top.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes a silicone sealant might be the thing to use, but
``I'm wondering if the silicone will dry clear enough or if it will
be noticeable when I'm finished. Also, will it adhere to both
materials _ wood and glass? Anything else I need to watch out for
when combining glass and wood?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes. If you glue the glass to the wood, you need to watch out
for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Wood moves. To the best of my knowledge, glass does not. If you
glue them together over any significant distance, either the glass
or the wood is going to crack.
</P>
<P>
   The gentleman already has the basic idea when he said he intends
to set the glass into the tabletop. That's all you do _ route a
ledge around the opening deep enough to set the glass flush with
the table top and just the right size to let it drop into place
easily but not shift around too much. He'll need to use a fairly
thick piece of glass _ ordinary window glass would be much too thin
and likely to break if someone sets a glass down hard on it.
</P>
<P>
   Since gravity will hold the glass in place, there is no need to
give it the full frame-and-panel treatment as you would with a
window pane or mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Paint is the answer
</P>
<P>
   Here's one we've addressed fairly recently, but with it being
summertime, it's probably worth going into again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinking of building some Adirondack chairs and wondering what
type of wood to use. Teak is too expensive. I was told red oak is
quite durable outdoors.''
</P>
<P>
   Teak is not only brutally expensive, it's brutal on tools. The
first coffee table I built was made of teak. It came out nicely,
but I used up every saw blade I had.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of woods that theoretically hold up well
outdoors. Most of them are somewhat weak for seating, however. The
fact is that most wood is going to get rather rough and unsightly
if left in the weather, no matter how durable it may be.
</P>
<P>
   It needs to be finished, and the only truly protective finish
for outdoor use is paint. Thus, any furniture I'm likely to build
for outdoors is probably going to be something like pine or maybe
poplar, since there is no point in spending extra money for
handsome wood.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid pressure-treated pine, however, It is most unpleasant to
work, and I'm not sure I'd want to sit on it, either.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the merger
</P>
<P>
   Some interesting developments regarding our recent discussions
of adequate and inadequate equipment, especially the latter.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow on the Internet reports he has bought a Kity table saw
and somehow thinks he can perhaps upgrade it by getting a Delta
contractor's saw and marrying the two.
</P>
<P>
   The Kity, if memory serves, is a European saw made of stamped
parts and intended, I would assume, as a portable builder's saw. It
is definitely not a sturdy piece of equipment for cabinetmaking.
However, the idea of somehow merging it with a Delta contractor's
saw would take a mechanical Dr. Moreau, and you know how his
experiments turned out.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite amazing how folks of a certain mindset, once they
realize they have made a regrettable purchase, dream up cockamamie
schemes like this rather than biting the bullet and buying
something they can be certain will fill their needs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
