<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6090 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-KISS-FANS14-COX     08-13 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KISS-FANS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KISS fans remain loyal through years
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ You can understand why KISS once held a
nation of teen-age boys in its black-fingernailed grasp.
</P>
<P>
   The group rocked with a brain-rattling loudness, singing about
cold gin, fast chicks and Dr. Love. They seemed perpetually juiced
on testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   And that Kabuki-inspired makeup! It made them look like
superheroes, albeit really, really mean superheroes who belched
fire and spat blood ...
</P>
<P>
   Now Gene Simmons, Paul Stanley, Peter Criss and Ace Frehley are
powdering 50-year-old faces. And their most devoted followers are
pushing middle age with no sign of surrendering their allegiance to
the KISS army.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anything wrong with holding on to your youth a
little bit,'' says fan David Torjak. ``If I'm 29 and I want KISS
dolls, I'm going to buy KISS dolls.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Wayne Lansberry, a 37-year-old father of two: ``When I
don't want to listen to Dave Matthews, I'll crank on the KISS....
My wife doesn't particularly like me jamming all those records, but
the kids love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents who encourage their kids to listen to KISS? Horrors! But
the band that warned Mom and Pop to lock up their daughters has
changed its tune. Now in its 26th year, the group is increasingly
puckering up to the cultural mainstream:
</P>
<P>
   _ Some of their rockingest tunes have joined the Muzak playlist.
</P>
<P>
   _ The group played the Super Bowl at Pro Player Stadium earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Warriors of KISS _ a team of wrestlers led by a grappler
named the Demon _ will make its WCW debut this fall.
</P>
<P>
   _ And how's this for wholesome: KISS even posed for a ``Got
Milk?'' ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``KISS might be unexpected in a milk ad, but that's why we chose
them,'' says spokeswoman Mia McWilliams.
</P>
<P>
   The band invades movie theaters today with the opening of
``Detroit Rock City,'' a comedy about four teen-agers' quest for
tickets to a 1978 KISS concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit Rock City'' undoubtedly will spark memories for fans.
In 1979, an 8-year-old Jim Brogan saw KISS from a front-row seat at
the Philadelphia Spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   And last month Brogan and his girlfriend dropped $1,400 on a
pilgrimage to see Paul Stanley perform the lead role in ``Phantom
of the Opera'' in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say I'm obsessed, and maybe I am,'' Brogan
says. ``They've just been a part of my life, all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But why? ``I've been asking myself that for years,'' he says.
``They're not the best musicians in the world, and they know it. To
me, they just wrote stuff that was catchy and had a groove.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, they knew the value of a good makeup brush.
``It's true escapism,'' Brogan explains. ``You're not thinking it's
Gene Simmons up there. You're thinking it's a creature walking
around and making music.''
</P>
<P>
   Brogan lives inside a KISS shrine. His bedroom is decorated with
KISS candles, a clock, mousepad, mirror and trash can. His KISS
comic collection is stashed under his bed, the quartet's four solo
album covers from 1978 look down on his bed, and a dozen KISS
action figures, still in their packaging, hover above his bathroom
door.
</P>
<P>
   All of which initially looked pretty odd to girlfriend Kristina
Parker. Raised in a Southern Baptist household, she grew up
thinking that KISS ``was pretty much Satan, pretty much the epitome
of all evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she has a grudging respect for the band members as
individuals. ``It's the music that I don't care for,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That puts her in good company, says Horacio Ochoa, who wears a
vintage KISS pin to his job at a music store. About the size of a
coffee mug, the pin sparks conversations. Shoppers ``ask me if I'm
a real KISS fan,'' says the 23-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   He's actually not wild about the group's music, but ``just the
idea of them I find interesting.'' Interesting enough that he's
purchased some of the group's ``Psycho Circus'' action figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's going to sound terrible, but they truly understand
the meaning of commercialism and exploitation of a trademark,''
says Tim ``Loud'' Mitchell, who has seen 17 KISS concerts.
</P>
<P>
   These are heady times for ``Love Gun'' lovers, says the
35-year-old Mitchell. ``You're getting the original article,'' not
the interim, makeup-free musicians who played with Simmons and
Stanley in the '80s and early '90s while Frehley and Criss were on
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Maher, 30, says he endured his share of teasing in the '80s
for being part of the KISS cult, but nowadays, ``everyone goes
around saying they were (KISS fans).''
</P>
<P>
   As a wise rock critic once noted, one of the best reasons to
love KISS is because ``it's fun to rub the fact that you still like
them in the faces of all those people who, for 15 years, told you
that you'd outgrow them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I going to be 76 years old and listening to `Love Gun'?''
Brogan says. ``I don't know. ... It hasn't stopped yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
