<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6095 &Cx1f; tad-z
r v BC-COMMENTARY-BJT14-COX     08-13 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, August 14 and Sunday, August
15, 1999 are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _WACO, Texas _ Even though I know that guns in
the right hands represent no more threat to society than
chocolate-chip cookies, I also know that far too many wrong hands
hold guns. (Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN - BUDAPEST _ The statues of Lenin and other
communist demi-gods are still around, some 40 of them that have
been gathered together at Statue Park. The difference is that now
they're standing their ground for capitalism, Statue Park being a
privately owned, money-making concern that profits through paid
admissions. So it is that Hungary has taken to the free-market
economy in every way that it can. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED
FOR SATURDAY. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
