<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Saturday, August
14 and Sunday, August 15, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ When considering a coffee table complete with
glass top, there is no need to give it the full frame-and-panel
treatment as you would with a window pane or mirror. Gravity and a
little planning will do that job. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HUNT-COUNTRY _ MIDDLEBURG, Va. _ The essence of Hunt Country was
captured on the Virginia license plate: POLO MOM. In this historic
piedmont in the shadows of the Blue Ridge Mountains, the scents of
money and manure have long mingled. (Dart, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   Moved Monday in (a) national and (l) lifestyle categories. FOR
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   BLIND-ARTIST _ ATLANTA _ When the Atlanta College of Art
accepted Gene Allcott as a student in the '70s, it was something of
a leap of fate: He was legally blind. But not only did the
nerdy-looking artist with thick glasses graduate, he captivated a
loyal Atlanta following with his whimsical portraiture _ painted in
bold, incandescent colors with an infectious zest for life. A
tireless self-promoter, he made greeting cards and T-shirts to
support himself, even as his work was being sought by wealthy
collectors. Since his death in 1992, at 39, of a freak accident,
his reputation has continued to pick up steam. Now the Atlanta
College of Art is presenting a retrospective, through Sept. 4. His
sister, an editor at Reader's Digest, is writing a brochure _
filled with memories from his acquaintances _ and there will be a
tribute on Friday, Aug. 27. (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
25. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   KISS-FANS _ The Kiss Story. A few old fans discuss the Kiss(ing)
disease. Parents who encourage their kids to listen to KISS.
(Sturrock, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TV-LIFETIME _ The host of one show speculates out loud about
trying on a showgirl's scanty G-string and the effect on her
``organs.'' The other show's host surrounds herself with candles
and soothing talk of spiritual phenomena. It's the start of another
new season of original programming on Lifetime, which seemingly is
amending its slogan to ``Television for All Different Sorts of
Women.'' With two new women's cable networks poised to enter the
marketplace, the mother of them all, Lifetime, is trying to cement
its hold on the female viewing audience that advertisers so love.
In the next week, Lifetime introduces two new series and kicks off
the second seasons of its original sitcom ``Oh Baby'' and the
Emmy-nominated drama ``Any Day Now.'' We preview the two new series
and provide a quick look at the returning programs. (Vejnoska,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 16.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   CRYOLIFE _ Nestled in view of the Kennesaw Mountain, Cryolife is
busy saing lives at minus 325 degrees. With two new products -
bioglue and synergraft - the publicly owned company (NYSE-CRY) is
not only helping patients who need heart valves, but it's making
record profits. Named one of the top 10 small businesses to watch
by Forbes Magazine, it is not only finding the best ways to
preserve human tissue, it's now deeply in the field of regenerating
human tissue. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TWIN-DOCS _ Identical twins Travis and Travan Jasper were born
37 seconds apart. In high school they were co-valedictorians; they
went to the same college, medical school, and residency program,
where they both chose emergency medicine as a specialty. Now they
both teach at Emory University School of Medicine and work in
emergency departments in the Emory system, though never in the same
one at the same time to cut down risky confusion. Their story's
already unusual, but it has an extra component: They're
African-American, working in one of the whitest specialties in
medicine. With pictures of the docs in the ER and out of their
white coats, together. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-JEWS _ WEST PALM BEACH _ Three hours after a
37-year-old gunman told police he shot three small children at a
Jewish Community Center in Los Angeles as ''a wake-up call to
America to kill Jews,'' President Clinton awarded seven Medals of
Freedom in the East Room of the White House to Americans who have
contributed greatly to this country. Three of the recipients were
Jewish. The message the Jewish community hears is simple,
straightforward and ancient. No matter how much you succeed, no
matter how hard you work to serve your country, there will always
be a man with a gun around the corner, saying: You may live in this
country, but you are not of it. Though one of the wealthiest and
most influential minorities in the country, Jews maintain a
wariness bred from a heritage of persecution. Despite their medals,
their money and their acceptance, it never quite goes away.
(Belkin, Palm Beach Post). MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTIST-HONORED _ He doesn't like to talk about himself or give
interviews to the press. He kept his church intown when all around
him were in a panic and moving to the suburbs. And yet the Rev.
Cameron Alexander _ a leader in the National Baptist Convention and
a force on Atlanta's political scene _ has managed to transform
Antioch North Baptist Church into a mega-church with 9,000 members.
It has been 30 years since he started his work at Antioch North,
and on August 14 the Rev. Jesse Jackson and other religious and
secular leaders will celebrate his achievements during a program at
the World Congress Center. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
