<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6115 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     08-13 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Aug. 13, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday and
Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-WHITE (Undated) _ A look at The Great White Way in fall
and winter fashions. Expect a blizzard of soft white and cream
clothing to smooth the way into clean living in the next
millennium. And then there are the trends to blankets, shawls and
colorful quilt and patchwork dressing. By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   FOLK-ART (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _ When most people think about folk
art, they think of Grandma Moses and her Northeast landscapes. But
there's much more to folk art. New York's rich folk-art history is
evident in the exhibition ``Empire State Mosaic: The Folk Art of
New York,'' on display at the New York State Historical
Association's Fenimore Art Museum in Cooperstown. By KRIS WORRELL.
(For release Sunday, Aug. 15.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-METHADONE (San Francisco) _ San Francisco is pushing to
become the first city in the nation to make methadone treatment for
heroin addicts widely available. The plan would allow physicians to
prescribe methadone, a federally regulated synthetic narcotic drug
currently available only through a handful of specialized clinics
in the city. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   SF-COPS (San Francisco) _ In 1849, San Francisco was a Gold Rush
boomtown grown out of control. There were no policemen in the wild
city by the Bay until Mayor John Geary, on Aug. 13, 1849, 150 years
ago Friday, hired a police chief and 33 cops _ at the rate of six
dollars a day _ to bring order to the streets of San Francisco,
which then had only about 12,000 residents. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Mesquite, Texas) _ More than 1,000 people
traveled to this residential city outside of Dallas to attend
QuakeCon 99. And many gamers played an early test version of Quake
III Arena, the next product from id Software. Although Q3A, as it's
called, won't be available for a while, the test version is in
great shape and has been drawing raves from players. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader asks, ``My son recently
gave me a hand-me-down Windows 95 computer so we can communicate by
e-mail. I like it a lot, but I am having a hard time looking at the
monitor for very long. It seems to be flickering, but it's
something I can really only see out of the corner of my eye. How
can I fix it?'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Pasadena, Texas) _ Houston is home to former
President George Bush and moderate political thought. But is it
also a mecca of the Socialist Workers Party? It just may be,
according to officials at Crown Central Petroleum Corp., who
believe the local union leader protesting the lockout at the
refinery is trying to overthrow capitalism and is using Crown to
foment revolution. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   SF-GASOLINE (San Francisco) _ U.S. Sen. Barbara Boxer has asked
the Federal Trade Commission to expand the investigation it is
conducting of gasoline pricing practices in California after seeing
the price of gas set aside for independent dealers surpass that for
major oil companies. Her request comes after the price of gasoline
in San Francisco reached an all-time high Tuesday when it was sold
for an average of $1.75 a gallon. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-BARENAKED-LADY (Houston) _ You'd think if a Barenaked Lady
walked into the room, most people would at least look up. But
Steven Page, lead singer with the Canadian rock band Barenaked
Ladies, remains pretty much invisible wherever he goes. Things
could change. With U.S. sales of the band's latest album,
``Stunt,'' at more than 3 million, Page and fellow Barenaked Ladies
Ed Robertson, Jim Creeggan, Tyler Stewart and Kevin Hearn have
emerged as the kings of nerd-rock. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   CARMELLO-PROFILE (Houston) _ Carolee Carmello, one of musical
theater's brightest young stars, is a hit in ``The Scarlet
Pimpernel,'' which is in the middle of a three-city tour but will
make its way back to Broadway in mid-September. By EVERETT EVANS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BOWFINGER (Undated) _ ``Bowfinger'' is neither the
funniest movie ever made nor the sharpest in Steve Martin's
wild-and-crazy canon. But it has some things going for it that no
other comedy banging around theaters currently has. One of them is
Eddie Murphy, who, for for those who live on the planet Xenon, is
an awesomely gifted comic. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BROKEDOWN (Undated) _ ``Brokedown Palace'' has many
earnest things on its mind, some of which it addresses with
competency and occasional art. And having Claire Danes around
automatically gives the movie both accessibility and edge, thanks
to her natural smarts and her equally natural well of compassion.
By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-VESSELS (Undated) _ In the medical tradition of
``MASH'' and ``Hospital,'' Scott Ziehl's seedy ``Broken Vessels''
makes a strong case in favor of on-the-job surveillance for Los
Angeles paramedics _ if not for our protection then for our
sadistic entertainment. They defibrillate the strong-hearted, curse
at the wounded and leave the ailing for dead. The small consolation
is that there's more substance abuse than patient abuse. By WESLEY
MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-OGRE (Undated) _ ``The Ogre'' is a chilling study of
delusions and moral blindness in a self-proclaimed innocent who
becomes a dedicated servant of his Nazi captors. He's a
simpleminded Frenchman with a special, disturbing affinity for
children who uses his gift in a hellish manner. By WALTER ADDIEGO.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-NOTES (Undated) _ A look at the lastest movies to be
released on video. Some of the movies are ``Shakespeare in Love,''
``Celebrity'' and ``The Mod Squad.`` By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-SALADS (Houston) _ Caesar still reigns. But as the heat
index climbs, threats to the crown are lurking in the shadows of
restaurants across Houston. The salad entree trend is hot, and
chefs are tossing up a storm to create a culinary oasis. By DAI
HUYNH.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-OLYMPICS (Houston) _ Houston, the city that can't define
itself, is once again trying to define itself. In recent years, the
city has come up with slogans such as ``Houston's Hot,'' and
``Houston: Expect the Unexpected.'' But none of these has the ring
of the Big Apple, or the Big Easy, or even the Big D, names that
give immediate recognition. Now, the Houston Olympics is committee
trying to come up with a slogan, but it's not an easy task. By JOHN
WILLIAMS.
</P>
</TEXT>
