<HEADER>
A6144 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     08-13 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORIED CHURCH PROVIDES A BAPTIST HISTORY LESSON IN LONDON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When I went looking for the church of Charles Haddon
Spurgeon, one of the greatest Baptist preachers of all time, I
didn't expect it to be so easy to find.
</P>
<P>
   I took a bus from Oxford to London early one recent Sunday, a
spur-of-the-moment decision inspired by a final lecture in a church
history course I was taking at Oxford University's Regents Park
College.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, Karen Bullock, theology professor at Southwestern
Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth, had talked about
Spurgeon and the ``Down Grade Controversy,'' a dispute over the
Bible that split British Baptists in the late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   It resembled the strife-filled, damaging controversy I have been
covering for 20 years that has split some very well-meaning people
in the giant Southern Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Besides that, I had heard the name ``Spurgeon'' spoken in the
same breath with other great preachers for as long as I could
remember.
</P>
<P>
   I had to find Spurgeon's old church. But I didn't know where it
was located in London.
</P>
<P>
   I learned from a telephone information operator that there was a
Metropolitan Tabernacle at Elephant and Castle, a major stop on
London's subway, or Underground. On blind faith, I traveled to
Elephant and Castle on the Bakerloo line.
</P>
<P>
   I asked an Underground attendant if we were near the
Metropolitan Chapel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just walk out the front door,'' he said. ``It's right there.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right. When I emerged from the Underground station, I
looked across the street and saw a large building with signs
reading ``Spurgeon's Church'' and ``Come Worship in Our Crowded
Sanctuary.''
</P>
<P>
   The church began in 1650 in a time of Baptist persecution, and
there were pioneering pastors before Spurgeon. But when he arrived,
in 1853, crowds became so large that services were moved to large
rented buildings, including one on The Strand in London's theater
district.
</P>
<P>
   The huge Metropolitan Tabernacle then was built on a site said
to be the spot where the Southwark martyrs, dissenters who were
forerunners of Baptists, were burned in the 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   All but the impressive columned portico of the church and its
basement was destroyed by fire in 1898. It was rebuilt. But in
1941, an incendiary bomb dropped by German planes again destroyed
everything but the church entrance and basement, requiring a second
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, the congregation dwindled, but today, under
leadership of the Rev. Peter Masters, who preaches in the same
conservative style as Spurgeon, the Metropolitan Tabernacle is on
the rise again, part of the Reformed Baptist movement.
</P>
<P>
   The end of Spurgeon's life was fraught with anguish, as he was
involved in the ``Down Grade Controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   It began when Spurgeon wrote about Baptists who ``downgraded''
the authority of the Bible, the decline of prayer meetings and the
worldliness of Baptist ministers who attended theater and sometimes
sponsored entertainment in their churches.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Baptist Union attacked Spurgeon and accused him
of smearing all preachers. In 1887, he withdrew from the Baptist
Union, which was still the major organization of Baptists in
England.
</P>
<P>
   Both Spurgeon's conservative brand of worship and the more
liberal form practiced by the Baptist Union have declined in
numbers. Today, there are about 139,000 members of the Baptist
Union in England, 39,000 in Wales and 16,000 in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptists might learn from their British cousins. Some
conservative U.S. Baptists blame the membership decline among
Baptists in the British Isles on the rise of liberalism. But could
it have been caused by the controversy itself?
</P>
<P>
   The 15.5 million-member Southern Baptist Convention is still the
nation's largest non-Catholic church group. But in 1998, the
denomination, which has been in conflict for two decades, recorded
a membership decline of 162,000. It was the first decline since
1926.
</P>
<P>
   Some Southern Baptists have opted to remove ``Baptist'' from
their church name. They say it drives away some who don't want to
be involved with the modern conservative-moderate ``Down Grade
Controversy'' that has split the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   If Spurgeon could counsel Southern Baptists today, I think he
would tell them to resolve their disputes and focus on teaching
Jesus' profound thoughts about loving one's neighbor, even if you
disagree with him.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones covers religion for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You
can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
