<HEADER>
A6166 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-BOWFINGER     08-13 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BOWFINGER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUNACY RULES IN `BOWFINGER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bowfinger'' is neither the funniest movie ever made nor the
sharpest in Steve Martin's wild-and-crazy canon. But it has two
things going for it that no other comedy banging around theaters
currently has.
</P>
<P>
   One is Eddie Murphy. The other is Mind Head.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, for those who live on the planet Xenon, is the awesomely
gifted comic whose famed characterizations have spanned a
linguist-veterinarian (``Dr. Doolittle''), a bulky academic (``The
Nutty Professor'') and an apple-green bendable toy (Gumby,
``Saturday Night Live'').
</P>
<P>
   In ``Bowfinger,'' a manic goof on Hollywood, he plays two more:
A paranoid, egomaniacal movie star named Kit Ramsey and a
look-alike dork with an orthodontic grin, Jiff. Both are welcome
additions to Murphy's rubber-faced oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   Mind Head, meanwhile, is Kit Ramsey's psychic balm _ a
glistening New Age think tank where disciples wear white pyramids
on their heads and chimes tinkle liquidly in the background. At
Mind Head, which looks like the bastard child of Scientology and
intense crystal therapy, Kit calms himself by reciting the three
``Happy Premises'': One, there are no aliens out to get him. Two,
there is no giant foot ``trying to squash me.'' And three, ``Even
though I feel as though I might ignite, I probably won't.''
</P>
<P>
   This is loopy stuff, and that's what makes it so delicious: It's
a treat watching Murphy wrap his face around some of the words
coming out of his mouth. Frank Oz (who helmed 1997's sweetly funny
``In &AMP; Out'') directed ``Bowfinger,'' but the film's out-there
humor has more to do with Martin's script than Oz's Muppets-honed
sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue is hyper-articulate, riffing and weird; Kit's first
scene has him attacking a screenplay because it contains 1,458
instances of the letter ``K'' (which means that ``KKK appears in
this script 486 times!''). We're used to hearing Martin speak his
own lines _ in ``The Man With Two Brains,'' for instance, or ``L.A.
Story'' _ but it's a wild incongruity when Murphy does it. The
results are inspired.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of the film, it's lopsided but scattered with
hilarity. Martin is Bobby Bowfinger, a permanently down-on-his-luck
director whose career, thus far, has included work on such
cinematic masterworks as ``The Yugo Story'' and ``A Bucket of
Blondes!!''
</P>
<P>
   Determined to direct a science-fiction epic called ``Chubby
Rain'' (in which aliens invade Earth via precipitation, ``making
the raindrops chubby''), Bowfinger tries to sign the industry's
hottest action star. Namely, Kit Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   When the star declines _ he actually shoots the script with a
revolver _ Bowfinger plows ahead anyway, filming entire
Kit-centered scenes without the actor's knowledge. Imagine Kit's
horror when strangers walk up to him and start spouting dire
warnings about ``pod people'' and extraterrestrial crusades. ``When
you left Phoenix, it wasn't because you wanted to raise soybeans!''
yells one such intruder. ``You've come down from Kentucky with your
damned aliens!''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy is a marvel in these scenes, and he's disarming when he
materializes as the squinty Jiff. Even if ``Bowfinger'' had nothing
else to recommend it, it would still feature Murphy's most
satisfying performance since ``The Nutty Professor'' _ and the
second, after ``Holy Man,'' in which he dodges cars on a whizzing
highway.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's self-centered-loser routine will seem familiar at best,
tired at worst, to anyone who knows his films, but ``Bowfinger'' is
so breathlessly odd that there's enough else to occupy us.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Baranski (``Bulworth''), playing a long-suffering
actress, is the brightest spot in a game cast that also includes
Terence Stamp as a wondrously oily Mind Head therapist and the
ever-doe-like Heather Graham as an eager starlet. But the film
belongs to Murphy _ and to Martin's screenplay, in which erudite
lunacy rules supreme. In a summer of baked-goods gross-outs, this
is fine news indeed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
