<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6169 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-VESSELS-H     08-13 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-VESSELS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS AMBULANCE NEEDS HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you tied a tourniquet to stop the gangrene from setting in?
Got a broken leg? Broken arm? Broken neck? Has a bloody park
shooting or drive-by left you badly wounded?
</P>
<P>
   If yes, then you're probably in need of medical attention. But
if the choices are dying or letting junkie paramedics Jimmy and Tom
take you to the hospital, you're better off with the former _ the
latter'll get you killed anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In that fine medical tradition of ``MASH'' and ``Hospital,''
Scott Ziehl's seedy ``Broken Vessels'' makes a strong case in favor
of on-the-job surveillance for Los Angeles paramedics _ if not for
our protection then for our sadistic entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   They defibrillate the strong-hearted, curse at the wounded and
leave the ailing for dead. The film's small consolation is that
there's more substance abuse than patient abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we supposed to be saints 'cause we wear these jumpsuits?''
Jimmy (Todd Field) half-comically asks Tom (Jason London), whose
coke 'n' heroin 'n' glue-induced downward spiral has him vomiting
in aquariums and behind sofas. London's Khaki purity gets a nicely
frayed makeover that eventually plays reluctant Trapper John to
Field's insinuating Hawkeye.
</P>
<P>
   Field has a quiet menace that makes Jimmy the paramedic from
hell without turning him into a monster. The only person more
in-and-out of it is Jimmy's wastoid of a neighbor (murmured and
flitted with something approaching eloquence by Susan Traylor).
</P>
<P>
   Written by Ziehl, David Baer and John MacMahon as a 12-step
cautionary tale, ``Vessels'' moves like the pitch-black-comedy
``Cops'' or ``Two Smack Fiends in an Ambulance,'' a bruising parody
given snapshots of force in its marriage of life-threatening
seriousness to fevered absurdity and cinematography under the
influence. The film's sickest joke is that for Jimmy this paramedic
thing is just a temporary gig. He really wants to work for the
LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
