<HEADER>
A6171 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-OGRE-HNS &LR;      08-13 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-OGRE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALKOVICH LIVES UP TO THE PART IN `OGRE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WALTER ADDIEGO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Ogre'' is a chilling study of delusions and moral
blindness in a self-proclaimed innocent who becomes a dedicated
servant of his Nazi captors. He's a simpleminded Frenchman with a
special, disturbing affinity for children who uses his gift in a
hellish manner.
</P>
<P>
   The film was directed by Volker Schlondorff, whose 1979
Oscar-winning ``The Tin Drum'' dealt with similar themes in a story
equally full of mythological overtones, though in a more grotesque
and surreal style. Both pictures (which the director co-wrote with
Jean-Claude Carriere) view Naziism through central figures who are
child-men convinced they have a special destiny.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Tin Drum,'' the hero literally refuses to grow up;
here, the main character, Abel, though an adult, is more like a
hulking boy _ a loner and a naif with a menacing (and unhinged)
side, and no great shakes at adult relationships.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1925 and Abel, an orphan, is a misfit student at a strict
French boarding school. Facing another severe beating for breaking
the rules, he angrily wishes that the school would burn down.
Immediately, a fire erupts in the chapel. Abel believes he has been
favored by the fates, even though his best friend is killed in the
blaze.
</P>
<P>
   The adult Abel (John Malkovich) works as an auto mechanic, but
his quiet life ends abruptly when a child he unwisely has
befriended falsely accuses him of sexually molesting her. It's
1939, and the judge sends Abel to the army instead of prison. He's
captured by the Germans and sent to a POW camp in East Prussia.
</P>
<P>
   The camp is located near the elaborate hunting lodge used by
Field Marshal Hermann Goering (Volker Spengler), Hitler's
designated successor. Abel winds up a servant and handyman there.
</P>
<P>
   The corpulent and corrupt Goering counts himself a master hunter
and relishes tracking and shooting stags in his forested domain _ a
fairy-tale setting infected by madness. This Goering is a barbed
portrait of the decay that results from nearly unlimited power, but
Spengler (a stalwart of R.W. Fassbinder's films) borders on
overplaying the blackly comical aspect. Abel's next assignment
takes him even deeper into the woods.
</P>
<P>
   At a castle that's both home to a German nobleman (Armin
Mueller-Stahl) and a military school where Aryan youth are molded
into SS officers, Abel's rapport with students and horses is
noticed. As he listens to the school doctor extol the Nordic racial
type, Abel admires the rigorous physical training these handsome
boys undergo.
</P>
<P>
   He is awarded a privileged position: In a robe and on horseback,
he patrols the countryside with a pack of attack dogs, seeking
``recruits'' _ willing or not _ among peasant children to fill the
school's declining ranks. He believes he is doing these youngsters
a great service. Thus he earns his nickname among the common folk,
The Ogre, and prepares the audience for the film's powerful ending.
</P>
<P>
   Schlondorff has said he built the film around Malkovich, and the
actor lives up to the responsibility. His fine performance never
permits us to oversimplify the character. His Abel retains a kind
of virtue despite his various services to the Third Reich; he has a
child's sensibility that makes him unable to see evil around him
for what it is. He is simply fascinated with the machinery, the
spectacle, of Goering's lodge and the SS school.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he clings fiercely to the notion of innocence and the need
to protect it; hence his identification with animals and children.
</P>
<P>
   The director's films, despite their sometimes dreamlike content,
generally avoid extravagant flourishes; they are tightly controlled
and distanced. Here, Schlondorff alternates between black and
white, color and sepia, which are employed carefully to recount
what he calls a ``realist fairy tale.'' (He used those word for the
film's source novel, ``The Erl King'' by Michel Tournier, which won
the Prix Goncourt, France's top literary prize.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ogre,'' by the way, was filmed in 1996 (Schlondorff's most
recent release in this country was last year's unsuccessful
``Palmetto''). That it's taken so long to arrive should tell you
something about the state of art film distribution these days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
