<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME THRILL SEEKERS ARE IN OVER THEIR HEADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every so often sea-loving adventurers should check in with Dodge
Morgan just for the heck of it.
</P>
<P>
   Since the entrepreneur-cum-world record setting
sailor-cum-newspaper publisher _ and philosopher always _ became in
1986 the first solo United States sailor to circumnavigate the
globe without stopping, Morgan's byline pops up all over the marine
world.
</P>
<P>
   From his 30-acre island off the coast of Harpswell, Maine,
Morgan, 67, writes regularly for Points East, a Portland magazine
that is one of the best on sailing in New England. He is planning
to launch a new, homemade, 35-foot steamboat called Quiet Presense
this month at Handy Boat in Falmouth Foreside, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   With 150,000 miles of blue water sailing past his stern, Morgan
recently has weighed in with authority on the matter of Coast Guard
rescues for boats in trouble. What most disturbs him is the clash
of a new culture of thrill-seeking adventurers with the cold, sober
realities the ocean can suddenly impose on recreational boaters,
or, as Morgan puts it, ``those who go to sea for the hell of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Morgan set out from Portland, Maine, on a Ted Hood
60-footer, American Promise, which suffered damage to the
self-steering gear in an October Atlantic storm, forcing it to put
into Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Having restarted the record attempt from there a few days later,
Morgan sailed around the globe nonstop, returning to Bermuda 159
days later to claim a world record. He is still the only American
to have made such a passage.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a team of sailors from the Naval Academy sailed
American Promise to Morgan's home waters in Maine. And though she
has been fully restored and fitted out as a training vessel, Morgan
enjoyed seeing the young sailors sail his record-setting boat, but
declined an invitation to board her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like,'' he quipped a few years ago, ``seeing your first
love in the hands of a bunch of midshipmen.'' He has never
reboarded Promise since dropping her at Annapolis a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Morgan is dead serious about the necessity of self-reliance
at sea. He was critical of a Naval Academy team that was sailing
Promise a few years ago when a collision with a coal barge resulted
in her sinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every boating accident,'' he said at the time, ``is due to
human error.''
</P>
<P>
   What especially troubles Morgan about the modern boating scene
is the mentality of thrill seekers who have ``been trained on
bungee jumping and sky diving _ activities that offer the thrills
without the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Boating is different, he says. From the time the sailor or
powerboater casts off from shore, he must assume full
responsibility for whatever happens, right down to drowning.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The skipper) has to assume,'' says Morgan, ``that the radio
won't transmit and the lifeboat won't inflate, that the Coast Guard
won't come _ and take care of the boat no matter what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan mentions the case of a sailor who called for a Coast
Guard rescue three days out of Bermuda recently. ``He wanted to
abandon his boat,'' says Morgan, ``because of sea-sickness.'' On
every one of his 27 passages from Maine to the West Indies, he has
found at least one boat along the way that has been abandoned by
its crew.
</P>
<P>
   The dangerous combination, he says in his argument against Coast
Guard offshore rescues, ``is a culture that celebrates adventure
seeking and the ease of taking a boat offshore.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety seminars, he notes, emphasize rescue procedures, such as
electronic emergency signals and helicopter rescues, rather than
individual responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is often too late,'' Morgan writes in a recent editorial
published in Soundings, ``that the sailor learns that the sea is
not an ersatz adventure or virtual experience. Too late to learn
that the vessel at sea is an oasis of independence and no place to
apply our land-oriented culture of `my mistakes are really someone
else's responsibility.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan scoffs at a culture that puts warning signs on snow
blowers reading ``DO NOT PLACE HANDS AND FEET IN BLADE AREA'' and
health hazard signs on cigarette packs.
</P>
<P>
   Another contribution to dangerous unpreparedness at sea is the
modern technology that can make hulls stronger, simplifies
sail-handling systems and self-steering gears, and gives skippers
simple, push-button navigation ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can lull anyone into complacency and trick many without
credentials into the ultimate trouble,'' says Morgan. The following
logical connections, he says, are essential to sailors: ``It is
truism that sailing in heavy weather is inevitable for anyone who
sails and that sailing through a storm is inevitable for any sailor
who goes offshore. . . . The boat under way becomes one's total
existence, a world isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan also scoffs at the ``absurdity of using the sea as a race
course'' and recalls that when he returned to Chebeague Island in
Maine after his world rounding with Promise, the locals were not
particularly impressed. ``They've made their living at sea for
generations, and every family has lost a member at sea,'' he says.
``They don't quite understand people using the sea for play.''
</P>
<P>
   But as long as people these days ``go to sea for the hell of
it,'' he adds, they should at least understand their fundamental
responsibility. ``The sea does have a way of culling out fools,''
says the ever-irascible Dodge Morgan, ``but from what I can see,
there also seems to be an inexhaustible supply of them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain covers the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
