<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAMA PAR FOR THE COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh, those crazy golfers.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, they will be hiring baseball umpires union boss
Richie Phillips and demanding even more money from the PGA, the
country clubs, product manufacturers, and spectators.
</P>
<P>
   It's never about the money. Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Tiger Woods and David Duval split $1.4 million in
a made-for-television match. Now the golfers are talking about the
Ryder Cup and charitable contributions.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is airing the PGA Championship this weekend from the Medinah
Country Club near Chicago, and the network's announcing team is all
over the latest golf dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Host Jim Nantz had his own take on the Woods-Duval showdown. ``I
thought the event got totally misrepresented by a lot of people in
the media,'' Nantz told reporters. ``It was one of those topics
that everybody in the world thought they were qualified to have an
opinion on, and really it was nothing more than two of the
top-ranked players in the world going and playing a round of golf.
I watched it and enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Nantz said, he thought the match was a great idea.
</P>
<P>
   Nantz was less passionate about the Ryder Cup contributions.
``The issue is whether the players will get a charitable
contribution for particpating in the Ryder Cup, where they could
donate $100,000 to a charity of their choice,'' Nantz said. ``The
players just want a chance to make a charitable donation; it's not
something the players are walking around in a fury about.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS golf analyst David Feherty also downplayed the story.
``There are a lot of players that would pay to be on the Ryder Cup
team,'' he said. ``What the PGA does with the money is a different
story. A lot more should be donated to charity. I think the players
are right that there should be some sort of contribution; but in
terms of personal gain, it's the one pure sport event of the year
that players go out there and play for something other than
money.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the subplots over this weekend is the Ryder Cup points.
Another is the course at Medinah. Broadcasting the event is tough,
largely because CBS will be doing live coverage Saturday and Sunday
between 1:30 and 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike other sports, we are on air for the entire time,'' said
CBS producer Lance Barrow. ``There are no halftimes or timeouts. In
this sport we go on air until we go off air, no matter what time it
is. It includes our people in the truck, our announcers, but more
importantly our technical people who are running up and down the
golf course with cameras on their backs and microphones.''
</P>
<P>
   And Medinah is an extremely long course. ``There are scenarios
in golf that you don't deal with in other sports,'' Nantz said.
``You have more than 100 golfers on 100 acres of the course, all
firing at the same time. There are a lot of different stories
spread out all over the place, and the coordination . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``What's very deceiving about Medinah is we are all gawking at
the 7,401 yards and saying, `It just keeps getting longer and
longer.' But a lot of that extra space is in the par-5s. An extra
100 to 200 yards has been stacked in those par-5s, and they are
going to be better suited to a guy like Justin Leonard, who's a
great wedge player and will know how to handle championship
pressure and keep his ball in play.''
</P>
<P>
   Nantz said the long course doesn't necessarily mean that a
long-ball hitter will win. ``You look at the history of Medinah and
all the winners here have been noted for being grinders,'' he said.
``They have been guys who could keep it in play and not guys
hitting ridiculous drives.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
