<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMINICAN-COLONEL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINICAN COMMUNITY HONORS TOP-FLIGHT FEMALE PHYSICIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, Mass. _ Antonia Silva-Hale left the rutted roads, palm
trees and sugarcane fields of the Dominican Republic when she was
just 10. But in her heart, the island country was always her home.
</P>
<P>
   Her family moved several times, always seeking to better their
educations and improve their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, at age 29, Silva-Hale, living in the United States,
completed medical school in Missouri. Young, single, and the
youngest of a protective family, she found herself looking for a
second home.
</P>
<P>
   A friend suggested the military _ an instant family providing a
good job, housing, and medical patients _ a structured, predictable
world within a world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had come from a very sheltered environment,'' she said. ``I
didn't even know how to drive.''
</P>
<P>
   She walked into the nearest Air Force recruiting office and
signed up. Quickly she rose, becoming assistant professor of
medicine, and then a colonel, the first woman from the Dominican
Republican to reach that rank in the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Boston's Dominican Festival is honoring Silva-Hale as
a role model for other women, naming her Woman of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's an example for Latino women because she has got this
important position,'' said Dominico Cabrale, president of the
Dominican festival, which will be held in Jamaica Plain this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very happy and proud for what she's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Dominican community is growing in numbers and
visibility. About 8,000 Dominicans lived in the area in 1990, when
the last census was taken. Although there are no official tallies,
community leaders say the population has jumped to anywhere from
20,000 to 100,000, including undocumented immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, Dominicans have been stereotyped as violent or
criminally minded, several said. ``But a lot of people do good
things and go in silence,'' said Maria Contreras, executive
director of Soldiers of Health, a health care program in Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   She described Silva-Hale as ``very humble, intelligent and
dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Just over 5 feet and barely 115 pounds, Silva-Hale doesn't
immediately look like the type who would have a commanding military
presence.
</P>
<P>
   However, the petite physician, who is Aerospace Medicine Flight
Commander at Hanscom Air Base is one of only 270 women who
currently hold the rank in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Silva-Hale, 44, is thrilled by the Woman of the Year Award,
which makes plain that ``remembering where you come from is what
it's all about,'' she said. ``If you forget that, you'll get lost
along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   She was born in San Pedro de Macoris, a poor, rural village
about 40 miles east of Santo Domingo.
</P>
<P>
   The village also was home to two other Dominican heroes whose
photos adorn her office walls: baseball stars Pedro Martinez and
Sammy Sosa. ``By being good players who also behave well, they've
made it easier for people to notice other Dominicans who are doing
good things,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Silva-Hale also hopes to inspire others _ as a Dominican who
used education to hit her own sort of homerun.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dominican Republic, her parents were high school teachers
with high aims for their four children. Even as a preschooler, she
sat in the back of a crude one-room schoolhouse, watching an aunt
teach. ``That's how I learned my first letters,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When she was about 5 years old, her father moved to Santo
Domingo to get an engineering degree, and the family followed.
``The biggest picture in the house was a photograph of my father in
his graduation gown,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But her mother was unsatisfied with opportunities in the
Dominican Republic. ``She said, `This is not going to cut it. We've
got to get these kids educated.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When civil war erupted in 1965, the family moved again, this
time to San Juan, Puerto Rico. There Silva-Hale earned a bachelor's
degree in science, graduating magna cum laude, and then a doctorate
in medicine at the University of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   She chose medicine, she said, ``because it seemed like the
toughest thing to tackle. Why go the easy way?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, she completed her postgraduate education with a
residency in internal medicine at St. Louis University Medical
Center, in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   She married Douglas Hale a few years later and they have three
children: Julia, 9, Douglas, 8, and David, 6. Her mother, Ramona
Silva, 72, also lives with the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very idealistic, which permeates everything she does,''
said Hale, a transplant surgery fellow at Beth Israel-Deaconess
Hospital. ``She's a big booster of medicine as a career, and
shepherds students through the process.''
</P>
<P>
   At Hanscom, Silva-Hale supervises a staff of about 35 people and
also provides direct patient care to about 150 pilots and their
families. She still makes house calls on the base. ``Our goal,''
she said, ``is to keep the flyers flying.''
</P>
<P>
   The times she treasures most are small moments when she can
treat a minor illness or allay someone's fears. She vividly
remembered one woman she treated several years ago who was
agonizing about whether she had cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Silva-Hale examined the woman and concluded she had a minor skin
irritation, perhaps a wart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget the look of relief on that lady's face,''
she said. ``It's simple things that make it all worthwhile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6178 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-BROKEDOWN-BOS &LR;      08-13 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BROKEDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT-SO-UGLY AMERICANS FACE PRISON ON DRUG CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
BROKEDOWN PALACE 
Directed by: Jonathan Kaplan 
Screenplay by: David Arata 
Starring: Claire Danes, Kate Beckinsale, Bill Pullman, Jacqueline
Kim, Lou Diamond Phillips, Daniel Lapaine, Tom Amandes 
Running time: 99 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (brief strong language and drug-related material) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Brokedown Palace'' is yet another in the sad little sub-genre
of films about young Americans imprisoned abroad, usually on
drug-related charges. The thing that sets it apart from such films
as ``Midnight Express'' and last year's ``Return to Paradise'' is
that its protagonists are innocent, female, and embodied in
uncommonly compelling fashion by Claire Danes and Kate Beckinsale.
They play recent high school grads whose only crime is a disastrous
naivete that begins when they tell their parents that they're going
to Hawaii, but go to Thailand, instead.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly have they been sweet-talked by the same Australian bloke
who gives them air tickets to Hong Kong, where he promises them
various treats, than they find themselves arrested at Bangkok
airport. Two tins of cocaine are found in one of their backpacks.
The number is escalated to six by the time the bureaucracy is
finished grinding out its paperwork. But that's the least of their
troubles. A stern judge sentences them to 33 years apiece in
prison. They're marched off to a women's correctional institute
whose nickname gives the film its name. The Aussie dealer, of
course, is nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Their only hope, after frantic phone calls home and many letters
to government officials, is an expatriate lawyer of apparently
rumpled decency named Hank the Yank (Bill Pullman), who owes a lot
of his success to his Thai wife (acted with unstereotyped freshness
by Jacqueline Kim). Meanwhile, they sit and stagnate. A few
well-meaning souls tell them that they at least have each other.
But they're not altogether consoled by this circumstance. Part of
the reason has to do with a mild romantic competition between the
two for the slick Aussie's attentions.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from that, Danes' Alice is annoyed at Beckinsale's Darlene
for having signed a confession in Thai that she couldn't even read
and simply assumed was her statement, not a document admitting
guilt. Darlene, meanwhile, sharply reminds Alice that she should
have checked the contents of her backpack, in which the drugs were
found. In addition, we gather from Alice's conduct that she's got
something of a chip on her shoulder, justified in the case of
Darlene's insurance broker father, who callously blames Alice for
everything bad, past and present, that ever happened to his
daughter. Also feeding Alice's anger is the fact that she grew up
motherless. And part of it is an underclass thing.
</P>
<P>
   With her thrusting glances and impulsive body language, Danes'
Alice personifies loose cannon behavior that's both defensive,
aggressive and anti-social. Beckinsale wears the clean-scrubbed,
together look of a young woman for whom the system has always
worked, and who thus busies herself writing letters to authorities.
The chemistry between them is dimensioned and complex and part of
the reason has to be the direction of Jonathan Kaplan, who after
``Heart Like a Wheel'' and ``The Accused,'' is indisputably at the
forefront of male directors of women. The film's most piercing
moment isn't an action moment, but one where the women are visited
by three American pals from back home. ``You're in college?,''
Darlene asks, jolted to realize how her own life has dead-ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brokedown Palace,'' filmed in authentic-looking locales in the
Philippines, is reasonably interesting as a detective story, too.
It unfolds credibly when it turns out that Pullman's lawyer
actually is conscientious about doing his job. Thanks to his wife's
savvy, he's not unaware of the ins and outs of local drug
trafficking and weak links in the chain of Thai law enforcement.
But mostly ``Brokedown Palace'' works as well as it does because it
gives two high-powered actresses a chance to play off one another.
It's reasonably subtle in making the point that their privileged
white American status works against them in the context of another
culture. It pretty much avoids self-pity, although it certainly
makes the point that the prison plumbing isn't all it might be and
that the cockroaches are tougher than the guards. Frankly, though,
this type of film is beginning to suffer from a certain
overfamiliarity. It also gives off a whiff of xenophobia. It may
just be that ``Midnight Express'' should be made mandatory viewing
in US passport offices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
