<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6180 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-13 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALY'S DISSERVICE TO OUR DAUGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sisters! If Mary Daly won't let our sons into her Boston College
classroom, she shouldn't teach our daughters either.
</P>
<P>
   It's unfair to BC's male students. And it's a disservice to BC
women. They can't learn what they need to know about the elements
of today's patriarchal and sexist world in her cloister.
</P>
<P>
   Banning men from Daly's classroom fails women in a big way. It
does as little to stamp out sexism as forced busing of
schoolchildren does to stamp out racism.
</P>
<P>
   Daly is most often described as a ``renowned radical feminist
philosopher.'' Some people consider her a prophet, others call her
a nut. There is no question this is one strong-minded, even
single-minded, woman _ now locked in a bitter legal dispute with BC
over its demand that she resign from her tenured teaching job for
refusing to allow men to attend her classes.
</P>
<P>
   The professor wants to teach her class on ``Feminist Ethics''
only to women. She took the position that she would rather resign
than admit male students. In a recent court ruling, Middlesex Judge
Martha B. Sosman said BC has adequate cause to fire Daly, citing
her defiance of college policy that all courses be open to male and
female students.
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of personal experience and plenty of anecdotal
evidence, I agree with Daly's underlying premise: Sexism _
discrimination on the basis of sex, most notably against women _
remains a fact of life.
</P>
<P>
   So what do we do about it?
</P>
<P>
   Studies prove that from grade school to graduate school, males
dominate the classroom. Statistics also show that more graduates of
women's colleges earn advanced degrees, especially in math and
science, than do women from co-ed schools. And no one needs studies
or statistics to conclude that women talk differently about just
about everything when men are not present.
</P>
<P>
   That information is often marshaled to buttress the case for
Daly's women-only classroom policy. But what we still need to do is
change the overall reality for women at BC and elsewhere _ not
create one tiny, protected piece of turf where a feminist teacher
teaches feminist ethics only to females. Daly may nurture her
female students and empower them within the narrow confines of her
classroom. What happens when they step outside her door to confront
the Heights and the world beyond?
</P>
<P>
   What might have made some sense in the late 1970s, when Daly
first started banning men, is harder to justify 20 years later. As
a way to remedy the much more subtle sexism of the 90s, it just
doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Women today have much more access to position. How to exercise
the power that comes with that position _ that is the piece of the
equation that still eludes many of us. We can't exercise power only
against each other and consider ourselves successful. So we must
include men in our lesson plan. We have to speak up with men in the
room, not just with women. We have to push, achieve, excel, and
compete woman-to-man, not just woman-to-woman.
</P>
<P>
   This silly fight over Daly's women-only classroom also lets BC
look reasonable, all the while obscuring some truths about the
college. Women were first admitted to the school in 1970; today, 54
percent of BC graduate and undergraduate students are female. At
the same time, women account for 33 percent of BC's 427 tenured
faculty members.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show that BC's student body is more diverse than
people often think. But there is still a lingering perception of an
old boy network made up of old boys. The term ``BC crowd'' gives
rise to a stereotypical image of mostly white men who left the
Heights for other heights of power and influence in Boston. The
image is intensified by the jock concerns of the BC crowd, such as
the rallying behind a football stadium or new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The power base at BC is still very, very male. And Daly is
making it very, very easy for those powerful men to tear her down.
Fighting to maintain a women-only class makes her sound
old-fashioned and rigid.
</P>
<P>
   I would love to have a teacher like Mary Daly explain the facts
of life to my son. But I would hate to have a teacher like Mary
Daly offer a false reality to my daughter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
