<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6183 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-KATZENMO     08-13 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-KATZENMOYER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS GROOM ROOKIE FOR OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ His nickname, ``Big Cat'', conjurs the image
of a sabre-toothed mauler, deftly sizing up its prey, ready to
pounce, to shred Oh, how that would suit the Patriots. How they
could use a big, agile, menacing Andy Katzenmoyer to step in at
middle linebacker and be the predator of their prayers.
</P>
<P>
   New England opens its 1999 NFL exhibition schedule Friday night
when the Redskins visit Foxboro Stadium, and the 21-year-old
Katzenmoyer will start at an unfamiliar position _ the sideline.
With barely two weeks of practice under his belt, and already one
position change into his career, he will begin the night looking at
veteran Marty Moore fill in for the injured Ted Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   For now, ``Big Cat'' will have to do what predators do best . .
. watch and wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way yes, but in a way no,'' he said Thursday when asked
if he was slightly relieved not to be starting this early into his
apprenticeship. ``No, because I've always been the starter.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt he'll be that here, too. There really isn't much doubt
about that. The Patriots used the 28th pick in this year's draft to
bring him here, and that was before Johnson, the club's starting
middle linebacker the last four years, tore up his left biceps
tendon last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is for Katzenmoyer to be groomed in the exhibition
season and then plugged into Johnson's spot for the Sept. 12 opener
against the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Ambitious? Yes. Practical? We'll see, perhaps as early as Friday
night, when he's expected to sub for Moore and get ample playing
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conditioning-wise, I'm fine,'' said Katzenmoyer, who in the
fall of 1996 became the first freshman linebacker to start at Ohio
State, only to follow that up by winning the Butkus Award as the
college game's top linebacker as a sophomore. ``The speed game,
it's hard to prepare for that _ you've just got to go out there and
just interact with people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mingling on the gridiron has never been much of an issue for
Katzenmoyer. Raised in Westerville, Ohio, at the outer edge of the
OSU campus, he didn't take up the game until age 12. Two years
later, he was a 230-pound freshman, playing two ways _ running back
and linebacker _ for Westerville South High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be physical,'' said Katzenmoyer, recalling the advice of his
high school coach, Rocky Pentello. ``Just run down the field, try
to run through people. Be mean, nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   The message became Katzenmoyer's, as well as Westerville's,
mantra. By his sophomore year, he recalled, upwards of 100 students
turned out for the varsity squad. The next year, the number had
dwindled to 40. His senior year, only 32 showed up for fall
practice. The problem wasn't shrinking enrollment, but rather
shrinking violets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost intimidiating for some guys, I guess,'' recalled
Katzenmoyer. ``It was just the nature of our team. We were a big
physical team, and we just loved to hit and make plays. Some guys
didn't like that, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, social interaction has proven a trickier playing
field for Katzenmoyer. He all but became a Sports Illustrated
whipping boy for his lack of tenacity in the classroom. The
magazine referred to him as a ``noted classroom slacker'' just two
months ago when it noted that his summer school curriculum at OSU
included a course entitled ``AIDS: What Every College Student
Should Know.'' Turned off, in part, by SI's portrayal of him in a
feature the previous summer, he went virtually the entire '98
football season without talking to the media, and ultimately issued
only a terse written statement in February when he decided to leave
OSU a year early and turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, Katzenmoyer was charged with drunken driving
in Columbus, his blood .033 over the limit at .133. He pleaded no
contest, the incident ultimately costing him a $300 fine, his
driver's license (suspended for six months), and a heap of bad
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I made some mistakes in college,'' Katzenmoyer
said. ``And (Sports Illustrated) decided to point that out to the
whole world. That's fine. I can't do anything about that. I just
hope kids growing up now can learn from my mistakes and not get in
trouble. The whole thing . . . it was just a bad time in my life.
But everything has moved on since then.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These days, with his name on a four-year, $3.5 million contract,
things are moving at warp speed. With Johnson considered a given at
middle linebacker, the coaching staff figured Katzenmoyer for an
outside spot heading into training camp. Even then, he would have
to knock veteran Tedy Bruschi out of the spot. All that was tossed
to the wind last Saturday afternoon when Johnson's biceps rolled up
like a window shade during the club's intrasquad scrimmage at
Foxborough. The very next morning, head coach Pete Carroll had
Bruschi making Johnson's calls in the huddle and Katzenmoyer
holding down Johnson's ``Mike'' position.
</P>
<P>
   ``His head's got to be spinning right now,'' said Steve Nelson,
the former Patriots great who, as a rookie in 1974, also had to
make a quick transition from college to the pro game. ``He'll be
fine, physically, but that college-to-pro adjustment takes time.
The kid's had, what, two weeks before his first preseason game? In
'74, heck, we reported on June 22 and practiced for six weeks, and
then we had six exhibition games to get ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson played his college ball at North Dakota State, a Division
1-AA program, and then started every game at middle linebacker his
rookie year. It wasn't until the following season, he recalled,
that he began to feel comfortable at the spot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
