<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
Aug. 14. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   BOMB _ For more than 80 years, chemical weapons and other
ordnance from a World War I-era research project have stayed buried
beneath a cozy upscale Washington, D.C. neighborhood. 32. David
Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   SEATS: When members of the U.S. House return from recess next
month, they will have new bulletproof seatbacks on their chairs on
the House floor, replacing less effective metal plates installed 45
years ago after some Puerto Rican nationals opened fire from the
gallery. The project is being done along with other Capitol
security upgrades, like better metal detectors and surveillance
cameras in the wake of last year's shooting that left two police
officers. Kevin Murphy. 23.
</P>
<P>
   BIO _ Gary Anson worries that even today's chicken manure ain't
what it used to be. He struggles mightily to keep his corn,
soybeans and wheat pristine _ free of chemicals and
laboratory-tinkered genetics. When he succeeds, his crops earn
organic status and fetch a premium price. But keeping his fields
unspoiled by high-tech agriculture is a chore without end. Anson
belongs to a growing class of farmers trying to sell food in a
lucrative market even as the planting of genetically engineered
crops explodes across the American bread basket _ threatening to
spoil the organic fun. 40. Photos. Scott Canon.
</P>
<P>
   CAUCUS: The voters in Lamoni, Iowa, are popular folks.
Presidential candidates pass through, knocking on doors, attending
their pancake dinners. That's because the Iowa straw poll is
Saturday. Just 30 miles away, Jean Nichols wouldn't even dream of
getting her calls returned by a campaign. That's because she's the
Democratic party chair in Harrison County. Mo. A lighthearted look
at the difference between adjacent counties, both with similar
concerns and demographics. One is a political prize, the other an
irrelevant piece of the electoral puzzle. ``We vote and we have
things to say, too,'' Nichols laments. Oscar Avila. 22. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHART: With a new school year just weeks away, some of the new
charter schools in KC are scrambling to find buildings to hold
classes. But the charters apparently are having no problems drawing
students from private and parochial schools and the school
district. Will include comments from parents enrolling their kids
in some of the charters. Photo of preparations at Southwest Charter
School. Phil O'Connor. 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   GAY: Joe Wetherbee didn't know much about gays or lesbians when
he opened the first gay nightclub in the Northland. He was just
trying to revive his sagging bar business. But the last two years
have been a learning experience for Wetherbee, perhaps the only
straight owner of a gay club in town. The ex-Marine is brash,
sprinkling conversation with four-letter words and politically
incorrect statements. But slowly, lesbians _ a long-ignored segment
up north _ have come to trust him. Two women even held a wedding
there. And he finds himself spending more time at his gay club than
at his biker bar in Grandview. This week, his bar is one of the
sponsors of the North American Gay Amateur Athletic Alliance World
Series in Kansas City. A look at The Education of Joe Wetherbee.
Oscar Avila. 35. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBE: Nez Perce Tribe holds a ceremony at Fort Leavenworth in
honor of tribal members who were confined at the forst in 1877 and
1878 after Chief Joseph surrendered to the U.S. Army. About 100 of
them died of malaria and other causes. Joe Popper. 32. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   KCLOB: When lobbyists bearing gifts make the rounds in Jefferson
City, Kansas City-area lawmakers get less than their colleagues
from around the state. It's not necessarily that Kansas City
lawmakers are more virtuous than the rest of the legislature. But
lobbyists on average lavish fewer tickets, expensive meals and
other benefits on the Kansas City delegation, a computer analysis
of lobbyist gifts shows. Kit Wagar. 28. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   VOTH: Profile of Kansas Board of Education vice president Harold
Voth, a moderate who provided the swing vote to pass new science
standards that de-emphasize the importance of evolution. Jim
Sullinger.
</P>
<P>
   BUREAU. Johnson County, Kan., where the numbers of county
employees have soared, shows what's happening nationally: a new
Census Bureau study, released today, finds that the total state and
local government workers in the U.S. has grown. In Kansas, the
numbers have grown, and on a per capita basis the state has the
sixth-highest number of government workers in the country. Missouri
is in the middle. 25. John A. Dvorak.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   FERC _ Though the Western Resources-KCP&AMP;L merger has hit a big
Kansas snag, there appears to be some progress in getting a
settlement with federal regulators. Steve Everly
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ Y2K column. David Hayes, Finn Bullar
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   BOGGS. Of the greatest 3,000-hit baseball players in history,
Wade Boggs may have the most human story of them all. It wasn't
just Boggs' career that played out on a public stage. His life also
earned tabloid headlines. He had a much-publicized affair in the
'80s. His mom died in a tragic car accident. And then, after
seemingly disappearing from the public eye in the '90s, he won his
only world championship with the Yankees two years ago. Finally, at
the end of a long road, Boggs smacked a home run for his 3,000 hit
last weekend, becoming the first member of the club to get more
than a triple for his milestone hit. He'll try to add to the hit
total this weekend at Kauffman Stadium, where he may be making his
final appearance as a player. Photos. Steve Rock. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Tampa Bay at Kansas City, 7:05 p.m. Dick Kaegel. 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   WHIT. Jason Whitlock column from Chiefs training camp.
</P>
<P>
   CORNERS. Second-year cornerback Eric Warfield is having a
productive camp and is challenging veterans Cris Dishman and
Carlton Gray for that left corner spot with the Chiefs. Adam
Teicher. 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   PGA. Second round coverage from PGA Championship. Howard
Richman. 18.
</P>
<P>
   HALLFAME. Tom Osborne, Brad Budde, Bo Jackson and Johnny Roland
are among the inductees into the College Football Hall of Fame
Friday night. Blair Kerkhoff. 15. Photos
</P>
