<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6187 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-KATZENMO     08-13 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-KATZENMOYER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 SMITHFIELD, R.I.: ... at the spot.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Chuck Fairbanks came to me before a preseason game against
Green Bay that second year,'' said Nelson, referring to the
Patriots' former coach and general manager. ``And he said to me,
`You're not improving like I think you should . . . you have to
start picking up your play.' Let me tell you, that gave me some
kind of push. It was coming from Fairbanks _ the coach and GM _ it
wasn't like it was some idle thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, for the most part, has been impressed by his rookie
wannabe. He likes Katzenmoyer's size, agility, and speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a little spark every day,'' said Carroll. ``I think you
should be excited about what this guy brings.''
</P>
<P>
   By the coach's account, the only downside has been what he has
perceived as a lack of itensity from the highly-touted rookie.
Carroll expected more overt, demonstrable fire and passion from the
``Big Cat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a personality trait that can transfer into a skill,''
said Carroll. ``It's not (totally) necessary . . . there are a lot
of guys who can play who are really quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer, apparently, is one of them. He refers to himself as
``a quiet guy, no matter what the situation is, I just let my
actions speak for me, instead of, you know, talking.''
</P>
<P>
   So where's the intensity that Carroll wants?
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, he told me that, too, but I really don't know what
he means by it,'' said Katzenmoyer. ``I'm a quiet person. I keep to
myself a lot. I'm not a yeller and a screamer, but that's doesn't
mean I'm not intense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Within that understated demeanor, though, there is a true
confidence. In the days when he was talking to Sports Illustrated,
Katzenmoyer said, ``Every 10 or 15 years, a new breed of athlete
comes along: bigger, faster, stronger. I see myself as a new breed
of athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday to expound on that thought, Katzenmoyer said, ``I
think you see that as part of the evolution of every sport. You've
had it in baseball with (Mark) McGwire and (Sammy) Sosa, and you
have that in football, too. There's always going to be change, no
matter what the sport. The style of the game is definitely
different today than even in the '80s. It's a matter of the natural
evolution of people. People are getting bigger, stronger, and
faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks into his pro career, is he still feeling that way _
bigger, stronger, and faster than the next NFL guy?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``I guess it's going to be a process
to feel out. I'll probably know better in a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Columbus, the Buckeyes' head coach, John Cooper, has
little doubt about Katzenmoyer's upside. He also doesn't think
there will be much of an adjustment period for his former star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense is not any different in pro football than in
college,'' said Cooper. ``You line up, take care of the gap, and
tackle the ballcarrier. I don't think there's a hell of a lot
secret to the game. I can't see that he'd be overwhelmed by
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is proof that the leap doesn't have to be great. A
second-round pick out of Colorado in 1995, he started 12 games for
the Patriots that season. The next fall, Zach Thomas, a fifth-round
pick out of Texas Tech, started all 16 games at middle linebacker
for the Dolphins and since has made himself a mainstay.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's hard, what happened to Ted Johnson,'' Thomas said
Thursday. ``He's a great linebacker, one of the best run-blockers
in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   A rookie stepping into the spot, said Thomas, shouldn't feel
overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough, having to learn a whole new system, things like
that,'' recalled Thomas. ``But there really isn't any pressure on a
rookie because they're expecting you to make mistakes. They know
that's just going to happen. If you're a rookie, and you play up to
your ability, that's great. And if you don't, and your season's
mediocre, then it's OK, you can only get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adjustment is the game's a lot faster, runners are
quicker, everything is different. But the advantage is you have
more studying here, and that really helped me. When I was in
college, class and studying took a lot out of the day, just to do
your work in school, but here, you go to class to learn football.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Ohio, a Columbus sports cafe, the Rush Creek Sports
Bar &AMP; Grill, is clearing out a wall to hang Katzenmoyer
paraphernalia. David Davis, the bar's president and CEO, got to
know Katzenmoyer when the pride of Westerville _ a dry town _ was a
star junior on the high school team. When Katzenmoyer made it to
the all-state game in Canton, it was Rush Creek that sponsored his
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'll tell you what kind of kid we're talking about here,''
said Davis. ``We paid for his trip there, including whatever
expenses were allowed, but we added a little extra money for
expenses _ not a big deal, just some spending money. The next day,
he politely told me, `No, you can't do that,' and returned the
money. He didn't want it to jeopardize anything with NCAA
eligibility. He's really a bright, honorable kid.''
</P>
<P>
   By Davis's account, Katzenmoyer is intelligent and sincere,
contrary to images that may have been gleened from media accounts
and interpreted from his media boycott in '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the brightest kids you'll ever meet,'' said Davis. ``I
mean this with all sincerity _ he's a rare find. The people of
Boston have a really good jewel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
