<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS IMPROVE IN MCAS ESSAYS, TEACHERS REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- This summer, nearly 800 Massachusetts teachers spent
three weeks doing what they normally dread during the school year:
correcting tests.
</P>
<P>
   But this wasn't just another algebra quiz, this was the essay
portion of the state MCAS exam, and, anecdotally at least, teachers
say there has been a marked improvement in student performance over
the first year of the assessement test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buzz going around the room from day one, was that people
felt good about it; that they were much improved over last year,''
said Adele Stock, humanities coordinator at Hopedale Junior/Senior
High School, who was a ``table leader'' overseeing teachers who
corrected 10th-grade exams.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Education officials are pleased with the early
positive signs, but warn that until the test results are officially
tallied within the next month or so, there should be no rush to
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can come out of the scoring with an impression, but it's
very shaky to draw conclusions,'' said Jeffrey Nellhaus, the
department's director of assessment and evaluation. ``But we are
pleased to see how many teachers enjoyed the scoring experience and
want to become ambassadors for the program.''
</P>
<P>
   The multiple choice portion of MCAS is currently being scored at
Advance System Measurement and Evaluation Inc., a Dover, N.H. hired
by the Education Department to oversee and conduct testing.
</P>
<P>
   A special MCAS-only division has been set up and employees work
under tight security checking off right and wrong answers eight
hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Advance is a nationally known testing center that helps states
design, develop and score specialized assesement tests. Although
the state of Kentucky fired the firm in 1996 after detecting
scoring miscalculations in school ranking, Nellhaus said
Massachusetts has had no problems with Advance.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, hundreds of teachers like Stock answered a
communique from the Education Department looking for essay scorers.
The state paid each teacher $500 for correcting 100 tests each day
for three days at three sites across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Security was tight with guards from Advanced Systems positioned
all around the test sites. Teachers were not allowed to drink or
eat or even talk during the correction process, and used yellow
sticky-notes to convey opinions about essays to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, though, there would be a joyous outburst over a
particularly ``funny or erudite'' essay, Stock said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a large mix of educators as well, the scorers said.
From English teachers to shop teachers, guidance counselors,
principals and librarians, all were involved in the process and all
were willing to suspend their own opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful having different people from different
disciplines give up their own standards and use the standard of the
state, which was very appropriate,'' said Bess Blunt, an 8th-grade
English teacher at the Hawthorne Brook Middle School in Townsend.
``Everyone brought their own perspectives to the table, but what
was really stressed, was leave your own standards at the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Several teachers said they wanted to be involved in the process
to not only see firsthand how the state was handling the correction
process, but to bring information about what makes a great essay _
or a bad essay _ back to their principals and students.
</P>
<P>
   Several teachers who corrected or oversaw the process for 30 to
40 percent of the MCAS essays taken by 4th-, 8th- and 10th-graders
agreed the students seemed better prepared, knew how to structure
an essay and were more focused than in 1998, the first year the
controversial exam was issued.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the fourth-grade essay asked students to describe a
great day in their lives; the 8th-grade essay wanted students to
discuss whether community service should be an elective or
mandatory activity; and 10th-graders had to select a scene or
episode in literature and explain what the situation appears to be,
and what it really is.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of kids who had a great time at Riverside
Park,'' laughed Mary Anne Rohde, a reading specialist at the West
Brookfield Elementary school who corrected 4th-grade essays two
years in a row. ``But even those were better than last year's where
we had a lot of 4th-graders writing `we left the house, and then,
and then and then. . .' This year they were written as essays, not
just a list of what happened and who was there.''
</P>
<P>
   The tests were graded on a scale of 1-6, and teachers were
trained for two days on the rubrics and criteria used to judge the
quality of the work. An essay that scored a 6, for example, would
have rich topic development, careful and/or subtle organization and
an effective and rich use of language.
</P>
<P>
   An essay that scored a one would have little topic development,
poor organization, few details and little or no awareness of the
audience or task.
</P>
<P>
   Each test was read and scored by two teachers. If there was a
disparity in their scores, a ``table leader'' would also read the
essay, discuss it with the original readers and all would have to
be in agreement over the score then reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were much better overall,'' said Rohde. ``I think the
kids know it's more serious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
