<HEADLINE>
BOXER SEEKS ANOTHER PROBE OF FUEL PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., has asked the
Federal Trade Commission to investigate whether the major oil
companies are trying to drive smaller suppliers in California out
of business through pricing practices.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said Thursday she suspected the price of fuel was being
manipulated by the large companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going after the independent dealers, and the
independents are the last line of defense the consumer has for
cheap gas,'' Boxer said.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC already is investigating the oil suppliers after several
price spikes in San Francisco and San Diego led to a mountain of
consumer complaints in the spring of 1998. This week, Boxer said
that from July 31 to Aug. 4, the price of wholesale ``unbranded''
gasoline was greater than that of ``branded'' gasoline, and she is
asking that to be explored, too.
</P>
<P>
   Branded gasoline is the supply from refineries that is sold
according to contracts to the major oil companies, and the
unbranded gasoline _ typically less expensive _ is excess fuel that
is sold to independent dealers.
</P>
<P>
   During the period July 31 to Aug. 4, wholesale unbranded gas in
California reached a high of $1.18 per gallon, with branded
gasoline selling for about $1.07 per gallon, said Rob Schlichting,
an analyst with the California Energy Commission. He said that on
Aug. 9, unbranded fuel had dropped to $1.10 per gallon and the
branded variety remained at $1.07.
</P>
<P>
   The major oil refiners denied the pricing reflected
anti-competitive practices.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon of unbranded prices being higher than branded
gasoline is ``a very temporary anomaly that occurs during periods
of very tight supply and it is evidence only that the marketplace
is working,'' said Mike Libbey, a spokesman for the Chevron Corp.
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The average daily refinery production in California for the week
ending Aug. 6 was 959,000 barrels per day, which is 7.5 percent
below the production of the same week one year ago, Schlichting
said. It was somewhat less than that one week earlier, when
production was reduced at Mobil Corp.'s Torrance refinery due to an
explosion, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said she has requested that FTC Chairman Robert Pitofsky
expand his investigation in California because of the very unusual
circumstances surrounding the price inversion _ that it came just
before this week's major price spike at the pump, and last occurred
in March, again before a price increase.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline in California is some of the costliest in the nation.
Suppliers attribute recent increases in prices at the pump to
tightening world oil supplies, several refinery accidents in the
state and increases typically associated with higher demand during
the summer driving season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you found Kmart charging more than Saks Fifth Avenue, you
would question it and that is what is going on in the oil
industry,'' Boxer said Thursday in a telephone conference call.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC has subpoenaed documents on pricing practices at the
major companies doing business in California. Separately, the state
attorney general is looking into the prices for any evidence of
anti-competitive forces.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Mangles, a spokeswoman for the Western States Petroleum
Association in Glendale, an oil company trade association, said of
Boxer: ``It seems like the senator keeps trying to create a problem
so that she can push a solution that really isn't necessary. The
market is working. When you have government interference you
typically have adverse effects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
