<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT WHITE WAY IN FALL, WINTER FASHION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent marks needed over e in boucle and e in appliqued) 
 
By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fashion, almost by definition, should include an element of
excitement. That said, what's the big deal with all the white in
stores now?
</P>
<P>
   Well, two words ... fall and winter.
</P>
<P>
   White is a given for summer, when it so successfully reflects
light and keeps us cooler. Even for spring, whites in nubby boucle
fabrics and other lightweight wools herald a symbolic reawakening
after the dreariness of winter.
</P>
<P>
   But this fall, department store clothing racks look as if a
blizzard has struck, and with the clothes on the racks in August,
it is difficult to describe these as winter whites.
</P>
<P>
   In cities where the past decade has witnessed a dourness in
dress akin to urban camouflage, out-of-season white is as rare as
whooping craneson Seventh Avenue. Hence its element of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   The trend to white began more than a year ago when Michael Kors
sent out a bright white and very ladylike reefer coat for the staid
Paris fashion house Celine. Fashion editors and groupies snapped up
the design, even though it drew dirt like a magnet.
</P>
<P>
   This year more designers followed Kors' lead, so many that women
are likely to look like snow bunnies from Labor Day until they open
their Valentines.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of designers included whites and off-whites _ from
cream to palomino blonde _ in their collections, in fabrics that
ranged from paper-weight quilted silks and nylons to felted wools
as thick and heavy as army surplus blankets.
</P>
<P>
   Felted wools have flat surfaces and are usually sewn with their
cut edges to the outside, as one sews Ultrasuede. Felt was
traditionally a serviceable student and sportswear fabric, popular
decades ago for uniform jumpers and treated to repel water in
British outdoor gear.
</P>
<P>
   In the '50s, there were those appliqued poodle circle skirts,
and from the late '60s through the mid-'70s, at the height of the
hippie era, felt garments included vests, skirts and coats accented
with felt appliques and naif embroidery. Think Heidi clothes and
you have the idea. Ready or not, these styles are also making a
comeback this year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the upscale designer whites, especially those from Ralph
Lauren and Donna Karan, are thick and woolly, designed to be
layered and even worn with white buck shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Whites from Helmut Lang look more high-tech, almost like space
suits. White is a clean-slate way to greet the millennium, even if
you don't plan to board a spaceship.
</P>
<P>
   Some designers hedged their bets for fall and winter, mixing
white with other colors or neutrals.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways with white is adding it to black, where its
pristine starkness adds snap to the black. For that reason, adding
a couple of white separates or a coat is a fine way to update all
the black most women already have in their closets.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Jacobs added a wool jacket and turtleneck over black velvet
pants and black leather boots, an especially elegant look for day.
</P>
<P>
   At Emporio Armani, a short black bolero jacket with long sleeves
topped a blonde tummy-teaser sweater worn over off-white pants.
</P>
<P>
   The whites with the most impact, however, are those worn only
with other whites, especially in the city. Environments that
sometimes call for urban survival gear are surprising places to
find women _ and even men, this year _ decked head-to-ankle, if not
head-to-toe, in white.
</P>
<P>
   One of the softest, yet richest ways to wear white will be with
furs, either full-blown fur coats or simple accessories such as fur
hats, muffs, collars or purses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
