<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6193 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CANADA-PIER21-BOS &LR;      08-13 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-PIER21-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA REOPENS GATE TO ITS IMMIGRANT PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ Too often the story of Canada is told as
the history of the original colonizers, the French and the British,
Canada's ``two solitudes,'' whose deep antagonisms have kept the
country politically off-balance since the 1700s.
</P>
<P>
   Although any visitor to any Canadian city would recognize that
this is a nation built of comers from every part of the earth, the
immigrant experience has never been celebrated with quite the same
fervor as in the United States. It has not defined the national
psyche nearly as much as the old quarrels between Quebec and ``the
rest of Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as part of a push to promote greater awareness of country's
polyglot past, Canada has reopened Halifax's Pier 21 immigrant
processing complex as the first national historic site
commemorating the human waves that made Canada one of the two most
multiethnic societies in the world, along with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For much of this century, Pier 21 served as Canada's major port
of entry for immigrants, refugees, and war brides. As immigrant
patterns changed, the hulking structure was abandoned and stood
derelict for nearly three decades.
</P>
<P>
   In July, however, the rat-infested ruins were resurrected as a
gleaming multimedia center telling the immigrant tale through video
screens, interactive computer links, and the more typical displays
of old photographs and artifacts. The timing has coincided with
continued migration, in airplanes from such hot spots as Kosovo or,
illegally, in evasive ships from China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada has has not focused much on its immigrants,'' said Ruth
Goldbloom, president of the society that led the effort to
refurbish Pier 21 as a museum and exhibition center. ``But we felt
if we didn't start capturing these people's stories now, it would
never happen.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1928 to 1971, roughly 1 million immigrants and refugees
entered Canada through Pier 21. Although billed as ``Canada's Ellis
Island,'' the facility probably had a greater impact on this
country's small population than the more-famous New York immigrant
center had upon the much larger United States.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pier 21 officials, one of every five living
Canadians has a blood connection to the site _ either they or some
relative passed through its portals.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Dalla Riva of Montreal fearfully disembarked at Pier 21 in
autumn 1953, at age 7, and remembers well the chaotic clamor of
unfamiliar languages echoing through the vast processing hall. With
its forbidding facades and smoke-belching ships riding the greasy
tide, Halifax was not the Canada he'd imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Back in northern Italy, where his family had boarded the SS
Omland with as much fear of the unknown as hope for the future,
Dalla Riva envisioned a vast snowy forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd thought we'd be living pioneer-style in the bush,'' he
said after visiting the harborside structure. ``But we simply
boarded a train for Ontario, where my father would work in the
steel mills of Hamilton. It was the typical immigrants' tale.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not entirely typical: Dalla Riva would escape the drudgery
of feeding furnaces to win glory as a Canadian football great,
playing tight end for the Montreal Alouettes in the 1970s, and is
today an executive with BGL Brokerage, a Montreal customs firm.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, like so many foreign-born Canadians, he still recalls the
footsteps he took down the gangplank as his most important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pier 21 was a kind of magic door for immigrants. You were
coming into a land where anything was possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the brick-and-steel structure, with its slatted benches
and quarantine wards, newcomers waited in long lines with squawling
infants, their frayed identity papers and their possessions stuffed
in cardboard suitcases or burlap sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I was on this pier I was so seasick and
frightened,'' recalled Rozina Chute, 61, who arrived as a refugee
from Romania in 1956 and last month paid an emotional visit to the
pier. ``My family had $5 and my father's carpenter tools. Not much
for a new life.''
</P>
<P>
   The reopening of Pier 21 as a historic site points to the
increasing pride of Canadians in their immigrant past. Until a push
by a Halifax-based community group, the complex was forgotten, just
another decaying harborfront relic. That it was the last
immigration ``shed'' still standing in Canada seemed nothing worth
memorializing.
</P>
<P>
   But now thousands of visitors are streaming through its gates
daily as the pier rapidly becomes one of the old port city's prime
attractions. Said Mary Tulle, director of marketing for Pier 21 and
the granddaughter of an immigrant who passed through its gates from
Lebanon: ``This was Canada's front door. The soul of our country is
seeped into these old bricks.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some ugly blotches on that soul.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate Jews trying to escape Hitler's Germany were denied
entry to Canada by Prime Minister Mackenzie King, a hard line that
condemned many to death in concentration camps. Barred also, until
the 1960s, were most Asians along with those deemed
``feeble-minded,'' ``loathsome,'' or, perhaps worst of all,
sympathetic to communism.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for a country that until the 1920s remained much more
ethnically homogenous than the United States _ dominated mainly by
descendants of the original English, Scots, and French colonizers _
the doors were flung remarkably wide. The country desperately
needed laborers and farmers, and after World War II, especially,
was ready to welcome most transplants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed by the real warmth of Canadians,'' said Alex
Deloukadis, who brought his young family from Greece in 1951,
settling in Montreal. ``I thought I was coming to the frozen edge
of the Earth. I hardly spoke a word of English. Yet this strange
country said, `Now this is your country, too.' I've never stopped
being amazed.''
</P>
<P>
   He was one of 93,578 individuals to pass through Pier 21 that
year. Most were trundled aboard Canadian National Railway trains
waiting just outside the immigration hall for passage to points
west _ to the factories of Montreal, the mines of northern Ontario,
the farms of Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalie Silberman Abella, today an Ontario judge, was among the
thousands of Jewish refugees finally admitted in the terrible wake
of World War II. Her parents were survivors of the Nazi death camp
Treblinka.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every immigrant who landed at Pier 21 has two stories: the
story they came from and the story they started when they landed in
Canada,'' she said at the dedication of the new interpretive
center.
</P>
<P>
   The $6.2 million restoration project, sponsored equally by the
Canadian government and private donations, has transformed the
battered ruins of Pier 21 into a multimedia showpiece dedicated to
the immigrant experience in Canada. There are photographs and
videotaped oral histories as well as poignant displays of passports
and other paraphernalia, from ticket stubs to a tattered teddy
bear.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most powerful is the memory book in which visitors,
many of them immigrants who entered through Pier 21 decades ago,
can jot down impressions or memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a day goes by that I do not give thanks to Canada,'' wrote
Georg Zichirman, a Romanian native, 34 years after his arrival at
the pier. Others, including retired football player Dalla Riva,
have made regular pilgrimages.
</P>
<P>
   It's sometimes surprising what immigrants remember most clearly
about their first few days in the new land.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was the vastness of the country, of course,'' said Dalla
Riva. ``But I was really stunned by the sliced white bread. I'd
never heard of such a thing. It was soft, and with not too much
flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Most immigrants arrived at Pier 21 aboard immense steamships,
such as the Beaverbrae, the Regina Calgaric, the Conte Biancamano,
the Arosa Kulm, the Lady Nelson, the Nelly, and the Nieuw
Amsterdam. Others came crammed aboard tiny vessels.
</P>
<P>
   But most immigrants interviewed recalled not so much the
difficulty of their voyage but the sheer joy of their arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``As bleak as the immigration hall was, as confused and
frightened as I must have been, the instant that official stamped
`landed immigrant' onto my pass card is seared into memory as the
greatest moment of my life. I'd been accepted and could breathe
free,'' said Joseph Panetta, who arrived from Malta in 1949 and now
lives in British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anything that sets immigrants apart from
native-born Canadians or Americans, it's probably the intensity of
our patriotism,'' Panetta said. ``I see my whole life as striving
to be worthy of my adopted homeland.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
