<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNS THAT ARE EASIER TO GET THAN DRIVER'S LICENSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let us do away with the terms of denial, phrases like ``another
senseless shooting'' or ``random mass shootings.'' The damning of
the perpetrators can no longer end merely with ``loner'' and
``madman.'' We just might get some action around gun violence if we
call it for what it really is:
</P>
<P>
   A riot.
</P>
<P>
   Riots have often forced this nation to deal with reality. For
example, the riots of 1967, dubbed ``the long, hot summer,''
resulted in President Johnson's Kerner Commission report. The
report called for many measures that resulted in programs to foster
opportunity and equality for African-Americans. Many
African-Americans who today are in their 40s and 50s were direct
beneficiaries of those programs.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, when Martin Luther King Jr. and Robert F. Kennedy
were assassinated, President Johnson spoke out even further, this
time against guns. Johnson, in an act of leadership rarely seen on
Capitol Hill today, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``On occasions before, I have spoken of the terrible toll
inflicted on our people by firearms: 750,000 Americans dead since
the turn of the century. This is far more than have died at the
hands of our enemies in all the wars we have fought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told the Congress and the nation of the brutal
loopholes in our laws. Two million guns were sold in the United
States last year. Far too many were bought by the demented, the
deranged, the hardened criminal, and the convict, the addict, and
the alcoholic. We cannot expect these irresponsible people to be
prudent in their protection of us, but we can expect the Congress
to protect us from them. . . . So today, I call upon the Congress,
in the name of sanity, in the name of safety _ and in the name of
an aroused nation _ to give America the Gun Control Law it needs.''
</P>
<P>
   After the assassinations, Johnson did get some gun- control
measures passed. But this country has watched the loopholes become
bullet holes. For instance, in that ``long, hot summer'' _ the
summer that forced a president and Congress into a bipartisan panic
to find ways to keep the ghettos from exploding _ 84 people died.
In death toll alone, that is not all that much hotter than the
temperature we're experiencing right now.
</P>
<P>
   The spree of multiple shootings in offices and schools has left
at least 50 people dead and 36 others wounded in the last year. The
school shootings of the last two years have left 31 dead and 73
others wounded.
</P>
<P>
   These, of course, are the more spectacular outbreaks in a nation
where more than 30,000 people will die by year's end from gunfire.
The death toll has been declining in recent years, but the decline
is of the barest note to the rest of the developed world, which has
far lower rates of gun killing. It is even less noteworthy when the
latest siege of killings suggest an America where even the least
bit of frustration on the part of the deranged makes the rest of us
feel more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot be an accident that at least three of the mass
shootings, the one Tuesday at a Jewish community center in Los
Angeles, the one-man killing spree near Chicago, and the horror at
Columbine High School (not to mention the Oklahoma City bombing)
were partially or fully inspired by racist and anti-Semitic hate.
The killers might have acted alone, but they were nurtured, if not
overtly encouraged, by hate groups who swear they don't advocate
murdering Jews and people of color but have to know in their heart
that someone in their midst will be infused with just enough hate
to pull the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not we actually have any more rage in our society is
subject to debate, but it is no accident that so many of the
killings involve people with histories of mental illness. We have
so drastically slashed institutions and services that mental health
is the hardest thing for many people to obtain coverage for. With
guns being easier to obtain than driver's licenses, we have too
many lit matches looking for spilled kerosene. The shooting at the
Jewish community center happened in Los Angeles, but the guts of
the gun came from Maine. In that respect, it was a coast-to-coast
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The Kerner Commission report said the riots of 1967 came at a
time of ``rising expectations'' but continued poverty in ghettos.
Today's riot comes at a time when the economy is booming, but many
people still feel threatened by financial insecurity and a
multicultural society. That might help explain why most mass
shootings are done by straight white males raised on the
anti-affirmative action politics of the 1980s. Their victims could
be anyone, but they are driven by the paranoia of losing their
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   We keep calling these shootings senseless, but when they add up,
a lot makes sense. This has been a riot that politicians and the
gun lobby have tried to blind us to. The death toll by now should
be so visible that in the name of sanity, in the name of safety,
and in the name of an aroused nation, America gets the Gun Control
Law it needs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
