<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEEKFEST MARKS THE SUMMER OF '99 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESQUITE, Texas _ Even if the frenetic, violent and rapid-fire
world of online death-match gaming is not your cup of tea, you'd
have to admit that the scene last weekend at QuakeCon 99 was pretty
cool.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 people traveled sometimes thousands of miles to
attend, and half of them brought along their own computers. In a
huge convention center ballroom, they set up their systems on
tables and jacked into a computer network that had more than 700
machines linked by a mile and a half of cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enough computer power in this room to run the New York
Stock Exchange,'' one of the network engineers boasted. And given
that gamers usually own the most muscular PCs around, with the
fastest processors and tons of memory, that probably was not an
exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   Those who made the pilgrimage to Mesquite, near Dallas, were the
hardiest of the hard core. ``No, I don't have a hotel room,'' I
overheard one gamer say to another late Friday night. ``I didn't
drive this far to sleep. Keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   What they kept playing _ Friday morning until midafternoon
Sunday _ was the early test version of Quake III Arena, the next
product from id Software, whose offices were less than a mile away.
Although Q3A, as it's called, won't be available for a while, the
test version is in great shape and has been drawing raves from
players _ even though it has only three playing levels and a subset
of the full version's features.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty happy _ we're running a huge event like this on a
test version,'' said John Carmack, an id co-founder. ``We'll be
releasing the game relatively soon.''
</P>
<P>
   (You can download the Q3Test for Win- &QL; 
dows-, Macintosh- and Linux-based computers at
www.quake3arena.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DEATH-MATCH IS THE THING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike past games in id's best-selling Quake series, there will
be no monsters to blast in the single-player aspect of the game.
Instead, Quake III Arena is all about death-match play _ battling
the computer-generated images of other people who connect to the
game over a network or across the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This is what has made id's Doom and then Quake series of games
so enduringly popular _ playing against other humans. By focusing
on this aspect in Q3A, id hopes to expose more people to
death-match play. The single-player part of the game will involve
action against computer-simulated players known as ``bots,'' which
will be considered as training for eventually getting online.
</P>
<P>
   This year's QuakeCon had two main components. In the ``Bring
Your Own Computer'' area, open 24 hours a day, more than 500 people
played against each other.
</P>
<P>
   In separate spaces nearby, clusters of computers were used for
tournaments. The largest group of PCs contained Advanced Micro
Devices' new 600-megahertz Athlon chip, which is a serious
challenger to Intel Corp.'s Pentium III processors. Here, a
500-person tournament was conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Next door, a cluster of Apple's Power Mac- &QL; 
intosh G3s were used to conduct smaller contests, including a
tournament for media people. (Yes, I played. No, I didn't win. In
fact, I was seriously humiliated _ 47 to minus 5 _ by a player who
went on to play in the media tourney finals, where he was soundly
beaten.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MOST GAMERS ARE NICE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first-person-shooter genre of computer games has gotten some
nasty press lately, because the killers in the Columbine High
School massacre were fans of id's Doom and Quake games. But at
QuakeCon, I found in person what I'd experienced from dealing with
the online Quake community _ that the vast majority of fans of the
game are exceptionally nice people.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was Will Barton, a 17-year-old who had driven all
the way by himself from Wytheville, Va. Soft-spoken, clean-cut and
technically savvy, he'd assembled his own computer just to bring
along.
</P>
<P>
   Barton got knocked out of the tournament early, but still had a
good time. He worked as a volunteer, got to rub shoulders with some
of the stars of the convention and came away with a nifty T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   In a few weeks, he'll start his freshman year at Virginia Tech,
but forget about that milestone. Playing Quake III Arena in a room
full of hundreds of other ``Quake geeks'' is what he'll remember
most about the summer of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
