<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TWIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TWIN' EXPLORES LONELINESS, IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TWIN FALLS IDAHO 
Directed and written by: Michael and Mark Polish 
Starring: Mark and Michael Polish, Michele Hicks, Lesley Ann
Warren, Patrick Bauchau, Jon Gries, Garrett Morris, William Katt 
Running time: 105 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Too many films play like something David Lynch shot on a bad
day. But ``Twin Falls Idaho'' plays like something Lynch might
shoot on a good day, assuming he ever has one again. It's bizarre,
shadowy, enticingly eerie and more moving than it would have been
if its makers had merely intended to settle for a freak show.
Instead, it's something more poetic, more tantalizingly original.
It's the best twin movie since ``Dead Ringers,'' but while that
movie was murderous, this one is about a pair of gentle conjoined
twins doing their best to stay alive in a world they have not found
to be filled with embrace, starting when their horrified mother
dumped them early on.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 25 years later, Blake and Francis are back in town, holed
up in the Platonic essence of seedy hotels, figuring out how to
handle the reunion they had planned with her, and gathering their
strength for it. To pass the time, they decide to celebrate their
birthday by ordering the services of a prostitute. The woman named
Penny can't handle their condition, and flees. But she forgets her
purse, returns, settles down, becomes curious about their permanent
bond and the subtle and profound ways they communicate, and sticks
around. Soon, she falls in love with Blake, the stronger of the
two, whose healthy heart is keeping Francis alive by pumping for
both of them.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when somebody finally comes between the brothers is
mesmerizing, not just morbidly, but philosophically, as issues of
bonding and identity and completeless are plumbed. Eventually and
not surprisingly, it is revealed that Penny, driven by guilt over
abandoning her own handicapped son, has intimacy issues. While the
twin characters are rare, the prostitute's role could easily have
degenerated into cliche. But so delicately and urgently does
newcomer Michele Hicks play it, and with so convincing a degree of
emotional involvement, that she becomes as much a reason to be
drawn into the film's gravitational field as the hypnotically
fascinating twins.
</P>
<P>
   Played by real (although not conjoined) twins Mark and Michael
Polish, they fill the screen with poignancy, reserve, and mystery.
Obviously the real-life brothers are attuned to those extra nuances
of communication available to twin siblings and few others. Their
heightened sensitivity is an element in the film's steady pull on
us. As makers of the film as well as its stars, they put on screen
an impressive level of craftsmanship. Their film, deliberately
drained of color, is a thing of oddly sheltering gloom. Wearing its
measured pace and carefully controlled tonal palette in such a way
as to conjure up a protective armor of the psyche, it's not unlike
the retro narrow-lapeled, three-button, touchingly formal double
that suggests a carapace for the fragile, vulnerable creatures
underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Without succumbing to bathos, the film makes incisive dramatic
use of the fact that the only time the brothers can venture forth
freely into the rest of the world is on Halloween night, which they
do. There's a painful meeting with their long-unseen mother (Lesley
Ann Warren), and Penny's back story is filled in by a world-weary,
humane physician (Patrick Bauchau). But the Polish brothers and
Hicks' presence as an unanticpated extension of their circumscribed
lives are rightly at the center of the hauntingly unforgettable,
nocturnally tender ``Twin Falls Idaho.'' In its dreamlike way, it
says more than any film this year about identity and isolation. So
pared-down yet so vivid is its flavor that you look to paintings _
Edward Hopper's, say _ rather to than other films for ways to
describe the way ``Twin Falls Idaho'' speaks its language of
loneliness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
