<HEADLINE>
BOSTON'S `BLAIR WITCH' CONNECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though perhaps not top-of-mind these days, there is a venerable
Boston-Hollywood money axis. Back when the Bank of Boston was known
as The First (before it became ``Terry Murray's ATM''), the Hub was
an early and generous lender to the emerging movie studios. Not for
nothing was former bank officer William Thompson a key figure in
David McClintick's classic 1982 Hollywood expose, ``Indecent
Exposure.'' But I digress.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Bain Capital of Copley Square bought a Hollywood
company called Live Entertainment. At the time, Live was best known
for the identity of its former owner: Jose Menendez, the
shotgun-impaired father of miscreant offspring Lyle and Erik.
Majority shareholder Bain changed Live's name to Artisan
Entertainment and installed Mark Curcio, the head of Bain's Los
Angeles consulting office, as chief executive officer. Geoff
Rehnert in Bain's Boston office monitors the Artisan investment.
Earlier this year, Rehnert was floating his name as a possible
Republican challenger for Ted Kennedy's Senate seat, before he came
to his senses. His former Bain Capital colleague, Mitt Romney, rode
into that same valley of political death in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Why do we care about all this? Because earlier this year Artisan
forked over $1 million for the rights to distribute a small-scale
independent film called ``The Blair Witch Project.'' The company
spent several hundred thousand dollars upgrading the film print and
pumped $15 million into marketing and distribution. The rest is
what passes for history in Bill Clinton's America: Artisan stood
back as ``Blair Witch'' (initial production cost, $30,000;
projected box office take: $100 million) turned the Summer of Stars
Wars into the summer of slacker horror hype. The Boston-Hollywood
connection appears to be back in business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clambake U.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Dave Barry would say, we're not making this up.
</P>
<P>
   Boston University is flogging two books by Dr. Christopher
Reaske, its vice president for development and alumni relations, on
the university's home page, www.bu.edu. That might be
understandable if the books dealt with education, but in fact
Reaske is pumping two books he wrote in the 1980s _ ``The Compleat
Clammer'' and ``The Compleat Crab and Lobster Book,'' which are
back in print. The BU Web site leads you directly to pictures of
Dr. Reaske (not the kind of doctor who can cure you; he's a PhD in
literature) knee-deep in tidewater, and of course to the Amazon and
Barnes &AMP; Noble sites, where you can buy Dr. R's contributions to
clam-und-crabology.
</P>
<P>
   Reaske's virtual Vanity Fair also quotes from a lengthy article
in the university-sponsored newspaper, headlined: ``Knee-Deep Veep:
Alumni and development VP Reaske's shellfish books back on the
shelves.'' Choice excerpts: `` . . . when he's not raking in the
clams for BU, Reaske is digging for real bivalves _ in East Coast
tidal flats, usually on Shelter Island, N.Y., his favorite vacation
spot.'' And: ``A few weeks before Reaske began to write the book,
he observed terns diving for fish and noted their smooth, symphonic
efficiency as they hunted. `Observing these beautiful birds made my
principal goal in this book come clear _ to convey a sense of
``doing it right,'' to explain that there are time-proven ways to
gather clams efficiently and to do so in harmony with nature,' he
writes. With a little practice, one can use a clam rake `almost
like a dancing partner.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Reaske says he didn't know that his books, which he calls
``legitimate academic works,'' were being teased off the BU site:
``I haven't had any involvement with this.'' Deflecting the bullet
aimed at his boss, BU's associate vice president for university
relations, David Lampe, says it was his decision to hype the books
on the Web site; ``I thought it had news value. It's just like any
other university, when faculty produce books of general interest,
you do what you can to promote them. Nobody's misusing any
resources here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
