<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6202 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV1     08-13 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV15-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILDEW MAY BE UNDER TUB CAULK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 15, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I put a bead of white silicone caulk between the tile and my
tub, and it works very nicely. However, there is mildew on it that
I cannot get rid of, even when using bleach and water to kill it.
What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   LEONARD SHAMES, Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Ah, the mildew that will not die. I think it is because the
mildew is growing under and through the caulk, not on top of it.
Or, the black marks are not mildew. That's not much of a help
because still nothing seems to take it off. OK, if that is the
case, dig out the old silicone, treat the joint with bleach to kill
any mold that might be still there and to keep it from growing
through the caulk. Rinse thoroughly, and install new caulk. Or,
instead of caulk, sandless grout, which will give better
performance, I feel, than caulk. If caulk worked for you, that's
cool.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I know that some wall-to-wall carpet lumps up in humid
weather as it unstretches, then flattens out again in dry weather.
My nylon carpet humps up permanently. How can I get it to flatten
out?
</P>
<P>
   MARIAN HATCH, Winchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Some nylon wall-to-wall carpeting will stretch and unstretch
more than other materials. You could have it restretched, which
will make it flat for a while, but probably not permanently. Better
yet is to replace it with wool, which I think is the best material
for any kind of carpeting except indoor-outdoor carpeting, unless
you are allergic to wool. If not, go for it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The siding on my house is Texture 1-11, the plywood panels
grooved to look like vertical board siding. I don't like it, and I
don't want to paint it anymore. Could I have stucco put on that
siding? If you had your druthers, what would you do?
</P>
<P>
   ARA AYKANIAN, Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Oh, the responsibility rests heavily on the handyman's aging
shoulders. But that is OK because the handyman has his opinions.
</P>
<P>
   First off, stucco, while a good product, is not very common
today, and there is only one stucco company that I know of that
does it in this area. And, some houses simply don't look very good
stuccoed; yours may be one of them.
</P>
<P>
   As for my druthers, that's an easy one. I suggest you install
white cedar shingles, and let them weather to that Cape Cod silver
so typical of New England. You say the window and door frames
(casings) are set on the Texture 1-11; that means that the Texture
1-11 is not only siding but also sheathing, the skin of the house
on which siding is usually attached.
</P>
<P>
   With this setup, all you have to do is put up Tyveck, the
standard material for installing under shingles or clapboards. You
can pry up the casing a bit so you can slip Tyvek under it for
further weatherproofing. Then put on the shingles. Since the window
and door casings are sitting on the Texture 1-11, the shingles will
butt up against them nicely. If not, install a wood molding around
the window and door casings to bring them out a little further for
proper shingle-butting.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like the way the white cedar shingles weather,
apply one coat of a bleaching oil.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You mentioned putting wedges under clapboards to open them up
to allow water vapor to escape, with the aim of preventing peeling
of paint. I have a lot of blistering paint, but where can I get
those wedges? I tried Home Depot, which claimed it has none.
</P>
<P>
   TOM SCOTT, Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I know they exist, because a caller informed me that they are
plastic, not aluminum as I once said. I checked a few catalogs
without success. Try Home Depot, and find a clerk who knows his
merchandise. Or, check a local well-stocked hardware store or
lumber yard.
</P>
<P>
   And if all else fails, you can make your own wedges from white
or red cedar shingles. Cut a wedge an inch long, an inch wide and
1/8 to 316 inch thick, and slip it under the clapboard, every 16
inches or so. You will need a lot of them, but if they work, your
Herculean labor is rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My chimney has a 2-foot-deep well at the bottom, just below
the outside cleanout door. It keeps filling with water, and I have
to bail it out fairly frequently. I have a chimney cap on top, to
keep out rainwater. The water must be from condensation of burning
wood, although I use well-cured hardwood in my stove. How can I let
that water drain out?
</P>
<P>
   THOMAS McQUILLAN, Manomet, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I was going to suggest you fill the 2-foot well and let the
water drain out the clean-out door set slightly ajar. But that well
is there for a purpose, to collect ashes from the wood burner; if
there were no well, ashes could conceivably build up until they
block the inlet from the stovepipe, causing a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   So instead, install a weep hole at the bottom of that well, with
a thin plastic tube running from the well through the chimney and
outdoors. This way the liquid will run out without staining the
outside of the chimney with soot, creosote, and other pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
