<HEADLINE>
WITH `MORRIS MATH,' NET PICKS DON'T ADD UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chip Morris knows something about technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   As manager of T. Rowe Price's $6.8 billion Science &AMP; Technology
fund, he has picked enough good technology stocks to generate an
average annual return of 33 percent over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   But he hasn't found an awful lot of Internet stocks to buy. As
he told shareholders early this year, ``In our view the current
valuation of virtually every Internet-related company grossly
exceeds any reasonable expectation of future economic returns.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris could make that statement because he has a method of
putting a value on Internet stocks, even those that don't make a
dime. The system allows him ``to slice through the BS'' surrounding
the stocks, as he puts it. It also lets him know when the stocks
have fallen far enough to be attractive _ a good thing to know
given the recent tumble in Internet shares.
</P>
<P>
   The method is pretty straightforward. To start, Morris and his
colleagues make an earnings estimate for each Internet company
based on the assumption that it will someday be as profitable as
its real-world competitors. In other words, an on-line bookstore
will earn profit margins comparable to an existing bookstore; an
Internet media company will be roughly as profitable as a
traditional media company.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Morris calculates a price/earnings ratio for each
company. Then he looks at projected five-year growth rates. Putting
the two figures together he arrives at a number, which goes by the
offputting name, ``price/earnings ratio to growth rate multiple.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds complicated, but the idea is pretty basic: It's a way
of calculating how much investors are paying for projected growth,
or even more simply, it's a way of comparing apples to apples.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Morris picked some pretty good apples _ stock
market leaders including Microsoft, Cisco, GE and Wal-Mart. On the
Internet side, he picked American Online, Amazon.com, Yahoo and
eBay, the blue chip names of the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   At mid-year, when Internet stocks were still soaring, what he
found was illuminating.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the stock market as a whole was selling for a
multiple of 2. The lower the multiple, the cheaper the stock. The
top companies _ the Microsofts and Ciscos _ were selling for about
2.5. At 2.4, America Online was roughly as expensive as the quality
traditional companies. At 3.3, Amazon.com was more expensive; at
5.7 and 6.1 respectively, Yahoo and eBay were off the charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave us a reality check,'' says Morris about the exercise.
It also confirmed his basic intuition that most Internet stocks
were unrealistically priced.
</P>
<P>
   Morris blames much of the Internet mania on overly exuberant
investors. ``There is a difference between investment and
gambling,'' he wrote to shareholders recently. ``Today the feeling
among some investors is that the casino opens at 9:30 a.m. and
closes at 4 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   He also criticizes investors for what he considers a perversion
of Peter Lynch's famous dictum: buy what you know. ``People visit a
Web site, think it's really cool and decide to own the company,''
he wrote. ``They don't know the company's profit potential and they
aren't asking.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris is just as tough on Wall Street for cranking out a steady
stream of Internet IPOs, many of them of dubious quality.
</P>
<P>
   But Morris is not anti-Internet. Not even close. He has bought
some Internet stocks and would be happy to buy more when the price
is right. That day may not be that far off.
</P>
<P>
   When Morris runs the numbers these days, he finds that Internet
stock prices have moved closer to the pack. America Online and
Amazon are no more expensive today than GE and Cisco. Yahoo and
eBay are still pricey, but, according to Morris, ``The gap is a
helluva lot smaller than it was a few months ago. If some of these
stocks trade off another 30 percent, things could get
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris is talking about stocks he could buy and hold for three
to five years. He is not interested in short-run swings and
suggests such movements are almost impossible to forecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I am confident of is that by the end of September,
these stocks will have moved 20 to 30 percent from their current
valuations,'' he says. ``I just don't know in which direction.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
