<HEADLINE>
CRAY ENJOYS BALANCE IN HIS BLUES CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Young upstarts in the blues world include Susan Tedeschi, Jonny
Lang, and Kenny Wayne Shepherd. Stalwarts include B. B. King and
Buddy Guy. And somewhere in the middle is Robert Cray, the
so-called ``Crown Prince of the Blues,'' though he doesn't trumpet
any one label for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I am,'' Cray says. ``I'm just still out
there doing it. This is our 25th anniversary tour.''
</P>
<P>
   The modest Cray is just pleased to see the blues movement
chugging along so well. ``There are more blues bands than there
have ever been,'' he says. ``There are more places to play _ and
there are blues festivals everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   With his glassy-smooth delivery, Cray is a bluesman's bluesman.
He is perhaps the genre's finest modern songwriter _ and he goes
overboard to please on his exquisite new album, ``Take Your Shoes
Off,'' his first for Salem-based Rykodisc Records.
</P>
<P>
   The new disc has some of the sweetest soul-blues singing since
the '60s heyday of the Stax/Volt label in Memphis, which featured
the likes of Otis Redding and O.V. Wright. ``That was one of the
greatest eras in music history,'' says Cray.
</P>
<P>
   The new disc is produced by Steve Jordan, who also drums with
Keith Richards' X-Pensive Winos. Jordan proved to be a nut for
getting a sweet soul sound. ``I've never seen anyone so dedicated
to sound,'' says Cray. ``He did a lot of tuning of the drums and
really worked with getting the right placement of the
microphones.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan also brought in Willie Mitchell _ the famed Memphis
figure who wrote and produced hits for Al Green on the Hi Records
label. ``Willie came in, all dressed in gold. I had never met him
before,'' says Cray. ``It was like meeting a great like Muddy
Waters. He was really cool.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Cray notes, Mitchell is ``one of those guys still making
records and still writing songs, but according to big business,
they're supposed to be dead.'' Mitchell, now in his 60s, wrote a
horn arrangement on Cray's album (for the song ``Love Gone to
Waste'') that sounds timeless.
</P>
<P>
   As does another tune, ``24-7 Man,'' penned by soul veteran, Mack
Rice of ``Mustang Sally'' fame. And, for further immersion into
Southern soul, Cray covered Solomon Burke's 1964 tune, ``Won't You
Give Him (One More Chance).''
</P>
<P>
   The album has six Cray originals, ranging from the erotic ballad
``All the Way'' to a song of lost love, ``It's All Gone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Internet ticket sales: The FleetCenter reports that Internet
ticket sales for Bruce Springsteen's upcoming five sold-out shows
in Boston were ``between 30 and 40 percent'' of all tickets sold, a
record for the Fleet, according to marketing spokesman Jim Delaney.
That record may be broken when tickets for the Backstreet Boys's
Sept. 29 show go on sale Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bracing for that one,'' says Delaney. ``That's a
younger, more Internet-savvy crowd, so we're paying close attention
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bits and Pieces: Fresh from their craziness at Woodstock '99,
the Red Hot Chili Peppers perform in Moscow's Red Square Saturday.
(Will bassist Flea perform nude like he did at Woodstock?) It will
be taped by MTV and air sometime in October . . . John Paul Jones,
the Led Zeppelin bassist, will release a solo album, ``Zooma,'' on
Sept. 14, then tour in October . . . Spice Girls founder Bob
Herbert died Monday in a car accident in London, at age 57. He had
recruited (then managed) the Spice Girls through an ad in a trade
magazine three years ago. . . . Dick Latvala, the Grateful Dead
archivist who compiled the excellent ``Dick's Picks'' CDs, died
last Friday at age 56, 10 days after suffering a heart attack.
Another tough loss for Deadheads.
</P>
</TEXT>
