<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-COUNTRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINCE GILL, DWIGHT YOAKAM: COUNTRY COUSINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are not linked geographically _ one lives in Los Angeles,
the other in Nashville _ but they could be soul brothers. At the
very least, Vince Gill and Dwight Yoakam are country music's
Renaissance men. Gill can sing with Patty Loveless one minute, with
Barbra Streisand the next. No problem. And Yoakam is as adept at
acting in films as he is at cranking out a honky-tonk tune.
</P>
<P>
   Each has a distinct, personal vision that always comes across as
sincere.
</P>
<P>
   Examples:
</P>
<P>
   --Yoakam just scored a hit with a seemingly uncharacteristic
remake of Queen's rock tune ``Crazy Little Thing Called Love.'' But
the Kentucky-born singer gave it an honest hillbilly interpretation
that would have made Elvis Presley proud.
</P>
<P>
   --While known for aching country ballads, bluegrassy folk, and
rockabilly, Gill showed he can go pop as well by recording a duet
with Streisand, ``If You Ever Leave Me'' (a Richard Marx tune),
which will be on Streisand's next CD.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge thrill. We recorded the song separately, but I
was in the room while she was singing. She still has an amazing
voice,'' says Gill.
</P>
<P>
   As for Yoakam's remake of the Queen song, he first did it for a
Gap commercial. He didn't feel compromised by that, because he
feels that the Gap, unlike some major corporations, actually cares
about music.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Yoakam and Gill are still best known for their
adherence to country tradition. They are country gentlemen with a
twist, but no other contemporary male artists have done more to
keep authentic country music alive.
</P>
<P>
   Gill's most recent album, ``The Key,'' not only pays homage to
his banjo-picking Oklahoma father, Stan, in ``The Key to Life,''
but adds the signature song ``Kindly Keep It Country.'' And there's
a duet with Loveless (``My Kind of Woman / My Kind of Man'') that
resurrects memories of the historic country duets between Conway
Twitty and Loretta Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a lot of people are jumping up and down about playing real
hard-core, traditional music these days,'' says Gill. ``It's kind
of a struggle, but that doesn't make it not a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want folks to know that I respect country music,'' Gill
adds. ``You don't often hear a lot of it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam, who has met Gill only a couple of times, at awards
shows, despite the seeming compatibility between the two, feels the
same way. Only in Yoakam's case, he is most indebted to the West
Coast, Bakersfield, Calif.-based honky-tonk sound pioneered by Buck
Owens and Merle Haggard. Yoakam has been living on the West Coast
for years, after migrating from Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buck and Merle are monumental influences and we all stand on
their shoulders,'' says Yoakam. ``It's important to educate the
public and make them aware of those artists.'' (Yoakam will perform
with Owens on New Year's Eve at the Crystal Palace in Bakersfield.)
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam and Gill also view this summer's tours in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Touring has become a sanctuary for me, a haven,'' says Yoakam,
referring to the need for an alternative to his time-consuming film
projects, which haven't stopped since he appeared in ``Sling
Blade'' in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really feeling inspired this summer. I'm just looking
forward to playing,'' adds Gill, who has endured a messy divorce
and is getting his life back on track. ``It's odd, because I've got
a bunch of pals who are really struggling right now, but my life
has turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill has also been invited back to host the Country Music
Association awards in Nashville in the fall. He's become the
perennial host, almost like a Supreme Court justice being appointed
for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, once you've got the naked pictures of the (country)
executives, then you can pretty much call your own shots,'' Gill
says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Catch Gill in concert while you can, because he's planning to
take next year off. ``There comes a time when you've got to pull
back,'' says Gill, whose vast array of '90s hits has included
``When I Call Your Name,'' ``One More Last Chance,'' and ``Whenever
You Come Around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking a year off may seem like a long time, but when you're
done with it, it's not that long at all,'' says Gill, 41, sounding
like the country pragmatist that he is. And the first thing he'll
do on that year off? ``Probably throw away my shaving kit,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Once Yoakam's tour is done, he'll head right back to finish the
film he's directing and starring in, ``South of Heaven, West of
Hell.'' It's an independent film for which he also wrote the
script. He describes it as a ``gothic Western'' set in 1907. It
also stars Bridget Fonda (Yoakam's real-life girlfriend), Natalie
Canerday (who played Yoakam's girlfriend in ``Sling Blade''), Billy
Bob Thornton (also from ``Sling Blade''), and hippie icon Peter
Fonda, Bridget's father.
</P>
<P>
   What role does Yoakam play in the movie?
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of a cast-adrift marshal who is not quite certain of who
he is and how he ended up where he ended up,'' says Yoakam.
</P>
<P>
   So he's not a villain, as in ``Sling Blade''?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm playing a drifting good guy this time,'' he concludes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
