<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES ALL YOU CAN DO WITH A FLICKERING MONITOR IS GET RID OF
IT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My son recently gave me a hand-me-down Windows 95 computer so
we can communicate by e-mail. I like it a lot, but I am having a
hard time looking at the monitor for very long. It seems to be
flickering, but it's something I can really only see out of the
corner of my eye. How can I fix it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sounds like the computer hasn't properly identified the kind
of monitor you have, or it's a very old and/or cheap monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Using beams of electrons, monitors actually draw an image on the
screen line by line, but it happens so quickly that it appears to
be one big picture to you. The faster it draws the image _ known as
the refresh rate _ the better it looks. The refresh rate is
expressed in hertz.
</P>
<P>
   (Some older models draw the image by painting every other line
on the screen. The electron beams then go back and pick up the
remaining lines on a second pass. This is called interlacing, and
it can also lead to nasty flickering. Most modern monitors are
non-interlaced, in which all the lines are painted in a single
pass.)
</P>
<P>
   If it draws the image at a refresh rate of under 72 hertz,
you're apt to detect a flickering. This can cause eyestrain and
ultimately lead to a headache.
</P>
<P>
   You can change the refresh rate in the Windows display
properties control panel. Right-click on the open desktop, and
choose Properties. Click on the Settings tab, and then click the
Advanced button.
</P>
<P>
   What happens from here depends on how your video drivers are set
up, or what version of Windows you have. In most cases, you'll
click on the Adapter tab, where you'll see a drop-down titled
Refresh Rate. If your monitor is properly supported in Windows, and
if it's capable of higher refresh rates, you should have options in
this box that let you set the refresh rate at 72 hertz or higher.
</P>
<P>
   If you have only a couple of choices, none of them above 72
hertz, your monitor may not be properly recognized.
</P>
<P>
   You should see a Monitor tab at the top of this dialog box.
Choose it and see if the system has identified your monitor
correctly. If not, click the Change button and follow the
instructions to set up your monitor.
</P>
<P>
   If the monitor is correctly identified and you still don't have
access to higher refresh rates, it's likely that this is an older
model and you may want to consider replacing it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently bought a new computer that came with Windows 98. I
had been using Windows 3.1. Try as I might, I can't get used to
using My Computer to see what's on the hard drive. I want the old
File Manager back. Is there some way I can use File Manager on my
new machine? What files would I have to copy from Windows 3.1?
</P>
<P>
   A: None. The File Manager is still present in Windows 98 _ it's
just not obvious.
</P>
<P>
   When Microsoft introduced Windows 95, the company knew that
people had grown accustomed to the File Manager _ even though it's
a pretty klunky way to work with files. Microsoft decided to leave
the program in the operating system, but not point to it with a
shortcut.
</P>
<P>
   You can invoke the File Manager by going to Start, Run and enter
WINFILE, then hit Enter.
</P>
<P>
   The old Program Manager is there, too, but it likely won't have
any program groups in it. From Start/Run, enter PROGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been thinking about getting a new iMac to replace my
aging Apple Performa, but I really like my printer, and I
understand the iMacs don't have a traditional printer port. Is
there a way I can use my old printer with an iMac?
</P>
<P>
   A: Check with the maker of your printer. Many manufacturers have
come out with adapters and drivers that let you plug an older
printer into the Universal Serial Bus port on a newer Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6212 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-BOWFINGER-BOS &LR;      08-13 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BOWFINGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOWFINGER' FALLS SHORT IN SLAP-HAPPY SNAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
BOWFINGER 
Directed by: Frank Oz 
Screenplay by: Steve Martin 
Starring: Martin, Eddie Murphy, Heather Graham, Christine Baranski,
Jamie Kennedy, Terence Stamp, Robert Downey, Jr., Adam
Alexei-Malle, Kohl Sudduth 
Running time: 96 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (sex-related material and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bowfinger'' isn't quite the deliriously slap-happy farce it
wants to be, but Steve Martin and Eddie Murphy generate just enough
laughs to keep you watching it. Nominally, it's a comedy about a
desperate band of wannabes trying to make a movie. At bottom, it's
Hollywood celebrating yet again the quality it most reveres, namely
chutzpah, garnished with delusion. ``Ed Wood'' did it better, and
with more sweetness and inventiveness, but Martin has his moments
as a would-be producer facing a now-or-never time in what he
laughably calls his professional life. Murphy, who apparently
experiences claustrophobia at the idea of limiting himself to
playing only one role, chips in by playing two characters here.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, as underachiever Bobby Bowfinger, staring his 50th
birthday in the face and realizing he's actually got to make a
movie if he's going to keep on calling himself a producer, is best
in the early going. Summoning his con man energies, he takes a
script called ``Chubby Rain,'' written by his Iranian accountant,
and heads off to Le Dome with high hopes and low everything else,
including a fake ponytail. Dropping the name of a hot-ticket action
star, he catches the ear of Robert Downey's studio exec, who says
he'll greenlight the script if Bowfinger can deliver it with the
star attached. Bowfinger, of course, can barely con his way into
the exalted one's presence.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after he does get in to see the A-list icon, he's tossed
out of the guy's limo. But the hustling Bowfinger, who can't bear
to return empty-handed to his tribe of wannabes waiting for him at
home, has a plan. With a camera spirited out of a studio by a gofer
who wants to be a cinematographer, Bowfinger plans a series of
candid camera guerrilla assaults on Murphy's Kit Ramsey,
photographing him, then fabricating a film around the bits of
unauthorized footage. In other words, he plans to deliver an action
film the star doesn't know he's in. It's a funny enough notion, fed
by the fact that the star is something of a paranoiac basket case.
</P>
<P>
   Kit Ramsey is not merely leery of white people; he's afraid of
aliens. Whenever the people in Bowfinger's movie come flying out of
the bushes at him, they do get reaction shots. That the shaky
action hero seeks counseling and refuge in an upmarket
self-actualization temple called Mind Head allows Martin to take a
few not-so-veiled shots at Scientology. And there is something to
be said for Christine Baranski's stagy leading lady, who accosts
the panicked star on the street in the style of Irma Vep, and
Heather Graham's ingenue, who literally steps off the bus from the
Midwest in full Dorothy mode except for the Ruby Slippers.
</P>
<P>
   Graham is funny at first in her wide-eyed but purposeful way of
sleeping with everyone on the set in an effort to figure out where
the power is so she can link to it. But she and the other
characters are written so thinly, with no back stories or
deviations from their single-function existences, that the film
begins to evaporate. Comely as Graham may be in her tight pink
toreador pants and midriff-baring tops, there are only so many ways
for her to run after Murphy's star waving her hands and sending him
into yet another fleeing mode. Eventually, the star gets so spooked
that he checks into Mind Head's sleek sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   To complete the film, Bowfinger is forced to find a double for
Ramsey, in much the same way the real-life Ed Wood pressed his
dentist into service when Bela Lugosi died during the filming of
``Plan 9 from Outer Space.'' Enter Murphy again, inverting his
``Holy Man'' character, giving the sagging film a lift. Murphy's
slow reaction shots as a sweet nerd with buck teeth and a shy smile
are the best thing in ``Bowfinger,'' especially when he's told to
cross a busy eight-lane freeway and not to worry because the
drivers are all stunt men.
</P>
<P>
   The scramble that ensues is a metaphor for the film within a
film _ and for ``Bowfinger'' itself. It plays like a string of
loosely (sometimes very loosely) connected bits, held together by
the desperation of the band of losers who will do anything to
sustain the belief that they're part of the world of moviemaking.
But even losers have more idiosyncrasy and personality than this
bunch. ``Bowfinger'' makes you wish Martin had run the script
through his word processor a few more times. It could have been a
lot funnier. It's not frantic enough and the characters don't have
enough character.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
