A6214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-SWEETWATER-BOS &LR;      08-13 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SWEETWATER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEETWATER, THE GROUP THAT COULDN'T SURVIVE WOODSTOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
SWEETWATER 
A True Rock Story 
Starring: Amy Jo Johnson, Michelle Phillips, Kelli Williams,
Frederic Forrest, Adam Ant 
Directed by: Lorraine Senna 
On: VH1 
Time: Sunday at 9 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody, as far as I know, has done a doctoral study on the bad
brown acid that journeyed through the mudpits of the original
Woodstock. And we can still look forward to an in-depth profile of
the 1969 concert's Port-a-San man, a deconstructive literary
analysis of ``Feel Like I'm Fixin' to Die Rag,'' and maybe a
fashion retrospective featuring the carnival couture of Mr. Wavy
Gravy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the 30th anniversary of the legendary ``three days
of peace and music,'' VH1 is providing us with its own unique
Woodstock-related project. Called ``Sweetwater: A True Rock
History,'' it's a ``fact-based'' made-for-TV movie about the first
rock group to perform at the legendary festival. Taking the stage
for their flute-heavy version of ``Motherless Child'' that August
day, Sweetwater was on the brink of fame and fortune, the object of
bidding wars among record labels hungry for the next Janis Joplin
and Grace Slick. But only a few months later, the 7-person fusion
band dropped completely out of sight, another sad tumble off the
ladder of pop stardom, another American almost-was. What every
happened to Sweetwater and, to borrow the title of a VH1
docu-series, where are they now?
</P>
<P>
   It's actually not a bad premise for a movie, as Tom Hanks knew
when he wrote and directed ``That Thing You Do!'' The story
presents an opportunity to reimagine the ironies of 1960s rock
stardom from an enlightened 1990s perspective, now that the
mystique of fame has been thoroughly disassembled. It also gives
filmmakers a chance to stretch beyond the plot arc of 99.9 percent
of all celebrity profiles _ the heady rise, the drunken fall, and
the sober resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   But despite a impressive lead performance by Amy Jo Johnson, the
young actress who plays Julie on ``Felicity,'' ``Sweetwater'' fails
to break on through to the other side of cliche. It takes some
strong raw matter _ Johnson, buoyant musical scenes, and an
electrified pace _ and hammers it into the overly familiar shape of
a cautionary melodrama. It's the same old shape as the channel's
own ``Behind the Music'' series, as well as ``The E! True Hollywood
Story,'' an easy-to-read shape that fails to capitalize on the
deeper truths that fictionalization can provide. Even worse, the
movie compounds its cliches by tacking on a present-day framing
device about a newly sober TV reporter (played tensely by Kelli
Williams of ``The Practice'') whose career hinges on her success in
creating a segment on the Sweetwater story.
</P>
<P>
   And so ``Sweetwater'' jumps from dynamic re-stagings of the
band's ecstatic performances in a sunny park and at Whiskey a Go
Go, to hokey pathos and ridiculous, screenplay-driven coincidences.
At the center of the story is Nansi Nevins, Sweetwater's unstable
lead singer. Amid the band's infectious rhythms, Nevins sings
soulfully and dances angelically, but offstage she stuggles with an
unsupportive mother and the temporary consolations of booze. This
being a paint-by-numbers rock story, Nevins is of course having an
affair with the leader of the band, Alex Del Zeppo, and, of course,
he breaks her heart by succumbing to the groupie temptations of the
road. Waiting in the wings at Woodstock, Alex and Nansi take about
60 seconds of screen time to transform their troubled relationship
into a warm friendship, and then they go onstage to lose themselves
in the music. In one particularly silly scene, Janis Joplin is
briefly seen swigging from a bottle of Southern Comfort, which she
hands to Nevins while mumbling, ``It's the only thing they can't
take away from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock turned out to be the zenith for Sweetwater: In
December of 1969, Nevins was injured in a car accident and the
tracheotomy that saved her permanently damaged one of her vocal
cords. The band proceeded into oblivion without her, while she hit
bottom after an unsuccessful solo career. Johnson manages to
maintain some dignity during these tired drunk scenes, but she is
at her best as the innocent Nansi, who simply walks onstage and
begins singing with the band after a dare from a friend. Johnson
also sings her own songs with authority. (According to the real
Nevins' comments on the Sweetwater website, VH1 couldn't use her
voice because ``Amy Jo's speaking voice didn't match my singing
voice.'') As the present-day Nevins, Michelle Phillips _ who had
her ups and downs with the Mamas and the Papas _ brings needed
grace to some trite older-wiser business. (Phillips lip-syncs to
the real Nevins at the end of the movie.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweetwater'' is notable as the first in what will be a regular
series of made-for-TV movies by VH1. It doesn't bode well. As the
TV archive of rock history, the channel needs to work harder at
finding material that's less formulaic and safe, two qualities that
aren't generally identified with rock and roll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
