<HEADER>
A6218 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-DETROIT-BOS &LR;      08-13 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DETROIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KISS THIS BRAINLESS `DETROIT' GOODBYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
DETROIT ROCK CITY 
Directed by: Adam Rifkin 
Screenplay by: Carl V. Dupre 
Starring: Edward Furlong, Giuseppe Andrews, James DeBello, Sam
Huntington, Melanie Lynskey, Nick Scotti, Shannon Tweed, Miles
Dougal, Natasha Lyonne, Lin Shaye and KISS (Gene Simmons, Paul
Stanley, Ace Frehley and Peter Criss) 
Running time: 96 minutes 
Rated: R 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No rock band pushes as much merchandise as KISS. To the already
hefty product line must now be added ``Detroit Rock City,'' a
sweet-tempered but on the whole lame and clumsy film about four
kids in 1978 who decide to break out of Cleveland and floor it all
the way to Detroit to attend a KISS concert there. Although we
glimpse the zigzag makeup mavens at the end, the film (Gene Simmons
is one of its producers) isn't so much about KISS as about kids
breaking out of the confines of adult authority, although the kids
in the film are hardly up to speed when it comes to mapping out new
frontiers of wildness. Their getaway car is a
borrowed-without-permission Volvo belonging to one of their moms.
</P>
<P>
   Not the hissing gargoyle mom of the most baby-faced of the four,
Jam (Sam Huntington). Lin Shaye (the dog-owning lady of ``There's
Something About Mary'') has a fit when she discovers a KISS record
hidden in a Carpenters record jacket. Denouncing the band as
satanic, she banishes her son to a Catholic boarding school. She
exists, in short, to serve as a speed bump, over which Jam and his
three equally innocent and naive buddies (Edward Furlong, James Di
Bello, and Giuseppe Andrews) roll once they break Jam out of the
boarding school with the help of hallucinogens. The film does take
a long time getting them to Detroit, where they are faced with the
need to score four tickets, having become separated from the ones
they had.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Jam, who has all he can do to overcome his
mother's domination, the others fan out in search of sex as well as
tickets, and find it in some pretty contrived and sexist ways.
Repeatedly, the actors bring more to the table than the script
gives them to play. This is especially true in the case of Furlong,
a talented young actor who must endure the film's most painfully
embarrassing scene, when he parades onstage in a club for male
strippers, hoping to win the money for a scalper's concert ticket.
Most of the Detroit scenes were actually filmed in Toronto, which
subtracts a certain gritty veracity. Sitting through ``Detroit Rock
City'' is a little like watching The History Channel with a
wallbanging soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   The few scenes that appear to have been shot in Detroit
presumably are more faithful to history than to geography. The
carful of kids from Cleveland enters Detroit via the city's Belle
Isle Bridge, which they could only have reached from Ohio by
driving underwater. Unlike the rest of the film, that would have
been worth seeing. There aren't many films that can be thought of
as loud, moronic, and quaint, but ``Detroit Rock City'' is one of
them. It's strictly for rabid KISS completists and audiences
exhausted from rising to the level of mental effort demanded by
``Austin Powers,'' ``Big Daddy,'' and ``American Pie.'' In all
other respects, ``Detroit Rock City'' gives brainlessness a bad
name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
