<HEADER>
A6219 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-FOLK-ART-$ADV15-HNS &LR;      08-13 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOLK-ART-$ADV15-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPIRE STATE EXHIBIT IS RICH IN ART WITH A COMMON TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 15)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KRIS WORRELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ When most people think about folk art, they
think of Grandma Moses and her Northeast landscapes. Or they think
of Howard Finster, the Georgia preacher-turned-artist. Or maybe
they think of those wooden cutouts people stick in their front
yards.
</P>
<P>
   But there is much more to folk art than Grandma M. and lawn
ornaments, and you don't have to be a Southerner to appreciate it.
New York's rich folk-art history is evident in the exhibition
``Empire State Mosaic: The Folk Art of New York,'' on display at
the New York State Historical Association's Fenimore Art Museum in
Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which runs through the end of the year, offers more
than 100 examples of work by New York state folk artists from the
18th to 20th centuries, arranged chronologically to provide
historical context.
</P>
<P>
   ``We define `folk art' as works of art created by people who
have no formal art training and who work in a style that is
deceptively simple,'' said Paul D'Ambrosio, chief curator for the
state historical association and the curator of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Folk art is the art of common people, done in an uncommon way.
Folk artists tend to use bold color and unconventional materials,
such as wood, metal, plastic, beads and found objects. There is
often a whimsical, almost childlike quality to their work, which
may be why some folk art is also called ``primitive'' or ``naive.''
Folk painters, for example, do not depict the world realistically
but more often two-dimensionally, showing a lot of detail in their
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes some folk paintings important historical
documents,'' D'Ambrosio said.
</P>
<P>
   One such example, called the ``Van Bergen Overmantel,'' is the
earliest known American genre painting and the only known scene of
everyday life among the Dutch of 18th-century New York. Painted on
wood, it hung over the mantel in Marten Van Bergen's Hudson Valley
farmhouse in the early 1700s. The painting shows the entire family,
their servants and slaves, their Native American neighbors and the
impressive Catskills in the background.
</P>
<P>
   The New York folk art style reflects the diverse ethnic and
racial cultures of the region. The 17th and 18th centuries were
dominated by the art of the Iroquois, Dutch and Germans. The
Iroquois created beautiful wood and bone carvings and detailed
beadwork. The Dutch made ornamental ironwork such as door-knockers
and weather vanes. The Germans painted furniture and decorated
family records such as birth certificates. The English were known
for their needlework, portraiture and landscapes. All contained a
strong sense of place and a robust spirit of commerce that was
reflective of the prosperity these groups experienced in their new
country.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s, Grandma Moses brought folk art to international
attention with her carefully wrought ``memory paintings'' of rural
scenes from her childhood. In 1957, the Abby Aldrich Rockefeller
Folk Art Center, a museum named in honor of the wife of John D.
Rockefeller Jr., opened in Williamsburg, Va. The Museum of American
Folk Art in New York opened in 1964 and expanded the definition of
folk art with such exhibitions as ``Twentieth-Century Folk Art and
Artists'' (1970), ``Tattoo'' (1971) and ``Occult'' (1973).
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1980s, hip alternative rock acts like R.E.M. and
Talking Heads featured paintings by Howard Finster on their album
covers and brought folk art into the realm of popular culture. The
art of common people was being embraced by, well, common people.
</P>
<P>
   While 20th-century folk art addresses some of the same themes
that concerned earlier folk artists _ religion, the rural life and
nature _ it has changed in significant ways. For starters, modern
folk art usually isn't created to fulfill a consumer demand, as
cigar-store Indians or handmade quilts were. ``It's more personal
or idiosyncratic,'' D'Ambrosio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twentieth-century folk art is more about an artist expressing
himself or herself: their hopes, their experiences, their region.
It tends to be more intense emotionally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the most vibrant and compelling pieces in the show is a
large painting of Marilyn Monroe and Joe DiMaggio by Malcah Zeldis,
an acclaimed Jewish folk artist who lives and works in New York
City. Painted in bold strokes and bright colors, it shows the
famous couple sitting together on a bed, DiMaggio holding flowers
for his wife while Monroe's image is reflected in a mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I identified with her, as many women do, because she had such
a difficult childhood and she was a vulnerable woman,'' said
Zeldis, speaking during a telephone interview. ``I admired him. I
thought he was the best man she had. It was a very beautiful and
sad romance.''
</P>
<P>
   Another theme of 20th-century folk art, particularly from New
York artists, is the idea of the rural landscape giving way to a
concrete metropolis. Ralph Fasanella was a master at expressing the
energy, hopes and frustration of people living in the confines of a
city. Born in New York City to Italian-immigrant parents, Fasanella
worked as a union organizer before turning to painting as a way of
raising the awareness of the working class regarding their own
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``May Day'' (1948) is Fasanella's homage to the workers movement
of the 1930s. Thousands of marchers, carrying banners for equality
and freedom, parade through New York's Union Square, past a
reviewing stand and shrine to labor heroes that includes Jefferson,
Lincoln, Roosevelt, Douglass and Ronald Reagan (who was president
of the Screen Actors Guild at the time).
</P>
<P>
   The marchers head toward a more humane, egalitarian society,
which Fasanella portrays as a beautiful, open park where people of
all races hold hands, the New York Giants win and the cigars are
cheaper. The vivid color, intricate detail and patterns within
patterns make ``May Day'' a rich and layered visual narrative.
</P>
<P>
   The show features a number of folk-art sculptures as well,
including ``Marla,'' a smiling girl made from metal that artist and
ex-sheet-metal worker Irving Dominick modeled after his 10-year-old
granddaughter. ``Empire State Building'' (1984), by Gregorio
Marzan, is a likeness of that famous edifice made from Popsicle
sticks and silver and purple foil. There's even a ``Trout Box,'' a
long, carved box by Michael Lavery, who belongs to the Hermitage
Artists, a group of homeless men in Troy who support themselves by
creating and selling their art.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not be the best artists in the world,'' Zeldis said,
``but we are authentic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
