<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6221 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-MUSCLE-BOS &LR;      08-13 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MUSCLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SIMPLE SUSPENSE OF `MUSCLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MUSCLE MEMORY 
By William G. Tapply 
St. Martin's Press, 257 pp., $23.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With her ``husky voice'' and ``warm, shy smile,'' Kaye Fallon, a
nice, wholesome schoolteacher, is magnetically attractive to men.
To students and friends and also her unhappily estranged husband,
Mick, a former pro basketball player with a bad temper, a gambling
jones, and a ton of debt. So when Kaye is murdered _ bludgeoned
with a 6-pound replica of Rodin's ``The Thinker'' _ Mick Fallon
makes a plausible suspect.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to praise ``Muscle Memory'' _ William G. Tapply's
16th Brady Coyne mystery and among the most smoothly crafted of the
many I've read _ without, unfortunately, slightly compromising the
reading experience. But one can't fairly describe the novel without
mentioning the central crime, which comes as a powerful jolt after
some 45 pages of silky, leisurely buildup and sharp
characterization.
</P>
<P>
   But not to worry. Tapply, a Cambridge, Mass. author who has
become a master of the serial crime novel, has created a book that
offers a wealth of pleasures. Not the least of them _ and something
that will appeal explicitly to other writers while pleasing other
readers perhaps less consciously _ is the polished economy of
Tapply's prose. The book is short, 257 rather large-print pages,
but replete. Here he is, for example, writing in the voice of his
protagonist Coyne, a Boston lawyer with a Copley Square practice
and an appetite for trout fishing and difficult criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I like to sit on a boulder in the middle of a
stream, watch the insects flutter over the water, try to spot the
gray shadow of a trout lurking in the currents. . . . And when I
locate a trout I'd like to catch, I want to feel I've got all the
time in the world to study his habits, divine his weaknesses, cast
to him, change flies, shift my position, cast again.''
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, Tapply, a published fishing and outdoors writer as
well as Coyne's chronicler, evokes the natural world with limber,
effortless-sounding sentences. On the other, at the same time that
he ripens Coyne's sensibility, he metaphorically explores the
lawyer's obsessive drive as a sleuth and catcher of villains.
Virtually every flowing phrase of ``Muscle Memory'' impels the
story or deepens character and, quite often, both.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a fine story, simple in conception but taut with
suspense from the moment of Kaye's killing in a spasm of offstage
violence _ we hear about the murder, we don't see it enacted.
</P>
<P>
   Coyne is a casual drinking buddy of Mick's when the lawyer
offers to represent him in the divorce suit filed by his wife. Mick
is angry and bitter and dishonest, too, so when Kaye is murdered,
however much the aggrieved husband protests his innocence, he's
hard to believe. Coyne's task, of course, is to find the real
killer. What distinguishes ``Muscle Memory'' is the convincing way
Tapply produces so many disturbingly suspicious suspects _ a
smitten student of Kaye's who works at a Jiffy Lube, a widower who
lives across the street from her, a roaming handicapped neighbor,
the principal of the regional high school where she taught. In
Coyne, Tapply has fashioned a good man who can see the potential
for evil in almost everyone, a quality essential to his work. And
it is this conviction, I suspect _ that we're all capable at least
of nasty crimes of passion _ that allows Tapply to spread suspicion
around so widely and effectively.
</P>
<P>
   What few flaws there are in the novel are mainly problems of
omission, disappointed expectations that only readers familiar with
the Coyne series could notice. For example, the Boston cityscape,
which has often enriched the books enormously, is scarcely
noticeable despite being the setting for much of the action.
</P>
<P>
   And although this is a niggling complaint, why does Tapply
elaborate in minute detail what Coyne wears when he dashes out of
his harborside apartment to meet a homicide detective? ``I hastily
pulled on a pair of jeans, a cotton shirt, socks, sneakers,
windbreaker. I patted my pockets for cigarettes, keys, and wallet,
then took the elevator down to the lobby.'' This reads like a goofy
mail-order catalog entry or else a parody of the kind of fiction
Tapply otherwise handles with coolly controlled lyricism.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider the lawyer-sleuth on his little balcony, smoking,
thinking, taking in the harborscape, smelling the ``mingled
low-tide aroma of seaweed, diesel fuel, mud, and salt.'' Tapply
then concludes the paragraph: ``The dolorous dong of the bell-buoy
out at the mouth of the harbor echoed in the damp night air.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few writers of crime fiction have managed to generate
prose this leanly poetic in the service of their hard-boiled
stories. Tapply does it all the time in ``Muscle Memory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
