<SLUG> BC-CELLPHONE-DEADSPOTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC SLEUTH FIND THE FADE IN CELLULAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTBOROUGH, Mass. _ Thousands of folks love to drive around New
England looking for the hot spots. Eugene Giordano, on the other
hand, racks up 3,000 miles a month looking for the dead spots.
</P>
<P>
   As wireless telephone companies serving the region battle for
best-coverage boasting rights and try to reduce customer gripes
about scratchy and dropped calls, Giordano pilots one of Bell
Atlantic Mobile's key weapons: a Ford Taurus station wagon
outfitted with $250,000 worth of electronics and a porcupine-quill
array of antennas on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of eight long days each month, Giordano drives a
1,700-mile route, plus another 1,300 miles deadheading back to his
Westborough laboratory, where he spends the rest of his time
analyzing and reporting data. As he drives, an on-board computer
makes thousands of calls from eight wireless phones housed in
gun-metal-grey boxes behind the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   With Global Positioning System receivers charting the car's
location every second, a laptop computer mounted on the dashboard
records and displays how well calls get through, how many calls
each carrier drops and where, and where Bell and its five rivals
have patchy or missing coverage.
</P>
<P>
   All six wireless companies serving Greater Boston routinely send
technicians on patrol to test their cell networks' calling
strength. But Bell Atlantic, with 6.2 million customers around the
country, has been among the most aggressive at marketing its tests
as a selling point to prospective customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell Atlantic has really tried to define network quality and
network coverage as a differentiator for them,'' said Mark
Lowenstein, a leading wireless-industry analyst with The Yankee
Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   While wireless calling remains ``the most competitive sector in
the telecom industry,'' Lowenstein said, ``prices have rapidly
converged, so the cost difference between one carrier and another
is not significant.''
</P>
<P>
   However, customers count on being able to make and get calls
from a carrier throughout their region. That makes network coverage
an increasingly important buying point for the 33,000 Americans who
sign up for cell phones every day.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bell's local rivals, for example, Omnipoint has four
two-person teams of ``drive testers'' who are out ``all the time''
checking on network reliability and even developing seasonal tweaks
to account for lost coverage in warm months when foliage grows
dense, spokeswoman Karin Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think what Bell Atlantic is doing is anything more
than what we're doing here,'' said John Redman of Nextel, which
made a special blitz of the Boston Marathon route earlier this year
to ensure the 325 radio-cell phone units it donated for calling in
race updates would have uninterrupted service.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Wireless, Cellular One, and Sprint PCS also do the same
rolling surveillance as Bell Atlantic Mobile, both to measure
performance and identify where they need to add towers or rent
antenna space on rivals' towers to fill service gaps.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, to ensure clear reception and enough
channels to serve demand, wireless companies need a broadcasting
site every 4 miles along a highway, many more in cities such as
Boston and Cambridge and fewer in light-traffic rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   For wireless companies, knowing exactly where new towers are
needed from on-the-road tests, and not just pins on a map, is also
economically vital. Local zoning boards throughout New England have
been toughening tower siting rules in response to complaints about
unsightly antenna proliferation and largely unproven but, among
some people, hard-to-shake fears that cell towers' electromagnetic
radiation is a public health menace.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, American Tower Inc. of Boston paid nearly
$381,000 per tower for each of 2,100 sites owned by Vodafone
AirTouch PLC, which American Tower will lease back to AirTouch and
use to install rivals' antennas. ``Towers are becoming a very
valuable commodity,'' Lowenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   In forested parts of Massachusetts, including one spot east of
Interstate 495 in Bolton, AT&AMP;T has pioneered cell towers camoflaged
as tall, if sickly looking, pine trees. The towers have rubber bark
and antenna-disguising branches made of a special plastic that lets
radio waves pass through unimpeded and, seen at 65 m.p.h., blend
into the tree line.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic has 380 cell sites around the region bounded by
southwestern Maine, Worcester, and Cape Cod, more than two-thirds
of which have been erected on structures including buildings, water
towers, and church steeples.
</P>
<P>
   In coming years, said Richard B. Enright, northeast network
engineering director for Bell Atlantic Mobile, the company will
spend over $100 million beefing up coverage in spottily served
areas such as Cape Cod, along Route 2 west of Concord, and on Route
3 in Plymouth. Earlier this week it added coverage in the
Massachusetts Turnpike extension tunnel under the Prudential
Center, using a coaxial cable system already installed in the three
harbor tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular networks operate by constantly determining which tower
is in the best location to serve a given telephone in use. As the
connection to one tower weakens, network computers decide which
tower should ``take the handoff,'' then transfer the call to the
next cell down the road, ideally with the caller hearing _ if
anything _ only a sudden improvement in clarity.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano's testing regimen regularly helps engineers determine
whether various towers' coverage should be extended or shortened in
certain directions to ensure the most efficient distribution of
calls among towers, although such ``tweaking'' can only go so far,
said Bell network manager Gian DaGama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any wireless carrier that tells you they're not going to have
dropped calls or other problems is really misleading you,'' said
Nextel's Redman.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano's job has nice perks, such as the chance to sightsee in
the rolling mountains of New Hampshire and Worcester County, and
the seashores of southern Rhode Island and Cape Cod. But he spends
many hours slogging along considerably less scenic, traffic-clogged
roads including I-495 and Route 128 and the streets of downtown
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He is also treated to a mind-boggling cacophony of
computer-generated chatter from the Comarco Wireless Technologies
testing system. During every 150-second-long simulated conversation
during a test session, computer-driven voice modules in the car and
at the Westborough lab speak a script of pre-recorded nonsense
phrases designed to include hard-to-decipher phonetic sounds and
different male and female voices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken leg is a rare dish,'' one phone might say. ``Fill the
ink jar with sticky glue,'' the lab computer responds. ``He smokes
a big pipe with strong content,'' adds another voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will drive you crazy if you listen too hard to all of it,''
Giordano said with a laugh as he cruised up I-495 toward a ``dead
spot'' near the Route 2 interchange in Harvard that Bell Atlantic
is trying to fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind the driving,'' said Giordano, but when he is
parked running tests, he does find that ``I seem to be a target''
for police officers who want to know what he is doing _ and
sometimes ask whether he is an FBI agent or a spy.
</P>
<P>
   And if he happens to stop along a highway to check cellular
coverage, he said, ``Traffic slows down to a crawl because they all
think I'm a state trooper,'' thanks to the 13 antennas on the roof.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
