<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV15-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAVE GOVERNMENT ISSUES BEHIND, BUT WATCH OUT FOR THE RISK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 15, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have $175,000 in Series H. bonds, which pay an interest
rate of 6 percent. I use this interest income to live on,
supplementing pension and Social Security income for my husband and
myself. We are ages 70 and 69. The bonds will mature in about a
year. While I could renew them, the current interest rate is about
4 percent. I need the $10,000. What suggestions do you have for
obtaining a return in that $10,000 range? I read a lot about
Vanguard. Can you enlighten me? We have other investments which we
do not touch, and we hope they will continue to do well.
</P>
<P>
   D.L., Allentown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, you certainly could maintain that $10,000 income stream
if you went to a portfolio of Vanguard's fixed-income funds. In
fact, you could improve on it a bit. But before you take the
plunge, you should understand that you would be moving from
government-guaranteed investments into the open market and, even if
you invest conservatively in the bond market, you face an element
of risk.
</P>
<P>
   You can get a pretty good idea of what I'm talking about if you
look at this year's results for the fund I would suggest as the
core of a fixed-income fund portfolio with Vanguard: its GNMA fund.
So far this year, the fund has lost 1.1 percent. Why? Not only
because interest rates have risen this year, but because investors
are afraid that they will rise higher still.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, long-term investors in this fund take the attitude
that share prices will rise and fall periodically, but the monthly
income checks will keep rolling in, and that's why they bought the
fund in the first place. Currently the fund offers a yield of 6.73
percent, which would represent an income stream of $11,777 if you
put your entire position there.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than do that, I suggest you hedge your bets, putting
only about half of the money in the GNMA fund, dividing the balance
between fixed-income holdings that are both more and less risky. At
the most conservative end, you might put a quarter in Vanguard's
Prime Money Market fund, which currently pays 4.82 percent. And at
the riskier end, an investment in Vanguard's High-Yield Corporate
Bond fund now yields 9.21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to follow those suggestions, the portfolio average
yield at current rates would be 6.89 percent, giving you an income
stream of $12,071 a year.
</P>
<P>
   If you take that course, my suggestion would be that for a time
you simply take withdrawals representing $10,000 a year, leaving
the additional yield in the account to eventually build a buffer
against those market swings I mentioned at the outset.
</P>
<P>
   If you're unhappy with the riskier end of the spectrum, you
could change the allocation, reducing the reliance on the high
yield (or junk bond) fund and adding to the money market or GNMA
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, let me end where I began. Before you make a move, get a
copy of the prospectuses and annual reports of these funds, read
the sections on risk carefully, and look back to the years when
they did not do well. If you're comfortable with the idea that you
can live with the market swings of well-managed funds in these
markets, then go ahead. Otherwise, seek out relatively short-term
CDs, which offer the best rates available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 45 years old and have about $145,000 in an IRA invested
in Vanguard LifeStrategy Moderate Growth fund. For the past four
years it has done well; however, with the year 2000 around the
corner, I feel it might be a good time to get more aggressive. If
you agree with me, which Vanguard funds do you think will do well
with the turn of the millennium?
</P>
<P>
   J.B., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the time to be more aggressive was four years ago.
Vanguard's LifeStrategy Moderate Growth is a balanced fund, holding
about a third of its assets in the bond market. It's the kind of
fund that some people use for the last half-decade before
retirement, having reached an age where they want to reduce their
reliance on the stock market because of its inherent risk. Other
people who are drawn to balanced funds are very cautious and want
to hedge their stock-market bet, no matter how old or young they
are.
</P>
<P>
   I agree that if you are somewhere between 15 and 20 years away
from your anticipated retirement age, you probably would be well
served in the long run by taking a more aggressive investment
stance, moving into all-stock funds such as Vanguard Windsor II,
Vanguard Index 500, and Vanguard Index Value.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm not all that enthusiastic about your timing. The recent
faltering of the market may be tied to high interest rates and the
prospect of more of the same, but it may also be that the market
has come so far in the last four years that it has run ahead of
itself. Prices at this point don't seems to me to be reflecting
current earnings or dividends or even next year's earnings or
dividends, but rather the anticipated earnings and dividends
several years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I started by saying I'm not all that enthusiastic
about your timing. If nothing changes for the balance of this year,
my guess is that the stock markets are likely to enter the third
millennium in a state of exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, I would propose a three-pronged strategy.
First, for the next six or eight months, I would do nothing. If the
markets at that point seem stable and if earnings have been
catching up with the stock prices, I'd begin with modest transfers
into Windsor II and Index Value. Only in the third stage, perhaps
two or three years from now, when stocks might have reached what
analysts call a neutral stance _ in neither a bull nor a bear
market _ would I turn to fairly heavy reliance upon Vanguard Index
500. You could then treat that as your core holding _ perhaps
representing 50 percent of your retirement portfolio _ until about
five years before retirement, when you could look again to balanced
offerings such as Vanguard's LifeStrategy Moderate Growth or its
Balanced Index funds.
</P>
<P>
   Another suggestion I would make is to put any ongoing
contributions you make to the IRA into funds that will get you into
different market sectors. You might start with Vanguard's Mid-Cap
and Small Cap Index Funds and, if it reopens by the time you're
ready, its Health Care Fund, as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 32 years old, and my husband is 34. He is self-employed,
and, despite many New Year's resolutions, he has not put anything
away for retirement. (Please feel free to comment on this.) I have
been putting some money away over the years, and I'm wondering if
you can tell me what shape we're in and where we might be by age
55. We would probably like to retire with an income of about
$50,000. I currently put $80 a week into a 401(k) plan, and my
employer matches it by 50 percent. The money is invested 30 percent
each in Fidelity Advisor Growth Opportunities and Invesco
Industrial Income and 40 percent in Invesco Total Return. I have a
total of $7,500 in the account so far. I also have saved $27,500 in
other mutual fund accounts. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   A.T., Canton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. So you want me to scare the old man into action, eh? Well,
let's go through the numbers, and my guess is that they will do the
job without requiring much of a bawling out from me.
</P>
<P>
   If you continue at your current pace and your portfolio produced
average returns over 23 years (I used your age, since you're the
one doing all the saving), you would accumulate $828,477, a tidy
enough sum. You could then transfer it to a fixed-income portfolio,
and, if that portfolio produced average returns of 6.5 percent, it
would provide you with an income stream of $53,851 a year. Q.E.D.?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. There are two additional factors that wreck those
pleasant visions. Both relate to inflation. If inflation runs at an
average 3.5 percent during those 23 years, you will need $110,305
to buy what $50,000 buys today _ meaning that your income stream
would represent less than half of what you target. Second, when you
retire at an early age, such as 55, you need to think hard about
the effects that inflation will have on your finances in the later
years of retirement. Thus you will not only want a fixed-income
portfolio to supply your living expenses, but also some
supplemental savings that would remain in growth instruments, such
as your stock funds, so as to provide extra capital to buffer you
against that inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In short, you can't do it alone; you've got to get hubby
involved. Why not suggest he start with a SEP-IRA, which would be
funded through automatic monthly withdrawals from his checking
account. You could perhaps begin with an amount that's small enough
that it doesn't make much of a dent in his cash flow, ideally
raising it later as his earnings improve or as the realities of
financing his retirement sinks in and he becomes willing to
sacrifice a little comfort today in exchange for comfort in
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
