   MUSIC-COUNTRY (Undated) _ At the very least, Vince Gill and
Dwight Yoakam are country music's Renaissance men. By Steve Morse.
930 words.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ROCK (Undated) _ Robert Cray is the ``Crown Prince of the
Blues,'' although he doesn't trumpet any one label for himself. By
Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MUSCLE (Undated) _ It's difficult to praise ``Muscle
Memory'' _ William G. Tapply's 16th Brady Coyne mystery, without
compromising the reading experience.By John Koch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CELLPHONE-DEADSPOTS (Westborough, Mass.) _ Gene Giordano drives
3,000 miles a month looking for dead spots _ places where Bell
Atlantic Mobile service isn't available within its antenna
territory. By Peter Howe. 1300 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Mutual fund manager Chip Morris
has come up with a way to put a value on Internet stocks, even
those that don't make a dime. By Steven Syre and Charles Stein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;   &UR; (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS-KATZENMOYER (Smithfield, R.I.) _ His nickname,
``Big Cat,'' brings to mind a sabre-toothed mauler, ready to
pounce. Oh, how that would suit the Patriots. Will Andy Katzenmoyer
be the predator of their prayers? By Kevin Paul Dupont. (2 takes)
PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   SAIL-COLUMN (Undated) _ With 150,000 miles of blue water sailing
past his stern, Dodge Morgan weighs in on the matter of Coast Guard
rescues for boats in trouble. By Tony Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SPORTS-COLUMN (Undated) -- Pretty soon, pro golfers will be
hiring baseball umpires union boss Richie Phillips and demanding
even more money. By Howard Manly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
