to _ that felt like a real accomplishment! Especially for someone
who had no sports skills growing up. It's just a fun thing. And
Reno was a heck of a player. I mean, she was scary.
</P>
<P>
   I remember I was playing first base when she was batting, and
when she was running the bases you definitely did not want to make
the mistake of being on the baseline. She was just an aggressive,
physical player. And I admired that, at the same time as it scared
me. When I met her, I just thought: Wow, who is this tall, strong,
aggressive player? Turned out to be Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you think about how Monica Lewinsky ended up? Was she
exploited or not?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think she's very young. I think you don't show your thong
bikini underwear to your employer without giving a signal of some
sort that you'd welcome a sexual advance. And I don't think anybody
tried to coerce her into anything, except Ken Starr and his merry
band of men.
</P>
<P>
   And at the same time I fear that she will live to regret this,
although she seems temporarily to be riding high. Part of what
happens with any young woman who comes to see her only value as her
sexual appeal and her conventional attractiveness, who is so
obsessed with her body being too large, and trying to fill that
insecurity with attention from men, is that the ageism of the
culture catches up to her.
</P>
<P>
   You are only sexually attractive, conventionally, for a very
brief period in an otherwise long life. And if you don't have
