<SLUG> BC-THE-PROGRESSIVE-MAG-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Patricia Ireland on Clinton, Softball with Janet Reno and Other
Events &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Russia's Nukes Remain A Threat &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Legacy of Land Mines, Cluster Bomblets and U-235 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The following articles from The Progressive are available from
The New York Times Syndicate as one-shot buys:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PATRICIA IRELAND ON CLINTON, SOFTBALL with JANET RENO and OTHER
EVENTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Ruth Conniff &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Ireland, president of the National Organization for
Women, is probably the most visible representative of feminism in
the United States. She's always in the hot seat _ called upon to
account for everything from feminists' ``coziness'' with the
Clinton administration to the perception that feminists are a bunch
of man-bashing radicals. She writes in her autobiography, ``What
Women Want,'' about her seven years as an airline stewardess, as
well as, years later, being one of the first women to make partner
in a corporate law firm.
</P>
<P>
   -- This interview is conducted by Ruth Conniff, Washington
editor of The Progressive. (slugged: BC-PATRICIA-IRELAND-INTERVIEW,
priority code r, category codes a,k)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA'S NUKES REMAIN A THREAT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Arjun Makhijani &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to widespread public opinion, the danger of a nuclear
confrontation between the United States and Russia has not receded.
It's no secret that Russia's instability makes the rest of the
world less secure. In response to its military weakness, President
Boris Yeltsin in April approved ``a blueprint for the development
and use of nonstrategic nuclear weapons,'' which would modernize
some of the tactical and short-range weapons Russia removed from
its arsenal several years ago. Russia and the United States had a
joint plan to address Y2K's potential nuclear command-and-control
problems; but the project has been put on hold.
</P>
<P>
   -- Arjun Makhijani is the president of the Institute for Energy
and Environmental Research in Takoma Park, Md. (slugged:
BC-RUSSIA-NUCLEAR-BRINK-NYTSF, priority code r, category codes a,k)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LEGACY of LAND MINES, CLUSTER BOMBLETS and U-235 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Bill Mesler &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   They are about the size of a paper-towel holder, bright yellow
with orange lettering. A little white plastic umbrella is attached
to one end, giving it a harmless, toy-like appearance. But these
little items are far from innocuous. They are bomblets from cluster
bombs _ NATO's deadliest anti-personnel weapon _ left behind by the
U.S. Air Force. The Kosovo landscape is littered with them, as well
as the remnants of anti-tank shells made of radioactive depleted
uranium.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bill Mesler, a Washington, D.C.-based journalist, writes
frequently on arms-control issues for The Progressive, The Nation
and other publications. Mesler has conducted extensive
investigative research on the health and environmental effects of
depleted-uranium weapons. (slugged: BC-LANDMINES-BOMBLETS-NYTSF,
priority code r, category codes a,k) &LR;  &QL;
