<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6244 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-PARENTS-INFLUENCE-COX     08-13 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTS-INFLUENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Books examine the influence of parents on their offspring
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``Stranger in the Nest''
 &HT;    By David B. Cohen, Ph.D.
 &HT;    John Wiley &AMP; Sons. 312 pages. $27.95.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``Hand Me Down Dreams''
 &HT;    By Mary H. Jacobsen.
 &HT;    Harmony Books. 224 pages $22.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents always wonder how much influence they have on their
children. Two recent books have interesting things to say on that
question. But because they go into much depth, neither seems likely
to reach a general readership. And that's too bad.
</P>
<P>
   Seen together, they open a dialogue on how much parenting
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stranger in the Nest'' by David Cohen, a University of Texas
psychology professor, looks at the nature vs. nurture question and
comes down pretty hard for nature _ though he does suggest that
events in the womb also can play a role in development. Backed up
by scientific studies, his book carries pages of chapter notes and
bibliography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hand Me Down Dreams,'' a book by Mary Jacobsen, a
Massachusetts social worker and psychotherapist, is heavier on
nurture. She suggests children often find themselves unknowingly
living out the dreams of their parents. She applies ideas commonly
accepted in family systems therapy and offers pages of tips for
readers on how to change.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, on the other hand, sees family behavior as less powerful.
He views parents as ``witnesses to the miracle of child
development,'' rather than the ones who make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me,'' he said, ``that parenting is about managing
behavior. While a kid is developing his intelligence and his
personality, parents are managing behavior. Keeping a lid on the
nasty inclinations and trying to promote potentials by giving
opportunities. ... Then the child moves out of the nest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A parent's ability to impose their agenda on their child is
rather limited, it turns out.''
</P>
<P>
   If most of what a child becomes is biology _ genetics and
prenatal, as Cohen argues, then both parental and peer influence
are not all we've thought, though they can have a strong effect at
least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that parents need not be blamed every time a
child does something horrible.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
