A6253 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-HOUSTON-OLYMPICS-     08-13 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HOUSTON-OLYMPICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON SEEKS NEW SLOGAN, NICKNAME FOR 2012 OLYMPIC BID 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston, the city that's hard to define, is once again trying to
define itself.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the city has come up with the ironic slogans
``Houston's Hot'' and ``Houston: Expect the Unexpected'' with its
sense of unintended irony.
</P>
<P>
   But none are the instant-recognition monikers such as ``The Big
Apple,'' or ``Tinseltown,'' or ``The Big Easy'' or even ``The Big
D.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Houstonians trying to lure the 2012 Summer Olympic Games
are hoping to come up with a slogan that defines the fourth-largest
city in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   It's no easy task, said Chuck Carlberg, president of the Rives
Carlberg advertising firm. Although Houstonians really like living
here, he said, at times they have trouble defining themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's population is seemingly always in flux. About 75
percent of its residents come from other cities. One in 10 has
lived in Houston less than four years, while almost half have lived
here less than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always trying to get a sense of who we are,'' Carlberg
said. ``And I'm not sure anyone has gotten it, yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Houston 2012 Foundation met recently at the
George R. Brown Convention Center to try and ``get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlberg, whose company is providing promotional consulting,
wants the group to focus on Houston being a frontier.
</P>
<P>
   That brings a sense of Houston being a rough-and-ready town of
the Old West, he said, but it also captures the idea that Houston
is a city of the new frontier. The city has been a pioneer in
several fields, including space, medicine, technology, energy and
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   So Carlberg tossed out two proposals for the group.
</P>
<P>
   The first, with its unintentional reference to the Kennedy
administration, was ``Houston: The Spirit of the New Frontier.''
</P>
<P>
   The second was ``Houston: Where the Frontier Spirit Is Alive and
Kickin'.'' Neither won rave reviews, especially the latter, which
had no supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Some foundation members are sensitive to Houston getting its
image too closely aligned with the Wild West. Yes, Houston has the
world's largest rodeo, but they don't want the city to be
identified simply as that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be careful not to cast ourselves as country
hicks,'' said foundation President George DeMontrond.
</P>
<P>
   Jordy Tollett, head of the Greater Houston Convention &AMP; Visitors
Bureau, which spends about $2 million annually to promote Houston,
expressed a similar concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that it's bad, but people might not think we're as
sophisticated as Dallas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, also seeking the 2012 Summer Games, was on everyone's
mind. The group wants to get its logo in place first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I want to get the Texas concept before they do,''
DeMontrond confided.
</P>
<P>
   Most agreed that having an association with Texas is important
to the effort, especially should Houston become the choice of the
U.S. Olympic Committee. At that point, the city would have to lobby
the International Olympic Committee for the final selection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People in South America, Central America, Canada _ when they
think of Texas, it's very positively,'' said City Councilwoman
Martha Wong. ``We ought to take advantage of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The group sent the proposal back to the drawing board, endorsing
the notion of bringing the frontier concept into the logo. Two
slogans may eventually emerge, one for the USOC effort and one for
the IOC drive.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they will ``get it,'' maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only slogan that seems to have any staying power in Houston
is the age-old ``Bayou City,'' which could fit half the cities on
the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   But it's better than a combination of the previous two,
``Houston: Unexpectedly Hot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6256 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     08-13 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OTHER SIDE OF THE LARRY ROBISON STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every parent in America who has more than one child has uttered
the words, ``Let me hear the other side of the story,'' before
passing judgment on who was guilty and who was innocent of whatever
infraction is being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Robison, the mother of convicted killer Larry Keith
Robison, is working overtime to make sure that the world _ or at
the very least the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles and the
governor's office _ hears her son's side of the story in an attempt
to win clemency from his date with execution next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Robison has been twice convicted _ by separate juries
before different judges _ of fatally shooting Bruce Gardner on Aug.
10, 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner wasn't the only one to die by Robison's hand that day.
Robison killed four other people, including a boy on his 11th
birthday, before taking a shower, changing clothes and leaving the
scene in Gardner's car. He stole Gardner's wallet, making it
difficult for police to identify the body and trace the stolen car.
He even changed the license plates on the car to evade capture.
</P>
<P>
   After his conviction, Robison accepted the death penalty
sentence as ``God's will'' and was initially ambivalent about his
attorneys' efforts to appeal his sentence. In a 1990 interview with
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram from his Death Row confines, he again
admitted to the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Robison says her son has been mentally ill all his adult
life but couldn't get treatment. The family tried repeatedly to
have him institutionalized for schizophrenia but was unsuccessful
because he didn't exhibit any signs of violent behavior, his mother
says. Lock him away forever, she pleads, but don't kill my boy.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, counters Melissa Estes, a Fort Worth native and
graduate of the University of Texas who practices law in Oregon.
Gardner was Estes' cousin. Although she no doubt understands a
mother's desire to save her son, she takes issue with people who
want to discount the decisions made by 24 jurors who agonized over
all the testimony and evidence before rejecting the defense
strategy of Robison's mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robison was never diagnosed as mentally ill until after he
committed these murders, and then only by defense expert witnesses
as a defense tactic,'' Estes wrote in a letter rebutting recent
Star-Telegram columns by Molly Ivins and Bob Ray Sanders that
called for mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Estes says that through court testimony it was learned that
Robison in fact was institutionalized, even jailed, on several
occasions, but it was for illegal drug use, not schizophrenia.
``Robison's defense attorneys selected a defense other than `a
drug-induced killing spree,' which didn't help Karla Faye Tucker.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll remember that Tucker was executed last year for her part
in a grisly 1983 pick-ax murder. Her defense strategy of ``I didn't
know what I was doing because of the drugs I took'' didn't cut it
with her jury.
</P>
<P>
   Robison admitted to using LSD, amphetamines, marijuana,
tranquilizers, PCP and other illegal drugs. Medical experts
testified that long-term drug abuse such as Robison's could cause
symptoms of schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, defense attorneys testified that Robison heard
voices, a symptom of his mental illness. In a taped conversation
that was transcribed and published in the Star-Telegram, Robison
admitted to a friend that the voices were an invention.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most strident capital punishment supporter balks at the
idea of executing an innocent man. There is no question in anyone's
mind that Robison is guilty of these heinous crimes, the details of
which I have deliberately omitted because they are too graphic to
review over your morning orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   The smoke screen that is being raised to stop his appointment
with the needle next Tuesday is whether Robison is mentally ill to
the point that he knew not what he was doing that hot August day at
two cottages near Lake Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four jurors and numerous appeals courts heard both sides
of the story, they reviewed every shred of evidence and testimony
provided, and they said Larry Keith Robison must face the
consequences for his actions. Next Tuesday. In Huntsville. Let God
provide the mercy.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
