<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6257 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-13 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN LAWS FOR A SAFER AMERICA?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   News of those shootings in Los Angeles had barely hit the
airwaves before the anti-gun crowd was exploiting this new tragedy
to advance their political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only hope that this latest incident will intensify our
resolve to make America a safer place,'' President Clinton said,
adroitly avoiding any specific mention of the gun-control measures
he's been promoting since the Columbine High School shootings in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't have to be specific. Everybody knew what he meant
when he spoke of the need to ``make America a safer place.''
</P>
<P>
   The insistence that more gun laws will make America safer is the
essence of the gun-control crusade. But it's a flawed premise
because the people we are trying to keep the guns away from will
always be able to get their hands on guns.
</P>
<P>
   We can restrict, regulate and even outlaw guns until the cows
come home, but the sad fact remains: People who are bent on
wreaking death and destruction on their fellow humans are no more
likely to be stymied by laws against guns than they are by laws
against assault and murder.
</P>
<P>
   The only certain result of ever-increasing gun control is that
law-abiding citizens find it ever more difficult to arm themselves
in defense of their lives and property. Law-abiding citizens will
obey gun laws just as conscientiously as they obey other laws;
criminals will violate gun laws just as relentlessly as they
violate any law that attempts to deter criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the biggest problem with the constantly intensifying
_ to borrow Clinton's word _ campaign to banish firearms: The
Constitution of the United States guarantees the citizenry's right
to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   The folks who want to rid society of guns obviously wish that
the founders had not adopted this guarantee in the form of the
Second Amendment to the defining document of our great nation _
just as those who loathe the media wish there were no First
Amendment guaranteeing freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
   Just as those who distrust the justice system wish that the
Constitution's authors had not devised a Fourth, Fifth, Sixth,
Seventh or Eighth Amendment to protect the rights of people accused
of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   As I always note when writing about this subject, I am not a
``gun nut.'' I'm not even a gun owner, and I have no plans to
become one.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bill of Rights is the Bill of Rights. These rights were
not intended to go with the flow, as it were, becoming targets for
restriction or even eradication whenever it might seem fashionable
to attack them.
</P>
<P>
   I howl in indignation when opponents of the First Amendment
attempt to undermine its guarantees of free speech, press and
religion. It would be hypocritical for anyone who opposes
governmental tampering with the First Amendment to sit idly by
while anti-gun forces try to destroy the Second Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   And make no mistake about it: They can wail all they want to
that they're only pushing for reasonable restrictions on guns, but
their ultimate goal is abolishing Americans' right to ``keep and
bear arms.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Tuesday's tragedy at and near the Jewish community center
in California, does anyone seriously believe that the white
supremacist wacko who perpetrated that shooting spree could have
been rendered harmless by any gun law? It appears that the weaponry
that felon Buford Furrow was hauling around the countryside was in
his possession illegally. What new law would prevent such a
homicidal maniac from committing murder and mayhem?
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: It is much easier to pass gun laws than to
address the challenging problems of evil and violence in our
society. Every time some crazed gunman shoots up a schoolyard or a
workplace, we react by passing some more gun laws, dutifully
reinforcing our commitment to ``intensify our resolve to make
America a safer place.''
</P>
<P>
   But one more gun law _ or 100 more gun laws _ will do nothing to
make America safer, because such laws do nothing to address the
underlying evil that causes these horrifying acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6258 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-ISRAEL-BARAKSTYLE-$AD     08-13 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAKSTYLE-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN EDS: adds new 13th graf updating Barak support from United
States . . .
 &HT;    BARAK'S MILITARY STYLE UNDER FIRE IN OFFICE
 &HT;    700&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 15 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ During his campaign, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak touted his reputation as Israel's ``Number 1 soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, some Israelis are chafing at the military outlook of their
new commando-in-chief. To their surprise, Barak has kept the peace
process on hold and sidelined the country's most famous doves.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, 57, won in a landslide in the May elections. Israel's
most decorated soldier, he promised to bring unity to the divided
country and to restart the peace process with the Arabs, which
predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu left in a deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks into the job, his standing with average Israelis is
still intact. But, he has alienated some within his own Labor Party
with the tight lid he keeps on his policies and the clique of
former army colleagues around which he centralizes power.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, he has brought new faces and a new _ possibly
risky _ approach to the six-year-old Oslo peace process with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the picture now is Barak's Labor Party rival Shimon
Peres, a Nobel Peace Prize winner. Barak gave him an ill-defined
new ministry post. According to newspaper reports, Peres needs
office space and is ``taciturn'' at meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Peres is an idealistic peacemaker and party politician. He wrote
a book about the ``New Middle East,'' where Arabs and Jews would
learn to trust each other and work together.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is a military man and systems engineer. He talks little
about trust, but rather ``separation.'' He is skeptical of the
Peres approach, spelled out in the 1993 Oslo Accords, of exchanging
concessions with the Arabs in step-by-step confidence building
moves.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of most in the region, Barak did not immediately
resume land transfers to the Palestinians. Instead, he has sought
to restructure the next phase, the Wye River Memorandum that Israel
signed in October.
</P>
<P>
   The goodwill many Palestinians offered Barak upon his taking
office has now deteriorated and small-scale terror attacks are
increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Before continuing the land transfers, Barak wants a better
picture of what concessions Israel may have to make later in the
process. That demand shows the difference between the military
approach of Barak and the diplomatic approach of Oslo's creators
like Peres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel put down a down payment without knowing the final
price,'' said political scientist Shmuel(CQ) Sandler, at Tel Aviv's
Bar-Ilan University. ``Military people like to see the real price.
They like substance. Politicians are more liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's harder line on Wye is consistent with the Israeli
apprehension about giving up land. Even some Oslo architects, in
light of difficulties that have occurred in implementing the plan,
have backed Barak's approach.
</P>
<P>
   Those who back the new prime minister say he reflects the
pragmatic approach of his mentor, slain prime minister, and fellow
general, Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Others say he differs from Rabin by defying Israel's old
political order.
</P>
<P>
   The debate crystallized two weeks ago when Barak snubbed a
leader of Israel's old political elite.
</P>
<P>
   He passed over Yael Dayan, an accomplished member of parliament
in Barak's Labor Party and the daughter of legendary general Moshe
Dayan, for one of his last minister posts. He gave the job to
another woman further down on the Labor Party hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Dayan confronted Barak on the floor of the parliament and
accused him of arrogance. Referring to a famous commando raid, in
which Barak was photographed poised on the wing of a hijacked
airliner, she told him he was metaphorically still on that wing,
looking down on his party colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But, Dayan remains hopeful that Barak's methods will not damper
public opinion about how he delivers in the job, especially in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not our favorite democratic sort of behavior, but I would
be careful in defining it as something that will bring opposition
to the results. His results will be judged on their own,'' she said
in an interview with Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Others have been tougher in their criticism, often keying on his
commando background.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't listen, bears grudges and, perhaps most important
of all, we learned that there is no one who can stop this
general,'' wrote political columnist Chemi Shelev in the Israeli
daily Ma'ariv.
</P>
<P>
   Columnist Nahum Barnea, in the daily Yedioth Aharanot, said
Barak fails to understand that, in politics, ``There is no squad
commander to map out the goal . . . no repeated shooting practices,
no training. You learn as you go.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Critics warn that Barak will need the help of those he is now
alienating.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Peres, Barak moved aside Yossi Beilin, an Oslo
architect and a Peres prodigy. Beilin failed to get the foreign
minister post he coveted. Instead, he was made justice minister, a
job with little influence over the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Another dove and Labor Party stalwart, Avraham Burg, got no
ministry post. Against Barak's wishes, he then set out on his own
and won the job as parliamentary speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Barak has given key jobs to those with military and
intelligence backgrounds like his. Danny Yatom, who ran Israel's
spy agency, the Mossad, is chief of staff in the prime minister's
office. Zvi Stauber, who worked in military intelligence under
Barak, is the key foreign policy adviser.
</P>
<P>
   For Israel's second highest-ranking job, defense minister, Barak
chose to do it himself. He holds that job with the prime minister's
post, as did Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Amos Eiran, who was a senior aide to Rabin and a regional
campaign chairman for Barak, sees other resemblances between the
two men. Like Rabin, Barak eschews party formalities and cares
little about public relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``All his life, he was a military man. Very practical. He
doesn't like the traditional political nonsense and debating
everything so openly,'' Eiran said. ``He doesn't want to waste time
on nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
