<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6259 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX     08-13 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THE PHONE ALL LINED UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am a newcomer to the Net and have only one
phone line. Are there any ways of receiving my phone calls while
I'm on the Net?
</P>
<P>
   _ Busy Signal
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BUSY: Who needs a phone? When I'm surfing, I just listen to
the voices I hear in my head and do whatever they say. At least,
that's what my attorney has advised me to say.
</P>
<P>
   One of those voices belongs to Al Gore. Maybe you've heard Al
babbling about the lack of ``infrastructure'' when he's not taking
credit for inventing the Internet, cold fusion and string cheese.
What he's trying to say in his own adorably English-impaired way is
``wires.'' And most of us just don't have enough wires for all we
want to do.
</P>
<P>
   Well, don't count on seeing the country completely rewired any
time soon. Our government can barely decide how big congressional
pay raises should be without coming to a complete standstill. And
if they get any more involved in this project, we'll wind up with
an over-spec'd network built from substandard hardware installed by
the lowest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, we make do with the wires we have and count on
industry to come up with new ways to squeeze the most out of them.
The easiest path for you, Busy, is to get a second phone line. The
good news is that most existing residential phone wiring can
already accommodate one. Sure, a phone guy will come out to pretend
he's still got an important job. He'll tighten a few screws, and
then he'll have the guys downtown open the circuit. You can buy
some dual phone jacks and take care of the inside wiring yourself.
The four-conductor cable carries one line on the green and red
wires and the second on the yellow and black. It's really hard to
mess it up.
</P>
<P>
   The next step up is DSL, which is geek-ese for a digital phone
line. The existing copper wiring in your house carries both a
high-speed, continuous Internet connection (as fast as 1.5 megabits
per second vs. a top speed of 53K on a modem) and regular voice
calls for as little as 40 bucks a month, depending on your area.
The downside is you'll have to lay out a couple of hundred for
hardware, and you have to live within a prescribed distance from
the phone company office.
</P>
<P>
   If they offer you ISDN _ another form of digital line _ instead,
take a pass. More expensive, more complicated and slower. See about
a cable modem if they have them in your town. Still expensive, but
under the right conditions it can be faster than DSL. They'll
probably give you a break on HBO, too.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Epson ink-jet cartridges cost $25 at Wal-Mart.
Hewlett-Packard sells ink in bottles. Epson cautions against
refilling cartridges. Is there really a reason not to refill?
</P>
<P>
   _Ink-A-Dinka-Doo
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DINKA: Definitely! You'd cut into Epson's profit margin.
Let's face it, though. Most people are just too klutzy to try
refilling. Ink winds up all over your hands and the new upholstery.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, if you do things wrong, you could wind up gumming up the
printer beyond all hope the night before you're supposed to have
that quarterly report ready. Are a few extra bucks worth taking
that chance? Buy your cartridges.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0149 </DOCNO>
