<P>
   Peres is an idealistic peacemaker and party politician. He wrote
a book about the ``New Middle East,'' where Arabs and Jews would
learn to trust each other and work together.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is a military man and systems engineer. He talks little
about trust, but rather ``separation.'' He is skeptical of the
Peres approach, spelled out in the 1993 Oslo Accords, of exchanging
concessions with the Arabs in step-by-step confidence building
moves.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of most in the region, Barak did not immediately
resume land transfers to the Palestinians. Instead, he has sought
to restructure the next phase, the Wye River Memorandum that Israel
signed in October.
</P>
<P>
   The goodwill many Palestinians offered Barak upon his taking
office has now deteriorated and small-scale terror attacks are
increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Before continuing the land transfers, Barak wants a better
picture of what concessions Israel may have to make later in the
process. That demand shows the difference between the military
approach of Barak and the diplomatic approach of Oslo's creators
like Peres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel put down a down payment without knowing the final
price,'' said political scientist Shmuel(CQ) Sandler, at Tel Aviv's
Bar-Ilan University. ``Military people like to see the real price.
They like substance. Politicians are more liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's harder line on Wye is consistent with the Israeli
apprehension about giving up land. Even some Oslo architects, in
light of difficulties that have occurred in implementing the plan,
have backed Barak's approach.
</P>
<P>
   Those who back the new prime minister say he reflects the
pragmatic approach of his mentor, slain prime minister, and fellow
general, Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Others say he differs from Rabin by defying Israel's old
political order.
</P>
<P>
   The debate crystallized two weeks ago when Barak snubbed a
leader of Israel's old political elite.
</P>
<P>
   He passed over Yael Dayan, an accomplished member of parliament
in Barak's Labor Party and the daughter of legendary general Moshe
Dayan, for one of his last minister posts. He gave the job to
another woman further down on the Labor Party hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Dayan confronted Barak on the floor of the parliament and
accused him of arrogance. Referring to a famous commando raid, in
which Barak was photographed poised on the wing of a hijacked
airliner, she told him he was metaphorically still on that wing,
looking down on his party colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But, Dayan remains hopeful that Barak's methods will not damper
public opinion about how he delivers in the job, especially in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not our favorite democratic sort of behavior, but I would
be careful in defining it as something that will bring opposition
to the results. His results will be judged on their own,'' she said
in an interview with Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Others have been tougher in their criticism, often keying on his
commando background.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't listen, bears grudges and, perhaps most important
of all, we learned that there is no one who can stop this
general,'' wrote political columnist Chemi Shelev in the Israeli
daily Ma'ariv.
</P>
<P>
   Columnist Nahum Barnea, in the daily Yedioth Aharanot, said
Barak fails to understand that, in politics, ``There is no squad
commander to map out the goal . . . no repeated shooting practices,
no training. You learn as you go.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Critics warn that Barak will need the help of those he is now
alienating.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Peres, Barak moved aside Yossi Beilin, an Oslo
architect and a Peres prodigy. Beilin failed to get the foreign
minister post he coveted. Instead, he was made justice minister, a
job with little influence over the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Another dove and Labor Party stalwart, Avraham Burg, got no
ministry post. Against Barak's wishes, he then set out on his own
and won the job as parliamentary speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Barak has given key jobs to those with military and
intelligence backgrounds like his. Danny Yatom, who ran Israel's
spy agency, the Mossad, is chief of staff in the prime minister's
office. Zvi Stauber, who worked in military intelligence under
Barak, is the key foreign policy adviser.
</P>
<P>
   For Israel's second highest-ranking job, defense minister, Barak
chose to do it himself. He holds that job with the prime minister's
post, as did Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Amos Eiran, who was a senior aide to Rabin and a regional
campaign chairman for Barak, sees other resemblances between the
two men. Like Rabin, Barak eschews party formalities and cares
little about public relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``All his life, he was a military man. Very practical. He
doesn't like the traditional political nonsense and debating
everything so openly,'' Eiran said. ``He doesn't want to waste time
on nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
