<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-LABASTIDA-$ADV     08-13 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-LABASTIDA-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LABASTIDA: PRESIDENTIAL ASPIRANT RESISTS IMAGE AS MEXICO'S
HEIR-APPARENT
 &HT;    1000&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Aug. 14 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUXTLA GUTIERREZ, Mexico _ By all counts, Francisco Labastida
should breeze into his party's nomination for Mexico's next
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   He describes exquisitely detailed plans for fighting poverty and
managing the economy. A veteran administrator, he's already thrice
been a cabinet minister and is widely perceived as his party
elite's favorite son. He also counts on loyalists who vow to
deliver thousands of votes.
</P>
<P>
   But what Labastida needs most, perhaps, is someone like James
Carville, the acid-tongued American campaign consultant who put
Bill Clinton in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great reputation and prestige. I wish we could get
him,'' said Labastida, who, despite his powerful connections, has
slipped behind in some polls with less than three months to go
before Mexico's historic Nov. 7 presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   The primary is the first for this country's Revolutionary
Institutional Party, or PRI, the dominant political entity here.
After only two weeks of campaigning, the election is already one of
the most unusual Mexican political events in years. It's considered
a dress rehearsal for an even more competitive presidential
election in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 70 years, Labastida's party _ the PRI _ has
controlled Mexico's presidency. But the party has never held a
primary to democratically elect its nominee. The sitting president
has always hand-picked his successor in a ritual known as the
``dedazo, or ``big finger.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, in response to demands for democracy within the
party, candidates have to win voters by aggressively campaigning on
the road, and in the media.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico keeps no party registration lists, so any citizen with a
voter credential will be allowed to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is assured of triumph,'' said the soft-spoken and
sleekly gray Labastida, interviewed as his campaign bus rolled last
weekend through the humid streets of this city, the capital of
Chiapas, Mexico's southernmost state.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the campaign, many Mexicans found
Labastida's claim disingenuous. In a country where rumors of
conspiracy run deep, many felt that Labastida, 56, was the
guaranteed victor because he was a member of President Ernesto
Zedillo's inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   In his own mild way, Labastida bristles at the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president doesn't have an official candidate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An economics graduate of Mexico's National Autonomous
University, Labastida has worked in government jobs since 1968. He
was secretary of energy and state-run industries before becoming
governor of Sinaloa state from 1987 to 1993. He most recently was
Zedillo's agricultural minister and then interior secretary, a job
that put him in charge of fighting crime and smoothing political
unrest in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   He resigned two months ago to pursue the nomination. His
recently named campaign manager is Esteban Moctezuma, also resigned
from Zedillo's cabinet to direct Labastida's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Because of these ties, Labastida has jokingly been called ``son
of the big finger.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he was taken by surprise by the first barrage of
television ads from his chief rival, Roberto Madrazo, that
exploited that perception.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo's ads called on Mexicans to end the ``dedazo'' by giving
it a ``madrazo'' _ a ``punch'' in Mexican slang.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo, who stepped down as governor of Tabasco state to run
for the nomination, is appealing to ``PRIistas'' who yearn for more
nationalistic, populist policies rather than Zedillo's free-market
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The audacious ads stunned Labastida's campaign, which denounced
them as unethical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced that the country doesn't want a climate of
violence or attacks,'' Labastida said, remarking on Madrazo's
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But some polls show Madrazo's two-fisted style is yielding
results. In a poll conducted by the Mexico-based Indemerc-Lou
Harris group, PRI sympathizers preferred Madrazo over Labastida by
7 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida claims other surveys show he's in first place, but he
admitted he needs to counterattack to fend off Madrazo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to confront a reality,'' he told Cox Newspapers.
``People know the face of Labastida as a public functionary and
don't know what he has accomplished during his career. And now I
have to make that happen . . . I think my main defense is to speak
the truth and speak with facts about what we've done and what we
could do to achieve change in our country without tearing it
apart.''
</P>
<P>
   During his tour of Chiapas he tried to strike a balance,
admitting the Mexican government had failed to do enough for one of
the country's poorest and most socially polarized states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chiapas' poverty is a wound that hurts me as a human being,
and challenges me as a presidential aspirant,'' he said. But the
answer, he said, is not ``force,'' a reference to the government's
five-year-old conflict with Zapatista rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors are circulating that Labastida may approach the
politically savvy Carville for advice on sharpening his campaign,
although Labastida's managers say they haven't taken such a step
yet. Carville, who has worked on foreign campaigns before, is known
for his ability to distill candidates into strong messages for the
media.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Labastida's television ads are mostly testimonials from
people in Sinaloa praising his abilities as governor. On the
campaign trail, Labastida prefers to stick to speeches on education
and the economy rather than personally questioning his opponents'
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   And because he was a key member of Zedillo's administration, it
would be awkward for Labastida to tap into anti-free market
sentiment as deeply as Madrazo has dared.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Sergio Aguayo said Labastida is handicapped by
his unwillingness or inability to sell himself, a new concept in
politics here, and by the shock of having to wrestle with his PRI
brethren.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very conventional,'' Aguayo said. ``He doesn't really
convince people. Maybe talking to them in person he can, but not in
groups . . . He is Mexico's Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In Chiapas, however, Labastida showed that he attracts his share
of the party faithful, who sent scores of leaders to greet the
candidate from PRI-affiliated organizations, Indian villages and
unions representing workers as diverse as shoeshine boys and
accountants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have decided to go with Labastida. We have a policy within
our organization that everyone will comply with our decision. It's
all or nothing,'' said Luis Rey Garcia, secretary general of the
PRI-affiliated Revolutionary Federation of Workers of Chiapas,
which boasts more than 10,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   PRI unions and neighborhood groups have for decades provided
solid backing for the party's candidates, dispatching voters in
bloc in exchange for government largess.
</P>
<P>
   The groups' collective strength has waned, but Labastida and his
rivals will still compete for their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be like this in every state,'' Labastida
said, almost embarrassed by the reception he received from PRI
groups in Chiapas. ``It's like this here because I began to visit
the state in 1971, making plans for development, supervising
projects for potable water, education and health.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI is going through a profound transformation,'' he
added. ``And we will have to compete vote for vote. There are no
certain results.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
