   That fact does not bode well for the recovery of Russia's
economy, in crisis since the ruble crashed a year ago, nor for its
short-term relations with the United States on issues like arms
control.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-Russian talks will begin this month on the next steps in
reducing their substantial nuclear arsenals _ being called START
III. But the Duma has yet to ratify the 1993 Start II treaty, and
with domestic politics dominating this fall's agenda, chances of
its passage appear dim.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has staked its Russian relations on Yeltsin,
and stood by him throughout the erratic times. As a result, the
U.S.-Russia agenda has been modest lately, as the Clinton
administration, and the rest of the world, adjusts to the parade of
prime ministers since March 1998: Viktor Chernomyrdin replaced by
Sergei Kiriyenko, replaced by Primakov, replaced by Stepashin and
now by Putin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin's team is concerned only with self preservation and
self interest,'' said Alan Rousso, director of the Carnegie Moscow
Center, a think tank. ``Unfortunately they don't have a vision for
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But in fairness, it is not clear any of his would-be successors
does, either.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing exists resembling a substantive debate on the issues of
how to fix Russia's deep problems. The pack of potential candidates
is busy scrambling for political alliances and benefactors among
the business-media tycoons. Democracy, communism, socialism hardly
matter much any more to the majority of disaffected Russians,
according to opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is a nation in search of a leader, someone who can bring
stability in a country buffeted by sweeping changes, some for the
better and many of them for the worse. While Russians enjoy their
personal freedoms under the fledgling democracy, most have seen
their standard of living drop in the painful transition to a market
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The lethargy of the country's political leaders and wild
profiteering by their business allies have created a deep apathy
among Russians.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party remains strong among the old party faithful,
but its leader Gennady Zyuganov, defeated by Yeltsin in 1996, is
not given much a chance to succeed in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Once the crusading reformer, Yeltsin's popularity ratings are in
the single digits. He is seen as a man who for the past two years
has spent more time in hospitals and seclusion than on the job; a
president who rested and allowed his friends and family to get rich
while most of Russia's 146 million people sunk deeper into debt and
economic recession.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe Yeltsin already has done irreparable damage to
Russia's attempts at democracy, and his own place in history _
something that Putin and no one else can redeem.
</P>
<P>
   ``When dinosaurs writhe in their death throes they destroy
everything around them,'' the daily Moskovsky Komsomolets said in a
commentary on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Russia's political factions are seeking to fill the void _
to create new political alliances like Luzhkov's, to promote a
blank slate like Putin or to turn to the 70-year-old Primakov, a
career policymaker who really doesn't seem to crave the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other political force, if we think about it,''
said Mintimer Shaimiyev, president of the semi-autonomous Tatarstan
region and leader of the All-Russia party, which merged with
Luzhkov's Fatherland movement. ``Somebody has to assume the
responsibility now.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of Russia isn't near, just the next chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
