<HEADLINE>
`LOVE' CONQUERS ALL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE'
</P>
<P>
   1998, R, Miramax, CC, VHS priced for rental; DVD price for
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, big-spending Miramax bullied Oscar voters into giving this
a best-picture upset (along with six other Oscars). But the film
still deserved it.
</P>
<P>
   Clever, funny and warmly romantic, ``Shakespeare in Love'' makes
credible fiction out of history.
</P>
<P>
   What if William Shakespeare (Joseph Fiennes) had writer's block
and couldn't write ``Romeo and Juliet'' until he was inspired by a
muse, or lady love (Gwyneth Paltrow)?
</P>
<P>
   Their courtship has a special glow, but it's the supporting cast
that steals the show, from Geoffrey Rush as the producer with bad
teeth to Judi Dench as the stern Queen Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the true stars are director John Madden, who conducts
this cast like a maestro, and writers Marc Norman and Tom Stoppard,
who slyly use scholarly details at the service of a rollicking good
yarn. (4 stars)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`CELEBRITY' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998, R, Miramax, CC, VHS priced for rental; DVD priced for
sales.
</P>
<P>
   This black-and-white comedy from director-writer Woody Allen is
an edgy, funny stab at the caustic costs and seductive rewards of
fame.
</P>
<P>
   As Allen's surrogate, Kenneth Branagh plays an entertainment
journalist who gets too close to his show-biz quarry.
</P>
<P>
   He and Judy Davis as his ex-wife and Winona Ryder as a
struggling actress embody the kind of New York neurotics Allen fans
know and love. Leonardo DiCaprio has a cameo that may be close to
real life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrity'' is hardly an original film from Allen, but it
snugly fits the mold of ``Stardust Memories'' and other underrated
gems, and it's far more agreeable than the loathsome
``Deconstructing Harry.'' (2 1/2 stars)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`DEEP END OF THE OCEAN' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1999, PG-13, Columbia TriStar, CC, VHS priced for rental; DVD
$24.95.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Pfeiffer stars in this sad, sobering saga of a mom who
loses her 3-year-old son in a hotel lobby and rediscovers him
almost a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the meat of the story arises _ following a common
TV-movie formula. As David Letterman puts it, ``I want my kid
back!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep End'' is a bit more complicated than that, although
Pfeiffer and Treat Williams as her husband lack solid arcs to play.
</P>
<P>
   Too many motivations are murky. Characters aren't ambivalent so
much as inarticulate.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer still has a heartbreaking aura. But the best
performance is by young Ryan Merriman as the son she thought she'd
never see again. He's not a child actor, in the common sense of
that term: He's an actor. (2 1/2 stars)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`THE MOD SQUAD' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, MGM, CC, VHS priced for rental; DVD $24.98.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Avoid. This bleak, boring revival of the 1960s TV show still
plays like a TV series _ and a very bad one.
</P>
<P>
   It's also peppered with today's state-of-the-art trappings in
terms of violence, profanity and sex _ if you want to call it that.
(1 star)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ANIMATED `MADELINE' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In its debut from Disney is ``Madeline: Lost in Paris,'' a
charming animated musical about the fun-loving French school girl.
</P>
<P>
   The 75-minute film (selling for $22.99) isn't elaborately
animated, but its visuals do evoke the illustrations from the
original Ludwig Bemelman books.
</P>
<P>
   Voice actors include Lauren Bacall, Jason Alexander and
Christopher Plummer, who mix English with basic French words. Check
it out _ c'est bon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Video ratings &LR;  &QL; 
4 stars _ Excellent &QL; 
3 stars _ Good &QL; 
2 stars _ Fair &QL; 
1 star _ Poor
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
