<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6273 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-BARENAKED-LADY-     08-13 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BARENAKED-LADY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DO YOU SAY TO A BARENAKED LADY? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ You'd think if a Barenaked Lady walked into the room,
most people would at least look up. But Steven Page, lead singer
with the Canadian rock band Barenaked Ladies, remains pretty much
invisible wherever he goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a day off in Boston, which is kind of the Barenaked
mecca,'' Page said. ``I walked around with my family. We went to
the museum and the aquarium. I didn't get recognized once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in D.C., we're playing to 15,000 people. Yesterday, I
walked around, and I think maybe one person recognized me, but they
didn't say anything. That's pretty cool _ except for on the days
when I have no self-confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if he wore leopard-skin pants and torn T-shirts like Keith
Richards, more people might realize that they are in the presence
of a bona fide rock star. But Page doesn't think he could pull it
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to lose about 50 pounds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With U.S. sales of the band's latest album, ``Stunt,'' at more
than 3 million, Page and fellow Barenaked Ladies Ed Robertson, Jim
Creeggan, Tyler Stewart and Kevin Hearn have emerged as the kings
of nerd-rock.
</P>
<P>
   Their hook-happy song-craft and fun-loving stage presence appeal
to a broad modern rock audience seeking an alternative both to
bubble-gummy pop and edgier rap/metal hybrids.
</P>
<P>
   Days when Page lacks self-confidence are becoming few and far
between.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back on how I felt when I was 15 or 16,'' he said. ``I
think if I could have seen myself now, I'd have felt a whole lot
better then. Now I'm in a really popular rock band, and I'm pretty
confident about the quality of what I write and what I do onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel as much like a nerd as I probably look.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fans may not realize that BNL has a Texas connection.
``Stunt'' was recorded early last year at Austin's Arlyn Studios.
Page said the band was looking for a place away from home to
concentrate on the album, and settled on Austin in part because of
its reputation as a cool music town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured we'd be done at midnight, and we'd go out and see
some bands for a couple hours every night,'' Page said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'd be so tired after working 14-16 hours straight, we'd
be like, `OK, I'm going to bed. Everybody else going to bed?' We
did go out one night and get our minds blown by Junior Brown, but
that was about it.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Austin sessions, keyboardist Kevin Hearn fell ill.
When he returned home to Toronto, he underwent a series of tests
and learned he had leukemia. After an intense round of chemotherapy
and a blood-cell transplant, he has rejoined BNL on the current
tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 100 percent cancer-free. He just had his one-year
all-clear,'' Page said. ``That's not to say he's in perfect health.
He's certainly not the same guy he was before he was sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's got a lot of energy for a guy who was that sick. I
saw him at death's door a year ago, and to have him onstage playing
with us and playing as well as he is playing, is a pretty amazing
gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Page, 29, grew up in the Toronto suburb of Scarborough. His
father was a high school guidance counselor and a '60s folk-music
fan who raised his son on a steady diet of the Beatles and Simon
and Garfunkel.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I look back, those are definitely my biggest benchmarks,''
Page said. ``But then, getting older, I discovered people like
Elvis Costello. Later still, Randy Newman and Harry Nilsson were
huge influences on my writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there's stuff that was on the radio as I was growing
up _ Duran Duran, Culture Club, whatever else _ just because it was
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Barenaked Ladies was born in 1988 when Page and Robertson became
friends at a summer music camp. (At the same camp, Page met his
future wife, music teacher Carolyn Ricketts, with whom he has two
young children.)
</P>
<P>
   Page and Robertson were a classic case of polar opposites
attracting. While the former has a tendency to become intense and
nervous, the latter is typically cool, calm and collected. That's
Robertson doing the fly white-guy rap on ``One Week,'' BNL's huge
modern rock hit of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was going to make one decision about anything in life, I
would probably make the opposite decision,'' Page said, ``except
when we're onstage. When we're onstage, we complete each other's
sentences. We know exactly where the other guy is going. There is
this kind of telepathy when it comes to writing songs or performing
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Barenaked Ladies' 1992 debut album, ``Gordon,'' sold 900,000
copies in Canada, which is roughly the equivalent of selling 9
million in the much-larger U.S. market. The album won BNL
group-of-the-year honors at the Juno Awards, Canada's equivalent to
the Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   But the group's massive popularity produced a backlash in Canada
that only recently has begun to ebb.
</P>
<P>
   ``You read a lot of stuff in the (Canadian) papers that'll say,
`Well, they're back, and they're big, and we're still not sure that
we like them. ...' Or people think that we've `dumbed down' for
American success, which is hogwash.''
</P>
<P>
   Page says he's given up trying to convince longtime BNL fans
that success hasn't changed the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really hit home for me was, in 1992, when Nirvana hit the
top of the charts. And in Ontario, the province in Canada where we
live, we elected a Social Democratic government, and in the United
States, you elected Clinton as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``And everybody who had worked so hard to make these things
happen immediately started second-guessing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of Nirvana, it was like, `Well, they're a sellout.
It's not our music anymore.' But they weren't moving over to the
mainstream; they were bringing the mainstream over to them, which I
think is the most amazing thing you can do. I just wanted to stand
on a mountain and shout, `You won! For crying out loud, you won!'''
</P>
<P>
   Page says he doesn't worry about those critics who've accused
BNL of being a little too clever for its own good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our immediate response would be, who cares? I think that's
from the point of view of people who analyze it too much, and I
just can't bring myself to pander to that. Our fans don't sit there
and say, `If they had just put a little less humor in it, I think
I'd like it better.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Joking around is how we communicate with each other, and I
think if we were to not do that, it'd be less than honest.''
</P>
<P>
   One more question: About that name ... ?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was naming the band now, I wouldn't name it Barenaked
Ladies,'' Page said. ``But we named it when we were 18 and never
even had any sense that we'd be playing gigs. Once we did, it was
always too late to change it. The five people who saw us and liked
us, how are they going to find us again if we change the name?
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking at the time when we named it, this'll keep
us alternative. This'll keep us cool, like the Violent Femmes or
the Jazz Butcher or something like that. You know, we've sold a lot
of records for a band with the stupidest name in rock.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
