<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6275 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-BROKEDOWN     08-13 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BROKEDOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLID PERFORMANCES SAVE A GLOOMY FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Released on Aug. 14, 1998, ``Return to Paradise'' was a dour
film about a young American lad held on drug charges in a scummy
Malaysian jail. It featured an awkward script and first-rate acting
by a small cast, most notably Joaquin Phoenix as the suffering
inmate. And it was very, very serious.
</P>
<P>
   A year later comes ``Brokedown Palace,'' a dour film about young
American lasses held on drug charges in a scummy Thai jail. It
features an awkward script and first-rate acting by a small cast,
most notably Kate Beckinsale and Claire Danes as the suffering
inmates. And it is very, very serious.
</P>
<P>
   How's that for an alignment of the planets? (On Aug. 12, 2000,
we'll see the release of ``Return to Brokedown Palace Paradise,''
set, for a change of pace, on Nantucket.)
</P>
<P>
   Not to read too much into this, but perhaps Hollywood is trying
to tell us something _ perhaps we're the inmates, imprisoned in a
hoosegow of our own imagining. When a film features an outraged
attorney yelling ``We had a deal! We had a deal!'' at venal foreign
officials, there is indeed cause to feel trapped.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, ``Brokedown Palace'' has many earnest things on its
mind, some of which it addresses with competency and occasional
art. Having Claire Danes around automatically gives a movie both
accessibility and edge, thanks to her natural smarts and her
equally natural well of compassion. Beckinsale (``The Last Days of
Disco'') also labors admirably, although her role _ as the more
innocent of two squeaky innocents _ is a fuzzy blur by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Neither actress is helped by David Arata's uneven screenplay or
Jonathan Kaplan's direction, which has neither the blunt pessimism
of ``The Accused'' nor the flared-nostril theatrics of ``Unlawful
Entry,'' two earlier Kaplan pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Danes and Beckinsale play Alice and Darlene, lifelong pals just
graduated from high school. On a whim they decide to celebrate
(sans parental knowledge) in Thailand, where they do a touristy
swirl through the sights and wind up, prostrate and giggling,
before proud rows of Buddhas. In this same chipper mood they barge
into a chi-chi Thai hotel, where they sneak drinks on someone
else's tab (``Oh, come on, they don't care!,'' says Alice, all
casual condescension) and promptly get caught.
</P>
<P>
   An Australian bloke (Daniel Lapaine) comes to the rescue, wines
them, dines them, beds one of them and then dupes the two into
trying to cart a few kilos of heroin into Hong Kong. Caught again,
they get arrested and shipped off to prison, a pest-infested
hellhole where Alice reveals her naivete by asking for a lawyer
(``Ah, yes, and one telephone call, too,'' smirks her
interrogator).
</P>
<P>
   Later, transferred to a slightly less-repulsive women's prison,
Alice and Dar don earth-tone muumuus and have their hair bobbed _
ragged and greasy, but tres chic; the waif look does Indochina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't even scared at first,'' says Alice in a
tad-too-flippant narration. ``I mean, I'd had worse haircuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with these scenes, aside from the fact that everyone
looks like a model for British Vogue, is their insufficient horror.
We're told repeatedly that being held in a Thai prison is a dread
fate, but we don't see the proof of it; aside from one incident of
physical abuse, two cockroach gross-outs and one short punishment
in a corrugated iron box, there isn't much that compares
unfavorably to the American prison system.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates are free to wander outside in the twinkling Asian
sunshine. They smoke hash whenever they like. They eat tropical
fruit. Their guards are easily bribed, their fellow prisoners are
more irritating than dangerous, and one of them, a hip Caribbean
woman with perfect dreadlocks, owns a Walkman.
</P>
<P>
   The entire film grooves to a slinky dance beat, its soundtrack
filled with cuts from Delirium and the Solar Twins _ the latter
offering an electronica cover of that 1980s club anthem ``Rock the
Casbah.'' (Incidentally, ``Brokedown Palace'' comes from a Grateful
Dead song.)
</P>
<P>
   As expected, much of the film consists of Alice and Dar trying
to get out _ they've been sentenced to 33 years _ and much of this
requires the aid of ``Yankee'' Hank Green (Bill Pullman,
bemused-gruff redux), an American lawyer living in Thailand.
Pullman doesn't have much to do here beyond the usual
shark-or-saint routine, although he does have one bizarro scene in
which he browbeats a local official by threatening to put him on
``Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lou Diamond Phillips appears as a hale-fellow-well-met in
the U.S. Embassy, which (as students of plot devices already know)
proves useless in the girls' quest.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``Brokedown Palace'' succeeds _ and it does, here and
there _ is in its most human moments, small studies of friendship
and tattered dignity that appear throughout. Danes has two of them:
the first a poignant shouting match with Darlene's father, the
second an extraordinary plea for mercy at the movie's climax.
</P>
<P>
   Danes' transformation from giddy child to flinty woman is a plum
of a performance, almost reason enough to sweat through a gloomy
film.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
