<SLUG> BC-SF-COPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO POLICE FORCE MARKS 150 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In 1849, San Francisco was a Gold Rush boomtown
grown out of control. The little city by the Bay was flooded with
fortune seekers, sailors, adventurers, crooks and scalawags. The
newspapers at the time described a daily litany of robberies,
stabbings and drunken brawls.
</P>
<P>
   Where were the police? There weren't any. That was the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are without a single policeman or watchman and have not
the means for confining a prisoner for an hour,'' Mayor John Geary
said in his inaugural address.
</P>
<P>
   Geary made good on his campaign promise to get tough on crime.
On Aug. 13, 1849, he hired a police chief and 33 officers _ they
were paid $6 per day _ to bring order to the streets of San
Francisco, which then had about 12,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   In 1849, good help was hard to find. It was the year of the Gold
Rush and, like everyone else working in San Francisco, the police
often quit on a whim to seek their fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a professional department at all back then,'' said
Sgt. Bob Fitzer, the present-day department's unofficial historian.
``They basically hired guys who could break up fights.''
</P>
<P>
   The police still have to break up drunken fights in this town.
But today the department employs about 2,000 officers to patrol a
city that has grown to 750,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The department began celebrating its 150th birthday on Friday.
The celebration will continue this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The history of the department is marked by numerous stories of
courage, from tales of officers who risked _ or gave _ their lives,
to accounts of savvy investigative work.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, no one is sure of the name of the first San Francisco
police officer to die in the line of duty, Fitzer said. While there
are voluminous records of the chiefs during the department's first
five decades, there are scant records of the officers who walked
the beats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys on the street are really the unsung heroes,'' Fitzer
said.
</P>
<P>
   There are some stories, like that of Sgt. Joe Brady, who was
shot down without warning on Oct. 1, 1924, when he walked up to a
car parked outside the Fairmont Hotel, or Officer Timothy Ryan, who
was killed by a drunken ex-husband in a domestic dispute in 1943.
There was Officer Antone Schoembs, who in 1919 was shot dead with
his own gun by a car thief.
</P>
<P>
   There are also some unflattering episodes to be told, especially
from those early days.
</P>
<P>
   Officers weren't required to wear uniforms until the late 1850s.
The Alta California newspaper ran several articles complaining
about officers who hid their badges and ducked away to avoid taking
on tough guys. During the anti-Chinese riots in the 1870s and
1880s, there were reports of police officers who looked the other
way or even joined in and beat up migrant laborers.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1906 earthquake, police officers broke into a saloon
across from the Hall of Justice and took its beer to douse a fire
that threatened to destroy the city's court records and police
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Press accounts at the time reported that the officers afterward
used large quantities of the confiscated beer to fuel their own
party.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the problem of overcrowded jails.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1849, as Geary pointed out in his inaugural speech, San
Francisco did not have a jail. To solve the problem, the Town
Council bought the wooden brigantine Euphemia and turned it into a
prison barge. The ``brig'' was soon overcrowded, mostly with rowdy
former sailors who had jumped ship into San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the jail didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco newspaper readers were treated to an almost
daily diet of jail escapes, rearrests and further escapes,'' wrote
retired deputy police chief Kevin Mullen in his book ``Let Justice
Be Done: Crime and Politics in Early San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some things have changed since the early days. At
least four of the escapees were hanged without benefit of a formal
trial. ``They hanged malefactors or banished them from the state on
the pain of death should they return,'' Mullen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Fred Lau said that the 150th anniversary was not
just an opportunity to embrace history but a chance to celebrate
the department's future. Lau, 50, is quick to point out that in his
lifetime the department has changed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest change that I've noticed has been diversity:
people of color, women, lesbians, gays,'' Lau said. ``It looks a
whole lot different than it did when I started 28 years ago. The
Police Department looks more like the community it serves than ever
before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
