<HEADLINE>
SALAD DAYS: THE FORMER SIDE DISH IS NOW THE HOT NEW ENTREE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: benjy is cq; accent mark needed over first e in Frisee) 
 
By DAI HUYNH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Caesar still reigns. But as the heat index climbs,
threats to the crown are lurking in the shadows of restaurants
across Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The salad entree trend is hot, and chefs are tossing up a storm
to create a culinary oasis _ signature crispy, green treats to cool
off their sweat-beaded customers on these roasting days.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when salads were just accompaniments to steaks,
the backup chorus, the opening act. No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our salads continue to replace a lot of our traditional
entrees in terms of sales,'' says Aldo Catania, co-owner of La
Strada Restaurant near downtown. His two Houston restaurants
currently feature six salad entrees, including the Angus Steak
Salad and Pepper-Crusted Yellowfin Tuna Salad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, we offered only one. Now they've become a menu
staple,'' Catania says.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 hot salad trends:
</P>
<P>
   (1) Caesar salads with all their variations and toppings.
</P>
<P>
   (2) Hot-and-cold salads (greens topped with hot grilled items
such as chicken, eggplant or shrimp).
</P>
<P>
   (3) Grain and pasta salads.
</P>
<P>
   (4) Seafood salads.
</P>
<P>
   (5) Goat cheese salads _ i.e., Daily Review Cafe's Baked Goat
Cheese Salad.
</P>
<P>
   (6) Trendy dressings, such as garlic parsley ranch and chipotle
vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   (7) Roasted- and grilled-vegetable salads.
</P>
<P>
   (8) Fruits and nuts in salads.
</P>
<P>
   (9) Spinach salad.
</P>
<P>
   (10) Southern-style fried-chicken salad.
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest survey by the National Restaurant
Association, 82 percent of restaurant menus across the country
offer main-dish salad selections _ up 5 percent from 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge because I haven't done salads that much,''
says James Nakayama, executive chef of benjy's in Rice Village.
</P>
<P>
   It makes it more satisfying, though, when something works well.
So far, Nakayama has discovered that customers like his
pecan-crusted salmon salad, crab cake over grilled vegetables, and
maple-smoked chicken with walnuts, apples, pickled onions and
honey-thyme dressing.
</P>
<P>
   For many Houston restaurants, the bulk of the salad business
occurs at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 40 to 50 percent of my business is &UR;  &LR; salad-based during
lunch time,'' says chef Tom Williams of the Fox Diner. ``People
want to eat lighter during the day because they have to go back to
work, and it's hot.''
</P>
<P>
   But gone are the days when a tossed salad or simple chef salad
would do. Diners today are demanding more choices, more flavors.
Instead of a Cobb salad, think more along the lines of Scott Chen's
Crispy Shrimp With Honey-Coated Walnuts Over Baby Frisee, Vallone's
Marinated Grilled Portobello Salad With Beef Carpaccio, Houston's
Seared Tuna Salad, the Texas Field Greens Salad With Fried Crawfish
at Ciro's Cibi Italiani, Cafe Noir's Ginger Shrimp With Endive,
Miyako's Salmon Skin Salad, or Dalat Vietnamese Bistro's Green
Papaya With Beef Jerky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rare nowadays for diners to order the Caesar salad,''
says Zumm Escudier, executive chef of Renata's Restaurant and Piano
Bar. ``They're become educated about food, and they want to
discover and try different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Paris-trained Escudier changes her salad entrees with the
seasons. Right now, Renata's offers grilled chicken over a bed of
snow-pea leaves, banana blossoms topped with grilled chicken, and
green, red and yellow tomatoes with grilled sea bass or blackened
tuna.
</P>
<P>
   Chef Carl Walker of Brennan's follows the seasons as well,
currently offering lump crab meat on a bed of tomatoes, asparagus
and corn relish. Meanwhile, Prego is dishing out the Crabmeat Tower
Salad, and the Blue Agave is serving Crab Claw With Avocado Salad.
</P>
<P>
   For those hankering for soft-shell crabs, they can find theirs
nestled among mixed greens at Vallone's or sauteed spinach at La
Strada.
</P>
<P>
   Steak is also a popular salad topper, and so is grilled, fried
or boiled shrimp. But chicken is still the main topping at many
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Some chefs, however, are adding a sweet/savory dimension to the
meat by smoking instead of grilling, such as the tea-smoked chicken
salad with kaffir-lime vinaigrette at benjy's and the smoked
chicken spinach salad at Solero.
</P>
<P>
   Dressing and salad are like bread and butter _ they just go
together. But instead of classics such as ranch or blue-cheese
dressings, restaurants are taking a more creative approach by
blending their own. Witness Scott Chen's caviar cream sauce,
Backstreet Cafe's pumpkin seed vinaigrette, Sambuca's pepper and
corn vinaigrette and Carmelo's mango vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, we were anchored to the classics. You just didn't
deviate from them,'' Carmelo's owner Carmelo Mauro says. ``Now
there's much more creativity. We're not scared to mix and match
ingredients anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, more women than men order salad
entrees, restaurateurs say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men tend to stick to the wraps or sandwiches,'' says
Martin Berson, manager of benjy's. ``It's a macho thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
