<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Aug. 14:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-POLL (Indianola, Iowa) _ Curtain-raiser on the weekend's
straw poll. Gov. Bush comes to Iowa for his first front porch
picnic with voters. Bush has campaigned very little in the state, a
strategy that has frustrated his rivals who say he does not have a
grasp for concerns of Iowans. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-CONSERVATIVES (Dateline to kum, Iowa) _ Beyond the
big-money battle between Bush and Forbes on the eve of the straw
poll is a crucial grassroots competition among Bauer, Buchanan,
Quayle and others who want to emerge as champion of the religious
conservatives. They are all trying to repeat Pat Robertson's
surprise success here in 1988. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY (Washington) _ Folo and reaction to prospective
Pentagon guidelines intended to end abuses of the ``don't ask,
don't tell'' policy, including limits on investigations of people
in uniform who are suspected of being gay. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT-ARBORETUM (Washington) _ The U.S. National Arboretum, a
mainstay on Washington's cultural landscape for more than 70 years,
is in danger of losing a significant portion of some of its plant
and tree collections because of this summer's drought.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LA-SHOOTING-RDP (Los Angeles) _ Developments: The man charged
with shooting at children and killing a mailman in Los Angeles had
searched for Jewish organizations to attack for some time. By James
Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TEN-GRAF-RETIRE (Undated) _ Just two months after winning the
French Open for her 22nd Grand Slam singles title, Steffi Graf, one
of the great players in tennis history, said she will retire
immediately. Graf had been plagued by various injuries in recent
years but she insisted she is healthy right now and simply doesn't
have the desire to continue her career. By Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   For other sports stories, see separate sports budget or the
AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DAGESTAN (Moscow) _ Russia announces a major offensive to
crush Islamic rebels in Dagestan and the north Caucasus region. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-U.S. (Washington) _ Folo on reports the U.S. may offer to
ease its trade embargo against North Korea if it forgoes a planned
test of a new long-range missile.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DRUG-ARREST (Los Angeles) _ American authorities have
arrested a fugitive in Los Angeles suspected as one of several
gunmen in the mass drug-related slaying of 19 people last September
on a farm near Ensenada, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a tentative sked:
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-WOMEN (Rawalpindi) _ Young Muslim women who are not
allowed to attend co-ed schools find new opportunities in
Pakistan's first publicly financed graduate school for women. A
Foreign Journal by Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BEAN-BOOMERS (Freeport, Maine) _ First came the indoor trout
pond. Then there was the barnlike addition devoted to children's
clothes and accessories. Now comes what is perhaps the ultimate
sign that L.L. Bean, the 87-year-old arbiter of what's what in
rugged outerwear, is kissing up to cosseted baby boomers in a big
way: the company's Maine Hunting Shoe, its first product and
essential icon, has been revamped to make it more comfortable.
Other recent changes within the privately held company reflect an
even bigger effort to revamp the traditional L.L. Bean approach. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Prices paid to producers registered a
smaller-than expected gain in July as the first drop in food prices
in four months offset a big increase in energy prices, bringing a
measure of relief to investors concerned about inflation
accelerating. The Labor Department said the Producer Price Index
for finished goods rose 0.2 percent in July after falling 0.1
percent in June. But the core index, which excludes the volatile
food and energy sectors, was unchanged, In June, the core index
fell 0.2 percent. The Dow surges more than 100 points; long bond
rises more than a half point. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EMERGING-MARKET-FUNDS (Undated) _ A feature looking at emerging
market funds. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-MS-INDEXES (Singapore) _ Malaysian stocks surge 6
percent on news that Morgan Stanley Capital International will
reinstate Malaysia in its international stock indexes, widely used
by global fund managers to allocate investments. The investment
bank's decision, another sign of slowly strengthening investor
confidence in Asia, comes 11 months after Malaysia was expelled
from the indexes for imposing sweeping capital controls, which have
since been partly relaxed. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Frank Rich's ``Journal,'' a double-length column.
</P>
