<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS _ We spend some time in Iowa before the straw poll
talking to voters and residents about what's on their mind as
election year approaches and what they think of the candidates so
far. (Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS, MUGS,
MAP.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS-HOW _ An explainer on how the Iowa Straw poll works.
(Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS-BOX _ A list of candidates in the Iowa straw primary ad
the munber of days they's campaigned in Iowa. (Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SMUGGLE _ Folo on Chinese men found hiding in squalid
conditions in a ship in Savannah. They are being brought to Atlanta
today. (Bixler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ Congressional investigators granted King
&AMP; Spalding attorney until today to submit an amended report on
excesses and violations involving Atlanta Olympic officials and IOC
members. We'll either have the report today or a short story
updating the situation. (Turner Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-LABASTIDA _ SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico _ He's
running slightly behind or neck in neck with his chief rival in
Mexico's first ever presidential primary on Nov. 7. But as an early
campaign trip to strife-torn Chiapas state showed, Francisco
Labastida has a loyal following among some hardcore Revolutionary
Institutional Party members. (Ferriss, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Wed., Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SAFE-SCHOOLS _ WASHINGTON _ Parents get advice and answers to
their questions on ``Safe Schools, Safe Students: What Parents Can
Do'' from Education Secretary Richard Riley and a half-dozen
experts during a national teleconference supported by the Pfizer
Foundation. (Mollison, Cox News Service).18.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SAFE-TIPS.
</P>
<P>
   DEMFIGHT _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. Cynthia McKinney is not suporting
Rep. John Lewis in his quest to become majority Whip in the next
Congress (provided the Democrats take back the House). In fact, the
delegation's senior congressman got the brush off from McKinney.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
