<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6323 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-NAVY-VIEQUES-$ADV15-H     08-13 1625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVY-VIEQUES-$ADV15-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY'S BATTLE FOR VIEQUES RAISES CANCER SCARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 15)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ Fisherman Fernando Robinson estimates
that 60 of his neighbors in the residential enclave near the Navy's
training and target range have died from cancer over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Residents call the decimated neighborhood ``the Second Front.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos ``Papa Fu'' Martinez blames decaying Navy bombs and
leaking explosives strewn on the ocean floor for damaging the
underwater stands of coral that serve as nurseries for the small
fish that feed the grouper, red snapper and hog fish that make up
the fishermen's catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Navy has to go, one way or another,'' says Martinez, a
wizened 63-year-old fisherman who says he's harvested these waters
since he was seven years old.
</P>
<P>
   But Eric Morales, 28, says the Navy is an important source of
income for some of the 9,300 islanders who live on civilian land
sandwiched between a Navy ammunition depot on the western end of
the island and the firing range at the eastern end, within sight of
the islands of St. Thomas and St. Croix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have nothing against the Navy,'' says Morales, who is
hoping a Navy contract might enable the local General Electric
Corp. electrical components plant to rehire him as a fork lift
driver after a four-week layoff. ``They just have to stop the
bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   And Roberto C. Nelson, a Navy spokesman, worries that unless the
Navy resumes target practice on Vieques by September when the next
aircraft carrier battle group comes through for training, the lives
of American aviators and Marines will be in jeopardy if they face
combat.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy and Marine Corps have used Vieques for 58 years to
prepare Atlantic-based forces for deployment in every conflict
since World War II, including Vietnam, the Persian Gulf and the
78-day campaign in Kosovo earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a game,'' says Nelson, who works at the nearby
9,000-acre Roosevelt Roads Naval Station that pumps $300 million a
year into the local economy. ``In the military, the penalty you pay
for improper training is people die.''
</P>
<P>
   Vieques, an arid, wind-swept 33,000-acre island lying eight
miles east of the Puerto Rican mainland, lies at the heart of an
escalating struggle between the Navy and Puerto Rico, a
Spanish-speaking territory of 3.8 million U.S. citizens that came
under American jurisdiction during the Spanish-American War in
1898.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Ricans' simmering resentments about the use of Vieques
for target practice exploded into the open in April when the pilot
of a Marine FA-18 fighter-bomber mistakenly dropped two 500 pound
bombs on a hilltop range observation post, killing David Sanes
Rodriguez, 35, a civilian employee of the Navy, and injuring four
others.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mishap, Puerto Rico's political leaders have united to
demand that the Navy stop using Vieques for target practice and
protesters have occupied the 899-acre target area, blocking any
resumption of bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   One protester, Puerto Rican Sen. Ruben Barrios, leader of the
Puerto Rican Independence Party, vows to remain at his sandy
encampment until the Navy announces plans to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Clinton can go into the next millennium as a protector of
the ecology or he can be one of the dictators of his age,'' says
Barrios, who like Clinton graduated from Georgetown University and
Yale Law School. ``The president cannot extricate himself from this
situation _ the pressure is too great in all of Puerto Rico.''
</P>
<P>
   Bombing and shelling have been suspending since the April mishap
but Navy Secretary Richard Danzig is eager to resume target
practice at Vieques to assure that Navy pilots, ships and Marine
Corps troops are prepared for combat before they go overseas.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has ordered a special Pentagon panel to
propose a compromise by Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton is confronting the issue in
her exploratory U.S. Senate campaign in New York, where Puerto
Ricans and other Hispanics make up 14.2 percent of the state's
population. City Council member Jose Rivera raised the issue with
Mrs. Clinton during her visit to Queens on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mrs. Clinton nor her likely GOP rival, New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, has taken a position on the dispute over Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates in 2000 are likely to confront the
issue, as well, as the result of a nationwide campaign that civil
rights leader Jesse Jackson launched last week to rally Hispanic
and African-American voters on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson joined Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello and Rick
Dovalina, national president of the U.S.-based League of United
Latin American Citizens, to map political rallies in key states to
challenge the Navy's ``occupation'' of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you that once we leave this place and take our
case to the people of New York in great numbers, and Illinois and
Texas and California and Florida, this issue will be a critical
matter on the agenda for 2000,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The five states control more than half the 280 electoral votes
that a presidential candidate must win to capture the White House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vieques is an unlikely setting for such a high-level dispute.
The 22-mile long island, covered with wind-blown vegetation and
surrounded by the glistening waters of the Caribbean, was used for
centuries by Spanish colonial overlords to raise sugar cane.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy began buying 22,000 of the island's 33,000 acres in
1941 for $47 an acre to establish a training area and ammunition
depot. Nazi submarines were prowling the Atlantic Coast at the
time, imperiling Navy ships' access to resupplies of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Today, cows and horses wander aimlessly down single-land roads
crisscrossing the island. Drivers slow at corners or road-side
homes to hail greetings to childhood chums. Vice Mayor Hector Ortiz
can see a visitor at a moment's notice, no appointment required.
</P>
<P>
   Economic development is fitful. The airport terminal and the
municipal hospital are brand new, washed in the soft pastels of the
Caribbean. A sprawling sports complex, including a cavernous gym
and baseball field, stand partially complete.
</P>
<P>
   But island life has changed since the bombing mishap. Printed
and hand-scrawled signs proclaim ``Fuera Marina Vieques'' -- Navy
out of Vieques. Citizens speculate constantly about the fate of
Vieques and the most frightening talk of late is about a rumored
but unproven epidemic of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just don't know,'' says Ortiz, the city's vice mayor.
``They read that islanders suffer a higher rate of cancer than
Puerto Rico. Everything negative that happens on Vieques gets
blamed on the Navy _ even if people don't have the facts to back it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales, who has driven a van for visiting government officials
and tourists since being laid off by GE, says islanders often
complain about getting sick from seafood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people, they are afraid of the cancer, the chemicals, that
sort of thing,'' says Morales. ``It's the poison fish. You start to
feel bad, like needles poking you, your tongue is heavy. There's a
lot of dizziness. You can get sick from good fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen fear that their catches may be carrying
disease-causing chemicals from decaying bombs on the ocean floor to
the dinner tables of their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, the 56-year-old fisherman sitting in the shade of a
tree at the beach where fishermen moor their skiffs, says his
neighbors are afflicted with lung, throat and skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many young people are dying,'' says Robinson, with an
insistent tone in his voice. ``My friends lose their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk of cancer has been around for years. A study by the
government of Puerto Rico completed in October 1997 found 482 cases
of cancer between 1960 and 1989, contributing to a cancer rate on
the island that stands 27 percent higher than any other
municipality in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Cesar ``Doc'' Salicrup, 37, a Vieques-based Navy hospital
corpsman who tried to save the mortally wounded security guard in
April, says islanders may be suffering high rates of cancer due to
the widespread use of tobacco, including smoking and chewing
tobacco. Sugar cane workers for generations commonly chewed tobacco
in the fields, Salicrup recalls, possibly contributing to high
rates of cancer now among the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of the bombing mishap and White House
involvement, investigators from a federal cancer-monitoring agency,
the Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry, have begun
investigating the islanders' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry could take six months and potentially delay any
decision by Clinton on whether to allow the Navy to resume target
practice with bombs, naval gunfire, and Marines' artillery and
mortars.
</P>
<P>
   Agostini, Puerto Rico's attorney general, says the Navy must
await the outcome of the federal cancer investigation before it
``even thinks'' of resuming target practice, adding: ``They have to
run studies to try to find out if what they are doing is the reason
for these terrible health results.''
</P>
<P>
   But fishermen like Robinson remain wary of any outcome that
falls short of ending target practice by the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people who come to do the studies are from the Navy, we
won't believe them,'' says Robinson. ``If they're sent by the Navy,
nothing is going to happen. The bombing will begin again.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached via E-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
