<SLUG> BC-RAC-AUCTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. PROSPECTOR FETCHES $3 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LINDA TRISCHITTA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ The auctioneer teased the audience with
a big pause when the bidding reached $2.6 million, and then moments
later announced the final price of $3 million for a Mr. Prospector
bay colt with a white diamond between his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga Springs Mayor J. Michael O'Connell denied with a laugh
that he was one of the competing bidders during the excitement that
came midway on the closing night of the 79th Annual Fasig-Tipton
Saratoga Select Yearling auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is obviously a special event,'' O'Connell said Thursday.
``And to see a horse go for $3 million is outstanding. It reflects
well on Fasig-Tipton.''
</P>
<P>
   The $3 million purchase was made by Aaron and Marie Jones of
Eugene, Ore., who bid from outside of the auditorium, where the
crowd burst into applause as the hammer came down.
</P>
<P>
   A Jones-owned horse, Prime Timber, finished fourth in this
year's Kentucky Derby and won the San Felipe Stakes at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   The sale equaled the third highest price ever paid for a
Saratoga yearling.
</P>
<P>
   The average price for the evening's 47 lots was $253,723, which
surpassed by 18 percent the 1998 final night figure of $215,250.
Average price for the entire three-day sale was $261,456, compared
with $211,395 in 1998, a 24 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Gross sales for the final night totaled $11,925,000, 15 percent
higher than 1998's $10,332,000. Gross sales for all three sessions
totaled $38,957,000 for 149 horses, 14 percent higher than the 1998
gross total of $34,246,000 for 162 horses.
</P>
<P>
   The record price for Saratoga was $4.6 million in 1984 for a
chestnut colt. Last year's high price was $1.7 million for a filly.
</P>
<P>
   How do buyers make such expensive decisions? Some thoroughbred
buyers use timeless techniques like studying a horse's physique,
gait and cardiovascular fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Others opt for a method called biomechanics, the study of
biological processes like heart action and muscle movement. It is a
field that has improved business for one company by 400 percent in
the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   According to Robert D. Fierro, president of EQUIX Biomechanics
of Lexington, Ky., about 250 clients confidentially use his company
to evaluate the racing and breeding potentials of stallions, mares
and yearlings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can measure the heart, but you can't measure the soul,''
Fierro said of intangibles like the will to win.
</P>
<P>
   EQUIX, which charges $650 for an analysis of a horse, advised 12
clients during the Saratoga yearling sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
