<P>
   TV-SWEETWATER (Undated) -- ``Sweetwater: A True Rock History''
is a made-for-TV movie about the first rock group to perform at the
first Woodstock. By Matthew Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-TWIN (Undated) _ Too many films play like something David
Lynch shot on a bad day. But ``Twin Falls Idaho'' plays like
something Lynch might shoot on a good day. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-BROKEN (Undated) _ ``Brokedown Palace'' is yet another in
the sad little sub-genre of films about young Americans imprisoned
abroad, usually on drug-related charges. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-BOWFINGER (Undated) _ ``Bowfinger'' isn't quite the
deliriously slap-happy farce it wants to be, but Steve Martin and
Eddie Murphy generate just enough laughs to keep you watching it.
By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-DETROIT (Undated) _ ``Detroit Rock City'' is a
sweet-tempered but on the whole lame and clumsy film about four
kids in 1978 who decide to break out of Cleveland and floor it all
the way to Detroit to attend a KISS concert. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-COUNTRY (Undated) _ At the very least, Vince Gill and
Dwight Yoakam are country music's Renaissance men. By Steve Morse.
930 words.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ROCK (Undated) _ Robert Cray is the ``Crown Prince of the
Blues,'' although he doesn't trumpet any one label for himself. By
Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MUSCLE (Undated) _ It's difficult to praise ``Muscle
Memory'' _ William G. Tapply's 16th Brady Coyne mystery, without
compromising the reading experience.By John Koch.
