<HEADLINE>
LIFETIME RIVALS COMPETE FOR WOMEN'S ATTENTION, CASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, in its ongoing effort to become a one-stop
sister-clique network where thoughtful original programming would
outnumber broadcast network rehashes like ``The Commish,'' Lifetime
hatched ``Any Day Now,'' a dynamic drama that begins its second
season Sunday night, dissecting the racially delicate relationship
of two strong-willed women.
</P>
<P>
   Also returning to the cable channel's schedule this week is ``Oh
Baby,'' the unconventional comedy series about a single woman who
opts for parenthood without one of the essential ingredients such
ventures often require _ a man.
</P>
<P>
   If I failed to mention the series premiere of ``Maggie,'' the
third new series introduced last season, it's because Lifetime
killed that half-hour comedy after, as new network President Carole
Black sums up factually if rather coldly, ``It failed to live up to
the promise of its pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: It tanked in the ratings, so it was dumped on the
trash heap.
</P>
<P>
   Canceling series is par for the course in the TV industry. But
Lifetime's quick trigger finger is an exception in cable, where
shows are usually given generous amounts of time to find an
audience. How else could you possibly explain the return of
``Linc's'' on Showtime?
</P>
<P>
   The death of ``Maggie,'' a marginally humorous but ambitious
series based entirely on a woman and her doubts about love and
marriage, are proof that there's a new marshal at Lifetime. And
she's circling the wagons, readying for a fierce battle.
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime, available in 73 million homes and partly owned by
Disney, has long fought off cable competition in the form of
female-friendly Home &AMP; Garden Television, Romance Classics, The
Food Network, E! Entertainment and recently E!'s fashion-oriented
programming. But its monopoly has never been challenged head-on.
That is due to change: Oxygen Media debuts Feb. 2, and Turner's The
Women's Network is set to begin programming later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   In the all-important brand-name sweepstakes, Oxygen has already
generated word-of-mouth publicity. It has also pulled off a clever
public bashing of Lifetime by saying women don't want more passive
entertainment or more movies depicting them as victims, criticisms
that Lifetime has defended against for most of its 15 years. And
for Oxygen mouthpieces to say it's high time that television caters
to ``intelligent women'' sounds like a direct smack in the Lifetime
kisser to me.
</P>
<P>
   The word-of-mouth buzz comes courtesy of Oxygen's big-name
pedigree: CEO Geraldine Laybourne is one of the industry's most
respected visionaries, having helped build Nickelodeon into a
kiddie-channel powerhouse. She also helped guide Disney's cable
ventures, which means that from '96 to '98, she had some say in the
handling of Lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough, Oprah Winfrey is also involved _ her Harpo
Entertainment Group will produce original programming, and reruns
of ``The Oprah Winfrey Show'' will hit Oxygen by 2002. Other
partners include the Carsey-Warner TV production house, which
hasn't dazzled us as of late but whose creations include ``Cosby,''
``Roseanne,'' ``Grace Under Fire'' and ``Cybil,'' all of which
rated highly with women.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen is keeping its programming game plan under wraps, but we
do know that actress Candice Bergen will host a Charlie Rose-style
talk show called ``Exhale,'' and that comedies, dramas, sports,
music and a series on money (called ``ka-Ching'') will be part of
the menu.
</P>
<P>
   On the theory that women ages 18-to-49 will find Lifetime too
fluffy and Oxygen too stuffy comes The Women's Network, a
middle-ground channel birthed by Turner Broadcasting and partnered
with publishing companies Time Inc. and Conde Nast. This means that
the channel will draw upon such publications as Time and Gourmet, a
synergy promising politics and the latest in one-dish dinners.
</P>
<P>
   With such resources, The Women's Network, too, is promising that
its viewers will not be subjected to the kind of movies or reruns
or sitcoms offered by, well, you-know-who. ``Just reliable and
relevant information,'' says Pat Mitchell, the channel's CEO.
``Information that addresses the needs of the lives of all today's
active and smart and time-challenged women.''
</P>
<P>
   All this makes for vexing times at Lifetime, which responded
last year by pumping $160 million into original programming (a 40
percent increase from the year before) in an effort to stop looking
like a cable channel living off broadcast network reruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Day Now,'' the Deep South drama starring Annie Potts and
Lorraine Toussaint, is equal to the best of network dramas. A
number of TV critics found the series dramatically nourishing and
its choice of story lines refreshing, particularly its depiction of
female friendship complicated by matters of race.
</P>
<P>
   It quickly set a renegade precedent of going against TV formula
and probably helped bring viewers to the network's half-hour
comedies, especially ``Oh Baby,'' which featured Cynthia Stevenson
as a marketing executive who was artificially inseminated. This
season, beginning Saturday, she shows us life with baby.
</P>
<P>
   Just like ``Any Day Now,'' the series shows an engaging
relationship between two women. If this were network fare, it would
have been brought together by other devices, like affections for
the same man. Instead, Stevenson and pal Joanna Gleason are a hoot,
often at odds but united emotionally in Stevenson's decision to go
it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it appears that Lifetime is failing to capitalize
on its momentum. This season's two new entries are reality-type
series that can be found anywhere. One was. ``Ruby,'' which aired
on Fox for a spell, features Ruby Wax, an acid-tongued talk host.
Wax is so over-the-top that she'll be hilarious to half the room
and annoying to everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond Chance'' is hosted by singer Melissa Etheridge, who
introduces stories about women who have experienced twists of fate
that changed their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime plans to continue its popular lifestyle program ``New
Attitudes'' and the biography series ``Intimate Portraits,'' a
high-gloss treatment of celebrities that, because of its dogged
emphasis on the positive, usually ends up offering half-truths.
</P>
<P>
   Since women make 70 percent of retail purchases and pay 95
percent of the household bills (including, coincidentally, the
cable bill) don't mistake this new courtship for anything except
the pursuit of dollars. Oxygen and Turner are positioning their
channels for the unlimited competition that digital television will
provide. It's the same reason that Black Entertainment Television,
a lone wolf for 20 years, may finally get competition for
African-American viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But if Lifetime plans to defend its throne against the new
intruders, it had better up the ante in quality programming and
steer clear of movies about wives who sue The Other Woman for
stealing their husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Price of a Broken Heart'' airs at 8 p.m. CDT Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
