<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SAFE-SCHOOLS14-COX     08-13 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFE-SCHOOLS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDUCATORS, PARENTS QUIETLY LOWER SCHOOL VIOLENCE
 &HT;    820&AMP;add. With SAFE-TIPS.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While President Clinton and Congress clash over
whether to tighten hate-crime and gun-control laws, tens of
thousands of educators and parents are working outside the
spotlight to minimize school violence in less controversial ways.
</P>
<P>
   While not ignoring the unlikely chance that a school will be
assaulted by a mass murderer, they spend far more time trying to
minimize painful, everyday violence.
</P>
<P>
   At the opening of a national teleconference on school safety
Thursday night, Clinton said recent multiple shootings made
``another compelling argument for the passage of hate crimes
legislation and common sense gun laws.'' Congress has resisted such
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   But neither proposal was mentioned by any of the citizens who
spoke up during the remaining 85 minutes of the teleconference,
which was hosted by Education Secretary Richard Riley and Attorney
General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us teachers spent a lot of time talking about violence
this summer, and at first we thought we ought to push for new
policies or new legislation,'' said Eddie Davis, an English teacher
and National Education Association board member from Durham, N.C.,
who serves on his state board of education.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we finally came to the conclusion that, for the most part,
we already have the policies in place, and we already have enough
laws,'' Davis said. ``What we have to do is consistently and fairly
enforce (them), so that children know that we are being consistent
and fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lydick, a school-safety activist from Fairfax County, Va.,
said she was impressed with a booklet she read recently called
``Early Warning, Timely Response.'' It is a school safety guide
prepared last year by the Education and Justice departments and 18
national educational, children's and police organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Lydick was reassured by reading the guide, because many of its
tips have already been tried by her local coalition, which
coordinates school safety efforts by parents, educators, community
activists and business volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   She also found a few other sound ideas, like ways to convince
parents to spend more time offering a positive example and
listening to their older children's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping there's enough funding that we could give (the
guides) to everyone in every school,'' Lydick told Riley and Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Riley was quick to respond that anyone could order a copy of the
32-page guide through a toll-free phone call to 1-800-USA-LEARN or
download a copy by clicking on ``Safe Schools'' at his department's
Web site (http://www.ed.gov).
</P>
<P>
   The department has already issued more than 300,000 copies of
the guide. That included mass mailings to more than 85,000 public
and 26,000 private elementary and secondary schools last fall and
again after the deaths of 14 students and a teacher at Columbine
High School in April.
</P>
<P>
   But the booklet, like the school-by-school struggle against
violence, has been overshadowed by fears arising from the
nationally publicized multiple-victim assaults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel safe in my school, but I don't think it will be safe
when I get in the big (secondary) school,'' said Lydick's
sixth-grade daughter, Elaine.
</P>
<P>
   Two new studies support the general consensus among educators
that they are making progress:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Centers for Disease Control confirmed that the number of
adolescents who report carrying a gun, carrying another weapon such
as a knife or club, or requiring treatment for injuries from a
fight fell steadily from 1993 through 1997. In each case, the
numbers were lower in the schools than in other locations.
</P>
<P>
   _ State education departments reported to the U.S. Department of
Education that, even though enforcement of ``zero tolerance'' laws
for firearms in schools is tightening, the number of students
expelled for bringing firearms to school dropped by nearly
one-third between the 1996-97 and 1997-98 school years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must remember that despite the tragedies at Columbine and
in Georgia and the scares in other places last year, schools are
still the safest place for children,'' Reno said. But, she added,
``We must realize that the facts may not translate into what people
fear.''
</P>
<P>
   A school security officer called from Chattanooga to ask Reno
and Riley, ``Is there a nationwide plan for educational
preparedness for violence and hate crimes in schools?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no national plan, per se,'' Reno replied, deferring
to the age-old American tradition of local responsibility for
schools. Any response plan, she said, ``is going to depend on each
school district and each police force and each local community.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley interjected, ``But our 'Early Warning' guide really sets
out exactly, good, well-thought-out ideas about how (local schools,
parents, police and emergency services) can can develop those
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   As a prime example, he pointed to Zavala Elementary School in
Austin, Texas, which has received national recognition as a safe
and effective school that has become a center of community services
and recreation during and after school hours in a high-crime,
low-income neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a united effort in the community and the churches nearby,
we have psychologists, counselors, social workers, priests, parents
and volunteer mentors coming in,'' said Olivia del Valle, Zavala's
assistant principal. A school with many adults is safer than one
occupied only by students and paid professionals, several
teleconference participants agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Del Valle was impatient with the lament that most parents stop
attending school events or listening at length to their children
after their youngest child leaves elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the school's responsibility to provide many avenues for
participation, because different parents need different ways,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her school informs and recruits adult volunteers and parents
with ice cream socials, booths at flea markets, meetings held
outside of working hours in the evening or on weekends , and
parent-teacher meetings that are held in houses and beauty or
barber shops that don't scare off parents who themselves did poorly
in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every school is different, and every school needs its own
safety plan,'' Del Valle said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
