<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-STRAWPOLL (Ames, Iowa) _ Republican presidential candidates
kiss babies and eat barbecue in preparation for the Iowa straw poll
on Saturday while the apparent front-runner, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, is campaigning elsewhere in the state. By BENNETT ROTH and
R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Ames, Iowa) _ During her tenure as Texas governor,
Ann Richards once stood atop the state Capitol steps and tried to
make an outlandish joke to a group of reporters. One reporter
looked up at Richards. ``Are you serious, governor?'' She replied,
``You people can just suck the humor right out of a person.'' Gov.
George W. Bush, the apparent front-runner for the Republican
presidential nomination, got a taste of what Richards meant this
week with the publication of interviews he granted to Talk
magazine. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EL-CENIZO (El Cenizo, Texas) _ While most towns along the
U.S-Mexico border are battling to keep illegal immigrants out, this
tiny locale on the outskirts of Laredo is embracing them. El Cenizo
recently passed two ordinances, one that makes it a ``safe haven''
for illegals and another that makes Spanish the town's official
language. The action is troubling to federal officials and has
English-only advocates warning of the break-up of the United States
along lines of race and language. By THADDEUS HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARZA-AMBASSADOR (Washington) _ Oliver P. Garza, a career
diplomat who was American Consul General in Guadalajara, Mexico, is
sworn in at the State Department as the new U.S. ambassador to
Nicaragua. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NAVY-VIEQUES (Vieques, Puerto Rico) _ Fisherman Fernando
Robinson estimates that 60 of his neighbors near the Navy's
training and target range have died from cancer over the years. A
possible link between Navy munitions and cancer is the latest
wrinkle in the Navy's controversial use of the island for target
practice for the past 58 years. The Navy wants to end a four-month
suspension on bombing and shelling. The local residents want the
Navy out. President Clinton is expected to resolve the dispute
later this year. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   NATO-KLA (Washington) _ NATO coordinated air attacks with the
Kosovo Liberation Army during the war in the breakaway Yugoslav
province, communicating indirectly through the Albanian government,
NATO's top commander says. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HONEST-COPS (Mexico City) _ On a busy intersection in this
capital of impatient, fast drivers, women are stopping traffic,
taking names and writing tickets. Mexico City officials _ at a loss
over what to do with rampant, almost-institutionalized police
corruption _ have banned male police officers from giving out
traffic tickets. Here, the fairer sex is now also the more honest
sex. By SUSANA HAYWARD.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-GOLAN-HEIGHTS (Jerusalem) _ If Israel does indeed return
the Golan Heights to Syria in exchange for security, what is the
price for the longtime settlers and the Arabs who live there? By
DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-GOLAN-WATER (Jerusalem)_ One contentious issue in any
peace deal between Israel and Syria is sure to be who controls the
water in the Golan Heights, which now goes to Israel. By DEBORAH
HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Whether she becomes a U.S.
senator or returns to a law practice, Hillary Rodham Clinton will
occupy a unique niche in the pantheon of American first ladies long
after she has left the White House. Not everyone will agree that
she deserves a place of honor. But most will concede that she has
been a most unusual and often controversial president's wife. By
ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
