<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6446 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-HUNTER-REACT     08-13 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HUNTER-REACT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hometown pulls together to support Jim `Catfish' Hunter
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Brian Zumbano
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERTFORD, N.C. _ As the baseball world holds its collective
breath for Hall of Fame pitcher Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter, the town of
Hertford simply prays for a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The Perquimans County native has been hospitalized in the Pitt
County Memorial Hospital intensive care unit since suffering a head
injury during a fall at his home Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, the 53-year-old was diagnosed with amyotrophic
lateral sclerosis, better known as Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Since the incident Sunday, residents of Hertford have come
together in support of the town's most favorite son.
</P>
<P>
   ``This community loves Jimmy and his family very dearly,'' said
Sherry Harrell, who has been Hunter's next-door neighbor for the
past 27 years. ``Everybody's been completely devastated by this.
But Jimmy is a fighter and won't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Harrell, who has been to the hospital and is in
close contact with the Hunter family, Hunter's heart stopped
briefly early Tuesday morning. Hunter's condition was then upgraded
from serious to critical.
</P>
<P>
   But Hunter has rebounded since then. Hospital spokesman Doug
Boyd said Friday morning that Hunter is breathing more on his own,
although he remains in critical condition and is hooked to a
ventilator.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's ALS fund-raiser, set for McDonald's in Hertford from
6 a.m. to 11 p.m., will still go on as scheduled. The event,
co-sponsored by East Carolina radio, will raise money for the Jim
``Catfish'' Hunter ALS Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Harrell said Hunter's health is of the utmost importance in
Hertford.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard when somebody you think so much of is going through
something like this,'' Harrell said. ``But I personally plan on
being right here when he comes home. We're already planning his
coming-home party. We're just so optimistic he's going to make
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrell also said that fellow Hall of Famer Reggie Jackson and
New York Yankees owner George Steinbrenner were among several major
league baseball luminaries who have called to inquire about
Hunter's health.
</P>
<P>
   But the most support and concern has come from Hertford Baptist
Church, which Hunter and his family attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime a family in our church has a catastrophe like this, we
all come together tremendously,'' said Hertford Baptist Rev. Keith
Vaughn, who has been with the Hunter family throughout the week.
``Even if this man never threw a baseball, the community would
still hold him in the same regard. He may be North Carolina's
favorite son, and it's not just because of his baseball career. It
has to do with his strength of character and the type of person he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter retired from baseball 20 years ago after winning five
World Series rings with the Oakland Athletics and New York Yankees.
After returning to Hertford to take up hunting and fishing on a
full-time basis, Hunter was once again thrust into the national
spotlight when he was diagnosed with ALS last November. Hunter used
his notoriety to start up the Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter ALS Foundation
to raise money to fight the illness.
</P>
<P>
   Since the inception of the foundation, Hunter has made numerous
public appearances to help raise money, including a trip back to
Oakland, Calif., in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunter said that nobody could imagine how much it meant to him
to go back to California and get the support he did,'' said
Harrell, who accompanied the Hunter family on the trip with her
husband, Thomas. ``It was just wonderful. The fans were so kind to
him. I can't describe how great it was. You would think as long as
he's been out of the game, people might not remember or know too
much about him. But there was this little girl in the stands with a
sign that said 'We love you Catfish.' It was so nice.''
</P>
<P>
   But while baseball fans across the country remember Hunter as
the long-haired Cy Young award winner with the bushy mustache, most
people in and around Hertford just talk about their friend Jimmy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a special person to achieve the things Jimmy did and
not let it get to their head,'' said Ed Nixon, a life-long friend
and former high school teammate of Hunter's. ``Jimmy never let what
he'd accomplished get to his head. He was always that same ol' farm
boy. He's a darn' fine man.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
