 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Aug. 15, and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   MAIDS-EMPLOY (New York) _ The number of people who are employing
domestics is rising. By Monique P. Yazigi.
</P>
<P>
   RAPPERS'-JEWELER (Undated) _ For those not in the know, Jacob
Arabo, 34, is the Harry Winston of the hip-hop world, the jeweler
who gives most of today's leading rappers their shine. His name has
popped up in the lyrics of Mase, Foxy Brown and Busta Rhymes. An
immigrant from Tashkent, Uzbekistan, Arabo now sips Champagne
regularly with famed Hamptons party-givers like Sean (Puffy) Combs
and Russell Simmons and flies out to Las Vegas with Jay-Z and Damon
Dash to sit in the good seats at heavyweight championship fights.
By Douglas Century.
</P>
<P>
   Photo.
</P>
<P>
   HAMPTONS-HITCHHIKERS (New York) _ In the last few years, I've
picked up nearly a dozen hitchhikers _ young and old, men and
women, and once even a member of the Maidstone Club in green golf
pants. But only, and exclusively, in the Hamptons. Summer
Hamptonites, liberated from their Manhattan cellblocks and
intoxicated by the small-town charm and impression of safety that
most resort towns exude, relax their guards. They leave alarm
systems off and the front-door key under the potted reindeer
topiary. And amid some of the country's most conspicuous affluence,
they sometimes hitchhike or pick up those who do. By Steve
Garbarino.
</P>
<P>
   LUXURY-PILLOWS (New York) _ In a triumph of specialization, the
Company Store has emitted a spinoff catalogue, the new 31-page
Pillow Source Book. It is mostly about bed pillows, and it is
absolutely riveting, particularly when read in bed. Are you a
feather-core or double-down kind of person? Silk or buckwheat?
Cotton or wool fill? (Hint: the silk one might prevent wrinkles,
according to the catalogue.) By Penelope Green.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-SOUTAR (New York) _ Tuesday night was the latest episode
in the education of Mike Soutar, the new editor of Maxim magazine,
the skin-drenched monthly. The September issue, the first under
Soutar, is just out, with a cover of a scantily clad Pamela Lee (or
is that redundant?). Since its United States debut in 1997, Maxim
has become a fast favorite of adolescent American boys and the
adults who think like them. The magazines, known in their native
Britain as lad magazines, focus on the purported essentials to a
young man's life: sex, beer, sports and giggles. By Jesse McKinley.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ In the desertlike conditions that have
befallen most Northeastern gardeners this year, it is gratifying to
see a few hardy specimens unfazed by heat and drought. One such is
the yucca plant that grows behind my mailbox post. It's no miracle
that the yucca is doing well. Yuccas are native to arid desert
regions in the Southwest and in Mexico, although a few species are
native to the Southeast, including mine, Yucca filamentosa. By Cass
Peterson.
</P>
