<P>
   TEAMSTERS-FEDS (Washington) _ Ten years after federal officials
gained a strict supervisory role over the International Brotherhood
of Teamsters in an effort to rid it of mob control, the union's new
leadership is pushing hard to get the government out. The Teamsters
president, James P. Hoffa, who took office in March, has made
ending federal supervision his chief goal, insisting that the giant
union can run its own affairs now that the Mafia's hold on it has
been broken. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY (Washington) _ The Pentagon today announced its
first major revision of guidelines for enforcement of its ``don't
ask, don't tell'' policy, but failed to satisfy gay rights
advocates who say that entrenched hostility toward homosexuals in
uniform continues to result in violent harassment, including last
month's brutal murder of a Army private in Kentucky. By Philip
Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-SHOOTING-MENTAL (Seattle) _ The mental health system in
Washington state got a clear and extensive look at Buford Furrow in
the months before he is alleged to have opened fire on school
children in a Jewish Community Center and killed a postal worker in
Los Angeles. What the mental health experts saw was a man who twice
slashed his arms so deep they required stitches, drank alcohol
until he blacked out, and espoused a deep hatred for anyone who is
not white. Yet, despite lengthy evaluations at mental institutions
here, and no shortage of resources, Furrow was never ordered to
remain under state psychiatric care. Instead, after serving nearly
six months for attempting to stab two hospital attendants, he was
released to normal parole supervision and required to take
medication designed to control psychotic impulses. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-CONSERVATIVES (Dateline to kum, Iowa) _ Beyond the
big-money battle between Bush and Forbes on the eve of the straw
poll is a crucial grassroots competition among Bauer, Buchanan,
Quayle and others who want to emerge as champion of the religious
conservatives. They are all trying to repeat Pat Robertson's
surprise success here in 1988. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   TEN-GRAF-RETIRE (Undated) _ Germany's Steffi Graf, the
iconoclastic tennis dynamo whose perfectionist strivings and sonic
forehands carried her to 107 singles titles as well as a virtual
monopoly of the number one ranking at the extended peak of her
17-year career, announced her retirement yesterday in Heidelberg.
Echoing statements she made this year at the French Open and
Wimbledon, where she disclosed that her 1999 campaigns would be her
last ever at those slams, Graf, who in 1988 became the only player
in history to capture all four Grand Slam plus the Olympic gold
medal, confirmed that her nonpareil career was over, effective
immediately. By Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DAGESTAN (Moscow) _ As fighting continued in southern
Russia, the new prime minister on Friday threatened to launch air
strikes against Islamic militants in the breakaway republic of
Chechnya, risking a widening of the seven-day-old conflict in a
neighboring region, Dagestan. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Prices paid to producers registered a
smaller-than expected gain in July as the first drop in food prices
in four months offset a big increase in energy prices, bringing a
measure of relief to investors concerned about inflation
accelerating. The Labor Department said the Producer Price Index
for finished goods rose 0.2 percent in July after falling 0.1
percent in June. But the core index, which excludes the volatile
food and energy sectors, was unchanged, In June, the core index
fell 0.2 percent. The Dow surges more than 100 points; long bond
rises more than a half point. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BEAN-BOOMERS (Freeport, Maine) _ First came the indoor trout
pond. Then there was the barnlike addition devoted to children's
clothes and accessories. Now comes what is perhaps the ultimate
sign that L.L. Bean, the 87-year-old arbiter of what's what in
rugged outerwear, is kissing up to cosseted baby boomers in a big
way: the company's Maine Hunting Shoe, its first product and
essential icon, has been revamped to make it more comfortable.
Other recent changes within the privately held company reflect an
even bigger effort to revamp the traditional L.L. Bean approach. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
