<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6494 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-STRAW-VOTERS14-COX     08-13 1469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAW-VOTERS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Farming, not politics, on the minds of Iowans
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE CENTER, IOWA _ People here are talking about losing money
on a bumper corn crop _ the weather has been perfect and the green
stalks are eight feet high with golden, glowing crowns _ because
prices are so low.
</P>
<P>
   They're talking about the state fair in Des Moines, and the
possibility of another playoff run by the Trojans, their beloved
high school football team.
</P>
<P>
   But as nine Republican presidential candidates and about 500
reporters descend on nearby Ames for Saturday's GOP straw poll,
politics is one thing most people here aren't talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets to where we take the phone off the hook so we can go
to bed,'' said Mike Riemenschneider, an active Republican who has
rebuffed three candidates' offers of free straw poll tickets.
</P>
<P>
   John Strawn, editor of the local Enterprise-Record, said he
should bill fax-crazy candidates for wasting his paper, and bank
President Joyce Buck wonders why the campaign season can't be
shortened.
</P>
<P>
   Riemenschneider describes the straw poll as ``overblown,'' and
he's right: The 20-year-old event, which has come to resemble a
political carnival, is basically a Republican party fund-raiser
masquerading as an election.
</P>
<P>
   This year's poll, which is expected to attract about 10,000
people, has taken on added significance _ at least in the eyes of
the candidates and the press. Because California and New York have
moved up their primaries, the campaign schedule is front-loaded
like never before, meaning that the nomination process will be over
almost before it begins.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Texas Gov. George W. Bush has built such a large
early lead that the straw poll stakes have been raised for the
candidates who aren't even in the second tier. A poor showing in
Ames may prompt some of them to drop out.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa's straw poll, together with its February caucuses that
officially kick off the presidential campaign season, give the
Hawkeye State a significance beyond its relatively meager 7
electoral votes. The state also has tended to mirror the nation in
recent presidential elections. So it makes sense to pay attention
to Iowa, even at this early stage.
</P>
<P>
   State Center, ``The Rose Capital of Iowa'' has a population of
about 1,300. By Iowa standards that isn't so small: The town is the
site of a regional school that serves kids from surrounding farming
communities that are even smaller. State Center has no
manufacturing, and about half of the residents work in nearby
cities (Des Moines is 45 miles away).
</P>
<P>
   But State Center, which is surrounded on all sides by some of
the richest soil in the world, is and always has been about
farming.
</P>
<P>
   Talk here is about corn and soybean prices, which are at 25-year
lows. Last Thursday, corn was selling for $1.60 a bushel and
soybeans were at $4.30. To break even, farmers have to sell their
corn for about $2.50 and their soybeans for about $6.00. The
presidential candidates crisscrossing the state have touted various
solutions to the problem: opening foreign markets, emergency aid or
low-interest loans to farmers, promises to embrace embargoes that
include food.
</P>
<P>
   But when one asks State Center farmers what a president could do
to help them, many just shrug their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farm economy is so bad, people are kind of scratching
their heads,'' said Kevin Whitaker, who grows corn and soybeans and
raises hogs. Whitaker, 43, doubts that low-interest loans would do
more than ``prolong the agony'' and he balks at the prospect of
emergency assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to trim production, that's all there is to it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the emerging farm crisis, which would hit Iowa harder
than most states, it's difficult to pin down the top concern of
State Center residents.
</P>
<P>
   Sipping coffee and smoking a cigarette in the Main Street
hardware store _ a popular hang-out _ 61-year-old retiree Bob
Knutson pointed to people's frustration with HMOs as the top issue.
State Center's most prominent Democrat, 82-year-old Rita Figgins,
worries that changes to Social Security and Medicare will ``mess
them up.'' Pasta plant worker Dave Gray, bouncing his 5-year-old
son Walker on his lap, chose education. Jackie Henchal, a former
farm wife who became State Center's deputy city clerk when her
husband was forced to sell his land, wants stricter welfare rules.
</P>
<P>
   Many State Center residents, often mentioning last year's White
House sex scandal and recent school shootings, said the nation's
most pressing problem is a decline in morals. But they were
hard-pressed to say what exactly a president could do about it,
other than to avoid extramarital affairs himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think myself that kids watch too much crap on TV,'' downtown
restaurant owner Charlene ``Char'' Hrnicek said of violent
teen-agers. ``They watch blood, guts and sex on television, so what
do you expect? You don't like somebody, you get a gun out and shoot
them _ that's about where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Riemenschneider blamed modern parents for not disciplining their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what's wrong with the United States? When I was a
kid, if I knocked my neighbor's window out, my parents would beat
the hell out of me. They made you pay for it, made you go over and
rake and mow the lady's yard all summer,'' Riemenschneider said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you raise a kid that age and not know he's making
grenades and bombs in the garage?'' he added, referring to the
teen-agers who went on a shooting spree in a Colorado school.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the comments of many other State Center residents, Buck,
the bank president, said Bush ``appears to have the morals that
should be required of a president and other elected officials.''
But she shook her head when asked what a president could do to
promote such high standards in the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you legislate morality? How do you legislate ethics?''
</P>
<P>
   In their fuzzy concern about ethics and their scattered interest
in a variety of other issues, State Center residents are
representative of the rest of the country, if a recent survey is
accurate. A Gallup poll found that for the first time since 1954,
there isn't a single issue that more than one-fifth of Americans
agree is the most pressing one facing the country. Eighteen percent
of those surveyed said the most important problem was a decline in
ethics and morality, 17 percent said crime, 11 percent said
education and 10 percent said gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The results stand in stark contrast to 1980, for example, when
44 percent of respondents cited foreign policy, or 1975, when 60
percent chose the high cost of living.
</P>
<P>
   The especially early start to the 2000 campaign and the absence
of a single galvanizing issue have kept most State Center residents
from paying close attention to the political spectacle that is
shattering Iowa's summer calm. But some are already tied to
candidates _ some even by blood.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Andersen, a Web site designer and computer repairman who
recently opened a small shop on Main Street, says he shares a
great-grandfather with Vice President Al Gore. Andersen, who
publishes a monthly family newsletter that he dutifully forwards to
his Washington cousin, says he and Gore are both great-grandsons of
Henry Gore, a Virginia farmer who lived from 1736 to 1791.
</P>
<P>
   He's also been inviting the vice president to family reunions,
but Gore hadn't been able to make one and the two had never met _
until last Wednesday, when Andersen attended a Gore luncheon in
nearby Marshalltown.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up (the next) morning I had to make sure I hadn't
been dreaming,'' Andersen beamed the day after his long-awaited
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Poling, who is a big backer of GOP candidate Steve Forbes,
also is linked to a famous world leader: Former Soviet premier
Nikita Khruschev. About 12 years ago, Poling answered an ad seeking
someone resembling Khruschev to appear in a film starring Richard
Gere. Poling got the job, playing a nonspeaking role in flashback
scenes of Khruschev's 1959 visit to Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Now Poling, a semi-retired financial adviser, is organizing
Forbes supporters for the straw poll. He's already recruited six
State Center residents and four from nearby Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not part of the inner circle, he's fresh blood and he
owes no debt to special interest groups,'' Poling said of Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Poling argues that the straw poll is an important test. ``It's
about the first indication of where people stand, the first measure
of how well the candidates are doing,'' he said. ``By the way,
Forbes has the best food going _ Holiday Park barbecue from Ames,
Iowa. Be prepared for the shock of your life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
