<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-SOUTAR-ART-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULL'S-EYES AND BEER: LADS WILL BE LADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15)  
 (af)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the testosterone-laden air inside the Chelsea
Piers sports complex, Mike Soutar stood tall in the batting cage,
staring down a mechanical pitcher with a smirk on his face. The
pitch came, Soutar swung furiously _ and missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost, so close,'' Soutar said with his light Scottish brogue
and big smile. ``Next time, buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night was the latest episode in the education of Soutar,
the new editor of Maxim magazine, the skin-drenched monthly. The
September issue, the first under Soutar, is just out, with a cover
of a scantily clad Pamela Lee (or is that redundant?).
</P>
<P>
   Since its United States debut in 1997, Maxim has become a fast
favorite of adolescent American boys and the adults who think like
them. The magazines, known in their native Britain as lad
magazines, focus on the purported essentials to a young man's life:
sex, beer, sports and giggles.
</P>
<P>
   And while Soutar, who previously edited the London-based
magazine FHM, is known for having a working knowledge of all four,
he was out with a couple of colleagues last Tuesday night as part
of a continuing mission to sample lad life, American style.
</P>
<P>
   After a few dozen awkward swings and the oh-so-faint glistening
of sweat, Soutar, 32, retired to the Chelsea Brewery with his two
buddies, Andy Clerkson, the editor in chief of Stuff magazine, and
Keith Blanchard, the group creative director of Maxim and Stuff.
There the talk turned to typical Maxim fare: girls, ideas to
improve bullfighting (more bulls, less fighters) and food.
</P>
<P>
   The gang went on to the studiously hip Lot 61, which none of the
three had heard of but was suggested by the sole woman in the
group, Clerkson's wife, Carolyn. Once they were settled in a
zebra-pattern booth, beers were ordered and the menu skewered.
``What's a hacked duck?'' Soutar asked, sounding genuinely
concerned. ``And pray tell, what is arugula?'' (Pronounced, by
Soutar, are-RUG-ool-uh.)
</P>
<P>
   For all his roguish charm, Soutar is married with two young
boys, and Tuesday would be his last night as a pretend bachelor
after four months alone in New York. His weekend plans would
include dashing to London to bring his wife and children back to
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited I can't sleep,'' he said. ``I had a cleaning
woman come in to make it look like I'd done the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   A pu pu platter (there were jokes), shrimp, dumplings and hacked
duck came, and went, in a hurry. Smokes all around. Talk strayed to
the differences between Marlboro Lights in Britain and the United
States. And football _ British, that is.
</P>
<P>
   En route to Ace Bar, an East Village dive with an emphasis on
bar games, Soutar explained Maxim's appeal. ``Guys want one thing
at the end of the day, and it's not what you think,'' he said.
``Guys want to be the funniest guy in the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   At Ace Bar, more beers were downed as the clock snuck past 1
a.m. By then, the boys had guiltlessly reverted to British pub
antics. A few rounds of arrows and then a wager: three darts to hit
one bull's-eye.
</P>
<P>
   If Soutar hit it, Blanchard would declare his love to a
stranger. If Soutar lost, he would declare his love to Blanchard,
in a loud voice to the entire bar.
</P>
<P>
   Soutar stared down the dartboard, threw _ and hit. Bull's-eye.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, as Blanchard fulfilled his end of the bet _ to
the confused stranger _ Soutar stood giggling heartily at the bar
and toasting his friend. ``Right now,'' he said, ``he is the
funniest man here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
