<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-LUXURY-PILLOWS-$ADV15     08-13 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUXURY-PILLOWS-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE $2,300 PILLOW AND THE MASS-MARKETING OF LUXURY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PENELOPE GREENE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a triumph of specialization, the Company Store has
emitted a spinoff catalog, the new 31-page Pillow Source Book. It
is mostly about bed pillows, and it is absolutely riveting,
particularly when read in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Are you a feather-core or double-down kind of person? Silk or
buckwheat? Cotton or wool fill? (Hint: the silk one might prevent
wrinkles, according to the catalog.)
</P>
<P>
   Have you considered pillow densities _ firm, medium and soft?
What about quilted covers or gusseted edges? Are you a back or a
side sleeper? Do you want extras like a knee wedge or a body
pillow? Isn't life grand! Perhaps you are one of the lucky ones, a
new dot-com millionaire, and you're wondering what to spend your
overnight fortune on. Try the Legends eiderdown pillow: $2,300 for
a king-size model.
</P>
<P>
   Try two!
</P>
<P>
   The Company Store is proudly hawking its eiderdown pillow as a
limited-edition ``masterpiece,'' the ``world's most expensive
pillow.'' It's an irresistible come-on and an increasingly familiar
one, the lure of ultimate luxury just a phone call away.
</P>
<P>
   Newly minted high rollers used to study magazines like The Robb
Report for clues on how to spend their wealth, and then they had to
run a gantlet of snooty salesfolk on Rodeo Drive or Worth Avenue or
Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   But now luxury is being mass-marketed. You can buy
cashmere-upholstered mattresses from Dial A Mattress, 16th-century
fountains on the Internet from Millionaire.com or crystal-studded
Wonderbras from Victoria's Secret. And a $2,300 pillow from my
favorite heretofore mid-price catalog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait, are you sure that's not a typo?'' said Dominique
Browning, the editor of House &AMP; Garden, when I told her about the
$2,300 pillow. I assured her it wasn't, and she said: ``Oh, my God,
I guess it's a labor thing, handpicked down or something. Clearly
the pillow is a luxury item, but at a certain point, I guess money
is just so meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Browning has been thinking a lot about luxury, which she
defines as what happens when time burnishes a beloved object. The
September issue of her magazine is devoted to the subject. So are
two new books, ``Luxury Fever: Why Money Fails to Satisfy in an Age
of Excess'' by Robert H. Frank (Free Press), and ``Lead Us Into
Temptation: The Triumph of American Materialism'' by James B.
Twitchell (Columbia University Press).
</P>
<P>
   Frank and Twitchell duke it out over that old chestnut, Can
money buy happiness? Their conclusions: Absolutely, Twitchell says.
Heck no, Frank says.
</P>
<P>
   All this chatter is because two years after Alan Greenspan
wagged his finger and warned stock market investors against
``irrational exuberance,'' Americans are spending more wildly and
exuberantly than ever, in every (italics)market.(end italics) What
fun!
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more. Spending is not just fun, ``it's
redemptive,'' Twitchell said in an interview. ``There is healing in
what all logic says is a totally ridiculous purchase.'' He
explained his theory that expensive purchases are a form of
therapeutic indulgence, in the medieval sense of the word:
indulgences were sold by the Roman Catholic Church ``to relieve the
sinner of part or all of a sin,'' Twitchell explained, adding,
``The price moved according to the naughtiness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the pillow is, I think,'' he continued. ``A
private compact with the self for indulgence. That it is over the
top is part of the allure. Not just `I'm worth it,' but `I deserve
it' and `They owe me big-time.'''
</P>
<P>
   With thoughts like these, I removed an eiderdown pillow from its
plastic wrapping, wondering why it didn't have a more impressive
package, like the felt bags you get with expensive shoes. The
Company Store had sent it to me as a loaner, strictly in the
interest of a scientific inquiry, mind you.
</P>
<P>
   The pillow's 435-thread-count silk cover was indeed lovely,
oyster-colored like the cover of an old down quilt. I gave the
thing a tentative poke. It squished in the normal manner and
recovered nicely. I don't know what I was expecting _ an aria,
maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has beautiful resilience,'' said David Pipkorn, the vice
president for manufacturing at the Company Store. He also told me
that eiderdown is extremely rare. Eider ducks are a protected
species, and their down is collected by hand from nests in Iceland
so as not to harm the ducks, Pipkorn said.
</P>
<P>
   The Company Store says that its Legends is the ``pillow of a
lifetime, and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Wondering how many other cheeks had lain on my pillow's smooth
surface, and worrying about a catastrophic and bizarre mishap
before I had to return it _ like an exploding coffee pot in the
kitchen that would seep, a la ``The Haunting,'' upstairs, I shoved
the pillow into two pillowcases. I took it nervously to bed,
feeling rather like a Russian mail-order bride.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was just a pillow. Nothing remarkable happened when I
laid my head down. In fact, it felt soft and squishy, which is not
my style at all in a pillow. I could not get to sleep and gave it
the heave-ho before even one night was through.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps I would have done better with a choice from the pillow
menu guests receive at L'Ermitage, a new luxury business hotel in
Beverly Hills that offers latex temperature-sensitive pillows,
air-pump-able pillows and anatomically designed Tempur-Pedic
pillows, any of which can be purchased right at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guests told us they wanted versatility in their pillows,''
said Alison Brainard, the director of sales and marketing at
L'Ermitage. All of which suggests that real luxury, for most
people, is a good night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Pipkorn said his pillow was for someone who was looking for the
absolute best in everything, ``not just a sleep experience,'' and
that the Company Store had sold fewer than a dozen eiderdown
pillows since the Pillow Source Book hit mailboxes in June. The
company wouldn't say who bought them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My clients would go for something like it,'' said Juan Pablo
Molyneux, an interior designer in New York who is fond of similar
rarities, opulent materials like travertine and lapis lazuli. But
he wouldn't say which clients.
</P>
<P>
   Molyneux, for one, thinks that no matter who you are, you can
say a lot with an eiderdown pillow. ``You know, like, `What is the
next step in life, now that I have this pillow?'''
</P>
<P>
   Probably a nap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
