<HEADER>
A6534 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-NATO-KLA-$ADV15-HNS &LR;      08-13 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-KLA-$ADV15-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO CHIEF OUTLINES LINKS WITH KLA DURING KOSOVO WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 15)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO war planners and the Kosovo Liberation Army
coordinated during the Yugoslav war by communicating indirectly
through the Albanian government, according to NATO's top commander.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the American four-star Army general who heads
NATO, said the KLA information was used by NATO officers to help
plot bombing attacks on military targets.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's comments confirm the widely held perception that while
NATO never had its own ground troops in Kosovo during the war, KLA
ground forces were effectively acting as NATO surrogates.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA, which sought Kosovo's independence from Belgrade, was
comprised of ethnic Albanians who lived in Kosovo, a province of
Yugoslavia. The KLA was a demoralized force of about 3,000 troops
in March but grew to about 17,000 troops by June, according to U.S.
figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received information from the Albanians and the Albanian
military about what was happening across the border in Kosovo. I
assume that came from the KLA,'' Clark said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any information we got from any source, we used,'' he said,
adding that KLA targeting intelligence had to go through the same
rigorous ``cross checks'' that other information about proposed
targets went through.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he set out four rules _ what he calls ``measures of
merit'' _ that guided NATO's target selection.
</P>
<P>
   First, NATO targeting specialists had to determine whether
attacking a target was too dangerous for NATO jets.
</P>
<P>
   Second, NATO had to decide whether destroying the target would
sufficiently damage Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   Third, NATO had to take steps to assure that damage to civilians
was minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth, Clark wanted to assure that attacking the target would
not fray cohesion among the 19 NATO member nations.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said KLA officials didn't consult directly with allied
commanders during the war, which started March 24 when NATO bombed
Yugoslavia to force Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to end
his ethnic cleansing campaign against the Kosovo's Albanian
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any direct communication with them, to the best
of my knowledge,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials are usually wary of any suggestions that the
alliance and the KLA worked closely during the 78-day bombing
campaign because NATO doesn't want to be perceived as having chosen
sides in a civil war. The alliance's official position is that it
doesn't support Kosovo's independence from Belgrade, as the KLA has
sought.
</P>
<P>
   Although there may not have been direct links between NATO and
the KLA, the alliance's operations directly benefited the KLA as it
waged a ground war against Yugoslav forces, while the KLA's ground
war buttressed the NATO air campaign and helped bring the conflict
to a close.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the punishing allied air campaign in March and
April against Yugoslav troops and facilities gave the KLA, battered
by a superior foe, time to regroup and rearm.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces had been attacking into Albania in pursuit of
KLA rebels but after NATO moved 5,000 U.S. troops armed with Apache
helicopters, tanks and artillery into Albania, Albania felt secure
in defending its border against Yugoslav incursions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That in turn enabled the KLA to mass and go on the offensive
at the end of May,'' said a senior alliance official, who asked to
remain anonymous. ``It completely changed the geo-strategic mindset
by putting those U.S. troops on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of May saw stepped up air attacks by NATO and a
resurgent KLA on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KLA was getting stronger with each passing day in May,''
Clark said. As NATO accelerated attacks against Yugoslav forces,
the KLA mounted an aggressive offensive.
</P>
<P>
   In these final weeks of the war, the KLA fought Yugoslav forces
to secure high ground in western Kosovo, while NATO functioned as
the de facto air force for the rebels. The relationship was in full
bloom by June when U.S. B-52 bombers attacked Yugoslav forces that
were mounting a counter-attack against the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Clark also said:
</P>
<P>
   _ The final tally of Yugoslav tanks, artillery pieces and
personnel carriers destroyed by NATO might not be as high as
anticipated. He said NATO is now completing the count.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll find that we didn't hit everything we said. But
the short answer is that we hit enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Preventing ethnic Albanians from killing ethnic Serbs in
Kosovo is one of Clark's top priorities. ``No one should be
surprised that it's not possible to prevent all of these
incidents,'' he said. The rapid development of an indigenous police
force is essential, he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Milosevic ``has been cautioned in numerous ways and numerous
times to keep his hands off Montenegro,'' the pro-West Yugoslav
province that has angered Belgrade by pushing for greater
independence.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the months leading up to NATO's war in Kosovo, Clark dusted
off a paper on how to mount contingency operations that he has
written in 1975 as a young captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, I used that paper. I learned what I studied
and it was what I applied to fight this war,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
