<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Aug. 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Through Friday, a mere 0.83 inches of rain has fallen this
summer at Central Park in New York City. During the course of this
weekend, up to an inch or more of rain could fall in New York and
most of the Northeast as a slow-moving low pressure system draws
moist air inland from the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The day will dawn partly sunny with spotty showers from the
Appalachians to the Northeast and Middle Atlantic seaboards. As the
sun heats the sultry air over the region, ascending currents of
humid air will yield numerous thunderstorms. A few of these storms
may cause local flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, a cooler, steadier rain will dampen areas from
western Pennsylvania to central New York on Saturday morning.
Meanwhile, residual moisture in the lowest few thousand feet of the
atmosphere will cause low clouds to linger across the eastern Great
Lakes and Ohio Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A broken zone of thunderstorms will erupt ahead of a cold front
pushing southward toward the Gulf Coast and Carolinas on Saturday.
Farther south, Florida will have partial sunshine, though spotty
afternoon thunderstorms will form in the very humid air. Elsewhere
in the South, extreme heat will persist across Texas and Louisiana
where afternoon readings once again exceed 100 degrees in many
places.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and scattered showers will accompany a jet stream
disturbance crossing the Northwest on Saturday where temperatures
remain rather cool. Meanwhile, mainly sunny skies will embrace
California, though patchy morning clouds will be found near the
coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THINGS IN THE SKY
</P>
<P>
   Major meteor showers like Perseids that streak across the sky
around this time each year prompt calls to meteorologists seeking
explanations of the event. However, despite the misleading name,
meteorologists have no special expertise concerning the meteors
that illuminate the night sky. Astronomers are the scientists who
can lay claim to detailed knowledge of meteor showers. In
antiquity, when science was in its infancy, the fields of
meteorology and astronomy were more closely allied. Indeed, the
word meteorology has Greek roots and means the study of ``things in
the air.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
