<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6547 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HAMPTONS-HITCHHIKERS-     08-13 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMPTONS-HITCHHIKERS-2TAKES-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS A RULE OF THUMB, THEY HITCH IN THE HAMPTONS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEVE GARBARINO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She didn't seem dangerous, with her tumbleweed of
bottle-blond hair and brown sarong. She had an overstuffed plastic
beach tote slung around one arm, the other arm extended out over
the road, its thumb signaling the need for a ride.
</P>
<P>
   I had nowhere particular to go. It was a sleepy Monday, and most
of my friends were toiling away in Manhattan. So I picked her up.
</P>
<P>
   Her name was Tanya, and she had the handsome hardness of Angie
Dickinson, roughly 40, a bridge worker's tan and a Tareyton 100
smoker's rasp. From somewhere on Long Island, not the ``phony''
Hamptons, as she referred to them, Tanya was heading for the free
Paul Simon concert at the Ranch field grounds in Montauk, hoping to
sell her attache case full of mood rings.
</P>
<P>
   I was considering an afternoon drink at Cyril's Fish House along
Montauk Highway. That would put her close enough to her
destination.
</P>
<P>
   I'd thumbed it myself in my teens, almost weekly during summers
at Rehoboth Beach, Del. (where I once was issued a $15 ticket for
doing so). In the last few years, I've picked up nearly a dozen
hitchhikers _ young and old, men and women, and once even a member
of the Maidstone Club in green golf pants. But only, and
exclusively, in the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   Summer Hamptonites, liberated from their Manhattan cellblocks
and intoxicated by the small-town charm and impression of safety
that most resort towns exude, relax their guards. They leave alarm
systems off and the front-door key under the potted reindeer
topiary.
</P>
<P>
   And amid some of the country's most conspicuous affluence, they
sometimes hitchhike or pick up those who do.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd. Spot the rare hitchhiker on an Interstate highway
anywhere else and a shiver goes down your back, like spotting a
chain gang chopping shoulder brush in the Deep South. See someone
hitching in the Hamptons, and well, it's almost quaint.
</P>
<P>
   Which may be an illusion. ``It's an extremely dangerous thing to
do, because you don't know who's picking you up,'' said Glen
Stonemetz, Chief of Police for East Hampton Village. ``Not to
mention the fact that with the kind of drivers we have around here,
I wouldn't stand on the edge of the highway. I'd walk before I'd
hitchhike.''
</P>
<P>
   Call me reckless, but on a Friday this month I set out to
explore the state of Hamptons hitchhiking for myself. I wore beachy
casual wear, intending to look like a local: gray bell-bottom
sweatpants, a faded University of Madrid T-shirt and black
flip-flops. Here is the diary of my hitchhiker's odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   12:10 I park my car at Turtle Crossing in East Hampton, a
favorite local barbecue pit, and go inside for a fortifying glass
of water.
</P>
<P>
   12:14 I cross Montauk Highway, stand under the shade of blowing
trees and stretch my right arm out as if it were a divining rod
channeling a ride. At first it feels liberating, rebellious. Then
it feels just plain stupid. The temperature is in the high 70s,
with a light zephyr blowing: a perfect hitchhiking day.
</P>
<P>
   12:17 My first ride, and in only five minutes! Through the open
passenger window of a green Saab 900 with Pennsylvania plates, I
spy the man driving: a bit hefty, salt-and-pepper beard, roughly
50. From the looks of him, I'd say he was married with children and
was heading in his work clothes to do some touch-up on his teak
sailboat. I get in.
</P>
<P>
   12:19 ``I'm not going very far,'' the driver says. ``It's
somewhere along here. I'm buying this table that I'm going to
paint.'' We drive about a half mile. Pulling into the parking lot
of the Animal Rescue Fund Thrift Shop, next to the Spielberg
Nursery and Garden Shop, the driver apologizes, ``Sorry it was such
a short ride.'' I thank him and get out.
</P>
<P>
   12:24 Back on the blacktop, it's hotter, and there's more
traffic. The midweek pickup trucks and older cars driven by
year-round Hampton residents are giving way to the brand-new
Lincoln Navigators, Cadillacs and Mercedes-Benzes of weekend
people. I begin to play Count the Mercedeses. Seven so far.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   12:26 The rotating lawn sprinkler at Spielberg Nursery sprays me
in the face. Setting my backpack down, I spot a greenback floating
along the pavement. It's a $50 bill. Pocketing it, I continue my
walk east, confidence at a new high.
</P>
<P>
   12:27 Joggers and bicyclists seem repelled by me. I offer a
cheery ``Hey!'' to all. No one responds.
</P>
<P>
   12:30 Approaching town, I pass the sign reading ``Historic
Amagansett, Settled 1680.'' My powder-blue Nokia cell phone beeps
from my backpack. I talk to a friend, holding the phone with one
hand, thumbing with the other. Jeering at the only-in-the-Hamptons
sight of a hitchhiker talking on a cell phone, a BMW sedan with
four blond young people honks at me.
</P>
<P>
   12:35 Sixteen Mercedes-Benzes.
</P>
<P>
   12:40 Outside the Amagansett General Store, a couple in their
30s are packing beach gear and a cooler into a car trunk. The
woman, in a pink jumper, calls, ``How far you going?'' I tell her.
``Well, we're just going to the beach.'' I thank her all the same,
and move on.
</P>
<P>
   12:42 Walking between the Hampton Chutney Company and Peace and
Carrots, I spot wild raspberries growing on the roadside. They're
plump and ripe. I fall upon them.
</P>
<P>
   12:45 A patrol car is approaching. I keep my thumb raised.
Without incident, it cruises slowly by.
</P>
<P>
   12:48 I Lose count of the Mercedes-Benzes at 32 or so and start
counting drivers on cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   12:50 From the back of a passing flatbed, three children with
crew cuts, about 8 years old, shout obscenities at me in unison.
</P>
<P>
   1:02 Finally, outside Amagansett, a ride. The man behind the
wheel looks normal: sandy hair with a boyish Kennedy forelock,
early 40s, dressed in paint-spattered khaki shorts. I hop into his
Chevrolet sport utility vehicle. A furniture painter? I wonder,
until he starts talking about how cars are ``microenvironments.''
I'm in luck. He's going all the way to Montauk. I tell him I'm
heading to Cyril's, the roadside reggae shack.
</P>
<P>
   1:04 ``So, do you work at Cyril's?'' he asks. I break my cover
and tell him I'm writing about hitchhiking in the Hamptons. His
name is Bob Ficalora, he's 42 and has two children. He retired from
a desk job at IBM a few years ago, and now is an owner of Breakers,
a Montauk hotel. He explains his criteria for picking up
hitchhikers. ``I do a quick visual of them,'' he says. ``If they
look ratty or down and out, I don't mind. I pick up hitchhikers all
the time, girls, guys, locals, tourists. But if they look edgy, I
won't stop.'' He pauses. ``A working man, I'll pick up a working
man any day,'' he says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   1:20 Ficalora drops me at Cyril's, where I talk to the owner,
Cyril Fitzsimmons, an Irishman in a straw cowboy hat and sarong. He
says that his mostly Irish staff hitchhikes all the time. ``The
girls get picked up by the summer guys, who later come back to ask
them out on dates.''
</P>
<P>
   1:45 I am back on the asphalt, returning toward East Hampton,
the sun beating on me. There's no cover. Less traffic this way,
too.
</P>
<P>
   1:50 A Mazda RX-7 pulls over to the roadside. It's a guy with
short dark hair, in khaki shorts, about 35. He looks like the actor
Guy Pearce. Speaking with an Irish accent, he tells me he is Mark
Corr, a bartender at McKendry's in Amagansett, just a short walk
from Turtle Crossing. He agrees to take me all the way back to my
car. ``I've hitchhiked all over Europe,'' he says. ``And here, too.
You get a lift in the Hamptons quicker than it would take to take
the bus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
