<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6549 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-HONEST-COPS-$ADV15-HN     08-13 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONEST-COPS-$ADV15-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MEXICO CITY, THE FAIRER SEX IS ARMED WITH TRAFFIC TICKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 15)   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ On a busy intersection in this hurried capital of
impatient, fast drivers, women are stopping traffic.
</P>
<P>
   They also are taking names and writing tickets.
</P>
<P>
   They are the only ones doing so.
</P>
<P>
   In a drastic reversal of authority roles in this male-dominated
culture, Mexico City officials _ at a loss over what to do about
rampant, almost-institutionalized police corruption _ have banned
male police officers from giving out traffic tickets.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, the fairer sex is now also the more honest sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is proven scientifically and psychologically that women are
less likely to commit acts of corruption,'' said Raul Tovar, a
spokesman for the Mexico City Police Department. ``This is a
historic moment for our citizens, for all those who are committed
to the rescue of our city.''
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, Police Chief Alejandro Gertz replaced 1,500
male traffic cops with 120 women officers who were dispatched to 30
strategic points in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The men's ticket pads were taken away and given to the women,
relegating the men to directing the perennially jammed traffic of
this metropolitan capital of 20 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, the new measure has not been welcomed by all, both
male officers, and some drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are some of them displeased? Because it was a source of
extortion for them,'' Tovar said of some male officers. ``But this
has been well received by the citizenry. The common good is
justified.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is called ``mordida,'' as in bite, but better known
as a bribe.
</P>
<P>
   For a motorist, it is much cheaper and faster to pay mordida,
the equivalent of $5 or $10, than to pay traffic fines that start
at $25. For a police officer, who earns about $200 a month, it is
an additional source of income.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers, however, are often pulled over just to dispense cash
like roving teller machines. The city says it loses millions of
dollars that could otherwise go to improving services.
</P>
<P>
   At a horn-blaring thoroughfare where traffic comes from eight
sides, Solis Gonzalez M. de Jesus is all business in her crisp
brown police uniform. At a red light, she won't even let motorists
inch into the pedestrian lane, stepping onto the street with a
stern look on her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman is always more decided and more honest,'' said
Gonzalez, 24, a thick pad of tickets under her arm. ``My job is to
not accept extortions because it is a crime. That is why we get
paid. But there are many people who get distressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, many male officers complained the women give out
fewer tickets, and they said the entire male police force is
getting a bad rap because of the actions of a few bad apples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there is everything in the department,'' said
Luis Estrada Manny, one of the officers who can no longer write
tickets. ``We are paying for some of our colleagues who don't do
everything on the up and up.''
</P>
<P>
   But crime specialists say corruption is endemic in the police
force. In Mexico, traffic cops are a different entity from the
regular police force, and there are other branches as well _ city,
municipal, state, judicial and rural.
</P>
<P>
   ``The apple is rotten to the core,'' said Rafael Ruiz Harrell, a
criminologist and university professor who also writes a column on
crime for the daily Reforma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are just as corruptible as men but to a lower degree.
They are not on the take as much as men,'' added Ruiz. ``And male
drivers have a more difficulty offering a bribe to a woman. I think
this has been an excellent measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Tovar said that since the new rules were put in force two weeks
ago, corruption has been reduced 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a better level of supervision and control,'' Tovar
said. ``Women have confidence, moral authority and a better work
habits. They show up for work, and they show up on time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The women are not alone giving out tickets. A virtual convoy of
reinforcements is on standby nearby, including a male police
supervisor, a city tow truck and several ``demoted'' male traffic
officers.
</P>
<P>
   In all, each female is bolstered by about 15 officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This operation is well controlled to see there are no acts of
corruption,'' said Rafael Torres, supervising the traffic operation
at a downtown corner. ``I feel good supporting the women. Some
drivers don't have good manners and are very aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Other male officers grumbled that they don't have a choice but
to accept the new rules and follow orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were fired or quit our jobs, we would not be able to get
another one,'' said one officer, who asked his name not be used for
fear or reprisal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encounter prejudice and stigma everywhere. A prospective
employer says: `Oh, police. You are all corrupt. Goodbye.' It
doesn't matter what your experience and education are. Nobody wants
you,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   Two nearby officers nodded in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Gertz, the police chief, is contemplating another radical change
to ensure tickets are paid: removing a vehicle's license plates
until the penalty is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The police department said that out of 1.6 million tickets given
out last year, only 10 percent were paid, a yearly loss estimated
at $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gertz, 60, was until recently the dean of the University of the
Americas and president of a non-government advisory council on
public security.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a citizen like anybody else. He doesn't belong to any
political party,'' Tovar said. ``He is an intellectual who was
worried about his community.''
</P>
<P>
   He joined the administration of Mexico City Mayor Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas, the first opposition leader of the capital, a year ago as
police chief.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas is running for president in 2000, the year his mayoral
term is up, and with every changing administration, new rules and
new people are put in place.
</P>
<P>
   So there is uncertainty whether the female-only policy will
survive in the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe by then we can generate a new consciousness in
society,'' Tovar said. ``A new culture committed together to
improve our city and our image.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
