u w BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     08-13 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS FIND PORK IN OCEAN WITH HUGE WATER BILL; NO JUSTICE; GONE
FISHING; HATE CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) (yn) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Before they cast off for their August recess,
lawmakers managed to land a whopper: a $4.3 billion bill that pays
for a host of water projects across the country.
</P>
<P>
   While the GOP tax-break legislation grabbed most of the
headlines as Congress rushed to adjourn, the House and Senate also
finished work on the Water Resources Development Act of 1999. That
bill, which was strongly supported by coastal communities and
development groups, authorizes a range of projects dealing with
beach nourishment, shore protection and navigation improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Sen. Connie Mack, a Republican, said the bill would help
to ensure that America's waterways, beaches and ``other national
treasures are protected, safe and navigable.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bill has drawn the ire of at least one environmental
group, which contends it encourages too much development along the
nation's coasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coast does just fine without us,'' said Steve Ellis,
coastal program coordinator for the Coast Alliance in Washington.
Ellis said the bill is simply a grab-bag of goodies for communities
along lakes, beaches and rivers. He said it's unfair to ask
taxpayers to foot the bill for improvement projects that benefit a
relatively small population.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anybody who would contest that it's a
big pork-barrel bill,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill does, however, reduce the federal share of one aspect
of beach nourishment programs. Currently, Uncle Sam picks up 65
percent of the estimated 50-year maintenance costs of such
programs. The bill reduces that share to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups successfully fought another proposed
provision in the bill that would have increased the federal subsidy
for harbor deepening projects.
</P>
<P>
   NO JUSTICE?
</P>
<P>
   Congress may be in recess, but that doesn't mean partisan
squabbling has to take a break.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the White House and the Senate have been trading pot
shots lately over the number of vacancies on the federal bench.
President Clinton says the Republican-controlled Senate has been
slow to act on his nominees and is playing politics because of
disputes over ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say they're acting responsibly, but the president
has been slow to name some nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Judiciary Committee has been pursuing its work in a
balanced and thorough manner,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican
who chairs that panel, said in a letter to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups are getting in on the act. People for the American
Way, a liberal-minded civil liberties group, is pressing the
committee to act quicker, noting that 21 vacancies have been
declared emergencies because they have remain unfilled for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans cannot get their day in court,'' complained Carole
Shields, president of that group.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there are 67 vacancies on the federal bench; 50
nominations are pending.
</P>
<P>
   GONE FISHING
</P>
<P>
   As the representative for a tobacco-heavy district, Rep. Howard
Coble from North Carolina has long been a champion of that
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it seems, boat designers may also have reason to sing his
praises.
</P>
<P>
   As the chairman of a House subcommittee that deals with
copyrights, Coble, a Republican, last year sponsored a bill to
protect the intellectual property of vessel hull designers. In a
recent ceremony at the Library of Congress, the hull design of a
bass fishing boat was registered with the federal government's
copyright office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I first became aware of the problem of knock-off hull designs
through Hatteras Yachts which used to have a large facility in our
congressional district,'' said Coble, who suggested the knock-off
designs may not be as safe.
</P>
<P>
   HATE CRIMES
</P>
<P>
   Southern conservatives may soon find themselves in the middle of
an emerging debate: whether to expand federal hate-crimes laws.
</P>
<P>
   The recent shootings at a Jewish community center in Los Angeles
are focusing new attention on a bill that would do just that.
</P>
<P>
   While it's been endorsed by the White House, the Hate Crimes
Prevention Act is finding resistance from some Republicans who are
uneasy with a measure that would broaden hate-crimes laws to
include gender, disabilities and sexual orientation. The law
currently covers crimes committed on the basis of race, color,
religion or national origin.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say such legislation promotes unequal justice by
categorizing victims according to their background.
</P>
<P>
   The likely flash point for the debate will be the House
Judiciary Committee, which has already held one hearing on the
bill. Committee members include Republicans Charles Canady and Bill
McCollum of Florida, Howard Coble of North Carolina, Spencer Bachus
of Alabama, and Lindsey Graham of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
