<SLUG> BC-NASA-CHANDRA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANDRA MANEUVER PAVES WAY FOR OBSERVATIONS, NASA SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The large door that admits radiance to NASA's recently launched
$1.55 billion Chandra X-ray telescope has opened, paving the way
for the first science observations later this month, the space
agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-foot long telescope was launched late last month by the
crew of the shuttle Columbia, whose skipper, Eileen Collins, became
the first woman spacecraft commander. The observatory was lofted
into space with the door closed, and the opening procedure carried
out Thursday was among the most critical of the post-launching
activities.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-foot diameter door was designed to remain open
throughout the five-year mission of the telescope. Chandra is
circling the Earth once every 63.5 hours in an elliptical orbit
with high and low points of 86,487 miles and 5,999 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Though the new X-ray telescope is in the midst of a 60-day
orbital checkout period, astronomers tentatively plan to make and
publicly discuss their first observations in late August.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a ways to go, but we couldn't be happier with
the way this mission has gone so far,'' said Fred Wojtalik, NASA's
Chandra program manager.
</P>
<P>
   Chandra was designed to study the highest energy phenomena in
the universe, including black holes, stellar explosions and
galactic collisions. Like the Hubble Space Telescope and the
Compton Gamma Ray Observatory, Chandra will help astronomers refine
their theories on the age and evolution of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
