<HEADER>
A6574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DIGITAL-DISPUTE-NYT &LR;      08-13 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE INTERNET, BALANCING THE FREE FLOW OF DATA AND PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a day when you get on the Web, and every time you check
a stock price, read an article or get a phone number, some hidden
cookie charges a fee to your credit card. Then imagine that you've
been running a nice business compiling a directory of services in
your area when suddenly your list appears on the Web, free.
</P>
<P>
   In more extreme terms, if the sum total of human knowledge
becomes instantly and universally accessible on the World Wide Web,
will every fact become private property, to be leased or sold? Or
will information become so cheap as to lose any value, eliminating
incentives for using it or adding to it?
</P>
<P>
   Doomsday scenarios, to be sure. But with the Web growing at a
rate that defies human and institutional experience, it is not
surprising that such fears have spread, and that both consumers and
purveyors of facts _ which includes almost everyone, really _ have
squared off over how and how much to regulate the proliferation of
raw and packaged knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   One such battle is currently being fought over two pending bills
in Congress. One is the Collection of Information Antipiracy Act,
introduced by Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C. The other is the Consumer
and Investors Access to Information Act, presented by Rep. Thomas
Bliley, R-Va. As the names imply, the bills approach the protection
of databases from fundamentally opposing sides. The antipiracy act
concentrates on specifying what cannot be done with a database or
the data in it, while the access bill emphasizes the argument that
facts themselves cannot be copyrighted.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, supporters of the bills have divided into
those who largely use data and those who largely sell it. Thus
research libraries, scientists, online brokerages and other
services that depend on digesting data are fervently lobbying for
the Bliley bill, while real estate agents, for example, are
lobbying for the Coble bill to protect their listings.
</P>
<P>
   There is no dispute that databases need protection in a medium
that can deliver the entire body of Western law to a home computer
in less time than it took for a medieval scribe to make one copy of
the Magna Carta. The problem is that existing means for protecting
intellectual property _ copyrights, trademarks, conventions,
professional ethics _ simply wilt before the sheer expanse of
information available on the Web and the associated potential for
huge profits, or huge losses.
</P>
<P>
   The very notions of ``intellectual property,'' ``information''
or ``database'' have taken on qualitatively new meanings when
translated into cyberspeak as ``content,'' just as the sins of
stealing, plagiarizing or extorting are transformed on the Internet
into ``content piracy'' or ``cybersquatting.'' If in the past
purveyors of data could expect to make some money simply by
packaging and delivering information _ whether by ticker tape,
books or CD-ROMs _ the Web has transferred value directly to
ownership of the data.
</P>
<P>
   One frequently cited example was the attempt by The New York
Times to prevent Amazon.com, the online booksellers, from posting
the Times best-seller list on its Web site. Though the list is
commonly posted in bookstores, The Times had an online partnership
with barnesandnoble.com, Amazon's chief competitor, and on the Web
the list gained a marketing force that it never had in the shops.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon countered by suing The Times. The case was settled on
Monday with an agreement that Amazon.com would continue to list the
best sellers only in alphabetical order and to publish the list
only when it became available to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   To John Barton, a professor of law at Stanford University, the
rush to claim ownership over databases is tantamount to a modern
land grab, with dangers for endeavors that traditionally build on
the work of others, like scientific research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say I'm sympathetic to the plight of a movie
producer who sees the product distributed digitally without any
payment,'' said Barton. ``But we are reaching the point where we're
creating serious complications for the kind of data flow you need
for democracy and scientific inquiry to work. People are
commercializing everything and selling it. I'm worried that we are
going to patent facts.''
</P>
<P>
   The proponents of stronger intellectual property rights have
their own worries. Testifying before the House Judiciary Committee,
Terry McDermott, the chief executive officer of the National
Association of Realtors, argued that cyberpirates were stealing
real estate multiple listings and threatening the very basis of his
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Internet has become the battleground, the fears of
the realtors and others reach back to a Supreme Court decision in
1991 that had nothing to do with the Web. In Feist vs. Rural
Telephone, the court ruled that the publisher of a regional
telephone directory had the right to copy numbers from a local
directory because he was in effect adding value to an existing body
of fact. The decision challenged a venerable doctrine of copyright
law, which held that the ``sweat of the brow'' expended in
compiling a list, even if the information was in itself openly
available, entitled it to protection.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what's really at stake, argues Jonathan Band, a lawyer who
represents the Online Banking Association, is money. He said there
are few cases in which companies have suffered seriously from
pirates or in which scientific research has been stymied. The
bottom line is that one of the oldest commodities on the market,
information, is suddenly in huge demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the piracy, or the fear that we'll lose the incentive
to invest in data,'' he said. ``It's that those who have
information can make a lot more money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
