<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6586 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-MAIDS-EMPLOY-2TAKES-$     08-13 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAIDS-EMPLOY-2TAKES-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO HARD TO FIND: GOOD EMPLOYERS THESE DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 15)  
 (bl)  
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a recent dinner party in Southampton, in a big
white house with a picket fence, the help couldn't keep up with the
orders thrown at them. The food was exquisite, lobster salad
followed by lamb; the house was picture perfect, decorated only a
year before. But the hostess, in a beige silk Bill Blass suit and
simple Harry Winston diamond earrings, had two faces. To her
high-powered guests _ Wall Street men and media moguls, and women
in linen and soft cotton _ she showed a radiant smile. ``It's so
nice to see you,'' she said to one dark-haired man as he arrived.
``Let's get Lee Ann to get you a drink.''
</P>
<P>
   But to the young serving woman in a black skirt and white apron,
she barked, ``Hurry it up.'' Minutes later, when the server was
drawn into conversation by a guest, the hostess bee-lined over and
scolded, ``I said, `Hurry it up.''' Pulling on her arm, she said,
``You're not to talk to the guests.''
</P>
<P>
   At the seated dinner, the hostess loudly upbraided another
server, one of the full-time staff of three, ``There aren't enough
water glasses on this table!'' As the woman retreated wordlessly to
the kitchen, the dozen guests looked away so as not to deepen her
embarrassment and theirs. The hostess, turning to the man on her
right, said, ``She's not very bright.''
</P>
<P>
   As the economic good times roll on and on, never before have so
many been able to employ so many others as servants. But a boom
market in domestic help is coinciding with a boom in boorish and
disrespectful behavior toward domestics, say maids and drivers on
Fifth and Park Avenues, nannies in Central Park, servers at parties
in the Hamptons, household employment agencies and chroniclers of
the social scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad behavior is epidemic,'' said David Patrick Columbia,
the editor in chief of Avenue, the magazine of Upper East Side
life, who circulates widely among the beau monde. ``There's a huge
amount of emotional and verbal abuse going on towards the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia is careful to keep an ear cocked to the servants who
otherwise go unnoticed in the city apartments and country homes of
some of the richest New Yorkers. He calls today's generation of
ladies and gentlemen of the house ``screamers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the hostess get up from dinner because the so-called
right fork isn't there, and they get into the kitchen and start
screaming at the staff,'' he said. ``Mind you, these are people who
didn't know what the right fork was until they married a person who
could afford the right fork.''
</P>
<P>
   On benches around the Central Park Boathouse, Upper East Side
nannies gather daily to trade stories about their employers. A
widely heard complaint is that children imitate the raised voices
and disrespect shown by their parents.
</P>
<P>
   A West Indian woman who works as a live-in nanny five days a
week on the Upper East Side said the family's young teen-age son
kicked her in the shins when she wouldn't make sandwiches for him
and his friends after school. She complained to the parents, but
they did nothing to the boy. ``His parents made believe they cared,
but they didn't,'' the woman said. ``They didn't punish him.''
</P>
<P>
   Complaints by these workers _ who are almost always women, and
foreign born _ is wide ranging, and includes illegal abuses like
payment below minimum wage for six- and seven-day workweeks,
failure to pay taxes, and sexual harassment. Domestic workers
deprived of their legal rights have been championed in recent years
by a number of groups across the country, including the Workplace
Project in Hempstead, which helps immigrant maids sue employers in
small-claims court for back pay.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond such clear-cut abuses, however, there is a vast category
of mistreatment that is not illegal, but simply boorish _ rude and
demeaning. While it is rarely discussed by the dinner or house
guests at elegant Fifth Avenue apartments or in the Hamptons, it is
perhaps inevitable as more people who did not grow up with domestic
help are able to afford it but remain unclear on where to draw the
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who come into money late in life or quickly, especially
women, don't know how to behave with subordinates and don't respect
them,'' said Nelson W. Aldrich Jr., the author of a 1988 memoir,
``Old Money: The Mythology of America's Upper Class'' (Alfred A.
Knopf), and a member of the extended Rockefeller family.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia agreed, citing employers who think any household chore,
even rinsing a dish, is beneath them. ``They go out of their way to
leave everything,'' he said. ``They let the food get stiff on the
plate. With a lot of these girls it's a measure of success to leave
the plates there overnight. The behavior is nouveau. Trophy wives
are always the worst _ girls who married wealthy men and never had
help before.''
</P>
<P>
   But this rudeness is hardly limited to women, or to those new to
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia noted: ``We live in an age that people in general that
work in stressful jobs in New York seriously lack the ability to
control themselves. People rage a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Scolding in front of guests is one of the most common
complaints. It humiliates the employee, and many employers seem to
think it adds power to their image. In fact, it often embarrasses
their guests.
</P>
<P>
   R. Couri Hay, a society columnist for Hamptons magazine,
recalled a seated dinner for 36 at an estate in Westchester County
when the hostess stopped the entire party because she thought the
table was not being cleared properly. She stood and, in front of
the table, chided her Hispanic maid for not knowing that she should
``serve left, clear right.'' The maid started shaking and dropped a
plate, a flowered antique, which caused the hostess to yell even
louder. The maid burst into tears and left the room. The hostess
apologized to her guests, rang her bell and had another maid come
out to clear.
</P>
<P>
   In their defense, a number of men and women described by guests
as having made such outbursts said that competent household help is
scarce and that good people can demand huge salaries _ up to $2,000
a week _ and are quick to leave for a better offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is this anyone's business how we treat our help?'' said
one hostess in New York and Southampton known for frequently
raising her voice and who spoke only on condition of anonymity
because she pays off the books. ``We pay them, and if they don't
like it, they can work somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Carol Mack, a decorator known for her dinner parties in
Southampton, New York and Palm Beach, Fla. _ but not known for
mistreating staff _ offered an explanation for why some hostesses
are prone to raise voices and dress down employees publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``How often do you go to a party and they serve the lamb, and
the rice and vegetables comes a half an hour after?'' she said.
``The reality is, people don't listen. You think they understood
what you told them, and they go off and do what they want rather
than what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mack employees a cook, housekeeper, laundress and house
manager (for washing the car, changing light bulbs and stocking the
refrigerator). ``You're not dealing with a level of professionalism
that I think once existed,'' she said. ``People don't view domestic
help as a profession. Half of them do it as a summer job.''
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Greenhouse, a co-owner of the Pavillion Agency, which
has placed nannies and other domestics in the homes of wealthy New
Yorkers for 38 years, said the disrespect shown the help is worse
today than ever. Well-paid domestics _ who earn at least $500 after
taxes for a five-day week while living in, or $400 while living out
_ used to remain two to three years with a family. Now, many are
leaving after two months, citing poor treatment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He described, but would not name, a ``very high profile'' couple
who do not allow their help to eat the household food. ``They
insist that their leftovers be thrown in the garbage,'' he said.
``They do not want their help to eat their leftovers. Few people
last more than a few months with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nannies, he added, increasingly find rudeness, and worse, in
children. ``There are lots of incidents of biting and kicking and
verbal abuse,'' Greenhouse said. ``The older the children are, the
more drastic their tempers can be. I'm always hearing stories
involving children, teen-agers robbing money and jewelry from the
nanny, threats of physical violence.''
</P>
<P>
   A live-in nanny in her 30s from Hong Kong said the lady of the
house calls her stupid in front of the children. ``I'm taking care
of their children and I'm not treated like a human,'' she said.
``The children won't listen to their parents. They won't listen to
me. The parents maltreat us, the children follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Coco Myers, a co-author with Susan Carlton of ``The Nanny Book:
The Smart Parent's Guide to Hiring, Firing and Every Sticky
Situation in Between'' (St. Martin's Griffin, 1999), said that in
hundreds of interviews with nannies, the No. 1 complaint was lack
of respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing we found made nannies leave more than
anything else _ not the money, not the hours, but the respect and
the lack of respect,'' she said. ``Employers don't think that they
have a life outside the family they are working for. We found that
once they feel the lack of respect, it's dispiriting. They
disengage.''
</P>
<P>
   Another day, at Carl Schurz Park, next to Gracie Mansion, Mina
Zayas, 29, sat with four friends, all domestics in some of the
wealthiest homes in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zayas said that when she first came to New York from
Paraguay in 1994, speaking no English and without a resident
alien's green card, she was hired as a live-in nanny by Muriel
Brandolini, a decorator who lives in a brownstone in the East 80s
with her banker husband.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brandolini asked Ms. Zayas for her passport. ``She wanted to
make a copy,'' Ms. Zayas said. But her employer held on to it. Ms.
Zayas said she was promised $300 for a five-day week, but when it
came to collect her pay, Ms. Brandolini only gave $200, complaining
that she didn't speak English. ``But she knew that in the
interview,'' Ms. Zayas said. The nanny job turned into housekeeping
as well, totaling seven days a week with no time off for the same
$200.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zayas said that Ms. Brandolini, whose interior designs have
appeared in Elle Decor magazine and whose fashion designs have been
featured in The New York Times and are sold at Barneys New York,
would take her to her Hamptons house on weekends, and she was
expected to work there full-time, too. When she said she wanted to
leave, she said Ms. Brandolini, still in possession of her
passport, would threaten to call immigration authorities. Finally,
Ms. Zayas had a friend intervene and she was able to quit, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brandolini, reached on a sailboat in the Greek islands last
week, said she did not remember Ms. Zayas, though she acknowledged
she has had many household workers in the last six years. Currently
she employs a housekeeper, a weekday nanny and a man who watches
the children on weekends. Two domestics who work for one of Ms.
Brandolini's relatives confirmed that Ms. Zayas had worked for her
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Ms. Zayas' specific charges of sub-minimum pay,
withholding a passport and threatening to call immigration agents,
she said, ``It's completely nonsense.'' She added: ``I take the
passport to make a photocopy, for security. I take their green card
and their Con Edison bill and take a Xerox and give it back. You
never know if these people live where they say they live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, at the end they get bitter,'' she said. ``They've
done something wrong and they ask for a raise. They break 10
dishes, you get mad and they talk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays if someone offers $50 more a week, they run,'' she
continued. ``There's no fidelity. It's rare to find that type of
people in help. They come to America to make money. It's hard to
find good help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
