<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BEAN-BOOMERS-2TAKES-N     08-13 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAN-BOOMERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.L. BEAN UPDATING ITS STYLE TO DRAW BABY BOOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(yn) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEPORT, Maine _ First came the indoor trout pond. Then there
was the barnlike addition devoted to children's clothes and
accessories. Now comes what is perhaps the ultimate sign that L.L.
Bean, the 87-year-old arbiter of what's what in rugged outerwear,
is going after cosseted baby boomers in a big way: the company's
Maine Hunting Shoe, its first product and essential icon, has been
revamped to make it more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The changes in the boot are subtle to the naked eye. What was a
vulcanized, hand-formed rubber sole is now molded in a
machine-driven method that the company says saves money and results
in a lighter, warmer, better-fitting product. ``It may look the
same on the outside,'' declares the literature that accompanies the
new boot, which is still arrestingly utilitarian-looking, ``but
there's an inside story.''
</P>
<P>
   Other recent changes within the privately held company _ based,
as it has always been, here in this tourist mecca of outlet stores
and lobster shacks _ reflect an even bigger effort to recast the
venerable L.L. Bean into a more up-to-date mold.
</P>
<P>
   The company has added a new brand aimed at working women,
expanded its home-furnishings department and ``turned up the
volume'' on its children's line, as one executive put it. Even more
startling, Bean plans to develop a bigger retail presence _ once
unthinkable in a company that made its name in mail-order _ by
opening three to five full-scale stores along the Eastern Seaboard.
The first is scheduled to appear by next summer in a sprawling
suburban mall at Tysons Corner, Va., outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   All this is meant to counter plateauing sales at L.L. Bean,
which does not publish a financial statement but says it sold just
over $1 billion worth of gloves, parkas, kayaks, coffee tables,
boot-shaped chocolates, rifles, fly rods, lamps, duffle bags,
snowboards, men's dress shirts, dog beds, khakis, blazers, skirts,
pillow shams, knapsacks and bathing suits last year.
</P>
<P>
   The company witnessed enormous growth until recently. In 1967,
it had just under $5 million in sales. Lately, however, the
commercial environment has grown more complicated, with shifting
consumer tastes and the explosion of electronic commerce _ two
areas where Bean has been slow to adapt.
</P>
<P>
   Now the goal, says Leon A. Gorman, who has been Bean's president
for the last 32 years, is to increase sales at a double-digit rate
every year, to about $1.4 billion by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Gorman outlined the challenges facing the company in a lengthy
memo last year. Among his points was that the company's traditional
attitude toward profits _ that they would emerge naturally if
customers were treated well and stakeholders were well served _ had
to go. ``This attitude was naive, perhaps, on our part, although it
served us well for many years,'' Gorman told his staff. ``In
today's environment, however, we are going to have to focus much
more intently on profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   Some see risks, however, in moving further into
bricks-and-mortar retailing. ``It's going to be intriguing to
watch, because often you find the folks who are successful with
catalogs are not successful with stores, and vice versa,'' said
Kenneth M. Gassmann, a retail analyst with Davenport &AMP; Co. in
Richmond. ``J. Peterman? We all know what happened there.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Peterman, whose catalogs were famously wordy and eccentric,
declared bankruptcy earlier this year after a high-speed expansion
into retail stores that didn't do well.
</P>
<P>
   But Bean executives, pointing to successful examples of
outdoor-oriented companies like Patagonia, a unit of Lost Arrow,
and REI that have expanded beyond mail order into retailing around
the country, insist that they have examined the issues carefully
and expect the concept of additional stores to work. While the
company has a handful of factory outlets in four states, and
through a partnership has a dozen or so boutiques in Japan, it says
its new, large stores will bring in many new customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 1.5 million Bean customers within five miles of
Tysons Corners,'' said L.L. Bean's general manager for retail,
William P. Shea, an exuberant proponent of the retail concept, so
much so that Gorman, his boss, refers to it as ``Bill's baby.'' He
added: ``And that's before we arrive. Just wait till we arrive.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea plans to move as many as 100 Bean employees to work in the
new store, ``to transfer the culture,'' as he put it.
</P>
<P>
   Gorman, a serene, athletic 63-year-old, is emblematic of the
old-school L.L. Bean, which his grandfather started in 1912.
Committed to as much domestic manufacturing as possible, especially
if it's located in Maine, he was pivotal in the effort to revamp
the Bean boot, whose rubber soles will be made by a small factory
near Lewiston, Maine (Another small factory made the old soles.) He
supports sturdy causes like the Nature Conservancy, the Boy Scouts
and the Maine chapter of the N.A.A.C.P.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he talks of brand loyalty like someone fresh
out of an M.B.A. program, citing the self-assessment and subsequent
reorganization the company went through last year as priming it
well for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the initiatives in motion now that will provide
substantial growth opportunities in the years ahead,'' Gorman says,
looking slightly embarrassed about the management-speak that has
invaded his vocabulary lately. Terms like ``brand management''
don't sound quite at home at a company that hacked its way out of
the wilderness, selling hunting gear and, when its thoughts turned
to domesticity, scratchy woolen blankets and chairs made from
snowshoes. ``I have to invent a new word,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all its cautious leanings, Bean set itself up for a
serious fall twice in the last two decades. First came its response
to ``The Official Preppy Handbook,'' a spoof of boarding-school
style, or lack thereof, published in 1980 that named Bean footwear
as part of the required wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Gorman says now he wishes that distinction had passed the
company by. ``The women's apparel in particular got this frumpy
appellation,'' he said, calling it ``not really reflective of the
product line.'' The company geared up to handle an influx of
orders, which came and went, leaving Bean with excess capacity.
</P>
<P>
   More devastating was the company's blighted love affair with the
Japanese. In the late 1980s, the Japanese became heavy users of
Bean products, part of it a fashion trend, part of it stemming from
interest in the outdoors, and all of it helped along by the strong
yen. Sales to Japan built steadily, reaching 20 percent of the
company's overall business by 1995, Gorman said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that, the bottom dropped out of the Japanese
economy, taking most of Bean's sales to Japan with it. At the same
time, domestic sales were weak, and competition from longtime
rivals like Lands' End, which posted $1.4 billion in sales last
year, intensified.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the matter of the Internet. Bean had jumped on the
concept early, and its Web site was open for business by 1996. But
competitors roared by it, embracing improved technology that helped
consumers find their sizes, for example, while the Bean site
puttered along exactly the way it had started.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a very basic level, there are some things L.L. Bean really
needs to get on, including offering more sizing information and
more tools,'' said Evie Black Dykema, an analyst with Forrester
Research in Cambridge, Mass. ``Overall, their site is very
thorough. It's basically their catalog, on line. But to realize
their full potential, they will need to expand their functionality
beyond what can be found in their catalog.''
</P>
<P>
   Other outdoor suppliers, like Lands' End and Recreational
Equipment Inc., or REI, have moved well beyond Bean's efforts in
cyberspace, she added. And other analysts were less charitable
about the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really fell behind the pack by not picking up on
E-commerce soon enough and not being more aggressive with it,''
said Alan Mak, an analyst with Argus Research in New York. ``They
lacked the vision to see how powerful the Internet was as a retail
medium. And trying to play catch-up on the Internet is extremely
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem seems to have been the revolving door at
Bean's E-commerce division. Patricia Robles, the current executive
in charge, is the third person to hold the post in the last two
years. One recent departure was Tom Harden, an executive vice
president who left to work for an Internet mail-order gift company,
Send.com. But Ms. Robles insists that the company's revamped
Website, which is supposed to be available in October, will counter
all of the criticism by being as efficient, user-friendly and
up-to-date as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a company that's known to be conservative and traditional,
we really were out on the Web early,'' said Ms. Robles, whose
15-year career at Bean has included stints as a women's apparel
product manager and a manager of inventory control. ``The
disadvantages are that you put in early infrastructure and it
quickly becomes outdated. We did not move quickly to replace some
of the infrastructure, but we're doing that now.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's electronic commerce recently got improved status
within L.L. Bean, Ms. Robles said. ``We are really putting
significant resources into the Web,'' she said. The new site, she
explained, will include tips on where to go on outdoor excursions,
as well as what someone might need and how to order it from Bean.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent addition is a brand called Freeport Studio, which
is supposed to appeal to working women with clothing that is
low-maintenance, relatively stylish and affordable. ``We're trying
to address the casualization of America,'' said Cindy Marshall, the
marketing executive for the line. ``We're certainly not
corporate.''
</P>
<P>
   The brand came out with its own catalog in January, and sales
are strong, Bean executives say. The line came about in response to
a letter from a longtime customer who bought other Bean products,
but pointed out that while they were useful on weekends, ``there
are only 52 weekends a year, and I need something to wear the rest
of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   She closed the letter by advising the company: ``Get with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
