<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MANUFACTURING MAGNATE CONSIDERS RUNNING FOR CONGRESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A wealthy Big Bend rancher with strong ties to
Houston said he is contemplating an uphill race for Congress in a
GOP-held borderland district that extends more than 500 miles from
San Antonio to El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat John B. Poindexter, a manufacturing magnate, has an
office in Houston but resides in Presidio County, one of 29
counties in the 23rd Congressional District that is currently
represented by four-term U.S. Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Poindexter, who recently toured the congressional district from
end to end, said he was encouraged from his meetings with voters
and plans to announce his political intentions in October.
Candidate filing for all state and federal offices is open through
Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   If Poindexter seeks his party's nomination, he could face
several other Democrats in the March primary. Potential candidates
from San Antonio and Laredo have expressed interest in the
Democratic race. The emerging winner presumably would tangle with
Bonilla in the 2000 general election.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, a television producer who has been a rising star in the
GOP since he took office in 1993, was on vacation this week and
unavailable for comment. A campaign spokesman in San Antonio could
not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla succeeded former Rep. Albert Bustamante, D-San Antonio,
in a district that was redrawn in the early 1990s to assure
continued election of Democrats. Yet, Bonilla, a staunch
conservative, defied conventional wisdom by cobbling together a
winning coalition of supporters that included disenchanted Hispanic
Democrats, city-dwellers, farmers, ranchers and oilmen.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic party officials have said that the 23rd Congressional
District still has enough Democrats to make Bonilla vulnerable,
especially if a well-funded candidate emerges to oppose him.
</P>
<P>
   Poindexter, with has never held elective office, owns the 25,000
acre Cibolo Creek Ranch between Presidio and Marfa. The former
frontier fortress, built in the 1850s, is now a dude ranch that has
enticed luminary guests including Mick Jagger and holds a spot on
the National Register of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   Poindexter also owns J.B. Poindexter &AMP; Co., a privately held,
long-term investment partnership whose holdings include Morgan
Trailer Mfg. Co. and Truck Accessories Group, Inc. Revenues will be
about $425 million in 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been encouraged to run, enough to undertake what was a
35-day tour through 29 counties, full time, every day, a very
rigorous tour,'' Poindexter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm contemplating the results of that. There really is nothing
more to say. It sounds so simple and superficial, but that's the
truth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Poindexter also said it's premature to discuss how his policies
might differ with those of Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating insinuations that he lacks enduring ties to the
district _ he bought the ranch in 1990 _ Poindexter said, ``I've
never owned personal property anywhere in Texas but Presidio
County.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
