<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6610 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CRYOLIFE15-COX     08-13 1833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRYOLIFE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia company may soon turn out customized heart valves, using
stripped-down pig tissue and human cells
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 15.
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In coolers shipped in cardboard boxes, the living tissues of
human heart valves, leg veins and knee tendons arrive at CryoLife
Inc., a spacious company in the shadow of Kennesaw Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Lab workers meticulously unwrap the bulky and bloody packages,
stripping and slicing tissue before bathing it in chemical
preservatives. The final product is stored _ still alive _ at minus
325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they do is process people parts,'' said Robin Young,
senior medical analyst for Stephens Inc., a Little Rock investment
firm that follows the publicly owned company. ``They were the
pioneer in this. And they continue to do it very, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   CryoLife _ listed last fall by Forbes magazine as one of the
nation's ``Ten To Watch'' small companies _ has provided more than
35,000 heart valves for transplants since it was founded in 1984.
More than half of those valves are used for pediatric patients. The
company has also shipped more than 17,000 veins and almost 7,500
orthopedic parts _ such as Achilles' tendons and meniscus cartilage
_ for transplant.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the company is aggressively entering the fledgling
field of tissue engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly the stuff of science fiction, tissue engineering
involves the manipulation of biology to create and grow custom-made
parts for patients that would not be rejected by a recipient's
immune system and could last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, medicine repaired or replaced (human) parts by
using some piece of plastic or metal, which would allow a patient
to regain some function of some part of the body,'' said David Ku,
an expert in tissue engineering at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   But now, scientists are working to find other ways to repair or
replace parts of the body. And what researchers hope to find are
ways to merge engineering techniques with biology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Implantable, living, biological devices will be the `norm' for
the new millennium and will replace all the synthetic implantable
devices,'' said Steven Anderson, CryoLife's president and CEO.
``Biochemistry and cell biology will be the technologies of the
21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days, CryoLife's newest product, SynerGraft _ a pig's
heart valve stripped of its cells and reseeded with human cells _
will be implanted in a human patient in Australia. If it takes, it
will be the first time a human has been successfully treated with a
heart valve partially grown in the lab.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the company might have discovered a Holy Grail of
medicine _ a way to provide millions of parts for patients without
needing human donors. No longer would patients have to depend on
the gift of strangers, or use metal or plastic parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would change everything,'' Young said. ``It would start a
revolution ... that would affect literally millions of patients.''
</P>
<P>
   An old theory revisited
</P>
<P>
   The theory behind these advances is not new.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a patient cuts his arm deeply and does nothing,
the gash will not heal properly for months. But if a surgeon
stitches the wound, the gash will heal much better and faster
because an outside structure _ the thread _ helps the patient's own
cells repair the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Tissue engineering is based on the same principle _ with the
goal being to create biomechanical structures that ``allow the body
to heal itself,'' said Ku, a professor of mechanical engineering at
Georgia Tech. A secondary benefit is that the body's immune system
is unlikely to reject its own cells. Now, many patients must take
drugs to keep their bodies from rejecting donors' parts or
mechanical parts. And often, with mechanical parts, the body must
be forced to adapt to technology _ not the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   CryoLife entered tissue engineering by experimenting with
something it already was familiar with _ heart valves. In 1991, its
scientists began stripping pig or ``porcine'' valves down to the
collagen, a group of proteins that form fibers and provide the
structural support for tissue. This, they believed, could provide
the scaffolding needed to attach and grow human cells onto the
valve.
</P>
<P>
   The company's researchers also improved upon SynerGraft's design
by splicing parts of several porcine valves and sewing them
together, forming a bigger and stronger valve. Researchers also put
in a sewing ring, a kind of hemline for surgeons who must suture
the valve into their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, they implanted customized pig valves populated with
sheep cells into sheep. The valves worked without the use of
immunosuppressant therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company, which has received $3.1 million in federal
funding for the valve research, is doing the first human implant in
Australia, which has different standards from those of the United
States for such experimental surgery. From there, it plans to
conduct international clinical trials. If all goes well, these
customized valves could be used in clinical trials next year in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   CryoLife has also produced another biological product, BioGlue
Surgical Adhesive, used to seal veins and wounds without the need
for sutures. BioGlue, a protein-based adhesive, is already used in
Europe and in select clinical trials in the United States. It could
be approved by the Food and Drug Administration as early as this
fall. BioGlue is a wonderful tool, doctors say, because it helps
them work against the clock when trying to repair severe vascular
or pulmonary problems.
</P>
<P>
   It could be particularly useful in surgery to fix a common
condition known as an aortic dissection, where the wall of a major
blood vessel splits in two. The surgery is almost always an
emergency and carries a high risk, said Dr. Steven Macheers, an
Atlanta cardiothoracic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   BioGlue, loaded in clear vials in what looks like a glue gun,
can be used to actually glue the walls of the artery back together,
he said. Its adhesive properties allow the glue to be used as a
sealant to prevent bleeding, a major complication in this type of
complex surgery. The seal holds for several years before the glue
disintegrates, after the tissue has healed.
</P>
<P>
   All of these innovations at CryoLife are possible because of its
successful core business of freezing and preserving tissue. It's a
business that has allowed the 420-employee company to post record
revenues for the first six months of the year for each of the past
seven years. Last year, it reported more than $60 million in
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Parallels to hibernation
</P>
<P>
   The process for freezing for each type of tissue is different _
which is why Austin Powers and his mojo cannot be frozen in
suspended animation. At this point, there's no way to freeze an
entire body without killing millions of cells in different organs.
</P>
<P>
   Cryopreservation involves the removal of water from cells. The
water is then replaced with a chemical compound such as dimethyl
sulfoxide, or DMSO, which bathes the tissues in life-sustaining
salts and proteins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot different than a steak you get at a supermarket.
That tissue is dead when you freeze it and dead when you thaw it
out,'' said Albert Heacox, CryoLife's director of laboratory
operations. ``We have a process that cools down tissue and slows
down its physiological functions. It's sort of like when an animal
goes into hibernation.''
</P>
<P>
   The company receives donated tissue _ and has staff to prepare
it _ 24 hours a day. Typically, tissue and parts are harvested from
hospital patients minutes after death and rushed to CryoLife's
100,000-square-foot facility in coolers shipped by plane.
</P>
<P>
   In 16 hyperfiltered ``clean rooms'' designed to keep microbes to
a minimum, technicians strip, prepare and bathe the tissues before
they are stored in large stainless steel tanks filled with liquid
nitrogen. Right now, the company has about 4,400 heart valves,
2,900 orthopedic parts and 2,500 veins frozen and ready for use.
The tissue can stay in the tanks for up to a decade until it's
needed.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain and supply tissues for surgery, the company relies on
a network of almost 300 tissue banks nationwide. CryoLife typically
receives $7,000 for heart valves it processes, $4,000 for veins and
a few thousand for other parts. Its gross profit margin, on
average, is about 10 percent. And it charges the processing fee at
the back end _ when a recipient needs the part _ not at the front
end of the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as a positive relationship,'' said Jeff Al-Mashat,
spokesman for LifeLink of Georgia, a local organ procurement
agency. LifeLink has used leg veins from CryoLife for about a year,
although it has its own tissue processing center in Florida for
other parts.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage for organ procurement agencies is that they retain
control of parts they gathered and can call the company to reclaim
those parts as needed.
</P>
<P>
   CryoLife's main focus is on heart valves _ still constituting 43
percent of the company's total revenue. The heart valves are
particularly useful in the treatment of children born with
congenital heart defects. Today, children can be fitted with a
human valve within eight hours of the surgeon's request for one.
And that means they are able to recover and live a normal life
quickly. In CryoLife's headquarters, posters of ``CryoKids'' line
the walls, all bordered with the slogan, ``Every child deserves the
chance to be a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   The valves also work well in adults, although fewer surgeons are
as familiar with them as mechanical heart valves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did the (heart) valve from CryoLife save my life, it
saved my dreams,'' said Phil Lanzatella of Sycamore, Pa., who is
vying to compete in heavyweight wrestling in the 2000 Olympics.
``This is allowing me to live life to the fullest.''
</P>
<P>
   More than two years ago, Lanzatella was getting ready to leave
for Sweden for a competition. His wife, Melody, gave him a goodbye
hug, but as she rested her head on his chest, she heard ``a
horrible sound.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like an old washing machine creaking,'' she said.
``It startled me, it was so loud. I knew something was terribly
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardiologists later discovered he needed open heart surgery
because of a large hole in his valve. The world-class wrestler was
given three options: Surgeons could implant a pig's valve,
mechanical valve or a human donor's valve. He decided to go with a
human valve, although the surgery is trickier and there is a chance
it will wear out in his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Lanzatella is thrilled with his human valve _ and
has just been given the OK to wrestle again in pursuit of Olympic
gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what CryoLife is doing,'' he said. ``They've
given my life back.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
