<HEADER>
A6614 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BAPTIST-HONORED14-COX     08-13 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-HONORED14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cameron Alexander _ a force in the religious life of the city
and of the nation _ takes the quiet way, pastors `the least of
these.' Now he'll be publicly honored.
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the funeral of an up-and-coming Atlanta minister six years
ago, now-Mayor Bill Campbell accidentally offended the Rev. Cameron
Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a mayoral candidate at the time, delivered a eulogy
characterizing the death of 22-year-old Aric Flemming, killed in a
car accident, as a ``mistake.'' A hush fell over the crowd of
7,000, mostly Baptists who generally believe that God is
all-knowing and all-wise.
</P>
<P>
   Two pastors speaking after Campbell said nothing about his
remarks. But Alexander, pastor of Antioch Baptist Church North,
couldn't ignore the comment.
</P>
<P>
   When it was his turn in the pulpit, Alexander said God never
made mistakes and wasn't running for office. The crowd erupted in
applause and ``Amens.''
</P>
<P>
   Few preachers would offer such a rebuke at a public forum, but
Alexander, 66, has long gone his own way.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the line between entertainer and preacher has
become perilously thin, Alexander has quietly built a 9,000-member
megachurch in Atlanta's inner city by defying conventional wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   He passed up a chance to move his church into the suburbs and
kept it in one of Atlanta's toughest neighborhoods. He doesn't
write books or sell tapes to promote his ministry. And his distaste
for the spotlight is legendary.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Alexander takes center stage today, when he will be
honored for three decades of service at Antioch during a luncheon
at the Georgia World Congress Center, with proceeds benefiting
church ministries. The Rev. Jesse Jackson, who calls Alexander his
mentor, will be the main speaker at the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is one of the most powerful black Baptist leaders in
the nation. He's the head of a group that presides over 800 Baptist
churches in Georgia and a member of the board of directors for the
National Baptist Convention U.S.A. Inc., the nation's largest body
of black churches.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta City Council President Robb Pitts calls Alexander a
``quiet power broker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not only a spiritual leader, but he also provides
tremendous support for elected officials,'' Pitts said. ``I don't
think a major decision is made, particularly where there's
controversy, in which his opinion is not sought.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Alexander disdains public displays of his influence,
canceling television interviews at the last moment and, when
possible, remaining behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   And he remains fearless in standing up for what he believes. He
still refuses, for instance, to allow women to preach at his church
because he doesn't believe the Bible supports the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't leverage his power for political or personal
gain,'' said the Rev. Fred Robinson, an associate minister at
Antioch.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander thinks self-promotion interferes with his duties as a
pastor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always seen myself as a local pastor,'' he said. ``That
means visiting the sick. If they're in the hospital, three or four
weeks, you're there. It means burying the dead, being there before
and after. It means paying the rent, going to their school. It
means being on duty every day, all day and all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, a native of Atlanta, is a graduate of Morehouse
College. He has been a pastor for 47 years, leading three churches
in rural Georgia before coming to Antioch in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   He has been married for almost as long as he's preached _ 45
years _ to Barbara Jackson Alexander. They have three sons and a
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Antioch is one of a handful of Atlanta megachurches that remain
in the city. About 12 years ago, a study commissioned by the church
suggested that it move from its Northside Drive location because
the area was crime-infested, transient, and there was little room
for growth.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said he decided to ignore the study after receiving a
revelation from God. Instead of relocating, he created ministries
to reach the needy in his community _ the homeless, drug addicts
and people with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``A church should be there to serve the least of these,'' he
said, ``the hungry, the alcoholics, the addicts _ a hospital needs
to be where people are sick.''
</P>
<P>
   And Alexander has been able to accomplish such deeds because
he's been free of scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one does not stay plugged in spiritually, one can drift and
use one skill more than all the other skills,'' Alexander said.
``If you're good at getting money or you're good at people skills _
you're charismatic _ it's easy to do something with those skills
for yourself rather than for the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Aaron Parker, an authority on the Baptist church, said
Alexander has survived in one pulpit for 30 years because he has
kept his focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's lasted because he serves,'' said Parker, pastor of Zion
Hill Baptist Church in Atlanta. ``He directs the attention of the
church toward serving the community as opposed to serving itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said he has no plans to change his low-key leadership
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather fill people up with the inspiration that comes from
a life with God than fill up any arena,'' he said. ``Success in the
Lord has nothing to do with quantity but quality. If you can fill
up one person, and they can go home and change their place, and the
house next to where they live and the jobs where they're working,
then you're being successful.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
