<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6620 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-LIFETIME14-COX     08-13 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LIFETIME14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Girl power for Lifetime original programming
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The star of ``Ruby'' studies a showgirl's scanty G-string and
wonders _ out loud _ what wearing it would do to her own
``organs.''
</P>
<P>
   On the set of ``Beyond Chance,'' meanwhile, the hostess nestles
in a cocoon of soft candlelight and inspiring talk of life-altering
``twists of fate.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the start of another season of original programming on
Lifetime, the cable network that's long billed itself as
``Television for Women.'' Increasingly, it seems it's all different
sorts of women they're after, if those two new series debuting this
week are any indication.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the returning shows ``Any Day Now'' (the
Emmy-nominated drama has its second season premiere at 10 p.m.
Sunday) and ``Oh Baby'' (season two kicks off at 10 p.m. Aug. 21),
the new programs are part of Lifetime's effort to consolidate its
girl power hold over the world of cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen, the new women's cable network whose big-name backers
include Oprah Winfrey and Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen, is
expected to launch in early 2000. While Lifetime got a little
breathing room Friday when Time Warner suspended plans for its own
Turner Women's Network, the 15-year-old cable channel clearly sees
continued development of original series as key to building viewer
loyalty among advertiser-desirable adult women.
</P>
<P>
   After all, everything can't be left up to twists of fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond Chance''
</P>
<P>
   Spooky.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be what producers are going for with this series of
real-life tales about people who have premonitions of danger or
receive life-changing messages in dreams.
</P>
<P>
   But working with someone who turns out to be your long-lost
sibling? That's downright scary, for many reasons.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the very first story told on ``Chance.'' Ignore the
fact that there's nary a mention of the legalistic and other types
of spade work that undoubtedly went into validating the tale. It's
still a tear-inducing saga of a woman who accidentally discovers
her co-worker is the sister she never even knew was given up for
adoption? It's the feeling of a greater force at work that really
counts here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's no simple answer for the mysteries of life, we
look for explanations that are often beyond our imagination,'' says
host Melissa Etheridge, who's bathed in so much mood-setting soft
candlelight and New Age music, it risks putting some viewers to
sleep. ``Beyond reason. Beyond chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Curious, then, that the episode's most compelling story seems to
be at least partially rooted in science.The heart and lungs of an
18-year-old male are transplanted into a delicate female dancer,
who gradually acquires his lumbering walk, his tastes in food (beer
and chicken nuggets) and other traits. By the time a doctor shows
up to suggest that we may store ``memories'' throughout our bodies,
you'll be intrigued and maybe a little bit unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   Give us one or two of these each week to balance out all that
candlelight and the unapologetically tearjerking tales, and this
show could have a chance at long life.
</P>
<P>
   Premieres Aug. 16 at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruby''
</P>
<P>
   That can't be her real name, can it? Ruby Wax? And what about
her hair? That's not, um, a natural shade of red, is it?
</P>
<P>
   And don't even get us started on the poker-faced cowboy she
somehow gets to open up and admit that his career choice was
largely guided by fear of trying new things. This stuff has to be
scripted, right?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows if Ruby's genuine or imitation? Who cares? Turns out
she's a gem, although like most big flashy rocks, she may not be
everyone's taste.
</P>
<P>
   The premise, such as it is, drops the tart-tongued Wax into
various fish-out-of-water settings. Thus, in the premiere episode,
filmed backstage with Las Vegas showgirls, we learn everything we
did (and a lot we didn't) want to know about G-strings.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to Wax's unique style of interviewing (she describes
her show as ```60 Minutes' on acid''), we also learn that showgirls
are pretty much like everyone else, albeit with a few delicious
twists (one knockout with legs up to here lost her Vegas magician
husband to an older woman).
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruby'' really hits her stride in the second episode, when she
sets out on the range with a group of cowboys and her longtime
friend, Carrie Fisher, for whom she's determined to find a
boyfriend. As Fisher clomps along on horseback, Diet Coke and
cigarette in hand, Wax chats up a potential suitor sporting a
lowslung cowboy hat and a forbidding handlebar mustache.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is she too complicated for you?'' Wax asks. ``What's the
vibe?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is vibes, and I live by that,'' comes the somewhat
surprising response. ``I live with vibes or an aura, somewhat,
amongst my horse. I know what my horse is feeling, what cattle are
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   And then danged if he doesn't do a spot-on analysis of Fisher,
much as he would his horse. Right out there in the desert, Ruby's
found a diamond in the rough.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers may feel the same way about ``Ruby.''
</P>
<P>
   Premieres Aug. 21 at 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: ``Showgirls'' B+; ``Cowboys'' A
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
