<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVY-CROCKETT-DAYS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE TOWN CELEBRATES CROCKETT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DENNIS SHERER   
 TimeDaily, Florence, Ala.  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCEBURG, Tenn. _ As America prepares to enter the 21st
century, a 19th century hero remains popular.
</P>
<P>
   About 30,000 people are expected to visit Lawrenceburg this
weekend to help celebrate the birthday of the town's most famous
citizen.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Davy Crockett Days Celebration is being held at David
Crockett State Park in Lawrenceburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how popular David Crockett is today. His
notoriety has spanned centuries,'' said Charles Norvell, regional
naturalist for Tennessee State Parks. ``He was a hero in his time
and he is still a hero today. There's a lot of people in America
who cannot tell you who the secretary of state is but they know who
David Crockett was.''
</P>
<P>
   Crockett was born Aug. 17, 1786, in what is now eastern
Tennessee, and moved to Lawrenceburg in 1817. He was elected to the
first Lawrence County commission in 1819.
</P>
<P>
   He built a grist mill, distillery and gun powder mill on the
banks of Shoal Creek on property that is now part of the state
park. He left Lawrenceburg and moved to western Tennessee in 1821
after a flood destroyed his businesses.
</P>
<P>
   While living in Lawrenceburg, Crockett was elected to the state
Legislature. He later served in Congress, from 1827 to 1831 and
from 1833 to 1835.
</P>
<P>
   Crockett died at the Alamo in 1836 while fighting for the
independence of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   During this weekend's celebration, re-enactors dressed in
clothing from the Crockett era will demonstrate frontier skills and
crafts. Norvell said the goal of Crockett Days is to show what life
was like in Tennessee in the early 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Re-enactors, who are known as longhunters, will set up more than
175 frontier-era lodges in the park. Men, women and children will
live in the lodges, cook their meals over fires and live as
frontiersmen did when Crockett lived in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do, we try to do just like they did before the
1840s,'' said Jim Nation, a spokesman for the Davy Crockett
Longhunters Club.
</P>
<P>
   Norvell said it is the largest educational event for any state
park in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   A Davy Crockett film festival will be held in the park's visitor
center.
</P>
<P>
   Norvell said Crockett called himself David but he often was
called Davy in stories about his superb frontiersman skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davy Crockett is the legend and you cannot separate the legend
from the man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Sherer writes for the TimeDaily, Florence, Ala., which is
a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
