<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARZA-AMBASSADOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARZA SWORN IN AS ENVOY TO NICARAGUA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Oliver P. Garza, the son of a Texas farm laborer,
raised his right hand over a Bible in the ornate Treaty Room of the
State Department Friday and pledged to ``support and defend the
Constitution'' as the new U.S. ambassador to Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   Garza, 57, a career diplomat, told about 100 friends and
supporters who crowded under a large crystal chandelier in the room
with tall white columns decorated with gold American eagles that it
was a testament to this country that someone from his humble roots
could attain the post of ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a dark suit, black shoes, a white shirt and yellow
tie and wearing conservative tortoise-shell reading glasses, Garza
joked that when he first walked into the State Department many
years ago wearing black and white shoes, others took one look at
him and said he would never make it as a diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Garza's wife of 38 years, Yolanda, held a Bible as David Pryor
Jr., the deputy chief of protocol, administered the oath, in which
the new ambassador pledged to ``support and defend the Constitution
against all enemies foreign and domestic.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Romero, acting assistant secretary of state for Western
Hemisphere Affairs, praised Garza as a ``recognized and respected
member of the San Antonio community'' who has ``steadily moved up
the ranks over the past 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Romero said the post would be a challenging one, especially in
the aftermath of Hurricane Mitch, which 10 months ago killed
hundreds of people in Central America and displaced thousands of
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nicaraguans and their government authorities are poised not
just to replace but to transform their society,'' Romero said.
``Nobody is better equipped than you to represent the U.S. in
Nicaragua.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicaragua, a nation of 4.6 million, has enjoyed relative peace
this decade after a long period in which the United States actively
supported the Contra rebels fighting the leftist government. But
the nation has struggled economically.
</P>
<P>
   Garza thanked some 20 family members in the crowd, including
those, he quipped, who are ``crying out for attention,'' referring
to his 11-month-old granddaughter Elisa Lopez, who squealed and
babbled throughout the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   He also apologized for not naming all the attending relatives,
adding ``we only have this room for an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Garza's four children, Desiree Denise Garza-Bell, Melissa
Garza-Lopez, Christopher Garza and Gregory Garza, and his two
brothers, Rudy and M.P. Garza, were among the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Garza said in an interview afterward he never aimed to become an
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell into this more by accident than design,'' said Garza,
who just completed a stint as consul general in Guadalajara,
Mexico. ``Having achieved this was something very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Garza grew up in Poteet, a small town south of San Antonio that
refers to itself as strawberry capital of the world..
</P>
<P>
   In addition to duty in Colombia, Panama, Korea, Uruguay and the
Dominican Republic, Garza worked as an agent for the Drug
Enforcement Administration in San Antonio from 1974 to 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Garza graduated from St. Mary's University in San Antonio in
1970. He also was a student at the National War College in
Washington from 1987 to 1988, where military officers and
government officials study issues such as national security and
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Garza's son Christopher, 34, of Reston, Va., said the
ambassadorship, ``is an achievement for us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Garza, 28, an agent for the Drug Enforcement
Administration in Los Angeles, said he was proud that his father
``finally made it. He's worked hard. I've always planned to follow
in his footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   M.P. Garza, who owns a company that sells computer products,
said he never imagined his brother would climb this high in the
diplomatic ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not have a very directed upbringing,'' he said. ``Back
in those days nobody talked about going to college or having a
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Pastrano, a retired Air Force flight engineer and the
new ambassador's uncle, said Hispanic teen-agers should draw a
lesson from Garza's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't give up just because you come from where you come
from,'' he said. ``If you come from a place where you have always
been put down, you can fight and get out of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
