<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DRUG-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN MASS KILLING IN MEXICO IS ARRESTED IN LOS ANGELES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A man suspected of being one of the gunmen who
killed 19 people last September on a farm in Mexico has been
arrested in Los Angeles, law-enforcement officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents from the Immigration and Naturalization Service,
the Drug Enforcement Administration, the FBI and the U.S. Marshals
Service took the man, Manuel Escalante, 24, into custody after he
picked up his mother and sister from a bus stop on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Agents had followed the two women from Ensenada, Mexico, after
getting a tip that they were going to visit him. The Mexican
attorney general's office in Los Angeles said 10 other suspects in
the shootings had been arrested in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Escalante, a Spanish citizen with longtime residency in Mexico,
was identified in court papers as a member of a gang with strong
ties to the violent Arellano Felix drug cartel of Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 16, 1998, he and 12 others spent the evening drinking
and consuming cocaine with Arturo Martinez Gonzalez, the head of
the gang, according to the court filing.
</P>
<P>
   In the early morning hours of Sept. 17, they decided to rob a
ranch near Ensenada owned by Fermin Castro, a reputed marijuana
grower for the Felix cartel who reportedly owed Martinez Gonzalez
money and who had nearly 1,800 pounds of marijuana in storage,
court documents said. Castro and 18 people from three families
living in a compound on the ranch were lined up and shot.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Wilson, a special agent in charge of the immigration
service's fugitive alien removal unit, said Escalante had been
arrested near his home in the South-Central neighborhood of Los
Angeles. Another immigration official said he was initially held on
suspicion of working as a carpenter while in the country on a
tourist visa. He is being held at the federal detention center in
Los Angeles pending extradition proceedings.
</P>
</TEXT>
