<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-MS-INDEXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA MARKET BOOSTED BY REINSTATEMENT IN MORGAN STANLEY INDEX  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ After 11 months as a financial pariah, Malaysia
earned a measure of redemption late Thursday when Morgan Stanley
Capital International said it would readmit the country to model
portfolios that many fund managers use as a guideline for where and
how much to invest. In response, the country's benchmark stock
index soared Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley said it would reinstate Malaysia in its so-called
All-Country Far East Free and Emerging Markets Free indexes as of
February, after having removed the country when Malaysia imposed
currency controls last September. Many overseas funds use the
indexes to judge their own performance, and some are bound by their
charters not to invest in countries that are excluded from the
indexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big booster,'' Ahmad Bachok, the head of sales at
Arab-Malaysian Securities Sdn. Bhd., said as the composite index in
Kuala Lumpur, the capital, rose 6 percent Friday. But many stock
markets elsewhere around Asia retreated.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean stocks fell by more than 3 percent, weighed down
partly by concerns about debt restructuring at the Daewoo Group.
Singapore stocks dropped more than 2 percent, and stocks in
Indonesia fell almost 1.5 percent as a spreading financial scandal
raised doubts about that country's economic restructuring plans.
Stocks also fell in Hong Kong and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley also said it would adjust its portfolios to
double the weighting of Taiwan, reflecting the growth of the market
there. Stocks rose 4 percent in Taiwan despite concerns that China
was mobilizing armed forces in response to what it sees as moves
toward independence by Taiwan, which it considers a renegade
province.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia was hurt badly by the Asian economic crisis that began
in Thailand two years ago. The government blamed foreign currency
speculators for much of the problem and, in response, imposed
severe controls on the movement of money in and out of Malaysia
last September. Those controls alienated many overseas investors
and isolated the country financially.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia has since been seeking to regain investor trust. In
February, it eliminated a ban on the repatriation of funds
overseas, replacing it with a tax of up to 30 percent. On Sept. 1,
Malaysia will go further, replacing the repatriation tax with a
capital gains tax that is considered much less onerous.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, analysts and traders feared that foreign investors, who
still have as much as $6 billion invested in Malaysia, were dumping
their holdings to prepare for a September exodus. The move by
Morgan Stanley helped allay those fears and halted almost a month
of stock-market declines.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia's improving economic picture is also contributing to
enthusiasm for its stocks, said Kevin Ng, an economist at ABN-Amro
Asia Securities Pte. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysian companies are producing and exporting more, he said,
and it appears that the country may have pulled out of recession in
the second quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   But some consultants and bankers say Malaysia has yet to deliver
the kind of transparency and accountability it needs, and Morgan
Stanley cautioned that its decision was contingent on continued
restructuring by Malaysia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1818EDT &QL; 
