<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6671 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PRELUDES-$ADV15-N     08-13 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PRELUDES-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GENERATION OF FREELANCERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget about that X, and all of its slacker implications. We are
now in the midst of Generation 1099 _ the once pitied but now
envied group of self-employed workers who dutifully file Form 1099s
to the Internal Revenue Service four times a year.
</P>
<P>
   Prime evidence of the new era is the emergence of two companies
that are making the life of a full-time freelancer even more
attractive, offering a lot of the perks that most permanent
employees enjoy. Freeagent.com and Aquent (Latin for not a
follower), both opened shop in the last two months, and act as
virtual employers that offer group benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to give the freelancer the same security earned by
traditional W-2 employees,'' said John Chuang, Aquent's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   As of February 1997, there were 8.5 million independent
contractors _ aka free agents, freelancers or consultants _
according to the government, 1.5 million of them between the ages
24 and 35. Not to be confused with temps, who are employed by one
agency, 1099ers have many clients and set their own hours.
</P>
<P>
   The life of the self-employed is not all leisurely lunches and
afternoons at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. Members of Generation
1099 spend an inordinate amount of time hustling, invoicing and
politely harassing accounts payable.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike full-time employees, who have taxes withheld, 1099ers
are responsible for paying their own state, federal and Social
Security taxes, and shelling out huge amounts for health insurance
_ if they have it at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been sick in my life, and I said I'd wait until I'm
30 to get insurance,'' said Kris Tobiassen, 29, a graphic designer
in New York who has been a full-time freelancer for five years.
``My birthday's coming up in a few short months, but I'm thinking
about waiting _ it's so expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Health insurance, stock options and retirement plans pull many
people toward full-time, permanent employment. ``The accessibility
of benefits can serve as a glue to an existing job,'' said Jeffrey
Bradach, an associate professor at Harvard Business School. Then
there's the camaraderie and the relief of more structure.
</P>
<P>
   Still, those boons are not enough to lure some people. ``It
would have to be a helluva lot of money for me to go back to an
office,'' said Michael Bassett, 35, a computer consultant in
Manhattan. ``Big fat six-figure sums. I like the freedom too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   But freedom's often just another word for nothing left to
deposit _ especially when the landlord comes knocking, the electric
bill lands in your mailbox, it's midnight on April 14th, your tooth
cracked on a piece of toffee and your latest client can't cough up
the cash. That's usually when 1099ers flip through the help wanted
ads, looking for permanent employment.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, professional groups like the National Writers Union
have offered freelance writers some benefits. Freeagent.com and
Aquent aim to offer more benefits _ group-rate health, dental,
life, property, casualty, professional and disability insurance;
401(k) retirement plans and pensions _ to freelancers in all
fields.
</P>
<P>
   Freeagent.com even offers stock options in its privately held
parent company, Opus360, for those who want to bet on its future.
</P>
<P>
   As a 31-year-old in Manhattan, I could join an Oxford Health
Plans managed-care plan for $224 a month through Freeagent.com,
compared with $270 on my own.
</P>
<P>
   Job seekers can display their resumes on these sites. The
companies also have billing and collection services, although they
collect only from established corporations. You invoice
Freeagent.com or Aquent and they pay the money owed you, less 3
percent to 5 percent. The companies collect fees or even
commissions from the other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Chuang says he wants Aquent to be the ``Rosetta stone which
translates the W-2-based world of financial services to the world
of independent professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradach of Harvard says that the new services will encourage
people to try new careers or take more risks. They will also give
freelancers more leverage.
</P>
<P>
   With all the possibilities, there seems to be only one reason to
get a full-time job: the company Christmas Party. Then again, that
might be a reason not to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
