<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6673 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-MADRAZO-$ADV15     08-13 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MADRAZO-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MADRAZO: WHILE HE CLIMBS IN POLLS, HIS OWN PARTY BRETHREN PAINT
HIM CORRUPT
 &HT;    With MADRAZO-BOX-$ADV15.
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 15 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ With a grin splitting his face and a gleam in his
eye, Roberto Madrazo exudes the confidence of one of the most
talked-about men in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a man who thinks like us. We don't need a man who went
to Harvard or Yale,'' shouted a fan at a boisterous rally here for
Madrazo, who wants to be Mexico's next president.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo, the former governor of Mexico's Tabasco state, did
study urban planning at the University of California for a year.
But it's not a biographical detail he trumpets as he works his
populist charm on Mexico's disgruntled masses _ and fights for the
presidential nomination of this country's Revolutionary
Institutional Party, known as the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI, the party that has controlled Mexico's presidency for
70 years, is attempting to shed its authoritarian, corrupt image by
holding its first presidential primary ever on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo, a 48-year-old lawyer and party veteran since his teens,
has vaulted unexpectedly onto center stage and taken a lead in
polls by doing the unthinkable: In aggressive ads and speeches, he
is attacking his party brethren and free-market economic policies
pushed by Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, the supreme PRI
commander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the candidate of the forgotten PRI!'' Madrazo
told a crowd of working and middle-class supporters at a rally here
last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With slogans urging an end to ``great results for few, and few
results for many,'' Madrazo is surging in popularity among Mexicans
who feel impoverished by free-market reforms and believe the PRI
has been hijacked by Ivy League-trained economists, such as
Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Some ``PRIistas'' credit Zedillo with taking a bold step to
democratize the PRI by endorsing a primary. But Madrazo lays claim
to that legacy through his father, Carlos, a PRI leader who he says
tried to similarly modernize the party 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo's father was killed in a 1969 airplane crash some
Mexicans believe was no accident. The crash left Madrazo an orphan
at 16, and that memory could be fueling his drive for the
presidency, according to some observers.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo's rising star threatens to eclipse former Mexican
interior minister Francisco Labastida, a candidate who emerged from
Zedillo's inner circle. This week, a Mexico City newspaper reported
that Labastida's campaign manager had described Madrazo as a relic
from ``the most corrupt PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard a (campaign) ad where Madrazo talked about
honesty, I thought of Hitler talking about human rights,'' Esteban
Moctezuma reportedly said in a closed breakfast meeting with
Mexican graduates of Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo's followers asked the PRI to reprimand Moctezuma, who
replied that his comments were made in confidence and were taken
out of context.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest television ads, Madrazo appeals to nationalist
sentiment and implicitly challenges Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is not for sale. And neither am I,'' he says, after
snapshots representing Mexico's state-owned oil and electricity
industries flash by.
</P>
<P>
   None of Madrazo's three rivals within the PRI have proposed
privatizing Mexico's oil industry, but a Zedillo proposal to
privatize some sectors of electricity production met a wall of
resistance this year.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed to explain his positions, Madrazo has a lighter touch.
</P>
<P>
   As a Tabasco senator, he supported the adoption of the North
American Free Trade Agreement, and says Tabasco, his own state on
the Gulf of Mexico, has benefited.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Madrazo's image as a PRI nationalist that's winning him
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the candidate of the people,'' said Mexico City
homemaker Rosa Maria Hernandez, a PRI loyalist who attended a
Madrazo rally.
</P>
<P>
   In a July poll conducted by the Mexico City-based Indemerc-Lou
Harris group, PRI sympathizers favored Madrazo over Labastida by 7
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   In the same poll, voters in general also favored Madrazo by 5
percentage points over the National Action Party's Vicente Fox,
considered the toughest foe the PRI could face in next year's
general election. Labastida trailed behind Fox by 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Madrazo's popularity, analysts say the PRI _ which
normally keeps its feuds secret _ could fail to regroup around him
should he win in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody hates (Madrazo). I'm not talking about the people.
I'm talking about the PRI system,'' said Vicente Licona of the
Indemerc-Lou Harris group.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have since publicly made peace, Madrazo feuded
with Zedillo in 1994 after he was elected to the Tabasco
governorship. In response to charges of vote-rigging by Madrazo
opponents, Zedillo ordered an investigation that found the
accusations warranted. He tried to force Madrazo to resign, but
Madrazo's supporters took to the streets and Zedillo backed down.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo has also been dogged by charges he spent as much as $36
million to get elected _ many times over the cost of a normal
governor's race _ and received donations from corrupt bankers and
other dubious sources. But because the PRI in general is widely
believed to have endorsed illicit donations, the allegations are
not likely to stick to Madrazo in a primary, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with their portrayal of Madrazo as retrograde,
Labastida's campaign is raising questions about where Madrazo is
currently obtaining money to air a generous number of expensive
television ads.
</P>
<P>
   One of the rumors is that Madrazo is receiving money from Carlos
Salinas de Gortari, the former president who went into self-exile
amid allegations that his brother stole public money and accepted
millions in bribes from drug lords.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard-educated Salinas is one of Mexico's most reviled
politicians, largely because the country plunged into economic
crisis following his term.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lie. It's totally false. The principal collaborators
of Carlos Salinas are in the Labastida camp,'' Madrazo said,
ridiculing the rumored link in an interview with Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In an act of political jujitsu, Madrazo is trying to turn the
tables on Labastida by appealing to Mexicans' disgust with the
PRI's anti-democratic habits.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception, the PRI's presidential nominees have always
been quietly selected by the president of the republic. The
decision to hold a primary this year is supposed to put an end to
that process, known as the ``dedazo,'' or ``big finger.''
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo's first television ads, however, implied that the PRI's
presidential candidate might still be imposed from above. In a
witty play on words, it urged Mexicans to give a ``madrazo'' _ a
``punch'' in Mexican slang _ to the ``dedazo.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's guidelines for the primary require that elected
officials who belong to the party _ including the president _
remain publicly mum on who they support for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Also prohibited is the use of state resources to bolster a
candidate. Madrazo recently accused Labastida of benefiting from
government resources during a recent tour of Chiapas state, where
the governor is known as a Labastida partisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the old PRI,'' Madrazo said, accusing his rival of the
same evils Labastida attributes to him. ``We want a new PRI to
surface that's stronger, more modern and more democratic, so that
people can choose candidates freely with their votes and not have
them imposed on them the same way as before.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
