<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV15-B     08-13 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV15-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY WE BROKE UP MA BELL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 15, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most powerful argument against monopoly is not that it
inflates its owners' profit (though of course it does), but rather
that it retards innovation. Remember that its chief reward is said
to be a quiet life for the the monopolists and their children _ and
a little more stability than is good for the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrate, therefore, the Justice Department's decision more
than fifteen years ago to break the hold of American Telephone and
Telegraph on the United States telecommunications system. More than
a little, the 1984 divestiture changed the network that today binds
together the nations of the world and which promises to change
still more in the years to come, propelling us into a state of
dense interconnection that was no part of Ma Bell's plan..
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that AT&AMP;T's Bell Labs was forever a cornucopia of
new ideas. Indeed, the transistor was invented there in the years
just after World War II, opening the crucial pass to the computer
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was International Telephone and Telegraph Co. that
instigated the key developments in fiber optics, the technology
that, more than any other, has turned out to be the basic
infrastructure of today's information highway. Yes, the very same
ITT that in the early 1970s became synoymous with the arrogance of
multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
   A few years before Dita Beard, its chief Washington lobbyist,
became famous for skulking around Washington in a cheap red wig in
the wake of the Watergate burglaries; before Harold Geneen, its
chief executive, truculently battled the Church Committee over his
corporation's attempts to overturn the Allende government in Chile,
it turns out an ITT scientist in England named Charles Kao
published an eight-page paper arguing that fiber optic
communications were a real-world possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Using glass pipes designed to carry pulses of light intead of
copper wire to carry electrons could offer huge transmission
capacity at low cost, Kao argued in early 1966, with co-author
George Hockham -- as long as the pipes themselves could be
successfully engineered.
</P>
<P>
   A series of breaks then put Kao in charge of a small development
effort at ITT's Standard Telecommunication Laboratories subsidiary
north of London, and the events he put in train (with direct
encouragement from Geneen himself) eventually created today's
long-distance revolution: overseas telephone connections as clear
as those with the house next door, and far more abundant.
</P>
<P>
   The decision of the British Post Office to pursue the new
technology; the discoveries by Corning Glass of new pure fiber
materials; the advent of the semiconductor laser as a source of
light (and the success of scientists at an obscure Russian
laboratory in beating their American counterparts at Bell Labs to a
room-temperature design); the rapid progress of the late 1970s, as
fiber optic began to outperform both coaxial cable and satellite
transmission; the climactic decision in 1984 of MCI to install a
transcontinental fiber network in North America _ all these
developments in some sense flowed out of half-a-dozen years of
missionary zeal by Kao, who unexpectedly took over Stantard
Telecommunication Labs' optical waveguide program at the age of 31,
closed it down and took off after the dream of fiber optics
instead.
</P>
<P>
   This is the story to be gleaned from ``City of Light: The Story
of Fiber Optics,'' by Jeff Hecht, the most recent in a series of
histories of technology underwritten by the Alfred Sloan
Foundation, published in this case by Oxford University Press. The
series itself has been uneven, but Hecht's narrative is a model of
the sort -- exactly what might have been hoped from a writer who
covered the industry for 25 years for trade publications, yet
retains both the detachment and perspective necessary to put a
narrative construction on events.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Newton, Mass., Hecht now covers all manner of topics,
from optics to paeontology, for Britain's New Scientist magazine.
But it is clear from the 11-page chronology (and the extensive
notes citing interviews with virtually evey major figure of the
modern period) that he has written an authoritative history of an
otherwise all-but-invisible industry. Trained as an engineer
himself, Hecht has a real gift for conveying the fog of uncertainy
about the possibilities in which scientists, engineers and managers
must make their choices about the approaches to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, Bell Labs was a surprising also-ran,'' writes
Hecht, ``a world-class laboratory that scored few conceptual
breakthroughs and spent untold millions chasing dead ends. Bell
suffered from being fat and happy and too quick to reject outside
ideas in favor of its own.'' The labs were slow to recognize
problems inherent in its preferred approaches, he concludes, not
surprisingly, since one of the hardest jobs research managers face
is ``to kill their own faltering projects before they grow into
money pits....'' Thus Bell bore down on hollow optical waveguides,
a technology that looks downright silly is retrospect (the light
pipes apparently would have had to have been absolutely straight)
as Kao began to explore glass transmission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is harder to explain why the Bell environment only rarely
sparked the creativity that ignited new ideas at Stantard
Telecommunication Labs, British Post Office/British Telecomm,
Corning, Lincoln Labs and Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Had the
prestigious lab become stuck in the mud?''
</P>
<P>
   Hecht's book only incidentally illuminates the principles behind
the antitrust statutes. Mostly it is a example of satisfying
technological history. He begins with an account of the spectacular
``luminous fountains'' that were centerpieces of the great
electrical expositions in London, Paris and Cicago at the end of
the 19th century, then traces the slow zig-zag development of the
idea from early applications (the illumination of out-of-the-way
spaces by doctors and mechanics) to theoretical investigation of
the underlying principles of light transmission by glass by those
involved in the telephone industry.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming moral here is that large numbers of persons are
involved in the accomplishment of any significant innovation - not
a solitary ``inventor'' or two. Hecht notes in passing that a
timeline of inventions that decorates the subway stop at
Massachusetts Institute of Technology records that fiber optics was
invented there by Narinder Kapany &UR;  &LR; in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   In fact Kapany was only one of many contributers to the basic
science, he says, and 1955 mainly marks the beginning of an epic
quarrel with Karinder's his thesis adviser Harold Hopkins about who
deseved credit for the ideas therein. If anyone deserves to be
singled out for the role he played in influencing the course of
events it is Charles Kao, who left the field once events were in
train to become professor and now president of Chinese University
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the point about ATT's embarassment at the hands of its
lesser-known competitors _ the British Postal Service, Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone and, especially, ITT _ deserves a wide and
retentive audience. The tendency of successful corporations to
overlook major innovations in rival technologies is well-known:
Kodak spurning Xerox, for example. Competition ordinarily finds a
way around stubborn conventional wisdom in due course.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens when the technological system is so dominant
that there is no effective way to offer an alternative to the
public? On these rare occasions, government must take a hand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
