<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CABLE-INTERNET-HACKER     08-13 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-INTERNET-HACKER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High-speed Net services enticing targets for hackers
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At first, Helene Jaillet thought it was a
glitch. She ignored it.
</P>
<P>
   Then the problem came up again. When she logged off her home
computer, her Windows software told her multiple people were logged
in. At one point, 20 ``users'' were poking around in her system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually caught somebody,'' said Jaillet, a graduate student
at the University of Texas. ``I went back and traced who the
Internet service provider was and I called them.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a growing number of home Internet users, Jaillet recently
jumped on to faster Internet service using one of Time Warner
Cable's Road Runner cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   But as she found out, higher speeds and 24-hour connectivity
come with a price: Users of so-called broadband services such as
cable and digital subscriber lines, or DSLs, are more vulnerable to
attacks from hackers than users who connect with traditional
dial-up modems.
</P>
<P>
   As broadband service continues to take off _ research group
Dataquest Inc. predicts 2.8 million cable and DSL modems will be
shipped this year _ a crisis in home security could be coming, some
say.
</P>
<P>
   The way hackers often worm their way into broadband service
systems is to use software that scans service providers' networks
for open ports _ an open port allows them to infiltrate a computer
system and have access to files, folders and applications on a
user's computer.
</P>
<P>
   Higher-speed Internet access offers hackers two advantages _ if
a user's Internet connection is constantly active, it makes finding
an open port an easier target. And the faster speeds make it easier
for them to get in and out of a system quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hackers out there that want to find an open port are going to
be looking for the faster access services,'' said Steve Farabee,
director of digital online services for Time Warner. ``It's kind of
like if you live in a nicer neighborhood, you're more likely to
have the burglars come to your place.''
</P>
<P>
   Road Runner, which has several thousand users, runs scans of its
own network twice a month in an attempt to detect hackers. The
company said it is trying to find software it will sell to its
customers for extra protection, Farabee said, but until that is
available, Road Runner users are on their own. He said users are
expected to take their own security measures, including setting up
passwords and seeking out information on security.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sticky area,'' Farabee said. ``We don't want to take
responsibility for a customer's security. We try to point them in
the right direction and give them some general pointers on what
they should do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaillet said she found that out the hard way when she tried to
call Road Runner's abuse line. She said she was told keeping
hackers out was her problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their attitude was that it was a buyer beware market, and it's
essentially my problem,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jaillet was advised to set up a firewall for her home network _
the computers she and her husband have linked together to share
Road Runner service. A firewall, widely used by companies on the
Internet, is software that purports to keep hackers out of a local
network while still allowing users to be connected to the Net.
</P>
<P>
   While Jaillet said she knows about firewalls, many other
computer users don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a lot of people that just bought their computer
three weeks ago and they have no clue what's going on,'' she said.
Dewey Coffman, vice president of marketing for Jump.Net, said his
company takes a hands-off approach to firewalls and security
software for its users.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our customers are sophisticated users _ they know how
to protect their information,'' he said. Some Jump.Net customers
use modems with tighter encryption or set up their own firewalls,
Coffman said.
</P>
<P>
   But even with firewalls and the latest security software, home
users may not be safe, said John Dickson, a marketing manager for
San Antonio-based SecureLogic Corp. Dickson, whose company
specializes in Internet security, said personal firewall technology
is weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a reason to be very afraid,'' Dickson said. ``At the
personal and small office level, there's going to be some lessons
to be learned. All of us are looking at this as being a huge, huge
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet provider Texas.Net says unlike other DSL companies, it
has a firewall built into all of its user networks.
</P>
<P>
   Jonah Yokubaitis, one of Texas.Net's founders, claims that so
far his company hasn't had a single hacker penetrate its firewall,
which was developed by Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it's a good business practice and saves us a lot of
headaches in the long run,'', Yokubaitis said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
