<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AMERICAN-VACATION-ART     08-13 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-VACATION-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POINT OF VACATION TAKES A REST IN A TECHNOLOGICAL WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to append art note)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(EDS: Spelling of `Aron' in 2nd graf is correct; spelling of
`Halttunen' in 5th graf is correct.) 
(yn) 
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time the rich played when the mood struck, and
almost everyone else worked their farms and confined relaxation to
the Sabbath. Although August is now established as prime vacation
time, few Americans realize that their treasured paid vacation is a
fairly recent phenomenon. The very concept reflects ever-changing
American ideas about work, leisure and the markers of middle-class
status.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have vacations without a certain kind of class with
the resources and the time to take vacations,'' said Cindy S. Aron,
an associate professor of history at the University of Virginia.
``That doesn't really happen in the United States until the first
half of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   The popular vacation owes its birth to such factors as the
changing nature of work and the rise of the railroad. Ms. Aron, the
author of ``Working at Play: A History of Vacations in the United
States'' (Oxford University Press, 1999), explained that as the
19th century drew to a close, more men became salaried employees in
the growing corporate world. Before then, most Americans were
farmers, artisans or self-employed in some capacity. Wealthy people
_ like the South Carolina planters who sailed up the coast to
Newport, R.I. _ went off to play; others ``went away'' primarily
for their health.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a culturally sanctioned, institutionalized break
from work made sense only as the nation was transformed from an
agricultural into an urban-industrial society _ with workers who
had benefits _ and a transportation network developed to move
people about. A new middle class with a few dollars in its pockets
and a taste for amusement allowed vacation places to take shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason scholars have gotten so interested in vacation is
because vacation says so much about work,'' said Karen Halttunen, a
professor of history at the University of California at Davis. She
says an increasingly frenzied consumer culture is blurring the
lines between work and leisure and changing the nature of
vacations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vacations were born in the industrial revolution, when the
pressure of industry time discipline _ working by the clock _ meant
we started separating work from life,'' Ms. Halttunen said. People
started dividing life into ``after work,'' she said, and weekends,
vacation and retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think modern life has whittled away at all of those and has
ended the demarcation between work and life set up by the
industrial revolution,'' she said. Technology has helped obscure
the line with cellular telephones, fax machines, e-mail and the
Internet, which make people always available.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Aron argues in her book that however captive to work people
may be while on vacation now, it originated as a benefit and then
became a marker of middle-class status. Thus, as an idea, it
changed from the prerogative of an elite in the early 19th century
to a mass phenomenon right before World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The term vacation did not even enter the lexicon until the
middle of the last century as journalists, physicians and religious
leaders began to ponder the concept of leisure. They wrestled with
the Puritan notion that amusements were either inherently wanton or
fraught with the dangers of dissipation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working at Play'' quotes The New Englander, a
Congregationalist publication, as saying in 1851: ``A recreation .
. . is something which recruits, restores and prepares the man for
better service and should be engaged in, always, with this end in
view.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ms. Aron writes, ``vacation resorts themselves
became sites of change _ creating environments in which vacationers
not only could enjoy new sorts of pleasures but could also
experiment with new, often less restricted rules of conduct and
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Aron documents how roles for women were relaxed at resorts
where they engaged in sports previously reserved for men, swam in
scanty clothes and walked about freely. Married people engaged in
flirtations, and class distinctions were dropped as vacationers
donned the more democratic garb of leisure.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy, however, was not the only coin of the vacation realm.
The campgrounds, resorts and other playgrounds became segregated by
class, race and religion. Jews and blacks faced exclusion from many
vacation places and began to establish their own. The Catskills,
for example, began to attract large numbers of Jews. Blacks
established and began flocking to places like Oak Bluffs in
Martha's Vineyard and Idlewild, a resort in northern Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many stories the story of vacation can tell,''
Ms. Aron said. Americans get more paid vacations today than they
did a decade ago, but historians like Roy Rosenzweig, a professor
of history at George Mason University in Virginia, see a trend
toward more frequent but shorter vacations, with the cellular
telephone and the computer going along to stay in touch with the
office. Some historians say it betrays American anxiety about
working hard enough to do more, buy more and be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The argument that Americans don't relax enough or have enough
fun is an old charge or a canard,'' counters Neil Harris, a
cultural historian who is a professor of history at the University
of Chicago. ``By the late 19th century there are psychologists
making the point that play is a good thing, that society is too
highly pressured.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE; OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several developments have altered the traditional vacation,
Harris said, like the use of television for entertainment; the rise
of the two-career family; the geographical dispersal of extended
families.
</P>
<P>
   Dual career families, obviously, mean that two date books have
to be consulted in scheduling time off. And because families are
far-flung, the family reunion often now means traveling somewhere
and getting together as a form of vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk about vacation as an instrument of leisure, how do
you fit in TV, which is a form of leisure, no matter how passive,''
Harris said. ``What time does TV replace? It may increase the
desire for more physically active vacations.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Halttunen says that how people fit technology like
television and the Internet into their lives reflects not so much
the influence of that technology as cultural and psychic needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is that we are an advanced consumer culture in
which people are chronically dissatisfied with what we have,'' she
said. ``So we work harder to get the wherewithal to make those
consumer purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The very concept of the career is getting more widespread,''
Ms. Halttunen continued. ``Once, doctors and lawyers had careers.
Now secretaries have careers and blue-collar workers have careers.
Secretaries take work home.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, the vacation has become something that one buys,
Ms. Halttunen argues, and increasingly _ and paradoxically _ people
rely on it both to relax from the career conveyer belt and to
further their own or their children's development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a work ethic run amok,'' Ms. Halttunen said. ``
You can't just sit on the the porch anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
