<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-OBIT-BUBIS-NYT &LR;      08-13 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BUBIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IGNATZ BUBIS, HOLOCAUST SURVIVOR AND POST-WAR LEADER, DIES AT 72  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Poland)   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Ignatz Bubis, who survived the Holocaust
and led Germany's small post-war Jewish community for nearly two
decades, died in a hospital here Friday. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Bubis' death was announced in a brief statement by the Central
Council for German Jews, which did not list the cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   A former businessman with a knack for getting along with many
kinds of people, he became revered as voice of reconciliation as
well as one who campaigned passionately for Germany's residual
Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, as a new generation of more confident and less
angst-ridden Germans came to maturity, Bubis became alarmed that
the country was sliding into forgetfulness and even nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Bubis became outraged last year when one of Germany's most
prominent writers, Martin Walser, argued that shame about the
Holocaust should not be ``exploited for present purposes'' and that
Auschwitz should not become a ``moral cudgel.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Walser's comments were nuanced, Bubis pounced on them as
``moral arson,'' and as the most dramatic example yet of Germany's
drift toward what he saw as an ominous ``intellectual
nationalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1927 in Breslau, Germany, now Wroclaw, Poland, Bubis and
his family fled from advancing Germans when he was eight years old.
They were later captured and sent to camps as forced laborers. His
father, brother and sister all died in the camps. His mother died
of cancer in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Bubis later described his survival as essentially a matter of
chance, and he remained devout to the memories of that time for the
rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the vast majority of other surviving Jews, Bubis decided
to live in Germany and settled in Frankfurt in 1956. Asked recently
why he had returned to Germany, after his release from the camp in
Poland, he remarked that Germany was the closest thing to a home
that he had.
</P>
<P>
   As West Germany began to enjoy a sustained economic boom in the
1950s, Bubis started up businesses trading jewelry and precious
metals in Frankfurt. He then went into the real-estate business in
the 1970s, developing high-rise office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   As a real estate developer in Frankfurt, Bubis clashed
repeatedly with Germany's left-wing and environmental groups, who
wanted more land preserved for ordinary housing and denounced him
as an unscrupulous speculator.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bubis' critics at the time was Joschka Fischer, a founding
member of the German Green Party who is now Germany's foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Bubis, who became president of the Central Council of Jews in
Germany in 1983, later achieved more amicable relations with
Fischer and other erstwhile activists who became less hostile to
business over the years.
</P>
<P>
   With his background as a businessman and his political clashes
as a real estate developer, Bubis became a politician in the small,
right-of-center Free Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Free Democrats campaigned against government regulation and
greater freedom for business, but they also supported stronger
citizenship rights for immigrant workers-both themes that appealed
to Bubis.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Free Democrats, he became a locally-elected
representative in the Frankfurt city government.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the German Jewish community, Bubis spoke out
repeatedly for the need to remember the horror of the Holocaust and
fought any tendencies to dismiss it as mere history.
</P>
<P>
   He became popular in Germany as a moderate figure who sought to
bridge the divide between Jews and non-Jews, but was also
discouraged at his progress. In an interview with Stern magazine
last month, Bubis said he felt he had accomplished ``nearly
nothing'' in his seven years as the chairman of the Central Council
of Jews in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do away with these divisions _ here Germans, there
Jews,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the years-long political debate about
building a memorial to the Holocaust in Berlin, Bubis remarked that
a memorial in Berlin as such was perhaps less important than
preserving and expanding memorials at actual sites of the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Bubis was a central player in the recent battles over forcing
German banks and industrial corporations to compensate Holocaust
victims whose property was stolen or who were forced into slave
labor during the war.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he heaped scorn on American class-action
lawyers who began filing lawsuits in the United States on behalf of
survivors. Accusing the lawyers of using the Holocaust to generate
big fees for themselves, he vowed at one point last year that he
would never sit down them.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Bubis' death evoked sadness from a remarkable swath of
German leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a great loss not just for the Jewish community but for
all of Germany,'' said Wolfgang Gerhardt, head of the Free
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Gregor Gysi, head of the Party for Democratic Socialism, the
successor to East Germany's old Communist Party, praised Bubis as
singular voice for tolerance and pluralism.
</P>
<P>
   ``His efforts against every form of racism and hostility to
foreigners must become a requirement for us,'' said Gysi. ``He had
the capacity for integration, for principled argument and for
tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Bubis is survived by his wife, Ida, and daughter, Naomi.
</P>
<P>
   In the Stern interview, he said he had decided to be buried in
Israel, because he feared that his grave would be desecrated, like
the gravestone of his predecessor at the Central Council, Heinz
Galinski, which was destroyed by a bomb in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
