<HEADER>
A6690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECHNO-FILE14-COX     08-13 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-FILE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Instant messaging can be stifling
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If you've ``instant messaged'' before, perhaps
using software such as America Online's Instant Messenger, you
understand the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Instant messaging lets you zap a quick message directly to
someone else's computer, provided they're using the same software
and are accepting messages at the time. Once they receive that
message, they can zap a message back, and then you've got your own
mini-chat room, making instant messaging more immediate and
personal than standard e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   If sending an e-mail is the online equivalent of a letter,
instant messaging is an Internet phone call.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly innocuous in nature, instant messaging has become no
less than a battle of good vs. evil between Internet titans
Microsoft Corp. and America Online Inc. And, this time _ depending
what you think of open information on the Internet _ Microsoft may
not be the bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   The fight started last month when a new version of Microsoft's
instant message software, MSN Messenger, was released. The new
version included a feature allowing users to message users of AOL's
Instant Messenger. Feeling that Bill Gates and Co. were
gatecrashing, AOL blocked access of MSN Messenger, effectively
rendering the new feature useless.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft shot back publicly, accusing AOL of failing to support
an open set of standards for instant messaging. For its own part,
Microsoft has never gone out of its way to share the secrets of
Windows with other developers, so, it's not surprising that AOL
feels Microsoft wants open standards only when it suits its needs.
AOL began a push soon after, aligning itself with Earthlink
Network, Mindspring Enterprises and Juno Online Services to
distribute its Instant Messenger in favor of Microsoft's software.
</P>
<P>
   What this means for regular users, though, is a step back in
terms of usability. Because of the bickering between the two
companies, users won't have the flexibility of messaging someone
who happens to be using a different piece of software.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing's not an issue _ both instant messengers are distributed
free on the Internet. What each company wants is to have control
over what users see _ they want to be able to push advertising,
links to their own products, and most importantly, their brand name
on the messenger that you'll see every time you send or receive a
message.
</P>
<P>
   AOL and Microsoft each say they want open standards and
interactivity _ but each is camping with its own group of policy
standards boards and neither seems willing to give up and join the
other.
</P>
<P>
   If you want an idea of what a mess this could turn into, think
about e-mail. What if every e-mail program used a different set of
standards and you could only e-mail people who used the same
program you use? That's what may happen if companies such as AOL
and Microsoft don't agree on way to open up the barriers to their
products.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company is completely in the right here _ Microsoft
could be seen as a poacher trying to piggyback on AOL's popular
product while AOL is being criticized for blocking users from its
database.
</P>
<P>
   As this continues, instant messaging continues to be seen as a
fringe application _ messenger programs such as AOL's and the
popular ICQ are handy, but they have been slow to evolve. The
future of instant messaging could be bright. We could see
messengers that make it easier to share files like photos or
documents or to extend a chat into a video conference. A sleeker
application than e-mail, it may be a good substitute in non-desktop
devices like personal digital assistants, set-top box Internet
terminals and digital phones.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these applications are already available, but until
instant messengers can talk to one another in the same standard
language, we won't see these technologies truly blossom and users
will continue to be fragmented into isolated instant messaging
camps.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
