<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6696 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-AUTO-INSURE-BOS &LR;      08-13 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-AUTO-INSURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO INSURERS SEEK 7.8%   RATE INCREASE FOR 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts' auto insurance industry have asked
regulators to approve a 7.8 percent rate increase for next year,
hoping they will get for the first time in five years a significant
increase in premiums.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the average auto premium would rise $69. But
insurance rates in Massachusetts, while still among the top 10
nationwide, have dropped in four of the last five years. Last year,
the industry ended up with only a .7 percent increase after asking
for a 15.5 percent increase. The current average premium is $887 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   While the industry's initial rate request is usually viewed by
state regulators and consumer advocates as a strategic high-end
bargaining position, an industry spokesman insisted this year's
number should be taken at face value.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Johnston, president of the Automobile Insurers Bureau of
Massachusetts, which represents the 42 auto insurers in this state,
said escalating expenses, from salaries and rent to computer costs
and taxes, explain why the industry deserves this increase for the
year 2000. He said his group will present state regulators with
volumes of documents and statistics to justify its request.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said the industry has been dealt so many setbacks by
state regulators in recent years that he worries about companies
fleeing the Massachusetts market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not in a crisis stage yet, but we will soon be there if
prices charged for auto insurance continue to be set below expected
costs and with unrealistic economic wizardry as a foundation,'' he
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After four months of review with state regulators, Insurance
Commissioner Linda Ruthardt is expected to issue a final decision
by December.
</P>
<P>
   Deirdre Cummings, consumer program director for the
Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group, said she has yet to
review any information to justify a nearly 8 percent rate increase.
She said she believes drivers of the state's 3.6 million insured
cars have reason to be optimistic that next year's auto insurance
bill will reflect a rate decrease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
