<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-XEDIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT TO BUY MAKER OF HIGH-SPEED NET EQUIPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing a Bay State shopping binge, Lucent Technologies
Friday announced plans to buy a maker of fast Internet
communications gear for about $250 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's deal with privately held Xedia Corp., an Acton, Mass.
company that employs 90 workers, is expected to bring its
Massachusetts employment roster to more than 9,200 and bolster its
position as apparently the state's 8th biggest private employer,
according to the most recent tally.
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old Xedia makes high-speed router devices that help
Internet service providers develop flexible, more easily expanded
networks. Its customers include MCI WorldCom, Sprint, and
Concentric Network.
</P>
<P>
   Xedia follows more than a half-dozen other Massachusetts
companies that have become part of Lucent through a series of
acquisitions and mergers over the last two years. Massachusetts now
ranks third behind New Jersey and Illinois in Lucent jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Sanford, president of Lucent's InterNetworking Systems
group, said taking over Xedia ``fills an important space in our
enterprise data networking portfolio with award-winning products
that are absolutely best-in-class.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent will tender 3.86 million shares of its stock for all
outstanding Xedia stock, worth $254 million at Friday's close on
the New York Stock Exchange. Lucent predicted it will close the
deal this autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Brooks, a telecommunications analyst with Aberdeen
Group, said, ``I think they got a great chunk of technology here.
I'm quite excited for both these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said she considers the price Lucent offered to be ``at
the high end of reasonable'' and reflects a sound strategy of not
waiting for ``fire-sale prices'' to add companies serving key
untapped markets for Lucent, the world's biggest telecommunications
provider.
</P>
<P>
   Xedia chairman Ashley Stephenson will become vice president and
chief technology officer with Lucent's Enterprise Wide Area Network
Systems group. Xedia president Robert Steinkrauss will become vice
president and general manager of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Among other recent Massachusetts deals over the last three
years, Lucent has added to its corporate stable Nexabit Networks of
Marlborough, Kenan Systems in Cambridge, Mass Media of Natick,
Prominet Corp. of Marlborough, Agile Newtorks of Boxborough and
1,200 Bay State employees of California-based Ascend
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's Massachusetts sites include the state's biggest
factory, in North Andover, where it employs 6,200 people
manufacturing fiber-optic networking products for transmitting
voice, data and images.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's last announced Massachusetts acquisition, a $99 million
bid in July for Sturbridge specialty fiber maker SpecTran, has been
challenged by shareholder lawsuits contending the $9-a-share price
is too low.
</P>
</TEXT>
