<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-STRAWVOTERS-HOW14-COX     08-13 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAWVOTERS-HOW14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The most meaningless meaningful poll in the country
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ It's county fair meets political convention. It's
part marketplace of ideas and part sideshow. It's the Iowa
Republican Straw Poll, this year's most meaningful meaningless
political event.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 15,000 people _ many whisked to Ames in buses paid
for by the presidential candidates _ are expected to pack a campus
coliseum today for an event whose importance is strictly in the
eyes of the beholders.
</P>
<P>
   And because the world press is making believe the make-believe
election matters, the candidates are playing it straight. Though
the straw poll has no official role in the nominating process _
it's merely a fund-raiser for the Iowa GOP _ the past week in Iowa
has looked like the week prior to the state's first-in-the-nation
caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference is that some of the candidates stumping
here this week will be gone by February's caucuses. And if today
doesn't go well for them, some could be gone by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it matters,'' said front-runner Gov. George W. Bush, who
has spent fewer days campaigning in Iowa than any of the other
straw-poll participants. ``It matters because it's part of the
nominating process.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Iowa caucuses, today's event will go further toward
determining who won't be president than who will be. Well-funded
candidates like Bush and wealthy publisher Steve Forbes are
expected to finish first and second because of their money and
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has rented about 90 buses to haul supporters here. Bush
has more than 100.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes spent all week in Iowa, crisscrossing the state in a
high-tech bus while his ads ran on TV. He paid for a 30-minute
infomercial that aired Thursdsay night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as a good milestone on the way to the caucuses next
year,'' said Forbes, who, like Bush, has spent more than $1 million
on the straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   And while he is convinced he has the message to move voters his
way, Forbes, like the other GOP contenders, is adding music to lure
Iowans out on the last summer Saturday before school starts in much
of the state. His campaign is paying for what it's calling ``the
biggest party in Iowa this year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we want to invite all of you to be our very special
guests,'' Forbes' aide Steve Grubbs said in his post-speech pitch
all week. ``This thing has gotten huge, and all of your favorites
from television are going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes party tent will feature singers Ronnie Millsap and
Debby Boone. The Bush rally site will feature singers Tracy Byrd,
Linda Davis and Emilio Navaira, as well as athletes Roger Staubach,
Nick Lowery, Sean Elliott and champion bass fisherman Johnny
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Today, when the concerts and rallies wind down this afternoon,
straw poll participants will move into Iowa State University's
coliseum for candidate speeches and voting. It costs $25 to get in,
but the candidates are picking up the tab for their supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll could be most significant for candidates
struggling to survive in the shadow of Bush's money and poll
numbers and Forbes' family fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, who has been campaigning
here for years, and ex-Vice President Dan Quayle could see their
White House dreams effectively snuffed out if they finish near the
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, whose campaign peaked the day it began and has
struggled since,
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is do or die for us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dole sounded a tad more concerned in an e-mail to
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do need to complete our plan by raising the last $5,000 of
our budget. Like our bus, the campaign needs the financial fuel to
complete its journey. Could you help me?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the further-right wing of the party, Pat Buchanan, Orrin
Hatch, Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes are waging an intramural battle
for credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Out of harm's way here today _ at least for now _ is Arizona
Sen. John McCain, a GOP presidential contender who called the event
a ``scam'' and is staying away.
</P>
<P>
   An Iowa Project 2000 poll completed last Monday, which showed
Bush way ahead of the pack at 37 percent, had Alexander in eighth
place with 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
