<SLUG> BC-BIZ-GOLF-CLUBS-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOLF COURSE OF THEIR OWN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Colo., Pa.)   (af)  
 By SASHA CAVENDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTUCKET, Mass. _ When H. Wayne Huizenga, the billionaire
founder of companies like Waste Management and Blockbuster
Entertainment, and other members of the nation's business elite
began jetting to this island in recent years, they flew into one
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Sankaty Head Golf Club, with the island's only 18-hole course
and members who have spent summers in Nantucket for years or
decades, closed its waiting list in 1994 with a backlog of at least
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   And so Huizenga, Roger S. Penske, Henry R. Kravis and others
jumped to join the new Nantucket Golf Club, which opened in April
1998. It is where John F. Welch of General Electric has played with
guests like Bill Gates and Warren E. Buffett.
</P>
<P>
   This Friday, President Clinton is expected to play. ``He's been
dying to do it since the day it opened,'' said Elizabeth Bagley,
his former ambassador to Portugal, who is holding a fund-raiser
here for Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said that the president would be in Martha's
Vineyard that day and that no trip to Nantucket had been announced.
</P>
<P>
   Memberships, which initially went for $250,000, were fully
subscribed before the summer of 1998 ended, even as the fee rose
past $300,000. Golf Magazine just named the new Nantucket club to
its list of the 100 best courses in the nation, and Golf Digest
named it the best new private course for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The clubs are both in Siasconset, known here as Sconset, at the
southeastern tip of the island. But the contrast between them
exemplifies the island's transformation from an understated haven
where the monied mixed comfortably with fishermen and farmers to a
theater for the display of Wall Street and corporate wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Sankaty Head, with the island's traditional, Yankee disdain for
status or rank, has long been the sort of place where
schoolteachers and corporate chiefs teed off one after the other.
Among the best golfers is a local sanitation worker.
Family-friendly, the club has a pool, tennis courts and bingo
nights.
</P>
<P>
   The Sankaty Head clubhouse, casual and comfortably worn,
maintains the same frugality that David Gray, a Detroit
businessman, intended when he founded the club in 1921. Shunning a
member's offer to buy a mantel clock for $150, he boasted of buying
one for $10 instead. None of the easy chairs cost more than $5.
</P>
<P>
   The initiation fee is $15,000 but would rise to $22,000 if
clubhouse renovations currently being discussed went ahead. For the
300 members with full golfing privileges, annual dues are $1,500.
In the off season, the course is open to the public for $550 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Nantucket Golf Club, by contrast, was first of all an
investment. In bidding for the land, Nelson Doubleday, a co-owner
of the New York Mets, and Jack Nicklaus lost out to a group led by
Frederick D. Green, a Colorado real estate developer who is now the
club's president.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the investors paid $8.25 million to buy 250 acres from
an old island family, the Coffins, and commissioned the designer
Rees Jones to lay the course out. While most golf courses are now
built as anchors for residential developments, the Nantucket Golf
Course stands alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we weren't here, there could be 140 houses instead,'' said
Charles Passios, the golf course manager. ``The golf course
preserves this open land, the moors, plant life, wildlife.''
</P>
<P>
   Open, that is, for its members, who pass through its guarded
gates to a clubhouse that, unlike Sankaty's, is not visible from
any public road. Attendants radio ahead so members' golf bags can
be set out for them.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of the members have no homes on Nantucket, and
some fly in and out the same day. Annual dues at the Nantucket Golf
Club are said to be $8,500, though the club will not confirm this
figure. There is no pool, nor are there tennis courts. There is
just golf.
</P>
<P>
   During the off season, the club shuts down. Like the island's
real estate, memberships are rising in value, and as some have
changed hands, the club has received a cut of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga, 61, is typical in his feelings about the new club.
``What I like most about the new Nantucket Golf Club is you feel
you could be in Ireland or Scotland,'' he said recently. ``The way
the course is laid out, the tall grasses, the weather and the
wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Wright, chief executive of NBC, his boss Welch and J.
Perry Ruddick, a former vice chairman of Smith Barney who is the
president of Sankaty Head, are among the 50 or so members of both
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are a few, though wealthy enough to play where
they want, who make a point of shunning the whole club scene.
Richard Mellon Scaife, the Pittsburgh billionaire, plays at the
public nine-hole course near the two private ones. With no
motorized golf carts and no caddies, the course costs $22 a round _
or $24 for those like Scaife who splurge on pull-carts for their
clubs. ``It's the best,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
