u a BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-13 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALAI LAMA TO LEAD HUNDREDS IN A SPIRITUAL INITIATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since he arrived in New York this week, the Dalai Lama has
maintained a busy intellectual schedule, devoted mainly to many
hours of public teachings.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he began three days of lectures at the Beacon
Theater on Broadway. And Sunday, he is to speak in Central Park's
East Meadow, where his theme will be training one's mind as a step
toward leading a virtuous life. The event, at 11 a.m., is free.
</P>
<P>
   But for some, the most spiritually powerful part of the Dalai
Lama's visit to the United States will take place farther afield,
in Indiana, beginning next week.
</P>
<P>
   It will come after the 64-year-old spiritual leader of Tibet
stops in Indianapolis on Monday, to receive an official greeting
from Gov. Frank O'Bannon and an interfaith group of clergy members.
The Dalai Lama goes from there to Indiana University in
Bloomington, where he will speak about ethics in the next
millennium, the subject of his new book.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also in Bloomington that the Dalai Lama will officiate
at a Kalachakra, a rite of spiritual initiation, and a highly
significant ceremony within Tibetan Buddhism. Its concepts come
from a sacred text nearly 1,000 years old, and these are discussed
in the ceremony by the officiating monk, in this case, the Dalai
Lama.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony takes place over the course of several days, and
hundreds, even thousands of people may participate. At the heart of
the experience is the goal of inner transformation for initiates.
But it is also intended, as a byproduct of that process, to help
bring peace to the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initiation mimics the process of being reborn and passing
through childhood,'' said P. Jeffrey Hopkins, a professor of
Tibetan and religious studies at the University of Virginia. But at
each stage, he added, the participants are being led to create
within themselves ``an altruistic and wise consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins served as the Dalai Lama's translator, for his speeches
and books, for a decade until 1989. He is also the author of an
English translation of the Dalai Lama's discourses of the ritual,
``Kalachakra Tantra'' (Wisdom Publications).
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings about internal peace as a way to bring peace to the
world,'' he said. Its effect, he added, is that ``one should
experience a dedication to the welfare of others, an expansion of
one's field of compassion and altruism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The more effective the initiation is,'' he said, ``the longer
and more efficacious the sense of altruism is that will come from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   What does the ritual look like?
</P>
<P>
   Timothy J. McNeill, Wisdom's publisher, has undergone it several
times. ``His Holiness is on the throne,'' McNeill said, referring
to the Dalai Lama. ``And you're sitting in the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of monks on stage with His Holiness,'' he
said. ``Off sort of facing His Holiness to the right is the
Kalachakra house, which is an elaborate structure.'' The key
element of the latter is a mandala, a complex, essentially circular
design, created out of colored sand over the course of several days
before the ceremony by Buddhist monks. In this case, the mandala
represents a palace, which initiates are asked to visualize, as
they are mentally guided through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the ceremony, you're sort of walked through,'' McNeill
said. ```Now you're at the north entrance to the palace.' You're
visualizing these various aspects of consciousness, or mind.''
</P>
<P>
   At the ceremony's end, in a vivid demonstration of the
impermanence of matter, the Dalai Lama goes over to the mandala
with a broom and sweeps it up. The sand is then placed in an urn,
McNeill said. ``And then he pours it into a body of water. That's
an important part of the closure of the ceremony.''
</P>
<P>
   McNeill described the overall experience as profound in its
impact on those who participate. ``From the initiator's point of
view, your mind is being changed, you're being blessed,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
