<HEADER>
A6723 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-EL-CENIZO-HNS &LR;      08-13 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EL-CENIZO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SE HABLA ESPANOL? BORDER CITY ADOPTS `SAFE HAVEN,' SPANISH-ONLY
ORDINANCES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL CENIZO, Texas _ Like so many communities along the Rio
Grande, this hardscrabble town on the river's edge seems to be
neither Mexico nor the United States, but some of both.
</P>
<P>
   So, local officials reasoned, why not conduct city government
meetings in Spanish, the language nearly everyone speaks? And why
not establish the town as a ``safe haven'' for illegal immigrants,
a nod to the traditional back and forth of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Last week El Cenizo's mayor and two city commissioners did just
that, establishing one ordinance that makes Spanish the town's
official language and another that forbids employees of El Cenizo _
there's only one _ from cooperating with the U.S. Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here so much to help illegal immigrants as we are to
help the people of El Cenizo,'' said Gloria Romo, a city
commissioner. ``Besides, the only true citizens are the American
Indians. Everyone else came from another country.''
</P>
<P>
   While municipal safe havens are by no means unprecedented in the
United States, there are few _ if any _ along the 2,000-mile
U.S.-Mexico border, which of late has been increasingly militarized
to turn back a steady stream of illegal traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially more explosive, however, is El Cenizo's
Spanish-language measure, believed to be the first of its kind in
the United States. Already English-only advocates are calling this
sun-beaten town of 7,500 just down river from Laredo, Texas, the
beginning of the end of a truly United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we've been predicting all along: the
Balkanization of America along linguistic lines,'' said Tim
Schultz, director of communications for U.S. English, a
Washington-based advocacy group. ``These people don't consider
English their first language. In fact they don't really consider
themselves American.''
</P>
<P>
   As volatile as both ordinances would seem to be in an era of
English-only measures and efforts to deny illegal immigrants access
to health care and public education, city leaders say their action
stems from practicality rather than politics.
</P>
<P>
   Because the city had been conducting its council meetings in
English, few residents attended, leaving local politics the domain
of the few. And while officials clearly sought tolerance for
illegal immigrants, they enacted their immigration measure largely
to dispel rumors that City Hall was behind a local Border Patrol
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Almost daily, Border Patrol agents descend upon this community
of vacant lots, trailers and mom-and-pop groceries, most frequently
stopping the bus that runs back and forth to Laredo. Almost
everyone has a story about being pulled aside by the men in green.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want everyone to know that we're not the ones calling
`la migra,''' said Flora Barton, a city commissioner, referring to
the Immigration and Naturalization Service in border lexicon.
</P>
<P>
   Locals are supportive.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Romero, a homemaker in El Cenizo, wants the Border Patrol
to stop bothering local residents ``who have children that go to
school and own their own land.'' As for the Spanish-language
measure, she said, ``If you speak English and Spanish and I speak
only Spanish, why not speak in Spanish?''
</P>
<P>
   The safe-haven ordinance forbids city employees from inquiring
into the immigration status of residents, a moot point since only
federal officials are authorized to do so. But the measure also
bars city employees from cooperating with the INS, under which the
Border Patrol operates.
</P>
<P>
   Such language potentially brings El Cenizo into conflict with a
federal law passed in 1996 that makes it illegal for state and
local governments to prohibit an employee from cooperating with
immigration officers. New York City, which adopted its own
safe-haven ordinance, challenged that law in court and lost.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials say they do not intend to challenge El
Cenizo's safe-haven measure, but they say they will go to court if
the city actively hinders the work of federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not seeking to establish an adversarial relationship,''
said Russ Bergeron, director of media relations for the INS. ``On
the other hand, a lawsuit becomes necessary if a conflict arises.''
</P>
<P>
   El Cenizo officials, who relied heavily on a local law school
student to craft their ordinance, seemed truly surprised that their
measure would generate so much controversy. Though Mayor Rafael
Rodriguez is not backing down, both commissioners seemed almost
apologetic about taking on the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be against the law,'' said Barton. ``If
somebody comes to me and says this is against the law, we'll amend
it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the language ordinance, the change in local law may have
been to assist the mayor as well as the town's residents. A U.S.
citizen who nonetheless came here illegally from Mexico years ago,
Rodriguez speaks no English.
</P>
<P>
   Still, El Cenizo is home to dozens here like the mayor. A former
colonia that sprang up on the edge of Laredo only to be
incorporated as a city 10 years ago, nearly all of its residents
are immigrants or the spouses or children of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Today the town has running water, electricity and paved roads,
conveniences that can't be taken for granted in the desperately
poor Tex-Mex borderlands.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say previous administrations took advantage of
the language barrier, conducting city business in English and
keeping the majority of residents clueless about municipal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rodriguez says, ``The idea is to communicate with the
people. When the meetings were in English, that didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the language measure, all city business, postings and
notices will be in Spanish, while ordinances will continue to be
written in English with translations available. Last Thursday, the
town held its first-ever city meeting in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration advocates applauded, saying that while the action
taken by El Cenizo underscores the growing political power of
Hispanics, it by no means undermines the nation-building process.
</P>
<P>
   But anti-illegal immigration groups see the borderlands slipping
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This portends what more and more communities are going to look
like,'' said John Keeley, director of communications for the
Federation for American Immigration Reform. ``This speaks to what
the trend will be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
