<SLUG> BC-IOWA-STRAWPOLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESULTS OF IOWA STRAW POLL WILL BREAK SOME GOP CANDIDATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ As Lamar Alexander tended to the pork chops
Friday at the Iowa State Fair, he was surrounded by television
cameras eager to catch the GOP presidential contender before
Saturday's Republican straw poll, a fund-raising event for the
state party that has evolved as a test of the candidates' strength.
</P>
<P>
   The event in Ames is assumed by many to be Alexander's last
stand in his battle to remain viable in a crowded field that
includes Texas Gov. George W. Bush, magazine mogul Steve Forbes,
former American Red Cross chief Elizabeth Dole, former Vice
President Dan Quayle and conservative activists Gary Bauer and Pat
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who campaigned across Iowa for the first time this week
Friday and who leads in statewide polls, has boasted he will win
the contest. And many observers believe Forbes, who has waged an
expensive and extensive campaign, will come in second or even best
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But it is anybody's guess how the rest of the field will stack
up at an event that is expected to draw as many as 15,000 hard-core
activists.
</P>
<P>
   While critics have derided the straw poll as a meaningless
barometer of political success, and a fund-raiser disguised as an
exercise in democracy, the conventional wisdom has been that those
candidates who do poorly will find it increasingly difficult to
raise the money necessary to remain competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The straw poll will not determine who the party's nominee will
be. But it will determine who it will not be,'' said Steve Grubbs,
the former chairman of the Iowa Republican Party, who is now
working for Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are particularly high for candidates such as
Alexander and Quayle, who are already struggling to raise money and
who have remained at the bottom of public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Despite spending more time in the state than any other
candidate, Alexander has had trouble competing against the
well-funded Bush and Forbes operations, which have been shelling
out hundreds of thousands of dollars to get their backers to the
straw poll. The Republican Party charges $25 a ticket for the
event, which entitles Iowa residents to vote for a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   While all the candidates have bought up tickets to distribute to
supporters, the Bush and Forbes campaigns could afford to do more
mailings to supporters and to provide extensive bus transportation
to get them to Ames. In addition, Forbes has been blitzing the
state with radio ads and is expected to host a half-hour call-in
infomercial Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is clearly miffed at these efforts, contending that
some candidates are substituting money for the kind of traditional
retail politics that he says will produce the party's superior
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes a better president? Coming to Iowa a hundred times
or raising a hundred million dollars?'' the former Tennessee
governor and U.S. education secretary asked. Alexander contended
that candidates such as Bush, who has raised $37 million, will be
unprepared to do battle with Democratic front-runner Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's he going to do in a debate with Gore? He gets a tough
question (and says) ... bring me my pile of money,'' Alexander
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush responded to such remarks by saying that while money helps,
it isn't everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't win elections with money alone. It requires message,
turnout and organization,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander has followed the traditional primary election formula,
returning to the state repeatedly after his failed 1996
presidential effort and building an organization filled with state
GOP leaders such as former Gov. Terry Branstad.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bush, who only announced in June that he was a
candidate, has only visited the state a handful of times. While
Forbes has tapped into his personal fortune to fund his campaign,
he has also been actively campaigning in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is clearly annoyed that he has not been rewarded for
playing by the rules. His comments are infused with barbs directed
at Bush and Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to his lack of presence in the state, Alexander
sarcastically remarked, ``Mr. Bush must have had an emergency
meeting with the Texas Legislature. He can't be here.``
</P>
<P>
   And commenting on the outcome of the straw poll, he said, ``In a
straw poll, money talks. So Mr. Bush and Mr. Forbes ought to be
arrested if they don't win tomorrow.``
</P>
<P>
   Although Alexander initially said he had to do well in the straw
poll to remain a candidate, he now says he must ``exceed
expectations'' set by the media.
</P>
<P>
   The other candidates were also doing some last-minute
campaigning in the state Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush arrived Friday evening at the Des Moines airport with his
confidence intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to go. Tomorrow is a day where we'll see how hard
I've worked and how hard our organization has worked,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush began Friday by meeting with about 30 Hispanics at
Jalepeno's Mexican Restaurant in Davenport, Iowa, though many of
those present were from nearby Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the group that he is ``working hard'' to make sure the
``Republican Party is welcoming new faces.'' He said he also wants
to make certain the American dream is for everybody, especially the
nation's children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're having a little trouble learning, maybe it's because
English isn't your first language, we're going to give you some
extra time, some extra focus, some extra help,'' Bush said. ``There
are no second-rate children and no second-rate dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ontiveros, a businessman from Milan, Ill., organized the
event. He said he had met with Bush's father once at the White
House as one of the nation's top 100 Hispanic businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Ontiveros said he was disappointed that many Democratic
Hispanics whom he invited to the breakfast refused to come because
he believed they would change their minds if they listened to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult getting people here because they are all
Democrats,'' Ontiveros said. ``But I know one person who is a very
active Democrat who was here today who said, 'Now, I've got to
think about this.'''
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll event begins at 4:30 p.m. at the Hilton Coliseum
on the campus of Iowa State University. The eight participating
candidates will each give 10-minute speeches. And ticket holders,
who are Iowa residents, will be allowed to vote between 3 p.m. and
8:15 p.m. The results will be announced at 9 p.m. The speeches will
be broadcast live on C-SPAN.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser and straw poll has come under increasing
criticism this year for turning into too much of a carnival, with
candidates competing to see who can persuade voters with the most
lavish food spreads and high powered celebrities in the hours
leading up to the voting.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign is boasting that it will have an
air-conditioned tent near the coliseum where people can hear
entertainers such as Christian singer Debbie Boone.
</P>
<P>
   Bush clearly hopes that a parade of current and former
professional jocks such as ex-Dallas Cowboys quarterback Roger
Staubach and former University of Iowa football coach Hayden Fry,
will motivate his supporters. The governor is also hosting a skeet
shooting event with the 1998 Olympic skeet shooting gold medalist
Kim Rhode.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
