<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DALAI-LAMA-ART-2TAKES     08-13 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALAI-LAMA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDDHIST LEADER PROJECTS OPTIMISM BUT WARNS AGAINST LOFTY
EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-DALAI-LAMA) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dalai Lama, 14th in a line of spiritual leaders
of Tibet stretching back 600 years, was in the midst of responding
to a reporter's question about Buddhism's growing popularity in the
West when he paused to poke a little fun at the expectations that
people can place on him.
</P>
<P>
   He had given a public talk in England, he said, and told his
audience that those who had come out of curiosity would be fine,
but those who had ``great expectations'' might be disappointed. As
for those who expected him to perform miracles or healings, the
Dalai Lama told them such beliefs were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, if there's a genuine healer there, then I need
one,'' he said, gesturing at the back of his neck, as if to
indicate soreness or stiffness. He laughed in delight at the
recollection, a full, open laugh that seemed to invite all around
to join in.
</P>
<P>
   It was a disarmingly friendly and modest moment that those who
know him say is typical of a man who has spent 40 years in exile
from his homeland, who is intensely aware of the political and
religious repression of 6 million Tibetans living there, yet who
speaks with immense seriousness of the need for compassion and
reconciliation among all people.
</P>
<P>
   His message is both simple and compelling, one that offers hope
on both individual and societal levels. And that may be what is
proving so attractive about him to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama arrived in New York on Wednesday to give a series
of teachings, one of which, Sunday at 11 a.m. in Central Park's
East Meadow, will be free and open to the public. Although he has
visited the United States often since he first came here 20 years
ago, he has probably never been so widely recognized nor so admired
here as now.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, for example, people have called the offices of
Tricycle magazine, a Manhattan quarterly that focuses on Buddhism
in America, seeking information on how to see the Dalai Lama. James
Shaheen, the magazine's publisher, said, ``There are people who
call who genuinely say, `I'm going to learn something that's going
to help my life be more peaceful.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is something compelling to Americans about
nonviolence,'' Shaheen said. ``We live in a very violent society
and a lot of us want relief.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama has a book, ``The Art of Happiness'' (Riverhead),
on the best-seller lists. Another, ``Ethics for a New Millennium''
(Riverhead), hit the bookstores last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the latter, he offers his ideas about a universal ethic for
living that depends on common sense rather than religious
tradition. He writes that ``establishing binding ethical principles
is possible when we take as our starting point the observation that
we all desire happiness and wish to avoid suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   P. Jeffrey Hopkins, a professor of Tibetan and religious studies
at the University of Virginia, said that part of the Dalai Lama's
appeal is the accessibility of what he teaches. ``I think that he
worked very hard to fashion a message not just for Buddhists, and
not just for religious people, but for all people,'' said Hopkins,
who served as the Dalai Lama's translator for his speeches and
books for a decade, until 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the teaching, the Dalai Lama possesses an unusual
ability to make personal his encounters with people, Hopkins said.
``It's as if he's looking at and contacting your feeling,'' he
said. ``He's qualitatively different in a very common way _ not in
an impossible, transcendent way, except you get the feeling, this
is what transcendence is.''
</P>
<P>
   Another person who has met him often, the Rev. Joan Brown
Campbell, general secretary of the National Council of Churches,
said, ``There's a certain resoluteness and clarity about who he is,
and that has a certain appeal in a time when leadership is so
questioned.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in an East Side hotel suite, the Dalai Lama sat
cross-legged on the seat of an armchair, wearing the maroon and
yellow robes of a Tibetan Buddhist monk. He spoke in English,
occasionally consulting with a translator who sat nearby. Although
he had agreed to the meeting only two hours earlier, shoehorning it
into what aides described as a packed schedule, he never once
turned his wrist to glance at his watch. Nor did he seem in any
hurry to bring things to a close.
</P>
<P>
   At 64, he is regarded by many Americans as a sort of Buddhist
equivalent to the Roman Catholic pope. But among Tibetans, he is
the living embodiment of the bodhisattva (enlightened being) of
compassion, and the reincarnation of his predecessor Dalai Lamas.
Enthroned in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa in 1940 at age 4, he has
lived in Dharamsala, India, head of a government in exile since
1959.
</P>
<P>
   On a secular level, he was honored for his commitment to
nonviolence with the Nobel Peace Prize in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhism, in all its varieties, has been growing in public
acceptance and in the number of its practitioners in the United
States since the Dalai Lama first visited two decades ago. ``The
Complete Guide to Buddhist America'' (Shambala, 1998), a book for
which the Dalai Lama wrote the preface, reports that the number of
Buddhist meditation centers nationwide more than doubled from 1987
to 1997, to more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   What has helped its acceptance may be the increasing
articulation of Buddhism as a socially concerned force. ``These are
developments in Buddhism itself which make it a comfortable
dialogue partner for us and possibly a refuge,'' said Christopher
Queen, dean of students for Continuing Education and also a
lecturer on the study of religion at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   One measure of how the faith is viewed comes from the experience
of Nicholas Vreeland, director of the Tibet Center in New York, who
recently returned to this country after spending 14 years in a
Tibetan Buddhist monastery in south India. In the early 1980s, when
he appeared in his monk's robes, passers-by looked at him askance,
he said. ``Walking around 14 years ago in these robes and walking
around today is a totally different experience,'' he said. ``I feel
people support me.''
</P>
<P>
   But when asked about Buddhism's growing popularity here, the
Dalai Lama struck no note of triumphalism.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhism as a path toward wisdom and inner calm, founded in the
2,500-year-old teachings of Siddhartha Guatama, the Buddha, has
attracted people seeking to deepen capacities for compassion and
forgiveness, he said. ``To some people, the Buddhist way of
approach is a more analytical way, more rational'' approach to that
end, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But others may be drawn to it because it is new in the United
States and human nature loves novelty, he said. ``And, of course,
there might be some who have maybe wrong impressions of Buddhism,''
thinking meditation can quickly lead to ``instant enlightenment,''
he said. ``That's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama also quoted from the late Cardinal Basil Hume,
the Roman Catholic archbishop in Britain, that an interest in
spirituality is rising in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Similarly, the interest toward inner values is increasing,''
he said. People have lots of material goods, but are not happy, he
said. ``People begin to realize that material facility alone is not
the full answer for life. That's my impression.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, Buddhism offers a practical prescription for living, a
spirituality based on obtaining peace and purpose, rather than
expectation of an afterlife. In elaborating the Four Noble Truths,
the Buddha taught that life contains suffering, but that there is a
way out, that wisdom and peace can be achieved through a change of
attitude and behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The actor Richard Gere, who has known the Dalai Lama for two
decades, said that after previously studying Japanese-style Zen
Buddhism, he found in Tibetan Buddhism a more intellectual approach
to attaining spiritual wisdom and also a greater emphasis on
achieving compassion.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of Tibet, the Dalai Lama advocates what he calls
the ``middle way'' seeking self-government within China that would
preserve Tibet's spiritual heritage and permit respect for human
rights and democratic freedoms. He has called for protection of
Tibet's natural environment and for an end to the ``transfer'' of
large numbers of Chinese into Tibet, through which Tibetans have
become a minority in their own land.
</P>
<P>
   But these are grim times. As of last fall, he said, the Chinese
government had cut off informal contact with him, and repression of
Tibetan life and religion has become harsher. At same time, he
said, younger Tibetans are becoming more impatient.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, he said, there is ``almost no hope'' for the
solution he envisions. ``But in the long run, I'm optimistic,'' he
said. ``The main reason is, the current situation of Tibet for the
Chinese government policy is neither good for Tibetans nor for the
Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese government, their top priority is stability and
unity,'' the Dalai Lama said. ``The current policy is actually
counterproductive in that respect. So I believe my middle approach
is the way to achieve genuine stability and stability.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama has pursued a nonviolent approach for 40 years,
ever since he and about 100,000 other Tibetans fled before the
Chinese army. That period has been longer than other historic,
nonviolent campaigns, like the mass movements for India's
independence and civil rights for African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really true nonviolence of the mind, which is true
spirituality, it takes a long time,'' said Gere. ``But the promise
of this approach is, once it is done, it is complete,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6754 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OLY-REPORT14-COX     08-13 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-REPORT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report to Congress on Olympic bid to be late
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ King &AMP; Spalding attorney Griffin Bell's report to
Congress on the Atlanta Olympic bid may not be ready until
lawmakers return to work after the August recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm planning on this being the last report,'' Bell, a former
U.S. attorney general, said Friday while indicating that he
intended for his revised account of Atlanta's bid tactics to be as
thorough and accurate as possible.
</P>
<P>
   A previous report signed by Billy Payne and Andrew Young, who
spearheaded the bid, contained discrepancies with what
congressional investigators uncovered in Atlanta records.
</P>
<P>
   The insufficient report prompted Bell, whose firm has handled
the Atlanta Olympic group's legal affairs since its inception, to
ask permission to amend it.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House Commerce Committee's subcommittee on oversight
and investigations, which is looking for possible violations of
federal bribery laws in the bid, granted Bell's request. Initially,
Bell indicated he might have his supplemental report ready by the
end of this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not finished the document search,'' he said Friday.
``We've looked at a lot of boxes, and we're almost finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell requested that Atlanta Olympic officials ship 30 boxes of
documents to King &AMP; Spalding's office in Washington for inspection
by his corporate internal investigations unit, which has taken over
responsibility for the congressional inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Eight additional boxes of documents, which Payne and Young say
contain personal papers and private fund-raising data, already had
been sent to the Washington office.
</P>
<P>
   After inspecting records in these and other boxes, investigators
said they found unreported evidence of scholarships, excessive
travel and expensive gifts for International Olympic Committee
members and their families.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Committee is trying to determine if the IOC should
be subject to the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Salt Lake City Olympic bribery scandal,
lawmakers raised questions about whether other bidding cities also
used improper inducements to secure the Games.
</P>
<P>
   In its earlier report, Atlanta Olympic officials disclosed three
dozen personal gifts for IOC members that violated a $200 limit,
athletic training funds for several African teens and a $25,000
donation to a South African anti-apartheid group.
</P>
<P>
   Bid officials have said they did not give scholarships, one of
the more serious infractions cited in the Salt Lake scandal.
</P>
<P>
   However, they acknowledge now to have discussed possible
scholarships with many IOC members and placing phone calls to
universities on behalf of the members' relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those calls are believed to have resulted in
relatives attending college in the United States. However, Atlanta
officials say they never financed the scholarships and thus felt it
unnecessary to include these efforts in their original report to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   They also acknowledge providing some members and their families
excursions to Disney World in Florida, golf outings in Augusta and
visits to Savannah and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   All of these trips, they contend, were essential to the bid,
which Bell is expected to spell out in his report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
