<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-REPORT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report to Congress on Olympic bid to be late
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ King &AMP; Spalding attorney Griffin Bell's report to
Congress on the Atlanta Olympic bid may not be ready until
lawmakers return to work after the August recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm planning on this being the last report,'' Bell, a former
U.S. attorney general, said Friday while indicating that he
intended for his revised account of Atlanta's bid tactics to be as
thorough and accurate as possible.
</P>
<P>
   A previous report signed by Billy Payne and Andrew Young, who
spearheaded the bid, contained discrepancies with what
congressional investigators uncovered in Atlanta records.
</P>
<P>
   The insufficient report prompted Bell, whose firm has handled
the Atlanta Olympic group's legal affairs since its inception, to
ask permission to amend it.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House Commerce Committee's subcommittee on oversight
and investigations, which is looking for possible violations of
federal bribery laws in the bid, granted Bell's request. Initially,
Bell indicated he might have his supplemental report ready by the
end of this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not finished the document search,'' he said Friday.
``We've looked at a lot of boxes, and we're almost finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell requested that Atlanta Olympic officials ship 30 boxes of
documents to King &AMP; Spalding's office in Washington for inspection
by his corporate internal investigations unit, which has taken over
responsibility for the congressional inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Eight additional boxes of documents, which Payne and Young say
contain personal papers and private fund-raising data, already had
been sent to the Washington office.
</P>
<P>
   After inspecting records in these and other boxes, investigators
said they found unreported evidence of scholarships, excessive
travel and expensive gifts for International Olympic Committee
members and their families.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Committee is trying to determine if the IOC should
be subject to the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Salt Lake City Olympic bribery scandal,
lawmakers raised questions about whether other bidding cities also
used improper inducements to secure the Games.
</P>
<P>
   In its earlier report, Atlanta Olympic officials disclosed three
dozen personal gifts for IOC members that violated a $200 limit,
athletic training funds for several African teens and a $25,000
donation to a South African anti-apartheid group.
</P>
<P>
   Bid officials have said they did not give scholarships, one of
the more serious infractions cited in the Salt Lake scandal.
</P>
<P>
   However, they acknowledge now to have discussed possible
scholarships with many IOC members and placing phone calls to
universities on behalf of the members' relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those calls are believed to have resulted in
relatives attending college in the United States. However, Atlanta
officials say they never financed the scholarships and thus felt it
unnecessary to include these efforts in their original report to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   They also acknowledge providing some members and their families
excursions to Disney World in Florida, golf outings in Augusta and
visits to Savannah and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   All of these trips, they contend, were essential to the bid,
which Bell is expected to spell out in his report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
