<HEADER>
A6756 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-GOLAN-HEIGHTS-     08-13 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GOLAN-HEIGHTS-$ADV15-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLAN HEIGHTS RESIDENTS FRETTING ABOUT HAND-OVER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds. For release Sunday, Aug. 15) 
 
By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIBBUTZ AFIK, Golan Heights _ It's dusk when farmer Dennis Van
Meter drives his big white pickup to the eastern edge of his
avocado, mango and litchi orchard on this windswept plateau.
</P>
<P>
   He stops within a few feet of a barbed-wire fence, jumps down
from his truck, sinks his brown cowboy boots in the dirt, pops open
a beer and gestures to the green mountains and valleys in the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Syria,'' he says in the clear tones of a transplanted
Californian, pointing eastward as he adjusts the white baseball cap
that covers a head full of gray-blonde curls. ``And that,'' he
adds, gesturing to the southeast, ``is Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All this is mine,'' he says, turning toward the rows of litchi
trees that line this southern stretch of the Golan Heights.
``You've heard of the Garden of Eden? I call this the Garden of
Dennis. I planted it, and I'm not leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   When Israeli politicians talk about trading land for peace with
Syria, they mean the orchards Van Meter has spent 16 years of his
life planting.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ehud Barak became prime minister July 6, a new sense of
urgency is evident in the discussions about returning the Golan.
Within 15 months, Barak has said, he expects to reach a deal with
Syrian President Hafez el-Assad. That prospect has left the 17,000
Israeli settlers who have built their lives here feeling
bewildered, angry and betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My government invited me here,'' says an indignant Van Meter,
who bristles when referred to as a Jewish settler. ``When I told
them at the consulate in San Francisco that I wanted to move to the
Golan, they said, `Hey that's fantastic.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't suddenly tell us to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   To prevent what many Israelis whisper might be an inevitable
climb down from the heights, some of the Golan residents have
reignited a campaign to convince their countrymen that ceding this
strategic plateau to Syria would endanger Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigners are plastering the country with bumper stickers,
busing people in to see the value of the land their government
wants to trade for peace, and lobbying the Knesset, Israel's
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   They are also taking their campaign across the Atlantic Ocean to
try to convince the U.S. Congress that it would be costly and
harmful for the United States if Israel were to give up the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an in-your-face kind of campaign,'' said Van Meter's
wife, Marla, spokeswoman for the Golan Residents' Committee. ``I'm
going to the Knesset ... and saying, `Hi, I'm Marla. Hi, I'm Marla.
Hi, I'm Marla.'''
</P>
<P>
   These settlers say that if the time comes, they don't plan to go
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   They invoke the trauma of leaving Yamit, the Sinai settlement
uprooted in 1982 after Israel's 1979 peace treaty with Egypt. They
say they hope those ugly memories will keep Israelis from wanting
to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yamit was only 3,000 people,'' said Yuval Tidhar, a
37-year-old dairy farmer from the central Golan Heights. ``Here you
have 17,000 people. I can't imagine it happening, all these people
getting on the bus and going to another place. I'll resist.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as hard-core activists pursue their campaign, they are
being undercut by a growing number of their fellow Jews who say
they would be willing to leave their homes if the terms of the
agreement with Syria were good.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 60 percent of the Golan's residents voted for Barak last
May, despite his pre-election promise to put peacemaking with Syria
at the top of the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   And last month, the Kibbutz Artzi Movement, a tiny left-wing
organization that has some collective farms on the Golan Heights,
announced that its members would not be ``obstacles to peace'' with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Most settlers on the Golan Heights are left-wingers, people
brought up on the Marxist ideology of collective farms who
traditionally vote for Barak's center-left Labor Party or for
Meretz, a smaller left-wing party that believes in trading land for
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the West Bank settlers, Golan residents have not been
forced to confront the possibility of being uprooted until
recently.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Most Golan settlers say they feel torn between their liberal
politics and their desire to continue living on land they feel they
built into a productive place: The Golan Heights provides Israel
with 25 percent of its dairy products, 10 percent of its water, 33
percent of its beef and 50 percent of its apples.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very much in the middle, swinging from one side to the
other,'' said dairy farmer Mauricio Betsalel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a really bad idea to leave,'' said Betsalel, who
voted for the Meretz party despite its willingness to give up the
region. ``But if we have to leave, I'm not going to chain myself to
a tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Weary of the low-grade guerrilla war in southern Lebanon that
continues to kill or wound Israeli troops, most Israelis say they
believe moving off the Golan Heights is the only way to bring
peace. Until then, they believe, Syria will continue to help supply
the Hezbollah guerrillas fighting to drive the Israelis from a
swath of territory in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, 25 to 35 Israeli soldiers die in Lebanon, prompting
public calls to pull the troops out and increasing pressure on the
politicians to make peace with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   For many Golan residents like Van Meter, this logic is the
height of lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   For 16 years, he's been growing fruit here so close to the
border that sometimes he can see the silhouettes of unarmed Syrian
soldiers walking in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Never has he felt unsafe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we give this back,'' he asks. ``It's the quietest
border in the Middle East. This is what we call peace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
