u a BC-CARLSBAD-DEHYDRATE-BO     08-13 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARLSBAD-DEHYDRATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEHYDRATION DISORIENTS, BUT DOESN'T HURT, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Severe dehydration like that reportedly suffered by two
Massachusetts men, David Coughlin and Raffi Kodikian, last weekend
in New Mexico, can cause alterations in mental functioning,
including delirium, confusion, disorientation, seizures, difficulty
concentrating and even hallucinations, scientists and physicians
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unlikely to cause severe pain. Kodikian, 25, allegedly
told authorities he killed his 26 year-old traveling companion
because Coughlin begged for an end to his extreme pain from lack of
water in the desert, according to the criminal complaint on file in
court in Carlsbad, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   People who are severely dehydrated ``are very uncomfortable
because they're so thirsty,'' said Dr. Ronenn Roubenoff, associate
professor of medicine and nutrition at Tufts University. ``But I
wouldn't exactly call that pain. That is one of the things I don't
buy about this story, the business of the pain.'' It is possible
that dehydration could cause muscle cramps, especially in the legs,
and this could be painful ``but it would come and go. It wouldn't
be constant agony,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montain , a physiologist who studies fluid balance issues
at the US Army Research Institute of Environmental Medicine in
Natick, agrees that pain is not a typical problem in dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you begin to get dehydrated, you get thirsty. Then you get
vague discomforts. You don't feel good and you're not afraid to
express it. Then you get changes in mood _ you become more
impatient, but more prominently, you feel tired, apathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, as dehydration progresses, you get changes in speech _
it becomes more indistinct and slurred. You may stumble as you
walk. You have dizziness,'' he says. These symptoms often occur
when a person has lost about six percent of normal body mass
through dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Delirium, trouble staying awake and difficulty swallowing
usually occur when a person loses 10 percent of normal body mass,
Montain said.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico officials have said they found urine in Coughlin's
bladder. By itself, noted Roubenoff, that is not enough to
determine whether he was seriously dehydrated. The more important
question, he said, is how concentrated was the urine. If it was
diluted, that would indicate he was not dehydrated; if it was
concentrated, it would fit with evidence that he was.
</P>
<P>
   It is not always easy to determine precisely how dehydrated a
person is after death. But in a living person, a simple ``pinch''
test is often revealing _ if you pinch the skin into a little tent
and it holds that shape, the person is probably dehydrated. Other
signs are sunken eye sockets, dry-looking skin and difficulty
maintaining blood pressure upon standing up quickly.
</P>
<P>
   At least in living people, blood tests can help, too, by
determining the concentration of sodium in the blood. If the
concentration is high, that may indicate dehydration. But ``you can
be dehydrated with normal blood sodium or even low sodium, too,''
said Roubenoff.
</P>
<P>
   For people in normal situations, he added, the rule of thumb for
staying properly hydrated is to drink a half ounce of water a day
for every pound of body weight. If you weigh 120 pounds, that's 60
ounces, or about 7 1/2 eight-ounce cups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
