<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IOWA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH COURTS VOTERS, DEFLECTS CRITICISM FROM OTHER CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVENPORT, Iowa _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush made a final dash
across this farmland state Friday, seeking to shore up support for
the first official test of his front-runner status in the
Republican presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Stump speeches were the order of the day for all the Republican
candidates who are participating in the Ames Straw Poll, a
fund-raiser for the Iowa Republican Party that has taken on
exaggerated importance in the 2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important event,'' Bush said Friday morning at a
Davenport restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation is watching to see what's going to happen on this
first step in a very long political process, the first step towards
the Iowa caucuses and then the primaries that follow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, interested Iowans will travel to the small town of
Ames where they will have to pay $25 _ a fee generally paid by the
candidates _ to vote in the straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the results don't mean anything.
</P>
<P>
   But GOP candidates have devoted an immense amount of money and
time to the poll in an effort to prove their organizational
know-how and political popularity.
</P>
<P>
   And given the early front-loading in the primary process, some
political observers believe a poor showing could starve some
campaigns of future donations.
</P>
<P>
   Only Sen. John McCain of Arizona has declined to participate,
calling the event a scam.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite end, the Bush camp is spending a whopping
$750,000 to buy an undisclosed number of tickets, bus in supporters
from all parts of the state and then feed and entertain them once
they get there.
</P>
<P>
   Some people participating in the straw poll will have to travel
100 miles or more to get to Ames.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush did not buy television or radio advertising,
millionaire businessman Steve Forbes and former Tennessee Gov.
Lamar Alexander have been running ads attacking Bush but without
mentioning his name.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates also have made veiled comments about Bush's
lack of experience in foreign relations.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush appeared unnerved by such criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to respond by smiling and saying, `Here's what I
believe in,''' he said Thursday night when asked about his comment
that ``Americans are sick of that kind of campaigning. People
better be beware of the backlash to negative campaigning in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day before the Ames extravaganza, Bush started off at a
Mexican restaurant in Davenport where he ate migas, spoke some
Spanish and talked to local Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working hard to say the Republican Party should welcome
new faces and new voices. I'm working hard to make sure that people
understand that the American dream is for everybody,'' he told
about 20 people there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American dream is for your children and my children,'' he
continued.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the Republican Party philosophy, correctly explained,
was that ``We welcome small business people. We understand the role
of government is not to create wealth but an environment in which
entrepreneurship can flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the summer, Bush has made a point of scheduling
events that cater to Hispanics as part of his attempt to
demonstrate he can reach voters who do not traditionally vote for
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   He also asked the Davenport group to support him in the straw
poll, apparently unaware that many in the crowd were out-of-state
residents from nearby Moline, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Non-residents are ineligible to vote in the Iowa poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to ask you to come to Ames tomorrow. I'm working
hard, and I'm here to ask you to come and help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Illinois resident David Navarro won't be voting in the
Iowa straw poll, he was impressed with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his Texas roots probably help him here (with
Hispanics). I think he thinks along the same lines we do,'' said
Navarro, who works for the restaurant's owner.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 35,000 Hispanics among the 2.7 million
residents of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   But asked if many area Hispanics were Republicans, Navarro
quickly replied: ``No.''
</P>
</TEXT>
