<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-DEMFIGHT14-COX     08-13 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMFIGHT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Rep. McKinney decides not to support colleague Lewis
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Cynthia McKinney (D-Ga.) recently hosted a
dinner supporting a California Democrat's campaign to become
majority whip of the House if the Democratic Party wins back
control next year.
</P>
<P>
   That shocked fellow Georgia Democratic Rep. John Lewis, the
state's senior congressman and fellow Congressional Black Caucus
member.
</P>
<P>
   While a return to a Democratic rule of the House is anything but
certain, Lewis has made no secret of his desire to win the post.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, a chief deputy whip, has said he wanted to run since the
Democratic gains in last year's congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that I wanted the job,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   So when he found out about McKinney's dinner in honor of Rep.
Nancy Pelosi (D-Calif.), Lewis said he was ``very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   After a fellow Democrat showed him an invitation to the dinner,
Lewis approached McKinney on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Cynthia, I have this flier saying you are having this
dinner (for Pelosi). I would have loved to have your support,'''
Lewis said. ``I told her that I wished she had told me about it.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinney told Lewis that she did not know that he was running
for job, which is the third-highest ranking job in the House behind
speaker and majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution about it, McKinney
said she is ``re-evaluating'' her decision. ``I will support the
best candidate for the office,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If John Lewis stands for anything, it's for keeping one's
word,'' McKinney said. ``If it wasn't for him, I wouldn't be a
member of Congress today.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect that McKinney would support anyone for whip other
than a fellow colleague from Georgia stunned longtime supporters of
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   They point out that Lewis has supported McKinney's campaign and
has used his connections in Atlanta's Jewish community to smooth
over tensions that erupted following her father labeling one of her
political opponents a ``racist Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Frank, the Southeast area director of the nonprofit
American Jewish Committee and founder of the Atlanta Black/Jewish
Coalition, said Lewis has been extremely supportive of McKinney in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   If McKinney supports a California Democrat over a fellow
Georgian, Frank said, it would not be received well in the Jewish
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is a sacred cow,'' Frank said. In addition, having a
Georgian in a leadership position would help the state, Frank
added.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's only other Democratic congressman, Rep. Sanford
Bishop, said he was endorsing Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we don't know what vacancies may occur, in the event Mr.
Lewis is running, my first choice will be the gentleman from my
home state of Georgia,'' Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
