<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE BECOMING AN EXCLUSIVE PLATFORM FOR GORE, HILLARY
CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House officials this week converted the
Agriculture Department's deco-styled auditorium into an elaborate
stage for talks on the futuristic uses of crops and plants as fuel.
</P>
<P>
   But it also was a stage for a political campaign. Half-way
across the country, Vice President Al Gore was touting the same
issue, biomass energy, to farmers in Iowa, site of the critical
opening caucus for the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It was no coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   While Cabinet officers, scientists and entrepreneurs gathered
around a USDA table to hear President Clinton expound on the
necessity of future energy sources, Gore was show-casing his own
expertise at the biomass event in Iowa and announcing the
initiatives being taken by the administration that day.
</P>
<P>
   As both Gore and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton gear up their
political campaigns, he for the presidency and she for the Senate
from New York, the White House more and more is becoming an
exclusive platform for both candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot recall anything remotely as well coordinated for the
vice president or anyone else. I don't think there's ever been a
president as eager to see his vice president win and willing to go
the extra mile,'' said Bruce Buchanan, a political science
professor and presidential scholar at the University of Texas at
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The assistance to Gore also is helpful to Clinton, perhaps
bolstering his legacy as president and retaining the core of his
agenda that would be undone by a Republican administration,
Buchanan said. He also noted that Gore's struggling candidacy could
use the help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make no bones about the fact the president would not only
like to see his wife be elected to the Senate if she chooses to
run, but the president has been quite open about the fact he'd like
the vice president to follow him in office,'' said Doug Sosnik, a
presidential adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried in the past to help them toward those goals and
this week is no exception,'' Sosnik said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Republicans cite Gore's embrace of Clinton as a reason he
should be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite his attempts to reinvent himself as his own man, Al
Gore is merely campaigning for a third term for Bill Clinton, a
term filled with scandals, higher taxes and cutting our national
defense,'' said Tom Yu, a spokesman for the Republican National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Ratcliff, the vice president's spokeswoman, said Gore
wants to ``expand on the success'' of the administration in areas
such as the economy and the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and vice president have been coordinating
efforts for more than six and a half years,'' Ratcliff said, adding
it was only natural that Gore would want to amplify an issue such
as biomass energy that has long been of interest to him.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan noted that there have been few two-term presidents and
those who were often tepid about their own vice presidents,
including Ronald Reagan toward George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have Gore and Clinton maintained a personal and
professional relationship but Gore aided Clinton during the
difficult days of impeachment when he predicted Clinton would go
down in history as one of the best presidents ever. And, Buchanan
noted, Clinton owes his wife an even greater debt for saving his
presidency during the sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Hillary Clinton for some time has been making some
minor announcements that affect key states but this week seemed to
mark a greater effort at coordination.
</P>
<P>
   Sosnik, however, said there was no change in strategy but
perhaps just more effectiveness. ``It's the same glide path,'' he
said, adding that perhaps interest is heightened only because the
election season grows nearer.
</P>
<P>
   The president last weekend kicked off his first of many planned
fund-raising efforts on the vice president's behalf, starting with
his homestate of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The togetherness continued during the week as Gore joined
Clinton at a small business in Virginia to tout initiatives
spurring economic growth in poor areas. They also met with Texan
Lance Armstrong, the Tour de France champion and cancer survivor.
Reporters were allowed into the session only between Gore and
Armstrong, where the vice president called for time off for federal
workers wanting cancer screening.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president and the first lady also condemned the
shootings of five people at a Los Angeles Jewish center before the
president did this week. And the president's conditional clemency
offer to 11 Puerto Rican independence leaders prompted questions of
whether he was helping his wife cater to a constituency in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Press Secretary Barry Toiv said the president's offer was
made, with the support of the Puerto Rican elected officials,
because the sedition convictions were viewed as unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Not all attempts to use the White House platform seem to work.
The first lady earlier this summer attended a traditional
photography session between the president and the World Series
champions, the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton, who rarely attends such events, donned a
Yankees cap and proclaimed herself a life-long fan, prompting
gleeful mocking from her probable Republican opponent, New York
Mayor Rudolph Guiliani, who had actually attended the games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
