<HEADLINE>
SMALL RISE IN PRODUCER PRICES EASES INFLATION JITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock and bond markets surged Friday after the government
released a reassuring report that showed a modest increase in
prices at the wholesale level in July, easing investor concerns
about inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department said the Producer Price Index rose 0.2
percent in July as the first decline in food prices since April
blunted the impact of a surge in energy prices. The July increase,
which followed an 0.1 percent decline in June, was below analysts'
forecasts and when the volatile food and energy components were
excluded, prices were unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average leaped 184.26 points, its
biggest since mid-June, as interest rates fell as much as 1/10 of a
percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   While most analysts believe the Federal Reserve will still raise
the target for a key overnight lending rate at its policy meeting
Aug. 24, the July producer price figures seemed to rule out any
need for a rate increase of more than a quarter-percentage point
and diminish the likelihood that further increases would be needed
to keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   But other soundings could still change things, including the
government's report Tuesday on inflation at the consumer level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a quite good number,'' Stan Shipley, a senior economist
at Merrill Lynch, said of Friday's report. ``Deflationary pressures
persist in the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called core rate, which excludes food and energy, was
unchanged last month, after a decline of 0.2 percent in June. That
figure was also a bit lower than the consensus of forecasters.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, analysts found no immediate cause for concern about
inflation at earlier stages in the production pipeline even though
price increases in some categories of goods were enough that they
might become unsettling if they were to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of intermediate goods, like cloth, 0.6 percent, while
those of crude goods, like coal, declined 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The drought that has ravaged grain, vegetable and other crops in
much of the Northeast and Southeast had little impact on food
prices, which tumbled 0.9 percent, offsetting the combined
increases for May and June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to find any food commodities that rose in price
that could be attributed to drought,'' said Joe Kowal, an economist
at the Bureau of Labor Statistics, noting that growing conditions
in the Midwest have been excellent.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, other analysts said, that the drought actually
helped restrain the rise in producer prices as farmers and ranchers
sped livestock sales up because of a lack of affordable feed.
Prices of cattle for slaughter, for example, fell 2.4 percent in
July after rising 3.8 percent in June and price declines
accelerated for hogs and chickens for slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Kasman, chief U.S. economist at J.P. Morgan, called the
latest inflation reading ``very benign'' but added that a long
period of steadily lower inflation was giving way to price
``normalization'' that would require vigilance at the Federal
Reserve.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other Labor Department reports in recent weeks have showed wage
acceleration and continued drum-tight job markets, intensifying
jitters about inflation in the securities markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no problem here right now _ no reason to slam your
feet on the brakes,'' Kasman said. But he added that some of
Friday's data did show ``reasons to be a little concerned'' if
increases persisted into the autumn. But James Glassman at Chase
Manhattan said that strong productivity growth by manufacturers was
likely to prevent these from being passed along.
</P>
<P>
   One sensitive area is durable items like copper and plywood used
in the manufacturing process, an element of the intermediate goods
category. These materials, which also include brass mill shapes,
building board and glass, jumped 0.8 percent in July after rising
0.7 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
   Construction materials jumped 0.7 percent while chemicals and
other nondurables consumed by factories rose 0.4 percent following
an exceptional surge in June.
</P>
<P>
   Energy prices were sharply higher at all stages of production _
3.4 percent among finished goods, 2.9 percent among intermediates
and 3.7 percent for raw material. More than half the jump in
finished energy was due to a 12.7 percent jump in gasoline
following a 1.9 percent decline in June.
</P>
<P>
   The index for beef and veal slumped 3.4 percent after rising
more than twice as much in June, while the price of fresh eggs
jumped 7.1 percent, both moves possibly reflecting the effects of
drought.
</P>
</TEXT>
