<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY PUSHES FOR NO. 2 IN CONFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Edging ever closer to a playoff position, the Los
Angeles Galaxy finally is showing the form of its 1998
record-breaking season.
</P>
<P>
   And what could be better to aid its run than a matchup against
the Dallas Burn?
</P>
<P>
   When the teams meet tonight at 7:30 at the Rose Bowl in a key
Western Conference showdown, the Galaxy hopes its victory trend
continues in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy (13-8, 33 points) has won seven of its past eight
meetings against the Burn (11-11, 31 points) and is looking to
close in on the second-place Chicago Fire (34 points), which plays
host to Miami tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked at a couple of the games where the Galaxy has
played Dallas,'' said Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid, who will be facing
the Burn for the first time, ``and I think part of it is just good
matchups. Dallas is just a team the Galaxy has had a lot of success
against.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has been having success against just about everyone
lately, winning eight of its past 10 to enter tonight's game as the
league's hottest team.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday's U.S. Open Cup quarterfinal loss against
Columbus, the Galaxy put together one of its most impressive
efforts of the season, a 4-1 victory at San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Zak Ibsen, Cobi Jones, Mauricio Cienfuegos and Seth George all
scored goals, with Cienfuegos picking up three assists.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas has struggled recently, winning only four of its past 10,
although the Burn boasts one of the league's leading scorers in
Jason Kreis.
</P>
<P>
   Kreis has 14 goals and 10 assists in 22 games. Dallas is the
league's second-highest scoring team with 37 goals, trailing only
D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas always plays us tough and because the league standings
are so close right now, it has that much more importance,'' Galaxy
defender Paul Caligiuri said. ``The game's actually worth six
points instead of three because if you win it, obviously you jump
ahead. We're kind of on an upswing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burn is coming off a humbling 2-1 loss Wednesday to the
Rochester Raging Rhinos of the A-League in the quarterfinals of the
U.S. Open Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Dallas' cross-country travel schedule, Schmid said he
didn't think that would have an impact tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same for both teams so I'm not worried about it,''
Schmid said. ``We're going in with equal rest as Dallas so that
makes it OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schmid also realizes the significance of tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important because we definitely want to finish in the top
two in the division. That's within our reach now,'' Schmid said.
``This game is important in terms of achieving that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   When Schmid took over for fired coach Octavio Zambrano, he said
it would take 10 games for the Galaxy to show what it could really
do. So what's been the difference lately?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing a good job of finishing opportunities and we're
defending with fairly good compactness,'' Schmid said.
``Offensively, we've got different options to go to. (Midfielder)
Roy (Myers) has been a big plus for us and different people have
stepped up at different times, even with people hurt right now.
We've found people to step in and do a job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
