<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6770 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WOMEN-TVCHANNEL14-COX     08-13 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-TVCHANNEL14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner Broadcasting delays launch of women-oriented cable
channel
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's been a busy year for Turner Broadcasting. So
busy, in fact, that the Atlanta-based cable TV programmer has
decided to scale back ambitious plans to launch three new channels
within the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The company, a unit of Time Warner, said it would indefinitely
postpone the launch of the Women's Network, a channel that was
announced two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Turner South, a regional channel, and Boomerang, a second
cartoon channel, will still launch as planned.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Network was to have begun airing after the middle of
next year. Now some industry observers think it may never air.
</P>
<P>
   The delay is a personal setback for Pat Mitchell, one of Turner
Broadcasting's top programmers. As president of CNN Productions,
Mitchell had worked for years to champion the idea of a channel
pitched to women.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, on business in Baltimore, Md., could not be reached
for comment Friday. The postponement also reflects a cultural
change at Turner Broadcasting, which used to fearlessly launch new
channels that many thought were ill-advised.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years Turner Broadcasting has been a unit of
Time Warner. The New York-based media conglomerate, much more
focused on controlling costs and producing returns, is less willing
to gamble on risky new ideas _ at least in cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Network, which was announced with great fanfare in
June, was canceled unexpectedly. Few of Turner Broadcasting's
rank-and-file in Atlanta knew of the decision until reading about
it Friday morning in The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to cancel the channel was made Thursday evening in
New York at a meeting between Gerald Levin and Ted Turner, chairman
and vice chairman, respectively, of Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   The two were concerned that the Women's Network, which would be
costly to produce, would take a long time to become profitable.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Women's Network faced considerable competition
for viewership. For one, there's Lifetime, marketed primarily to
women, which has some 70 million subscribers. Another group, led by
famed cable TV programmer Geraldine Laybourne, is trying to begin a
channel for women called Oxygen. Laybourne already has signed up
some big cable operators, including the 5 million subscribers of
Charter.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Turner and Levin decided it better to focus their
company's resources on new channels more likely to gain quick
acceptance. Those channels are Turner South, a regional channel set
to air Oct. 1, and a second 24-hour cartoon channel called
Boomerang.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Levin nor Turner would comment, but the company released
a prepared statement that confirmed its reported strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said, in part, ``TBS has decided that it is not in
the company's best interest nor in the best interest of our
affiliates to actively pursue the creation of the Women's Network
at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the time being, we feel it best to concentrate on the
development of the other two networks preparing to launch.''
</P>
<P>
   What made the Women's Network so costly was a strategy to air
largely original programming. That is, after all, Mitchell's
expertise. She planned to fill her channel's airtime with women's
interest shows about cooking, fashion, world events and lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Shows were to have been made in a partnership with Conde Nast's
large portfolio of women's interest magazines. Those magazines
include House and Garden, Glamour and Mademoiselle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
