<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPPER-SPRAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE TO DROP ETHNIC REFERENCES IN PEPPER SPRAY TRAINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Police Commissioner Ronnie Watson apologized
Friday for his department's practice of instructing officers that
pepper spray, which is used to temporarily ``calm situations,'' may
be ineffective against Latinos, Indians and other ethnic groups who
eat spicy food. Watson said the department will stop teaching the
unsubstantiated instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate that these comments were made,'' Watson said
referring to news reports that Cambridge officers were taught some
ethnic groups may have a built-in immunity to pepper spray. ``There
is no empirical or scientific evidence to support these
statements.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Watson said that ``we have met with our instructors
to ensure that all future training includes only material that is
part of the Massachusetts Criminal Justice Training Council's
curriculum.''
</P>
<P>
   The instructions were not part of the current written training
material, said Cambridge Police spokesman Frank Pasquarello.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper spray, a mixture of cayenne pepper and natural oils
sprayed from a pressurized container, is a nonlethal device used by
law enforcement officers. It is effective only when sprayed
directly into the face or eyes, and causes severe burning for about
45 to 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Most police departments have policies regulating the use of
pepper spray, which is to be used to incapacitate people who are
resisting arrest and only after a warning.
</P>
<P>
   Medical specialists and pepper spray manufacturers said there
was no scientific evidence that any particular ethnic group has
been desensitized to pepper spray when it was sprayed in their
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Pasquarello said the statements about pepper spray made by
officer Frank Gutoski were not intended to be derogatory, but were
instructions he had received as a part of his training, and passed
onto others. ``All he was trying to say was that if you sprayed
someone and that person kept coming at you, there may be many
reasons why it isn't working, such as weather conditions,''
Pasquarello said.
</P>
<P>
   Pasquarello said the office did receive several calls from
members of the Cambridge community about the issue. The police
department does not plan to discipline or reprimand Gutoski for his
statements, Pasquarello said.
</P>
<P>
   But the apology is not enough for Nicolas Carballeira, director
of policy and planning for the Latino Health Insituate and chair of
the governor's Latino-American Advisory Commission. ``It is
certainly the right step and in the right direction,'' said
Carballeira. ``But we would also like to see effective corrective
measures taken for the people who have already been trained with
this misinformation.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Carballeira said the Latino community would like to
see what steps will be taken to reprimand or discipline the people
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the people who are supposed to protect us are making
these types of generalizations, it's time to get serious,'' said
Carballeira, who noted that Latinos spend $4.8 billion in goods and
services in Massachusetts each year. ``It's time we receive the
respect that is due.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
