<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6774 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-UPS-TAXES14-COX     08-13 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-TAXES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS to say how it might pay tax bill
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ United Parcel Service is expected to disclose Monday
how it will deal with at least part of what could be a $1 billion
tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure would come in the package delivery company's
quarterly filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the U.S. Tax Court agreed with the Internal Revenue
Service that UPS owes $64.9 million in back taxes for 1983 and
1984. Penalties and interest could push UPS' bill for the two years
to $200 million to $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS also wants additional taxes for later years. If the IRS
continues to win its case in court, UPS could owe $1 billion or
more, according to published reports. The company does not dispute
the estimate.
</P>
<P>
   UPS has been setting aside an undisclosed reserve for its
potential liability, spokesman Ken Sternad said Friday. The company
had a ``fiduciary'' responsibility to do so, he said, ``although we
anticipated winning this case and still have the option of
appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   How the outcome of the tax case will affect UPS' planned public
offering is not clear, according to analyst Jeffrey L. Pittsburg of
Pittsburg Institutional Services, who follows competitor FDX.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it could affect pricing somewhat,'' he said, referring
to the initial public offering price, which has not been set. The
company has said it hopes to have the offering before the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what they do, I'm thinking I would like to buy
(the stock) in any case,'' Pittsburg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't anticipate this case will impact our plans for the
IPO,'' said Sternad. He said UPS still hopes to go public this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The company will amend earlier SEC filings related to the
planned public offering, Sternad said, but no timetable has been
set for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   On the tax issue, UPS has several options:
</P>
<P>
   _ It could appeal, but only after reaching agreement with the
IRS on exactly how much it owes under the Tax Court decision, and
after the court makes the decision final.
</P>
<P>
   Winning on appeal ``would be an uphill battle for UPS,'' said
attorney Jonathan E. Jackel of Burt, Maner &AMP; Miller, a Washington
firm that represents corporations in tax disputes. ``As a matter of
practice, the Tax Court is considered to be the expert on
interpreting federal income tax law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there are grounds for appeal,'' Sternad responded.
``We think the judge is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   _ UPS could pay what the IRS says is due. It has the wherewithal
to do so: $3.3 billion in cash and marketable securities, as of
March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Paying the bill would have two advantages. One, it would stop
the clock on interest charges on the unpaid taxes. Interest is
piling up at a current rate of 10 percent, according to the IRS,
although the rate changes quarterly. Two, it would free UPS to seek
a refund of the taxes in U.S. District Court or U.S. Claims Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at all the options,'' Sternad said.
</P>
<P>
   The major issue in the tax case is the money the company's
customers pay to cover the possible loss of a package or damage to
its contents.
</P>
<P>
   The Tax Court ruled that UPS engages in ``sham transactions''
with a Bermuda insurance company it formed, in order to avoid
paying income taxes on profit from that service.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, if UPS changes the way it accounts for the damage
and loss service charges because of the Tax Court decision, it
could report higher profits.
</P>
<P>
   That's because UPS doesn't count as revenue the money it charges
to cover damage and losses. If it did, profit from the service
would be added to the company's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
