<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-WOMEN-ART-NY     08-13 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-WOMEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT GRADUATE UNIVERSITY IN PAKISTAN, WOMEN CAN LET DOWN THEIR
VEILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphics are being sent to NYT photo and
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036. 
(EDS: Non-possessive `Women University' in 3rd graf is correct.
Ditto `Woman Bank' in 22nd graf) 
(yn) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAWALPINDI, Pakistan _ The young women, some stylishly dressed
in high-heeled sandals and colorful tunic and pants, others
shrouded completely in black, spilled out of the gleaming white
Victorian mansion that houses Pakistan's first and only publicly
financed graduate school for women.
</P>
<P>
   Most are from socially conservative Muslim families who would
have never allowed their daughters to attend a coeducational
university. Some have lived so strictly secluded that the only men
who have ever seen their faces are their grandfathers, fathers and
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   But they have come to Fatima Jinnah Women University to earn
master's degrees in an environment that their parents can tolerate.
Except for a few gardeners, all staff members, from the vice
chancellor to the deans to the professors to the janitors, are
women.
</P>
<P>
   Tauseef Fatima, 25, begged her parents for the chance to earn a
master's degree in education here, and they consented, though only
on her promise that she would leave if they found her a husband. At
the university, she has listened to scholars lecture about the
rights of women in Islam _ to divorce, to have property, to think
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am from the Sindh Province and men are very dominant
there,'' she said. ``So these were new ideas for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting up a state-supported graduate school for women was a new
idea that made many Pakistani women who are educators or other
professionals uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   The university is financed by the province of Punjab with the
enthusiastic backing of its chief minister, Shabaz Sharif, who also
happens to be the very powerful younger brother of Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the prime minister was pushing legislation to
make Islamic law supreme, some Pakistani women who are educators or
other professionals feared that the creation of a university just
for women was another sign of creeping fundamentalism in Pakistan.
The nation's founder, Mohammad Ali Jinnah, was a barrister with a
taste for hand-tailored suits and silk ties and a more liberal,
tolerant vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you saying _ that we're separate, but unequal?''
Maleeha Lodhi, editor of The News, an English-language daily in
nearby Islamabad, asked tartly. ``This kind of segregation fosters
the forces of conservatism, not modernism.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasreen Rehman, director of the Mahbub ul-Haq Human Development
Center in Islamabad, was also uncomfortable with the idea of a
segregated university.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rehman knows what women are up against in Pakistan. In 1998
the research institute she directs published a report on education
in South Asia that laid out the baleful statistics: Only a quarter
of the women in the country can read, compared with half the men.
More than half the girls of elementary school age are not in
school.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Rehman changed her mind about the wisdom of a university
for women after she visited it. Young women can study here and feel
secure and comfortable, just as they do at women's colleges in the
United States and England, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She was present when Aziza Al-Hibri, a law professor at Richmond
University in Virginia, addressed the student body, telling them
that it was up to women to interpret the Koran for themselves and
not to rely on the say-so of men.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're no pushovers, the girls in that university,'' Ms.
Rehman said. ``They asked Dr. Al-Hibri very difficult questions
about women's rights in Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   Syeda Natiqabatool, 24, is one of the students who has found the
university to be a place where she can remove the veil that always
covers her face when she is in the presence of men outside her
immediate family, even of her own cousins, and take part fully and
casually. She hopes one day to teach Islamic studies in a women's
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can walk freely in this university,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The university's animating intelligence is Najma Najam, formerly
a professor of psychology at Punjab University and and now the
first head of the university, with the title of vice chancellor. A
wife and a mother of two adolescents, she describes herself as a
practicing Muslim who wears her hair short, plays tennis, drives
and enjoys an evening at the movies. ``I live a modern life,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She took on the job of starting this new university on Dec. 3,
1998, with what she called ``a staff of two _ a night watchman and
myself,'' and opened for classes on Dec. 28, quickly conjuring up a
faculty, an administrative staff and a curriculum. ``There was
nothing, not even furniture,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She did, however, have a beautiful building to house the new
university: a mansion that once belonged to a fabulously wealthy
family of Sikh hoteliers who had fled to India in 1947 when
Britain's subcontinental empire was divided into Pakistan and
India, unleashing sectarian violence. Its walls are still encrusted
with hand-painted Persian designs in gold leaf and from its
ceilings hang crystal chandeliers.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for admission to the university, named for the sister
of Jinnah, the nation's founder, was great. While there is a
tradition of women's undergraduate colleges with limited graduate
programs, Fatima Jinnah Women University is the first
research-oriented graduate school for women.
</P>
<P>
   About 7,000 women applied for the 350 spots in the first class.
By this fall, there will be 1,000 students. And Ms. Najam dreams of
a student body of 6,000 10 years from now.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition is about $150 a year and most of the students are from
lower-middle-class families. The entire university, with a faculty
of 35 and a support staff of 35, runs on a budget that would just
about pay the salary of the president of a very modest American
college: $116,000. Ms. Najam herself earns slightly under $5,000 a
year, and assistant professors make a little over $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   She hopes to build an endowment, but so far the university's
account at the First Woman Bank of Pakistan contains only about
$300 donated by a retired army officer.
</P>
<P>
   The young women here have generally come for practical reasons.
Farida Saleem, 21, who excelled at statistics and economics in
college, is aiming for a degree in business administration. She is
resigned to the fact that her father will allow her to work outside
the home only if family finances go bad, but she still regards a
master's degree as a kind of insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's essential to have something in your hands,'' she said.
``If at any time I need to work, it will help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Saima Talat, 27, and a student of English literature, plans to
teach. Her parents will find her a husband within a couple of
years, but her master's degree will still be an asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan is suffering economic problems,'' she said. ``So the
women have to work, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
