A6778 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BRONNER-HAIRSHOW14-CO     08-13 0280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRONNER-HAIRSHOW14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bronner Brothers staging its 52nd annual hair show
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the Bronner Brothers International Hair Show
opens its doors at the Georgia World Congress Center today, it
won't be a run-of-the-mill show.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there will be exhibits, just as there are at any industry
trade show. But what sets Bronner Brothers apart from others is a
heavy dose of glitz, glamour and music, and tons of hair.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 52nd year for the event, one of the largest shows
for the ethnic beauty products industry.
</P>
<P>
   Several events are open to the public, including a comedy show
today and the Hair Battle Royale on Monday, which carries a $10,000
prize.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers expect more than 100,000 stylists, manufacturers and
distributors to attend the show, whose theme is Hair Odyssey 2000.
The show ends Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has become larger,'' said Darrow Bronner, show
director and a vice president of Bronner Brothers, an ethnic hair
care products maker. ``It's a multibillion industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the show drew about 40,000 and had 300
exhibitors. This year, he expects 400 exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like the show will remain in Atlanta. Bronner recently
said that Orlando, Fla., convention officials tried to get the show
to move there, but that such a move is unlikely now.
</P>
<P>
   The show was held in Orlando in 1996, when its scheduled time
conflicted with the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel Atlanta is our home base,'' he said. ``We're really
not looking to move anywhere outside of Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
