u i BC-ISRAEL-GOLAN-WATER-$A     08-13 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GOLAN-WATER-$ADV-15-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER RIGHTS AN ISSUE IN GOLAN HEIGHTS  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 15) 
 
DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIBBUTZ ORTAL, Golan Heights _ If Israel withdraws from the
Golan Heights, Eitan Sadeh, wants to know, what will happen to the
country's water supply?
</P>
<P>
   The question has been on the minds of many of the 17,000 Israeli
settlers on the Golan Heights as they contemplate the possibility
that their homes and lands may soon revert to Syria's control.
</P>
<P>
   Blessed with high mountains in the north and natural springs in
the center, the Golan plateau has provided Israel with roughly
one-third of its water since Israel captured the heights from Syria
in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   The water trickles down mainly from Mt. Hermon, a ski resort in
winter months, and the nearby Banyas Springs. Then it flows through
tiny tributaries until it reaches the biblical Sea of Galilee,
which is actually a freshwater lake. From there, Israel's national
water carrier takes it to farms and cities.
</P>
<P>
   While water has often been a problem in this semidesert climate,
particularly in southern Israel, the region is gripped by the worst
drought in decades, and many Israelis are convinced the country
must protect scarce water sources in any land-for-peace agreement
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is very crucial,'' said Moshe Inbar, an Israeli
water expert who heads the department of geography at the
University of Haifa. ``We must reach an agreement that all waters
flowing into the (Sea of Galilee) belong to Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Syria is demanding that Israel withdraw from the heights all the
way to the shores of the Sea of Galilee, the border that existed
June 4, 1967, the day before Israel captured the region. That would
give Syria access not only to water on the Golan Heights, but also
the right to tap into the Sea of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Israel has balked at giving up that much. An
alternative, if Israel agrees to cede the region at all, would be
to move to what is locally known as the ``international border,''
the boundary decided by Britain and France after World War I.
</P>
<P>
   After the creation of Israel in 1948, Syrian soldiers slowly
pushed the international border southward, eventually making their
way to the shores of the Sea of Galilee and creating a new de facto
border, the so-called ``June 4 line.'' The difference is only a
matter of a few yards, but it would keep the Syrians far enough
away from the Sea of Galilee to keep them from dipping their toes
in the water, as one Israeli commentator put it.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, a complete withdrawal from the Golan Heights would
spell the end of Israel's largest bottled mineral water company,
Eden, which supplies Israelis 65 percent of their bottled drinking
water, according to a company spokeswoman. The water comes from a
natural spring found in the center of the plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say Israel's water problems pale compared to those faced
by the Palestinians and the Jordanians. Jordan rations water year
round.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Inbar predicts, it will be Israel's agriculture,
which accounts for 60 percent of the country's water consumption,
that suffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe no more citrus,'' he said. ``Ten years from now, the
famous Jaffa oranges maybe will disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
