<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURROW-IDENTITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN IDENTITY LEADER SAYS FURROW HAD SOUGHT `TRUTH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dave Barley recalls welcoming Buford O. Furrow Jr.
to his church, America's Promise Ministries in Sandpoint, Idaho,
just like the pastor would any newcomer who wanted to hear the
``truth'': that God's chosen people are white, American, Christian
men with northern European roots.
</P>
<P>
   When the FBI visited Barley on Thursday and asked if he knew
Furrow, the suspect in six Los Angeles hate shootings two days
before, the pastor acknowledged he did. ``He came here about two
years ago, and he came about two times, and that was about it,''
Barley said in a telephone interview. ``I don't know why he came. I
believe he was associated with the Aryan Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, investigating Furrow's links to white supremacist
groups like the Aryan Nations in northern Idaho, had good reason to
question Barley. He is one of the leading lights in the Christian
Identity movement, a loose federation of fringe ministries
preaching an anti-Semitic, racist message that claims America is
threatened by the power of Jews, who are agents, even descendants
of Satan, and by minorities, who are inferior to the white race.
</P>
<P>
   Barley denies that he incites his followers to violence, and he
condemns Furrow for ``a very ungodly and awful thing'' in allegedly
murdering Joseph Ileto, a Filipino-American postman, and shooting
three children, a teenager, and a 68-year-old woman at the North
Valley Jewish Community Center in Granada Hills, Calif., on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not sit back and say, `Hey, great, he went after the
Jews, he is our hero,' '' said Barley, who in photos bears a
striking resemblance to Furrow. ``Give me a break. That would make
people think that we hate Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people I do not hate Jews, but I am against Judaism and
Zionism, because they are not for Jesus Christ,'' Barley added.
``As a race, Jews have a right to exist, and if you had people
going out and shooting anybody just because they are different _
Jews, blacks, Asians, homosexuals _ that would be anarchism. We
aren't anarchists. That would be insane.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian Identity's tenets are racist, insane, and incendiary,
according to scholars on contemporary Christianity, and its
theology is increasingly being embraced by right-wing paramilitary
groups, neo-Nazi skinheads, the Ku Klux Klan, and survivalists as a
justification for waging a holy war against groups they hate and
fear.
</P>
<P>
   Because Christian Identity's teachings are literally apocalyptic
_ followers believe God's chosen people must destroy Satan's army
at Armageddon _ violence against Jews and minorities is on the rise
with the approach of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we ramp up to the millennium, we can expect to see a period
of ritual cleansing _ racial scapegoating and acts of violence _
aimed at those groups perceived as evil and wrong,'' said Chip
Berlet, senior analyst with the nonprofit Political Research
Associates in Somerville, Mass. ``As we ramp down from the
millennium and these disappointed extremists realize the world
didn't come to an end, we could be in for a period of ritual
retribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way, this situation will be with us for some time, and
it is getting worse as it gets to the year 2000,'' Berlet said.
</P>
<P>
   Barley says the media and groups that monitor hate crimes
conspire to distort the teachings of Christian Identity and brand
its mostly peace-loving followers as terrorists, murderers, and
``kooks.'' He says his church is not connected either to white
supremacist Richard Butler, a longtime Christian Identity pastor,
or to Butler's Aryan Nations group that Furrow joined in 1995 in
nearby Hayden Lake, Idaho. ``There is too much Hitler-worship going
on there,'' Barley added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Christian Identity, which is estimated to have from
35,000 to 50,000 followers nationwide, is what Mark Potok of the
nonprofit Southern Poverty Law Center calls ``the glue that binds
the radical right together,'' and it appears to be the common
demoninator in a series of recent hate crimes. For example:
</P>
<P>
   --Authorities in California say Benjamin and James Williams,
brothers recently charged in the murder of two gay men and the
firebombing of three synagogues in the Sacramento area, have been
involved in the Christian Identity movement.
</P>
<P>
   --Benjamin Smith, who went on a Fourth of July weekend rampage,
shooting Asians, Jews, and a black man in Illinois and Indiana, was
a follower of the World Church of the Creator, an anti-Semitic sect
in East Peoria, Ill., closely aligned with Christian Identity.
</P>
<P>
   --Eric Rudolph, the fugitive wanted for the Atlanta Olympic
bombings in 1996 and attacks on abortion clinics, has been linked
to the Christian Identity movement.
</P>
<P>
   --A book called ``War Cycles, Peace Cycles,'' by Richard Kelly
Hoskins, a prominent Christian Identity writer whose works
reportedly have inspired terrorist acts and bank robberies, was
found in Furrow's van. Butler, the Christian Identity pastor, is
believed to have married Furrow and Debra Mathews, widow of Robert
Mathews, a founder of the Order, a white supremacist-terrorist
group.
</P>
<P>
   Those who monitor the Christian Identity movement _ mostly
academics and organizations that track hate groups _ get the bulk
of their information from the Internet, where many of the
ministries maintain websites for spreading their doctrine, selling
publications, and promoting radio broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   America's Promise Ministries, for example, has only 40 members
in Sandpoint, but a much larger virtual community can read Barley's
monthly newsletters, which accuse Jews of controlling the media,
corporations, and the White House, and can purchase books titled
``America: Free, White, &AMP; Christian,'' and ``Who Killed Christ?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Conquer we must, for our cause is just,'' is the motto of the
Kingdom Identity Ministries in Harrison, Ark. A doctrine statement
on its website calls homosexuality ``an abomination before God and
should be punished by death,'' and Jews ``the literal seed of
Satan...a curse to true Israel...an evil race'' that will have its
ultimate end on Judgment Day.
</P>
<P>
   The roots of this modern-day Christian Identity movement are in
nineteenth-century England, where an ideologue named John Wilson
popularized British Israelism, a theory that Northern European
Christians were the descendants of the lost tribe of Israel and
that the birthright of God's chosen people belonged to white
Anglo-Saxons, not Jews. Howard Rand, a Haverhill lawyer and
stalwart of the Massachusetts Prohibition Party, imported the ideas
to the United States in the 1920s, created the Anglo-Saxon
Federation of America, a white supremacist group, and published
widely on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Identity theory percolated for years _
industrialist Henry Ford was intrigued by it _ but in the 1940s and
1950s a group of anti-Semitic California ministers spun a more
radically racist theology. The Jews, they maintained, were
descendants of Cain, offspring of Eve and Satan, and people of
color were subhuman ``Mud People,'' created by the devil as lazy,
soulless parasites.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Lamy, a sociology professor at Castleton State College in
Vermont and an expert on the millennium, says forms of Christian
Identity are flourishing now because right-wing extremists can plug
almost any threatening group _ feminists, gays, government
officials, Jews, immigrants, African-Americans _into its
``millennial myth'' that the end of human history is near and evil
must be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like Buford Furrow or the Unabomber are motivated to
violence by emotional and psychological problems, not
philosophies,'' Lamy said. ``But now, when something happens that
tips them over the edge, they are more likely to act on their
ideology or theology because we're in an apocalyptic age.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some momentous end-of-the-world scenario, they are the
martyrs,'' Lamy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
