<HEADER>
A6792 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     08-13 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAILEY TRYING TO MAKE THE COWBOYS BETTER DAILY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Every day at 3 o'clock, or whenever they
get around to it, The Ticket broadcasts Cowboys coach Chan Gailey's
daily press briefings from Wichita Falls. It's ``live'' radio, or
semi-live, depending on whether the Hardline boys are in the middle
of their esoteric opening or, more important, Gailey's mood.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, some days Chan just isn't very ``live,'' period.
</P>
<P>
   Some astute marketing genius at the station has dubbed this
training camp feature ``Gailey Daily.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that daily, by increments and inches, this football
team gradually is coming to bear, for better or worse, Gailey's
indelible stamp. More and more, this is becoming his football team.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, don't try to sell that to the Cowboys' modest,
take-no-credit head coach, who shakes his head and resorts to his
best Georgia drawl to wave off such notions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at it in terms of control and power,'' Gailey
said one day recently after a morning practice. ``I look at it in
terms of what's best for the football team. Jerry and Stephen
\RJones\S and I have discussions about what needs to happen and how
things need to go. We come to a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good working relationship. I'm not into who has the
power and who has the control. I'm into doing what's right for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the daily Gaily stamp we're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you,'' owner Jerry Jones said, unsolicited, ``how
impressed I am and continue to be with Chan.''
</P>
<P>
   He's the same coach who came out of nowhere to take the Cowboys'
job even when close friends in the fraternity were telling him he'd
be making a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Only a year wiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know our players better,'' Gailey said. ``I have a better
idea about what people can do, what their strengths are, what their
weaknesses are. I have a year more of experience. Where the exact
places are that that comes into play, I don't know, but hopefully
I've learned some things from having been through them last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a head coach before, so I had a little bit of an
idea about what was involved, but I've been willing to adjust and
listen to other ideas, realizing that I might not have every
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Gailey what his biggest mistake was last year and he's
stumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't evaluate things that way,'' he said, because he
doesn't really like negative questions, ``but if you ask me what I
did really good last year, I don't have an answer for that one
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan was to develop as much as depth as we could this
off-season. We tried to do that last year, but, the way things
worked out, a lot of things happened that kept us from doing what
we wanted to do. If I start listing them, then I become an
excuse-maker and I refuse to do that. The bottom line is that we
didn't do it, and we just need to move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   He is convinced that this year's team will be better than last
year's squad, which cratered in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more knowledge of the system, so we should be better
whether we brought anybody else in or not,'' Gailey said. ``We try
to see a weakness and then we try to shore it up the best we can.
Sometimes the salary cap doesn't allow you to do exactly what you
want to do _ Jerry would do anything, if it wasn't for the cap _
but you do what you can. You always want to improve your speed, and
we think we've done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the team's personality. If Gailey stands for
anything, it's integrity. No one hurts more than Gailey when
there's an off-field problem that reflects badly on the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has had to come to grips with reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to avoid all that off-field stuff, but guys are
human,'' he said. ``When something happens, you have to decide if,
(1) this is a bad person and if they are, how you can extricate
them from the team; and (2) even if they're not a bad person, is
the behavior detrimental to the team? Is the action becoming too
much of a distraction? If it is, then you have to find a way to
rectify it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a hard line. When we were growing up, they used to
draw a line and if you walked over that line, you were wrong and
you were punished for it. That line's not there any more. Everybody
comes from different backgrounds, they grew up different, they have
different sets of standards and values and you have to take all
that into account.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have is different players who have different
standards and backgrounds, and you're trying to mesh them into a
team and sometimes they don't understand how somebody else grew up
or perceives right and wrong. We're trying to get everybody on the
same page and still let everyone be their own person.''
</P>
<P>
   That is Gailey's daily challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the chance to be a very good football team. We
really do,'' Gailey said, ``but we have to play with consistency.
Not 12 games worth, not nine games worth, but 16 games worth. Then
we go make a run at the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Consistent: That's Gailey in a nutshell.
</P>
<P>
   Same guy, same time, same station, every day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
