<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6793 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-BONDS-ART-$ADV     08-13 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BONDS-ART-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 HOW TO PLAY THE TREASURY BOND BUYBACK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of outstanding level of debt securities is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans on occasion have suffered various shortages _ of
gasoline, for example, or pennies or sensibly priced Internet
stocks. Never in memory, however, have they even imagined a
shortage of government debt.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the first budget surpluses in a generation emerging,
the government is moving to make its obligations a little bit
scarce. That is, if anything amounting to $3.6 trillion can be
thought of as ``scarce.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan, announced earlier this month and still lacking
details, is to buy back some outstanding Treasury bonds and to sell
fewer new ones. The government will eliminate one of three auctions
a year it holds for bonds with the longest maturity, 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   This prospect, many analysts believe, not only offers the chance
of a modest profit to some bond holders, but also suggests that
some rethinking may be in order on the part of those supercautious
investors who put their faith in Washington's promises.
</P>
<P>
   A shrunken supply of Treasuries implies higher prices and lower
returns, thereby making competing high-quality bonds, especially
the $1.1 trillion issued by federal agencies and
government-sponsored organizations, like the Federal National
Mortgage Association, more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how William H. Gross, managing director of Pacific
Investment Management and a prominent figure in the world of bonds,
recommends playing the buyback, which isn't slated to occur until
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start to buy what the government is going to buy'' several
months from now, he suggested. ``Individuals can actually front-run
the government.''
</P>
<P>
   However, transaction costs are significant relative to the
potential profits, in the view of William C. Dudley, a vice
president at Goldman Sachs. You may need to make a six-figure
commitment to benefit enough to compensate for broker fees and
other costs.
</P>
<P>
   But other things being equal, the buyback program provides a
cushion if rates rise, because the government is acting as a
support for bond prices. If they fall, it can only give your
portfolio some extra juice.
</P>
<P>
   You might suppose the government would target its most expensive
debt, such as its 14 percent bonds due in 2011 or its 15}s of 2001,
for buybacks, which will be conducted through dealers. But
specialists say you would probably be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   This is because such bonds now sell at prices way above their
face, or maturity, value. The government is required to treat any
amount it pays above face value as an extra budgetary expense
rather than a run-of-the-mill refinancing. That is something
Washington presumably wants to minimize. And so, analysts say, the
more likely issues to be repurchased are those due from 2015 to
2025 with coupons of between 7 percent and 9 percent. Today, these
trade at far smaller premiums to their face value.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gary Gensler, undersecretary of the Treasury for domestic
finance, cautioned that budgetary concerns would not necessarily
bar the buyback of double-digit coupons since other factors,
including market conditions, would also affect the choice.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to saving interest costs, the government is hoping
to improve the liquidity of benchmark issues _ such as the 30-year
bond auctioned last week _ by trimming the number of older,
competing ``off the run'' issues, such as the bonds sold last
August and now due in 29 years. Off-the-runs now yield about
one-quarter of a percentage point more than their newly minted
cousins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're taking inactive ones out and issuing more
on-the-run,'' said William Quan, senior economist at Aubrey G.
Lanston, a specialist in government securities. That will save the
government interest payments in the short term and insures more
demand in future auctions.
</P>
<P>
   With one of the goals being to shorten the average length of
outstanding debt, another focus will likely be on issues with 15 to
25 years left until maturity, most of these with coupons in the
high single digits. And it's almost certain that the Treasury won't
be bidding for any bonds with call features under which it can
force redemption, many of these, not surprisingly, carrying the
highest coupons.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of trying to guess which Treasuries the government
will seek to retire, investors may well decide to shop more
profitably elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bound to encourage a widening of interest-rate
differentials'' between Treasuries and the debt of federal agencies
and corporations, said Henry Kaufman, proprietor of a New York
advisory firm bearing his name. ``That's where the opportunities
lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Agency debt includes bonds of the Federal Home Loan Bank as well
as those of the Federal National Mortgage Association and the
Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. _ the latter two actually private
companies chartered by the government. Their debt already yields
between one-half and three-quarters of a point more than Treasuries
of similar maturity. That differential will probably be wider in
the future due to the lower rates offered by increasingly scarce
Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   If you insist on a federal stamp of approval, don't forget one
obvious alternative: certificates of deposits available at your
local bank. The six-month variety is yielding nearly a percentage
point more than a comparable Treasury bill _ though, of course,
you'll pay both state and federal taxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
