<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CHEROKEES-ART-NYT &LR;      08-13 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEROKEES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHIEF HOPES TO MEND A BROKEN CHEROKEE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(yn) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAHLEQUAH, Okla. _ As a member of the Cherokee Nation and a
student of its history, Chad Smith need only look to his family
tree to find a famed leader of his tribe. Redbird Smith, his
great-grandfather, was a patriot who went to prison rather than
accept the federal policy that deprived the Cherokees of millions
of acres.
</P>
<P>
   A century later, Smith will take office on Saturday as the
principal chief of the Cherokee Nation, and, like his
great-grandfather, who served in the Cherokee Senate, he is
assuming leadership at a time of crisis. For the last four years,
the Cherokees have engaged in political infighting so bitter that
it almost undermined their constitution and ultimately led to
intervention by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the priorities of his administration, Smith, a
48-year-old lawyer from the Tulsa suburbs, replied simply,
``Healing.''
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated 200,000 members, half of whom live here in
northeastern Oklahoma, the Cherokees are the country's
second-largest tribe, behind the Navajos. And they have enjoyed a
degree of prosperity and autonomy that has made them a model to
other tribes. Now Smith must restore confidence in the tribal
government not only among Cherokees but also among federal
officials, who stepped in two years ago at the height of the
tribe's crisis, after members brawled outside the tribal
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely important that the tribe come back together,
and I think it will,'' said Rennard Strickland, dean of the
University of Oregon School of Law, who is half-Cherokee and has
written five books about the tribe. ``The Cherokees have a very
long history of being able to heal these kinds of tribal divisions.
It has been a long 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   For many Cherokees, the last four years alone have seemed
interminable. The election of Joe Byrd as principal chief in 1995
followed the disqualification of his runoff opponent by the tribe's
highest court. That opponent, George Bearpaw, was ruled ineligible
because he had once pleaded guilty to an assault charge, though the
conviction was later expunged. Many Cherokees regarded Byrd's
victory as tainted, and his predecessor, Chief Wilma Mankiller,
refused to attend his inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the tribal government, with headquarters here at
Tahlequah, teetered on collapse. First, Byrd dismissed 15 members
of the Cherokees' marshals service who had executed a search
warrant of his office as part of an investigation into the
possibility of financial wrongdoing. Then, at the urging of Byrd,
eight members of the tribal council _ the seven other members were
absent _ ousted by impeachment the three justices on the court who
had issued the warrant. And on June 20 of that year, an armed
security force hired by Byrd seized the tribal courthouse and
locked out all the employees, a move tantamount to taking over the
judicial branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed that every month we would have a new problem,'' Ms.
Mankiller said the other day. ``Just when we would think things
wouldn't get any worse, they did.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom came on Aug. 13, 1997, when the fired marshals, led
by their director, Pat Ragsdale, tried to take back the courthouse
at the behest of the three impeached justices. A fight broke out
with Byrd's security force, and town police officers and county
deputies arrested Ragsdale. federal officers eventually came to
Tahlequah (pronounced TAH-luh-kwah), and Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt helped mediate the dispute. The justices were ultimately
reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 election, with a field of nine candidates, including
Chief Byrd, became a referendum on his administration. Respected
leaders like Ms. Mankiller and Julian Fite, a former U.S. attorney,
endorsed Ragsdale in the primary, but Smith, who had finished third
in 1995, built a coalition with an appeal to Cherokee tradition,
heritage and culture. He had worked as a tribal prosecutor, as well
as a public defender in Tulsa, and had served in two tribal
administrations. He had also taught Indian law and history at
several colleges, including Dartmouth.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Smith's candidacy was not without problems: It came out
during the primary that he had fathered three children outside his
marriage. But his wife, a former Miss Cherokee, issued a statement
titled ``In Support of My Husband,'' and when Smith emerged as
Byrd's runoff opponent, the defeated candidates and their backers
rallied behind him. He won by 1,600 votes, of about 13,000 cast, in
the runoff balloting last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of coalition that came together to bring in new
leadership and defeat this administration was really something that
I haven't seen in a long, long time,'' Ms. Mankiller said.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken Smith says his ``defining moment'' came on June
20, 1997, the day Byrd's officers seized the courthouse. County
deputies had cordoned off the building, essentially enforcing the
chief's takeover, but Smith ducked under the police tape. As he
began to walk toward the courthouse to protest, he was tackled and
arrested. He says he considered the seizure of the courthouse a
challenge to the legitimacy of the Cherokee Nation's government and
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges facing Smith and his new administration are
formidable. The Cherokees, who have no reservation per se but
exercise certain jurisdictional rights in 14 northeastern Oklahoma
counties under agreements with the state and federal governments,
operate on an annual budget of $150 million, about $90 million of
it from Washington. But the government, having found a lack of
accountability in the use of federal money, has placed the tribe
under a monthly draw for those grants, rather than yearly. Byrd
himself also faces misappropriation-of-funds charges brought by
tribal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week, Byrd denied any wrongdoing and said
that he had never overstepped his constitutional bounds. He said
that he would leave the tribe with a $12 million surplus in the
fiscal year and that under his leadership improvements had been
made in the tribe's high school and its business, Cherokee Nation
Industries, which builds computer boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're leaving the goose that lays the golden egg,'' said Byrd,
who remains popular among the people from whom he sprung, the
tribe's many rural Oklahomans.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and his allies are far less certain of the tribe's fiscal
health. Ms. Mankiller, whose daughters are now working on Smith's
transition team, said initial financial reviews had found a
bookkeeping mess. She said only one independent audit of government
finances had been conducted since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he planned to institute new rules and procedures to
ensure the tribe's fiscal integrity. He also hopes to promote
economic development, improve services and promote the Cherokees'
culture and heritage. At the inauguration, he said, he will plant a
tree on the courthouse grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It symbolizes rebirth,'' he said. ``We reach into our history,
and we try to honor it and remember it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
