<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FRANK-ECONOMICS-1STLD     08-13 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANK-ECONOMICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT FRANK: ECONOMIST WHO WOULD REIN IN GALLOPING CONSUMPTION
WITH A TAX  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to correct spelling of `galloping' in hed)   By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ITHACA, N.Y. _ On the bulletin board of Robert H. Frank's office
at Cornell University are two glossy photos.
</P>
<P>
   One is of a Porsche 911 Turbo, price $105,000. The other is of a
Patek Philippe Calibre '89 timepiece, price $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   They are not there as objects of lust, but they are not there
quite as objects of mere censorious academic disapproval either.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they symbolize the subject of Frank's work on the
psychology and utility of spending and the relative virtues of
public and private consumption. Indeed, Frank, whose newest book is
``Luxury Fever'' (Free Press, 1999), has become the popular
economist of the moment and academia's most conspicuous critic of
the dizzy spend-athon of the '90s. He argues that people are caught
in an arms race of consumption and that tax policies need to be
changed to encourage public investment over private spending.
</P>
<P>
   Frank's new-found celebrity _ he has become an opinion-page
regular of various newspapers and an ascendant talking head on
television _ has not come without criticism. Even some friendly
economists fault his work for being long on supposition and short
on data. And conservative economists say the government has no
business encouraging or discouraging people from buying luxury
goods they want.
</P>
<P>
   But even some who see his prescriptions as political nonstarters
concede that Frank has ventured into one of the most intriguing
thickets in economics and modern life: why people spend money, what
they spend it on, whether they spend it on the right things.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's smart for each individual may not make sense for the
group,'' said Frank, 54. ``It's very often smart for one, dumb for
all. It's my core idea. I've been pushing it for 25 years, but when
I wrote about it back in 1985, no one wanted to discuss it. I'm
glad people are listening now.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank, who has an undergraduate degree in mathematics, a masters
degree in statistics, and a doctorate in economics, has taken a
textbook route from cloistered academic to op-ed page regular and
talking head.
</P>
<P>
   His early books, like ``Choosing the Right Pond: Human Behavior
and the Quest for Status'' (Oxford University Press, 1985) focused
on rivalry and cooperation in economic and social behavior and were
written for a largely academic audience.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, Frank has emerged as a purveyer of
deceptively simple ideas that have skillfully tied economic issues
to broad social problems. In 1995, he and his co-author, Philip J.
Cook, published ``The Winner Take-All Society,'' which argued that
our economy and public life is being warped by a society
increasingly dominated by a few big winners and many losers.
Instead of thousands of privately owned coffee shops, there are now
thousands of Starbucks. Students, instead of happily going to their
local college, are funneled into a national sweepstakes in which
the lucky few get into Harvard. The outcome, they argue, is a
high-stress society that directs too many resources in the wrong
direction and generates wasteful spending patterns.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Luxury Fever: Why Money Fails to Satisfy in an Era of
Excess,'' Frank updates many of the ideas of ``Choosing the Right
Pond,'' to the Land Rover-stock options-Chateau Latour era. In the
earlier book, he examined the ways, as he saw it, in which ``people
come into the world equipped with an inner voice urging them to
rank as high as possible on whatever social hierarchy they belong
to.''
</P>
<P>
   In the new one, he analyzes the boom in luxury spending, whether
for a $5,000 Viking-Frontgate Professional Grill, a $17,500 Patek
Philippe wristwatch, a $1,800-a-night suite at the Four Seasons
Resort in Palm Beach, Fla., or a $48,000 Lexus LX450 sport-utility
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   He argues, as he did in ``Choosing the Right Pond,'' that
spending choices have more to do with comparative values than
absolute ones. A 3,000-square-foot house that would be a palace in
Japan, for example, or even in 1970s America, no longer measures up
if your neighbor's house has 4,000 square feet. If competitors are
wearing $1,500 suits to job interviews, you need to do the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   There are other critics of consumption, many of them allied with
the notion of ``voluntary simplicity,'' which argues for
individuals to scale down their lives and demands.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Unlike them, Frank contends that hyper-consumption can make
sense for individuals. If they want the best school district for
their child, it might make sense to buy an overpriced house in an
exclusive town. If others are driving enormous sport utilities
vehicles, people might not be safe in an economical,
environmentally friendly Honda Civic. Like a crowd of people at a
concert, who all decide to stand because the row in front of them
has done so, individual behavior _ standing at a concert, instead
of comfortably sitting _ can sometimes make sense if it is dictated
by group dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   The problems arise when the needs of the individual are contrary
to the needs of the group. The result of luxury fever, he argues,
is that individuals work too many hours and undergo too much
stress; that society neglects too many critical public needs,
ranging from better roads to cleaner air and water, at the expense
of often-frivolous private ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The left basically got it wrong from the beginning,'' said
Frank, who votes Democratic and is clearly closer to the left end
of the spectrum than the right. ``They said the market is bad
because the firms are too powerful and they take advantage of us.
They manipulate us through advertisements. They control the
political process. It's totally wrong. If there's something really
good out there, you'll buy it with or without advertising and if
there's a crumby thing, the ads can make you try it once, but you
won't come back. So corporations have an incentive to spend their
advertising dollars on things you are going to like.''
</P>
<P>
   The right, he said, gets it wrong by putting all its faith in
the wisdom of the market and the idea that individual demands give
the best outcomes for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, they do,'' he said. ``But often they don't. When
whatever I want has negative consequences for someone else, then
the invisible hand doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   To Frank, the solution does not lie in the good intentions of
the ``voluntary simplicity'' movement or the imposition of luxury
taxes on yachts or diamonds. Instead, he says, it lies in a
progressive tax on consumption _ not the conventional sales tax,
under which all purchasers pay the same thing, but a tax on total
spending, with rates increasing as spending increases. Consumption
would be calculated, essentially, by subtracting savings from
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The tax would act like boxing gloves or steroid bans, he said,
to keep the competition at a more sensible level by deterring
runaway spending on luxuries: the biggest houses and biggest boats
and costliest cars would tend to get smaller and less costly and
the restraints on spending would ripple down through society, just
as the luxury arms race now ripples up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, I love stuff,'' said Frank, who has a Saab and BMW in
the garage of his 1911 Arts and Crafts-style house in Ithaca, N.Y.
``I like cars. I like food and wine. I buy rugs and lamps. You
can't change human nature. You can just change the rules of the
game. You don't eliminate the race. You just make it cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Many mainstream economists applaud the idea of a consumption
tax, and say the idea makes sense, however dim its political
prospects may be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you don't use the argument Frank does about
consumption, it's an excellent way to encourage savings,'' said
Kenneth Arrow, a retired Stanford University economist and Nobel
laureate. And many liberal economists applaud Frank's ability to
put broad issues about consumption and public investment on the
table.
</P>
<P>
   To many free-market conservatives, however, Frank's scholarship
and newfound celebrity are equally suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Sherwin Rosen, an economist at the University of Chicago said
Frank's views on why people spend are based on supposition, not on
research. He said the government has no business telling people
what to spend money on, and the robust economy is eloquent
rejoinder to Frank's critique. And he argues that data showing an
alarmingly low savings rate fail to take into account the degree to
which a rising stock market has allowed people to accumulate wealth
in ways that savings figures do not measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should some guy in Ithaca be telling me what I should be
spending money on?'' he asked. ``How does he know why people spend?
He has no data, no proof. You can't have economic policy or
government involvement in the economy based on pure speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say an overall consumption tax is too crude an instrument,
one that would still allow people to spend on the most socially
harmful goods if they chose. Others said that a proposal, in
effect, to take resources from the rich and give them to the
government is the kind of solution only a liberal academic could
seriously propose at a time when politicians are battling over the
size of tax cuts. And conservatives argue that private spending is
more efficient than government spending, so a dollar taken from
consumption need not mean a dollar in services like better roads or
federal food inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Frank concedes that his argument can sound too simple,
particularly when he adds the seemingly contradictory kicker that
if people followed the incentives to save and invest rather than
spend, their extra earnings would allow them to spend even more
than they did earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even the critics tend to give credit to Frank for being
onto something truly vexing and insufficiently examined in American
life at a time houses built in this country have doubled in size
since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Hirshleifer, a retired University of California at Los
Angeles economist, reviewed ``Luxury Fever'' unfavorably in the
publication ``Reason.'' But he concluded: ``Still, I am inclined to
defend Frank in one important respect: as a moralist and a
Jeremiah. If our society is to remain at its barely civilized
level, from time to time we do need to be reproved for the
vulgarity of wasteful consumption, not to mention the in-your-face
boorishness currently recommended by ideologies of
self-assertiveness and self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank sees his work as scholarship, not moralizing. But he is
comfortable with the degree to which his work has taken economic
issues and raised overarching social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been natural for me to think of everything as an
economic question,'' he said. ``It's all choice. It's all scarcity.
You want to do more of one thing, you have to do less of another.
Money is just a unit of accounting to think about how much we care
about different things. I think one of the problems with economics
is that it has insisted on too narrow a model of human nature, too
impoverished a view of social interaction. You can't explain
everything as trying to squeeze our every ounce from the bottom
line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
