<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6799 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-IOWA-CONSERVATIVES-NY     08-13 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-CONSERVATIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS CONSERVATIVES VIE FOR STRONG SHOWING IN IOWA POLL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IOWA-POLL) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES _ Becky Bell, a corn and soybean farmer from Malvern,
Iowa, bounded up to Patrick Buchanan at the State Fair here Friday
with words of encouragement on the eve of the Republican Party's
straw poll. ``Good luck, Pat!'' she said as the candidate, sporting
a red, white and blue tie, broke into a smile.
</P>
<P>
   But moments later, when Drew Ivers, Buchanan's state chairman,
tried to sign up Mrs. Bell as a backer, she demurred, saying she
was still browsing _ and was quite taken by Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's between him and Bauer,'' said Mrs. Bell, 46. ``It's a
hard choice. We need someone with principles and values who stands
up for Americans. We need it for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivers, who ran Buchanan's operation here in 1996, knew Mrs.
Bell's dilemma all too well. He told her that he had almost gone
with Bauer himself before he signed on with Buchanan again several
months ago. ``I had to wrestle with it, too,'' he said. ``If I was
in a foxhole, I'd have equal faith in Pat Buchanan and Gary
Bauer.''
</P>
<P>
   There are really two contests going on in Saturday's important
but nonbinding straw poll. Beyond the big-money rivalry between
Texas Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and publishing mogul Steve
Forbes, a hard-fought competition is under way among several
contenders hoping to emerge as the champion of religious
conservatives. These candidates make the case that Bush, despite
his success winning over some conservative leaders, is too
pragmatic to champion causes like halting abortions, encouraging
prayer in schools and taking sex and violence out of movies.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike four years ago, when Buchanan had much of the
conservative field to himself, this time he finds himself in
competition with Bauer; former Vice President Dan Quayle; radio
talk show host Alan Keyes, and even Forbes, who is making an
energetic play for social conservatives. Elizabeth Dole, though
more moderate on social issues than the others, has also emphasized
her Christian beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not frustrated by it at all,'' said Buchanan, who faces an
uphill drive to replicate his third-place finish in the straw poll
four years ago. ``But it's a tougher race in terms of folks' being
well organized early and knowing the importance of it. But you go
with the flow. You've got to adjust and adapt to the conditions,
and we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The dream of these contenders is to pull a surprise Saturday by
following the model of Pat Robertson, who stunned the political
establishment, not to say the two leading contenders, Sen. Bob Dole
and Vice President George Bush, when he triumphed in the straw poll
of 1987. Relying on networks of loyal, grassroots backers based in
churches, he captured 34 percent of the vote and immediately
emerged as a national leader of religious conservatives. But
Robertson lost the 1988 Republican nomination; and in fact, no
victor in the straw poll has ever made it to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Most campaigns expect Forbes and Bush to take the top two slots
in the straw poll, a significant early test for the candidates even
though not an impartial indication of voter sentiment. Forbes, who
in his campaign four years ago enraged religious conservatives on
the eve of the Iowa caucuses by asserting that ``the Christian
Coalition does not speak for most Christians,'' is pumping
resources into winning them over this time.
</P>
<P>
   One glossy mailing the Forbes campaign sent throughout Iowa
declares, ``Steve Forbes has become the leader of America's
conservative movement.'' Another mailing features a baby on the
cover, with the headline, ``If you don't respect this child. . .,''
followed inside by a photograph of a judge with the headline, ``You
won't wear this robe.'' The mailing assures Republicans that Forbes
``won't appoint judges to the federal bench if they do not value
unborn children.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Forbes, several Republican strategists and organizers
here raised the prospect that Bauer, who has worked through the
churches to build an aggressive grassroots network, has the
potential to emerge as a force. He also benefits from the
grassroots network established by the conservative organization he
headed, the Family Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Bauer, as a result of the fact that he has worked the
churches _ it's a niche he has found _ he can do well,'' said Rep.
John Kasich, R-Ohio, withdrew from the race in July.
</P>
<P>
   At event after event, the Bauer campaign distributes cards
asking people to sign up to be ``a contact at my church'' or to
become ``a part of the Bauer Prayer network.'' They also pass out
copies of testimony Bauer delivers at churches in which he says,
``I know that you, with Christ working in your lives, can help
transform our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said in an interview, ``I've heard this sort of buzz that
I might do better than expected.'' But then, perhaps seeking to
contain expectations, he played down the role of the churches. ``In
the last four or five months, I have visited a number of
churches,'' he said. ``This is not a Pat Robertson-type operation.
But when somebody writes and says, `I'm a supporter of yours and I
go to such and such a church,' of course we say to them, `try to
find some people in your church.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At a picnic last Sunday in the tiny town of Huxley, Joyce
Andrews, 38, greeted Bauer with other supporters who chanted,
``Bauer Power!'' and told the candidate, ``I saw you at church this
morning.'' She turned to a friend and gushed, ``He was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has not ruled out the possibility of seeking the Reform
Party's nomination should he fare poorly Saturday. And many
Republican strategists say Quayle might have to bail out unless he
places well. His campaign chairman, Kyle McSlarrow, said he was
closely watching Forbes because ``he really cuts into our base.''
</P>
<P>
   McSlarrow said he was trying to get Reggie White, the Green Bay
Packers star who called homosexuality ``one of the biggest sins in
the Bible,'' to appear on behalf of Quayle at the straw poll. But
he conceded that White has also been a staunch backer of Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that the battle for conservative issues is only
beginning, several conservative groups placed a two-page
advertisement in The Des Moines Register on Friday calling on the
candidates to sign pledges affirming the strength of marriage and
opposing ''the promotion of homosexuality as normative in America's
public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle insisted that he had no idea how he will do. ``I'm just
focused on getting as many people as we can that support us to
Ames, Iowa,'' he said. ``I don't know how the other candidates are
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer offered this assessment: ``I can't get my arms around it.
I'll go to an event and there will be 75 people there, and I'm
floating until my next stop. And then I get out and there's two
people _ and one of them is there by mistake. And I'm thinking,
`Why did I do this.?'''
</P>
<P>
   But Donald and Betty Hanson, Bauer supporters from northeast
Iowa who are in their late 70s, said they were hopeful. ``He's a
man of integrity _ and nothing is impossible with the Lord,''
Hanson said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hanson added, ``The Lord is in control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
