<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ALL RYDER REMARKS ARE CHARITABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ Officially, the word from the Ryder Cup rebels
on the U.S. team is that they would be happy with a chance to
direct charitable donations generated by the event and no longer
are pushing to be paid for their services.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, Tiger Woods, Mark O'Meara and Phil Mickelson _ the
four players singled out Tuesday for selfish attitudes by U.S.
captain Ben Crenshaw _ all reiterated yesterday that they would be
satisfied with a say in directing donations from the Sept. 24-26
event, which is expected to generate a $23 million profit.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow players, however, question if that truly is the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's bull,'' said Paul Azinger, a three-time Ryder Cup
participant. ``It wasn't about charity at first. That's just spin
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Players present in a Tuesday meeting with Ryder Cup officials
said Davis Love III expressed exasperation with the play-for-pay
quartet when he told them: ``Let's be honest, this isn't about
charity. It's about putting money in your pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, players would receive a tax break from such donations.
But Duval seemed mystified that people would question the sincerity
of his charitable intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know how that works. I'm not at all looking for
a tax break,'' Duval said. ``That's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in the estimation of Brad Faxon, who suggested the U.S. team
would be better off with lesser players willing to represent their
country for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``This talk about the money going for charity is a crock,''
Faxon said. ``I know a lot of guys ... who would pay to play on
that team. I think we would be better off having them than the guys
who are complaining about how much they're not getting.''
Second-guessing semantics After helping stir up the Ryder Cup
controversy by terming the event ``an exhibition'' and scoffing at
its $5,000 travel stipend, David Duval said he regrets making those
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't have joked about the stipend,'' Duval said. ``And
calling it an `exhibition' might have been a poor choice of
words.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is exactly the term Tiger Woods continues to use in
reference to the event, much to the chagrin of its organizers and
Ben Crenshaw. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a winner's check?,'' Woods asked.
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it's an exhibition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Duval drew the ire of Crenshaw when he joked about
the Ryder Cup's paltry travel stipend by saying he ``just might
take that money and retire.'' Kendall's record day Skip Kendall
broke the Medinah Country Club course record in yesterday's second
round, bagging seven birdies in his first 10 holes en route to a
7-under 65. Kendall, who opened with a 74, collected eight birdies
and one bogey in eclipsing the previous mark of 66, held by five
others, including first-round leader Sergio Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only missed one fairway all day, and I birdied that hole,''
Kendall said. ``It was one of those rounds you dream about,
especially in a major.'' Many happy returns After withdrawing from
the tournament Thursday morning, Steve Elkington gave his golf bag
to a young spectator and headed to a Chicago hospital to visit his
caddie, Joe ``Gypsy'' Grillo, who was hospitalized with chest
pains.
</P>
<P>
   One problem.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington forgot to remove a pouch filled with personal items,
including his wedding ring and some prescription medications,
before giving away the bag. So he asked TNT announcers to make a
plea during yesterday's telecast for the return of those items.
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter, Scott Kent of Winfield, Ill., received a call
at work from a neighbor who had seen the telecast and knew that
Elkington had given his bag to Ryan Kent, Scott's 4-year-old son.
By 6 p.m., tournament officials had reunited Elkington with his
pouch and Ryan Kent had a souvenir _ as well as a story for the
ages _ as a memento of his first trip to a professional golf
tournament.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
