<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-GARZON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIANS OUTRAGED AS BELOVED HUMORIST, PEACE ACTIVIST SHOT TO
DEATH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Castano) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ Jaime Garzon, who was Colombia's most beloved
humorist and an occasional go-between in the nation's peace
process, was shot dead Friday by two motorcycle gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   Garzon, 38, was shot four times in the head and chest while
driving to the Radionet station in Bogota, where he was host of a
popular morning program, Colombian police said.
</P>
<P>
   As his Jeep Cherokee slowed through an intersection, the gunmen
opened fire, a witness told Bogota's Caracol television station,
where Garzon also worked. ``There was nothing we could do,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Colombians were outraged. Television and radio stations carried
extensive coverage of the investigation, and the entire country
seemed to go into mourning. A friend, actor Luis Fernando Orozco,
explained Garzon's appeal. ``It's as if, in the United States, they
had assassinated Woody Allen,'' he said, adding: ``It's the
equivalent of killing Charlie Chaplin.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said they suspected that Garzon was slain by gunmen for a
right-wing death squad. According to friends and police, Garzon had
received death threats in the past week and was trying to arrange a
meeting with the country's top paramilitary leader, Carlos Castano,
to discuss the warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Garzon's comedy routines and his work as a radio and
print journalist, he was also a committed peace activist. He had
promoted talks between Colombia's rebel groups and the government
to end the 35-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Navarro Wolf, a Colombian congressman, said Garzon had
told him about the threats. ``I told him 'Jaime, this is serious.
In this country, they kill people.'
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point,'' the congressman said, ``he had bodyguards, but
then he got tired of it. This morning, he was by himself.``
</P>
<P>
   Tearful fans placed flowers, messages and Colombian flags at the
scene of the slaying. University students demonstrated in the
streets, and protests against political violence were planned for
Saturday in Bogota and other Colombian cities.
</P>
<P>
   President Andres Pastrana canceled a trip to the Colombian
interior and named a commission to investigate the killing. The
government put out a $268,000 reward for information leading to
arrest of the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaime identified with the feelings of average Colombians. Like
all Colombians, I am very sad,'' said Pastrana, who vowed that the
gunmen would be captured and punished.
</P>
<P>
   Police launched a citywide dragnet, impounding more than 600
motorcycles and detaining a handful of people. But they refused to
say whether they considered anyone as a suspect in the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Garzon rose to fame through his scathing political satire and
spoofs of figures ranging from Pastrana to Napoleon to talk-show
host Larry King.
</P>
<P>
   In one long-running gag, while impersonating the Colombian
president, Garzon would call up ambitious politicians and offer
them ministerial posts.
</P>
<P>
   His most famous TV character was a toothless, down-and-out shoe
shine man who would polish the footwear of the rich and famous
while making biting social commentary.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he traveled to the Colombian jungles with a camera
crew to shine the combat boots of a Marxist guerrilla leader.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Pastrana named Garzon to a commission to jump-start
negotiations with the rebel National Liberation Army, or ELN, the
smaller of Colombia's two major guerrilla groups. Following several
guerrilla kidnappings, Garzon served as an intermediary between
rebels and families of hostages. He also arranged several press
conference for rebel leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Such activism may have angered the paramilitaries, who number
about 5,000 and have been waging a terror campaign against the
rebels and their civilian supporters, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything indicates that Carlos Castano was responsible,''
one high-ranking police investigator told Radionet.
</P>
<P>
   The paramilitaries, who have at times received covert support
from the Colombian army, have criticized the government's peace
strategy. They have also killed journalists, human rights workers
and government officials whom they have branded as guerrilla
collaborators.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement, the main paramilitary umbrella group denied
involvement in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not willing to accept responsibility for acts that are
contrary to our struggle and are recklessly attributed to us,''
said the statement, signed by the United Self-Defense Groups of
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   A stream of government ministers, journalists, actors and
friends visited the Radionet studios to denounce the crime and pay
tribute to Garzon. Throughout the day, the station played ``Taps.``
</P>
<P>
   Colombia is the most dangerous nation in the hemisphere for
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Pastrana condemning the Garzon murder, the
Miami-based Inter American Press Association noted that 82
Colombian journalists have been slain in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
