<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6809 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-TEN-GRAF-RETIRE-ART-2     08-13 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-GRAF-RETIRE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEFFI GRAF, ANNOUNCING RETIREMENT, GOES OUT WITH NO REGRETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Down and almost out of her 1999 French Open final against
Martina Hingis, the indomitable Steffi Graf narrowed her eyes,
squared her shoulders and stalked to her changeover chair. That
Saturday in early June, she gave herself a terse pep talk that
would, in a matter of minutes, reignite her powerful strokes and
reduce her top-ranked opponent to a sobbing runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last time you'll sit in this chair, so you better
make her earn it,'' Graf told herself about the Grand Slam event,
definitely her last in Paris and potentially her last ever.
</P>
<P>
   After making a career of ignoring whatever and whoever was
across the net, not out of arrogance but out of a conviction that
what mattered most was the purity of the strokes she produced with
her racquet, Graf had done it again: 29 years old, with an ache in
her back and a tug in her heart that told her there might be no
more Slam finals in her future.
</P>
<P>
   Graf steeled herself to win her 896th _ but in that moment her
most important _ match.
</P>
<P>
   That was the way she wanted to go out, as a winner, and just
after winning her seventh French Open, Graf calmly announced that
she'd never be back again: ``This is an incredible moment that I've
had; I just want to keep it the way it is.'' Keeping things close
to perfect on the tennis court had been a way of life since she
turned professional at 13; playing for the memories was something
she began to do this year in earnest because she suspected that,
for her, there would be no next year.
</P>
<P>
   Graf's perfectionist strivings and unreachable forehands carried
her to 107 singles titles as well as a virtual monopoly of the
number one ranking at the extended peak of her 17-year career, but
Friday from her home in Heidelberg, Germany, she announced her
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, she had said that her French Open and
Wimbledon campaigns would be her last. Friday, less than a month
before the U.S. Open, where she was still scheduled to compete, she
said that her nonpareil career was over, effective immediately.
With her decision, she joined a Hall of Fame roster of 1999
retirees that include Michael Jordan in basketball, John Elway in
football and Wayne Gretzky in hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel the time is right to move on,'' said the
30-year-old Graf, only the fifth player and third woman beside
Maureen Connolly (1953) and Margaret Court (1970) to accomplish a
Grand Slam by winning the sport's four crown jewels, the Australian
Open, the French Open, Wimbledon, and the U.S. Open, in a calendar
year, in 1988. Later that year, she won the gold medal at the Seoul
Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   A partial list of Graf' other accomplishments are equally
remarkable:
</P>
<P>
   _ She is the only player, male or female, to win all four Grand
Slam events four times.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1987, she reached the final of every event she played,
which no other player has done since the Open era began in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   _ Her on-court earnings surpass $21 million, the most for any
female athlete in any sport.
</P>
<P>
   _ She assumed the No. 1 ranking for the first time on August 17,
1987, and her 186 consecutive weeks at the top remain unmatched by
any player, male or female. In all, Graf accumulated a record 377
weeks at No. 1 and finished more seasons at the top than any other
player: from 1987-1996, she ended the season ranked No. 1 eight
times in 10 years, another untouched record.
</P>
<P>
   But records and rankings meant little to Graf.
</P>
<P>
   She said Navratilova's record nine Wimbledon titles were safe
from her, and after collecting her 22nd slam crown in Paris this
June, she denied that the proximity to Court's record 24 would
serve as inspiration for prolonging her career.
</P>
<P>
   Graf's motivational forces were internal, not external. And she
never longed for the sort of rivalry shared by Navratilova and
Evert because her main opponent was always herself. Perfection was
her goal in every match, and her consistent pursuit of perfection
left her with a 902-115 win-loss record and a winning percentage of
.887, second only to Evert's .900.
</P>
<P>
   Graf later said her victory at Roland Garros against top-ranked
Martina Hingis, her only title this year and her first Grand Slam
title since she won the 1996 U.S. Open, was all the more special
because it happened unexpectedly. Sidelined by leg and back
problems this spring, Graf had entered the French Open merely to
gird herself for Wimbledon, her favorite tournament, and not to
eclipse the field and tie Evert's record of success there. Less
than a month later despite ``running on fumes,'' she reached the
Wimbledon final, only to lose to Lindsay Davenport, who by then was
the new No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Despite saying after Wimbledon and the French Open that she
would never play those tournament again, the German had been
characteristically secretive about her retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   The introverted Graf, wary of trying to combine actual
competition with the distracting hoopla of a farewell tour the way
her predecessors Chris Evert and Martina Navratilova had, preferred
to say that she had no plan to quit and would compete until she
stopped enjoying the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Graf, renowned for being a self-starter, notorious for her
marathon practice sessions and incessant off-court training
regimen, realized that she'd lost her resolve after losing in the
Wimbledon final and preparing for the summer hard court season in
advance of the Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motivation to perform at the highest level was no longer
there, and the fun had gone out of practicing and training,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   She did not trace her retirement to the wear and tear of
cumulative injuries. Nor did she blame the hamstring pull that
provoked her to abandon what turned out to be the last match of her
career, a second-round loss against Amy Frazier last week in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Graf pinpointed the dissipation of what had been her
most reliable, and most feared, mental attribute: her unflagging
will to excel. In the end, said Graf, it wasn't her finely-honed
body but her finely-tuned motivation that began to fail her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt right after Paris and Wimbledon that the motivation
wasn't what it was in the past,'' said Graf. ``I thought long and
hard after Wimbledon about where I wanted to go and what I wanted
to do with my tennis, and for the first time in my career, I didn't
feel like going to a tournament.'' While her abdication was not
without tears, the 3rd-ranked Graf said she had no regrets about
the timing of her decision, which comes two weeks before the start
of the U.S. Open, a slam she's won five times: ``I've done
everything I wanted to do in tennis. I haven't had one second
thought.''
</P>
<P>
   What Graf had experienced lately, said her longtime coach, Heinz
Gunthardt, were second thoughts not about retiring but about
continuing to play: when Graf first mentioned retirement two years
ago during a lengthy recuperation from knee surgery, Gunthardt
cautioned her about leaving the game too soon. This year he didn't
dissuade her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt she had earned the privilege to quit anytime she likes;
after all, what was there that she hadn't already accomplished at
least once,'' Gunthardt said of the only player, male or female, to
win all four slams at least four times. ``The French was like a
fairy tale ending, and Wimbledon came close, but even during
Wimbledon she was running on empty a little bit; she didn't enjoy
it as much as she'd expected she would, and she was completely
empty afterward. Steffi was never one to play for records or
titles: she played for love of the game, and when you take that
away, what's there?''
</P>
<P>
   Initially coached by her father, Peter, whose skirmishes with
German tax authorities over his misrepresentation of her more than
$20 million in prize money eventually led to a jail term, Graf
broke into the game in 1982 at 13, the youngest player to turn
professional.
</P>
<P>
   By her own measure, she not an instant success: skinny and
lacking in strategy, it took the gangly teenager more than three
years to win the first of her 107 WTA titles. But the first, a 6-4,
7-5 defeat of Evert at Hilton Head in 1986, was a harbinger of
bigger upsets soon to come. Later that year, Graf ambushed the
top-ranked Navratilova in the Berlin final, and in 1987, Graf
captured her inaugural slam championship with a 6-4, 4-6, 8-6
decision against Navratilova at the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   Graf was, according to Evert and Navratilova, emblematic of a
new generation of power player: insulated by an entourage, largely
uninterested in the game's history, obsessed with excellence,
satisfied by nothing less than a championship.
</P>
<P>
   While Graf has been upstaged by a rash of teen-age newcomers
_Hingis, Venus and Serena Williams, and Anna Kournikova _who seem
to model their on-court hauteur after hers, her tunnel-vision quest
for the perfect match isn't likely to find replication in a new
generation of players for whom image looms almost as important as
results.
</P>
<P>
   And in Germany, a tennis-hungry nation stung also by the
official retirement of Boris Becker, the loss of Graf has
devastating implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without her, I'm not very optimistic about the future of
women's tennis in Germany,'' said Karl Weber, head of the German
Tennis Federation.
</P>
<P>
   But Phil de Picciotto, president of Graf's U.S. management firm,
Advantage International, specified that her future plans include
sponsorship of several German prospects and some consulting work
with the German Fed Cup team. Graf will also embark in December on
a six-month exhibition tour that opens in South Africa, a nation
she's never visited, but one where she's involved in charity work
with underprivileged children as well as the World Wildlife
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always so disciplined in her tennis that everything
else was a distanced priority,'' he said. ``I think she's relieved
and calm that she can finally explore some of the other sides of
her personality. Once she saw her motivation level diminish, but
still being a perfectionist, she knew it was time to make it
official and leave tennis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
