<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR STOCK TECHNICIANS, GLOOM AMID ALL THE CHEER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as stocks rose like a phoenix from their slump late last
summer and advanced to new highs this year, market technicians
looked at their charts and grumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Major averages are now off their peaks, but the technicians are
still edgy. In the charted world of new highs and new lows,
advance-decline lines _ which measure the number of stocks rising
in price against those that are losing value _ and 200-day moving
averages, these are not sunny days.
</P>
<P>
   Trends are important to the technicians, who are paid to follow
the movements of stocks and bonds, not companies or industries or
the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The trends just now are troubling them. Alan R. Shaw, director
of technical research at Salomon Smith Barney, took some time last
week to talk about those trends, and about why the Dow Jones
industrial average might still wind up at 20,000 in the next few
years despite his concerns. Here are excerpts from the
conversation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. To the uninitiated, technical analysis looks a lot like what
the folks who compile and massage baseball statistics do for a
living. Is that a fair comparison?
</P>
<P>
   A. We are navigators as well as scorekeepers. We try to read the
charts and maps and figure out the course we are covering as well
as see if the trend we are witnessing might be in the process of
reversing itself.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are the charts telling you?
</P>
<P>
   A. One of the things we have learned is that if you go back
through history, if you see a divergence between the
advance-decline line and price averages, there has always been,
with some degree of time lag, a period when the averages give up.
</P>
<P>
   The advance-decline line is the army, and the average, the Dow
for example, is the general. If we start to witness a trend where
the army is in a phase of retreat, if it continues, history is
replete with evidence that the generals will follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the advance-decline line has had a lack of confirmation
with the market averages since April 1998. And in the last week or
so there have been a number of sessions when the number of stocks
falling in price was extraordinarily greater than those which rose
in price.
</P>
<P>
   This is not positive stuff. It is telling you the phase of
direction is in retreat. And you can also see this regression in
the ratio of stocks making new 52-week lows to those that are
hitting new highs. That is worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some analysts are arguing that interest rates have risen too
much, and that yields _ now well over 6 percent on the long bond _
will move lower from here. Do you agree?
</P>
<P>
   A. We went negative on bonds in early January and have remained
defensive since then, and we are worried about a further spike in
rates. I would not like to see bond yields move above 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Conceptually, though, we still believe the long-term trend in
rates is down.
</P>
<P>
   And just as interest rates fell too much last fall because
investors sought safety in Treasuries, right now they are
overshooting on the upside.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You see the potential for an additional 15 percent to 20
percent correction in market averages from these levels. But you
are of the view that the market could go higher, much higher, after
that. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A. Lots of things are at work.
</P>
<P>
   We think there is a likeness to 1957. We had a major shift in
market leadership around then, and we think that now there is a
shift from consumer goods to capital goods, with a primary emphasis
on technology. And there might be some evidence that the big bull
market that began in 1982 is possibly in its early stages of coming
to an end, with sequential toppings in sectors and groups.
</P>
<P>
   The bull market in the '50s and '60s started to top out in 1956
and 1957. But from 1957 to 1966 the Dow still doubled. But it did
so with a different leadership in which fewer and fewer stocks
participated. So we still think there is a chance the Dow could
reach 15,000 or 20,000 before this run ends.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What sorts of stocks will get the market to those levels?
</P>
<P>
   A. We continue to believe that the only way the market will get
to 15,000 or more is if the technology sector continues to be the
leader.
</P>
<P>
   In technology, we like computer hardware companies like IBM,
Hewlett-Packard and Gateway, electrical equipment companies like
General Electric, Rockwell International and Solectron. We have
been very bullish on EMC, the leading computer peripheral company,
and on Intel and Texas Instruments, semiconductor companies.
</P>
<P>
   And we also like Tyco International, Minnesota Mining, Allied
Signal and Illinois Tool as diversified manufacturing companies.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there groups you would avoid?
</P>
<P>
   A. In our view, many of the groups that were the leaders from
1982 to 1993, specifically food, tobacco and soft drinks, are in a
structural bear market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
