<HEADER>
A6815 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PROFILE-SANDS-ART     08-13 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-SANDS-ART-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SUPERHEROES ON WALL STREET  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MICHAEL STROUD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At age 76, Stan Lee is a popular guy. Fresh from
signing autographs last week for hordes of fans at Siggraph, the
country's premiere computer graphics show, the creator of
Spider-Man, the Fantastic Four, X-Men and other modern superheroes
was trying to conduct an interview outside the Convention Center
here. But he kept getting sidetracked by well-wishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to shake the hand of one of the greatest men of
this century,'' said Lance Powell, who works for the game company
Adrenalin Interactive Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why stop at this century?'' Lee asked, throwing up his arms in
mock frustration. ``I hate people like you!''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, whose grey-black hair and robust manner make him seem 10
years younger, is about to see how popular he is with Wall Street.
Stan Lee Media Inc., his first independent venture after more than
five decades with Marvel Enterprises, will begin trading Monday on
the NASDAQ market. Last week, the company completed its takeover of
Boulder Capital Opportunities Inc., a thinly traded company created
expressly to merge with another company. Monday, Boulder Capital's
ticker symbol, BCOI, will be replaced by SLEE.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Lee Media's mission: drive his millions of fans worldwide
to Stanlee.net, where he will introduce a new breed of Web-based
superheroes this fall. The company, based in Encino, Calif.,
intends to make money through licensing, electronic commerce,
advertising, sponsorship, Internet auctions, 3D movies, toys, TV
shows and anything else that Lee, his business partner, Peter Paul,
and their 42-person staff can dream up.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's name has already lured some heavy hitters. The
Oscar-winning special effects supervisor Mark Lasoff now works for
him; IBM, seeing a platform to promote its latest graphics
equipment, is outfitting his digital studio free, and Time Warner
Inc.'s Warner Bros. Online is promoting Lee's characters as part of
its 400,000-member Acme City online community, where fans can build
their own Warner Bros.-branded home pages free.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Warner Bros. Online will start offering 20 megabytes
of free Web space to anyone who registers at Acme City's Stan Lee
site.
</P>
<P>
   Lee did not need to convince Warner Bros. Online's president,
Jim Moloshok; as a kid he watched Lee's scary Spider-Man TV series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pleasure to work with the man who kept me up at
night,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Lee, ``I've never had more fun,'' he said, striding off
for a two-hour drive to a San Diego comics convention. ``I feel
like a kid again.''
</P>
<P>
   A kid with equity: Lee's 35 percent stake in Stan Lee Media is
worth nearly $27 million.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Paul, Lee and a small group of private investors
to skip an initial public offering _ through the merger with
Boulder Capital _ and leap right into the market was driven at
least partly by a desire to spare the aging icon grueling roadshows
and investor grilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be the best use of his energy,'' said Paul, a
lawyer who has brokered deals for celebrities like Salvador Dali
and Muhammad Ali. ``He's a creative guy, not a businessman.''
</P>
<P>
   That lesson was evident in Lee's last years at Marvel. Locked
into a lifetime contract as chairman that left him largely
powerless, Lee watched helplessly as overexpansion forced the
company to seek bankruptcy-law protection in 1996, and the
investors Ronald O. Perelman and Carl Icahn fought bitterly for
control. Today Marvel is controlled by Toy Biz, a consortium of
banks and an investment group.
</P>
<P>
   For Lee the ordeal proved a blessing. Eager to cut costs, the
new owners asked him to renegotiate his lifetime contract. Paul and
a New York lawyer, Arthur Lieberman, persuaded the group to name
Lee chairman emeritus of Marvel for a seven-figure salary, while
allowing him to spend most of his time at the new venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in my life, I can do things that belong to
me,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, who met Lee 10 years ago while recruiting him to head a
nonprofit group, dreamed up Stan Lee Media while watching in
frustration as Marvel's button-down owners repeatedly bypassed Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took the century's most prolific storyteller and
character creator and relegated him to consultant status,'' Paul
said. ``They missed an opportunity to create greater franchises.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee has churned out 28 new characters and 15 plot lines for the
company so far, enough to enable it to continue growing even if Lee
is no longer around.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to him excitedly discuss his first Internet project,
his absence is hard to imagine. ``It's about youthful beta testers
mystically transported over the Web to another dimension where an
evil warlord's super-villains are preparing to invade our
unsuspecting dimension through the Internet's enchanted Seventh
Portal,'' he explained. ``The frightening thought occurs to me:
what if this isn't fiction?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
