u f BC-ALUMINUM-ALCOA-NYT &LR;      08-13 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALUMINUM-ALCOA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REYNOLDS METALS, SOUGHT BY ALCOA, NOW HAS ANOTHER SUITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reynolds Metals Co. is now officially in play.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Alcoa Inc., the world's largest aluminum
producer, offered to buy Reynolds in a half-cash, half-stock deal
valued at $5.8 billion, another bidder emerged Friday with a
higher, all-cash offer. McCook Metals, a metals company owned by
the Chicago investment firm Michigan Avenue Partners, delivered a
letter to Reynolds management Friday, saying it wanted to buy the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Alcoa deal is anti-competitive and bad for the industry,
but we know that we can make Reynolds profitable again,'' said
Michigan Avenue chairman Michael Lynch. ``Ours was a friendly
bearhug letter, because we're one of the white knights out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter did not specify a price, but did say that McCook
would pay more than Alcoa. Analysts and investment bankers say they
think the offer is somewhere between $67.50 a share and $72 a
share. Alcoa's offer came to $65 a share.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, Reynolds shares had already surpassed Alcoa's offer,
closing at $69.375, up $3. Shares of Alcoa fell $1.25 Friday, to
$66.50.
</P>
<P>
   How McCook will finance a Reynolds deal remains unclear. A spate
of wire service stories Friday said that the company was backed by
GE Capital Corp. and Bear Stearns. One even suggested that General
Electric Co. chairman John Welch was supporting the deal himself.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital has been involved in financing some small McCook
purchases in the past, but insists it has no part in the current
offer. ``We are not backing them for this bid,'' said Mary Horn, a
GE Capital spokeswoman. Bear Stearns also has not put up funds.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch would not divulge his funding sources. But he insisted
that ``We are a well received player in the aluminum business, Bear
Stearns is our adviser, and we have the financial capability to do
this deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The new offer comes after widespread speculation that Pechiney
of France, the Alusuisse Lonza Group of Switzerland and Alcan
Aluminium of Canada, the three big aluminum companies involved in
their own three-way merger, will come in with their own bid, either
as a group or separately. People familiar with those talks say that
the companies had felt no rush to make a counteroffer to Alcoa,
because they believed that an Alcoa-Reynolds hookup would be
scuttled by American regulatory authorities.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say that a deal between Reynolds and McCook, which
is small and has few products that overlap with Reynolds, would be
unlikely to trigger antitrust problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're focused on the merger that we've announced, and we have
no plans for Reynolds right now,'' said Daniel Gagnier, vice
president for corporate affairs at Alcan, which will be the
surviving entity in the three-way merger. ``But anything's possible
and the situation is fluid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reynolds board is scheduled to meet Sunday to discuss the
Alcoa deal, and Louanne Nabhan, a Reynolds spokeswoman, said the
company would not comment on ``this new information that is
circulating in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa issued a statement saying, ``We are the only ones who have
a bona fide offer on the table for Reynolds to consider.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reynolds shareholders, who have been pressuring Reynolds to
seek a buyer for some time, are now demanding that the board form a
committee, hire advisers and auction the company off. ``They've got
to open it up for a bidding war,'' said Edgar Wachenheim, chairman
of Greenhaven Associates Inc., an investment management firm in
Purchase, N.Y., that owns about 1.5 million Reynolds shares.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds shareholders have been furious ever since Reynolds
rejected a $60 a share offer from Alcoa in March; Alcoa's stock has
run up so nicely since then that by now, that deal's value would
have been close to $96 a share.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen of the largest Reynolds shareholders met in
New York last month to discuss their dissatisfaction with Reynolds'
apparent unwillingness to consider a sale. Yet investors say that
as recently as last week Jeremiah J. Sheehan, the chairman of
Reynolds, was telling them that he was not actively seeking to sell
the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry said, `If someone wants us, they can pick up the phone
and call,''' said Richard Grubman, an investor at Highfields
Capital Management, which owns 6.5 percent of Reynolds shares. ``We
said, `you've got to solicit the highest bid.''
</P>
<P>
   The board may not have the option of refusing. Reynolds' bylaws
say that its directors can be replaced at any time. Disgruntled
shareholders have implied that they would propose their own slate
of directors if the board does not solicit bids.
</P>
<P>
   Both Grubman and Wachenheim say they think Reynold's assets are
worth $95 a share, and that the company would be a bargain at $75.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Reynolds has gone through a major restructuring in the
last few years. It has sold its lackluster fabrication and canned
sheet plants. But it retained its lucrative packaging division,
which includes such well-known names as Reynolds Wrap, and its
aluminum smelting operations. Although Reynolds is a high-cost
producer in the United States, about 53 percent of its smelting is
in Canada, where costs are routinely lower than here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a much better-positioned company than Wall Street
or the press give its credit for,'' Wachenheim said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year Reynolds had talked about spinning off its
packaging operations, which are highly profitable, to shareholders.
Wachenheim believes that if it had done so, the packaging company's
stock would be selling at $30, Reynolds itself would be selling at
$40, and by law, it would have protection against a takeover for
two years. ``It was probably a strategic mistake on their part,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Alcoa said it would sooner walk away from the
deal than pay even $70 a share. ``People who talk about Reynolds
being worth $95 are forgetting about taxes, about debt, about
operating profits that are only about $500 million a year,'' said
one person close to Alcoa's talks with Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Although the McCook bid came out of left field, many industry
specialists say it was a logical one. McCook's nucleus is a
fabricating plant in McCook, Ill., that Michigan Avenue Partners
bought from Reynolds in 1997. A few months ago it acquired an
aluminum rolling mill in Scottsboro, Ala., from Noranda, a Canadian
aluminum company. And, although it lost out in the bidding, it
tried to buy some smelting operations from the Columbia Falls
Aluminum Co. in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch is fast garnering a reputation among industry experts as a
hands-on manager who can wring costs out of money-losing
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no fly by night operation,'' said Lloyd T. O'Carroll,
a metals analyst at the brokerage firm Scott &AMP; Stringfellow. ``Mike
Lynch is building a real metals company by buying underperforming
assets and turning them around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
