<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ISLAND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATSU ISLAND MAY BE FLASHPOINT IN CHINA-TAIWAN CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MATSU, Taiwan _ If military conflict breaks out between China
and Taiwan any time soon, military experts say, it is as likely to
begin on this little island as anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   A mere three miles off the coast of southeast China, Matsu still
belongs to Taiwan, which is more than 100 miles away. By its
location alone, Matsu is highly vulnerable to attack from the
Chinese army, and is guarded by a slim force of about 6,000 Taiwan
soldiers, roughly the same number of civilians who live here.
</P>
<P>
   Yet life is calm on Matsu, and there are few signs here that
military action is imminent. Beijing and Taipei may be engaged in a
rich shadow play, bickering over the terminology of sovereignty as
each side boasts about its military might. Ordinary people on Matsu
are going about their lives as they have for years.
</P>
<P>
   At the crest of a hill on one side of the island, the Wang
family store sells a variety of simple fare, virtually all of it
brought over from China despite an official ban on trading with the
mainland. Several members of an extended family spend the afternoon
sitting outside in the warm breeze, and talk flows easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why Lee Teng-hui is stirring things up again,''
Wang Chong-yu, the family patriarch, who has lived here since his
family came over in 1949, said, referring to Taiwan's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics,'' his son, Wang Chi-fan, 32, cut in.
</P>
<P>
   Wang, the son, said that when tensions flared in July, after Lee
asserted that Taiwan would deal with China in ``special
state-to-state relations'' rather than as two parts of the same
country, many traders in Matsu feared that the Taiwan authorities
might crack down on the heavy smuggling trade with China,
technically illegal but long permitted. But nothing has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't seem to be taking things too seriously,'' young
Wang said. ``Why should we?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're used to this,'' his father added. ``When there is always
danger, you don't feel the danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Matsu is, as a favorite Chinese phrase puts it, a ``problem left
over from history,'' one of many that abound in the bizarre and
potentially explosive conflict between Taiwan and China since
Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalist forces, defeated by Mao Tse-tung's
Communists, retreated to Taiwan in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Matsu and another set of islands called Kinmen, formerly known
as Quemoy, were the site of serious battles between the Communist
and Nationalist armies in 1949 and again in 1958. In an odd truce
that was negotiated in 1958, Taiwan and China agreed that military
forces on Matsu and mainland China would shell each other on
opposite days of the week, so that each could keep up the pretense
of fighting, albeit in a pretty nonserious way.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Wednesday and Friday, China would fire at Matsu. On
Tuesday, Thursday and Saturday, Matsu would fire at China. On
Sunday, both sides would rest. That went on for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty silly,'' said Tsai Cheng-li, a 55-year-old
resident of Matsu. ``But you never knew when one would land on you.
A lot of people were killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, residents of Matsu use old shell casings to drink beer,
toasting their brothers and sisters on the mainland, an act tinged
with irony.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, people on Matsu do indeed feel closer to mainland
Chinese than they do to their Taiwan compatriots, since they have
more contact with the mainland. As restrictions on boat traffic
between Matsu and Fujian province in China relaxed in recent years,
it became far easier to take a three-mile hop in a fishing boat
than a 100-mile journey by plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``If trouble breaks out, we'll go that way, not back to
Taiwan,'' Chen Siu-chen, a taxi dispatcher, said, pointing west
toward China.
</P>
<P>
   She laughed at the thought, as if it seemed pretty
inconceivable, after 50 years of threats and no action. Pressed,
she said she was being honest. If the Chinese army actually
attacked Matsu, she said, the quickest route out of harm's way
would be to get on a fishing boat and head for China's coast.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the recent tension, tourists still fly to Matsu every
day from Taipei, to peer across the slim stretch of water that
separates Matsu from the mainland. There are five flights a day,
and during the summer they are booked solid on weekends, even
though planes have to fly into mainland airspace to get here. There
are even more flights to Kinmen _ 16 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Ting, a research fellow at Taiwan's University of
Politics who specializes in military affairs, said China could well
choose to attack the relatively easy targets of Kinmen or Matsu.
But if it did so, he said, it would face the possibility of a huge
retaliatory strike of Taiwan missiles aimed at mainland cities.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan has clear air superiority over China, Ting said, making
any amphibious assault on Taiwan difficult because China would lack
sufficient air cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taiwan could cause a lot of damage to the mainland,'' Ting
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Matsu, most civilians seem to shrug off the possibility that
their home will be the site of military conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be war,'' Ms. Chen said with a dismissive laugh.
``There's no point in war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
