u s BC-GLF-PGA-RYAN-COLUMN-B     08-13 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTER LETS GARCIA DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, ILL. _ If driving were all there was to golf, Sergio
Garcia would have had a great score.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to realize my long game was almost perfect,'' he
said. ``The way I was hitting the ball off the tee, I felt I was
going to have another good round. I thought 70, 69, something like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but golf encompasses so much more. Spain's precocious golf
celebrity converted but one of seven legitimate birdie
opportunities. No 70. No 69. And surely no duplication of
Thursday's opening-round score of 66. Sergio Garcia shot a more
mundane 1-over-par 73. He's no longer the leader of the 1999 PGA
Championship. He's merely among 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``The putter did not work very good today,'' he said with a
sigh. ``I know you're going to have one of these rounds in every
tournament. I hope this will be the worst one.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, so sage, so prescient, so casually knowledgeable and so
supremely confident. But why should we be surprised? He is, after
all, 19.
</P>
<P>
   Or is he?
</P>
<P>
   ``At 19 years old, I see far more composure with these players
and more experience,'' said playing partner Hale Irwin, 35 years
Garcia's senior. ``Sergio, for instance, played so many tournamnts
around the world. And he's won how many of those amateur events? If
I played in two or three tournaments a summer, I felt lucky between
working on a construction job for eight hours a day and playing
some golf at a daily fee course.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergio doesn't know from construction jobs. A son of a golf pro,
he is nothing less than the Spanish Tiger. He started playing at 3.
He was club champion at 12. He made his European Tour debut at 15.
He had a 32-1 record in match play as an amateur. He turned pro
earlier this year and he's already got a European Tour victory (the
Murphy's Irish Open). He also had that surreal British Open
experience (an 89-83 weekend), which, being 19, he has easily
erased from his memory bank.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday he set a competitive Medinah Country Club record
(since eclipsed by Skip Kendall) with a sizzling 66. That gave him
a two-shot lead. Asked if having a two-shot lead so soon in the
tournament were perhaps a bit daunting, he said, ``I think there's
nothing better than that. And if (Saturday) I can be four (up), I
can tell you that I'm not going to feel any pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't pressure that got him Friday. As he correctly stated,
it was his putter, which was, plain and simple, a naughty little
(itals)nino.(unitals) Sergio routinely boomed drives 300-plus
yards, and most of them landed in the fairway. He routinely hit
crisp iron shots to the green. But given six legit (i.e. 15-feet or
less) birdie opportunities in the first 12 holes (and one more on
18), he nailed just one putt. It was one of those days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I played pretty solid,'' he said. ``Better than
Friday. The putter just didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergio is listed at 5 feet 11 inches and 160 pounds, but he
really doesn't seem that tall and he could pass for 17, easy. You
can kind of figure out where Tiger's strength comes from, but how
this kid sends 'em out there three football fields long is a
definite puzzler. But he does.
</P>
<P>
   He went out for his second round of PGA play early in the
morning (8:19 CDT). He wore black slacks, a brown shirt, a black
Titleist baseball cap, and white shoes. He was neither chatty nor
distant.
</P>
<P>
   He regularly acknowledged the gallery, which would grow very
large by the 10th hole and remain big thereafter, with a tip of the
cap and a smile. He broke into a huge grin when someone shouted
``El Nino!'' on the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   He does not dawdle, either at the tee or out on the fairway. He
sizes up putts from every conceivable angle, but he makes his looks
brief, and when he gets over the ball he is just about ready to
hit.
</P>
<P>
   He has a reasonably calm demeanor, but he is no robot. He hung
his head after missing a 10-foot birdie putt on the fifth. He found
it necessary to ask for quiet before missing a 10-footer on the
seventh. He knew he had mis-hit a putt on the 11th, chasing after
the ball while waving his putter. He swung his club in anger when
his bunker (fourth) shot on the 583-yard par-5 14th wasn't close
enough to the pin for his liking (he had pushed a 3-wood into the
trees on his second shot).
</P>
<P>
   He was not self-absorbed. He twice applauded superb shots by
Irwin, for example, and he completely surprised Phil Mickelson, his
other playing partrner, on another occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very impressed with him, both as a player and as an
individual,'' said the noted southpaw. ``He came up to me on No.
10, after I had gone 4 over on the first nine. He said, `Do you
mind if I say something?' I said, `Please do.' He said, `Let's have
a great back side.' I thought that was class.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was impressed that Irwin, who put himself into
contention with a 3-under 69, could hit the ball as well as he does
at age 54, but ``I certainly didn't think he played any better than
me.'' He is confident, bordering on arrogance. When someone asked
him if Irwin could teach him anything about Medinah, he replied,
``Learn? I don't know. I think I know how to play the golf course,
and I think I'm doing fine the way I'm playing the golf course. If
I putted well, it could be another great round, but it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   He's good. He knows it. And so does everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of talent in that young man,'' said Irwin, who
took off his own cap and waved it in El Nino's direction as they
approached the 18th green.
</P>
<P>
   He's 19. Check back in 40 years. He'll probably be shooting his
age.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
