<HEADLINE>
HOW NABISCO'S NEW COOKIE CRUMBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J., Mass.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of Nabisco stock and the spun-off tobacco
holdings stocks is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15)  
 (af)  
 By JOANNE LEGOMSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure, kids argue about the best way to eat an Oreo cookie. But
since the breakup in June of the old RJR Nabisco into separately
traded food and tobacco companies, investors have been wondering
about the best way to own the stock of the company that makes the
cookies, along with Ritz crackers and other snack foods.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization has resulted in three publicly traded stocks.
The tobacco business, whose brands include Winston and Camel, was
spun out as R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Holdings. It now has nothing to
do with food, and could face billions of dollars in liabilities if
it ever has to pay damages to individual smokers or the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   That helps explain why the food business seems to be attracting
the lion's share of attention these days. Analysts also say the
business has sharply improving fundamentals. So for investors, the
question is which of the two stocks that track the cookie maker
represents the better bet.
</P>
<P>
   The parent company is Nabisco Group Holdings, which trades under
the ticker symbol NGH. Its only asset, now that the tobacco
business has been spun off, is 80.6 percent of Nabisco Holdings,
the operating company, whose stock trades under the ticker symbol
NA. (The remaining 19.4 percent has been publicly owned since early
1995.)
</P>
<P>
   Craig Albert of Sanford C. Bernstein favors the operating
company. At $39 a share, it is trading at just 17 times his
estimate of per-share cash earnings _ net income plus goodwill
amortization _ for 2000. That is about 10 percent cheaper than the
shares of its rivals, which include Kellogg and Keebler Foods.
</P>
<P>
   The riskier _ though potentially more lucrative _ tactic, some
other analysts say, is to buy shares of the parent company. At
$18.125, Nabisco Group shares trade at what analysts calculate as a
29 percent discount to the value of its investment in the operating
company. If it were trading at 100 percent of that value, the price
would be over $25, they note.
</P>
<P>
   The parent's stock yields 2.7 percent, versus 1.9 percent for
the operating company. And because the parent company's stock is
part of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, the shares are more
easily traded and therefore attractive to institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   The catch with the parent company's shares is that they carry a
potentially huge tobacco liability. While all the big states have
reached settlements with tobacco companies to recoup the cost of
treating smoking-related illnesses, the federal government or
individuals could still win big settlements or judgments.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, the discount that Nabisco Group shares trade at
relative to the operating company shares is a measure of the
market's fear that Nabisco Group could be liable for claims lodged
against the spun-off R.J. Reynolds, if the tobacco company cannot
meet its obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you like Nabisco's food business, you should own it through
NA,'' the operating company, Albert said. ``The only reason to buy
NGH is if you believe the tobacco liability is mispriced,'' he said
of the parent.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts think it is. Nomi Ghez, a food analyst with
Goldman, Sachs, says the current discount on the parent company's
shares is far too high, especially since R.J. Reynolds has agreed
to indemnify its former parent against any claims that might arise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way plaintiffs in smoking lawsuits could sue the
holding company is if the tobacco company goes bankrupt,'' Ms. Ghez
said, a risk she and others think is increasingly remote.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Cohen, a tobacco analyst at Goldman, Sachs, added, ``The
bankruptcy risk is considerably less than one in five based on our
evaluation of the legal challenges the industry faces and the
financial capabilities of industry participants to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Feldman, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney, says that
the parent's discount has fluctuated from 18 percent to 34 percent,
mainly in response to tobacco litigation news. Such sensitivity can
wreak short-term havoc on its stock price, Feldman said, but he
added that he thought tobacco worries would recede over the next 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman expects the parent company's shares to rise 27 percent,
to $23, in 12 months, based on a 20.5 percent rise in the price of
the operating company's shares, to $47. That would shrink the
discount from the current 29 percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some institutional investors are also tempted by the valuation
gap.
</P>
<P>
   David N. Dreman, head of Dreman Value Management in Jersey City,
thinks the parent company is attractive. ``The enormous spread
doesn't make a lot of sense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Robinson, an analyst with Eaton Vance Management, a mutual
fund company in Boston that holds shares of both the parent and the
operating company stocks, also thinks liability fears are
overblown. R.J. Reynolds' ``huge cash flow cushion,'' he said,
strengthens its ability to withstand legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   And R.J. Reynolds has benefited from improved efforts by the old
RJR Nabisco to shore up its finances. A month before the breakup,
RJR Nabisco sold its foreign tobacco operations to Japan Tobacco
for $8 billion, and used the proceeds to slash its debt load, a
legacy of the $25 billion leveraged buyout of RJR Nabisco a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts are sanguine about the fundamentals of the food
business. They credit James M. Kilts, chief executive of the
operating company since January 1998, with the turnaround in its
business. After years of starving the flagship brands, Nabisco
began increasing its marketing expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nabisco's biscuit business responded immediately to the
increased spending,'' Albert said. The company has sold more
crackers and cookies year-to-year every quarter since the marketing
push began, after having lost market share for 14 consecutive
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ghez expects the operating company to earn $1.30 a share in
1999, up from $1.21 in 1998, reflecting double-digit growth in the
second-half of 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
