<HEADLINE>
RED SOX GOT A REAL DEAL IN DAUBACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's baseball's deal of the year: Brian Daubach for Mo Money.
When Mo Vaughn said no to the Red Sox' five-year, $65 million offer
last fall, the masses of Nitwit Nation were on the march. How could
the team survive without Mo? Without his big bat? His (ahem)
leadership? His fan appeal? No one, they said _ through their
number one media outlet, WEEI, the home of Nitwit Radio _ could
replace Mighty Mo, let alone some unknown journeyman named Brian
Daubach.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the season is two-thirds over, and it's time to take a
look at the numbers and see how the multimillion-dollar man, Mo
Money, is doing compared to the $215,000 man, Brian Daubach.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of the tape going into Friday night's games:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(! used as column separator) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AB ! R ! H ! HR ! RBI ! Avg. &QL; 
Vaughn 338 ! 34 ! 92 ! 18 ! 64 ! .272 &QL; 
Daubach 266 ! 49 ! 86 ! 17 ! 53 ! .323 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think Bill Bavasi, the general manager of the Angels, would like
to have this signing back? Over the length of the six-year
contract, Bavasi gave Mo $80 million, including a $13 million
signing bonus, so Mo, with a $5 million salary this season, is on
the books for $18 million this year. Mo's entire contract is
guaranteed, so as poorly as he has been performing, if the Angels
wanted to send him to the minors, he would still have to be paid in
full. Conversely, Daubach, who did not get a signing bonus, has a
salary of $215,000 for this year, and if he is sent down to
Pawtucket, he gets paid at the rate of $42,000.
</P>
<P>
   To this humble scribe, the Angels are getting exactly what they
deserved. As soon as things started to go bad in Anaheim, Mo turned
on Bavasi just like he did Sox management. Mo has no qualms when it
comes to biting the hand that feeds him, no matter how much food it
puts on his plate. This is not to say Daubach is a better hitter
than Mo. What it does say is that when a team invests that kind of
money in a player, it should know for sure what it is getting. With
Mo, you never know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's the Celtics' mindset regarding Antoine Walker as training
camp nears: They feel he doesn't want to play in Boston, but as of
now there isn't any team out there that will give them anything of
substance for him. So the Celtics/Rick Pitino are going to tell
Walker to play his heart out this season, get the team to the
playoffs, and prove to the rest of the league how great he is; then
the team should be able to trade him and get something decent in
return. In other words, Walker will be given a chance to work his
way out of town. Sounds fair to me . . . Want some good season
tickets to the Patriots, Red Sox, or Celtics? The US Bankruptcy
Court in Boston will provide an unusual opportunity to some
well-heeled fan to ``win'' the rights to season tickets for each
team. A businessman who is a longtime supporter of all three teams
had to file for personal bankruptcy under Chapter 11. The court has
decided his creditors would be best served by an auction of the
tickets, with the rights to the tickets being sold to the highest
bidder. The auction is scheduled to be held in the Federal Building
in Boston, located right next to the FleetCenter, Aug. 27 at 11
a.m. The Red Sox and Patriots are not pleased with the decision
because they hold the rights to all of their tickets. They have
informed the court, through Boston attorney Dan Goldberg, that they
will not fight the situation but want it noted that they consider
this an isolated case that will not set a precedent. The judge will
allow the businessman to keep his tickets, which are on the 25-yard
line at Foxboro Stadium, for six of the Patriots' l0 games this
season. The successful bidder at auction will get tickets for the
remaining four Patriots games this year and the rights to all
tickets to those seats in the future; any Red Sox playoff tickets
this year and the rights to the seats in question for all Sox games
in the future; and all of the businessman's Celtics tickets this
season and in the future. Attorney Steve Shamban, representing the
bankrupt fan, said two Celtics season tickets were auctioned off by
court order several years back and brought in $27,000 just for the
rights to those seats in the future. Paul E. Saperstein, who will
conduct the auction, said he thinks the tickets for each of the
three teams will go for substantially more than that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The irony surrounding the major league All-Star Game in Boston
last month is this: The Red Sox lost money while seemingly everyone
else in the city made a score. It cost the Sox close to $2 million
to put on all of the All-Star events . . . Willie Clay told some
folks with the Saints when he arrived at their training camp in
Wisconsin this week that Ty Law is close to signing a lucrative
deal with the Patriots. Clay signed for short money _ $200,000
bonus and $400,000 salary _ but can double his money if he starts
at least seven games this year . . . Have any of the European
players who will compete in the Ryder Cup asked for money for their
favorite charities? I think not. My understanding is when the Ryder
Cup takes place in Europe, the European version of the PGA keeps
the money, and when it's in America, as it will be this year at
Brookline, Mass., our PGA keeps the money. To me, there is nothing
wrong with players wanting some of the money going to charity, as
long as it it not their own charity. The PGA and the tour players
should sit down and pick out national charities related to golf
where the players' contributions could be directed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will have a private luncheon for retiring executive
Tom Johnson next Tuesday at the FleetCenter. It's a fitting tribute
for Johnson, who has served the club so well for so long . . . The
plans for a new Fenway Park are on hold until Mayor Tom Menino
decides what Boston is willing to spend on the project. That, in
turn, will determine how much the Red Sox will have to spend . . .
Don't be shocked if the NFL doesn't put an expansion team in either
Los Angeles or Houston. The LA effort is all but dead, and some
owners don't think Houston can afford the going price for an NFL
team. Expansion franchises Cleveland and Washington went for close
to $600 million . . . You are not retired in the NFL until you send
an official letter of notification to the commissioner and your
team has placed you on the retired-reserve list. Neither Barry
Sanders nor Reggie White was on either list as of Friday. This
reporter heard from a source close to White this week that he would
love to come back and play. Green Bay doesn't have room for him
under the salary cap, and only a handful of teams would at this
point in time . . . Don't be surprised if Sox team doctor Arthur
Pappas decides to retire from that position in the next year or
two.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
