<SLUG> BC-MA-HMO-LOSSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMBERS FACE STIFF RATE INCREASES AS HMO LOSSES MOUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Faced with mounting losses, nearly all the state's
major health maintenance organizations are asking customers to
absorb double-digit premium increases beginning this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The increases, the largest in nearly a decade, are the
industry's responses to an alarming surge in health care costs that
HMO executives are at a loss to explain.
</P>
<P>
   They signal an abrupt end to years of modest premium increases _
and in come cases decreases _ during which HMOs claimed victory
over medical inflation using ``managed care'' techniques to
eliminate unnecessary health care.
</P>
<P>
   But the triumph has proved short-lived. Nationwide, HMOs are
calling for rate increases of 10 percent to 12 percent, according
to Jack Reichman, a director at Standard &AMP; Poor's insurance rating
service in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Tufts Health Plan, the second-biggest HMO in
New England with 1.1 million members, Friday said premium hikes
will average ``in the low double digits.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallon Community Health Plan in Worcester said it will raise
rates ``10 percent plus'' next year. The announcements follow a
similar decree by Harvard Pilgrim Health Health Care, the region's
largest HMO, to hike rates 12 percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim, New England's largest HMO with 1.3 million
members, hasn't levied a double-digit increase since 1990, when
rates jumped 13 percent on average, according to company figures.
Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts, which sells HMO Blue,
has not yet settled on its 2000 rates, but has predicted premiums
will go up.
</P>
<P>
   Most HMOs say the increases are needed to pay mounting medical
bills, which have pushed them into financial distress in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim Friday reported a net loss of $48.9 million in
the first six months of this year on revenue of $1.5 billion. That
compares to a $5.3 million net loss in the same period last year on
revenue of $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   To help cut its losses, Harvard Pilgrim reported it has laid off
50 workers in the past two weeks as part of a previously announced
plan to eliminate ``hundreds'' of employees, said Alan G. Raymond,
spokesman and senior vice president of the Brookline-based HMO.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts Friday posted larger-than-expected net losses _ $16.9
million on $988 million in revenue. Last year, the Waltham-based
HMO made money during the same period _ $500,000 on revenue of
$796.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting losses, just not in the double digits,''
said Richard Hallworth, Tufts chief financial officer. ``We've been
experiencing dramatic increases in (medical costs), but we're not
sure why it's happening. We're working to try to understand it
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallon, meanwhile, lost nearly $8 million in the first half of
1999 on revenue of $266.2 million, according to Jay Egan,
co-director of Fallon, which has 220,000 members. While the losses
were greater than the $2.2 million net loss incurred during the
first half of 1998, Egan said losses in the second quarter this
year were half what they were in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't continue to lose money year after year, but we feel
we're pretty well poised to turn the corner,'' Egan said. ``Our
strategy is to get better with every quarter. So far, we're on
target with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan said much of Fallon's losses stem from its effort to gain
customers. Such aggressive competition is partly to blame for part
of the industry's financial troubles, said Reichman of Standard &AMP;
Poor's. Vying to gain new members, HMOs in New England have
artificially pushed premiums below costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But raising rates is only part of the answer, Reichman said.
HMOs must also do better in reining in medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``HMOs exist today because employers did not want to keep paying
higher rates every year,'' Reichman said, hinting of a consumer
rebellion. ``Just raising rates every year will provoke an answer
from employers and from the government, which pays for Medicare and
Medicaid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
