<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shifting Gear To Computers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley visited the rust belt this week, when Scott G.
McNealy, chairman and chief executive of Sun Microsystems, showed
up at a press conference that General Motors called to tout its new
Internet unit, e-GM. Sun is handling all of GM's Web sites and
otherwise helping the auto giant get connected.
</P>
<P>
   McNealy, who grew up in the land of navy suits, as the Detroit
area is often known _ his father was vice chairman of AMC Motors _
showed up wearing faded jeans. Several GM executives, straining for
casual, had taken off their ties and changed into sport coats for
the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   McNealy insisted that they were committed to the wired world,
appearances aside. ``You wouldn't know it by looking at them,'' he
said. ``I see no body piercing, no tattoos.''
</P>
<P>
   McNealy, who now hails from Palo Alto, Calif., sees dollar signs
when he thinks of bringing computers to cars, because ever-longer
commutes are making for a captive audience. Just think of all the
``dashboard hours per day'' that GM captures, said McNealy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often think of the automobile as nothing more than a Java
browser with tires,'' he said. That's because all the major auto
companies, through the Automotive Multimedia Interface
Collaboration, have selected the Java computer language, ``rather
than going with Microsoft and putting control-alt-delete buttons on
every dashboard,'' McNealy added with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   _Robyn Meredith &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not Shy, or Cheap &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Frank Quattrone, the flamboyant West Coast investment
banker for technology companies, moved his operations in July 1998
from Deutsche Bank to Credit Suisse First Boston, a collective
titter could be heard throughout Silicon Valley. It was the second
time in two years that Quattrone had finagled a multimillion-dollar
compensation package for himself and more yet for his team of
bankers. Could he deliver for his new employer?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. As lead manager of initial public offerings sold in
the United States, Credit Suisse moved up to third place for the 12
months ended Aug. 1 from sixth for the 12 months prior (and 18th
two years ago). His partners also advised Ascend Communications
this year when it was bought by Lucent Technologies for $24
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Quattrone and his group took out full-page ads in newspapers
this month lauding their recent achievements. Credit Suisse had the
building blocks, Quattrone said, adding, ``They were just missing
our technology team.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Laura M. Holson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Avon Joins the Fight Against Cancer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Avon is doing more than calling these days. Charles Perrin, the
company's chairman and chief executive, plans to lead hundreds of
Avon employees, from senior management to sales people, who are
walking, marching or jogging 55 miles in three days to raise money
to fight breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Perrin, 54, and his wife Sheila will be among the expected 2,400
walkers who will leave Bear Mountain on Friday, Aug. 27, and walk
through Rockland County and New Jersey to the closing ceremonies
for the Avon Breast Cancer 3-Day in Central Park on Sunday, Aug.
29.
</P>
<P>
   Perrin and his company are seeing to it that en route, the
walkers will have catered meals, hot showers and medical services,
plus shelter in tents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a very important program,'' Perrin said, ``and
I think it's important for the CEO to walk the talk.'' He's a
jogger and his wife takes aerobics classes. Even so, the Perrins
and their friends have been training for the event all summer.
</P>
<P>
   With similar events, backed by Avon, in Chicago, Los Angeles and
Atlanta this year, Perrin predicts that about $20 million will be
raised to help women with the early detection of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   _Jan M. Rosen
</P>
</TEXT>
