<SLUG> BC-CARLSBAD-KILLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN DESERT KILLING ALLOWED TO RETURN TO BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, N.M. _ Composed and businesslike, murder suspect Raffi
Kodikian won temporary freedom Friday after a judge said he could
return home to Boston until he stands trial on charges that he
killed his best friend and buried the body in a crude grave in a
canyon desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine right now,'' Kodikian, 25, said after a 10-minute
hearing in Eddy County Magistrate Court, where he was ordered to
surrender his passport and be ready to return to New Mexico at a
judge's command.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian, dressed in brown hiking boots, blue jeans, and a white
T-shirt, said he wanted to offer his sympathies to the family of
David Coughlin, the man Kodikian said he stabbed twice in the chest
last weekend in a remote area of Carlsbad Caverns National Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to, but I can't,'' Kodikian said in a brief
sidewalk interview after the hearing. His lawyer said his client is
bound by a court order not to contact any possible witnesses in the
case against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really can't say anything,'' said Kodikian's father,
Howard, his voice choked with emotion. ``Our condolences go out to
them. We know they're hurting. We're just sorry about the whole
situation. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian has told authorities that he and Coughlin, 26, of
Millis, Mass., had gotten lost in the desert park and had run out
of water. Desperate and dehydrated, Kodikian told them, his
longtime friend begged him to end his misery.
</P>
<P>
   Eddy County Magistrate Judge Monte L. Lyons presided over
Friday's hearing. He noted Kodikian's clean record and the fact
that the local prosecutors did not object to allowing Kodikian to
return Boston, and to his father's home in Doylestown, Pa. In
exchange, Kodikian agreed to air-mail his passport back to the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian, who was released Tuesday on $50,000 bail, also waived
his extradition rights if he violates the conditions of his
release, which also include a ban on the use of drugs, alcohol, and
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to get into any problems,'' Lyons told
Kodikian.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian told Lyons that he would like to contact two people _ a
former girlfriend who he said is ``a mutual friend of mine and
Dave,'' as well as Coughlin's roommate. ``I was hoping to speak to
him _ not about the case,'' Kodikian told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   But after Gary W. McCandless, the local sheriff's chief of
detectives, told the judge that both friends are potential
witnesses, the judge declined Kodikian's request. ``I'll have to
get back to you on that,'' Lyons told him.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Kodikian and his father, Friday's unscheduled hearing
was attended only by the judge, McCandless, Eddy County Sheriff
M.A. ``Chunky'' Click, and a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Click said detectives from his department and FBI agents
interviewed Kodikian again Friday morning. Kodikian told them about
events leading up to Coughlin's death in the desert last weekend,
which was discovered when a National Park Service ranger approached
the Massachusetts men's campsite in Rattlesnake Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I killed him,'' Kodikian allegedly told Ranger Lance Mattson,
who discovered Coughlin's body under a blue cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Click called Kodikian cooperative, well-mannered, and
respectful. He said he is not considered likely to flee.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities expect to decide next week whether Kodikian, now
charged under an open count of murder, will face prosecution by
state or federal authorities. A preliminary hearing scheduled for
Thursday most likely will be waived, said Click.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement sources said that while prosecutors have strong
evidence against Kodikian, including his incriminating statements
to the park ranger and a journal that officials have called
tantamount to a signed confession, the case is far from open and
shut.
</P>
<P>
   They say Kodikian has two likely defenses: that the desert heat
and sun diminished his capacity to tell right from wrong, or that
he was near-delusional at the time of the stabbing. Both arguments,
the sources said, could be compelling before juries.
</P>
<P>
   But Click, who has said he is skeptical of Kodikian's account,
said he is confident a thorough investigation will yield the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that Mr. Kodikian was moderately to severely
dehydrated. But there's no question that Mr. Coughlin was very much
alive'' when Kodikian stabbed him, Click said.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian and Coughlin were on a cross-country trip to Santa
Barbara, Calif., where Coughlin intended to study environmental
science this fall.
</P>
<P>
   As Kodikian traveled back to the East Coast, officials here were
preparing for forensics tests on items found at the canyon camp
site, including the hunting knife authorities believe was used in
the stabbing, a poncho and plastic cover with a red stain, a rock,
a blue T-shirt, a sock, and a bedroll.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Deputy District Attorney Les Williams said under New
Mexico law, Kodikian's trial must start six months after he is
formally arraigned in court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
