<SLUG> BC-SPRINGER-SENATE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Springer silences talk of possible Senate run
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Three weeks of ``Springer fever'' ended Friday
as Jerry Springer announced he won't give up his chair-throwing,
hair-pulling television talk show to seek the Ohio Democratic
nomination to run against U.S. Sen. Mike DeWine.
</P>
<P>
   And, as far as state Sen. Rhine McLin is concerned, it might be
better for her party to give up altogether on next year's U.S.
Senate race than to run a relatively unknown candidate, such as
former Columbus-area state Rep. Richard Cordray, against DeWine, a
Republican from Cedarville who's in his first term.
</P>
<P>
   Springer, a former Cincinnati mayor and city councilman, issued
a statement announcing his decision. News that he was considering
the race _ partly at the urging of Hamilton County Democratic
Chairman Tim Burke _ first surfaced in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   ``As tempting and attractive as the notion of serving in the
U.S. Senate is, what I suspected might be the case is, in fact, the
case,'' Springer said. ``My current contractual obligations and
commitments here in the United States as well as in England, make
it impractical if not impossible for me to make a run for the
Senate at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer said he appreciated the interest expressed by Ohio
Democrats and hinted that eventually he may try a return to
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, before my talk show most of my adult life was spent in
public service. I loved it. I look forward to returning to it. Just
not now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McLin was not one of the Democrats encouraging Springer,
although she had not been as critical as U.S. Senate Minority
Leader Tom Daschle, who called the idea of a Springer candidacy a
``joke.''
</P>
<P>
   McLin said Cordray, who has lost races for the U.S. House and
Ohio attorney general, is not ready to face DeWine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Cordray. He needs to run for the state Senate. He's way
ahead of himself. ... I'd rather see us not run someone than to
make a mockery of it,'' McLin said.
</P>
<P>
   The state party should concentrate on recruiting good candidates
for the state Legislature and getting a head start at taking on
Sen. George Voinovich (R-0hio) when the former governor comes up
for re-election in 2004, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cordray, who has formed an exploratory committee to determine
whether he should run against DeWine, said Springer's decision was
the right one for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would have been a mistake,'' Cordray said. ``He is
associated in the public mind with an approach to people and values
that is dramatically out of step with the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordray, who was state solicitor under Ohio Attorney General Lee
Fisher, said he will decide in a ``matter of weeks'' whether to
run.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Democratic Chairman David Leland said he talked briefly
with Springer on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My focus is to find a candidate that will be aggressive and
will fight for Democratic Party values and will beat Mike DeWine in
the year 2000,'' Leland said. He said other Democrats besides
Cordray may come forward.
</P>
<P>
   Burke, the Hamilton County chairman, said he was disappointed by
Springer's decision and said Springer could have defeated DeWine.
He said that those who criticized Springer don't know him well.
</P>
<P>
   Burke called Cordray a ``very talented guy'' and said he would
be a ``viable candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Republican Chairman Robert Bennett kept up the ridicule he
started when talk about Springer first surfaced. Democratic leaders
might not be done searching for candidates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they're interviewing candidates like Marilyn Manson,
Madonna or Ru Paul,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
