u s BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     08-13 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OLD MAN OF MEDINAH HAS A SHOT TO WIN THE PGA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ With a red 5 next to his name on the scoreboard,
Hale Irwin was walking to the 17th tee Friday when a voice in the
grandstand yelled, ``You're not 50.''
</P>
<P>
   The oldest golfer in this PGA Championship looked up, smiled and
said, ``You're right.''
</P>
<P>
   Hale Irwin isn't 50, he's 54, the monarch of the Senior PGA
Tour. And as he marched to a 3-under-par 69 for 139 halfway through
this PGA, he was hailed with warm applause at every green from
those who remembered him winning his third U.S. Open Championship
here at the Medinah Country Club in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   After holing a 45-foot birdie putt on the final green in that
Open to force an 18-hole playoff with Mike Donald, Irwin celebrated
by running around the green, slapping hands with fans in the
grandstand. The next day he won with a 10-foot birdie putt on the
first extra hole of what evolved into a 19-hole playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Although Irwin is only four strokes off the lead, he's probably
too old to win, but you never know. And if he did win, he would be
the oldest golfer ever to win a major tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Julius Boros was 48 when he won the 1968 PGA at Pecan Valley in
San Antonio, Texas., and Jack Nicklaus was 46 when he won the 1986
Masters. And don't tell Irwin he can't win at 54.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go back to 1975, I finished third in the U.S. Open here
at Medinah, so I have had success here,'' he said. ``I feel
comfortable playing the golf course. It doesn't mean it's not
challenging. Far from it. But it's the kind of course that I think
elicits my better golf. Can I continue that? Possibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin has a reputation for playing well on the toughest
traditional courses; he won his other two Opens in 1974 at Winged
Foot and in 1979 at Inverness. And Friday he outplayed 19-year-old
Sergio Garcia, the Spanish prodigy who skidded to a 73, and
29-year-old Phil Mickelson, who had 72.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm longer than I used to be,'' Irwin said, ``but when I'm
comparing my distance to Garcia and Mickelson, I can't compete. I'm
hitting 4-irons, they're hitting 7-irons. But my irons are pretty
good, I keep the ball in play. I make a putt every now and again. I
control my game and get the most out of it. That's my game.''
</P>
<P>
   That game produced 20 victories, including those three Opens,
and nearly $6 million in prize money on the PGA Tour. Ever since
Irwin turned 50, that game has dominated the Senior PGA Tour _ 26
victories, including one Senior Open and three PGA Seniors, and
more than $9 million in prize money. And that game impressed
Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It surprised me the way he hits the ball,'' the Spanish
teen-ager said. ``I knew he was a great player, but I didn't know
he was that good. He hits the ball very straight, he rarely misses
a fairway and he's a good putter.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin isn't even listed in the Ryder Cup standings, but he was a
member of five cup teams, including his memorable halved singles
match with Bernhard Langer in 1991 that assured the Americans'
recapture of the trophy from the European pros. So he was asked, if
he were to win this PGA, would he be an asset to this year's team?
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we getting paid?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the laughter from his audience over his allusion to the
Ryder Cup controversy about the American golfers' request for
payments that would be donated to charity, he quickly added, ``I
would pay to play, to tell you the truth.'' And then he addressed
the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``That team has a personality right now that I'm not sure that I
know,'' he said. ``It's not like the teams I've been on. I think
the best thing we could do for the Americans is to put all of this
furor behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled looking at the leader boards here and seeing names
such as Lee Westwood, Sergio Garcia and Miguel Jimenez.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all going to be on that other Ryder Cup team,'' he
said. ``I think our guys better buckle down and think about playing
golf. And could I be an asset? Well, very possibly. The Country
Club, that's the kind of course I could play. But my better chance
for the Ryder Cup team came two years ago in the PGA at Winged Foot
because I was probably playing a little bit better than I am right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   But this time Hale Irwin is at Medinah and if anyone can win a
major at 54, he can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
