<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-NYT &LR;      08-13 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. GIVES FORCES AUTHORIZATION TO DETAIN, EXPEL TROUBLEMAKERS IN
KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MITROVICA, Yugoslavia _ The U.N. administration gave its troops
and police extra powers Friday to detain and even expel
troublemakers from town or from Kosovo altogether, in a new attempt
to control the violence and ethnic tension in the province.
</P>
<P>
   The regulation, which was signed by the U.N. special
representative, Bernard Kouchner, is a direct reaction to the
tussles French troops have had with noisy demonstrators in this
divided city over the last week, according to a spokesman for KFOR,
the NATO force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   French peacekeeping troops were clearly expecting the new
regulation and welcomed it as a ``supplementary tool'' as the
looting and arson of early weeks gives way to demonstrations and
even attacks on peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The new rule allows police and soldiers to ban someone from an
area, or detain them for up to 12 hours, if they are thought to
present a threat to public peace and order, including infringing on
someone else's human rights or jeopardizing public or private
property.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a preventative tool,'' said Hansjoerg Strohmeyer, legal
adviser to Kouchner. ``It allows us to remove people who are
instigating violence through hate speech or provocations, and it
can be done within 10 minutes. It means the person can be removed
from the city limits or even from Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost daily demonstrations of several hundred people are
occurring in Mitrovica as Serbs and ethnic Albanians gather and
trade insults, and even blows, on either side of the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians have been protesting the division of the city
and the creation of a Serbian quarter on the north side of the Ibar
River. They say the peacekeepers have failed to provide the freedom
of movement and security necessary for them to return to their
homes on the north side.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian population, swollen by refugees from other towns and
villages, have made Mitrovica the last main town on the road north
to Serbia, a last outpost of Serbian defiance in Kosovo. The Serbs
stand guard on the bridge and seek to prevent Albanians from
crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the demonstrating is orchestrated, aimed at the media
and the authorities, and the crowds of mostly young men and youths
disperse once they have made their point. But recently the
demonstrations have turned violent , and one French soldier
suffered a head injury.
</P>
<P>
   The French peacekeepers say their priority is to keep the two
sides apart in order to prevent violence. They point out that
Mitrovica, with its 50,000 Albanians and 20,000 Serbs, compares
favorably with other towns in Kosovo and has had only five murders
in two months, out of over 200 in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is obvious that Mitrovica is tense and unhappy. The
Albanian side is a wasteland of burned shops and houses and
makeshift market stalls among destroyed rubble.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian side has an eerie, run-down feel. Many shops are
empty or boarded up, and elderly shaken looking civilians walk the
streets slowly, not venturing far from their apartment blocks.
Thickset men sit around in street cafes, scrutinizing the strangers
who venture over the bridge into the Serbian quarter.
</P>
<P>
   There have been four grenade attacks in the area in recent
weeks, the latest on Tuesday when grenades were fired across the
river and landed close to a Serbian restaurant and an apartment
building. The attack raised tensions sharply and the Serbs
retaliated against the Albanians, approximately 700 of whom still
live in the Serbian section.
</P>
<P>
   Alban Kadriu, 20, a young Albanian shop worker, was ordered out
of his apartment two days ago by 20 Serbian civilians who came to
his building. After having survived the entire war in the
apartment, protected by a Serbian neighbor, Kadriu, his mother, two
brothers and his sister were told to leave after the grenade
attack.
</P>
<P>
   They moved a few blocks away to his uncle's house on the edge of
the Serbian district and never mentioned the incident to the
peacekeepers. Asked why, Kadriu shrugged. ``They are sitting in the
cafe with the Serbs, drinking with them,'' he said of the French
troops. ``They are not doing any good at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he welcomed the new regulation, as did most Albanians who
see the Serbian demonstrations as threatening reminders of the
`ethnic cleansing' during the war. ``It is good. They should have
done that in the beginning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs were more cautious, some approving the regulation but
some wary that it would be used only against Serbs. ``How will they
use their power?'' asked Snezana Pavlovic, 29, who was selling
coffee and newspapers in a kiosk. When told Albanians could be
detained too, she asked cynically: ``Do they have enough room for
them on the other side?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
