<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOOD NEWS ON INFLATION SENDS MARKETS UP SHARPLY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks soared following news that inflation was not a problem
last month at the producer level. July's Producer Price Index rose
by just two-tenths of a percent. The so-called core Producer Price
Index, which excludes food and energy prices, was unchanged last
month. The Dow Jones industrial average surged 184.26 points, or
1.71 percent, at 10,973.65. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
jumped 29.52 points, or 2.27 percent, to 1,327.68. The
technology-laden Nasdaq composite rose 88.32 points, or 3.46
percent, to 2,637.81.
</P>
<P>
   In the inflation-sensitive bond market, the benchmark 30-year
bond jumped 1432, to 1001232. The bond's yield, which moves in the
opposite direction from the price, fell to 6.10 percent from 6.27
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. MORGAN SUED BY SUMITOMO
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan was accused of lending at least $535 million to a
copper trader in the mid-1990s, money that helped fuel a trading
binge that inflicted $2.6 billion in losses on the Sumitomo
Corporation. The information was disclosed in a lawsuit filed by
the Japanese bank this week.
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTERS SEEK END TO SUPERVISION
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after federal officials gained a strict supervisory
role over the International Brotherhood of Teamsters in an effort
to rid it of mob control, the union's new leadership is pushing
hard to get the government out.
</P>
<P>
   WIRE TRANSFERS RAISE QUESTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Many of the estimated six million Mexicans who live and work in
the United States send money to relatives in Mexico. But as the
wire transfer business has boomed, more customers have complained
about the costs. Class-action lawsuits have accused the dominant
wire transfer companies of profiteering, while internal debates at
the two companies over wire transfer rates are said to have led to
the departure of high-ranking Hispanic executives in the United
States and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   DAEWOO UNIT GETS $3.2 BILLION BID
</P>
<P>
   An investment group led by a little known California businessman
has agreed to buy most of Daewoo Electronics, the consumer
electronics unit of the troubled South Korean conglomerate.
Daewoo's president, Yang Jae-yeol, left, said that Walid Alomar &AMP;
Associates, based in Beverly Hills, will pay $3.2 billion for the
Daewoo Electronics assets and operations in North and South
America, Western Europe, Japan and South Korea. The price includes
the assumption of some Daewoo debt.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA REJOINS A FINANCIAL FOLD
</P>
<P>
   After 11 months as a financial pariah, Malaysia earned some
redemption when Morgan Stanley Capital International said it would
readmit the country to portfolios that many fund managers use as
guides to determining where and how much of their clients' money to
invest. In response, the country's benchmark stock index soared.
The composite index in Kuala Lumpur, the capital, rose 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   DEVILBISS AIR POWER SOLD TO PENTAIR
</P>
<P>
   Pentair, a maker of professional tools, agreed to acquire
DeVilbiss Air Power, the air power tools unit of Falcon Building
Products of Chicago for $460 million in cash. Pentair said the
acquisition would increase the annual sales of its professional
tools and equipment business to $1.5 billion and raise its total
sales to around $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTMENT BANKER JOINS SOFTBANK
</P>
<P>
   Bill Burnham, the young investment banker who helped define the
Internet brokerage industry by compiling its first rankings and
statistics, is leaving Credit Suisse First Boston to become general
partner of a new $1.2 billion venture capital fund of Softbank,
Japan's largest distributor of packaged software and hardware.
Burnham, 28, will be one of four general partners in the fund,
which has already made a half-dozen investments, and will develop a
research staff for Softbank.
</P>
</TEXT>
