<HEADER>
A6848 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-TEN-GRAF-CAREER-TEX     08-13 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-GRAF-CAREER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF ENDS GRAND CAREER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was an unseasonably cold and windy night in south Florida,
prompting a handful of fans to build a small bonfire in the
makeshift stands overlooking the tennis court where the sport's
reigning queen, Chris Evert, was playing against a teen-ager with
blond ambition. This was in February, 1985, at the inaugural Lipton
Championships, which was being held at a temporary site in DeLand.
Despite the elements, the business-like Evert dispatched her
opponent before the last embers of the fire had died.
</P>
<P>
   But those who had come to watch Queen Chris give a free tennis
lesson to a virtual unknown were impressed by the tall, slender
15-year-old from Germany whose loss that night could be attributed
more to inexperience than a lack of talent or will. Tennis often
devours its young, leaving teen-age phenoms physically and
psychologically scarred, but there was something about Steffi
Graf's resolve even then that hinted she might be special.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, no one could have predicted that Graf would
exceed expectations and become the most dominant player in the game
_ perhaps the best player and athlete in the history of women's
tennis. Now, 14 1/2 years after that cold night in Florida, and in
the autumn of her career, Graf has announced her retirement.
</P>
<P>
   She goes out in style, winning this year's French Open for her
22nd Grand Slam singles title and reaching the final of Wimbledon.
But at 30, the succession of injuries and the demands placed on a
globe-trotting tennis pro have taken their toll. The player whose
signature shot earned her the nickname ``Fraulein Forehand'' is
leaving on her own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning Roland Garros was an unbelievable moment for me and
getting to the finals of Wimbledon so soon after was incredible,''
Graf said in a news conference yesterday in Heidelberg, Germany.
``I just felt the motivation to perform at the very highest level
was no longer there, and the fun had gone out of practice and
training. I have come to the stage in my career when it is time to
start looking at other things. I just feel the time is right to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Her list of accomplishments equals or surpasses those of any
tennis legend. Graf won 107 singles titles and spent 377 weeks
ranked No. 1 in the world _ a record for any tennis player, woman
or man. She emerged a top player in the final years of the
Evert-Martina Navratilova era and forged her own spirited rivalries
with Gabriela Sabatini and Monica Seles.
</P>
<P>
   What sets Graf apart from her contemporaries and all but four
other players in the history of the sport, however, is the Grand
Slam she won in 1988. In a tour de force unrivaled in tennis'
professional era, Graf won the Australian Open, French Open,
Wimbledon and U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   She then capped an extraordinary year by winning the gold medal
in the Seoul Olympics, becoming the only player in history to win a
Golden Slam.
</P>
<P>
   She won with that remarkable forehand that she hit with
laser-like precision, a slice backhand that was unspectacular but
rarely exploited, and athleticism that enabled her to cover the
court like a tarp on a baseball infield. She was fast and loved to
run; during the Seoul Olympics, she was drawn to the track and
field events. She said wistfully that she would have loved to have
been a sprinter.
</P>
<P>
   Although she quickly earned the respect of her peers and the
game's icons with her results, Graf was not readily embraced off
the court during the early years.
</P>
<P>
   Because women believed that they were treated like second-class
citizens compared to men, the women's tour was like a loosely
formed sorority. Billie Jean King, then Evert and Navratilova were
the sorority leaders. But as prize money increased, thus raising
the stakes, younger players led a more solitary existence. Graf did
not join the sorority and was perceived as aloof. Her father, Peter
Graf, was considered domineering and was widely resented by the
leaders in the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   The players' choice was Argentina's Sabatini, who was
personable, had the looks of a model and a game that could have
rivaled Graf's if she had ever been motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Sabatini was Graf's opponent in the final of the 1988 U.S. Open,
the last obstacle between Fraulein Forehand and the Grand Slam.
With two publicists from the women's tour openly cheering for
Sabatini in the press box, Graf dismissed her rival and joined Don
Budge, Maureen Connolly, Rod Laver (twice) and Margaret Court as
winners of the Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   She was only 19 and dependent on her father to handle her
business affairs and the politics of the sport. Peter Graf was
difficult to deal with, although fiercely protective of his
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Graf and Boris Becker had emerged as larger-than-life characters
in Germany, unable to visit their homeland without being engulfed
in a sea of paparazzi and reporters. Peter Graf talked about the
boys bearing gifts who would scale the picket fence in front of
Graf's home in Bruhl, Germany, and knock at the door. He talked
about the occasional threats against his daughter and the love
letters from obsessed young men. He would never tell her about any
of this.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, there was a glimpse of what life might have been
like had Graf not wielded a tennis racket with such impunity. On
the weekend before his daughter began her quest to complete the
Grand Slam at the U.S. Open, Peter Graf invited a journalist to
dinner at the home of friends in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Steffi played pinball with the journalist's 8-year-old son; she
set the table and cleared the plates after each course. Later that
evening, she went to her room and danced alone in the dark to her
favorite music on the stereo. She blushed when her father knocked
on the door and she was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   As the years unfolded, she began speaking more often on her own
behalf and became the best advertisement for the women's game. But
there were more hardships on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if Graf was found guilty by association when one of
her misguided fans dashed from the stands at the German Open in
1993 and stabbed Seles in the back. Seles had overtaken Graf as the
No. 1 player and was gaining an upper hand in their rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1996, Graf's father was found guilty of income-tax
evasion by the German government and sent to jail. There were also
reports that he was having an extramarital affair. Steffi stood by
her father throughout the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   And there were the injuries. Navratilova and Evert occasionally
intimated that Graf exaggerated her aches and pains, but the
injuries were serious enough to sideline her for extended periods
during the last few years of her career. Ironically, Graf said that
her history of injuries had no part in her decision to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not been forced into this decision by my injuries,''
she said at yesterday's news conference. ``Right now, I'm perfectly
fit.''
</P>
<P>
   She will embark on a farewell tour of exhibitions at the end of
the year, visiting places she has never been. Always stoic in
victory and defeat, she may even shed a tear or two as she did
after defeating Martina Hingis to win the French Open in early
June.
</P>
<P>
   She will continue to be associated with tennis, she said,
working with youth groups and the German federation. But now, she
can fade into the background where she always felt more
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing left to accomplish,'' Graf said. ``I am very
happy and relieved to have made this decision and I look forward to
what the future brings.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6850 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CHINA-SMUGGLE14-COX     08-13 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SMUGGLE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Botched smuggling of 132 Chinese in Georgia sets records
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ The discovery Thursday of 132 Chinese men in a
secret compartment of a ship is the biggest and most sophisticated
smuggling case immigration and port officials in Georgia say they
have ever encountered.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth major instance over the last 15 months in the
United States in which smugglers stood to profit by transporting
Chinese into this country, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Reese, a spokeswoman for the Georgia Ports Authority,
said Friday she could not recall another large-scale case of
immigrant smuggling in Savannah in the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something of this scale is just unprecedented,'' said Reese,
adding that 2,169 ships docked at the port authority or nearby
private docks last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service transported the
stowaways and the ship's 28 crew members to jails in DeKalb and
Fulton counties Friday afternoon. The stowaways, 51 of them between
the ages of 14 and 17, were on the ship for at least two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   All of the people seized from the ship spent Thursday night at a
National Guard armory in Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Fischer, INS district director, said agency officials
plan to interview the stowaways today and Sunday, hoping to
discover their destination _ the ship was headed for Georgetown,
S.C., after its scheduled stop in Savannah _ and whether an
employer awaited their arrival. The INS brought in agents from New
York who speak Chinese to help interrogate the detainees.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials will decide whether to file charges against the
ship's crew members. Authorities had not charged anyone as of
Friday night. The INS can legally detain the stowaways and crew
members because they are in this country illegally, Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Savannah is seen as a gateway to the United States for
illegal immigrants, as are many seaports. Illegal immigration
problems in Savannah have not significantly worsened in the last
few years, he said, but they have not improved, either.
</P>
<P>
   Congress ordered the INS last year to spend more money to help
local law enforcement agencies crack down on illegal immigration in
11 states that do not share a border with Canada or Mexico. Georgia
is one of those states, and the INS identified four regions in
which it plans to bolster its presence, including Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Smuggling Chinese nationals into the United States has become
big business in the last few years. Investigators say criminal
organizations in China typically charge each passenger $30,000 to
$47,000 for the trip, usually aboard a ship and very often in
squalid conditions where disease, rape and hunger can be rampant.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gilhooly, INS spokesman for 25 states in the eastern
United States, said the agency intercepted 700 Chinese being
smuggled into this country in 1996. The number rose to 1,100 in
1998, and 1,900 so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the aliens come here for work, he said, but they often
spend years repaying the debt they owe to smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Other recent interceptions:
</P>
<P>
   _ In May 1998, 23 Chinese aliens waded ashore on an affluent New
Jersey beach after a small boat they were riding in ran out of
fuel. INS agents found a much bigger boat in the waters nearby. The
captain and his engineer were convicted of smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   _ In September 1998, the INS discovered 174 Chinese nationals on
a ship near San Diego, Calif. The captain and four crew members
were convicted.
</P>
<P>
   _ In December 1998, investigators charged 30 people in a scheme
to smuggle 3,600 Chinese into New York City over a two-year period.
Organizers of that ring charged $47,000 a trip and made about $170
million, Gilhooly said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Chinese nationals who were detained in those cases
are awaiting deportation. Gilhooly said an immigration judge
reviews any requests for political asylum, but he did not know
whether such requests were made in the three 1998 cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smugglers put human beings at risk,'' he said. ``The
linchpin in smuggling is that people are profiting from human
misery.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on a tip two weeks ago, the U.S. Coast Guard on Wednesday
used a dog trained to sniff out humans in searching the Prince
Nicolas, a cargo ship from Cyprus owned by Cosmomar Shipping, when
it was six miles off the coast. They found nothing suspicious,
Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   INS agents searched again after the ship docked. ``We had a
sixth sense that something was wrong,'' Fischer said. On Thursday,
officials inspected the ship after it docked in Savannah and
discovered a secret hatch that was welded shut to conceal the
Chinese immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese slept in bunks and had air conditioning, but they
shared tight quarters and had to use a hole in the floor as a
restroom. ``This was not part of the Carnival cruise line,''
Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   The would-be immigrants were carrying large sums of American
money, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer said the government probably will order medical
examinations to see whether any of the detainees have tuberculosis
or other diseases that could be easily transmitted in a jail. He
said his agents planned to seize the 40,000 ton ship, which is more
than two football fields long.
</P>
<P>
   Waves lapped against the massive black hull of the Prince
Nicolas on Friday afternoon. American and Cypriot flags flew near a
``SAFETY FIRST'' slogan and a ``DANGEROUS CARGO'' warning stenciled
by rusting metal equipment. Giant ropes anchored the ship to a dock
in one of two deep-water ports maintained by the Georgia Ports
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
