<HEADER>
A6851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TEN-GRAF-RETIRES14-CO     08-13 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-GRAF-RETIRES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No farewell tour as Graf retires
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Steffi Graf rested her case Friday. The argument is
whether she's the greatest women's tennis player in history.
</P>
<P>
   In a teary press conference near her home in Heidelberg,
Germany, the 22-time Grand Slam singles champion announced that she
was retiring immediately, declining to stay on for a final farewell
at the U.S. Open next month.
</P>
<P>
   All that's left following a 17-year career that earned her more
than $20 million is for historians to decide where Graf ranks among
the all-time greats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steffi is definitely one of the greatest tennis players of all
time, and she is the all-time greatest singles player,'' said
Billie Jean King, who won Wimbledon six times, one fewer than Graf.
</P>
<P>
   King made that assessment based on Graf's singles record in
Grand Slam championships. Graf's 22 major titles are second to
Margaret Court, who won most of her 24 prior to the open era.
</P>
<P>
   Graf is the only player to win each of the four majors at least
four times each, and in 1988 she won them all, joining Court in
1970 and Maureen Connolly in 1953 as the only women to achieve the
Grand Slam of tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, a lithe 5 feet 9, was the superior athlete of her time,
hopping and sprinting along the baseline to crunch the most famous
forehand in women's history. She was the pre-eminent player for a
decade, finishing No. 1 a record eight times. She won at least one
Grand Slam each year from 1987 to '96. Starting with her Australian
Open title in 1988, Graf won 20 of the next 33 majors she entered
and made the final of six others.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what simmered in her personal life, Graf was virtually
incomparable when the stakes were highest. She was 107-30 in
finals, the best of any player in the open era. She won all six
majors she played in 1995 and '96, winning 42 straight matches.
</P>
<P>
   Graf turned pro in 1982 as a bony 13-year-old and won her first
title four years later in '86, beating Chris Evert at Hilton Head,
S.C.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Graf made the final of every tournament she entered and
opened the year with 45 straight wins, still a tour record.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, perhaps her greatest, Graf won the four majors
plus the Olympic women's singles title for a ``Golden Slam.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Graf won 86 of 88 matches, the second-best record in
history behind Martina Navratilova's 86-1 mark in 1983. Graf held
the No. 1 ranking from Aug. 17, 1987, to March 10, 1991, for a WTA
Tour-record 186 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the rise of Monica Seles, two-fisted off both sides
with groundstrokes more powerful than anyone before her. The
contrast in styles _ Graf's speed and forehand against Seles' will
and fearless baseline assault _ made for a potential rivalry of the
ages.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy of Seles' stabbing in 1993 by a Graf fan in Hamburg
was also a loss for Graf. How many Grand Slam titles did Graf win,
her critics ask, because of the absence of Seles?
</P>
<P>
   Head-to-head, Graf won 10 of their 15 meetings, with a 4-1 edge
after the stabbing, and a 3-0 record before Seles' first major
title, the 1990 French. They were 3-3 in between, when both were at
the height of their powers.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Graf was unchallenged as the sport's pre-eminent
player for the next three years despite personal turmoil. Her
father and coach, Peter, was imprisoned for tax evasion on her
income in 1995, a year when Graf won three more majors.
</P>
<P>
   It was Graf's body, not her spirit, that began to wane. In 1997,
she missed Wimbledon and the final seven months of the year
following knee surgery as Martina Hingis ascended to No. 1 while
asserting that Graf was finished.
</P>
<P>
   This year, in her final comeback, Graf scored what she called
her most meaningful victory of all when she stunned top-seeded
Hingis in the French final. Graf announced then she'd played her
final time in Paris. She made it her last Wimbledon, too, after
reaching the final against Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   It was assumed she'd stay on until the U.S. Open, which she had
won five times. But Friday, 10 days after pulling out of the San
Diego tour stop because of a hamstring injury, Graf, 30, said she'd
play no more.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
