<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6852 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-LA-SHOOTING-MENTAL-86     08-13 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-SHOOTING-MENTAL-860(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE DID NOT COMMIT FURROW, DESPITE DOCUMENTED MENTAL HEALTH
DANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (See also LA-SHOOTING) 
(bl) 
 By TIMOTHY EGAN  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Washington state mental health system got an
extensive look at Buford O. Furrow Jr. in the months before he
admitted to opening fire in a Jewish community center and killing a
postal worker in Los Angeles on Tuesday. What the experts saw was a
man who twice slashed his arms so deeply they required stitches,
drank alcohol until he blacked out, and espoused a deep hatred for
anyone who is not white.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite lengthy evaluations at mental institutions here,
and no shortage of resources, Furrow was never ordered to remain
under long-term state psychiatric care. Instead, after serving
nearly six months in jail for trying to stab two workers at a
private hospital near Seattle, he was released under parole
supervision and required to take medication to control psychotic
impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Furrow should have fallen under this state's standard
for involuntary commitment to a mental institution is a question
now shadowing the ground where the justice system meets psychiatry.
Furrow was an avowed racist who told a court last year that he
fantasized about committing a mass killing. His temper and violent
threats were so grave that the officer who arrested him for assault
in the Seattle area last year said he nearly had to shoot Furrow in
self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow's attorney in the case had said he would plead not guilty
by reason of insanity. But Furrow pleaded guilty, court records
show, avoiding what could have been a lengthy confinement in a
mental facility.
</P>
<P>
   And while mental health experts here say Furrow did not slip
through the cracks of a strained system _ as has happened with
troubled people in other states _ they say his case is the latest
high profile crime to raise questions about whether states should
tighten the laws on holding violent, mentally ill people in
confinement.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does society do with these people?'' said Dr. Renee
Binder, a professor of psychiatry at the University of California
at San Francisco and the chairwoman of the American Psychiatry
Association's Council on Psychiatry and the Law. ``Most people
would say that being a racist with violent fantasies is not against
the law. Racism is not something that is designated as an illness
that can be treated by mental health professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   New York officials recently agreed to expand state authority to
force mentally ill patients to undergo treatment or face
involuntary commitment, joining nearly 40 states, including
Washington, that have enacted similar laws.
</P>
<P>
   In Furrow's home state of Washington, the debate is over whether
he met the requirements of someone who should have been held in a
mental facility instead of serving a few months in jail for
assault. The Washington state law, similar to the standard of most
states, says the person must have a mental disorder and pose a
threat to harm himself or others, in the eyes of professional
examiners.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Furrow slashed his hands up with a knife and told
police he wanted to shoot people at random in a mall. Those
statements, alone, along with his threats to stab two women at a
mental hospital, where he was trying to be admitted, should have
been enough to bring a civil commitment case against Furrow, some
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This person went to a psychiatric hospital to ask for help,
pulled a knife on two women, stated very clearly that he was
homicidal and suicidal, and is tied into a Nazi hate group,'' said
Sherry Storm, the mental health ombudsman for King County, which
covers the Seattle area court system. ``All of those things put
together would seem to make a pretty strong case that he poses a
threat to himself or others.''
</P>
<P>
   But other officials say Furrow was simply a violent, hateful
man, and that trying to blame the shootings on the failures of the
mental health system is futile. They note that Furrow had only one
run-in with the law, that he had a college degree in engineering,
and that he held numerous jobs, including employment at Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem I have is that people are trying to build a case
that this killing was done because the man was insane,'' said King
County Executive Ron Sims. ``What he did was cowardly, repulsive
and a very irrational act. But mental illness was not the cause.
Hatred was. This guy came out of a culture of hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   National groups representing the mental health profession are
also reluctant to tie the shootings to a failure in the system.
They cite the case of Andrew Goldstein, the schizophrenic man who
pushed a woman to death in New York, or Russell Weston Jr., who
killed two people in the U.S. Capitol, as examples of how
potentially violent, mentally ill people who sought treatment were
largely ignored. But with Furrow, they say, the case is less
compelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all understand that Goldstein and Weston should have had
more treatment,'' said Bill Emmett, deputy executive director of
the National Alliance for the Mentally Ill, an advocacy group based
in Arlington, Va. ``But we're not that eager to have Furrow's case
equated with Goldstein and Weston. We simply don't have enough
facts.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Confidentiality laws prohibit officials from disclosing details
about Furrow's mental health record. But court records show that
last year, during his first encounter with the criminal justice
system, he was extensively examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it is not a question of whether we have the
resources,'' Amnon Shoenfeld, a supervisor with the mental health
professionals who evaluate inmates for King County. ``We always
have adequate beds.''
</P>
<P>
   Of about 5,000 people referred for evaluation in this county
every year, nearly half are sent to some form of involuntary
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Within a day of Furrow's arrest last Oct. 28, mental health
officials sent him to to the psychiatric ward at Harborview Medical
Center in Seattle _ a large public hospital. Later, he was sent for
several weeks of evaluation at the Washington state mental facility
south of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   If the experts concluded that he posed a significant enough risk
to merit long-term involuntary commitment, it was never reflected
in the court record. The record shows that he returned to jail in
King County on Dec. 11, and stayed there until his release May 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``With civil commitments, you're always trying to strike a
balance between protecting society and the rights of the
individual,'' said Dr. Binder.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow's court-appointed attorney in last year's assault case,
Leona Thomas, told the court she planned to enter a plea of
not-guilty by reason of insanity. But Furrow entered a guilty plea
instead.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Furrow avoided what could have been a sentence of
up to 10 years of involuntary confinement in a mental facility. He
was sentenced to 5 1/2 months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a case like that, when a person pleads guilty, most people
think that's a way of getting off,'' said Ms. Storm. ``The real
question is whether the judge should be forced to accept the guilty
plea or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the case, King County Superior Court Judge Harriet
Cody, did not return phone calls requesting comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Cody did require, as a term of Furrow's release, that
he stay on his medication, refrain from drinking alcohol and not
own a gun. State officials say Furrow met his parole requirements,
as near as they could tell, until later this summer when he left
the state.
</P>
<P>
   By requiring Furrow to stay on an anti-psychotic medication, the
state has considerable leverage over him, in the eyes of Ms.
Binder. ``In some cases, that sort of requirement is stronger than
civil commitment,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state has been through several well-publicized cases
in which mentally ill people who were allowed to remain free
committed violent crimes. Two years ago, after a mentally ill man
stabbed to death a retired Seattle firefigther after a Mariners
baseball game, the law was changed, making it easier to refer
people to mental evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   This state's law also prohibits the family from committing a
member who is older than the age of 13 to a mental facility.
Furrow's father, Buford Furrow Sr., wanted his son to be under
closer supervision of a mental health care system as a condition of
parole, said the family's neighbor in the town of Old Nisqually,
Wash., Clint Merrill, in a brief interview Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
