u r BC-CAR-NASCAR14-COX     08-13 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wallace pole ends Gordon's streak
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ Friday the 13th at Watkins Glen had these
frightful developments: a 3 1/2-hour rain delay that wiped out most
of the practice time, a road kill by Dale Jarrett, and Jeff Gordon
failing to win a road course pole for the first time in four races.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace weathered the stormy conditions to grab the pole
for Sunday's Frontier at the Glen with a track-record qualifying
lap of 121.234 mph. He breezed around the 2.45-mile course in
72.752 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   It's Wallace's first pole since Bristol in April, 14 races ago.
</P>
<P>
   Road course specialist Boris Said, who also drives in the NASCAR
truck series, will start on the outside pole after qualifying the
No. 14 Ford second with a lap of 120.915 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cars are like women, they've all got their own
personalities,'' Said said of his temporary move. ``I like all
women and I like all cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, whose streak of four consecutive road course wins is at
risk Sunday, qualified third at 120.632 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup points leader Dale Jarrett qualified ninth on a lap
that included an encounter with a woodchuck in the inner loop. ``If
I could have gotten in there quicker, we wouldn't have been there
at the same time,'' Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to keep sacrificing animals like this. In '96 I hit a
bird in the (Daytona) 500 and won that. In July, I hit a turtle in
practice at Daytona and we won that race. Now I've hit a woodchuck.
I'm sure the animal activists out there are gong to be after Dale
Jarrett, but I'll assure you, there's nothing I'm trying to do. I'm
not aiming at 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's qualifying lap may have been a surprise only to him.
He was fast when the cars took to the track on rain tires for some
morning practice. The drivers quickly changed to regular tires when
the track dried.
</P>
<P>
   But Wallace got in only six laps, including a field-fastest
103.840 mph, before the rains wiped out the remainder of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte lost a transmission in his No. 18 Pontiac on a
practice lap, hit the wall on the inner loop and had to go to a
backup car to qualify 22nd.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Mayfield provided the only qualifying-run adventure,
spinning out on his attempt and finishing slowest among the 49 cars
at 105.768 mph. ``When your lap ends with the crew congratulating
you for keeping the car off the wall, that's usually not a very
good sign,'' Mayfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace got the congratulations that counted most.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done much to the car, except put some spring
rubbers in the back and adjust the chassis a little bit,'' Wallace
said. ``We put some timing in the motor and leaned the thing out a
little bit, and the thing really came alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
