NYT-08-13-99 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6857 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GAMECOCKS14-COX     08-13 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GAMECOCKS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holtz giving Gamecocks a case of Lou-mania
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ South Carolina finished 1-10 in 1998, the worst
season of the program's 105. But its fans couldn't be more excited
about this fall if the Gamecocks were the defending national
champions.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Two words.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old grandfather hasn't coached in two years and has
not won a game at South Carolina. But the impact he's had on this
town and this state is off the charts. It is called ``Lou-mania''
and these are some of its effects:
</P>
<P>
   _ Despite four consecutive losing seasons, the school has set a
record for season-ticket sales with more than 53,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the spring, after listening to Holtz's pep talks, the
always-generous South Carolina boosters set a record by forking
over $8.3million.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hotels in and around Columbia were booked faster than ever.
Restaurant owners are expecting a record season. ``We ought to put
him on the front of our travel guide,'' said Lou Fontana, a
representative of the South Carolina Department of Parks,
Recreation and Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   _ A football clinic for women started by former coach Sparky
Woods had never drawn more than 800. More than 1,200 showed up this
summer to see Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe so much enthusiasm exists for a team that
will have to overachieve to finish fourth in the SEC's rugged
Eastern Division. South Carolina just doesn't have the depth of
division rivals Tennessee, Florida and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But one day in Columbia makes it clear that the town is buying
what Lou Holtz has to sell _ hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally our fans are looking at the schedule and counting how
many games we can win and wondering if we can go to a bowl game,''
said Kerry Tharp, South Carolina's longtime sports information
director. ``This year it's different. They are just excited that
something very positive is happening. They're not worried about the
present, because the future looks bright.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope is not confined to the fans. Strong safety Arturo
Freeman was a preseason All-SEC choice last year before tearing up
his right knee in practice. If not for the injury, Freeman would be
in an NFL camp now. He believes it was fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything happens for a reason,'' said Freeman, whose
knee is 100 percent. ``I think my injury happened so I could come
back and play for somebody the caliber of Coach Holtz. I really
feel blessed.'' To break from its history of mediocrity, South
Carolina needs the kind of exposure Holtz generates _ and the
ability to translate it into better recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 89 Gamecocks teams that have played at least eight games
in a season, only one has won more than eight; the 1984 team went
10-2. South Carolina has played in nine bowl games, winning one.
Things got tougher in 1992 when the school joined the SEC and was
placed in a division with Tennessee, Florida and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to be competitive with those teams, we've got
to go out and get the kind of athletes in the numbers that they
do,'' athletics director Mike McGee said. ``Lou Holtz gives us
instant credibility in that regard. He can go into any home in
America and sell our program. That's a tremendous boost.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz has made no promises about how fast he can turn things
around. He knows that the program can improve significantly and
still not measure up to the top of the SEC. But he knows he has all
the ingredients to win. ``To me there's not a question of if we can
win,'' Holtz said. ``The only question is when, and I can't answer
that, because of the toughness of the schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with a tough schedule, things are going South
Carolina's way. The Gamecocks' opener, at North Carolina State on
Sept. 4, normally would not make a ripple. Because it's Holtz's
first game on the sideline in two years, ESPN has chosen it for a
Saturday prime-time telecast. The following week's game at Georgia
also will be televised.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to do is get out there and let people know what
we have here at South Carolina,'' Holtz said. ``We have a great
university in a great state. We have a great product to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   And at long last, South Carolina has hope.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
