<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6866 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN-GRAF-RETIRES-HNS &LR;      08-13 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-GRAF-RETIRES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Graf calls it a career
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JODY GOLDSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   HoustonChronicle
</P>
<P>
   It has been the year of retirements, and now one of the best
ever to pick up a tennis racket is calling it quits.
</P>
<P>
   Steffi Graf, who turned 30 a week after winning the French Open
in June, called a news conference near her hometown of Bruehl,
Germany, on Friday to announce she is leaving the sport, effective
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt right after Paris and Wimbledon that the motivation
wasn't what it was in the past,'' Graf said. ``I have done
everything I wanted to do in tennis. After Wimbledon, for the first
time in my career, I didn't feel like going to a tournament. I went
to San Diego just to make sure, and I felt it right away. It is
time to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf is the latest in a list of sports legends to make 1999
their final year of competition, joining Michael Jordan, Wayne
Gretzky, John Elway and most recently Barry Sanders. All walked
away while still near the top of their sport.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego last week, Graf suffered another in an exhaustive
series of injuries that have plagued her career over the past two
years. She strained her left hamstring, causing her to retire from
a second-round match against Amy Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was thought she would play in the U.S. Open, which
begins Aug. 30. But she knew almost instantly her heart wasn't in
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, the decision (to retire) was very easy, maybe too
easy,'' Graf said. ``I was pulled back and forth, but when I made
my decision, I didn't think about it one minute afterward. On the
plane coming back from San Diego, I just started poring through
these magazines and thinking of all the places I could go.''
</P>
<P>
   There are few places she hasn't been. Graf has won tournaments
on six continents, the most notable being her 22 Grand Slams, two
shy of Margaret Court's record. But now she would like to travel
without a racket in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to enjoy the privilege of having time to do the
things I haven't had time to do before and to discover what I want
to do with the rest of my life,'' Graf said.
</P>
<P>
   Her spot in tennis history is established, with several records
that aren't likely to fall any time soon. She was the world's No. 1
player for a total of 377 weeks, the most of anyone _ male or
female _ in history. She held that ranking consecutively from Aug.
17, 1987, to March 10, 1991, a total of 186 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Her biggest achievement was a calendar, or ``Golden'' Grand
Slam. She won all four majors _ the Australian Open, French Open,
Wimbledon and U.S. Open _ in 1988, becoming one of only five
players to accomplish the feat. She also won the gold medal at the
Seoul Olympics that year. There were four years in which she won
three of the four major events, and she is the only player to win
all four Grand Slam titles at least four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steffi is a class act,'' said Bart McGuire, chief executive
officer of the WTA Tour. ``As a motivated, well-conditioned,
disciplined and competitive athlete, she has been a role model for
women athletes in all sports. She has been a catalyst for the
resurgence of women's tennis, especially in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steffi is leaving, characteristically, on her own terms. We
wish her well and hope that she will continue to be an ambassador
for women's tennis and for women's sports worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf has suffered chronic sinus and back problems, in addition
to various other pesky maladies. She missed most of 1997 with
injuries and underwent surgery on her left knee.
</P>
<P>
   She played only 44 matches in 1998 because of injuries and had
surgery on her right wrist. And she had played sparingly in 1999
before arriving at Roland Garros in May.
</P>
<P>
   That made her summer achievements that much more spectacular.
Graf won her first Grand Slam in three years, stunning even herself
as she rallied for a three-set come-from-behind victory over
Martina Hingis in the French Open final. A month later, she reached
the final at Wimbledon, only to lose to Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Graf bid an emotional farewell after both events, saying she
would not return. She called the French Open final her best ever
and even took out a half-page ad in the French sporting daily
l'Equipe to thank the French public for its support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you to all my French friends for the many years of
support and those unforgettable moments that I had the opportunity
to live in your company. From the bottom of my heart, thank you,''
Graf wrote in a message she had drafted in French and signed.
</P>
<P>
   She then made an impromptu retirement announcement in New York
in July, hinting 1999 would be her final season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am privileged to be able to leave when I wish without being
pushed toward the exit door,'' Graf said. ``It was not easy to make
this decision, but the competition had become too difficult for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   She retracted the statement, along with the two at the French
Open and Wimbledon, claiming she had spoken hastily.
</P>
<P>
   But this time she's certain. Graf turned pro at 13 and has spent
more than half her life traveling the circuit. She won her first
tournament at 16, beating Chris Evert at Hilton Head, S.C., in
April 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Graf beat Evert again 11 months later at Key Biscayne, Fla.,
becoming the youngest player (17) to pass $1 million in earnings.
She won at Roland Garros in 1987, beating Martina Navratilova for
her first Grand Slam title. She earned the No. 1 ranking for the
first time by the end of that year, two months after her 18th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   After 17 years in the sport, she finishes with 107 tournament
titles. She ranks third on that all-time list, trailing only
Navratilova (167) and Evert (157).
</P>
<P>
   Graf has proved she can overcome injuries. This decision wasn't
based on her physical health, but on her mental well-being.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm perfect physically,'' Graf said. ``I've been
biking, doing everything. This is in no way about injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf will appear at the U.S. Open for one more en masse
interview with the international tennis media. And though she won't
compete in WTA Tour events, she plans to announce a series of
exhibition matches to serve as a farewell tour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
