<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 08/13/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) MEXICO CITY -- Aug. 13, 1999 -- MEXICO-MONEY-TRANSFERS,
08-13 --Miriam Sagaon Rojas learned that money transfers could be
costly. Many of the estimated six million Mexicans who live and
work in the United States send money to Mexico. But as the
cross-border wire transfer business has boomed, some customers have
been complaining that they pay too much to deliver cash to needy
relatives at home. (Wesley Bocxe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) MATSU, Taiwan -- Aug. 13, 1999 -- TAIWAN-ISLAND, 08-13
-- Even during times of political tension, many tourists from
Taiwan visit Matsu to try to glimpse mainland China, three miles
away. There are five flights a day from Taipei, and they are booked
solid on weekends. (Seth Faison/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) RAWALPINDI, Pakistan -- Aug. 13, 1999 --
PAKISTAN-WOMEN-2, 08-13 -- Students on the campus of Fatima Jinnah
Women University in Rawalpindi. Setting up a state-supported
graduate school for women was a new idea that made many Pakistani
women who are educators or other professionals uneasy. (Celia
Dugger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) RAWALPINDI, Pakistan -- Aug. 13, 1999 --
PAKISTAN-WOMEN-1, 08-13 -- Students on the campus of Fatima Jinnah
Women University in Rawalpindi include Tauseef Fatima, 25, studying
for a master's degree in education. Men in her home province of
Sindh ``are very dominant,'' she says, so lectures about the rights
of women in Islam - to divorce, to property, to think for
themselves - are ``new ideas for me.'' (Celia Dugger/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 1999 -- TEN-GRAF-RETIRE, 08-13 -- A
somewhat doused Stefi Graf holds her 1996 U.S. Open trophy aloft
during the rain-dampened awards ceremony following her finals
victory over Monica Seles. After a 17-year career, she announced
her retirement Friday from her home in Heidelberg, Germany. ``I
just feel the time is right to move on,'' says Graf, 30. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 1999 -- DALLAI-LAMA, 08-13 -- The
Dalai Lama, 14th in a line of spiritual leaders of Tibet stretching
back 600 years, in New York recently. His message is both simple
and compelling, one that offers hope on both individual and
societal levels. And that may be what is proving so attractive
about him to Americans. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SAN DIEGO -- Aug. 13, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 15 --
BIZ-PROFILE-SANDS, 08-13 -- Stan Lee, the creator of Spider-Man and
X-Men, displaying a T-Shirt at a comics convention in San Diego.
Stan Lee Media Inc., his first independent venture after more than
five decades with Marvel Enterprises, will begin trading Monday on
the Nasdaq market. (Dave Gatley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) CAPE COD, Mass. -- Aug. 13, 1999 --
AMERICAN-VACATION-B&AMP;W, 08-13 -- Some vacationers go for
self-improvement, as in a Provincetown art class on Cape Cod in
1927. ``Vacations were born in the industrial revolution, when the
pressure of industry time discipline - working by the clock - meant
we started separating work from life,'' says Karen Halttunen, a
professor of history at the University of California at Davis.
(Times World Wide Photos/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) FREEPORT, Maine -- Aug. 13, 1999 -- BEAN-BOOMERS-3,
08-13 -- As part of an attempt to update the company's image, kids
can now climb to their little hearts' content at the revamped LL
Bean store in Freeport. Such attention to image is meant to counter
plateauing sales at L.L. Bean, which does not publish a financial
statement but says it sold just over $1 billion worth of gloves,
parkas, kayaks, skirts, pillow shams, knapsacks and bathing suits
last year. (Herb Swanson/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) FREEPORT, Maine -- Aug. 13, 1999 -- BEAN-BOOMERS-2,
08-13 -- Patricia Robles, the current executive in charge of LL
Bean's E-commerce division, insists that the company's revamped
Website, which should be available in October, will be efficient,
user-friendly and up-to-date. ``For a company that's known to be
conservative and traditional, we really were out on the Web
early,'' says Ms. Robles. ``We are really putting significant
resources into the Web.'' (Herb Swanson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) FREEPORT, Maine -- Aug. 13, 1999 -- BEAN-BOOMERS-1,
08-13 -- LL Bean, the 87-year-old arbiter of what's what in rugged
outerwear, is going after cosseted baby boomers in a big way: the
company's Maine Hunting Shoe, its first product and essential icon,
has been revamped to make it more comfortable. ``In today's
environment, however, we are going to have to focus much more
intently on profitability,'' says Leon A. Gorman, who has been
Bean's president for the last 32 years. (Herb Swanson/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Aug. 13, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 15 --
LUXURY-PILLOWS-B&AMP;W, 08-13 -- The Company Store is marketing what it
calls the ``world's most expensive pillow.'' In a triumph of
specialization, the company has emitted a new 31-page Pillow Source
Book. Mostly about bed pillows, it is absolutely riveting -
particularly when read in bed. (The Company Store/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WESTBOROUGH, Mass.-- Aug. 13, 199 --
CELLPHONE-DEADSPOTS-BOS, 08-13 -- From his Ford Taurus station
wagon outfitted with $250,000 worth of electronics and an array of
antennas, Eugene Giordano racks up 3,000 miles a month looking for
cellular phone dead spots. Giordano's testing regularly helps
engineers determine whether various towers' coverage should be
extended or shortened to ensure efficient distribution of calls
among towers. (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SMITHFIELD, R.I. -- Aug. 13, 199 --
FBN-PATRIOTS-KATZENMOYER-BOS, 08-13 -- Andy Katzenmoyer, ``The Big
Cat'', won't be starting when the New England Patriots open their
1999 NFL exhibition schedule Friday night against the Washington
Redskins in Foxboro Stadium. When asked if he is slightly relieved
not to be starting he replies ``In a way yes, but in a way no. No,
because I've always been the starter.'' (Barry Chin/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 15 --
NITEOUT-SOUTAR, 08-13 -- Mike Soutar taking batting practice at the
Chelsea Piers sports complex Tuesday night. His time spent in the
batting cage was the latest episode in the education of Soutar, the
new editor of Maxim magazine, the skin-drenched monthly. (Linda
Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 15 --
RAPPERS'-JEWELER, 08-13 -- Jacob Arabo, a jeweler made famous in
story and song by his rapper clients, loads on diamands and
platinum by the pound. Asked how he feels about the anti-Semitism
that flares up occasionally in rap lyrics, Arabo, 34, who is
Jewish, says: ``What, are you kidding me? They all say, 'Jacob, I
want to marry a Jewish girl.' `` (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BEDFORD, Mass. -- Aug. 13, 1999 -- DOMINICAN-COLONEL-BOS,
08-13 -- Dr. Antonia Silva-Hale, 44, is the first woman from the
