r a BC-SEATS-CAPITOL-KAN &LR;      08-13 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATS-CAPITOL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. HOUSE MEMBERS' SEATS TO GET EXTRA LAYER OF SECURITY AT
CAPITOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When members of the House return from their summer
recess Sept. 8, they all can claim to have safe seats, even if they
are in trouble politically.
</P>
<P>
   Workers are installing bulletproof seat backs in all chairs on
the House floor, replacing flat metal plates inserted about 15
years ago after a Capitol bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The new material, a heavy fabric, is less likely to produce
ricochets and more likely to absorb or safely deflect bullets,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Capitol police declined to give details about the seat-back
project but said it is among several new security measures at the
Capitol, including installation of better metal detectors, alarm
systems and surveillance cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just an ongoing security enhancement taking place,''
said Dan Nichols, spokesman for the Capitol Police. ``That's about
as far as I can go.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress approved $106 million last September for improved
security, including the addition of 240 new officers, after a
Capitol shooting left two officers dead. The shootings were in
hallways, not in the House chamber.
</P>
<P>
   House officials would not disclose the cost of the seat-back
project because it is security-related. It is not part of the $106
million appropriated by Congress, Nichols said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many House members knew they had
bullet-resistant plates in their chairs in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not know it,'' said Rep. Ike Skelton of Lexington, Mo.,
who is ranking Democrat on the Armed Services Committee. ``We sit
around a lot waiting for votes. You'd think someone would have said
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Capitol police ordered the new material inserts at the request
of the House sergeant-at-arms, officials said. The material also
can be used in bullet-proof vests, furniture, vehicles and walls
and is intended to either trap bullets or have them fall to the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Jeffries, spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert, said
he was unaware of the project but that it would have come with
Hastert's approval at the request of the sergeant-at-arms.
</P>
<P>
   There are 448 seats on the floor, 435 for House members. They
are attached in semi-circular structures, unlike the 100 individual
swivel chairs in the Senate. Several officials said they did not
think Senate chairs had bulletproof backing, but that could not be
confirmed because of security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Security officials said it is highly unlikely anyone could get
into the House or Senate galleries with a gun because visitors have
to pass through metal detectors at the Capitol entrance and again
before entering the galleries.
</P>
<P>
   But the bullet-proof seat backs would provide cover on the
chance someone did open fire, as occurred on March 1, 1954, when
three Puerto Rican nationalists opened fire from the gallery and
wounded five members of the House.
</P>
<P>
   The assailants reportedly yelled out, ``Freedom for Puerto
Rico,'' as they fired 30 bullets from the House gallery. About 200
House members were present when the shots rang out. Bullets
splintered chairs and desks and chipped plaster from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Emerson of Missouri, who later became a congressman, was
chief page at the time of the shooting. Years later, he often told
the story of the shooting while giving House tours, said Jeffries,
who worked for Emerson from 1991 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``He heard some pops and everyone started to duck,'' Jeffries
said. ``He said one bullet breezed over his head and lodged in a
marble column in the corner of the chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   House Parliamentarian Charles Johnson and former House Historian
Ray Smock said the metal plates were installed not after that
attack but after a bomb exploded in a second-floor Senate hallway
in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was if someone started firing you could dive under
the seats and at least you'd have some metal protection,'' Smock
said.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 19th century, guns and bombs were less of a threat
than other items visitors brought to the House and Senate
galleries, said Don Ritchie, associate historian for the Senate.
Even a horseshoe was a potential weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``During some heated debates, especially before the Civil War,
they had a number of cases where people threw objects, and one of
them was a horseshoe,'' Ritchie said.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie said House and Senate members often carried guns
themselves. In 1835, Vice President Martin Van Buren regularly wore
a pair of pistols while presiding over the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In one celebrated incident during debate on the Compromise of
1850, Sen. Thomas Hart Benton of Missouri faced the gun barrel of a
colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Henry Foote of Mississippi got mad at Benton during the
debate and pulled a pistol on him, Ritchie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other senators sort of grabbed Benton's arms and Benton
yelled out, `Let the assassin fire,' '' Ritchie said. The fracas
ended without a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only occasion when a pistol has been pulled on the
floor,'' Ritchie said. ``At least by a senator.''
</P>
</TEXT>
