<P>
   CUBA-PHOTO-ADVISORY -- Editors pleas note: Photos NYT1-NYT5,
below, were shot by Mark Courtney of the Wilmington Star-News from
August 1-8. The photos, which depict the U.S. Coast Guard's efforts
to control the flow of illegal Cubans into the United States, may
be used as a photo package or with your own coverage.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ABOARD THE U.S. COAST GUARD CUTTER DILIGENCE -- Aug. 13,
1999 -- CUBAN-ILLEGALS-5 -- Aboard the U.S. Coast Guard cutter
Diligence an eight-month-old illegal Cuban looks out over the
ocean. She and her family are meeting the USCG cutter Sapelo which
will take them directly back into Cuba for repatriation. Her trip
to freedom was cut short when, six miles from the U.S. coast, the
Coast Guard had to foul the propeller of the boat in order to stop
it before reaching land. (Mark Courtney/Wilmington Star-News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ABOARD THE U.S. COAST GUARD CUTTER DILIGENCE -- Aug. 13,
1999 -- CUBAN-ILLEGALS-4 -- A crowd of illegal Cubans on the deck
of the U.S. Coast Guard cutter Diligence listen to the megaphone
voice of officer Jerry Morfin, who is an interpreter, make an
announcement relayed to him by officer LT Cary. Many of these men
found out that they would be repatriated. After the announcement,
the ship transferred 21 men off the ship since their Immigration
and Naturalization Service ruling was not complete and their status
undetermined while 26 others, were en route to Cuba within two
hours. (Mark Courtney/Wilmington Star-News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ABOARD THE U.S. COAST GUARD CUTTER DILIGENCE -- Aug. 13,
1999 -- CUBAN-ILLEGALS-3 -- A mother and her two sons are escorted
across the deck of the U.S. Coast Guard cutter Diligence after
being picked up with 18 others trying to flee Cuba in a small
sailboat. After conducting eligibility interviews by the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service's agent on board the ship,
the fate of this family will be determined. (Mark
Courtney/Wilmington Star-News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ABOARD THE U.S. COAST GUARD CUTTER DILIGENCE -- Aug. 13,
1999 -- CUBAN-ILLEGALS-2 -- A ten-foot boat that was used to try to
bring nine Cubans illegally into the U.S. burns in the Florida
Straights Crew members of the Diligence set it on fire in order to
sink the craft and eliminate another chance of illegal migration.
The boat master of the small fiberglass craft was at a stand-off
with the Diligence, cutter Nantucket and a 41 foot patrol boat for
12 hours as he said he would rather die than be forced to go back
to Cuba. (Mark Courtney/Wilmington Star-News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ABOARD THE U.S. COAST GUARD CUTTER DILIGENCE -- Aug. 13,
1999 -- CUBAN-ILLEGALS-1 -- A migrant Cuban holds sits alone in his
board holding a knife during a 12 hour stand off with the U.S.
Coast Guard. The boat, which left from Cardenas, Cuba, had engine
problems in the Florida Straights. It had come to within 15 miles
of the U.S. coast whose waters lie 12 miles off the coast of the
country. If the he had made it to land, he would have been allowed
to stay in the country, and possibly become U.S. citizens. (Mark
Courtney/Wilmington Star-News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
