<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6875 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CAUCUS-BETHANY-KAN &LR;      08-13 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAUCUS-BETHANY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME IN MISSOURI WONDER ABOUT POLITICAL SPOTLIGHT ON IOWA
NEIGHBORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHANY, Mo. _ Thirty miles away, voters will board buses today
for an event that could knock presidential contenders out of the
race. An army of journalists will eagerly await results.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse Jean Nichols if she's not excited.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols thinks the election is important. Unfortunately, she
lives in Bethany, on the wrong side of the political tracks.
</P>
<P>
   As global attention turns to the Iowa Straw Poll in Ames, some
voters in northern Missouri are viewing their neighbors with a bit
of envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have trouble getting any national candidates to this
county. That doesn't seem right,'' said Nichols, who leads the
Democratic committee in Harrison County. ``We vote and we have
things to say, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's straw poll is not an official vote, but Republicans can
register their support at the Ames rally. Candidates are scrambling
to position themselves behind frontrunner Gov. George W. Bush, and
analysts expect the poll to weed out some of the lowest finishers.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a quirk of a nominating process in which small states
such as Iowa and New Hampshire wield a lot of clout. Missouri, for
its part, moved its primary up to March to secure greater influence
in the national election process.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents complain that Bethany doesn't get the attention
received in Kansas City and St. Louis. Or even Lamoni, Iowa _ 30
miles north.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Bethany and Lamoni appear similar.
</P>
<P>
   Both are tranquil towns just off Interstate 35 with fewer than
3,000 residents. Their downtowns are dotted with small hardware
stores, barber shops, cafes and brick post offices just off the
town square.
</P>
<P>
   In both towns, you'll hear the same political dialogue about tax
cuts, Social Security, health care and the budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   But Lamoni voters get to tell presidential hopefuls how they
feel.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Vice President Al Gore spoke in Lamoni at Graceland
College's commencement. He outlined his plan for education reform,
including shrinking class sizes and improving teacher quality.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Alexander, a Republican candidate, was recently in Lamoni
to shake hands. He bought a quilt from Yesterday's Treasures
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Lamoni area has been host to candidates such
as Paul Simon, Pat Robertson, Michael Dukakis, Richard Gephardt,
Bruce Babbitt, Gary Hart, Morris Udall and George McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   The attention is enough to make some Bethany residents wistful.
</P>
<P>
   In a Wednesday column titled ``Those Lucky Iowans Have All the
Fun,'' Phil Conger of the Bethany Republican-Clipper lamented that
Mamie Eisenhower was the only national figure he could recall
visiting Bethany.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a political junkie like I am, you would also get a
little green-eyed thinking about a place like Iowa being hip-deep
in presidential contenders and reporters from the national news
media,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the big news in Bethany wasn't politics but the
relocation of the town library and the search for a new high-school
band director.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols said she thinks Bethany residents would take greater
interest in government if they could meet the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But William Russell, a political science and history professor
at Graceland College, said that isn't necessarily the case.
</P>
<P>
   Although dozens of Lamoni residents will board buses for Ames,
most residents haven't paid much attention to the straw poll, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shocks me how little many Iowans appreciate or take
advantage of their opportunity to do the major sorting of the
candidates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Bethany residents say Iowa's prominent role doesn't bother
them.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Shelby, who leads the Harrison County Republican committee,
said he expects candidates to pay closer attention to Missouri once
the fall campaign begins. Missouri is considered a critical ``swing
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hensley, part of a coffee klatch that meets at
McDonald's almost every day, agreed that Bethany voters shouldn't
worry.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he speculates that the Senate race between incumbent
John Ashcroft and Gov. Mel Carnahan will put Missouri on the
national political map.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we might get as much attention as Iowa and we
might get more,'' Hensley said. ``They can have their fun for
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
