<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6877 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-IRIDIUM-BANKRUPTCY-48     08-13 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRIDIUM-BANKRUPTCY-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRIDIUM, PHONE SATELLITE VENTURE, FILES FOR BANKRUPTCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Just eight months after it started an ambitious
satellite telephone service that promised to communicate ``with
anyone, anytime, virtually anywhere in the world,'' Iridium LLC has
filed for bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which had been delinquent on a $90-million interest
payment and in default on more than $1.5 billion in bank loans,
said Friday that it was seeking Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection
while trying to reorganize its finances and attract new customers.
</P>
<P>
   The move came after weeks of intensive negotiations with
creditors broke down. A large group of bondholders filed a petition
in federal court Friday to force Iridium into involuntary
bankruptcy and speed up talks. Hours after the petition was filed,
Iridium filed for bankruptcy in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium, with heavy backing from Motorola Inc., the
telecommunications and semiconductor giant, has spent more than $5
billion to build a global communications system with 66
low-orbiting satellites.
</P>
<P>
   The company said its global satellite service will continue to
operate even as executives attempt to come up with a plan that
would satisfy its creditors and the bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium now faces its ultimate test: it must restructure a huge
debt load, regain the confidence of its investors and find a way to
bolster sales of a satellite telephone service that many say is
outdated, outmoded and unpopular with consumers. If the company
cannot adequately restructure its debt and find a market for its
product, investors stand to lose billions of dollars. The worst off
would be shareholders, who would be paid last.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the company _ which have been plummeting for months
after it failed to attract heavy subscriptions _ were halted at
midday Friday after reports of the bankruptcy filing. Iridium had
declined $1.1875, to $3.0625, before NASDAQ halted trading. Shares
of Motorola, which owns an 18 percent stake in the company, makes
its equipment and operates its satellites, rose $5.25, to $93, in
trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the filing, executives at Iridium and its prime
benefactor, Motorola, continued to voice optimism about the
company's future, insisting that its satellite and telephone
technology is sound and that there is worldwide demand for its
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly a business that's going to flourish,'' said
John Richardson, the chief executive of Iridium, which is based in
Washington. ``The phone is working incredibly well. There is a
great deal of pent-up demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, which has invested heavily in Iridium and guaranteed
more than $750 million in bank loans, said it would continue to
support the company and participate in the restructuring talks.
Executives say they believe Iridium will reorganize itself and then
build up sales as a set of new and more attractive satellite
telephones come to market.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This is not liquidation. This is an opportunity for Iridium to
seek protection from its creditors and restructure,'' said Scott
Wyman, a spokesman for Motorola, which is based in Schaumburg, Ill.
``Our hope is that Iridium can be successful if it restructures.''
</P>
<P>
   Nippon Iridium Corp. of Japan, the second largest investor in
the venture after Motorola, also said Friday that it supported the
company's effort to revamp itself by filing for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts, however, have been highly critical of
Iridium. They say the company's product introduction last November
was a flop. There were technical glitches, phones did not work, a
huge marketing campaign that fared poorly, and customers complained
about huge, brick-sized telephones that were costly and failed to
work indoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They launched a service but consumers didn't want a big,
clunky phone,'' said Walt Piecyk, an analyst at Paine Webber.
``Cellular telephone rates have gotten really cheap, and there's
just not a demand for their services.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Iridium and Motorola disagree. There is a new
management team in place, they say, and many changes have been made
to refocus the company. Richardson, who took over as chief
executive last April, says the company introduced its product too
early _ before the technology, marketing and distribution were
ready. And instead of using equity, the company saddled itself with
a huge debt load that made a blockbuster startup a necessity if the
company was going to keep up with interest and dividend payments.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the company has lowered its prices
significantly, from $3,000 to $1,500 and subscriber rates have
plummeted from $5 a minute to about $2.99.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the company's focus is on restructuring. Investors have
offered to put up an additional $400 million to $600 million,
Richardson says. The company has the cash to operate for some
months, but it must move quickly to remove the ``clouds of
uncertainty'' that are preventing the company from making progress,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Within 30 days, Iridium hopes to restructure its debt, and if it
is to be a viable company, the company says it would have to make
substantial progress in increasing revenue by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the bankruptcy filing was triggered by the
company's failure to make good on its interest payment this week
and not a response to the bondholder filing earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had not concluded a financial reconstruction and we had no
other alternative but to file,'' he said. ``This process gives us
the breathing room we need.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Geczi, a spokesman for Weil, Gotschal &AMP; Manges, the law
firm that filed the bankruptcy petition on behalf of a group of
bondholders who represent about two-thirds of the more than $1.4
billion in debt, said their filing Friday came after talks with
Iridium had stalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought this was the way to get the process moving,'' Geczi
said. ``To the extent that their filing gets us there, we view that
as a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   To stave off liquidation, however, Iridium is going to have to
move quickly even as it competes against other satellite telephone
technologies. The company has failed to meet subscriber targets,
and though it says new equipment will resolve some of those
questions, many analysts believe the debt load is too huge to
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders have already turned sour. Iridium went public in
1997, rose as high as $70 a share in May 1998 and has since
plummeted to penny-stock status, giving the company a market value
of about $60 million with a multibillion-dollar debt load.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a grand vision to make a phone call anywhere in the
world,'' said Jeremy Diamond, the publisher of Grant's Interest
Rate Observer. ``But at the end of the day the product didn't
overwhelm the market. It was like an Internet stock, it held all
the promise of making fortunes but it didn't happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
