<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6884 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GAME-BALL     08-13 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GAME-BALLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS KICKERS MULL NEW RULE ON GAME BALLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ They've beaten 'em with baseball bats,
baked 'em in ovens, washed 'em and tumble-dried 'em.
</P>
<P>
   They've kicked 'em, dropped weights on 'em, rubbed 'em down,
even soaked 'em in Carnation instant milk. NFL kickers book for
young kickers:]probably have more than 101 ways to break in
footballs for optimum performance.
</P>
<P>
   That's for the history books now. Beginning this season, the NFL
prohibits players from handling game balls during the week before
the game. Before the change, kickers for each home team were in
charge of breaking in game balls, usually to the specifications of
their quarterbacks, as well as their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would bring them in the racquetball court \Rat Valley
Ranch\S and kick them around in there,'' place-kicker Richie
Cunningham said. ``It's just a matter of wear and tear on the ball
and breaking the seams in and breaking the leather in. Whichever
way was best in doing that, that's what people would do. Everyone
had their own technique.''
</P>
<P>
   Too many techniques, NFL officials felt. The theory goes that
some kickers who play with quarterbacks who don't mind using a
roughed-up ball would hold an advantage over kickers whose
quarterbacks prefer a newer, or at least a less worked-in football.
So the NFL now requires a new football be used for every punt,
kickoff and field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like making a shortstop play with a brand new glove,''
Cowboys kicking coach Steve Hoffman said. ``It will make for a lot
less touchbacks and a lot fewer 57-yard field goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Which seems to be at least part of the NFL'splan. If Toby Gowin
can't boom every kickoff out of the end zone then there should be
more returns, more opportunities for highlight footage. If Gowin
can't produce five-second hang times, perhaps opponents will have
fewer fair catches, more returns and better field position.
</P>
<P>
   you have to be more consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   As Cunningham said: ``The sweet spot has been shrunk.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is griping among some]Some NFL kickers gripe that
their already-tenuous jobs were just made more difficult, others
say the playing field is now level. Hoffman, who says he likes the
rule, believes using a new football will reduce a field-goal
kickers range 5 yards, maybe more. It could cut Gowin's hang time
from five seconds to 4.6 or so.
</P>
<P>
   Kickers who play in cold-weather cities wince at the notion that
the playing field is indeed level. Footballs already carry poorly
in cold temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys kicking up in Green Bay and Cleveland and those
places, it's going to be tough on them,'' Cunningham said. ``One
thing us kickers do when we get ready to start the season is we
look at the schedule and see where the games are, because, I can
tell you, it makes a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The preseason should be enough to at least compare old vs. new
in moderate conditions and give coaches an idea if they need to
re-evaluate their philosophies on when to attempt long field goals.
</P>
<P>
   After one exhibition game, Cunningham and Gowin have yielded
little change. Gowin punted twice for an average of 47.5 yards
against Cleveland, surpassing his average of 43.4 yards last year.
His net average of 36.0 after one exhibition game nearly matched
his 1998 net average of 36.6.
</P>
<P>
   In one field-goal attempt, Cunningham made a 49-yarder. Last
season, Cunningham made 10 of 11 field-goal attempts from 40 to 49
yards, missing from 49 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go through a preseason and see if there is an effect. If
not then we've cried wolf,'' coach Chan Gailey said. ``We'll know
at the end of preseason if we need to change our thinking.''
\Ntagtop:Jeff Caplan, (817) 390-7971
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
