<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-POLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CONFIDENT IN IOWA, DESPITE RIVALS' QUIPS ABOUT HIS INFREQUENT
VISITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IOWA-CONSERVATIVES) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANOLA, Iowa _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush swept into the home
of Bob and Shirley Lester in this town amid the cornfields of
central Iowa on Friday night to partake in a tradition of
presidential politics in this state: one-on-one campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Bush expressed confidence that he would continue to steam-roller
toward the Republican presidential nomination by meeting
expectations and triumphing in a straw poll Saturday sponsored by
the Iowa Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Standing with his wife, Laura, on the front porch of the
Lesters' house, Bush said, ``I hope you can join Laura and I to
send a message that I'm the right guy.'' He added, ``I'm running
with one thing in mind _ I'm running to become the next president
of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bush's visit here, though a common exercise for presidential
candidates, was relatively uncharacteristic of him. On his
high-profile first trip to Iowa, Bush had vowed to take his
campaign to every front porch of the state. But since then, he has
largely stayed clear of front-porch-style political events, while
most of his rivals have traversed the state for months, if not
years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made little time for answering questions from ordinary
citizens at town meetings. And he has not yet even traveled to some
important sections of Iowa, including Council Bluffs on the state's
western border across the Missouri River from Omaha in one of the
state's larger media markets.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bush has stuck to his stump speech _ and has done
little to endanger his monumental lead in the polls and in
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Bush has campaigned in Iowa nine days since June 12,
when he announced that he would participate in the straw poll.
Almost every other candidate has been here far more times. In the
same period, for example, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and
publishing magnate Steve Forbes have been here nearly three dozen
times.
</P>
<P>
   While some acknowledge it may be wishful thinking, virtually
every one of Bush's rivals made it clear that they hoped the
governor's flouting of the Iowa tradition will ultimately cost him
with the voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take up with Governor Bush why he passed up these
opportunities to talk with interested Republican activists,''
Forbes told reporters. ``I'm delighted to get our message out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest entrant to the presidential race, Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R- Utah, said: ``I've been here more days that George W. Bush. But
we only got in a few weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who has been here more than any candidate, groused,
``The rewards this year seem to go to those who avoid meeting with
the activists, who drop in the Des Moines airport two or three
times, rent a bale of hay and pretend they know Iowa _ and who say
they'll wait until next year to speak out on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle said: ``Sooner or later, the
American people are going to demand a discussion of the issues.
Maybe it's wishful thinking that we'll focus on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gary Bauer, the former head of the Family Research Council,
weighed in, saying that Republicans were disappointed because of
``the few times the governor actually shows up and takes
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked Friday night what he thought of his opponents' criticism,
Bush said his campaign had gotten a late start because he had not
ventured out of Texas until the state Legislature adjourned at the
end of May. ``I have been working very hard in the state of Iowa.
We've had fantastic crowds, and we'll see what happens tomorrow.
We'll see whether or not in the limited amount of time I had to
come to Iowa that we have done what's necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's communications director, explained that the
governor does not favor town meetings. ``We've chosen to have
community receptions where he can visit with people one-on-one,''
Ms. Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McKinnon, Bush's media consultant, who was looking for
footage for future commercials here Friday night ``if the light
gets good,'' said the rap was unfair. ``He's been to Iowa more than
he's been anywhere else.'' He added, ``There's still a lot of time
left _ and a lot of porches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
