<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-IRWIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWIN CHASING SNEAD, MORE MEDINAH GLORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ Hale Irwin shimmied in his chair, mimicking the
moves he watched Payne Stewart make in the driver's seat of his
courtesy car before yesterday's round.
</P>
<P>
   Curious, Irwin tapped on the window to get Stewart's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He opens the door, and this music just knocks me over,'' Irwin
said. ``I don't know what it was, but it wasn't quite the Mamas and
the Papas or Elvis Presley or any of the stuff I'm used to. I like
all music, unless it's something that hurts my ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, 54, laughed as he shared the story. Just as he chuckled
when someone asked about 19-year-old playing partner Sergio Garcia
and he responded: ``You mean my grandson?''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, the 600-pound gorilla of the Senior Tour, clearly has
relished his underdog status this week at the PGA Championship. But
he reached a crossroads yesterday at Medinah Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the front-runners on the leader board after 36 holes,
Irwin (5 under par) can no longer be viewed as a courtesy inclusion
to the field because he won the last major championship played at
Medinah, the 1990 U.S. Open. Instead, he must be considered a
serious threat to break Sam Snead's record as the oldest winner in
PGA Tour history.
</P>
<P>
   Snead won the 1965 Greater Greensboro Open two months before his
53rd birthday. Irwin, competing at the PGA on a special exemption,
turned 54 on June 3.
</P>
<P>
   In yesterday's second round, Irwin threw down a 3-under 69,
dusting a pair of whippersnappers in his group _ Garcia and Phil
Mickelson (29) _ by four and three strokes, respectively. It marked
Irwin's second consecutive sub-par effort on the 7,401-yard layout,
the longest ever for a major championship played at sea level.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the oldest player in the field is four strokes off the
lead at a course where he won in 1990 and finished third at the
1975 U.S. Open. And he's starting to think he can do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sit up here and tell anybody that I expected
to play like this,'' said Irwin, who has won five times in his past
nine starts on the Senior Tour, albeit on courses that usually are
700 yards shorter than Medinah. ``In my heart, I hoped to and
wanted to. But it's not always the easiest thing to do, especially
in an environment in which you're not terribly accustomed.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was Irwin, watching Garcia blast 3-woods past his
drives and wincing when Mickelson selected 7-irons from lies where
he would hit 4-iron. Through it all, Irwin has compensated by
keeping his shots out of Medinah's heavy rough while offsetting
seven birdies with just two bogeys through two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   He clearly impressed Mickelson, who said Irwin ``would still be
winning a tournament a year if he played on our tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin isn't so sure. But he sounds ready to make a run at
Snead's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hadn't entered my mind until the last few minutes,''
Irwin said after completing his round. ``And I won't give it much
thought. But I am pleased with how I played. I don't want to go
backwards and say I can't continue that. Just the opposite. I know
this course, and I've had success here.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he could make history here as well.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
