<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BEGIN SHORT-HANDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was an offseason of emotion and tension,
headlines and investigations. But for UCLA, nothing symbolizes the
tumult as crisply as not having a preseason depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. With 12 players suspended and several others
injured, coach Bob Toledo doesn't have enough experienced bodies to
list a starter and reserve at each position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recall not having a depth chart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven starters and four reserves are suspended for two games for
the handicapped parking fiasco. Another, Audie Attar, is out for
fighting. Add the quarterback quagmire, the kicking question and
the retirement last spring of three veteran reserves, and Toledo is
so desperate he may let tailback DeShaun Foster and receivers Danny
Farmer and Freddie Mitchell play both ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might use them at defensive back in passing situations,''
Toledo said. ``That's a real possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   With practice beginning today, here's a look at the positions
most affected by the suspensions:
</P>
<P>
   Defensive back: Two starters (safety Ryan Roques and cornerback
Marques Anderson) and one reserve (safety Eric Whitfield) are out.
That makes Jason Bell's return from heal surgery essential. Bell
doesn't have full strength and will practice on a limited basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be ready to go,'' said Bell, who was UCLA's most
dependable cornerback last season. ``I'm just taking it slow and
doing everything I can to get my strength back.''
</P>
<P>
   The other cornerback is anyone's guess. Sophomore Julius
Williams, red-shirt freshmen Lovell Houston and Joe Hunter, and
true freshman Ricky Manning will compete for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Stephens is solid at one safety, but the other spot is
wide open until Roques returns.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker: The projected starters, Ryan Nece, Tony White and
Ali Abdul Azziz, have been suspended; so has top reserve Robert
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Santi Hall temporarily has been moved to outside
linebacker. Reserve Billy Pieper probably will start on the other
side. And Ed Stansbury, who has not played a down at linebacker
after switching from quarterback last year, is expected to start in
the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've labeled this my coming-out year,'' Stansbury said. ``Last
year, I gave myself time to learn the position. This year, I'm
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Two rookie linebackers probably will play. The top candidates
are prep All-American Marcus Reese; the Ball twins, Matt and Eric,
who have moved from defensive end; and unheralded recruit Asi Faoa,
who looks the part at 6-4, 240 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line: Starting guard Oscar Cabrera and reserve guard
Jim Ghezzi are out.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for the Bruins to start two red-shirt freshmen, Mike
Saffer and Blake Worley, sophomore Troy Danoff and seldom-used
senior Matt Phelan.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo does not want to play his true freshmen, Shane Lehmann
and Bryce Bohlander, but he may not have a choice if injuries
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we won't have to use either,'' Toledo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
