<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTH-VOTE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUIET MAN IN THE MIDDLE OF THE KANSAS EVOLUTION CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVEN, Kan._ A couple of miles from Harold Voth's house, an
Amish woman in a long, plain dress and sunbonnet sits with three
small children in an open horse-drawn carriage.
</P>
<P>
   To some passers-by, the antiquated rig and the people in it
might be a curiosity. They seem out of place next to the
fast-moving cars and trucks on the four-lane stretch of Kansas 96.
</P>
<P>
   With a single vote this week on evolution, critics are accusing
Voth, elected last year to the Kansas Board of Education, of taking
Kansas back to the horse-and-buggy era and making the state a
national curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   In the struggle to adopt new science standards for Kansas
students, this 70-year-old retired school superintendent on
Wednesday became the sixth and deciding vote that deleted the
concept of macro-evolution from the state's recommended curriculum
beginning in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the soft-spoken man from this hamlet between Wichita
and Hutchinson was being sought by television networks and
newspapers across the country.
</P>
<P>
   At home, his vote was being condemned by his education
supporters, including Gov. Bill Graves, and praised by his
political enemies, including the conservative Republican he
narrowly defeated in last summer's party primary.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy, something Voth has largely avoided most of his
life, was swirling around him, and he wasn't enjoying the
intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   The phone rang and a woman on the other end told Voth, ``I
always thought Kansans were hicks, and now you've proved it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Voth, a tall, thin man with a passion for growing giant
watermelons, just shrugged off such criticism with a quiet,
understanding smile.
</P>
<P>
   This was a decision he agonized over for months. Now he was at
peace.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks he had worked with two conservative board members to
come up with a compromise between their anti-evolution position and
evolution supporters in academia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped to make people only half mad, but I guess no one's
happy now,'' said Voth, who will become board chairman next year.
</P>
<P>
   Before the vote, he was considered a political moderate. He
replaced Wanda Morrison, a Hutchinson Republican who had held the
7th District board seat for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   But Morrison decided not to run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The board had been split between five conservatives and five
moderates.
</P>
<P>
   With Robin Jackson, a math and science teacher at a private
Hutchinson Christian school, campaigning to take Morrison's place,
teachers active in the National Education Association and political
moderates became alarmed. Jackson could tip the scales in favor of
the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   They needed a champion and turned to Voth.
</P>
<P>
   At first he refused. After all, he was trying to retire _
something he found difficult. For 28 years he had served the small
school district of Haven as its superintendent. Then three nearby
school districts asked him to fill in temporarily until they found
permanent superintendents.
</P>
<P>
   Voth, a Mennonite, was called again when the education
establishment faced the prospect of a Jackson victory. He had been
elected to the Hutchinson Community College board of trustees, a
prestigious job, and was considered a civic leader and pillar of
the community.
</P>
<P>
   Voth won the election by 29 votes, but Jackson, a former
chemist, wasn't bitter. The two remained friends, and Jackson
advised Voth during the evolution debate.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when evolution supporters said students would be at
a disadvantage without the concept in the standards, Jackson
reviewed questions on ACT tests and found no reference to
evolution, information she passed along to Voth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat down with him and he listened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said she doesn't object to the teaching of evolution as
a theory. But she and other conservatives said the state board was
being asked to adopt this theory as fact, and they refused to go
that far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not religion vs. science,'' she said. ``It's truth vs.
untruth. I think Harold is someone with a clear-cut idea of right
and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of those who supported him in the last election said
his vote disappointed them.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was Sherri Yourdon, a high school counselor in the
Nickerson School District in Reno County and a Kansas-National
Education Association board member.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt he ran as a moderate and would continue the GOP view
that Wanda Morrison did,'' she said. ``I thought he'd support the
(science) committee better than he did. It's really kind of a slap
in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yourdon said that as an educator, she understood his desire
to find a compromise. To remain a superintendent for almost 30
years, she said, Voth would have called on such skills many times.
</P>
<P>
   Yourdon said the Haven-Yoder-Mount Hope area is composed of very
conservative, religious people and that Voth's vote is a reflection
of that area.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Voth has gotten out of bed at 5:30 a.m. and driven
six miles to the Carriage Crossing Restaurant in Yoder for coffee
and conversation. After Wednesday's vote, he made the morning drive
and was greeted with handshakes and people saying, ``Thank you for
voting for the compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Voth said he was able to make his decision without worrying
about the politics. He doesn't plan to run for re-election when his
term expires in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't the easy route,'' he said. ``I was expected to
vote for a deadlock.''
</P>
<P>
   But Voth said those who believe this vote would end evolution
instruction will be disappointed, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the same teachers, the same textbooks,'' he said.
``How much change are you really going to have?''
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, he drove to his garden near Partridge to tend to
the large watermelon he hopes to take to the Kansas State Fair this
year. Two years ago, he grew a melon that weighed 174 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   This year's melon has suffered from the weather and his absences
while serving on the board. He'll have to work harder to get a
champion this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a reputation to uphold,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
