<HEADLINE>
MONETARY AND SPIRITUAL RICHES IN 6 STEPS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Part hard-nosed advice about personal finance, part touchy-feely
self-help, ``Invest in Yourself: Six Secrets to a Rich Life''
argues that for readers who can learn to shave a few cents here, a
few dollars there, monetary and spiritual riches await. For anyone
too frugal to buy the book, here, in summary form, are the authors'
``secrets'':
</P>
<P>
   MAKE YOUR OWN LIFE-STYLE DECISIONS Besides return on investment,
consider time, energy _ even fantasies _ as equally manageable
assets in your portfolio. That might mean downsizing from a
two-income household to a one-income one, say by moving to the
country.
</P>
<P>
   PUT YOUR FAMILY FIRST Your love for your family isn't judged by
how much you can buy them. The book quotes Paul Tsongas, the late
Massachusetts senator: ``Nobody on his deathbed ever said, `I wish
I'd spent more time at the office.'''
</P>
<P>
   BE IN BUSINESS FOR YOURSELF Jobs are no longer secure. Think of
yourself as a consultant, not an employee. Freelance on the side.
</P>
<P>
   MAKE THE MOST OF YOUR TAKE-HOME PAY To paraphrase Ben Franklin:
A dollar saved is $1.40 you'll never have to earn, assuming a 28
percent tax bracket. Wealth is having slightly more than you need;
poverty is having slightly less _ so adjust accordingly. When you
are about to buy something, ask: If I didn't need it yesterday, why
do I need it today?
</P>
<P>
   TURN YOUR DEBTS INTO INVESTMENTS A typical $100,000 mortgage
costs $250,000 over 30 years. Prepay $25 more a month and you'll
save more than $20,000 in interest. Paying down credit card debt
returns the equivalent of as much as 20 percent on a taxable
investment, which beats the Street.
</P>
<P>
   MAP OUT YOUR OWN FINANCIAL FUTURE Don't adopt financial habits
just because they're popular. For example, college is not a
parental tithe; think of it as the six-figure investment it is.
Likewise, determine how much you really need for retirement, not
what planners want you to invest. Consider a working retirement.
Touch the nest egg; you don't have to end up with a big estate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
