<HEADER>
A6895 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-13 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLOWED-OUT BOOKS COULD OPEN YOU UP TO ROBBERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS and DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do they have a deal for you!
</P>
<P>
   Preying on fears that banks won't be ready for Y2K, mail order
firms are peddling hollowed-out books in which consumers can stash
cash they withdraw from their banks.
</P>
<P>
   Don't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   The Better Business Bureau believes that, in at least some
cases, the books may be robberies in the making. Many of the
companies are unknown and have no track record, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies that produce these `book safes' ship them directly
to the customer's home,'' according to the bureau. ``Once shipped,
these companies have each purchaser's address and are able to
easily keep tabs on who has cash stashed in their homes. Thieves
can then be sent out to steal the customer's cash, because they
know exactly where the money is hidden _ on the book shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one of several Y2K ripoffs that Better Business Bureau
offices have heard of around the country.
</P>
<P>
   In one scam, a caller claiming to be a government employee tells
senior citizens they will not get their Social Security checks
after the first of the year, and their paper money will be no good.
The scammer tells senior citizens to turn all assets into paper
money and mail it to him so he can convert it into gold and mail it
back. ``Of course, the con artist keeps all the cash,'' the bureau
said.
</P>
<P>
   And here's yet another age-old scam with a Y2K twist:
Replacement magnetic strips for your credit card. The typical
scammer will offer to make your credit card Y2K ready by sending
you a new magnetic strip for your charge card. But first, you must
forfeit your card number.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau and the federal government have published brochures
to alert consumers to such scams:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Year 2000, Your Bank and You,'' is available at
{www.fdic.gov} or by calling 1-800-934-FDIC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Year 2000 and You'' is available at
{www.bbb.org//library//y2k.html} or by writing the CBBB Publication
Fulfillment Department, 4200 Wilson Blvd., Arlington, Va., 22203.
</P>
<P>
   ``The BBB's brochure will help consumers and businesses alike to
recognize the most common Year 2000 scams and to take proactive,
common sense steps to protect against problems that might arise
from Y2K,'' said James L. Bast, president of the Council of Better
Business Bureaus.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet also offers some good advice regarding financial
records, generators and stockpiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carefully evaluate offers for Y2K resource//survival//disaster
kits,'' the bureau said. Kits, which are being sold for $299 plus
$22 shipping, provide toothpaste, flares, flashlights, pancake mix,
emergency candles, chili, bleach, aluminum foil, Kool-Aid and Spam.
</P>
<P>
   A consumer can ``easily build your own kit for around $50,'' the
bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Dave Higgins and Ken Orr of Topeka said they got
tired of reading all the silly things being said about the Year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly it struck us like a wet marmot,'' the two wrote in
the introduction to their new Y2K quote book. ``Let's feature
stupid quotes on the Web and give away a prize for the stupidest
one we find! We had no idea what a deep well we had stumbled
into.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest competition, Kansas City's own Teresa Loar,
co-chairwoman of the Mid-America Regional Council's Y2K Elected
Officials Task Force, got a Duh Award under the heading, ``Stupid
Politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   We quoted her as saying she did not plan to make any special Y2K
preparations at home: ``I seldom plan an hour ahead, anyway,'' she
said. Yet City Councilwoman Loar also said she expected that there
might be ATM glitches and traffic-signal snarls. She was nominated
by five readers from across the country, Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
   You can read all the goofiness at {www.duh-2000.com}. To
nominate an item for the Duh-2000 contest, e-mail the quote (just
not any of ours) and the Web address citation to
{contest &LR; duh-2000.com}
</P>
<P>
   The person submitting each month's winning quote receives a free
six-pack of HeaterMeals, a pre-cooked and sealed shelf-stable
entree that heats itself, plus a copy of the quote book.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Connolly, chief operating officer of the Boston Federal
Reserve, says the government may consider upping its Y2K cash
cushion by $20 billion to provide a ``super abundance'' of currency
in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, other federal regulators say they sense Y2K is
less of a concern than at this time last year. So far, no banks
have sought extra cash because of Y2K concerns, said Rose Pianalto
with the Federal Reserve in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Reserve officials keep $150 billion in cash on
hand, but because of Y2K they said earlier this year they would
boost that amount by $50 billion.
Calls continue to flood the federal government's Y2K call center
since it opened its doors in a two-story brick building in the
Appalachian foothills of Cumberland, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The government's Federal Information Center has added 60 phone
lines just for Year 2000 queries. The special number _
1-888-USA-4Y2K _ logged 134,439 calls from Jan. 7 to June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The center has one mission: ``We want to provide the facts to
the public, and our reading of the facts is that the public should
be calmed,'' said manager Stephen Smith. Hot-line staffers advocate
personal preparedness, storing a couple weeks' worth of food and a
little spare cash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
