<HEADER>
A6896 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-GORILLA-BIRTH-BOS &LR;      08-13 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORILLA-BIRTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS MONITORING CONDITION OF BABY GORILLA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KRISTIN VAUGHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Officials at Zoo New England are anxiously watching
the development of a baby gorilla, the first one ever born at its
Franklin Park Zoo, after its mother recently started showing signs
of illness.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo personnel this week were quietly celebrating the arrival of
the 4-pound baby and were pleased that the newborn gorilla and
mother Kiki were progressing well following Sunday's dramatic
birth.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials had hoped to begin exhibiting the baby gorilla to
the public this week but have delayed plans until they are sure it
will survive. Until then, the zoo is keeping the baby gorilla under
wraps and no photos or public viewing will be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday afternoon, Kiki and the four other adult gorillas
at the park contracted a common gorilla illness _ diarrhea. If the
illness spreads, it could endanger the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's caused by a protozoan that is very common in apes and
when they get stressed it causes diarrhea,'' said Dr. Hayley
Weston, chief veterinarian. Changes in the gorillas' routines, such
as the addition of the baby to the troop, can be stressful and
cause the ailment to flare up, she said. ``We started medication,
decreased the stress, we're cleaning up as soon as possible so that
it won't spread and now we're just going to sit back and wait and
see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the adult gorillas have been placed on a 10-day course of
medication. The baby gorilla, whose sex is still unknown because
workers have not yet had an opportunity to get close to it, shows
no signs of illness and doctors are cautiously optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the dehydration that we're worried about. Any newborn
that gets diarrhea is'' life-threatened ``because its body mass is
so small that it can get dehydrated,'' Weston said. ``I don't think
that we'll have to step in, but if the baby got sick enough and the
mom couldn't keep her strong we step in . . . put fluids in her and
get her back quickly to her mom.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the 17-year-old western lowland gorilla and her
baby had been doing fine since Kiki gave birth without
complications around 11 p.m. in a gorilla holding room.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials, an outside veterinarian and an emergency response
team of human doctors have been on standby for weeks in case she
experienced problems in childbirth or required a caesarean section.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to interrupt the bonding process, zoo workers have
not approached the baby to determine the sex and haven't yet
selected a name.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials were concerned that Kiki, who was ``hand-raised''
by humans as a baby, would not have mothering instincts and would
reject the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a hand-raised female you will often have the
biggest difficulty,'' said Dan Beetem, the zoo's curator of
mammals. ``It could be that she could not know a way to love (the
baby) or that she would not be able to find a breast to nurse.''
</P>
<P>
   But the normally 230-pound gorilla has apparently taken to
motherhood splendidly, according to Weston, who said Kiki was
``certainly a success story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiki's a really good mother, very nurturing, very gentle. She
cradles it all the time. I don't think she's put it down yet,''
Weston said. ``She strokes it and kisses it and inspects the
fingers and toes. We thought she'd be a good mom and she is
definitely showing her mothering instincts.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the zoo staff actually demonstrated mothering
behavior for the gorilla to mimic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a baby doll that one of the keepers would carry around
and carry like a gorilla for a few months off and on and the
horticulturist's wife (who recently had a baby) would actually
breastfeed so that Kiki could see. She came in twice a week so for
a few months and Kiki was very interested in the whole thing. She
wanted one of her own,'' Weston said.
</P>
<P>
   All of the gorillas at the zoo are western lowland gorillas, an
endangered species found in western African countries. There are
about 700 of them in captivity in the world, about 365 of them are
in zoos in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Kiki and the gorilla father, Kit, are considered ``genetically
valuable'' under a process called the Species Survival Plan. The
SSP is a way to coordinate breeding with endangered species _ a
kind of computer dating service to pick compatible gorillas.
Because they are very social animals and there are so few in
captivity, we are ``trying to prevent inbreeding,'' Beetem said.
</P>
<P>
   Kiki, who was born at the Bronx Zoo, is on loan from the
Philadelphia Zoo. The father, Kit, was a gift to the Franklin Park
Zoo from the Audubon Zoo in New Orleans about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're turning the corner. We've been pushing for many years to
have a gorilla birth and we haven't had one in 16 years and that
was at Stone Zoo,'' said John Linehan, Zoo New England's vice
president of living collections, who has been at Franklin Park for
18 years. ``We've had males brought here (for breeding) who didn't
work out. We've finally achieved one of our goals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
