<SLUG> BC-NJ-MARTINI-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WHO SOUGHT EXECUTION CHANGES MIND
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ After arguing for nearly four years in New
Jersey courts in favor of his own execution, a convicted murderer
has reversed himself and told his lawyer to appeal his death
sentence in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The condemned prisoner, John Martini, 69, changed his mind
earlier this week, about six weeks before his scheduled execution
by lethal injection on Sept. 22, his court-appointed lawyer, Alan
L. Zegas, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned,'' Zegas said of Martini's decision. ``He was
always very emphatic about it. As time progressed, he became more
determined to submit to execution.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Zegas said, the fast-approaching execution date and pleas
by the Catholic chaplain at Trenton State Prison and the 14 other
inmates on death row there prompted Martini to drop his wish for a
speedy execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, what everyone had talked about in the
abstract had become real for him,'' Zegas said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Martini acceded to the admonitions of the prison
chaplain, Sister Elizabeth Gnam, and his fellow inmates on death
row to continue appealing his death sentence, Zegas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their feeling was once the first person is executed, it makes
it easier to execute the next,'' Zegas said, recounting the
explanation Martini gave Wednesday during their meeting at the
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Gnam ``very much wanted him to live,'' Zegas said his
client told him.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had not spoken to Sister Gnam about Martini
abandoning his desire for a speedy execution. Chris Carden, a
spokesman for the corrections department, said Sister Gnam did not
want to discuss her conversations with Martini.
</P>
<P>
   Martini began seeking a speedy execution in late 1995 in New
Jersey Superior Court here. The state Supreme Court rejected his
request in 1996 and ordered that the appeals that were filed
against Martini's wishes by the New Jersey public defender's office
proceed routinely through the state court.
</P>
<P>
   Martini had barred any federal appeals after his case was
resolved in the state court system. On July 27, the state Supreme
Court rejected the public defender's final appeal for Martini. A
few hours later, in a ruling that surprised the state Department of
Corrections, Superior Court Judge Bruce A. Gaeta, who sits in
Hackensack, set an execution date for Martini _ Sept. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Martini was sentenced to death for the 1989 kidnapping and
murder of a Bergen County businessman, Irving Flax, of Fair Lawn.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when his appeal came before Gaeta, Martini testified
that he viewed execution as a form of absolution for his murder of
Flax. Psychiatric tests found Martini mentally competent.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeals since then, Zegas, who opposes capital
punishment, has argued that Martini's wish for execution should be
granted based on constitutional rights of privacy and religious
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   But judges focused instead on that contended Martini did not
receive adequate legal representation in his murder trial because
the trial jury never heard evidence that might have convinced them
to sentence him to a life in prison instead of death.
</P>
<P>
   The state Supreme Court rejected the final appeal in July. At
Martini's insistence, state judges have sealed the evidence and
kept it confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Friedman, an assistant public defender, said Friday he
planned to meet with Martini at the Trenton prison on Monday to
confirm that he has changed his mind, and then ask the state
Supreme Court to postpone the execution. Then, he said, he plans to
start an appeal in U.S. District Court. ``If this pans out, we'll
be nothing short of thrilled,'' Friedman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
