<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF TAKES STARTLING, BUT UNDERSTANDABLE, STEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ The women's tennis tour came to this
seaside town with Martina Hingis and Lindsay Davenport juggling the
No. 1 ranking _ and got upstaged Friday by somebody half a world
away in Heidelberg, Germany. That somebody, an all-time somebody,
was Steffi Graf, who startlingly said that's all, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Far from washed up, but _ she said _ nonetheless finished, Graf,
whose swift and relentless legs carried her to a 1988 Grand
Slam-plus Olympic gold, and 22 major titles, is
uncharacteristically walking to the nearest exit. She is walking at
the tender, though physically and mentally battered, age of 30.
</P>
<P>
   Steffi wouldn't be the first of her breed to proclaim retirement
(e.g. Billie Jean King, Chris Evert, Margaret Court) and then
reappear, homesick for the road, and to win more championships.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubting Fraulein Forehand's sincerity of the moment.
But if she sticks to her announcement, Friday will be remembered,
in the words of 27-year-old rival Arantxa Sanchez Vicario as, ``A
very sad day for the game. And for me. I feel very bad about it. I
can't believe it. Steffi was playing so good, winning the French,
in the final at Wimbledon. I can't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the year of hail and farewell for the gods: Jordan,
Elway, Gretzky, Sanders, Becker. And now Graf.
</P>
<P>
   She always played with the vivacity of the girl I first spied at
Flushing Meadow in 1983, on a back court, beating up on another
junior. She was a rookie pro, flying at balls with bloodthirsty
eagerness to bruise them beyond recognition, especially with that
distinctive bludgeon of a forehand.
</P>
<P>
   Steffi dealt with each point as an opportunity not to be missed.
She couldn't wait for the next, the next, and the next, moving
between them like somebody late for the last bus.
</P>
<P>
   But, she says, ``After Wimbledon (a 6-4, 7-5 title bout loss to
Davenport), for the first time in my career, I didn't feel like
going to a tournament. To make sure, I went to San Diego (last
week) and I felt it right away. It's time to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   It probably didn't help that a strained left hamstring caused
Steffi to surrender in her first start following Wimbledon to No.
26 Amy Frazier, 4-6, 7-5, 2-1. That was her ninth loss of the
season against 33 wins, the last of a 17-year career during which
she batted .886 _ 902-115 with 107 singles titles _ and was the
universe's No. 1 a record eight years between 1987 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Graf should have traveled with the guys from MASH. She prevailed
over more wounds than St. Sebastian, played hurt so often. Her
heart was so big that you thought she had two of them. She drove
herself as if she were a mule team. ``I'd have to drag her off the
practice court at times when she shouldn't have been out there at
all,'' says her longtime coach Heinz Gunthardt.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she says it wasn't the injuries, the constant
rehab, and the frustrating layoffs that convinced her to quit. The
fun was gone. And Steffi felt that there was no way to eclipse her
French Open victory over Hingis. It was a victory that punctured
Graf's normal reserve, opening a teary floodgate.
</P>
<P>
   A primadonna, no doubt, cool and wary, she was a stoic's stoic,
finding sanctuary in a tennis rectangle, a haven from the emotional
storms created by her wayward father, Peter Graf. A court was her
safe house where she could do what she loved most and did best,
without having to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving at No. 3 _ ``on her own terms as an all-time singles
player,'' says Billie Jean King _ Graf combined supreme athleticism
with dauntless desire. That and her fearless thrusts with the
finely sliced backhand and the mother of forehands kept her among
the elite, the top 10, for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   She was debatably the finest to flap a racket. Certainly she's
unique in winning all four majors at least four times _ seven
Wimbledons, six French, five US, four Australian _ to wind up two
behind Margaret Court's record total.
</P>
<P>
   For me she's in the top five ever, a list headed by Martina
Navratilova.
</P>
<P>
   Graf feels her final major triumph, 4-6, 7-5, 6-2 over Hingis
two months ago in Paris, was her magnum opus. Though magnificent,
it didn't quite measure up to two masterpieces against Sanchez
Vicario, the 1995 Wimbledon final (4-6, 6-1, 7-5) and the 1996
French final (6-3, 6-7, 10-8).
</P>
<P>
   But there are so many memories to feast on. The goddess-to-be's
first title, Hilton Head in 1986, came at the expense of another
goddess, Chrissie Evert, 6-4, 7-5, from way behind in the second.
Evert, winner of their first six encounters, said, ``She's gonna be
hard to stop now.'' Chrissie couldn't in seven more tries.
</P>
<P>
   Another Hall of Famer, Tracy Austin, remembers Graf's
professional debut in 1982. ``Stuttgart. I was on the other side of
the net. Steffi was 13 and about this thin,'' Tracy holds up one
finger, ``but she was hitting the ball so hard. I wondered, who is
this? I beat her, but I knew we'd be hearing from her.''
</P>
<P>
   So we have. Hearing no more? The comeback sirens will sing, and
I for one hope they catch her ear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
