<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6903 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     08-13 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Youth served in Garcia, but senior Irwin has moment
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ Hale Irwin competed in his ninth PGA
Championship four months before Sergio Garcia was born. Irwin, 54,
also had won two of his three U.S. Open titles before El Nino was
even El Bebe.
</P>
<P>
   But kids these days . . . they have no grasp of history.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Garcia, 19, was asked what he thought of Irwin after
they had played the second round of the PGA together and Irwin had
bested the precocious Spaniard by four strokes, producing a 3-under
69 on the vast Medinah track he has been tearing up for almost a
quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was a great player,'' Garcia said. ``I didn't know
he was that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the tournament _ Irwin's 85th major as a pro and
Garcia's third _ they are four shots behind leader Jay Haas, 45.
Garcia also was asked which was the more impressive feat: a
teen-ager in contention or a codger?
</P>
<P>
   That answer the kid got right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both,'' Garcia said, winking.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin has been the recent scourge of the Senior Tour, winning
five of the last nine tournaments he has entered and sharing third
place in two, including the U.S. Senior Open. But those successes,
worth almost $1.6 million, haven't come on courses such as Medinah,
at 7,401 yards the longest to host a major at sea level.
</P>
<P>
   And the intensity level of the competition on the flat-belly
circuit is just slightly more intense than Irwin has encountered of
late. Senior golf is a gravy train, a final dash for some easy cash
for the nifty 50s such as Hale. Irwin admits when he watches Garcia
pulverize a golf ball he realizes the two of them are playing a
vastly different game.
</P>
<P>
   And Garcia's is one with which he remains barely familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``These young people now come out, and they hit the ball
full-out and blast away and go for it, and they're very straight,''
Irwin said. ``It's an awesome thing when you have the controlled
power they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to do something else along the way to make up for
that. When I'm comparing my distance with Garcia and (Phil)
Mickelson, those two specifically, I can't compete. Still, my irons
are pretty good. I keep the ball in play. I make a putt every now
and again. I control my game and get the most out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these young guys, they're hitting shots with irons I can't
even begin to contemplate, which is why I'm over where I play. I'm
hitting 4-irons where they're hitting 7-irons. That gets your
attention very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, as physically gifted for his age as anyone who ever
picked up a 4- or a 7-iron _ the Bear and the Tiger included _
doesn't know enough about golf to realize what questions he should
ask a Hale Irwin when he spends four hours in close proximity.
Mostly, they made small talk, Garcia said. Such as?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing really important,'' he said. ``We were talking about
clubs (as in Pings, not nightspots), those kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Their worlds are as vastly different as their games. After all,
Irwin's two children are much older than Garcia, who happens to be
the same age as Haas' caddie's son. Hale said he has little
recollection of what it felt like to be 19. But he's certain he
didn't feel like Garcia does, self-assured and convinced of his
lucrative future.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I played in two or three tournaments a summer,'' Irwin
recalled, ``I felt lucky between working on a construction job for
eight hours a day and playing a little golf at a daily-fee golf
course. The difference between these kids coming out now vs. when I
was 19 is just light-years. I pretty much learned how to play golf
on the tour. My game was held together with gum and sticks. I see
far more composure with these players and more experience. I'm not
painting an `oh, poor guy' picture. It's just the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   But what separates golf from most other sports is that a
54-year-old and a 19-year-old can line up side by side and, using
their respective assets, chase the same prize. Irwin's length might
be ill-suited for Medinah, but his reservoir of knowledge is an
equalizer. He finished third in the 1975 U.S. Open here, then drew
on that success to win the '90 Open.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia bullied the real estate into submission Thursday,
fashioning a 66. It counterpunched Friday when his putter betrayed
him intermittently.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin's 69, meanwhile, was accomplished with a gentle caress. He
stayed within himself and kept to a minimum his, uh, senior
moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to perform at this level,'' Irwin said, ``I'm very
pleased with that. I don't want to sit up here and tell anybody
that I expected to play like I did today. In your heart you hope to
and you want to, but it's not always the easiest thing to step into
an environment with which you're not terribly accustomed.''
</P>
<P>
   El Nino could be Hale's grandson, making it clear neither should
be where he is today, pursuing a major golf championship. But
that's golf. Brains and brawn count the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
