<HEADER>
A6912 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN--ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      08-13 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets sign top pick Thomas, near deal with Barkley
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JONATHAN FEIGEN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The revolving door that had the Rockets spinning this week began
turning in the other direction Friday when Charles Barkley moved
close to signing with the team, rookie Kenny Thomas did sign, and
the chances of acquiring Jazz guard/forward Shandon Anderson
improved.
</P>
<P>
   Rockets owner Leslie Alexander said Friday the team was close to
an agreement with Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect Charles will definitely be back,'' Alexander said.
``We have been talking to him, and we haven't reached a deal yet. I
think we will soon, but nothing's done until it's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander did not offer specifics about the contract other than
to say it was a one-year deal. Barkley, 36, who averaged 16.1
points and 12.3 rebounds for the Rockets last season, was
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Besides progress on that front, the Rockets also made headway in
trying to land Anderson. Considered the Rockets' top outside
free-agent target, Anderson has narrowed his list to three teams,
including the Rockets, his agent, Dan Fegan, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fegan would not identify the other teams Anderson is
considering, but before narrowing his list, Anderson, 25, had
considered Indiana, San Antonio and the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The news was not as good regarding Rockets guard/forward Sam
Mack, who also is a free agent. After meeting with Milwaukee on
Thursday, Mack, 29, was in San Antonio on Friday, according to his
agent, Bill Duffy. The Suns also have indicated they want to sign
Mack, Duffy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milwaukee was interested,'' Duffy said. ``They want to sign
Sam. They were impressed with his workout, and they were impressed
with his conditioning. They definitely want him.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Rockets) don't show too much interest in Sam Mack. My
feeling is they have done three or four long-term contracts in this
last year that maybe they regret. I don't think Sam should be
penalized for that. I wasn't asking for seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack had been looking for a five-year deal, but Duffy said his
client probably would accept a four-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   For the Rockets, after a tumultuous week in which assistant
coach Bill Berry and senior executive vice president Robert Barr
moved on and word Scottie Pippen had asked to be traded to the
Lakers had become public, bringing in the potential of a
first-round pick was welcome and well-timed.
</P>
<P>
   According to a source familiar with the deal, Thomas signed for
$2.7 million over three seasons, with the Rockets holding an option
for a fourth year at $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of being with the Rockets and being able to
play in the NBA,'' Thomas said. ``That's the important thing. It
really hasn't hit me yet. I'm just happy to be a Rocket. All the
signing and the paperwork is all done now. All I have to do is come
in here and perform.''
</P>
<P>
   As welcome as the signing was for the Rockets, it was as
well-timed for Thomas. Unable to play this summer because of a
badly sprained ankle, Thomas was cleared to begin workouts Monday
and was officially a Rocket by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty hard, because before Monday I didn't play for a
month and a half,'' Thomas said. ``Playing basketball my whole
life, it was kind of difficult not being able to play. But I'm
playing now. I'm getting in shape now. I'm dying now, but it's
going to be all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``My leg's better. It's 100 percent. I just started working out
this week, and I'm trying to get in shape right now.''
</P>
<P>
   A 6-8, 260-pound forward taken with the 22nd pick, Thomas
averaged 17.8 points and 10 rebounds last season at New Mexico. He
became the first Western Athletic Conference player ever to collect
1,800 points, 1,000 rebounds and 200 blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny Thomas is an outstanding talent and we are thrilled to
have him as part of our team,'' executive vice president of
basketball Carroll Dawson said. ``He is a very versatile player who
is good at post-ups, and he passes the ball extremely well. We're
excited to get him into camp with the rest of our team and get him
adjusted to the NBA game.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he has a good idea what he can bring the Rockets
when he gets in shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just Kenny Thomas basketball,'' he said. ``Just being able to
play my type of basketball, rebound and trying to score and
whatever role I'm going to have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
