<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6933 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LEVIS-LEVIS_SFCHRON &LR;      08-13 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVIS-LEVIS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEVI'S OPENS MEGASTORE ON UNION SQUARE  
 BY CAROL EMERT
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. enters the ranks of high-tech,
entertainment-oriented retailers with a showy megastore opening
Tuesday on Union Square.
<P>
   Levi's, whose sales have been skidding for two years, has pulled
out all stops to generate shopper buzz. If it works, 300 Post St.
will be the jeansmaker's first successful attempt at operating its
own retail space in the U.S., following a number of botched
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The project means enough to family-owned Levi's that it is
spending approximately $60 million on its 15-year lease. That
doesn't include the cost of building the store, which one source
estimated at a minimum of $5 million, ``and probably a lot more
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the souped-up Metreon shopping center and ultra-hip
Niketown close by, Levi's has managed to stuff its
24,000-square-foot ``Levi's Store, San Francisco'' full of unique
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   A custom-tailoring service uses light rays rather than a
measuring tape to size up customers. Computer stations identify
shoppers by their fingerprints. A hot-tub-sized pool is available
for shoppers who want to sit in water and shrink their
shrink-to-fit jeans; they can dry off in a waist-high glass booth
filled with warm air.
</P>
<P>
   The four-level store, decked out in galvanized metals, warm
woods and cast concrete, affords Levi's a rare chance to control
the presentation of its merchandise. It is designed to reflect the
best qualities of the Levi's brand: originality, cool, and youthful
verve.
</P>
<P>
   One of Levi's most debilitating problems is its reliance on
other companies, from Sears to corner denim shops, to sell its
clothes. Meanwhile, vertically-integrated competitors like Gap
Inc., which control their own products and selling space, are
gaining market share.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's Store visitors will likely be surprised at the gamut of
fashions made by the 146-year-old company, including trendy
European labels and hip American styles sold only in specialty
boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   One of the European lines is a revival of Sta-Prest, a Levi's
brand discontinued decades ago. The stretchy, polyester-blend
shirts and pants come in shades of gray and blue, and resemble
1950s workmen's uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's Vintage Clothing reproduces gold miner styles from the
1800s, like baggy jeans with oversized suspenders. The company's
new Red Line, prominently featured in store windows and on the
ground floor, ranges from dark denim pants to dressier pieces such
as a $500 black leather jacket and a flouncy skirt made of shiny
fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's basic Red Tab line, the uniform of the Woodstock era,
accounts for more than half of the product mix, but is relegated to
the third floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to think of us as more than a maker of
five-pocket jeans,'' said Karen Childress, general merchandise
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Customization is a major theme of the store, based on Levi's
belief that today's youth want clothes that reflect their
individuality. In a workshop on the third floor, shoppers can alter
or ornament their jeans for $8 to $125.
</P>
<P>
   Pants can be converted into skirts, straight legs can be made
into bell bottoms, leather fringes can be sewn into seams. The
workshop also contains one of the store's most unique elements, a
laser that sears designs into clothing. (The laser doesn't hurt the
fabric, but it does produce a thin waft of smoke.)
</P>
<P>
   Levi's has also updated its ``Original Spin'' program, formerly
called ``Personal Pair,'' a custom-tailoring service for
hard-to-fit customers.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers can don a body suit and enter a dark booth, where light
beams are projected on them. Computers read the reflected light
rays and, if all goes well, take more accurate measurements than an
old-fashioned measuring tape. The jeans cost $55.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected features pop up in every nook of the Levi's Store.
</P>
<P>
   On level two is a miniature version of Spundae, a Haight Street
record shop, including a live DJ spinning vinyl. In a nearby photo
booth, shoppers can take a photo of themselves and e-mail a digital
version to 10 friends for $3.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``vortex,'' a cylindrical staircase that curls up the
center of the store, arty film clips are shown on multiple screens.
A catwalk leads shoppers to a fourth-floor art gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with all the new technologies, the Levi's Store has
run into some glitches. For example, the fingerprint-identification
feature, designed to recognize and greet customers as they log onto
Web-surfing PCs throughout the store, worked half the time in a
recent demonstration. (The fingerprinting is voluntary and the data
is deleted every 24 hours, according to Levi's.)
</P>
<P>
   Levi's new megastore contrasts sharply with the company's past
attempts at retail. In 1991 the company announced plans to open 10
test stores in Ohio. A handful were opened and all but one have
since closed.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the company planned to open as many as 50
Original Levi's Stores in the United States, some in partnership
with a store operator called Designs Inc. The Original Levi's
Stores failed miserably, in part because they sold pants at full
price in malls where nearby stores sold them at deep discounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stores looked goofy, they had bad locations, bad
assortments and high prices,'' said one source close to the
company. The OLS division bled tens of millions of dollars, sources
said. Closings followed, leaving 13 full-priced Original Levi's
Stores, down from a high of 30 in 1997. Similarly, the company
announced, and then retreated from, grand plans to open shops for
its Docker's khaki line.
</P>
<P>
   Today the only profitable domestic Levi's stores are its
outlets, which are used to liquidate unpopular merchandise,
according to sources close to Levi's. Designs Inc., which no longer
runs any full-priced Original Levi's Stores, continues to open
outlets to get rid of unwanted clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's vice president Janie Ligon downplayed the company's
retail mistakes. She said a strategic decision was made to
concentrate on a few urban locations.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one store can do only so much for the troubled
jeansmaker. But Tuesday's grand opening culminates Levi's longtime
goal of operating a showcase location in its hometown. The company
has acknowledged that, with its pricey lease, chances are close to
nil that the new locale will ever make a profit _ but that's not
the goal, since its main function is promote the Levi's brand.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the megastore will hurt local
Levi's sellers such as Macy's. Just across Union Square from the
Levi's Store, Macy's operates a large Levi's department that
includes an Original Spin custom-tailoring service. Macy's says it
isn't worried. ``There is enough business to go around,'' said a
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   A local jeans boutique manager said she doesn't expect the
Levi's Store to hurt her business. ``When the Diesel store opened
up we were concerned, but it hasn't affected our business and I
expect the same with Levi's,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
