<SLUG> BC-DAEWOO-SKOREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GROUP TO BUY DAEWOO ELECTRONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ An investment group led by a little-known
California businessman has agreed to buy most of Daewoo Electronics
Co., the consumer electronics unit of the sprawling but troubled
South Korean conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   The group, Walid Alomar &AMP; Associates, based in Beverly Hills,
said Friday that it had agreed to pay $3.2 billion for the assets
and operations of Daewoo Electronics in North and South America,
Western Europe, Japan and South Korea. The price includes the
assumption of an undisclosed amount of Daewoo debt.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the investment group, Walid Alomar, is a 56-year-old
engineer from Saudi Arabia who designs systems for refineries but
has been involved in other international business projects in
energy and telecommunications. Other participants in the investment
group were not identified and Alomar was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The sale, which both sides said they hoped to complete Sept. 9,
is part of an effort to reduce the crippling debts of Daewoo Group,
one of the largest of South Korea's family-controlled
conglomerates, which are known as chaebol. Daewoo's creditors and
the South Korean government are forcing the conglomerate into a
drastic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase would create a rare American-owned consumer
electronics company, since most American manufacturers left the
low-profit business years ago under intense competition.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase also represents a reversal of the trend a few years
ago when South Korean companies were buying American ones. LG
Electronics bought Zenith, the American television set
manufacturer, while Daewoo Electronics itself tried to buy Thomson
Multimedia, the French company that owns the former RCA and General
Electric consumer electronics businesses. The deal was stopped by
opposition in France.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar is buying about 80 percent of Daewoo Electronics'
operations, with sales of about $3.3 billion, said Steven Kalabar,
a member of the investment group. Daewoo is not a big force in the
United States under its own brand name but makes products sold by
others, like monitors for some Compaq and Hewlett-Packard
computers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase price is nearly 10 times the market value of Daewoo
Electronics. But Kalabar said if Alomar had purchased the entire
company, it would have had to assume all of its more than $4
billion in debt, a prohibitively huge sum.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar was born in Saudi Arabia to Iraqi parents and then
studied engineering in London, said Kenneth Chiate, his attorney.
Alomar now has American citizenship, and, contrary to news reports
from South Korea, is not related to any Saudi prince or Cabinet
member, Chiate said.
</P>
<P>
   During the Persian Gulf war, Alomar helped arrange transport of
medical supplies to U.S. troops. He helped develop the $4.8 billion
Shoaiba power plant in Saudi Arabia and helped establish a cellular
phone company in China now run by Metromedia, said Chiate, who is
with the firm of Pillsbury, Madison &AMP; Sutro.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar is also involved in Internet ventures, though some are
led by his son, Karl. One would allow Web surfers to view video
scenes of nightclubs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
