<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6942 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-STEFFI14-COX     08-13 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEFFI14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Graf bows out
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Steffi Graf, one of the greatest women's
tennis players in history, retired Friday, saying her motivation
had waned and the joy had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not having fun anymore,'' Graf said, adding that she had
``nothing left to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf retires ranked No. 3 in the world, the highest-ever ranking
for a retiring player.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Wimbledon, for the first time in my career, I didn't
feel like going to a tournament,'' she said. ``It is time to
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   In her 17-year career, Graf won 22 Grand Slam singles (second to
Margaret Court's 24), 107 tournaments and spent 377 weeks, longer
than any other man or woman, at No. 1 in the world. Graf turned 30
in June and has struggled with a variety injuries but said they did
not play a part in her retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm perfectly fit,'' she said during the
announcement in Heidelberg, Germany, near her hometown of Bruehl.
``This is in no way about injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennis observers in South Florida, where Graf owns a second home
in Boca Raton, weren't surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll be missed,'' said promoter George Liddy, who ran the
Virginia Slims tournaments, among others. ``I'm not surprised. I
thought it was the proper time.''
</P>
<P>
   One of just five players to win all four Grand Slams _ plus
Olympic gold, making it a 1988 Golden Slam _ in a single year, Graf
has enjoyed some of her best results in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a 1998 knee surgery, Graf won the French Open, then
reached the final at Wimbledon, losing to Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really expecting her to kind of end her career at the
U.S. Open,'' said Davenport, the Wimbledon champion and defending
U.S. Open champion, ``so it is a little bit of a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I thought was really great was the older she got and the
more she was winning, probably in the mid-'90s, the happier it
seemed to make her,'' Davenport said. ``When she was playing in the
'80s and just dominating, she never looked that happy and I think
she really learned to appreciate the game the older she got and
more she played.''
</P>
<P>
   Her appreciation seemed to peak with the French Open victory,
where she beat top-ranked and top-tennis brat Martina Hingis in the
final. John Evert, brother of Boca Raton's Chris Evert and former
agent to Jennifer Capriati, said he thinks when Graf was injured
she felt she could still compete at the top. The players who
replaced her while she sat out much of 1997 probably challenged
her, even though she denied that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think once she came back and she proved that she could beat
them, that probably was the pinnacle of her career,'' said Evert,
who runs the Evert Tennis Academy in Boca Raton. ``I don't think
she has anything left to prove to herself now.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf told fans in Paris, during her victory speech, that she
wouldn't be back, and she repeated that sentiment after losing at
Wimbeldon.
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't seem happy about it at Wimbledon. She answered
some questions but not others. She later said it was ``a mistake''
to announce her retirement from those tournaments during such an
emotional time.
</P>
<P>
   Graf's outstanding results and her devastating forehand _ the
leaping crusher that earned her nickname ``Fraulein Forehand'' _
will go down in history as one of the best ever. But her classiness
and grace might be better remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's the only one who modeled herself after Chrissie
(Evert),'' Liddy said. ``They both started young and their
essential contribution was their good manners they showed to other
players. You'll be hard pressed to find that kind of conduct in
today's top players.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf said she decided she'd had enough of the travel and the
tennis life on a plane to San Diego two weeks ago. A few days
later, she strained a hamstring and had to retire from a
first-round match against American Amy Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be her final match.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weeks following Wimbledon weren't easy for me,'' Graf
said. ``I was pulled back and forth, but when I made my decision I
didn't think about it one minute afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   The final tournaments of the summer certainly have been thinking
about it, though. Officials in New Haven, Conn., where Graf was
scheduled to play starting Aug. 23, took dozens of calls from media
and corporate sponsors Friday.
</P>
<P>
   USTA officials, along with many U.S. fans, also had hoped Graf
would make a final run at a major title on the hard courts of the
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed she's not going to be at the U.S. Open to
take some bows, even if she loses in the first round,'' said Jim
Martz, longtime tennis writer and editor of Florida Tennis. ``She
should take her 10-minute standing ovation. She deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf said she plans an exhibition farewell tour. She then hopes
to travel _ without her tennis bag _ and work with her marketing
company and developing juniors in Germany. She probably won't move
to her Polo Club home full-time, as Jana Novotna plans to when she
retires.
</P>
<P>
   She earned nearly $22 million in prize money as a player, more
than all other players except Boris Becker and Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   But Graf probably will keep the Boca Raton home for the same
purpose she's always had it _ as an escape. She likes to shop, go
to concerts and follow the Miami Heat, but otherwise, she's rarely
seen out on the town.
</P>
<P>
   Graf also played a good bit of her career in the South Florida,
though. She played in one of Liddy's tournaments in Bonaventure
soon after turning pro in 1982 at 13 years, four months old.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't get very far and of course nobody knew who she
was,'' Martz said. ``Except that she was a phenom from Germany. She
didn't speak much English then and she was awfully shy.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the court, she was determined, almost fierce, despite the
pigtails. Buchholz saw her three years later at the first Lipton in
Delray Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``She played Chrissie (Evert) in the semifinals,'' Buchholz
said. ``I remember watching that match and seeing her hit that
forehand and you knew then that she was going to be a great tennis
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf went on to win Lipton five times, starting in 1987. That
was 11 months after her first tournament title in Hilton Head,
S.C., and two months before her first major championship, the
French. In August 1987, she reached No. 1 in the world for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, she dominated three generations of tennis players
and nearly two decades of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``She brought a lot to the game,'' Evert said. ``She'll probably
go down as the greatest player of all time with her record.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
