<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGE HAS AN AFTERNOON AS MEDINAH TURNS CUDDLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ On a day when the leaders shot in the 60s, a
player born in the '50s led the way.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Haas, a 45-year-old veteran who has not won on the PGA Tour
since 1993, played like someone in the prime of life Friday.
Shooting a 5-under-par 67, after an opening-round 68, Haas led by
one stroke over Mike Weir of Canada after Friday's birdie-filled
second round of the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Haas was 9-under for the tournament (135), just ahead of Weir
(136, 68-68), and two strokes ahead of Tiger Woods, who started his
5-under-par day with birdies on the first three holes. Lee Westwood
of England was alone in fourth place at six under, while four
players were deadlocked at 5-under _ the 54-year-old Hale Irwin,
Stewart Cink, the first-round leader Sergio Garcia of Spain, and
Skip Kendall, who set the Medinah Country Club course record with a
65.
</P>
<P>
   The barrage of birdies was the theme of the day, as the leader
board was covered with red numbers, unusual for a major
championship. Rain Thursday and Friday softened the greens,
allowing players to fire approach shots at the pins and diminishing
the speed of the greens. Haas used his accuracy off the tee and a
pure putting stroke to keep going lower and lower, reaching
10-under before his only bogey of the day at No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Can Haas, who has not contended at a major tournament since the
1995 Masters, win his first major at an age when most players are
looking forward to the Senior Tour? He was eager to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played a long time out here without a major win, and I'm
disappointed that hasn't happened,'' said Haas, who led the 1995
Masters after 36 holes but finished tied for third. ``I'm not
devastated by it, but we all think we can do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of days I've been nervous. But it's a good
nervous because I'm playing well. I need to embrace that. I need to
enjoy the fact that I will be nervous, because that's what I've
worked for my whole career.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the year's final major has been the least demanding.
Jose Maria Olazabal shot 8-under par to win the Masters. Payne
Stewart was the only player who finished under par at the U.S.
Open. And at Carnoustie, where Paul Lawrie won the British Open
(290, 6-over par), the rough was so deep and the fairways so narrow
that some players were defeated before the tournament started.
</P>
<P>
   But Medinah, the 7,401-yard course that was billed as the
Monster of the Midwest, has been a hospitable beast. On Friday,
many players left the golf course smiling. At Carnoustie, players
left the course looking like dazed boxers who had just been
pummeled.
</P>
<P>
   In these conditions, anyone under par _ like David Duval
(3-under), Jim Furyk (3-under), Lanny Wadkins (3-under), Nick Price
(3-under), Nick Faldo (2-under), Colin Montgomerie (2-under), Fred
Couples (2- under) and Davis Love III (1-under) _ remained well
within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   Woods shot a solid 67, finishing with seven consecutive pars,
despite ending his round in steady rain. While he has played
consistently in this year's majors, whatever he does this weekend
will go a long way toward defining his year. He has won four times
worldwide in 1999, including three times on the PGA Tour, but he
has not won a major since his record-setting victory at the 1997
Masters. If he wins the PGA Championship, an excellent year will
become a great one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep giving yourself chances,'' said Woods, who
tied for third at this year's U.S. Open and tied for seventh at the
British Open. ``You're not going to win every time. I've proven
that. But I'm playing well now. It's not that I put less pressure
on myself at majors. It's just that I'm a better player. When
you're striking the ball well, outwardly it looks as if you are
feeling less pressure. Inside, it's a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone will feel the pressure this weekend, but Haas will have
the comfort of having his 18-year-old son, Jay Jr., as his caddie.
Haas' son has caddied for his father several times, but this is the
first time father and son will work together in contention at a
major. The elder Haas said he had complete faith in his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust him,'' Haas said. ``He agrees with everything I say,
and that's his job as a caddie. On No. 12 today, I was between a
4-iron and a 5-iron. I said, `I think it's a four.' He said, `I
like four.' That's good for me. I have to make the decision
ultimately. And just to have him out there to talk with him, walk
with him, is fun. He's been an inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   The least known of the leaders is Weir, a 29-year-old
left-hander who is looking for his first career victory but who
finished second at the Motorola Western Open in July. This is his
first PGA Championship, and he won't forget it. As his name crept
up the leader board, some fans in his gallery started to sing ``O
Canada.'' Weir's game was better than the singing, as he made six
birdies to reach 10-under par before making bogeys at Nos. 16 and
17.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had told me before the week that I'd shoot 68-68, I
would have taken it,'' said Weir, one of only five left-handed
players on the PGA Tour. ``Hopefully I'll be in this position again
come Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who started the day with a two-stroke lead, shot a 73,
but that score was misleading. Putting was Garcia's downfall, as he
missed birdie attempts from 12 feet, 9 feet, 7 feet, 8 feet, 13
feet and 18 feet. But if he keeps striking the ball as well he did
through the first 36 holes, the championship could still belong to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed, because I probably played better
than I did yesterday,'' Garcia said of his opening-round 66. ``I'm
a little mad because I didn't deserve a 73. But I still have a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for many people, but Haas will wake up
Saturday halfway to a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get that many opportunities to win majors, I don't
care who you are,'' Haas said. ``Obviously, I'm not going to have
20 more chances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
