<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GOLF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDING THE RYDER CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In less than a decade, the once-obscure Ryder Cup match between
the best US and European golfers has become one of the world's
premier sporting events. The reason: It is different. Its format is
varied, including pairs and match play. It occurs every two years
and takes three days, not the four of the weekly tournaments. It is
a team contest; there is no purse for individual players.
</P>
<P>
   So when Germany's Bernhard Langer slid a 6-foot putt past the
last hole on a windy South Carolina course in 1991, he did not lose
$50,000 or $100,000; he lost something much bigger: Europe's claim
to the Ryder Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   Continental pride and the drama produced by a series of close
matches in recent years have built a huge following. Much of that
is threatened by several American players whining about money.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing short of a three-day hurricane could prevent this year's
Ryder Cup from being a huge success next month at The Country Club
in Brookline, Mass. But the future of the event will be in jeopardy
if bickering and one-dimensional thinking aren't laid to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods and David Duval are among those suggesting that the
talent in the event should be better rewarded, at least through
charitable contributions. Their view is understandable from one
perspective. This year's Ryder Cup will gross something over $60
million, according to estimates, with more than $20 million left
after expenses. With this in mind, it might be reasonable for the
organizers to share a bit more with the players.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, however, each player receives $5,000 _ roughly the
amount paid to tour players who make the cut but don't challenge
the leaders _ and automatic qualification for a later, $5 million
tournament. Plus, the Professional Golfers' Association has pledged
$13 million to a new outreach program.
</P>
<P>
   The point that Woods, Duval, and others are missing is this: If
the tournament changes so that the putts are for $100,000 instead
of for team, country, and pride, the Ryder Cup will lose its
uniqueness _ and its success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
