<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-VACATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTING GO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 15, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally. After shimmering on the horizon for months, impossibly
distant, the vacation begins. How rich a person feels on that first
morning, for there is no greater treasure than time.
</P>
<P>
   A mere Sunday cannot compare with the bonanza of vacation days
stretching languidly into what feels like infinity. No Sunday night
shadow here. No ``leisure'' crammed with ``have-tos.'' The dry
cleaning can wait.
</P>
<P>
   The pulse quickens as one packs the suitcases, then the car,
feeling a little like Marco Polo _ something that rarely happens
when loading up for the weekly trip to the dump. At its start, a
vacation is an uncharted course. Even if a person is returning to
the old cottage or a favorite beach, he or she returns with a new
block of time, capable of yielding all manner of discovery and
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the garage with way too many books wedged into
canvas bags, enough camera and hiking equipment to open a store,
and creative expectations on overdrive _ ``I'll write the first
chapter of the novel!'' _ a person prepares to launch into the
country with no clocks.
</P>
<P>
   But first there is one more tour of the house to check doors,
windows, pet food dishes, plants, and lights. There's the
inevitable hesitancy one feels when turning the last lock, because
it seems as though something vital has been left behind. That
something is, of course, the daily routine with all its demands,
clamoring to go along. Its grip will loosen as the car pulls out of
the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Passing familiar landmarks on the way out of town, the
vacationer smiles, knowing he or she is not going to stop at any of
them, for the luscious new block of free time is transporting car,
passengers, and bulging bags to a place far away from the mundane
neighborhood grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   If the vacation is a good one _ and most of them are _ a person
returning home will see that store as welcoming rather than boring.
The rested spirit regains perspective, which is, after all, the
point. The novel is optional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
