u k BC-EDITORIAL-TAXCUT-BOS &LR;      08-13 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TAXCUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN $80 BILLION GIVEAWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 15, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When politicians in Washington talked about ``ending welfare as
we know it,'' they didn't mean the corporate kind. That is
abundantly clear in the $792 billion, 10-year tax cut bill Congress
will send to President Clinton after the summer recess. The bill _
touted as tax relief for the average citizen _ contains more than
$80 billion in new tax breaks for corporations. The lucky
beneficiaries include oil, gas, and timber companies, executives
who eat a lot of business lunches, and firms producing energy from
chicken excrement.
</P>
<P>
   It is a kind of Washington parlor game to juxtapose rhetoric
with reality. When House Speaker Dennis Hastert calls the bill ``a
good deal for the American people,'' is he talking about the
families who pay high electric bills in his state or the utility
companies that will be able to write off the costs of
decommissioning their nuclear power plants to the tune of $1.1
billion?
</P>
<P>
   When Representative Bill Archer of Texas, chairman of the Ways
and Means Committee, says the bill ``is about downsizing the power
of Washington and upsizing the power of the people,'' doesn't he
really mean the power of special-interest lobbyists who use
campaign contributions to ensure a favorable tax status for their
clients? Insurance companies, for example, get $1.2 billion in new
tax shelters, and multinational corporations will be able to write
off their interest payments overseas _ a whopping $36 billion in
savings, according to figures provided by the Joint Committee on
Taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Tax breaks are a popular way to give away goodies because they
do not show up as spending programs in the budget. But they are not
free. The provision that increases the write-off for business
meals, for example, will cost $1.3 billion a year _ more than
Massachusetts spends on its entire ``transitional assistance''
welfare program.
</P>
<P>
   Some corporate tax breaks are useful for encouraging research
and development or getting companies to create jobs in blighted
areas. But this bill is bloated with expensive gifts that could
otherwise go to Social Security or health care. It is time for
Washington and corporate America to break this cycle of dependency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 2259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6950 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-SAIPAN-BOS &LR;      08-13 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SAIPAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEATSHOP LOOPHOLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Tuesday, August 16, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Made in USA'' label ought to mean that a garment was not
made in a sweatshop. Too often that is not the case with clothes
made in Saipan, a US outpost in the central Pacific. The settlement
of a lawsuit guarantees that there will be independent monitoring
of factories in the US Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana
Islands, including Saipan, but it is not enough to guarantee that
workers are protected from substandard wages and working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is a step toward focusing attention on the
Northern Marianas, where loopholes in federal law allow textile
companies to import foreign workers with no regard to immigration
laws and to pay them the local minimum wage, which at $3.05 an hour
is $2.10 less than the federal figure. Many end up working 70 or 80
hours a week without overtime and live in crowded, company-owned
dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   Saipan, largest island in the Northern Marianas, is also
attractive to manufacturers because they avoid tariffs and can
market their products as if they were made in the 50 states. They
import thousands of workers who are grateful for the $3.05 an hour.
Local and federal labor protections are not vigorously enforced.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement by four companies, including Nordstrom and J.
Crew, to settle the suit offers hope that working conditions will
improve. Verite, an Amherst-based group that will monitor the
settlement, will face formidable obstacles in establishing a
permanent presence on an island that is closer to China than the US
mainland. It may also face problems with an indigenous power
structure that has close ties to garment manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Even with this private initiative, the federal government should
improve its efforts to monitor the enforcement of labor laws, and
Congress needs to look closely at the minimum wage exception.
Representative George Miller of California has filed a bill that
would raise the Northern Marianas wage to the federal level. This
could prompt Saipan's factories to move to a nation where the wage
is even lower, and the economy of the islands would be weaker.
Still, the federal $5.15 minimum is hardly munificent, and if
``Made in the USA'' is to mean anything, it ought to imply a
commitment to this basic standard of pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990813.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-DRAPEAU-NYT &LR;      08-13 0918
