<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIDEWALK-OF-NY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPERILED WALK OF FAME HAS HOPEFUL SECOND REEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Florence Otway's little slab of movie-star history on
St. Marks Place, her 50-foot-long homage to actresses who once had
Betty Boop eyes and ultrashort, ultrawavy hair, got a reprieve from
repaving Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Department of Transportation, who on
Thursday called the strip of cement signatures a safety hazard,
said Friday that a work crew would sidestep that sidewalk when it
replaced the others in the East Village next month. Mrs. Otway's
husband, Howard, created the sidewalk in 1971 when he turned a
theater at 80 St. Marks Place into a revival house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to have the contractor go over there,'' the
Transportation Department spokesman, Mark Patterson, said. ``We're
not going to do that. We'll tell them not to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But the reprieve _ sparing imprints from the likes of Ruby
Keeler, Myrna Loy and two Joans, Crawford and Blondell _ may only
be temporary.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department told Mrs. Otway that she must fill
out a ``sidewalk, curb and roadway application'' and that the
sidewalk would have to be approved by the city's Art Commission, an
11-member panel whose duties include screening and approving
proposals for landscape architecture and ``street furniture'' on
city-owned property. Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani is an ex officio
member.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear what the Art Commission's standards for
sidewalks are. Calls to the commission were not returned Friday;
the mayor's press office said that the commission's executive
director, Deborah Bershad, was on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said that if the Art Commission approved the
application, it would go back to the Transportation Department.
``We will meet with the applicant to enter into an agreement
whereby any responsibility for liability for maintenance is
transferred from the city to the owner of the property,'' he said.
``It's up to them afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Otway said that was more or less what she was told by Leon
W. Heyward, the deputy commissioner for street and arterial
maintenance, who rang her doorbell shortly before 5 p.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They went outside to look at Mrs. Otway's shrine to pert faces
and velvet voices of the silver screen _ and, in a sense, to her
husband, an actor and author who died in 1994. ``It was raining,
and water was collecting in the little round heel,'' she said. ``It
was either Ruby Keeler or Joan Blondell. He said a woman in high
heels could trip and fall there. I've never in 28 years known
anyone to catch a heel there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Transportation Department softened its position
_ on Thursday, the agency had said it would remove the sidewalk if
Mrs. Otway did not repair it _ preservationists were defending it
as a near-landmark. (It is too new for landmark status. The
Landmarks Preservation Commission does not consider anything under
30.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Grauman's, but not nearly as organized,'' said Frank
E. Sanchis 3rd, the executive director of the Municipal Art
Society, an organization that has championed historic preservation
in New York City. ``It's a patchwork. There's garbage cans sitting
on top of some of them and Ruby Keeler's footprints were filled
with cigarette butts when I went by.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, it was well worth saving. ``It's one of those
little things that makes life more interesting,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-99 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
